<HEADLINE>
A BUSY CLINTON MAKES TIME FOR PALACE-GAZING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE _ Russia is bombing Chechnya, the Greeks and the Turks
are feuding, demonstrators in Athens are smashing windows, and
there's the challenge of wiring Africa to the Internet to address.
Who has time to sightsee?
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, President Clinton did this past week. Despite an
action-packed schedule of meetings, conciliations, attempted
mediations, and state dinners, Clinton went into Uber-tourist mode,
managing to squeeze in visits to some of the world's most
extraordinary historical sights.
</P>
<P>
   It was classic Clinton _ constantly on the move, switching
quickly from touring an archeological site to scolding Boris
Yeltsin, then back to palace-gazing and a boat ride before popping
back to sign an international security charter.
</P>
<P>
   The president seems rarely to sleep, scheduling an event or
address into nearly every waking moment. This is, after all, a
leader who took a day trip to Bosnia this summer.
</P>
<P>
   So it wasn't a surprise to Clinton's entourage that the
president _ while cramming foreign policy events in seven cities in
five countries into the space of 10 days _ was determined to play
tourist as well as president.
</P>
<P>
   Even the pounding rain that has fallen nearly every day on the
Clinton tour has not discouraged the president from visiting major
art and archeological attractions.
</P>
<P>
   But then, when you're the First Tourist, sightseeing is a little
easier _ at least for the man himself.
</P>
<P>
   He awoke early Sunday in a walking mood, squeezing in a stroll
along the Arno before heading to a conference to discuss such
issues as the future of the welfare state, and how to wire the
world to the Internet. He was trailed, as usual, by a string of
reporters, cameramen, secret service agents, and staff.
</P>
<P>
   When the president visited the ancient Turkish city of Ephesus
last week, he flew Air Force One to Izmit, then was squired in a
42-car motorcade to the excavated site. And there was no need to
worry about lines because the place was closed for his visit.
</P>
<P>
   In Istanbul, Clinton took a private tour of the 16th-century
Topkapi Palace. Less than an hour after being in his presidential
role, signing an international security agreement, Clinton switched
into history-professor mode at the palace, enthusiastically
explaining to a reporter how one of the Sultans brought Delft tiles
from Holland to mix in with the Turkish tiles on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton managed to get in a boat ride, albeit hardly a leisurely
one. The First Family took a 35-minute cruise on the Bosporus,
followed, naturally, by yet another luxury boat for the press corps
and a flotilla of police boats. Some secret service agents were in
wetsuits, just in case the president fell into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Athens, where demonstrators set fires and smashed
storefronts to protest Clinton's visit, the president took an
unplanned excursion to the Acropolis. Usually, such an unscheduled
trip would be a security nightmare for a host city, but because
that part of Athens was closed to traffic and loaded with police,
the visit wasn't much extra effort for Greece, said Rachel Howard,
a spokeswoman for the Greek Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   But ``imagine,'' she said, ``what it would have been like if
he'd stayed three days'' as originally planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
