<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE IS OFF FOR TROJANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC gets to start the 2000s with a clean slate.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike any team in the 1990s, next year's Trojans will not enter
the season with a major losing streak to an archrival gnawing at
its psyche. Thanks to Saturday's 17-7 victory over UCLA, the
Trojans have eradicated the endless debate about whether it would
ever end the Bruins' winning streak, which had stretched to eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a dollar for every time somebody came up to me and
said, `Just beat UCLA,' I'd be a rich man,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said. ``No matter what else we did all year, I kept hearing, `Find
a way to get me out of my misery' about this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett accomplished that mission and also took a major amount
of heat off himself. A victory over the Bruins is like a
``get-out-of-jail-free card.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, a lot of USC fans are probably happier today with
a 5-6 record and victory over UCLA than they would be with an 8-3
record and a loss to the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so glad we got it for coach Hackett,'' tailback Chad
Morton said. ``It's a shame he took so much bad press this year
when it was our fault. We screwed up our season, not him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the magnitude a losing streak can have when it builds and
builds. The Trojans had a similar experience with Notre Dame after
going winless for 13 seasons before beating the Irish in 1996, a
victory that basically gave then-coach John Robinson an extra
season.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration over losing year after year to UCLA was just as
intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much animosity built over eight years,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why so few people will focus on the poor records of both
teams, or the fact that it was one of the sloppier games of the
rivalry. Or that the Trojans committed 16 penalties, including an
astounding 11 by the offensive linemen, if you count left guard
Faasea Mailo's personal foul when he played fullback.
</P>
<P>
   None of that matters after USC defeats an arch-rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely inexplicable. I can't explain it. It's a joy I
haven't seen around here in a long time,'' cornerback Kris Richard
said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was willing to magnify the importance of the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the alumni, it makes up for everything,'' wide receiver R.
Jay Soward said. ``To me, we're still 5-6.''
</P>
<P>
   USC (5-6) now gets a reward for its big victory: a
less-than-scintillating finale Friday against 25th-ranked Louisiana
Tech. But in 10 years, hardly anyone will remember that game. The
same will not be said of defeating UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Linebacker Markus Steele is questionable after
suffering a deep bruise in his stomach after getting stuck by a
cleat during the game. Offensive lineman Jason Grain is unlikely to
return from his knee injury for the final game. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
REPORT CARD &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GAME: 11 &QL; 
RESULT: USC 17, UCLA 7 &QL; 
RECORD: 5-6, 3-5 &QL; 
THIS WEEK'S GPA: 2.67 &QL; 
CUMULATIVE GPA: 2.41 &QL; 
NEXT GAME: Louisiana Tech &QL; 
QUARTERBACKS &QL; 
Would USC be in a bowl if John Fox had started earlier? His most
impressive stat was no turnovers for the second straight game and
he took only two sacks. &QL; 
B &QL; 
RUNNING BACKS &QL; 
Chad Morton went over the 1,000-yard mark by being the Trojans'
workhorse with 143 yards in 36 carries. Sultan McCullough showed
the speed everyone hears about with his 48-yard run. &QL; 
A- &QL; 
RECEIVERS &QL; 
Kareem Kelly drew the headlines, but Windrell Hayes made two
impressive catches over the middle. Remember when people worried if
R. Jay Soward would be a factor? &QL; 
B &QL; 
OFFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
Eight false starts is an unmitigated disaster and inexcusable in
the 11th game of the season. Add two holding penalties and you
wonder how the Trojans won. &QL; 
D- &QL; 
DEFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
All six sacks were registered by linemen, with Matt Childers, Ryan
Nielsen and Lonnie Ford each getting two. They also held UCLA to 45
yards rushing. &QL; 
A- &QL; 
LINEBACKERS &QL; 
Zeke Moreno had an impact with an interception, forced fumble,
fumble recovery, pass deflection and seven tackles. The rest of the
unit was merely OK. &QL; 
B- &QL; 
DEFENSIVE BACKS &QL; 
Ryan McCann was making his first start, but he had Freddie Mitchell
open all day. It could have been a lot worse if Mitchell hadn't
dropped a couple of passes. &QL; 
C- &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS &QL; 
It's time to admit that the kicking game has been awful, and far
more than just a snapping or blocking problem. USC has made 11 of
21 field goals this season. &QL; 
C+ &QL; 
COACHING &QL; 
A great deal of Paul Hackett's critics took the weekend off. The
fake field goal was an inspired call, as were the five-receiver
formations. Again, about those 16 penalties. . . &QL; 
B-
</P>
