<HEADLINE>
BIDING HIS TIME IS KNIGHT-MARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Travis Knight spent a month of his summer playing
with rookies and free-agent hopefuls in the summer pro league. A
three-year veteran with a long-term contract, Knight didn't need to
play in Long Beach, but he chose to spend the time learning Los
Angeles Lakers coach Phil Jackson's triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   His payoff? A badly sprained ankle, several weeks of rehab and,
so far, about five minutes per game of playing time. And this on a
team with no depth at power forward and center, Knight's two
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jackson has chosen to play Shaquille O'Neal for 40
minutes a game and use either John Salley or a small lineup instead
of using the 7-foot Knight.
</P>
<P>
   That's partially a reflection on Knight's comfort level on the
court _ Jackson has yanked him quickly for making mistakes _ and
partially a reflection on his health. Knight's right ankle isn't
100 percent healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do the things that I used to do,'' Knight said. ``It's
frustrating for me. There's not a whole lot I can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Knight has also struggled to gain confidence on the floor,
which isn't helped by his short stints. Not that he's complaining
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil's the coach, I trust his judgment,'' he said. ``I'm fine.
I'm trying to get back and find a rhythm. It will come, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, meanwhile, is happy with O'Neal's production in
extended minutes _ witness the 41 points in 43 minutes Friday night
_ and joked, ``I don't know if I'll ever go back to the usual.''
</P>
<P>
   So Knight and Salley might have to wait for garbage time to get
on the court. Jackson said he's also limited Knight because of the
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been giving him short minutes and trying to see if he can
get comfortable out there,'' he said. And has Knight looked
comfortable? ``No. I don't think he's really played to where he
feels good yet. I think he's just feeling his way out there right
now. We'll see what we can find in the rotation. I haven't found
out how to use him yet. That's still us getting to know each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Reaching out: Guard Derek Fisher will pledge $1,000 to Big
Brothers for every assist he gets in the Lakers' Christmas-day game
against the San Antonio Spurs. Fisher will announce the pledge
Saturday during an appearance from 2 to 4 p.m. at The Athletes Foot
in Marina del Rey.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers also have announced their annual Magic Johnson
Foundation toy drive, which benefits charitable organizations
throughout Los Angeles. Fans are asked to bring toys to any of the
following games: Nov. 24, Dec. 3, Dec. 5 or Dec. 7.!dlim! &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
