<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUSTRATED EMMITT HAS QUESTIONS ABOUT STRATEGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ In his postgame frustration, Emmitt Smith, the
man with the broken hand, pointed an accusing finger yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' running back pointed to the third quarter. He
pointed to the stats sheet. He pointed to yet another road game
that the fickle Cowboys couldn't sock away.
</P>
<P>
   And in so doing, he directly pointed at the play calling. And
the one who calls those plays, of course, happens to be the head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Emmitt has grumbled about a
perceived slight or a game plan that suddenly, to his dismay, took
to the air. The headline, ``Smith wants football'' is not a novel
one.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of a wrenching, 13-9 loss to the Arizona
Cardinals, Smith's grumblings this time carried an unmistakable
bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let you do all the writing with that,'' Smith first said,
when asked whether he thought the Cowboys abandoned the running
game in a telltale third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just frustrating as I-don't-know-what.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, the question about the running game was reworded,
and Emmitt was lobbed a verbal softball about the Arizona defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job in the third quarter,'' he answered. ``But
I didn't think we made a legitimate effort to go at them in the
third quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Ears immediately perked. Please elaborate, someone suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the statistics _ go and check it out,'' Smith
answered.
</P>
<P>
   What Emmitt was referring to was a halftime ledger that listed
him with 83 rushing yards on 18 carries. Smith, broken hand and
all, had come out like a true warrior, dashing through holes that
were there and picking his way through ones that weren't.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to play against the 3-6 Cardinals. He could have
waited and mended for another Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No _ it didn't hurt at all,'' he said after yesterday's game,
though the hand was wrapped in white bandages at least an inch
thick.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys dominated the first half in _ stop me if you've read
this before _ everything but the scoreboard. They had 12 first
downs (seven on the ground) to the home team's four. They enjoyed a
21:30 to 8:30 edge in time of possession, and this was despite the
absence of redoubtable blocking force Larry Allen.
</P>
<P>
   But as Emmitt said, ``Go and check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Smith meant, the Cowboys snapped the ball
nine times other than when they were punting. Seven of those snaps
led to pass plays. Smith got the call to run the ball only twice.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the game swung. The Cowboys were never able to
regain the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when you're backed up, you've got to do certain
things,'' Smith said, couching his earlier remark.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, yes, the Cowboys never snapped the ball
beyond their own 31-yard line. Six of those nine plays were in the
literal shadow of their own goal.
</P>
<P>
   But head coach Chan Gailey, for whatever reason, chose to let
stand-in quarterback Jason Garrett go to the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do that,'' Gailey explained. ``We try to keep them off
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of penalties that set us back. We had some
situations that were putting us in bad down-and-distance
situations, coming out of our end zone a couple of times. We tried
to catch them off balance with the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not like we abandoned \Rthe running game\S
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but on a day that cried out for somebody, anybody, in a
Cowboys uniform to make a big play, why Gailey even momentarily
abandoned his proven big-play runner in favor of his backup
quarterback is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Smith had one giant carry, an 18-yard gain on the
Cowboys' second play of the second half, that was called back
because of holding.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Emmitt found his number being regularly called
again, it was the fourth quarter and the offense was trying to play
catch-up, a game it does not engage in well.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's last carry of the day was another riddle. With rookie
Solomon Page subbing for injured Erik Williams at right tackle,
Gailey sent Emmitt off the right side on fourth down-and-one. The
Cardinals' Kwamie Lassiter met him for no gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey _ I just run what's called,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Cowboys' final possession, needing to move 43 yards in
101 seconds, Gailey had Chris Warren, not Smith, in the backfield.
Smith had, indeed, caught a pass earlier in the game, despite the
wrapping on his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   What sort of coach leaves his best player on the bench on the
game's final, desperate drive?
</P>
<P>
   A 5-5 coach, as it turns out. A coach that says he thinks
everything will be all right, once December comes and his battered
team heals.
</P>
<P>
   A coach that couldn't seem to see yesterday which Cowboy
represented his best chance of beating the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, by all means, Emmitt Smith, let's point fingers.
 &LR; tagtop:Gil LeBreton, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:lebreton &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
