<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COME SHOWDOWN TIME, COWBOYS COME UP SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The final details were grim, but in all honesty,
those details provided a tell-tale ending to an afternoon of
immense offensive frustration, ineptness and yes, sour luck.
</P>
<P>
   Game on the line late in the fourth quarter. Two downs to make 1
yard inside the 10. Can't do it. Game over. Cowboys lose.
</P>
<P>
   But why should it have been any other way? Back-to-back failures
by the Cowboys in that particular showdown situation meant football
justice smiled upon the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   They got what was deserved. A 13-9 victory that left the Cowboys
precious little regrouping time to recover from yet another heavy
dose of despair. But at 5-5, at least the Cowboys have had plenty
of practice this season at attempting to rise from the emotional
ashes of a game that somehow got away.
</P>
<P>
   Miami will be at Texas Stadium on Thursday, and Chan Gailey said
for the next 72 hours he knows what's coming from the multitudes
back home _ a ``ton of the sky is falling'' commentary.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dolphins will no doubt be looking toward Thursday the
same way Cardinals coach Vince Tobin said his club was looking
toward the second half yesterday, trailing 7-3 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players realized this was a football team that was very
beatable today,'' Tobin noted. The Cowboys had certainly left
enough clues on that subject in a first half of yardage dominance
that produced just seven points.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens against Miami, Troy Aikman's postgame
observation here yesterday suggested it wouldn't be with him as a
sideline spectator for the third consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing,'' said Aikman, although Gailey was not close to
being that definite when asked after yesterday's game. Due to the
state of his noggin, Aikman will have to receive medical clearance
to return. For what it's worth, Troy has already given himself that
clearance.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about urgency, of course. The season is on the edge,
even in the totally-up-for-grabs National Foo-Foo Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday was considered a swing game for the Cowboys _ a chance
to pad the victory column against a Cardinals club that was a
meager 3-6 and also without its top quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   All wrongs through nearly four quarters could have been made
right in the final minutes. The Cowboys were driving behind Emmitt
Smith and a pounding ground game that had again found its
first-half steam.
</P>
<P>
   When Emmitt bounced up the middle for 8 big yards, it left the
Cowboys with a second-and-two from the Arizona 10. But disaster
struck right there. Right tackle Erik Williams was injured on the
play, knocked woozy by a blow to the helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, offensive-line coach Hudson Houck had to reshuffle up
front. With Larry Allen injured last week, Houck was already
testing his depth. When Williams went down, he moved rookie Solomon
Page to right tackle from left guard, and brought in Tom Myslinski
at Page's spot.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing went right after that. Emmitt got a single yard up the
middle on second down, was stuffed for no-gain on third, and then
tested the right side on the critical fourth-and-one. He appeared
to have daylight inside, but broke outside, and was smacked down
for a devastating no gain.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, with 3:22 to play, Emmitt's big yardage afternoon
(he finished with 127 yards on 29 carries) meant nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think that was an excuse,'' said Houck, meaning
the unlucky Williams injury and the quick changes up front. ``But
that's what you look at the film for _ to see where the breakdowns
were. It's just a shame it got to that point. We certainly had the
opportunities to have this game taken care of earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Like in the first half, of course, when the Cowboys had a
touchdown pass to Ernie Mills nullified on a play-clock violation,
and a 38-yard field goal wiped out on a holding penalty _ both on
the same possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was really a devastating afternoon for a bunch of proud
men,'' Houck said. ``It hurts. But we've hurt before, and bounced
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had done just that in last week's victory against
Green Bay, except Jason Garrett couldn't duplicate that quarterback
relief performance yesterday. Garrett threw for a meager 111 yards,
and while making no glaring mistake, also generated nothing after
capping a first-quarter drive with a TD pass to tight end David
LaFleur.
</P>
<P>
   This loss, however, was not about Garrett. And despite the
first-half frustration, and a third quarter without a first down,
the Cowboys were still where they needed to be at the end of the
game. The opportunity to win was there.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Arizona Cardinals who seized that opportunity,
and sent a reeling team back to Dallas, trying to regroup in time
for the Dolphins. Not even Jimmy Johnson, from way down there in
Miami, could have scripted this ending any better.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
