<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7337 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     11-22 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS AGAIN JUMP TO LEAD BUT FALTER DOWN THE STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ This is becoming a tired story. If it ever goes
Hollywood, the part of the Cowboys will be played by the rabbit who
starred in ``The Tortoise and the Hare.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have scored first in every game this season. They've
never trailed at halftime. Yet they're 5-5 after losing 13-9 in
another game of self-destruction yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   This time it came against an Arizona Cardinals team that two
weeks ago was considered to have its bags packed and waiting by the
door.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Cowboys are the ones feeling despair. They did manage
to get a good look at the enemy yesterday and make a positive I.D.
The enemy, as you might have expected by now, wore big blue stars
on the side of their helmets.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Cowboys team that came into yesterday's game leading
the NFL in penalty yardage (717) and was third only to Chicago and
Cincinnati in total penalties (72), then did nothing to diminish
their hold (no pun intended) on ignominy.
</P>
<P>
   Injured wide receiver Michael Irvin apparently went off angrily
inside the losing locker room immediately after the game. Nobody
was happy. Nobody liked what they had just seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penalties killed us. We can't have it, and this isn't the
first time it's happened, either,'' said Cowboys center Mark
Stepnoski. ``Considering all the personnel that we have out \Rwith
injuries\S right now, we're already at enough of a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make it any harder on ourselves by letting positive plays
be negated by penalties, or taking points off the board ... well,
we're not that good to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys find themselves at .500 again after having gotten
off to a 3-0 start with a 35-7 victory against these same Cardinals
seven weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have lost five road games in row and are 3-3 against
NFC East teams, which they swept a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   They face a mini-Mount Everest as they try to get back into the
NFC East race. Washington is 6-4 after beating the New York Giants,
23-13, yesterday. The Giants are 5-5, and have beaten the Cowboys
once this season with the rematch scheduled for Jan. 2 at Texas
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not good enough right now to lose scoring
opportunities,'' said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey. ``We're getting
penalties at critical times. That's what is getting us right now
... \Ralthough\S I don't know when there is a noncritical time for
a penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, none were bigger than two flags on the same Cowboys drive
in the second quarter. Jason Garrett, making his second consecutive
start for the injured Troy Aikman (concussions), hit Ernie Mills
for what appeared to be a 26-yard touchdown pass, but a flag was
thrown for delay of game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I did not think the play was sent in
late, and I didn't think there was any way that we were in a
delay-of-game situation,'' said Gailey, who noticed two plays later
that the 25-second clock had to be reset because it started early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened. ... I didn't think it was an
abnormal situation where we were even close to a delay of game.''
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, Richie Cunningham kicked a 38-yard field
goal, but the play was erased by a holding call on Robert Thomas.
Cunningham then missed a 48-yard attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a judgment call,'' Thomas said. ``The guy anchored
himself, and it looked to the official, I guess, like I wrapped
around him. The same thing happened the next time, and they didn't
call anything. Was I surprised \Rto be flagged\S? Sure, what player
ain't?''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Cowboys looked comfortable early. Garrett's
11-yard touchdown pass to tight end David LaFleur gave the Cowboys
a 7-0 first-quarter lead.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith played with a broken hand _ a metal plate and six
screws were inserted 12 days ago _ and rushed for 83 of his 127
yards by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   But the Arizona comeback began late in the half when the Cowboys
found themselves pinned back at their own 7 following an
unnecessary-roughness penalty called on rookie Ebenezer Ekuban on a
punt return.
</P>
<P>
   After forcing a Cowboys punt, the Cardinals turned a short field
into a 24-yard field goal by Chris Jacke just before halftime. The
Cowboys had dominated the first half (21 1/2 minutes to 8 1/2
minutes in time of possession and 180 to 55 yards in total
offense), yet they led only 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona scored on its first possession of the second half with
Dave Brown, subbing for the injured Jake Plummer, hitting Rob Moore
for a 21-yard touchdown pass less than two minutes into the third
quarter. The Cardinals led 10-7 and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Cardinals are ranked 29th offensively in the NFL,
the Cowboys were in the game to the bitter end. Smith was stopped
in his tracks on a fourth-and-one attempt off right tackle from the
Arizona 9 with less than 3 1/2 minutes left, on a play in which
right tackle Erik Williams was out of the game because of a blow to
the head.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game of ``almosts'' for the Cowboys. In the third
quarter, Raghib Ismail made what appeared to be an acrobatic catch
of a 36-yard Garrett pass at the Arizona 43. But the Cardinals
challenged the call, and it was overturned by instant replay. The
Cowboys came away with no points on that drive.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Cowboys had a chance to win it at the end. After the
Cardinals took a safety rather than punt out of their own end zone,
Deion Sanders, playing with groin and hamstring strains, returned
the free kick 31 yards to the Arizona 43.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the ball with 1:41 left in the game, the Cowboys'
offense ran eight plays, picking up a first down on a
fourth-and-one pass to Chris Warren for 5 yards at the Arizona 29.
But four plays later, this time facing fourth-and-three, Garrett
hit Ismail, who was stopped by J.J. McCleskey short of the first
down.
</P>
<P>
   And all those earlier missed opportunities came rushing back for
every player who wore a blue star on the side of his helmet.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
