<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW OWES ITS FOOTBALL PLAYERS A MILLION THANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In former Seahawks coach Chuck Knox's endless supply
of hoary football aphorisms was one that explained the University
of Washington's semi-astonishing season as well as anything:
</P>
<P>
   It's not always who you play, Knox said, but when you play 'em.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Huskies happened to catch Oregon on Oct. 2
with the Ducks' top two running backs injured loomed as large as
anything in getting the Huskies to the Holiday Bowl bid.
</P>
<P>
   Beating the Ducks that day, 34-20, not only opened the
conference season with a good buzz, it paid off at the end. The 7-4
Huskies were chosen for the San Diego game largely because of the
win over the 8-3 Ducks, who finished tied in league with Washington
at 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   In a sea of meaningless postseason games, the Ducks ended up
with one of college football's larger booby prizes, the Sun Bowl.
Not to demean the good folks of El Paso, but as a reward, the game
plainly sucks. Not only is it on the wind-swept desert of West
Texas, but this year it is played on a New Year's Eve that is not
only historic, but potentially hysterical, owing to the Y2K
doomsayers.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in Seattle wants to be there, especially the Huskies,
some of whom wondered privately about opting out. It wasn't the
first time the urge was felt at Montlake: Many of the '86 Huskies
wanted no part of El Paso on Christmas Day, but the attempted
rebellion was quashed by then-coach Don James.
</P>
<P>
   At least this year's Holiday Bowl is on Dec. 29, leaving time to
get back to the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego dalliance holds another virtue, besides the
beaches and warm weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holiday Bowl is for the No. 2 Pac-10 team, which is what
we are,'' said Barbara Hedges, Washington's athletic director. As
one who has been on a toasty seat since January, when she hired
Rick Neuheisel, Hedges couldn't be more proud, not to mention
relieved that she and the program didn't spontaneously combust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty amazing how this season evolved,'' she said
after the 24-14 Apple Cup win over Washington State on a November
Saturday for which the term ``bleak'' was invented. ``The best
thing that I can say about what happened is that Rick and his staff
embraced this team, and the team embraced the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the usual football analysis about zone blitzes and
option pitches, Hedges' expression sounds a little squishy. But
given what transpired in the Pac-10, which has not played football
this badly since the USS Milwaukee and Aberdeen High School were on
the schedule for Huskies coach Gil Dobie, little things such as
trust and commitment were assets as valuable as anything.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching change from the Jim Lambright regime could have
gone south this season, even when the logic for change was there.
But the senior leadership, despite misgivings and careers full of
annoyances and disappointments, gave Neuheisel the nod.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided they were going to buy into the change and do
everything they could to take Husky football to the level they
wanted it to be,'' Neuheisel said. ``They put it back on top, at
least in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seniors made sure this wasn't a rebuilding year.''
</P>
<P>
   A sweep of their Northwest rivals restored what the Huskies
consider the rightful order and took considerable heat off
Neuheisel's $1 million-a-year contract, as well as his recruiting
blunders that brought minor sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of football people, not just in the Pac-10 but nationally,
were eager for Neuheisel to fall on his face. Fortunately for him,
none were his own players.
</P>
<P>
   While some will lament the lost opportunity for the Rose Bowl,
the fact that the Huskies made any bowl remains remarkable,
particularly after an 0-2 start. Aside from quarterback Marques
Tuiasosopo, this is a team of surpassing ordinariness.
</P>
<P>
   But so was the rest of the Pac-10. With the exception of WSU, a
handkerchief could have been thrown over the other nine teams and
nothing would have stuck out. Having Stanford as conference champ
for the first time since bushy sideburns says it all. It's like Don
Knotts winning a Frank Sinatra impersonation contest.
</P>
<P>
   But opportunity comes to ordinary teams, too, and advantage must
be taken. That's what the Huskies did Oct. 2. The Ducks finished
1999 with a 35-point scoring average that ranks in the top 10
nationally, but on that afternoon in Husky Stadium, injuries to
tailbacks Reuben Droughns and Herman Ho-Ching helped hold the Ducks
to 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies did not hold another conference team to under 21
points until Saturday. Nor did the Huskies, with the exception of a
freakish start against Oregon State, beat up on an opponent. Nearly
every Saturday was a cliff-hanger that created endless what-if
games for the second-guessers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the first guesses by Neuheisel and his staff worked out.
The wins against the other halfway decent conference members,
Stanford and Arizona, were largely tests of will that would not
have worked had the players not bought into Neuheisel and his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   The wins also paid off Hedges' gamble on Neuheisel, who had won
little of significance as a head coach yet pulled down a stupendous
salary and a gym full of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some people's minds, it was a big risk,'' she said. ``In my
mind, it wasn't at all. It was apparent to me that Rick was the
very best for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only real risk was the question about what Rick was being
paid. It was not an insignificant issue, but the reality was Rick
was paid very well at Colorado. For him to leave, we had to put
together a very good package.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedges called Neuheisel on the search's first day, and both
agreed it wouldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was something lingering,'' Hedges said. ``We stayed
in touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel returned Hedges' calls after midnight. Often they
would talk until 2 a.m. Finally, Neuheisel said, ``Make it a
blockbuster.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedges did. So Neuheisel said yes. Colorado, and the rest of the
college jockocracy, said, ``Ohmigawd.''
</P>
<P>
   But it took the Husky players saying, ``OK,'' before the biggest
off-season coaching story not only averted disaster, but made the
breaks pay off in three months of restoration of the Huskies'
football profile.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it won't last. Maybe the Pac-10 will again play serious
football. For now, it isn't El Paso in the dark, it's the UW
football program in the light.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
