<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-CHIEFS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS SMACK CHIEFS FOR FIFTH CONSECUTIVE VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As the Kansas City Chiefs were driving the
ball right at Seattle's patchwork defense on the game's opening
series, feelings of self-doubt and visions of yet another
disheartening loss in Arrowhead Stadium had to be consuming the
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Not these Seahawks. Maybe the Seahawks of seasons past that had
not won here since 1990 and had a lone, one-point victory to show
for their past 17 trips to what had become their personal house of
horrors.
</P>
<P>
   But not this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. No. Never,'' said quarterback Jon Kitna, who was equal
parts perturbed and defiant that anyone would even broach such an
obvious subject. ``We don't have that kind of attitude around here
anymore. This is not the same old Seahawks. We never feel like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's beginning to look more and more like these really aren't
the same old Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Their 31-19 victory over the Chiefs Sunday was just the latest
step, and one of the largest, in proving it.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' fifth consecutive victory pushed their AFC
West-leading record to 8-2, giving them a three-game lead over the
Chiefs (5-5) and a 2{-game edge over the Oakland Raiders, who are
5-4 entering their game against the Broncos in Denver tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of having a three-game cushion with six games to
play, coupled with this rarest of triumphs at Arrowhead, should
have signaled the point where history gave way to hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. Not these Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge win for us. No doubt,'' running back Ricky
Watters said. ``But every time you win it makes the next game even
bigger. We just have to keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks won Sunday as they have won so many times this
season. Despite not playing their best, they made key plays at
critical junctures of the game:
</P>
<P>
   -- Like the injury-depleted defense, which was playing without
leading tackler Darren Smith and disruptive defensive tackle Sam
Adams, and had strong safety Darryl Williams for only part-time
duty and Pro Bowl defensive end Michael Sinclair playing at only
partial speed.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing the Chiefs 71 yards on that initial drive _ which
ended in a Pete Stoyanovich field goal because Sinclair pressured
Elvis Grbac into throwing away a third-down pass _ and giving up
another 71 on a second-quarter possession _ which didn't end until
Donnell Bennett had slammed into the end zone _ the Seahawks
limited the Chiefs to 111 yards on their next seven series as
Seattle's offense was pushing to a 24-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play 60 minutes. We are going to fight,''
linebacker Chad Brown said. ``But it would be nice to have a game
where we go for the jugular, rip it out and just bite on it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Brown quickly added: ``We had a lot of guys who had to play
hurt and guys who had to come in for guys who couldn't even play.
So we really sucked it up. It was a pretty good effort for a team
that's hobbled.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Like the offense, which did not get a reception from leading
receiver Derrick Mayes and saw Kitna complete less than 50 percent
of his passes (14 of 33) for the first time this season, but still
managed to score the most points against the Chiefs at Arrowhead
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up the slack were Watters, who scored three touchdowns
while rushing for 107 yards and catching four passes for 67 yards,
and Sean Dawkins, who highlighted his five-catch, 114-yard
afternoon with a 45-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City has a very stout run defense, but we felt we
needed to run,'' coach Mike Holmgren said. ``We haven't scared
anybody running the ball this year, but we are getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we were able to run the ball and the fact that
Ricky gets a couple of touchdowns makes my life better.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Like the special teams, whose generally solid efforts all
season have been blemished by intermittent twinges of
inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Feagles picked a most opportune time to snap out of his
recent slump, dropping punts at the Chiefs 9 and 14 to help the
Seahawks outscore KC 17-6 in the second half. Feagles' best, and
most timely, effort came in the third quarter when his 26-yarder
was fair caught at the Chiefs 9 after Holmgren decided against
trying a 47-yard field goal
</P>
<P>
   ``Feags made the perfect punt,'' Holmgren said. ``If he punts
the ball into the end zone, no one looks very smart on that. But he
put it down, we held them, got good field position and we scored
(on Dawkins' TD catch).''
</P>
<P>
   As they have done so many times this season, the Seahawks found
a way to win on a day when they didn't play up to their own
expectations. And they did it in front of a boisterous crowd of
78,714 to run their road record to 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   It was another step in a season of small strides. Still, it was
a giant leap toward the franchise's first playoff berth since 1988
and perhaps even its first division title since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's done yet. We have some real tough games ahead of
us,'' Holmgren said of a schedule that includes this week's game
against Tampa Bay at the Kingdome and then rematches with each of
the four AFC West teams before closing the regular season at the
New York Jets. ``I'm just proud of the fact that the team has
managed to stay focused, one game at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   With that said, Holmgren added what can be used to keep his team
focused, even after it removed the Arrowhead jinx.
</P>
<P>
   ``We at times looked like we haven't figured the whole thing out
yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Look ahead? Not with this coach. Not these Seahawks, who are
proving week by week that they are not the same old Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
