<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED RULES AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribute  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; FOXBORO, Mass. _ Whether it's the rain, winds or beautiful blue
skies that hung over Foxboro Stadium on Sunday _ nothing seems to
go right in this town for the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   For another season and possibly many more to follow, the Galaxy
will have to deal with another blown opportunity. A few days ago,
it was the only Western Conference team to reach the MLS
championship twice.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's the only team to blow it twice.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after D.C. United scored three goals in the final 21
minutes to beat the Galaxy by a goal in a muddy monsoon to claim
the inaugural trophy _ United added another championship, its third
in four years, with a 2-0 victory over Los Angeles in front of
44,910.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it likes it or not, this is a franchise yet to prove it
can win the big one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always going to linger and it's always going to be
there,'' defender Danny Pena said of the Galaxy's history in title
games. `It's not something we are going to forget or the fans are
going to forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``As players, it's always something you're going to remember.
You don't get too many opportunities like this, but you have to
move forward and keep fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts as bad as it can hurt right now. But somehow, when
training starts next year, we've got to turn this into motivation
to get back to this game.''
</P>
<P>
   What will make this defeat tougher to deal with than '96 were
the freak events that went against Los Angeles in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes into the match, Galaxy defender Robin Fraser took a
nasty forearm from Roy Lassiter to his back, sending the MLS
defender of the year to the turf, which broke his collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first half, Cobi Jones beat United defender
John Maessner to the right of United's goal. Maessner swiped at
Jones, clipping his heel, but no penalty kick was called.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman received a
bouncing ball to the goal area from Steve Jolley. Lassiter rushed
on as Hartman nearly tripped trying to free himself. Hartman
avoided disaster, but he stumbled again trying to make a routine
play. He chunked a pass like a weekend hacker, giving a free ball
to United's Ben Olsen, who fired into an empty net to give United
its second goal of the match.
</P>
<P>
   One minute it looked like the Galaxy would tie the game with a
penalty before intermission. The next minute, it was down 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid, disgusted earlier when Lassiter wasn't
blown for a foul on Fraser, nearly lost it when no foul was called
on Maessner. He walked off at halftime screaming at referee Tim
Weyland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, losing Fraser, who has a broken collarbone, was
significant and it's an amazing feat that such a gifted athlete
like Robin would fall down on his own without a call,'' a sarcastic
Schmid said. ``On Cobi, I have the benefit of the big-screen
replay, but I guess that picture's fuzzy. It certainly looked like
he was taken down in the box.''
</P>
<P>
   That was press-conference talk. Minutes later, Schmid explained
how he really felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might as well say it, and they can fine me for it, but I
thought the referring was crap,'' Schmid said. ``I thought the
refereeing impacted the game. It wasn't just the non-call on
Fraser, but it was several calls that continually changed the
course of the game. I don't want to take anything away from D.C.,
they played a great game, but we deserved better officiating in a
championship than that.''
</P>
<P>
   United's opening goal in the 19th minute was also opportunistic.
Hartman made a brilliant save from an initial shot from Lassiter.
Galaxy defender Paul Caligiuri was there to clear it off the line
but got tangled with Hartman, losing the ball off his toe to Jamie
Moreno, who had an easy tap-in to the right netting.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy had chances to score, missing two golden
opportunities in the first half. A Pena header from a Greg Vanney
corner kick hit the post. Earlier, Jones almost scored on a through
pass from Ezra Hendrickson, but United defender Carlos Llamosa
cleared it out at the last second.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a difference, however, it was United's toughness
and the man-marking job D.C.'s Richie Williams did on Galaxy
playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos.
</P>
<P>
   United seemed to be more physical than the Galaxy _ winning most
of the one-on-one battles, leaving Los Angeles out of sync at
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I thought we did a fairly good job,'' Schmid said.
``I just think there was a lot of stuff that wasn't called.''
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, the Galaxy's midfield general, admitted he was taken
out of his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was marked real tight most of the time and I was receiving
the ball at my back,'' Cienfuegos said. ``I didn't have much space
to turn. There was tight marking on me all day and I was never able
to turn and get off some passes off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
