<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7341 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     11-22 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAIT 'TIL THIS TEAM GETS IT TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Ladies and gentlemen, boys and girls. It will
be downright frightening when the 1999 Seattle Seahawks actually
put together a real-live, honest-to-goodness, dominating
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because if the Hawks can go into Arrowhead Stadium, as they did
Sunday, and put up a 31-19 victory over the Chiefs despite missing
two key defensive starters, despite a so-so day from quarterback
Jon Kitna, despite an as-yet underutilized Joey Galloway and
despite enough dropped passes to make you think it could have been
51-19, then watch out when all of that actually goes right.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a league-wide warning should be issued on behalf of the
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Like: If you think that a record of 8-2 is gaudy and probably
Teflon-coated in terms of a playoff berth, just wait until the
Hawks really get their act together.
</P>
<P>
   We may be talking first-round bye. We may be talking home-field
advantage. We may be talking AFC Championship game. And, yes, why
not just go ahead and pin the tail on the donkey.
</P>
<P>
   Start visualizing Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Can't you see Cortez Kennedy and Michael Sinclair riding down
one of those ubiquitous Peachtree Streets in limos?
</P>
<P>
   Can't you see Kitna in the middle of the Super Bowl media swarm,
that shaved head bobbing and that big kid-next-door heart pulsing
to the beat of the biggest sideshow on Earth?
</P>
<P>
   Can't you see Ricky Watters volunteering to rap with Puff Daddy
during the Nestle Crunch/Volkswagen Beetle/Hanes Underwear/Charmin
Toilet Tissue halftime show?
</P>
<P>
   Can't you see Mike Holmgren cooly holding court all the way
until the last Sunday in January _ a day we're beginning to suspect
the guy believes he should own.
</P>
<P>
   In some cities, this call for postseason glory would be a
tradition known as ``cranking up the bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   This call would have been appropriate in any week since the
Hawks went to Green Bay and dumped on the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Monday Night Football'' victory was impressive, as was
their comeback victory over the Bengals. Last week, the Hawks were
just resilient enough to stave off a defensively angry Denver team,
while Sunday, the Hawks used just enough weapons on just enough
right calls to keep the Chiefs in an Arrowhead stew.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair, just off a groin injury that still looked like it
bothered him, had the defensive gem of the game.
</P>
<P>
   With the Chiefs trailing 23-13, Sinclair flushed quarterback
Elvis Grbac out of the pocket and over to the sideline where,
brainlocked, Grbac neglected to get rid of the ball and instead
stepped out of bounds with the ball in his hands, taking an 11-yard
sack.
</P>
<P>
   Now that alone was enough to kill the drive. What if injured
tackle Sam Adams and lineback Darrin Smith had been available?
</P>
<P>
   Elvis would have left the building _ hair on fire, in fear.
</P>
<P>
   To be smart, though, all this Seahawks bandwagon cranking must
come with an official warning: This is no juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   At times, like in the third quarter with the Hawks up only
14-13, Kitna overthrew balls to the likes of Sean Dawkins or Itula
Mili and Ricky Watters to cripple a drive. It seemed as if the kid
with only a dozen NFL starts under his belt might buckle under the
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We at times looked like we haven't figured the whole thing out
yet,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on that drive, when Kitna saw Mili lined up as a wide
receiver with no cover guy on him, Kitna took the snap and
immediately threw to him behind the line _ only Mili had already
run about five yards past the line and was helpless except to watch
the ball skitter away on the grass behind him.
</P>
<P>
   With that slim, one-point lead, tensions were high enough that
Mili and Kitna actually yelled at each other. Mili pushed Kitna's
hand away in anger as he ran off the field.
</P>
<P>
   But the poise of Kitna to continue to try and make plays is what
makes the Seahawks so competitive. The calls are there. The game
plans are solid. The book on what the Hawks opponents are going to
do is so thoroughly digested by the Seahawks that they took a
blitzing Chiefs team and drew them into exactly the sort of
coverage Holmgren told his team to expect.
</P>
<P>
   It allowed the Hawks to sprinkle several big offensive plays
into a game plan that called for conservatism in the face of the
Chiefs' blitzing and ball-hawking.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, early in the second quarter, after Kitna had
thrown two incomplete passes deep in KC territory, the Hawks had a
third-and-10 on the Kansas City 22-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Kitna took the snap and the Chiefs sent four lineman
in to blitz, it was immediately clear that the Hawks had made the
perfect call. Kitna, under attack, just dumped the ball in the flat
to Watters, who ran the screen pass in for the unscathed touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only call in that situation, otherwise you throw
the ball into the dirt,'' said an ecstatic Watters, who scored
three TDs by carrying for 107 yards and adding 67 more on four
catches to lead the Hawks to their AFC West victory.
</P>
<P>
   In a football stadium in which the Seahawks had not won a game
since 1990, the fact that Holmgren's playbook was open just enough
to ensure just enough timely ammunition helped the team discard
another bit of heavy baggage.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, despite the momentus history of this victory, what
strikes you most about this team is that it seems completely
disconnected with all that losing, all that it was.
</P>
<P>
   Where this team's going is the only story right now. And if and
when these Hawks start to really click, well, why not visualize
Atlanta? Secretly, the Seahawks are.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
