<HEADLINE>
YESTERDAY IN L.A. SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from
the book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles
Sports History'' in parenthesis, where applicable):
</P>
<P>
   __ Nov. 26, 1989: The Rams' Flipper Anderson breaks the NFL
receiving-yards-in-a-game record with 366 against New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   __ Nov. 27, 1924: A record 57,000 see Los Angeles High tie
Polytechnic High 7-7. It's the largest crowd then on record to
watch a high school football game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Nov. 27, 1965: UCLA's freshman team beats the varsity 75-60
in the first basketball game played at Pauley Pavilion.
Eighteen-year-old freshman Lew Alcindor, who, like the rest of his
class, isn't eligible to play varsity, scores 31 points and has 21
rebounds. The varsity Bruins are the two-time defending NCAA
champions and will go on to an 18-8 mark this season but fail to
make the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   __ Nov. 28, 1964: In the first coaching meeting between John
McKay and Ara Parseghian, USC upsets unbeaten Notre Dame 20-17 on
Craig Fertig's 17-yard TD pass to Rod Sherman before 83,840 at the
Coliseum to knock the Irish out of a certain national championship.
But the celebration ends quickly. The 7-3 Trojans find out hours
later that the Athletic Association of Western Universities has
voted to send 8-2 Oregon State to the Rose Bowl instead to face
Michigan. (49)
</P>
<P>
   __ Birthdays: Tuesday: L.A. native and basketball Hall of Famer
George Yardley (71). Wednesday: Former Dodgers catcher Steve Yeager
(51) and former UCLA basketball star and USC basketball coach Henry
Bibby (50). Friday: Angels pitcher Chuck Finley (37), former L.A.
Raiders coach Art Shell (53). Saturday: New Angels manager and
former Dodgers catcher Mike Scioscia (41). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
