r s BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-NOTEBOOK     11-22 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINCLAIR TURNS INTO REAL PAIN FOR CHIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Michael Sinclair stretched that old line
about playing in pain to absurd lengths Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with a pulled groin that kept him on the sideline last
week, the Seahawks' Pro Bowl defensive end pressured Elvis Grbac
into a sack and three incompletions in the Seahawks' 31-19 victory
over the Kansas City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play bad. I wanted to help this team win,''
Sinclair said after being on the winning end at Arrowhead Stadium
for the first time in his nine-year career. ``This was a huge game,
and if we're going to slay some demons I want to take out my little
six-inch pocket knife and jab him in the side, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Sinclair was wielding the pass-rush equivalent of a
hunting knife, if not a machete.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs' game-opening drive stalled at the Seahawks 12
because Sinclair flushed Grbac from the pocket and forced him to
throw the ball away. Sinclair did it two other times in the second
quarter. But his rapier move came in the fourth quarter when
Sinclair chased Grbac out of bounds for an 11-yard sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably my worst play of the day,'' said Grbac, who
completed 30 of 49 passes for 322 yards. ``I should have gotten rid
of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't, so it ended up being Sinclair's best play of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurting, I really was,'' Sinclair said. ``But adrenalin
is the best kind of medicine because it really helps you to give
what you've got. Your body knows. It says. `Hey, I'm injured, but
I'll go ahead and shoot a little morphine in there for you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never won here,'' he said. ``So I'm going to drive a
stake in the ground and declare when we come here we're going to
make it a competitive situation and we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   SUN SCREEN: The Chiefs repeatedly burned the Seahawks with
screen passes. Grbac picked up 82 of his yards on short passes that
running backs Rashaan Shehee and Tony Richardson turned into long
gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The screens were killing us,'' strong safety Darryl Williams
said. ``He just caught us in a defense that was vulnerable to the
screens, but we still could have made the play.''
</P>
<P>
   COME BLOW YOUR HORN: Chiefs wide receiver Joe Horn provided some
extra incentive the Seahawks really didn't need with his scathing
comments last week about Seahawks cornerback Shawn Springs, whom he
called ``adequate''; quarterback Jon Kitna, whom he said would be
knocked off his roll by the KC defense; and the Seattle defensive
front, which he said was living on the team's 7-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of fired us up,'' Sinclair said. ``I thought he was a
spokesman for the atmosphere. Not that he was saying that, but he
was like the figure head for the atmosphere. I thought we
responded. A lot of guys didn't go in and make it personal against
him. We were like, `OK, if you're going to call us out and
challenge us like that, let's play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   BROWN IS GOLDEN: With leading tackler Darrin Smith sidelined
with a pulled groin, linebacker Chad Brown helped pick up the slack
for the Seahawks defense. Brown had six tackles, tipped two of
Grbac's passes on blitzes and forced a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like we had a good game plan and I thought we executed
well,'' Chiefs wide receiver Derrick Alexander said. ``I think
their defense stepped it up.''
</P>
<P>
   STAT-IC: The Chiefs had more yards (373-369) and first downs
(22-20), a better third-down conversion percentage (.470-.333) and
ran more plays (76-65) than the Seahawks. But they lost were it
counted most _ on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the game as late as the end of the third quarter;
we were in the game as late as five or six minutes to go,'' Chiefs
coach Gunther Cunningham said, ``and we don't make the plays to win
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   STAT DU JOUR: With 107 yards, Ricky Watters moved past Jim
Taylor into 14th place on the NFL's all-time rushing list with
8,685 yards. That Packers' Hall of Fame fullback had 8,597.
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: CB Willie Williams suffered a concussion in the
fourth quarter, but after the game he said he was feeling OK. It
was the only injury of consequence for the already battered
Seahawks. . . . SS Kerry Joseph started for Darryl Williams, who
was slowed by a sore hamstring. But Williams was able to play in
the nickel defense and finished with six tackles. . . . Despite the
loss, the Chiefs are 16-3 against AFC West opponents at Arrowhead
Stadium since 1995. . . . The Seahawks' 92-yard scoring drive in
the second quarter was their longest of the season, and the longest
of the year against the Chiefs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
