<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SUNS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATIGUE CATCHES UP TO HOBBLED SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Gary Payton sat undaunted in the visitors' locker room
with an ice pack wrapped around his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Ruben Patterson had kicked the Sonics point guard the
day before, bruising his calf and forcing him to play with padded
support.
</P>
<P>
   However, Payton took his induction into the damaged-goods
section of the Sonics' roster like he did their early demanding
schedule, which ended with four games in fives nights and a 99-86
loss Sunday to the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got through the (tough schedule) pretty good to me,''
Payton said after the Sonics had their four-game winning streak
snapped at America West Arena. ``Now it's over. ... I ain't worried
about this game. They caught us when they wanted to catch us.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from emphasizing that they will be better prepared when
Phoenix pops up on the schedule Jan. 11, the Sonics know, too, they
will at least be well-rested and healthier for their next game.
</P>
<P>
   After playing nine games (seven on the road) in 14 days, the
Sonics have the next four days off before hosting the L.A. Clippers
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The rest could not come at a better time for a more banged up
team.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Barry did not play Sunday because of a hip pointer.
Patterson has a sore left knee and sprained left ankle. Vin Baker,
who sat out Saturday against Houston, was recovering from the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Jelani McCoy (sprained right ankle) and Shammond Williams
(bruised right thigh) didn't make the trip so they could continue
treatment in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   No one is feeling sorry for the 9-3 Sonics. Not even the
surprisingly 9-3 Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Sonics trailed only 83-81 with 5:02 left in the
game, they weren't far from pulling out their best victory of the
young season. However, fatigue became a factor as the Sonics
faltered down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's Jason Kidd made back-to-back baskets _ a short jumper
and a 3-pointer _ followed by Rodney Rogers' uncontested layup. The
Sonics, looking tired and disenchanted, struggled to get back on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   The result was watching the Suns (7-4) finish the game with a
16-5 spurt.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being in the game throughout, the Sonics never had an
answer for Kidd. He nearly finished with a triple-double,
collecting 25 points, 14 assists and seven rebounds. Kidd's
uncharacteristic but timely 3-point shooting was deadly. He made
4-of-5 shots from long range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to playing these guys again,'' said guard
Vernon Maxwell, who led the Sonics with 20 points off the bench.
``They can't beat us. No disrespect to their players, but we're a
better team than they are. We took their best punch, and we could
have still won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, anytime the Sonics' backcourt is off, winning becomes
increasing difficult. Maxwell converted just seven of his 20 shots.
And Payton struggled to the tune of 11 points on 3-for-14 shooting
with nine assists and six turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Emanual Davis started in place of the injured Barry, but was
ineffective. He missed 7 of 8 shots and finished with two points,
three assists and two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd and Anfernee Hardaway controlled the backcourt duel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won some tough games in some tough situations,'' Payton
said. ``Tonight wasn't our night. It was just one of those games.
They knew we had played a lot, and they just went at us and
attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Sonics did not look the part of the walking
wounded in jumping out to an early 20-11 lead. But the Suns
outworked the Sonics on the boards in the first half, gathering 10
offensive rebounds that became second-chance scores. Clifford
Robinson' put-back dunk put the Suns ahead 47-46 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed by 10 after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fatigue played a big part,'' forward Horace Grant said. ``We
had a lot of energy in the first quarter-and-a-half, and we just
really ran out of gas. We couldn't get our legs under our shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The game, though, was one where the Sonics took solace in
knowing they could have played much better. They shot just 38
percent as a group, and turned the ball over 19 times.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had been averaging 46-percent shooting and just 13.8
turnovers going into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, for running on fumes, we still had a chance to win
the game,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``Ordinarily, we are
very good at taking care of the ball, but we turned it over on some
fast breaks where we had a chance to bring it right down to the
wire. ... As banged up as we are and as tired as we are, I was
proud of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
