<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7348 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      11-22 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The better the team, the shorter the list. The list, that is, of
what it cannot do.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the season, the Texas Longhorns' ``can't-do'' list was a
long one, and it got longer after a season-opening loss to North
Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   But now, nearly three months later, the list is short. About the
only thing Texas can't do is win the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   With victories over Texas A&AMP;M on Friday, in the Big 12
Championship Game (Dec. 4) and in the Fiesta Bowl (Jan. 1), the
Longhorns could finish the season ranked as high as No. 2 and
surely no worse than No. 3 in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Already, national TV and talk-radio personalities are
proclaiming Texas will be next year's preseason No. 1. But the
Longhorns don't want to forget the task at hand. This is a team
that wasn't even ranked after the fourth week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids have worked so hard to separate themselves from last
year's team and its magical year, but if last year was a magical
year, then to this point, this season fits in the same category,''
Texas coach Mack Brown said. ``Our motto for the group this week
will be, `Are you satisfied?' We've got to be ready to go forward,
because we've got a lot of special things left that could happen to
our football team if we're good enough and we handle it well
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns (9-2, 6-1 Big 12) appear to have handled their
success quite well, though they'll admit it is something of a
surprise to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us really tried to predict the future before the
season,'' fullback Ricky Brown said. ``To sum it up, I'd say we're
all really excited about where we are now, and we're really happy
about what we've overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we started the season, we set goals to win the Big 12
South and to be Big 12 champs and to not be beaten by any Texas
school, and those goals are what led us to where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns have taken on each goal as methodically as they
have crossed out these items on the can't-do list:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1) They can't find a suitable replacement for Heisman
Trophy-winning running back Ricky Williams. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they did. After a slow start, Hodges Mitchell has stepped
up and become the man. He is the first back in school history to
rush for more than 1,000 yards and have more than 300 yards in
receptions in a season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2) Texas' offense can't be as potent after losing seven
starters, including a running back (Ricky Williams) and a wide
receiver (Wane McGarity) who had the best seasons in school history
at their respective positions. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it can. The Longhorns are ninth in the country in total
yards with an average of 414.2 per game and are one of only two
Division I-A teams with a 3,000-yard passer, a 1,000-yard rusher
and a 1,000-yard receiver. Texas finished 11th nationally in
offense last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3) Major Applewhite can't be as successful in his second year
as a starter because of the key offensive personnel his team lost. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he can. Applewhite is a finalist for the Davey O'Brien
Award, which is handed out annually to the nation's top
quarterback, and has thrown for more yards (3,132) and touchdowns
(21) this season than any previous Texas quarterback, surpassing
James Brown's 2,468 yards in 1996 and 19 touchdowns in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4) With five new starters, including at tight end, the
Longhorns' offensive line can neither open holes against the strong
run defenses of the Big 12 nor protect Applewhite against the
league's blitzing defenses. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it can. Mitchell has averaged 133.7 yards per game (and 5.6
yards per carry) in Big 12 play. Save for one disastrous afternoon
against Kansas State when it allowed the Wildcats to torture
Applewhite, the offensive line has kept him off his back, allowing
19 sacks overall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5) The Longhorns can't be consistent, because they are too
young. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they can. Despite beginning the year with 23 freshmen and
sophomores on their two-deep roster, the Longhorns have avoided the
roller-coaster season that has plagued much of the rest of the
conference, putting together four- and five-game win streaks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6) The Longhorns' defense can't make up for the loss of
emotional leader Dusty Renfro at middle linebacker. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Au contraire. Though Brown says this defense is the quietest he
has ever coached, it obviously has done its talking on the field.
Texas is sixth in the country in defense, and should it finish
there, this would be its best showing since 1991, when the
Longhorns finished third in the nation in yards allowed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7. Wide receiver Kwame Cavil can't be an effective go-to guy,
because with the loss of Williams and McGarity, defenses will focus
on him. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Forget that. Cavil has established school and conference
single-season reception marks with 85 catches. And with his 1,016
yards, he is only 72 yards from setting a UT yardage mark as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 8. Texas can't beat Nebraska for a third consecutive time. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, really? The Longhorns fought off the Cornhuskers 24-20 on
Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9. Texas can't win the Big 12 South.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Wrong again. The Longhorns have clinched the division and can
win it by two full games with one more win.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10. The Longhorns can't win the Big 12 South, because they
can't win at Kyle Field in the regular-season finale. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Nine down, one to go. The final tally comes this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Winning the Big 12) was one of the goals we had as a team
this year and every year,'' safety Greg Brown said. ``The only
problem is that we are in the same position that A&AMP;M was last year.
They overlooked us, and we can't overlook them. There is no coming
back to Austin if we lose to A&AMP;M.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 0116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
