<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7349 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-HELTON-FIRED-HNS &LR;      11-22 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HELTON-FIRED-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
One day after his football team won its seventh game of the season,
University of Houston head coach Kim Helton was finished as the
Cougars' coach. A source close to the school's athletic program
confirmed Sunday night that Helton will not return for the final
two years on his contract.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Helton, who will receive the remaining $600,000 due on his
contract, ends his seven seasons as UH coach with a 24-53-1 record.
The Cougars finished the regular season with wins over Tulane, LSU
and Army and are eligible for their first bowl since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Helton nor athletic director Chet Gladchuk was available
for comment Sunday night. An official announcement of Helton's
departure is expected today.
</P>
<P>
   The news came as a shock to one of Helton's assistant coaches,
who noted the staff had Sunday off after returning late Saturday
from West Point, N.Y., and was due to meet this morning to discuss
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's 26-14 win over Army, Helton had predicted,
``We're going to have a great recruiting year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars finished sixth in the final Conference USA standings
with a 3-3 league record, having dropped out of championship
contention with losses to Alabama-Birmingham and East Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth of four C-USA teams that are eligible for bowl trips,
UH was hoping Louisville would find a spot outside the conference's
three tie-ins, thus leaving a spot for the Cougars in the third
C-USA bowl, the Humanitarian Bowl in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is now unclear whether the Cougars would accept such
an invitation since they would then be in the midst of a coaching
search. It also is unclear if Gladchuk asked for Helton's
resignation Sunday and was refused, leading to the coach's
dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive 3-8 seasons following a share of the first C-USA
championship in 1996 led to rising criticism of Helton, 51, whose
team was 2-9 in 1995. Prior to this season, he hired new
coordinators _ Dick Bumpas on defense and Les Koenning Jr. on
offense _ and the changes seemed to produce positive results.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Ketric Sanford set school career records for
rushing yards, all-purpose yards and rushing TDs during the season,
and the rushing offense ranked 17th nationally going into the Army
game. The defense was 14th against the run, 26th overall and 25th
against scoring.
</P>
<P>
   But following a sellout of nearly 32,000 at newly renovated
Robertson Stadium for the season opener with Rice, Gladchuk had to
wrestle with an apparent decline in interest in the football
program.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rice game, attendance dwindled markedly for the
remaining four home games, and UH ended with an average of
approximately 20,000 for the season, based on announced figures.
That apathy could not have been encouraging in regard to selling
season tickets and raising private contributions badly needed for
next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 0134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
