<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-KINGS-HNS     11-22 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-KINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The script changed in the final act. The
fourth-quarter collapses have been rewritten. The stars are
different.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the final scene remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   As if to torment themselves, the Rockets refuse to go quietly.
They rallied and tested the Sacramento Kings on Sunday night as
they could not down the stretch at Compaq Center. But again the
sound and fury amounted to nothing. The scene-stealer wore another
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Kings guard Jason Williams nailed Sunday's game-breaker to beat
the Rockets 110-105 and send them home 2-10 with their second
five-game losing streak of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen this,'' guard Shandon Anderson said. ``We can
find a way to get over the hump, and we always fall short. We're
close and close and close. The games are so close, but in the
fourth quarter we never seem to execute like teams that have been
together like Sacramento and Utah.''
</P>
<P>
   And Seattle. And Indiana. And even Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the Rockets lack that keeps victory beyond their
reach, Charles Barkley said: ``We're missing a lot. We're just not
very good. We're still making the same mistakes we made in the
first game, the same mistakes we made in the preseason. Jason made
big shots. But until we accept the challenge, we're going to
struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had their chances, as usual. Playing the second of a
road back-to-back, they were outmanned inside. Kelvin Cato sat out
with a sore right knee. Tony Massenburg was out with a stomach flu.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings shot well, making 48.5 percent. But they held off the
Rockets in large part by controlling the boards, scoring 18
second-chance points, including seven in the last seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played hard in a back-to-back situation short-handed,''
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``They wore us out on the
boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Rockets had a last-minute chance. The Kings _ 7-1 for
their best start since they were the Rochester Royals in 1952-53 _
had been pulling away as if following the familiar script.
Averaging 5.1 points per game, Scot Pollard came off the bench for
a season-high 12 points. His dunk on a perfect pick-and-roll caught
Hakeem Olajuwon high in the lane, putting the Kings up by seven
with 2:15 left.
</P>
<P>
   On their next time down the court, the Rockets could not get a
shot before Olajuwon had to rush a long jumper to beat the shot
clock, putting the Kings in position to put them away. But Williams
quickly missed a 3, and Steve Francis was fouled. His free throw
cut the lead to six. And after a Jon Barry turnover, Francis nailed
a 3 to move the Rockets to within 106-103 with 52.4 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   But after running the shot clock down to its last few ticks,
Williams drove hard to his right and fired a 23-footer over Bryce
Drew, his swish pushing the lead to five.
</P>
<P>
   Williams finished with 25 points, 12 assists and six rebounds.
He left Arco Arena without comment, though Kings coach Rick Adelman
said, ``Jason was really good.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets were ready to sing his praises, and their
misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game, it seems like we're in it,'' Francis said. ``Every
time we play better. Then with the clock running down, someone
throws something up and it goes. He wasn't even facing the
basket.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets still had a chance. Francis followed an Olajuwon
miss with a rebound and layup to cut the lead to 108-105 with 9.6
seconds left. Forced to foul, the Rockets sent Darrick Martin to
the line. He nailed both free throws with eight seconds left to ice
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We executed all right,'' Barkley said. ``We just can't stop
anybody when we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets seemed a few stops short all night. They trailed by
12 in the first half and rallied back to a lead. They trailed by 12
again in the third quarter and came back to within shots of the
lead. The Rockets pulled to within one when Francis broke free for
a slam and Olajuwon, who had 20 points and 15 rebounds, completed a
break and a 9-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   With less than two minutes left in the quarter, the Rockets were
within two. They even had an open 3 for the lead. But Walt Williams
missed everything and Francis had turnovers on three possessions to
end the quarter with the Kings leading by six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned it over too many times,'' Francis said after
finishing with 21 points but eight turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets quickly moved to within a field goal again. Barkley
(19 points) hit a short jumper, then passed to Francis for another
dunk. Even in the fourth quarter, they only briefly fell back by as
many as six before rushing back. But the game came down to a final
few possessions, and the game-deciding shot was on the wrong end of
the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hung in there, but it's the same story _ just not enough,''
Tomjanovich said. ``We were bad when we first started. Before we
became the Rockets that won championships, we lost seven in a row
and were completely blown out. We're competitive, but whatever that
little extra is ''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, it is missing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
