<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7375 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-DEBATE-AZR &LR;      11-22 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYES, FORBES, HATCH, MCCAIN ASSAIL BUSH AT GOP DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES AND CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Arizona _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush skipped his third
nationally televised debate on Sunday, and this time he may have
had reason to regret it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of slugging away at each other, the four GOP
presidential contenders hammered away at Bush, with some saying he
is more interested in raising money for his campaign than in facing
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this campaign is about talking to George W.
Bush,'' said conservative talk-show host Alan Keyes when asked what
he would say to Bush if the candidate were present. ``He doesn't
want to talk to anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Before an audience of about 2,000 at Arizona State University in
Tempe, near Phoenix, the candidates sparred on questions ranging
from Russian attacks on Chechnya to gun control and
campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The debate drew four of the six remaining GOP presidential
candidates _ publisher Steve Forbes, Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, former
U.S. diplomat Keyes and Arizona Sen. John McCain. Missing were
conservative activist Gary Bauer and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was sponsored by the Arizona Republican Party and
telecast live by C-SPAN.
</P>
<P>
   It was Forbes who took the most shots at Bush, critiquing the
Texas governor's recent foreign-policy speech and suggesting Bush
is obsessed with raising money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to life than fund-raisers,'' Forbes said. ``When
you address a question to George W. Bush, you rarely get an answer.
You get something that came off a TelePrompTer or that his tutors
just gave him.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes painted Bush as a puppet, someone who, ``if you put the
words into his mouth, he would be a perfect press secretary.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bush, who has long said he would not attend
Sunday's debate, called the attacks on Bush ``uncalled for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The comments made by other candidates disparaging Governor
Bush's absence tonight were out of line and all uncalled for,''
said Mike Hull, Bush's Arizona campaign director, in a statement
released after the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush will be participating in three debates during
the first half of December, including one in Arizona on December
6,'' Hull added.
</P>
<P>
   McCain found himself under fire during the debate when Hatch
lashed out at the Arizonan's campaign-finance proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, give me a break,'' Hatch said testily after McCain praised
his own bill, so far unsuccessful, to limit unregulated campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If McCain's bill passed, we wouldn't have a Republican Party
two years later,'' Hatch said. Republicans have historically relied
on so-called soft-money donations from corporations while Democrats
get help from unions in the form of independent-expenditure
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In the portion of the debate devoted to foreign policy, Forbes
hit Bush again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed that George W. Bush, in his speech on
China, did not take a forthright attitude on human-rights abuses,''
Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain accused the Clinton administration of conducting a
``feckless, photo-op'' foreign policy and lacerated the president
for his policies on Kosovo. McCain said Kosovo was a military
action that was poll-driven and ``conducted in the most immoral
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates differed slightly on their approaches to gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   McCain argued that some gun-control measures are legitimate, but
he said other social reforms are also necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I took every weapon in Arizona and dumped them into the
Gulf of Mexico, I could still take you to a Web site that teaches
children how to build a pipe bomb,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, who said the focus of his platform is pulling America out
of its ``moral crisis,'' said, ``The answer is not gun control but
self-control.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, about 100 McCain supporters wearing shirts emblazoned
with the American flag crowded around the senator and his wife,
Cindy, as they edged into the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller group of Forbes backers appeared in orange T-shirts to
rally for their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Harper, 17, of Phoenix, who wants to attend the Naval
Academy, as McCain did, said he supports the senator because ``he
is an honorable man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes is a very basic-type politician with sound values and
character instead of flamboyance,'' said James Collins, 46, of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he was ``discouraged'' that Bush decided not to
attend the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think taking this for granted is an insult to the people he
expects to vote for him,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with several campaigns said the debate marks the
beginning of an intense battle to win Arizona's early Feb. 22
primary.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore that point, Forbes will begin airing a
television ad on Tuesday highlighting his position on Social
Security and targeting the older voters whom the candidate sees as
crucial to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Today, McCain will begin a two-day campaign swing through the
state, and Bush, who has said he will attend the Dec. 6 debate,
will send his wife, Laura, to Phoenix for several campaign stops.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' campaign chairman, Bill Dal Col, said Arizona has become
even more important than it was in 1996, as the nation waits to see
whether McCain can manage a victory in his home state. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 0201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
