<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CARDS-HNS     11-22 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
TEMPE, Ariz. _ The Cowboys couldn't hold on to a 17-point lead in
Minnesota, a 14-point lead in Indianapolis or a seven-point lead in
Philadelphia, so it was not surprising that a seven-point lead
wouldn't be enough in Arizona.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they had in eight of their previous nine games this season,
the Cowboys led at halftime Sunday. And as has happened five times
this season, they were outplayed in the second half as the
Cardinals rallied for a 13-9 victory in front of 72,015 at Sun
Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The loss drops the Cowboys (5-5) into a tie with the Giants for
second place behind Washington (6-4) in the NFC East. With
back-to-back wins, the Cardinals are 4-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, there is no constant theme,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey
said. ``If there was, I'd try to solve it. We are just not getting
execution in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had their opportunities. There was a third-and-one
they couldn't convert, followed by a fourth-and-one that was
stymied late in the fourth quarter. There was a final drive that
stalled just 22 yards from victory. There was a touchdown called
back. There was a field goal taken off the scoreboard because of a
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough right now,'' Cowboys safety Darren Woodson said.
``We've got veterans that have won Super Bowls. To come out and not
play the way we're capable of playing, a lot of guys are hurt right
now. And it's not just this game. It's three or four games that
have really hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just mention Philadelphia or New York, and the Cowboys cringe.
Throw in Indianapolis and Minnesota, and it turns into more of a
shudder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same kind of loss,'' Woodson said. ``You know you're
better than the other team, and it's frustrating. Very frustrating.
We have a lot of veterans who just can't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   There were penalties that came back to haunt and Arizona
defensive stands that hurt, the most notable on a late
fourth-quarter drive that stalled at the Cardinals' nine-yard line.
Emmitt Smith went up the middle on third-and-one but was stuffed
for no gain. The Cowboys went for it on fourth down, again giving
the ball to Smith, who attempted to get through on the right side.
He was met at the line by Kwamie Lassiter and Ronald McKinnon,
again falling inches short of the first-down marker.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mile,'' Smith said in describing how long that yard felt.
``It's frustrating as I don't know what to be out there, and
everybody's fighting and doing whatever it takes to win, and not
come away with a victory. Especially to be down there 10, 12 yards
from the goal and not make a first down. It's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Cowboys got another chance after Deion Sanders'
31-yard return of a free kick with 1:41 to play. Backup quarterback
Jason Garrett, starting again for Troy Aikman, threw three
consecutive short passes, then Chris Warren carried five yards to
earn a first down. After three more short pass attempts but only
one completion, the Cowboys faced fourth-and-three at the Arizona
22. Garrett connected with Rocket Ismail, but he was stuffed just
beyond the line for a gain of only one.
</P>
<P>
   There were no final stabs at the end zone, but that's largely
because of what the defense was showing, Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing short zones, and what I think you have to do
in those situations is throw the ball underneath and give your guys
a chance to catch it and run with it and get a little something
going,'' Garrett said. ``They were pretty consistent with that.
They played it well. It was an excellent call on their part.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't only in the second half that the Cowboys missed
chances. There was a touchdown nullified by a delay-of-game penalty
in the second quarter. On second-and-10 from the Arizona 26,
Garrett connected with Ernie Mills in the corner of the end zone.
At the time, Dallas was clinging to a 7-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was even aware the play was late, and according to
Garrett no whistle ever blew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty aware of the clock,'' he said. ``We had a shift
and movement on that, and it was obviously one that was coming down
to the wire. I thought I got the ball off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys could have salvaged three points out of the drive
when Richie Cunningham successfully booted a 38-yard field goal.
Those points were wiped off, however, thanks to a holding penalty
by fullback Robert Thomas. The ball was moved back 10 yards, and
Cunningham attempted a 48-yarder. That one went wide left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not good enough right now to lose scoring
opportunities,'' Gailey said. ``We have to take advantage of every
one of those. That did hurt. It hurt enough to lose the ballgame,
obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' only touchdown came courtesy of the ground attack.
On their second possession of the game, Smith, Ismail and Chris
Warren combined to run the ball on seven consecutive plays, driving
Dallas from its 19 to the Arizona 17. After a 10-yard holding
penalty, Garrett connected with Mills for 16 yards, then hit David
LaFleur with an 11-yard touchdown pass for a 7-0 Cowboys lead with
58 seconds remaining in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But as in their other losses this season, when they got to the
second half, the Cowboys stopped doing what they do best. Smith,
running with a padded glove to protect his broken right hand, had
racked up 83 yards on 18 carries by halftime. He carried only twice
in the third quarter as the Cowboys ran seven passing plays
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my job to question,'' Smith said when asked why the
Cowboys seemingly abandoned their ground game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' first scoring opportunity came late in the first
half when they pinned the Cowboys deep in their own territory, then
took possession at the Dallas 37. The Cowboys held them to a
24-yard field goal by Chris Jacke, who later added a 38-yarder
early in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The only Arizona touchdown came on the first drive of the second
half as Rob Moore escaped Sanders and George Teague to score from
21 yards out on a flea-flicker pass from Dave Brown. It capped a
four-play, 69-yard drive, the Cardinals' longest of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' only other points came on a safety that was
deliberately allowed by the Cardinals late in the fourth quarter
when two points weren't going to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players have been in the position we were in so many times
in the last four years. I don't think they panicked at halftime,''
Arizona coach Vince Tobin said. ``They realized here was a football
team that was very beatable today.''
</P>
<P>
   And beatable every time they venture outside of Texas Stadium,
it would seem. The Cowboys have won only one game outside Texas
this year, that being the season opener in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, you have to be a good road team to be a Super
Bowl team,'' Woodson said. ``I know in '92 and '93, we won a lot of
road games. We dominated on the road. Right now, we're not playing
that way. We haven't played like that in the last two or three
years. We're just not a good road team right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 0212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
