<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     11-22 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT has come to this. After the Nets lost another game Saturday
night, mercifully keeping them to the rear of the Rockets in the
NBA standings, Stephon Marbury's mother sternly berated her
offspring within earshot of lingering media types.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase, Mom was telling Stephon to get his head up and
stop acting like the bunch of losers with whom he shares a locker
room. Noticing the eavesdroppers and their poised notebooks, she
turned and redirected her lecture: ``This team is burning (my son)
out and I don't want my son burned out. Write that!''
</P>
<P>
   You bet they did. When Mother speaks, you listen.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there's a place for her in David Stern's office because
the entire league, not just the sorry-as-ever Nets, needs a
tongue-lashing. Besides admonishing the multimillionaire players
for not caring, she could get in the megamillionaire owners' faces
for their predictably shameless avarice, not to mention for
delivering unto the increasingly apathetic/fed-up public a product
that's 75 percent packaging and 25 percent substance.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been to Compaq Center since the Rockets' hellbound
season began, you know what I'm talking about. All the
bells-and-whistles theatrics ring hollow _ it's almost silly,
really _ with so many empty seats and such desultory play on the
floor. Even Turbo's trampoline dunks elicit mostly been-there,
seen-that yawns.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, not the sideshow, must carry the night. And at
present their games wouldn't be decent value for half of what you
pay to watch them.
</P>
<P>
   But Houston isn't a glaring exception to the norm in the NBA to
date. Fan-tastic? Phooey. While quality plummets, costs soar.
Ticket prices, on average, are up close to 14 percent around the
league. It requires nearly $270 to drag a family of four to a game,
if you factor in minimal purchases at the concession stand plus a
couple of souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the NBA, good grief, is intended for families anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But suckers are no longer born every minute, in Houston or
elsewhere. The Rockets' drop in attendance _ after 176 consecutive
sellouts, they are 2-for-6 so far _ has been mirrored league-wide.
Except for the four teams playing in new arenas plus Minnesota and
Sacramento, whose figures are padded by humongous gates in Tokyo,
only two franchises have managed what could be considered
meaningful increases.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason Cleveland is up 11.5 percent, and 10-1 Portland,
for obvious reasons, is up 10.4 percent. But the most amazing
number is that the Bulls are down just 1.1 percent. Apparently, a
candle burns in the United Center window for M.J.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a candle should burn in every arena for Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of it's the Jordan effect continuing,'' suggests
Brandon Steiner, a sports marketing specialist in New York. ``You
have to have a couple must-see guys to fuel the league, and you
don't have that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, about 1,000 tickets fewer per game are being sold
around the league if the aberrant statistics are discounted. Were
the trend to continue through the end of the season, such a decline
would result in about $2 million less in revenues per club. After
two decades of continuous growth, the post-lockout NBA is facing
back-to-back attendance drops for the first time in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their world championship, the Spurs have shown a
14.5-percent decrease. Boston shows promise and plays an exciting
style, yet the FleetCenter has been 11 percent emptier than a year
ago. Seven teams are down at least 10 percent, led by the Nets'
drop of nearly 20 percent. Although Atlanta, ensconced in a new
palace, is up 13 percent, 5,500 seats went unsold with faceless
Orlando in town on a Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Could Hawks fans possibly be less than enthralled with the
uplifting presence of Isaiah Rider in their midst?
</P>
<P>
   Could Leslie Alexander actually be interested in trading for
Rider? We hear rumors. Boy, that would fire up you folks and make
you want to drag the kiddies down to the gym.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the spectrum, the Clippers have realized
a whopping 65-percent increase after moving into the Staples Center
with the Lakers, but they average about 7,000 under capacity. The
glamour-puss Lakers have realized an 11-percent gain with the new
digs and a gaudy coaching hire in Phil Jackson, but they are close
to 1,000 empty seats shy of being SRO.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA, of course, professes a haughty disregard for the
evidence presented here and, for the record, insists there's
nothing to be concerned about, not in the least. Nero lives in the
smug personage of the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Stern could use a stern talking-to from Stephon's mother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
