<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 03:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7378 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-NEWHAMPSHIRE-PRIMARY-     11-22 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWHAMPSHIRE-PRIMARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY CHANGES TONE OF NEW HAMPSHIRE PRIMARY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Moose-crossing signs still line the freeways that
roll through densely wooded mountains and hardscrabble farmland.
But developments along the information superhighway are giving this
tiny rural state a new identify.
</P>
<P>
   From the picturesque hamlets surrounding Nashua to the
colonial-era shipyards of Portsmouth, New Hampshire is going high
tech. The decade that began with closed mills, high unemployment
and economic stagnation is ending on an e-economy high.
</P>
<P>
   As the national political spotlight returns to the
first-in-the-nation primary state for its quadrennial presidential
sweepstakes, it will shine on an electorate that has been basking
in the prosperity of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to seeing our snow-covered villages and general
stores,'' New Hampshire Governor Jeanne .Shaheen recently boasted
to a group of visitors, ``you will see a state with the highest
percentage of high-tech workers in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer necessary for candidates to feel New
Hampshirites' pain, as Bill Clinton tried so hard to do in 1991.
Pat Buchanan's angry pitch to disenchanted ``peasants with
pitchforks'' no longer resonates as it did when he won the GOP
primary in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Those messages have been replaced by more upbeat appeals for
improving education and health care, getting money out of politics,
and an unabashed pitch to the state's technology workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not hearing those hard-core conservative views coming
out here. Even Buchanan has toned down his rhetoric,'' noted
Concord-based Republican campaign strategist Chip Griffin. ``High
tech is really shifting the demographics.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech boom is most evident in the more densely populated
southern part of the state. Attracted by New Hampshire's proximity
to mountains and the ocean, affordable housing (starter houses are
easily found for $200,000) and the lack of a state income tax,
skilled workers are moving in from congested border communities in
nearby Massachusetts as well as from the Midwest and California.
</P>
<P>
   Firms specializing in defense electronics, instrumentation,
e-commerce and emerging software have clustered along the
Interstate-93 corridor from Nashua to Manchester, and near coastal
communities such as Portsmouth. The 18-mile stretch of New
Hampshire's oceanfront often is referred to as the ``e-coast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are moving for the quality of life,'' said Jan
Schneider, a software consultant who used to travel to Boston to
find clients but now has plenty of business close to her New
Hampshire home.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton first ran for president, the state of 1.2 million
people had lost about 59,000 jobs and was in the depths of a
recession. Eight years later, the state has regained those jobs and
added an additional 33,000, according to the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 1,000 software companies in the state. The
concentration of high-tech workers is three times higher than the
national average. Venture capital is readily available.
Unemployment is close to 2 percent, and the poverty rate is the
nation's lowest.
</P>
<P>
   There is still evidence of the state's famed conservative and
fiercely libertarian character. The Manchester Union Leader, the
state's largest paper, prints a daily prayer _ and occasionally its
conservative editorials _ on the front page.
</P>
<P>
   The state is 97 percent white and overwhelmingly Protestant. One
of its senators, Bob Smith, recently quit the Republican Party
after accusing leaders of abandoning their conservative principles.
When Smith returned to the party several months later, some New
Hampshirites congratulated him for having taught the party a
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the changes are unmistakable. There are now as
many registered independents as Republicans. Shaheen, a Democrat,
was elected the state's first female governor three years ago, and
she has signed measures prohibiting discrimination against gays and
permitting gay adoption. In the name of better schools, the state
Legislature came close last month to enacting what once had been
considered the ultimate New Hampshire taboo _ a state income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the economy of the state and the profile of the
state has changed in the past 10 years,'' Shaheen said in an
interview. ``And that has an effect on everything from the jobs in
the state to growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Demographic changes in a place with a population scarcely larger
than Santa Clara County would not be of national consequence were
it not for its February 1 primary, which gives the state a
disproportionate influence. Here, where only one president has been
elected in the past half century without first winning the primary
(Bill Clinton in 1992), every development is magnified.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom is that the strong independent vote
favors Democrat Bill Bradley and Republican John McCain. Although
none of the leading candidates holds a big advantage on tech
issues, Bradley and McCain both have exhibited strength among
nonaffiliated voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both impress me as least susceptible to campaign slush
money'' said software entrepreneur David Hallenbeck, a registered
independent and transplant from the Midwest. ``After the past few
years in Washington, they seem refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallenbeck is typical of the new breed of New Hampshire voter.
He supports Republicans on many issues but shuns the social
conservatism of candidates like Steve Forbes or Gary Bauer.
Independents are free to vote in either party's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth professor James Shoch, who moved to New Hampshire
after spending 20 years in the Bay Area, said the new tech workers
``tend to be much more upscale, better educated and more white
collar'' than the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Added University of New Hampshire business Professor Ross
Gittell: ``These aren't liberals, but they aren't
arch-conservatives either. You're not getting the same people who
live in Berkeley or Cambridge, but it's far more diversified in
terms of the political spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns are doing what they can to take advantage of the
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is to go after independents as hard as we can,''
said Mike Dennehy, McCain's New England political director. Rather
than dwelling on matters such as job loss and economic assistance,
``the issues that are resonating are campaign finance reform and
health care,'' said Sue Calegari, who is running Bradley's New
Hampshire effort. ``Pat Buchanan was really appealing to people who
were angry. This campaign is very different now that we are in a
strong economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, McCain, who boasts his technology record as
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, unabashedly courted
software executives in Nashua. (``Politicians are given to great
hyperbole,'' McCain said, ``but the fact is that what is happening
in America can only be compared to the invention of the printing
press or the industrial revolution. ... I'd like to congratulate
you for being a part of this exciting technology, which is changing
America.'')
</P>
<P>
   Bush has scheduled a New Hampshire ``high-tech day'' for next
month. Gore used a New Hampshire forum to make a significant tech
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It focuses our message on the new economy,'' said Gore
campaign spokesman Doug Hattaway, who noted that the emphasis is
not confined to the southern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent campaign swing through a remote corner of this
wooded state, Vice President Al Gore sat in a living room with a
dozen New Hampshirites in the timber town of Berlin (motto: ``The
Town That Trees Built'').
</P>
<P>
   ``This was definitely moose country,'' Hattaway recalled. ``This
was a part of the state that has not benefited as much from the
economic expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   And what was the top concern in moose country? A high-speed
Internet hookup, of course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
