</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 28)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MISTLER'S EXIT &LR;  By Louis Begley. Fawcett/Ballantine, $12. In
this dark novel by an author long preoccupied by the falsification
of the self, a rich executive who can't, or won't, separate his
truth from his lies escapes to Venice after learning he has
terminal cancer. ``The theme of self-deception at the end of life
... may be the supreme test for a novelist with this of all
obsessions,'' Jack Miles wrote in The New York Times Book Review in
1998. ```Mistler's Exit' meets the test.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TIME OF OUR TIME &LR;  By Norman Mailer. Modern Library, $24.95.
Not surprisingly, this bulky retrospective of Mailer's work since
he kicked things off in 1948 with ``The Naked and the Dead'' shrugs
off conventional literary form; instead of organizing the
selections chronologically or thematically, the author arranges
them based on the period they describe. The resulting grab bag of
hits and misses is ``that rarity, an anthology that can be read
straight through,'' James Shapiro wrote in The New York Times Book
Review last year. ``Its neatly interwoven sections collectively
tell a story of their own, a social history of postwar America, at
the heart of which is Mailer's own tangled love affair with this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAKFAST ON PLUTO &LR;  By Patrick McCabe. HarperPerennial, $13.
Patrick ``Pussy'' Braden is an effusively cheerful Irish
transvestite with a temper, looking for love in a London paralyzed
by IRA bombings during the swinging '70s. This novel by ``a master
of the literary macabre'' may be ``the most successful book yet to
be born'' out of the Troubles in Northern Ireland, Courtney Weaver
wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THE WHEREABOUTS OF ENEAS McNULTY &LR; , by Sebastian Barry
(Penguin, $12.95), a patriotic out-of-work Irishman joins the Royal
Irish Constabulary after World War I and finds himself marked for
death by his boyhood friend, an enforcer for the IRA. Throughout
his hero's travails, ``Barry's sweet, lyrical pitch never
falters,'' Aoibheann Sweeney wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I WILL BEAR WITNESS: A Diary of the Nazi Years, 1933-1941 &LR;  By
Victor Klemperer. Modern Library, $14.95. In this intensely German
insider account of the Nazi tyranny, a Jewish-born Protestant
professor tells of Hitler's escalating persecution of the Jews and
of the many episodes of cruelty, cowardice and decency he
encountered in his daily life. The result is ``a fascinating
self-portrait and an equally fascinating portrait of a regime whose
consequences haunt the world to this day,'' Peter Gay wrote in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; OFFICIAL SECRETS: What the Nazis Planned, What the British
and Americans Knew &LR; , by Richard Breitman (Hill &AMP; Wang, $13), a
history professor argues that the British government knew more
about the Holocaust than they let on. Breitman ``weaves solid new
scholarship into a gripping narrative that reveals a startling
nonchalance in facing evil,'' Peter Grose wrote earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MACHINE DREAMS &LR;  By Jayne Anne Phillips. Vintage Contemporaries,
$14. The author's first novel explores the private legends of a
small-town American family, as expressed by each of its members.
The shocking moments arise from small, ordinary ones. In 1984 the
reviewer Anne Tyler called Phillips ``an assured and gifted
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WIDOW'S CHILDREN &LR;  By Paula Fox. Norton, $13. The widow in
this novel dies in a nursing home while her middle-aged children,
only one of whom learns of her death, are holding a family reunion
of sorts in which feelings of resentment and hostility boil over.
In 1976, Norma Rosen admired Fox's ``special brand of unemphatic,
perceptively detailed writing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLIND MAN'S BLUFF: The Untold Story of American Submarine
Espionage &LR;  By Sherry Sontag and Christopher Drew, with Annette
Lawrence Drew. HarperPaperbacks, $7.99. Sontag is an investigative
journalist, Christopher Drew is a reporter at The New York Times,
and Annette Lawrence Drew is a researcher. Together hey explore the
history of underwater spying during the Cold War. In 1998 the
reviewer Timothy Naftali called this an ``important look'' at one
of the ``most harrowing battlefields of the superpower conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; APPALACHIA &LR;  By Charles Wright. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $12.
The Pulitzer Prize-winning poet's 13th volume reveals a yearning
for mystical or religious transcendence. Earlier this year the
reviewer Adam Kirsch called Wright's self-reflective, questioning
verse ``a significant and true reflection of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEN MINDED: Working Out the Logic of the Soul &LR;  By Jonathan
Lear. Harvard University, $15.95. A psychoanalyst and philosopher
issues a defense of Freud, arguing that democratic societies need
Freudian insights to comprehend the dark side of the psyche in
order to make the best-informed choices. The result is ``a
remarkable book _ highly articulate, learned, thoughtful and
fresh,'' Mark Edmundson wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ACHESON: The Secretary of State Who Created the American World &LR; 
By James Chace. Harvard University, $17.95. This biography portrays
Dean Acheson, the secretary of state from 1949 to 1953, as a
visionary public servant who laid the groundwork for today's
international order. Last year the reviewer Francis Fukuyama found
the book to be ``engrossingly good reading.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
