<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7492 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-CHINA-TRADE-REVIEW-     11-22 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CHINA-TRADE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE GIANT STEP FOR JIANG'S CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Only a few weeks ago, after the uninspired 50th
anniversary extravaganza for the People's Republic that equated
President Jiang Zemin with Mao Tse-tung and Deng Xiaoping, Jiang
became a victim of Beijing's merciless joke circuit. In stories
told in quiet tea houses and at raucous dinner parties _ the
nearest thing here to Jay Leno's monologues as an index of
political fortunes _ Jiang was portrayed as lacking the vision and
stature that this foundering country needs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most-repeated jokes imagined the president's thoughts
during the anniversary parade. He looks to the north, the story
goes, and sees millions of unemployed workers. He looks to the
south and sees millions of prostitutes. He looks to the east and
sees the vast smuggling of goods and he looks to the west and sees
ethnic rebellions. He looks to the sky and sees NATO bombs falling,
then he looks down and finds himself surrounded by Falun Gong
demonstrators intent on continuing their spiritual movement.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang walks to the Mao mausoleum to ask the Great Helmsman's
advice. After hearing all the woes, Mao rises up from his crypt and
says, ``You'd better lie down here, I'll take charge.''
</P>
<P>
   They weren't telling that one any more last week, after Jiang
and his fellow party chiefs signed a trade deal with America that
seemed breathtaking in its implications and anything but lacking in
vision. After months of speculation that conservative,
protectionist forces were gaining the upper hand, China made
sweeping commitments to slash barriers to trade and foreign
investment and to accept international rules governing these
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese experts even compared the agreement, which
Americans demanded in return for supporting the country's entry
into the World Trade Organization, to Deng Xiaoping's momentous
``opening and reform'' of the late 1970s, when he cast aside Mao's
screwball economics and introduced market incentives.
</P>
<P>
   China's signature Monday showed that Jiang, and most if not all
of the other six Communist Party leaders who make major decisions
here, are convinced that radical change is the only hope if China
is to attain long-term prosperity and greatness. Since these seven
men, who serve on the all-powerful politburo standing committee,
are also politicians, they are most likely making this risky leap
in the belief that it is the only way to save the party's monopoly
on power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sort of pact with the devil,'' said Andrew J. Nathan, a
political scientist at Columbia University. ``You compromise on
some aspects of social and economic control, and hope you can keep
political control.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the risks are obvious. Wringing out the state sector and
creating competitive companies, as China hopes to do as a member of
the World Trade Organization, should eventually bring about a
richer, more efficient country. But the lower agricultural tariffs
China agreed to last week will mean a ``blood bath'' for farmers,
as a Western economist said here, forcing more migrants into cities
where they will compete with laid-off factory workers for jobs. In
urban areas, freer trade and investment will cause temporary
dislocations as leaner, technologically advanced foreign companies
wipe out bloated domestic ones.
</P>
<P>
   Even without foreign competition, angry workers and farmers have
protested often enough to put the government on edge. Leaders and
citizens alike know that, at this point in Communist rule,
political obedience depends on the party's ability to deliver
greater wealth.
</P>
<P>
   For the party, there is also a deeper long-term risk. From
President Clinton to eternally hopeful liberals inside China, some
openly voiced the thesis last week that an influx of foreign
companies, and the enforced discipline of global trade rules, will
promote the rule of law and prod along political change.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts think, too, that a growing middle class that owns
homes and businesses and pays taxes will demand a greater voice in
government, and form interest groups outside party control. In the
last two decades, the Mao era's grip over personal decisions like
how and where to live and work has greatly weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Fair and predictable enforcement of rules, in business and
throughout society, will certainly improve daily life and aid
China's development. But this is already a prime goal of the
Communist Party leaders, who know that widespread corruption and
arbitrary decisions are corroding the last remnants of popular
faith. In the battle against corrupt provincial and local officials
and in their efforts to build a trimmer, better-educated
bureaucracy, the leaders hope to gain efficiency and also bolster
the party's rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese leaders clearly don't embrace the theory that
political change is inevitable,'' said Nathan. ``They intend to
keep a monopoly on political power while still opening the economy.
They no longer insist on compete control over everything because
they realize they don't need it.''
</P>
<P>
   The global corporations speak in evangelical terms about their
ultimate impact on society, but they are in China for one reason _
to make money. Their greatest need is clear rules, predictability
and social stability. It may well be, as U.S. diplomats argue,
that, as society becomes more sophisticated and diverse, a
political opening will be vital to preserving stability. But it may
also be that political change, when it happens, will not come
smoothly or peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the rest of the world might do well to assume
that Jiang and his comrades know more about how to survive as
Communist Party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   When all is said and done, common sense suggests that the
expanding flow of information _ now aided by the Internet, a true
devil with which the Communists feel they must consort _ will
create deep and unsettling consequences. Monday's pact should
accelerate this subversive exchange of facts and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the mythical patience of the Chinese, politicians
here have to worry a lot more about tomorrow than about the next
year, or the next decade. With his bold promise last week to
embrace the modern world, Jiang has given the Chinese people hopes
and dreams that may sustain them for a while. If all the
contradictions come crashing together one day, well, he is gambling
that may be on someone else's watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 0940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
