</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-POLLING-APATHY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF A POLL FALLS IN THE FOREST AND NO ONE HEARS IT ... 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(sidebar with POLLING-RELIABILITY-REVIEW) 
(bl) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There was lots of news on the campaign trail last
week, from Texas Gov. George W. Bush's foreign policy debut to new
polls in New Hampshire showing a tightening horse race in both
parties. But is anyone paying attention, beyond the rapt little
world of journalists, consultants and political groupies?
</P>
<P>
   A new survey suggests that most Americans are not. When people
weren't prompted with a list of candidates, which is routinely done
in political polls, nearly two-thirds said they did not have a
favorite. More than 8 in 10 did not know whether former Sen. Bill
Bradley advocated government-paid health insurance for low-income
people. (He does.) Nearly 8 in 10 had no idea whether Sen. John
McCain supported or opposed an overhaul of the campaign finance
system. (He supports it.)
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two-thirds said they found the previous campaign week
``boring,'' and only a quarter found it ``informative,'' according
to the poll, which was conducted Nov. 10 to 14 for Harvard's
Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The public is rarely engaged in a presidential campaign this
early, but many experts warn that Americans are growing
increasingly detached from the political process in more
fundamental ways. Turnout in the 1998 midterm elections was 36.06
percent, the lowest level since 1942, when millions of Americans
were away at war, according to Curtis Gans, an analyst with the
Committee for the Study of the American Electorate. Turnout among
young people is particularly ominous: just 11 percent of 18- and
19-year-olds voted in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is longstanding _ in the 1960 presidential election,
62.8 percent of the voting age population turned out; in 1996, 49
percent did _ and has to do with sweeping changes in American
society, Gans argues.
</P>
<P>
   These include the loss of public trust in politicians during the
Vietnam and Watergate years; the rise of an often corrosive new
campaign technology; the creation of ``something beyond
skepticism,'' as Gans puts it, among the journalists who report
about politics; and a decline in basic civic values that becomes
self-perpetuating.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some analysts say, the 2000 campaign has the potential
to feed this disaffection. Front-runners have been declared and
fields winnowed, largely on the basis of fund-raising prowess,
while most Americans were looking elsewhere, underscoring the image
of politics as an insiders game. And ahead lies a primary and
caucus schedule so compressed that it could well pass most voters
in a confusing blur.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways to engage voters, as debates have done in the
general election, says Thomas Patterson, a Harvard professor and
co-director of the Shorenstein Center poll, the first in a series
called the Vanishing Voter Project. But changing political
calendars and campaigns is notoriously hard, and renowned for
unintended consequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 0948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
