</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Build a Better Mouse, and . . . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is death inevitable? Biologists who study aging are beginning to
suspect that the final curtain may at least be postponable. The raw
material of living cells is very robust. It is just that the
evolutionary forces that shape it have no incentive to make a
mouse, say, live forever, when hawks, cats and disease will let the
luckiest mouse survive for only a year or so.
</P>
<P>
   Now Italian researchers report they have made mice live 30
percent longer than usual by deleting part of a gene. The gene
makes a protein with a deadly role. When cells are damaged by free
radicals, dangerous chemicals generated by ordinary metabolism, the
protein triggers a self-destruct mechanism that forces the stricken
cell to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   This hair-trigger response must benefit animals during
development because it zaps any cell in danger of becoming
cancerous. But the organs of older animals may start to run out of
spare cells, and could probably make good use of the slightly
damaged cells killed off by the trigger protein. That is presumably
why the Italian mice genetically incapable of making the protein
lived longer.
</P>
<P>
   People have a version of the gene the Italians manipulated.
Experts say it should be fairly easy to make a drug that inhibits
the trigger protein made by the gene.
</P>
<P>
   So will that bump the average life span to 100? Doubtless some
Catch-22 will emerge to thwart this scheme, but it is surely
comforting to know someone is working on the death problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   History Stumbles Again &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's a one-sentence history of the American West in the late
1800s? The politically correct answer, of course, is that the white
man came in and wrecked everything.
</P>
<P>
   Is it true? Well, yes and no. There can be little doubt of the
horrors visited upon American Indians by expansion-minded folks
from across the Mississippi. But what of that other staple of
Western lore _ the near-extinction of the noble buffalo, symbol of
all that is rugged, shaggy and free, by greedy white hunters? It
might be time to rethink that one.
</P>
<P>
   New studies suggest other culprits. First, a centuries-long cold
snap ended about 1850 _ weather that had nourished the grass that
buffaloes eat. Home on the range was also home, by mid-century, to
some 2 million horses, descendants of a long-ago gift of the
Spaniards. The grazing wasn't easy. And Indians, once they had
guns, hunted countless buffaloes themselves.
</P>
<P>
   White hunters  &UR; did &LR;  do their part, slaughtering millions of
buffaloes in the 1870s and 1880s, but many historians now say this
was merely the final blow _ the buffalo was already doomed.
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Movement Toward Peace In Northern Ireland
</P>
<P>
   The politicians of Northern Ireland have never had problems
talking. For five years they have been at it, in marathon
negotiating sessions seeking a lasting peace plan. But this time
the words were different _ conciliatory, accommodating and thought
out _ where before they had always been obdurate, insulting and
impulsive.
</P>
<P>
   First George Mitchell, the former U.S. senator turned Ulster
mediator, spoke, then John de Chastelain, a retired Canadian
general who heads a panel on disarmament, then David Trimble,
leader of the Ulster Unionists, and his rival party leader, Sinn
Fein's Gerry Adams, and finally _ and most important _ the Irish
Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   The choreographed statements proposed a series of interlocking
steps that would allow the start-up of a new Northern Ireland
government and the simultaneous appointment of an IRA officer as a
representative to the disarmament panel. The formula seeks to get
around a stalemate over guerrilla weapons that has stalled progress
in putting the April 1998 peace settlement into operation.
</P>
<P>
   If Trimble can get backing for the deal at a party meeting in
Belfast next weekend, the new Ulster home rule government, with its
powers divided evenly between Protestants and Catholics, could be
up and running just days later.
</P>
<P>
   _ WARREN HOGE
</P>
<P>
   Air Crash Sets Off An Ambiguous Probe
</P>
<P>
   An informal axiom among aviation investigators is that if you
don't know the reason for a crash within the first three days, you
are in for a long haul. But three weeks after Egyptair 990 plunged
toward the water so fast that people inside were weightless,
investigators cannot demonstrate why _ although some theorized from
cockpit conversations that a reserve pilot may have intentionally
set the plane on its plunge toward the sea.
</P>
<P>
   So the investigators laid out a plan that will take weeks or
months to raise a substantial part of the Boeing 767 from more than
250 feet of water, twice as deep as Swissair 111 or TWA 800. The
flight data recorder shows a plane that flew ``straight as an
arrow,'' as one crash specialist put it, until it plunged, but the
cockpit voice recorder is ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   Every crash yields new safety measures, and one has already been
proposed for this crash: adding cameras to the microphones and data
recorders that monitor cockpits.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   A Campus Accident Kills 11
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of a giant wooden tower intended for Texas A&AMP;M
University's annual football bonfire left 11 students dead and much
of Texas in mourning. In a university steeped in traditions, the
bonfire was one of the most revered, marking the annual football
game against the rival University of Texas. The school canceled
this year's Thanksgiving night bonfire, and officials planned to
reconsider the event.
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM YARDLEY
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Decides to Pay Up
</P>
<P>
   The White House and House Republicans struck a deal to repay
nearly $1 billion that the United States owes the United Nations,
ending a three-year battle that had begun to jeopardize
Washington's vote in the General Assembly. The dues were freed
after President Clinton agreed to a Republican demand to halt
federal financing to international groups that promote abortion
rights overseas.
</P>
<P>
   _ ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Takes Some Blame
</P>
<P>
   Four years after the fall of the Bosnian town of Srebrenica,
followed by a Serbian massacre of many of its Muslim residents, the
United Nations issued an exhaustive report on the debacle, taking
much of the blame on itself for trying to be evenhanded in dealing
with the two sides in the civil war. But the report also laid the
groundwork for the tragedy at the feet of the Security Council, led
by the United States, which failed to authorize enough troops to
defend Srebrenica or other ``safe havens'' in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   General Pays a Price For Adultery
</P>
<P>
   In its most severe punishment to date for adultery, the Army
stripped a general of his two stars and forced him into retirement
as a colonel for having affairs with the wives of two subordinates.
Maj. Gen. John Maher, who had been a vice director for the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, was demoted following an administrative hearing in
Georgia where the general was found guilty of conduct unbecoming an
officer. The cost is high: with the demotion, Maher's annual
pension will be reduced by $18,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ ELIZABETH BECKER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A Notorious Drug Is Back, but with Benign Intent
</P>
<P>
   Thalidomide, the notorious sedative that maimed thousands of
babies in the 1960s, may well be the wonder drug of the 1990s. It
won approval last year for treatment of leprosy, and has shown
promise in AIDS. Now scientists at the University of Arkansas have
announced a new use for it, as a treatment for multiple myeloma, a
rare bone cancer. They tested thalidomide at the urging of a New
York lawyer whose husband was dying of myeloma. It didn't help him,
but one-third of 84 patients who had failed to respond to other
therapies improved, and two went into complete remission.
</P>
<P>
   _ SHERYL GAY STOLBERG
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   New Round in ATM Wars  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Banks won a victory in their effort to stamp out a spreading
uprising against fees charged for use of automated teller machines.
A federal judge in California, saying such regulation is the
purview of the federal government, blocked San Francisco and Santa
Monica from enforcing the nation's first two local laws banning
such surcharges. But with the fees having touched a public nerve,
the issue is not likely to die. For example, New York City Council
Speaker Peter Vallone said he intended to press ahead to enact a
similar ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANDREW POLLACK
</P>
<P>
   Clinton at Quake Sites
</P>
<P>
   Still reeling from the effects of two strong earthquakes in
three months, Turkey gave a warm welcome to President Clinton when
he arrived three days before a summit meeting in Istanbul of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe and spent the
time touring the country.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, a devastating quake killed more than 17,000
people in northwestern Turkey. Three days before Clinton arrived,
another struck the same region and left more than 675 dead.
</P>
<P>
   On his tour, the president left behind hosts of admirers, some
awed by the emotion he seemed to show while visiting earthquake
survivors and others impressed by his clear advocacy of greater
political freedom there.
</P>
<P>
   Then he traveled on to Greece, where violent protests against
his visit were staged. Many Greeks believe Clinton is guilty of
crimes against Serbia, which they consider a friendly neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEPHEN KINZER
</P>
<P>
   A Civil Rights Hero Loses a Lawsuit
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Parks was voted a medal by Congress last spring for having
helped launch the civil rights movement by refusing to move to the
back of a bus in Montgomery, Ala., in 1955. But when Outkast, a rap
group, put her name on a song containing expletives and racial
epithets, she sued in federal court, contending that her name was
being exploited for commercial gain. A judge ruled against her,
finding that the First Amendment protected the group.
</P>
<P>
   _ KEITH BRADSHER
</P>
<P>
   Congress Passes a Budget
</P>
<P>
   Fifty days after the new fiscal year began, Congress completed
work on a budget that totals about $610 billion. For the second
consecutive year, the budget broke the spending limits that
lawmakers had set for themselves. It includes $17 billion more for
the military and $2.3 billion more for medical research than last
year, even as it frees money to pay $351 million of $926 million in
back dues to the United Nations and offers 41 of the world's
poorest countries some relief from their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had sought the military and medical research funds,
while President Clinton had sought the U.N. and debt relief money.
Clinton also is getting most of the funds he sought for hiring
primary school teachers and local police officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
