<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Build a Better Mouse, and . . . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is death inevitable? Biologists who study aging are beginning to
suspect that the final curtain may at least be postponable. The raw
material of living cells is very robust. It is just that the
evolutionary forces that shape it have no incentive to make a
mouse, say, live forever, when hawks, cats and disease will let the
luckiest mouse survive for only a year or so.
</P>
<P>
   Now Italian researchers report they have made mice live 30
percent longer than usual by deleting part of a gene. The gene
makes a protein with a deadly role. When cells are damaged by free
radicals, dangerous chemicals generated by ordinary metabolism, the
protein triggers a self-destruct mechanism that forces the stricken
cell to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   This hair-trigger response must benefit animals during
development because it zaps any cell in danger of becoming
cancerous. But the organs of older animals may start to run out of
spare cells, and could probably make good use of the slightly
damaged cells killed off by the trigger protein. That is presumably
why the Italian mice genetically incapable of making the protein
lived longer.
</P>
<P>
   People have a version of the gene the Italians manipulated.
Experts say it should be fairly easy to make a drug that inhibits
the trigger protein made by the gene.
</P>
<P>
   So will that bump the average life span to 100? Doubtless some
Catch-22 will emerge to thwart this scheme, but it is surely
comforting to know someone is working on the death problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   History Stumbles Again &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's a one-sentence history of the American West in the late
1800s? The politically correct answer, of course, is that the white
man came in and wrecked everything.
</P>
<P>
   Is it true? Well, yes and no. There can be little doubt of the
horrors visited upon American Indians by expansion-minded folks
from across the Mississippi. But what of that other staple of
Western lore _ the near-extinction of the noble buffalo, symbol of
all that is rugged, shaggy and free, by greedy white hunters? It
might be time to rethink that one.
</P>
<P>
   New studies suggest other culprits. First, a centuries-long cold
snap ended about 1850 _ weather that had nourished the grass that
buffaloes eat. Home on the range was also home, by mid-century, to
some 2 million horses, descendants of a long-ago gift of the
Spaniards. The grazing wasn't easy. And Indians, once they had
guns, hunted countless buffaloes themselves.
</P>
<P>
   White hunters  &UR; did &LR;  do their part, slaughtering millions of
buffaloes in the 1870s and 1880s, but many historians now say this
was merely the final blow _ the buffalo was already doomed.
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Movement Toward Peace In Northern Ireland
</P>
<P>
   The politicians of Northern Ireland have never had problems
talking. For five years they have been at it, in marathon
