<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7530 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-PUNDIT-CENTRAL-SLATE     11-22 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUNDIT-CENTRAL-SLATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNDIT CENTRAL: DUBYA MEETS THE PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Slate commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL BRUS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his first weekend talk show appearance -- on NBC's ``Meet the
Press'' -- George W. Bush touched on foreign policy, health care,
Social Security and sex education, among ther issues.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, he said the Somalia and Haiti invasions would
not have happened under his watch. When host Tim Russert reminded
him that his father had initiated the Somalia intervention, George
W. simply reasserted that he would not intervene on humanitarian
grounds, except in rare circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Bush went out of his way to emphasize the need for a ``theater
antimissile defense system'' -- both for the U.S. and Taiwan. He
downplayed the importance of arms control, stressing instead the
need for nonproliferation, antimissile systems and the safe storage
of existing nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged to increase military salaries and military R&AMP;D
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Clinton administration had been too supportive of
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, Bush replied cryptically, ``That's
going to be an interesting debate in the fall campaign if I'm the
nominee, let me just put it to you that way. We'll find out about
Victor Chernomyrdin and the (U.S.) vice president and the
relationship they have.''
</P>
<P>
   On health care, Bush supported allowing a patient to sue her HMO
if an independent review board decided she had a reasonable
dispute. (This position is more lawsuit-friendly than the House GOP
leadership.)
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Social Security, George W. indicated a willingness
to raise the current benefit-receiving age. (Responding to Bush on
CNN's ``Late Edition,'' Steve Forbes advocated transforming Social
Security into ``personal savings accounts,'' which would allow
recipients to choose their own retirement age.)
</P>
<P>
   When Russert read a Naomi Wolf quote advocating that sex
education instructors promote fondling and mutual masturbation as
an alternative to sex, Bush said Wolf's advice was ``pathetic,''
said condom promotion hadn't decreased teen pregnancy rates, and
advocated teaching abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   Many pundits -- such as Tucker Carlson (``Late Edition''), Bob
Novak (CNN's ``Capital Gang,'' and Mark Shields (``Capital Gang'')
-- felt that the GOP caved to the Democrats on important budget
issues, like tax cuts and across-the-board spending cuts. Paul
Gigot (PBS's ``NewsHour With Jim Lehrer'') noted that spending in
this year's budget had grown at twice the rate of inflation since
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But some, such as Kate O'Beirne (``Capital Gang'') argued that
Republicans reined in the Clinton administration's spending
requests, kept Social Security funds intact, and prevented the
subsidization of international abortion providers through the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Most pundits continued to be pessimistic about Hillary Clinton's
chances against New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. Al Hunt (``Capital
Gang'') said her campaign needs a James Carville figure to rev
things up, and Mark Shields (``Capital Gang'') said she had an
uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos (ABC's ``This Week'') said focus groups
show that the voters wish there were different candidates running.
O'Beirne predicted Hillary will drop out of the race and wondered
how she'll ever be able to run for president if she can't win New
York.
</P>
<P>
   But several shows flashed the results of a New York Post poll
showing Clinton only seven points behind Giuliani; Bill Kristol
(``This Week'') noted that seven points behind--one year before the
election in a Democratic state--is not exactly the kiss of death.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Fox News Sunday,'' Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., said
Hillary had ``raised more funds than any candidate for any office
in the nation other than president.''
</P>
<P>
   Both ``This Week'' and ``Late Edition'' reviewed a new Bush
campaign commercial in which George W. pledges to ``restore
dignity'' to the presidency. Kristol noted that the message is not
just anti-Clinton, but also aimed at stealing some of John McCain's
patriotic thunder. Steve Roberts (``Late Edition'') felt that Bush
was alluding to his family's history of honorable public service.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   Visit Slate on the Web at: http://www.slate.com
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1999 Slate
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
