<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stand up for nerd gear, Al Gore!
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ As if he hasn't caught enough ridicule for
his unfortunate choice of image advisers, Vice President Al Gore
now is being razzed for his hand-held computer. It's so unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Most accounts of Gore opening his headquarters in Nashville,
Tenn.,
</P>
<P>
   mentioned it, at least in passing, as a quirky detail on a
person
</P>
<P>
   maddeningly free of quirky details. The Washington Post noted
the
</P>
<P>
   accessory under the headline: ``Nerd Alert?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were dubious about the earth-toned suit at the New
Hampshire
</P>
<P>
   debate, and now we're starting to wonder about the Palm Pilot
Vice
</P>
<P>
   President Gore insists on clipping to his belt,'' the Reliable
Source
</P>
<P>
   column said. ``What's next _ a plastic pocket protector?''
</P>
<P>
   You would think we as a people would have progressed beyond such
crude cultural stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   And it is untrue on several counts. For one thing, because of
the unjust stigma they carry, it's now all but impossible to find
pocket protectors. Just try.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, palm computers are not badges of nerdhood. I
use one myself.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe a stronger counterargument is called for. I admit I
also wore a digital watch back when they were the size of hockey
pucks. But palm computers are different. Really.
</P>
<P>
   My advice to Gore is not to listen to this petty sneering. A man
with a palm computer on his belt strides with confidence. The
gizmos have a comforting feel and flip open like a communicator on
the classic episodes of ``Star Trek.'' They can do the work of a $2
road map, a 99-cent pen, a $10 clock, a $6.50 paperback, a $3
</P>
<P>
   address book, a $1.50 notepad and a 35-cent newspaper _ all in
one $180 package!
</P>
<P>
   They can hold maps, books, address books, to-do lists, e-mail,
calculators that turn miles into meters and even into microns if
you're interested (I commute 8 billion microns to work!), a chess
program that always beats me; periodic, sun, moon, tide and guitar-
</P>
<P>
   chord tables, and the U.S. Constitution, New Testament,
Shakespeare's sonnets and Tao-te Ching all displayed in tiny,
jagged letters.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Swiss Army knife of data retrieval. Nerd alert,
indeed!
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, not everyone is convinced. Even the makers of the devices
seem to be fleeing from the nerd label. Advertisements for
hand-helds show fast-lane executives and shapely women using them.
People whose lives are so fast-paced, glamorous and intense that
they require high-tech help.
</P>
<P>
   It's as though they are ashamed of consumers like me, people who
use it to enter orthodontist appointments, detention schedules, car
mechanic numbers and to-do lists that chronicle the gradual
breakdown of house and garden.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their gee-whiz capabilities, the neatest thing about
palm computers is their aid to mobile and compulsive readers.
People who, if without a newspaper or book, read cereal boxes for
breakfast and the chemical makeup of sweetener packs over lunch.
</P>
<P>
   With these little computers, you can hold the equivalent of a
book bag in your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you do have to squint sometimes and the type may be little
and jiggy, but mobile readers are used to discomfort. People who
lug brick-sized books on planes and buses trade weight for
eyestrain and find it a liberating deal.
</P>
<P>
   I urge the vice president not to flee the nerd label. He should
keep the Palm Pilot on his belt and use it to record the name of
anyone who laughs.
</P>
<P>
   This nation has a proud history of nerd-presidents _ James
Madison, John Quincy Adams, Woodrow Wilson and Jimmy Carter all
fall into this category. Gore should lay claim to this tradition.
</P>
<P>
   By listening to his inner nerd _ and then maybe recording the
monologue on his hand-held computer _ the vice president could
attract the sizable nerd vote and project a new authenticity to
everyone else. Here is a man who doesn't try to hide his digital
watch or sensible shoes and can instantly calculate a 20 percent
tip no matter how many people are at the table.
</P>
<P>
   How can people fail to respond to that?
</P>
<P>
   Keep your portable computer strapped on, Al. The advisers who
tell you otherwise are just jealous they can't work one.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.) News-
</P>
<P>
   Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
