<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7578 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX     11-22 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coming together on `Dannsgiving'
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Invariably, when I reflect on Thanksgivings
past, my memory locks in on a unique celebration that took place
over 25 years ago in the small Georgia town my young son Kristofor
and I called home at the time.
</P>
<P>
   It was Thanksgiving eve and a group had gathered at Kate's house
for one of
</P>
<P>
   our ``just getting together for no reason'' evenings that
invariably ended up with someone playing the piano and the rest
singing show tunes and ignoring the fact that a couple of us had a
range of four notes, two of which were flat. Eventually, the
conversation switched from music to food _ as it always did.
</P>
<P>
   Dann was the first to admit he had no Thanksgiving Day plans. As
it turned
</P>
<P>
   out, neither did the rest of us. Wendell was going to eat peanut
butter and bologna and watch football games; Peggy had been
thinking about driving into Atlanta for a movie. Kate had a
brainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a commercial-size kitchen out there, and a dining table
that will
</P>
<P>
   seat all of us and then some. Be a shame to let it go to waste,
wouldn't it?'' was how she worded her invitation.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us jumped at the offer and set about planning the
menu. ``Cornbread stuffing,'' was Dann's first choice. Betty Jane
added sweet potato
</P>
<P>
   souffle to the list. We were well into the pumpkin pie before
Susan brought us up short. ``Who knows how to cook a turkey?''
</P>
<P>
   We confessed. Not one of us had ever even watched somebody else
prepare a
</P>
<P>
   turkey much less cooked one ourselves. Enthusiasm waned with the
realization there was not a real cook among us.
</P>
<P>
   We were a glum group, feeling sorrier for ourselves by the
minute, but Kate
</P>
<P>
   insisted we would not be split up for Thanksgiving dinner. We
were in this
</P>
<P>
   thing together, she said, even if it meant grilled cheese and
canned tomato soup. Kristofor said that sounded good to him, and an
idea was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not celebrate an all new kind of Thanksgiving?'' Dann
asked. ``Why don't we each cook our favorite dish in Kate's
kitchen?'' Unanimous approval and Kate even suggested we make a
list of folks who might like to join us, warning them first that
our feast would not be a traditional one.
</P>
<P>
   Hank, the town barber, was happy to be invited and said he'd
bring corn
</P>
<P>
   pudding. Mr. Johnson, a bachelor recently retired from the local
department store, volunteered to do the souffle. Carly was thrilled
to be called because she and her two sons had just moved down from
Indiana and had no family in town. She brought Waldorf salad.
Josephine signed up for gnocchi _ a recipe from her hometown in
northern Italy. And so it went. We kept calling folks until every
chair was filled _ and then some.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Jane worked on the menu and each of us made a list of the
ingredients we had on hand and what we needed from the store.
Wendell and Dann headed for Atlanta in search of an all-night
market while the rest of us dug through the pantry for linens and
dishes, silverware and candlesticks, and anything else we
</P>
<P>
   could find to lay a festive table. Way in the back of a cupboard
we found a chipped ceramic chicken that had belonged to Kate's
mother. Perfect for the centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   It was barely daybreak when we began filtering into the
old-fashioned kitchen. We helped ourselves to coffee and set to
work. There were the expected disasters _ dropped eggs, spilled
sauces, and too many cooks stumbling over one another, but by 4
o'clock that afternoon, the feast was ready and 23 diverse souls
ringed the table loaded with the fruits of a day's labor.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell prayed, and Dann proposed a toast to our originality.
</P>
<P>
   When we left Kate's later that evening, it was with far more
than a full stomach and a bowl of leftovers. In fact, we all felt
so good about our
</P>
<P>
   special holiday we renamed it in honor of its founder _
``Dannsgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
