<HEADER>
A7579 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MARS23-COX     11-22 1583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cool planet makes for a hot online topic
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Mars is just a bright dot in the sky on a starry
night, but personal computers and the Internet have brought the Red
Planet as close as your keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Most space missions now have at least one, and sometimes many,
Internet sites, and the large number of missions aimed at Mars in
recent years has caused a proliferation of sites for the fourth
rock from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   NASA, charged with an educational mission and always savvy about
marketing, has put vast quantities of information online, from raw
scientific data to glitzy pictures and animations. Private groups,
particularly the Mars Society, have used the Internet and e-mail to
reach millions of potential supporters in their grass-roots
campaigns to mount human expeditions to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, television was the medium that brought the
Apollo moon landings into our living rooms with grainy,
black-and-white, but live images of Neil Armstrong taking the first
step onto the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Today, anyone with Internet access can view the latest color
pictures from Mars orbit, click on a browsable atlas to zoom in on
almost any spot on Mars, or download 3D images of the Martian
surface.
</P>
<P>
   If mouse clicks were votes, the exploration of Mars would be an
even bigger program than Apollo. When Mars Pathfinder landed in
1997, its Internet site recorded more than 700 million visits. NASA
scrambled to set up duplicate ``mirror'' sites on servers around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   That scenario may repeat itself Dec. 3 when the Mars Polar
Lander is scheduled to touch down near Mars' South Pole. It doesn't
carry a rover, as Pathfinder did, but the polar landscape is likely
to offer surprising new scenery. Mirror sites of the polar lander
Internet site have been set up for the expected flood of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Zubrin, founder of the Mars Society and guru of the Mars
exploration movement, has used the Internet to broaden his crusade.
Downloadable slide shows are available to illustrate his plan for
sending an expedition to Mars within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Zubrin's Mars Society went from a founding convention
in August to an international organization with chapters around the
world, thanks in part to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tamarack R. Czarnik, a medical doctor in Wright State
University's aerospace medicine program, said e-mail helped him
organize the society's Ohio chapter almost immediately after the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Like the parent organization, the chapter distributes a biweekly
electronic newsletter. About 120 people around Ohio subscribe to
it, including 40 paid members, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Czarnik said the interactive nature of e-mail has spurred
involvement at the state level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not on a daily basis, but certainly on a weekly basis I get
comments from people'' who receive his newsletter, he said. He also
mails out a traditional paper version of the newsletter, but he
gets noticeably less response from that medium, he said.
</P>
<P>
   From the warmth and comfort of a home or office PC, the Martian
landscape looks almost Earth-like, with a sunny sky and rocky
terrain not unlike some areas of the American Southwest. It's hard
to imagine that the picture on your screen has come from that
little point of light in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   At its closest approach, Mars is more than 100 times farther
away than the Moon, and a round trip to Mars would take years
instead of days. Even at the speed of light, signals from Mars
probes take from three to 20 minutes to reach Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there is still a risky business, as the loss of the Mars
Climate Observer spacecraft in September demonstrated. A
miscalculation aimed it too close to Mars; instead of swinging into
orbit, it apparently plunged into the atmosphere and burned.
</P>
<P>
   The polar lander is another risky mission. Engineers recently
discovered that its descent engines, chilled after months in space,
might not work when they're needed. The engineers hope a method
they worked out to warm the engines before firing will solve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaker James Cameron, a self-declared Mars exploration
``wacko'' who is producing a TV miniseries and an IMAX film about
an expedition to Mars, fears a generation of ``Star Trek'' and
``Star Wars'' has given young people a false impression that space
travel is easy and other planets are hospitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mars is really, really far away, and it's really, really
cold,'' he reminded the crowd at Zubrin's Mars Society convention,
held at the University of Colorado in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``By showing a commonplace abundance of intelligent humanoid
aliens from all over the galaxy, and interstellar planet hopping in
a matter of days or hours, these fantasies have raised the
expectations of the youthful public to absurd heights which can
never be fulfilled by the realities of space travel,'' Cameron
said. He said his miniseries, depicting an expedition set in the
near future, will be as realistic as possible.
</P>
<P>
   An Earth-like Mars has been a part of popular culture for more
than a century, triggered by American astronomer Percival Lowell's
electrifying reports in the 1890s that canals crisscrossed the Red
Planet's parched landscape. Romantic notions of thirsty Martian
cities drawing water from the polar icecaps fired the imaginations
of writers. Edgar Rice Burroughs penned ``A Princess of Mars'' and
other Martian adventures. H.G. Wells imagined rampaging Martians in
``The War of the Worlds,'' and Ray Bradbury portrayed a wise,
ancient race in ``The Martian Chronicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Lowell was wrong. Mariner 4 shattered the image
of an Earth-like Mars when it swept past the planet in 1965 and
sent back grainy pictures that showed moonlike craters, not canals.
Two Viking landers probed Mars' red soil in 1976 and didn't even
find germs, much less intelligent life.
</P>
<P>
   But interest in Mars has been growing again, and probes planned
for the next several years are likely to keep it stoked, with help
from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Internet may reach Mars before people do. Vinton
Cerf, a senior vice president at MCI and a developer of the TCP/IP
protocol used to transmit information on the Internet, has been
working on interplanetary data networks with NASA engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Czarnik said an interplanetary Internet may follow in the
footsteps of the old ARPAnet, the precursor of the Internet that
was developed to allow scientists to exchange research data. The
interplanetary version would serve space scientists and might even
allow some to control spacecraft from their keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   Czarnik said such an internet won't give the public direct
access to space probes, but it's likely to give individuals an even
more intimate feeling of involvement in deep-space missions, such
as virtual-reality images of Mars or other planets.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever people finally go to Mars, only a select few will get
to make the voyage. But millions may get to tag along vicariously.
</P>
<P>
   _ mars.jpl.nasa.gov/msp98/lander/
</P>
<P>
   The Jet Propulsion Laboratory's Mars Lander Home Page. JPL
manages the Mars missions. This page includes a countdown clock to
the Dec. 3 landing and detailed information and images of the Mars
Polar Lander spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.seds.org/nineplanets/nineplanets/mars.html
</P>
<P>
   A rich source of information about Mars with links for more
historical and scientific information, as well as pictures.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.marssociety.org/
</P>
<P>
   Home page for the Mars Society, founded by rocket scientist and
Mars exploration advocate Robert Zubrin. Includes many links to
news and information about Mars programs, NASA funding, society
activities, etc. An electronic mall offers a wide variety of
products, not all Mars-related.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.drfast.net/mars/
</P>
<P>
   Mars Society's Ohio chapter home page. Includes information on
Ohio activities, contacts, information about long-duration
spaceflight and links.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.exploringmars.org
</P>
<P>
   An easy-to-use site that offers information and pictures of the
planet Mars and past, current and future exploration missions.
</P>
<P>
   _ mpfwww.jpl.nasa.gov/mgs/
</P>
<P>
   Mars Global Surveyor home page. Latest news and pictures of Mars
from Mars Global Surveyor, which has been orbiting the Red Planet
since September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ mars.jpl.nasa.gov/MPF/
</P>
<P>
   Mars Pathfinder home page. Pathfinder was the first spacecraft
to land on Mars in 20 years. Its tiny rover, Sojourner, was the
first successful Martian rover.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.marssociety.org/content/toolkit/
</P>
<P>
   Build your own Mars base. This Mars Society page offers a
shareware ``MarsArt Toolkit'' that allows you to construct Martian
terrain and arrange elements of a Mars base. Software can be
downloaded in PC or Power Macintosh versions.
</P>
<P>
   _ mars.jpl.nasa.gov/MPF/ops/stereopan.html
</P>
<P>
   If you have red-blue tinted glasses, these stereo images will
give you a 3D view of the Martian surface. Images can be viewed on
screen or downloaded and printed.
</P>
<P>
   _ cmex-www.arc.nasa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   NASA Ames Space Sciences Division's Center for Mars Exploration.
Special features include Mars news, Mars atlas, map, images, and
education resources.
</P>
<P>
   _ mars.jpl.nasa.gov/msp98/mplmodel.html
</P>
<P>
   Too much time on your hands? This page has instructions for a
paper model of the Mars lander, including parts sheets that can be
printed and cut out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
