r l BC-NETWATCH23-COX     11-22 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Registering at retail sites can be the path to bargains
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This holiday season when you are shopping online, why
not opt to ``opt in?''
</P>
<P>
   Opting in is a high-tech way of saying that when you visit an
online retailer, you will check the little box on nearly every site
that asks if you'd like to be on its e-mail list.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, a lot of people are thinking, ``What, check a box
that says, `Please send more junk mail spam to my e-mail account?'
No way, man.'' There's also an equally large group out there
saying, ``Hey, I value my privacy. I don't want some money-grubbing
retailer knowing everything about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, for those two groups, there's just one thing to say: ``Get
over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Online retailers want to be your friend. Well, they want you to
be their friend, anyway. They've read those Jupiter studies saying
online shoppers are going to leave somewhere in the neighborhood of
$6 billion at online checkout counters this holiday season. The
last thing they want to do is upset you and your disposable income.
</P>
<P>
   While they may wish they could invade your privacy, crawl into
your brain and rewire it so you will buy expensive things from them
in great quantities, they know you'd rather they didn't. They know
most shoppers don't want to give away much more information than an
e-mail address and possibly an area of interest, like women's
clothing or toys for toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   The retailers also have privacy policies that they don't have to
have, but prominently display in response to consumers' rightful
concerns that they'll distribute your name and credit card number
to every online con artist between here and Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, online retailing was uncharted territory.
A few online retailers like Amazon.com or CDNow.com were selling
things, but unless you were a serious Web surfer, you had no idea
what they were and whether they were legitimate. Traditional
brick-and-mortar stores like Macy's or Tower Records were still
trying to figure out how to navigate the unfamiliar waters of
online retailing.
</P>
<P>
   But those days are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ads for online retailers during a National Football League
halftime show nearly outnumber ads for cars, beer and mutual funds,
and the companies advertising are stores like the Gap (www.gap.com)
and KB Toys (www.kbtoys.com), where consumers have been spending
money offline for years. They are not likely to run off with your
money or your credit card number if you decide to do business with
them online.
</P>
<P>
   Most sites just want your e-mail address, so they can try to
sell you more stuff more often. That's what they want when they ask
you to opt in. What you get is news of special offers that will
save you time and money. That's the real value of sharing
information with retailers.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to opt in, you will get a weekly or maybe a
monthly or even a less frequent e-mail from your favorite online
retailers advising you of what's new at their respective sites. The
types of offers can range from discounts to special offers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at CDNow, you'll find out when new releases are
going on sale, and you'll get coupons offering free shipping,
discounts or other special offers available only to the online
mailing list. Online clothing company Land's End (www.landsend
</P>
<P>
   .com) has a weekly overstocks newsletter of discounted
merchandise that you must visit the site and request. Major
airlines offer subscribers a weekly list of discounted Web fares.
Other sites, like the Bobbi Brown cosmetics site, will let you know
about special items that are only being sold online.
</P>
<P>
   During the holidays, when every dollar counts, e-mail bulletins
about shopping bargains and exclusives, shipping discounts or what
performances of the Nutcracker are still available Christmas week
can be handy.
</P>
<P>
   To drag out Martha Stewart's well-worn phrase: ``It's a good
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And remember, you can always chose to opt ouonic versions of
books lying in bed at night, after my wife is asleep, there quietly
in the darkness. ... I format the pages so the lines are equal to
my reading style, which helps me to read fast and comfortably. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to bend down the pages to mark a favorite
passage. You do that electronically, or copy it and file it or
share it with somebody in an e-mail, all right there in the quiet
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have academic meetings, they like to make me the
secretary. I take notes as we go, highlighting what is important,
and when the meeting is over I offer everybody a copy of the
minutes, which I download to the printer in the room. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``No, my wife does not wear a computer, but in me she has a good
executive assistant. ... When she runs across something, a passage
in a book or whatever, she asks me to `file it,' and I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The family that computes together ...
</P>
<P>
   Actually, his wearable computer is like a member of the family,
with special needs, all of which Starner has le to say `remind me
about my meeting with Jonas Tuesday at 3:30 at the office ... and
let's include Fran and Jennifer and Mark,' and the machine will
know which Tuesday and the place and the identity of Fran and
Jennifer and Mark and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   In another example, someone may place a call via the Internet,
only to have the machine say, ``Sorry, Thad is teaching right now,
but he has been waiting to talk to you. ... Please call back at
3:30, when he should have some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today Starner says he often boards a plane to keep an
appointment in another city with no record of specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I can access a file at any time, either my
calendar or an e-mail message, that tells me exactly the time and
place and who will meet me or whatever,'' Starner said.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of steps between today's equipment and the point
where computers understand us and what we want in context, Starner
said, but that system will take shape, bit by bit.
</P>
<P>
   He did not add that even though he foresees 20 years in the
development, these things occur at an accelerating pace.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how it ever occurred to him to wear a computer, Starner
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in ninth grade when I asked my father for an answer to
a trigonometry question. He said that, even though he used trig
every day, he had forgotten much of the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that age, I couldn't understand how my father could have
forgotten such useful training. I learned the value of staying in
touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first idea that the interface might be interesting was when
watching a science fiction movie.''
</P>
<P>
   And now Starner is operating personally on the edge of science
fiction, and always in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
