<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online help for holiday overeaters
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thursday is when we start packing it on. Thanksgiving
usually heralds the beginning of the heavy eating season. From
there, it's one long month of holiday parties, Christmas-colored
M&AMP;M's and mall fast-food _ a big, sugar-coated slide toward a New
Year's resolution.
</P>
<P>
   One Web site, www.phys.com, offers an attempt at moderation. The
site contains information about nutrition, weight loss and
pregnancy. But this fall, it has started a holiday survival guide
designed to get you to perhaps drop that second chalupa.
</P>
<P>
   The average person gains at least five pounds during the
holidays, according to phys.com's dietician. The survival guide's
goal is to keep you from overeating and to squeeze in some
occasional exercise along with that last cookie.
</P>
<P>
   The site is geared toward women between 20 and 40, but features
such as calorie counters and calorie-burners could be worthwhile
for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION SITE RESPONDS TO POKEMON SCARCITY
</P>
<P>
   They're as freaky looking as Teletubbies, and the movie
apparently is awful, but kids love Pokemon, the furry Japanese
pocket monsters, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a parent to do this holiday season? Stand in line at
the toy store like you did for Cabbage Patch Kids, Tickle Me Elmo
dolls and Furbys?
</P>
<P>
   In the past, those lines led to a few fistfights and some nice
economics lessons. Toy demand was greater than toy supply, so
instant auctions were started, with people offering way more than
face value for a tangible piece of pop culture history.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Internet, people are getting a head start on what
is expected to be a sought-after, and fought-after, item this year.
</P>
<P>
   An auction Web site, www
</P>
<P>
   .pokemonnation.com, has more than 1,500 Pokemon items for sale.
Signing up for the site costs nothing. Membership lets you buy,
sell or trade Pokemon merchandise. Pokemon e-mail accounts are
available, as are trading boards and chat rooms. The site also
includes a Pokemon glossary to help tell the difference between the
150 characters.
</P>
<P>
   PokemonNation.com is a subsidiary of CollectingNation.com, a
Connecticut-based auction site.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-A-THON ASSISTS AILING GARY COLEMAN
</P>
<P>
   Gary Coleman, the former actor who once sought your viewing
attention on TV's ``Diff'rent Strokes,'' now wants your money.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old, once worth $18 million, filed for bankruptcy in
August. Now he's selling stuff from a Web site, webathon.ugo.com/,
to help pay his creditors.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the public relations firm representing UGO
Networks, the Web site sponsoring the auction, told the Reuters
news service that the site had Coleman's approval and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-foot, 8-inch Coleman suffers from end-stage renal disease
and requires kidney dialysis three times a week. In an August
interview, Coleman said the treatments helped drain his bank
account.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the star of the former NBC sitcom will be able to donate
money and bid for Coleman's personal items, including an
autographed spatula, a natty, pin-striped suit and an ice scraper.
Donors are eligible to receive such items as Gary Coleman votive
candles, Gary Coleman Zippo lighters and Gary Coleman commemorative
plates, featuring a picture of Coleman and Nancy Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The site features Gary Grooves, a three-dimensional image of
Gary dancing to house music. Visitors to the site can register for
a $1,000 shopping spree with Coleman tagging along to help.
</P>
<P>
   Also included is a pop-up timeline that lets site visitors
follow key events in Coleman's life, complete with images and text.
Key moments include:
</P>
<P>
   _ May 1978. The series pilot, ``45 Minutes from Harlem,'' is
shot. The show is picked up, renamed ``Diff'rent Strokes'' and
starts airing on NBC that November.
</P>
<P>
   _ November 1984. Coleman has his second kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 15, 1999. The Gary Coleman Celebrity Web-a-thon kicks
off.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
