<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adobe kit the ultimate for Web page design
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you intend to go into Web site production in a big
way, consider a new Adobe package called Web Collection, built
around the firm's redoubtable Photoshop image-control program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Photoshop 5, the collection includes Illustrator
8, for creating your own drawings and images, ImageStyler for
creating even fancier objects and GoLive, Adobe's Web page editor.
</P>
<P>
   For most folks, this package constitutes major overkill. It is
intended for professionals, and one way or another it will do
everything imaginable in terms of creating a Web page or a major
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who haven't been into computers for long, or
haven't been paying attention, Adobe Systems sprang to life within
the Macintosh world with its venerable page layout program
PageMaker and is still centered there. All these programs have been
ported to the PC system for years now, but for PC users the
dichotomy will present a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Adobe programs don't use a second mouse button,
let alone a third, is not so bothersome as the manuals, which are
exceedingly complete but intended to serve both masters. Thus, many
of the instructions are issued twice _ here's how you do it on the
PC, and here's how you do it on the Mac. This inevitably becomes
confusing and also accounts to a degree for the bulky manuals. The
problem seems somewhat more obvious in GoLive, perhaps because this
is its first appearance in the Windows world.
</P>
<P>
   Photoshop, which is by far and away the most popular of
professional photograph manipulation programs, and Illustrator have
been around for a long time, as their version numbers suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Since GoLive is new to to the PC platform and is, after all, the
program that will be used to get all the fancy pictures up and
running on the Internet, I concentrated on it.
</P>
<P>
   It is a former Mac-only program called GoLive CyberStudio,
acquired by Adobe to give it an entry in the high-end Web design
field.
</P>
<P>
   The layout of a page in GoLive is much more like working in a
standard layout program than any site editor I've used. The page
construction screen uses a grid for precise layout and as an
alternative offers to set up columns and rows as the user wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Images and text can be dragged and dropped from various
palettes. It offers a dozen working JavaScript functions and a
movie editor (for Quicktime flicks) for enhancing a page with
action.
</P>
<P>
   Like its companion pieces, GoLive is an enormous and complex
program. Inevitably, complexity steepens the learning curve, and
GoLive's is steep indeed. The manual runs over 400 pages, and it
will be fairly dog-eared before a serious user is fully comfortable
with the program. In the course of it, the user can expect to
become more familiar with HTML code operations, which underly all
Web pages, than with most lower-end programs. That, of course, is
to be expected also.
</P>
<P>
   GoLive is a direct challenge to Microsoft's FrontPage, and while
it may very well do more _ I haven't looked at FrontPage's last
couple of iterations _ it is not as intuitive and easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, GoLive costs about $300. The powerhouse, four-program
Web Collection runs over $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
