<HEADER>
A7592 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DELLHOUSE23-COX     11-22 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELLHOUSE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell house makes family Net work
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Christmas is closing in, and ``Dellbert,'' an
imaginary teen-age inhabitant of Dell Computer Inc.'s ``Holiday
House,'' suspects that his parents forgot his Christmas wish list.
</P>
<P>
   Better to put it on paper, he decides, using a festive font and
full color, with photos downloaded from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He sends it from his bedroom personal computer to his parents'
printer and then e-mails it to his mother _ who can read it in the
kitchen on her notebook PC. It can't escape his mother's attention,
Dellbert figures, because she is always surfing the Web wirelessly
for new recipes.
</P>
<P>
   These were a few of the visions evoked last week during a tour
of Dell Computer Corp.'s Holiday House, set up in a quiet red-brick
townhome at the Las Vegas Country Club, a mile or so from the din
of Comdex. The giant PC-industry trade show attracted more than
150,000 visitors and 2,100 companies, but Dell, following its
custom, did not have a big booth at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, the No. 1 personal computer maker in the United States,
rented the townhome to demonstrate how available technology from a
variety of hardware and software providers can establish
high-speed, local-area networks in any house. Dell has assembled
several PC packages with these features and more in time for the
holidays, ranging in price from $2,899 to $1,849. All include
56-kilobit Internet access from Dell for one year. Installation
costs and monthly fees for high speed Internet access via DSL or
cable systems are not included in those prices.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, whose vision includes fully functioning PCs throughout the
house, believes some type of desktop computer will become the nerve
center of Internet connectivity for households.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers and communication are coming together,'' said Ron
Van Dell, director of branding for Dell's Dimension, adding that
communication, or networking, means linking multiple PCs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers are going to be able to do a lot more than they've
done in the past,'' he said, sitting in the living room of the
Holiday House with a lighted Christmas tree behind him. ``But that
freedom of choice brings a surprising degree of complexity.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell believes it has solved that problem.
</P>
<P>
   But before we get into that, let's tour the house.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, Dell's Inspiron notebook for consumers gets
Internet access through a wireless link to a Dimension, Dell's
consumer desktop PC, in the family room or living room. The
wireless network is based on a standard format known as 802.11 that
is effective up to 150 feet and can accommodate several PCs and
offer speeds of up to 11 megabits per second. The notebook with the
wireless network connection is expected next month. All other
features are available now.
</P>
<P>
   The Dimension is connected by a VCR-type cable to a large-screen
TV that allows the TV to show a DVD movie running on the PC.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the notebook in the kitchen also could pick up the
movie. But encryption rules designed to prevent piracy forbid
transmission of digital content over the network, said Marc
Padovani, a Dell product-marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't stop whoever's in the kitchen from tapping into
holiday music from dozens of CDs whose contents are stored on the
Dimension's 13.6-gigabyte hard drive using MP3, a technology that
takes up less space. Using an easy-to-follow screen and software
from MusicMatch Jukebox, music stored on the hard drive is
accessible from any PC in the LAN, or local-area network. Music
also can be downloaded via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   After storing music on one hard drive and backing it up on
another, these CDs could be stored in a closet, or even sold at a
used-CD store. Dell, however, isn't recommending that.
</P>
<P>
   Being a Dell house, every bedroom has a Dimension and big-screen
monitor. These upstairs PCs are linked to each other and the
downstairs Dimension in a high-speed network using existing
telephone wiring. That is a feature of pre-installed hardware from
3Com Corp. and software from Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   All desktop PCs in the house can share music and video files
stored anywhere, but parents can restrict access to files with
passwords.
</P>
<P>
   In their bedrooms, Dellbert and his sister, Dellila, can play
computer games with each other or send the full-color Christmas
lists to their parent's printer. They also can see each other
through small cameras on the monitors.
</P>
<P>
   With user-friendly software from Homestead.com, and Internet
access through Dell.com, Dell encourages consumers to build their
own Web pages. Home-movie clips or stills from digital cameras can
be added to the pages. For family and friends who prefer a hard
copy, a Sony Corp. recordable CD-ROM drive lets you put all that on
your customized CD.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds fun, but pretty darned complicated for the average
family, right? And we haven't even mentioned that existing
Dimensions in the house have to be upgraded to connect to the
network.
</P>
<P>
   The first test groups that Dell assembled when it was creating a
special CD to guide consumers through installation and set-up had a
perfect record _ of failure, said Van Dell, the branding director.
</P>
<P>
   But Dell believes it has made the process easy enough for a
family that doesn't know a LAN from a lunar lander to master
without anxiety. It now expects at least an 80 percent success
rate. ``It's not, `Where is our specialist in the neighborhood who
can help us?''' Van Dell said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is perhaps one drawback that the computer maker
hasn't anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   With all the diversions available in Dell's wired house, parents
with children _ say, 3 and older _ might wonder how they'll get
everybody disconnected so the family can sit down together and
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
