<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7594 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-FAILURE23-COX     11-22 1820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FAILURE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When hard work doesn't pay offBy Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Todd Rogers' story is one you don't hear very
often in a town like Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he quit his job and became a high-tech entrepreneur.
But he didn't become a member of one of Central Texas' growing
league of overnight high-tech millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' company, which developed software for veterinary
clinics, failed. Today, nearly a year later, he's still paying off
debts. He drives a Honda Accord, not a Porsche. He doesn't live in
a mansion. And he's back working for somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted was to write a really nice piece of software that
people would use,'' says Rogers, 29. ``But there were a lot of
things I didn't take into account. Nothing went as planned. We had
a lot of bad luck. And we made a lot of mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the visible success of Austin's high-tech industry, the
truth is that far more tech upstarts fail than succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody tracks how many high-tech companies go under annually,
but venture capitalists use a formula for assessing the odds. It's
called the four-three-three, and it assumes that of every 10
companies that raise money, four will fail quickly, three will fail
slowly, three will survive, and hopefully one of those three
survivors will be a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear so much about the huge successes that we forget that
there are many more startups that sink,'' says Kirk Walden,
national director of venture capital research for the
PriceWaterhouseCoopers accounting firm. ``Every entrepreneur has a
chance to fail or succeed, and failure is a heck of a lot more
common.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Rogers' company sank in late 1998 after a two-year
struggle. Eighty-hour weeks produced solid software and a handful
of loyal clients. But that wasn't enough to make up for a small
market, a chronic shortage of cash and poor marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers poured $140,000 in savings into the company before it
closed. What he has to show for it today is stacked in the garage
of his Southwest Austin home: Boxes and boxes of unused CD-ROMs and
worthless stock options. ``You never hear about the other side of
startups,'' says Rogers, who, with his boyish smile and
close-cropped hair, could be played by actor Chris O'Donnell if
they made a movie about his defeat. ``It's kind of the untold part
of the high-tech story that a lot of us have lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Some days, like last week when a surprise $200 tax bill arrived
from the comptroller's office, Rogers regrets ever having dared to
launch his company, Tower Software Inc. But other days he's more
philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent hours and hours thinking about it,'' say Rogers,
who is now a consultant at a software services company. ``I've
beaten myself up over it. But now I'm realizing that I probably
learned more from failing than if it had succeeded. I've grown up a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Destiny of a company
</P>
<P>
   If Rogers' decision to start his own company can be traced to
one thing, it's boredom.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Vanderbilt University in 1995 with a
degree in computer engineering, he joined a software contractor
doing data modeling and analysis for General Motors Corp.'s Saturn
division in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a job, just a job,'' he says. ``You never felt like you
were having an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   He had toyed with starting his own company, but never had an
idea that felt right. Then he got a call from his brother, a
veterinarian in Hawaii. All the software for managing vet clinics
was lousy and expensive, he complained. Why don't you come up with
something better?
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, Rogers began researching the market. It seemed ideal
_ 35,000 to 40,000 veterinary clinics in the United States, and a
handful of small companies selling behind-the-times software
(mostly based on the ancient DOS platform).
</P>
<P>
   ``The software was four to five years behind, techwise,'' Rogers
says. ``I mean, the stuff was crummy.''
</P>
<P>
   The assumption that veterinarians wanted something snazzier was
his first mistake. ``The thing I didn't anticipate was the vets
being completely unreceptive to new technology. Looking back, I
realize that just because I could write software using Delphi (a
programming language) didn't mean anyone would buy it. At the time,
though, it seemed like I had stumbled across a great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   During his year as a programmer, Rogers had stashed away $70,000
for graduate school. A zooming stock market sent his savings
soaring to $140,000. He had paid off his car, and could live for
free in a mobile home on some property his parents owned in Blanco.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1996, Tower Software was born.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers went to work pounding out code from the mobile home,
later from a rented house with a roommate and finally from free
office space at the Texas Dental Association he got in exchange for
doing computer consulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go out and socialize, I didn't do anything but sit in
front of the computer and code for six months,'' says Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   He recruited an old friend, Chris Jackson, to move from Houston
to be his partner, and the two proudly visited their first vet
clinic to test the software, which manages vet medical records.
They chose the Houston clinic where Rogers' family had taken its
ducks, rabbits, cats and dogs for years. They left humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just tore the thing to shreds,'' Rogers says. ``I was
just so way off in terms of usability. It was useless.''
</P>
<P>
   The next time around, the two spent nights at an emergency
animal clinic watching how workers entered data and used their
software. Days were spent doing a massive software rewrite. Six
months later, they were ready to face the vets again. This time
they worked closely with three clinics _ in Austin, Schertz and
Houston _ to make sure the software did what it should.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Dr. Corky Trlica of Travis Country Veterinary
Hospital, took a special interest in Tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked their entrepreneurial spirit,'' he says. ``I don't
have computer experience, and they helped me learn it. In exchange,
I was hoping I could help them build the software from a vet
standpoint. Usually, it's the computer monkeys that design the
systems, and then us knothead vets have to try to learn them.''
</P>
<P>
   Trlica says he was impressed by the software, but skeptical of
Tower's viability. ``The system was pretty bulletproof, it was the
best I had seen. But I kept asking them if you sell 10 of these a
month can you make a living? I didn't see how they could keep
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was wondering the same thing. He hadn't taken a salary in
24 months, the company had burned through $70,000 and it was
gearing up to spend thousands more on direct mailings.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Rogers and Jackson estimated they could live on
selling four or five copies a month (at $2,000 to $3,000 per
clinic). But even after sending out 300 demos and getting positive
response from ads in vet trade magazines, sales were slow.
</P>
<P>
   The thing Rogers didn't realize, Trlica says, is that vets don't
like change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd misjudged the marketplace, and how conservative this
business is,'' Trlica says. ``Vets as a rule don't go for the
latest and greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tower ``would sell a couple copies, then a couple
more, but we weren't selling enough to cover our expenses,'' Rogers
says. ``It was getting really old not having a paycheck. We were
sinking our hearts into it and getting nothing back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers knew he desperately needed to invest heavily in direct
marketing and hire a full-time salesperson to work the phones all
day _ but he couldn't afford either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met with some venture capitalists, but our market was too
small to interest them,'' he says. ``Finally, we sat down and said
`We have no money. Let's find a competitor who has really crappy
software and sell them ours.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another six months was spent negotiating a promising deal with a
software company, but in the end they couldn't agree on a price. A
phone conversation with a friend in Houston is what finally
convinced Rogers it was time to rethink his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked how my relationship with my wife was and I realized
our marriage was kind of decaying,'' he says. ``That was when I
realized I could find another job, but I could never find another
Erin. It became really clear that this wasn't going to cut it. It
was time to be realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, Tower Software closed for good.
</P>
<P>
   THE AFTERMATH
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, pulling the plug felt like a huge relief to
Rogers. But then came the pain: Sending out resumes to get another
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was finally admitting that Tower was over,'' says Rogers.
``I kept thinking about the people who had spent their money on our
software, and how they believed in us, and we were letting them
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tower found a software consulting company that agreed to take
over its 12 customers. Recently, he put his software up for sale on
online auction site eBay Inc. He says he got a bite, which he hopes
may still pan out.
</P>
<P>
   Failure didn't hurt when it came to job hunting. Jackson got a
job designing computer networks for Temple-Inland Corp., and Rogers
was hired quickly by Catapult.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high-tech, failure isn't a stigma,'' says Walden of
PriceWaterhouseCoopers. ``Tech companies would rather see someone
who struggled to get a business off the ground than someone who sat
in a cubicle for 20 years. It's all about `What did you learn?'''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' list of lessons is long.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I realized is that hard work in software is about half of
what you need to make something successful. The other part is good
management and good marketing,'' he says. ``I should have spent
more time studying the industry, and I needed to hire people rather
than do it all myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 11 months since Tower went out of business, Rogers has
supplemented his Catapult income by working nights as a software
contractor to pay off debts. This year he settled $10,000 in
Tower-related debt, and has another $3,500 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Filing for bankruptcy crossed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legally we could have blown it all off,'' he says. ``But I
teach a Bible study to high school kids, and I can't go in there
and tell them all this stuff about honesty and not be living it.''
</P>
<P>
   As time passes, and the disappointment fades, Rogers is
beginning to understand that he met more goals than he initially
realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to be a millionaire,'' says Rogers. ``What I
dreamed about was seeing someone use something that came out of my
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget walking into a vet's office and seeing a
receptionist using our system. She wasn't complaining or anything.
She was just using it to get stuff done.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the coolest moment, and it's what I want to remember
about Tower Software.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
