<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7597 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-IPO23-COX     11-22 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPO23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grabbing stocks at IPO price tough, risky
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We've all heard about high-tech employees making
huge amounts of money when their companies start selling stock to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   So how do the rest of us get in on the action?
</P>
<P>
   It depends on how daring you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard truth is that initial public offerings just aren't
set up for the individual investor,'' says Pat Dorsey, a stock
analyst with investment research company Morningstar Inc. ``But if
you want stock in a newly public company, and you don't mind paying
a premium and taking your chances, you can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, eight Austin-area high-tech companies have
gone public, more than in any other year. Hundreds of employees
have become overnight millionaires _ at least on paper.
</P>
<P>
   In an initial public offering, a company raises money by selling
stock to investors outside the company for the first time. Some of
the stock typically is sold to employees, company insiders and
others. The rest of the shares are sold to investment banks, which
in turn resell them to brokers and institutional investors, such as
mutual fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   The only time most average investors can buy the stock is after
it starts trading on the open market. And in the case of the hot
tech companies, the stock generally trades at a price well above
the IPO price.
</P>
<P>
   The IPO price depends on how well a company is received by
institutional investors like pension funds and insurance companies.
If the institutional investors like a company, its offering price
will be high, say $18-$20 in the case of a tech company. If the
response is lukewarm, it will most likely be priced lower, perhaps
at $8-$10 a share. Since in recent offerings tech stocks have
tripled or quadrupled on their opening day, for those lucky enough
to get in on the IPO shares, ``it's basically guaranteed money,''
says Kent Fuka, a venture capitalist with CenterPoint Ventures in
Austin. ``Everyone wants those kind of odds, which is why getting
the stock is so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Crossroads Systems Inc., an Austin tech company that went public
Oct. 20, is a case in point. The company priced its stock at $18,
and the stock closed the first day at $78.71 7/8. That means those
who had IPO stock paid $18 for shares that gained 337 percent when
they went public.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Crossroads shares closed at $76.50.
</P>
<P>
   If you want in on an IPO badly enough, there are ways to do it.
It starts with who you know.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage houses often get some shares for customers _ but you
have to be a very good customer, meaning you have an account worth
several hundred thousand dollars and trade frequently.
</P>
<P>
   For most folks, the best bet _ and it's still a long shot _ is
to be buddies with someone who works at the company that's going
public. Many companies allow employees to give a set number of
shares to friends and family. But even executives, employees and
their lucky friends can't cash in right away; securities
regulations require them to hold on to their stock for a certain
amount of time _ usually six months _ before they can sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's Vignette Corp., for instance, gave each employee 200
shares of so-called friends and family stock when it went public in
February. The stock was on top of whatever shares employees could
buy through stock options. Employees could keep the stock, or give
it away.
</P>
<P>
   Kala Ranganathan, the company's public relations manager, split
the shares between her parents and in-laws, who were able to buy
the stock at the offering price of $19. Ranganathan, who later left
to join another tech company, recently sold the shares for her
relatives at $153 a share, giving each side $13,400 before taxes.
She has held on to her own Vignette stock. ``The stock was trading
at a high, and it seemed like the perfect holiday gift, so I sold
it for them,'' she says. ``It's not a really large amount of stock,
but it was a way to show my appreciation.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some signs that the Internet could help democratize
the IPO process. Online brokers such as Wit Capital and E-Trade are
increasingly touting their ability to get IPO shares for customers
through their relationships with investment banks. These companies
typically get just a handful of the total number of shares being
offered, and make them available over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of hype about getting Internet IPO shares, but
very few people actually pull it off,'' Dorsey of Morningstar says.
``The number of shares available is still too small to give many
folks a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet auctions are also gaining popularity. W.R. Hambrecht &AMP;
Co. has begun what it calls an OpenIPO, which allows institutions
and individuals to bid on shares in an IPO on its Web site
(www.openipo.com).
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the companies have gone public using OpenIPO _
California vintner Ravenswood Winery and online magazine Salon.com
_ have been big successes. But IPO watchers say it's only a matter
of time until the idea catches on.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get in on an IPO and you're hungry enough for a
company's stock to buy it shortly after it begins trading, be
prepared for a rough ride.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of hot companies almost always jump from their offering
price. But there's no telling how long they'll stay up. If you buy
when they're up, you have to be ready for them to come back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a strong stomach,'' says Ray Hilton, a retired pet
store owner and stock investor. ``You also need to be lucky. It's a
big risk, and like any risk, there's a lot of luck involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, the early trading is fast and furious. Experts recommend
that you put a cap on how much you're willing to spend per share,
and if it can't be had at that price, count yourself out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should really decide what price you think is the right
price before the trading starts,'' says Mike Dunn, an attorney with
Brobeck Phleger &AMP; Harrison in Austin. ``Otherwise, you can get
caught up in the frenzy and end up buying at a price that quickly
takes a dive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilton's most recent gamble on Vignette has paid off, even
though he didn't get in on the IPO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get IPO stock, but I couldn't, so I told my
(investment company) I wanted to buy it as soon as possible,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   After Vignette stock began trading, Hilton got 100 shares at $36
a share. Not as good as the $19 offering price, but better than its
first day closing price of $42.68 3/4. And far better than its
Friday closing price of $172.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I didn't give up when I couldn't get IPO shares,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't work that way for Wade L. Smith Jr., an Austin
retiree. He bought $21,000 worth of online pharmacy PlanetRx.com
Inc. stock at $34 a share shortly after it started trading on Oct.
7. But the stock closed at $26 the first day, and it has been
downhill since then. On Friday, it closed at $21.93 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, I've made more than $300,000 on Wal-Mart stock,
so this isn't going to hurt me,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying stock the first day is an extremely risky venture,''
says Dorsey of Morningstar. ``There's a lot of hype right at the
beginning, and when that dies down, the stock often dies down as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 459 IPOs that took place nationwide through Nov. 10, 316
are still trading above the offering price, while 140 are trading
below offering price and three are unchanged, according to the IPO
Reporter, which tracks the market. The average return over the
offering price was 103 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``IPO stocks tend to soar in the beginning, but the track record
is pretty poor in general over the long haul,'' Dorsey says. ``A
lot of energy that people spend focusing on IPO watching would be
better spent researching high-quality companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as exciting, but in the long run it can be a lot more
profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
