r f BC-CYBERSCENE23-COX     11-22 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You could look it up: Reference tools sharp
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The World Wide Web was pretty much a toyland in the
beginning. It was an amazing place to visit in its earliest days.
And almost everything you found there was fascinating and also
without any practical value.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, it's a very practical world for the most part. It's a
place where you can shop, check the weather, get a quick look at
the traffic you can expect on the way to work and find information
on everything from beekeeping to epoxies.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the handiest uses for the Web, whether you're at work
or doing homework for school, is the way that _ increasingly _ it
can substitute for a whole shelf of reference books. Since many
reference books get dated fast, the Web has real advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Today we'll look at some of the places on the Web that _ when
used together _ form a handy collection of reference works.
</P>
<P>
   About the most mundane, and useful, reference book around is the
dictionary. Whether you need help in pronunciation, spelling or
just nailing down the definition of a word, a dictionary is the
anchor for most reference desks. Several sites on the Web offer
dictionaries, but one stands out: Dictionary.com at www
</P>
<P>
   .dictionary.com.
</P>
<P>
   The definitions come from Webster's Revised Unabridged
Dictionary. But there's a lot more on this page than just the
dictionary. You'll find links to Roget's Thesaurus (www.thesaurus
</P>
<P>
   .com if you want to go there directly); to dictionaries in
almost any language you can name; hints on grammar and style for
writers; and even a crossword section where you can put some of
those new words to quick use.
</P>
<P>
   There are times, of course, when a dictionary isn't enough. If
you want to know more about Will Rogers, for instance, you won't
get any help in the dictionary. But there is a great free online
encyclopedia. In fact, it's the online version of one of the best
electronic versions ... Microsoft's Encarta. You'll find it at
encarta.msn.com/. And if you key in the name Will Rogers, you'll
get a brief biography, a photograph and a selection of links that
will take you out into the Web to find out even more.
</P>
<P>
   Reference works aren't limited to dictionaries and
encyclopedias, of course. As the world has grown smaller _ thanks
in part to the Web _ the need has increased to understand people in
other parts of the world. In Europe, for instance, temperatures are
often expressed in Celsius degrees, rather than Fahrenheit, as is
used in most U.S. weather forecasts. To find an instant converter,
just type in the temperature and click the mouse to convert at www
</P>
<P>
   .isotech.co.uk/convert.html.
</P>
<P>
   And if you get an urgent e-mail from a customer who wants one of
those superdeluxe widgets that your company builds and is prepared
to budget up to $8,922 Singapore dollars, you'll know that amounts
to $5,344.46 (on the day this calculation was performed) in U.S.
currency. Most currencies that you've heard of _ and a few that you
haven't _ can be found here at www.asia1.com.sg
</P>
<P>
   /cgi-bin/bt/fxconv.pl.
</P>
<P>
   Translation can be a problem with the language itself, of
course. What if you get an e-mail from an Italian customer who
tells you ``Desidero comprare piu widgets''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's good news. That customer wants to buy more widgets.
You can do the translation yourself at babelfish.altavista
</P>
<P>
   .com/. You'll find help for German, French, Italian, Portuguese
and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
