<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FileMaker Pro database program updated for network, Web use
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you're an entrepreneur who needs to track clients
or a just a collector desperate for a way to catalog your holdings,
you might take a look at the latest version of FileMaker Pro.
</P>
<P>
   This venerable database program, controlled by Apple, lets you
create everything from client and product lists to CD catalogs,
address books, calendars and invoices _ whatever you need to track.
</P>
<P>
   With version 5.0, you can also share your address book with
others on a network or post a list of products or clients on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Database programs let you store and analyze any kind of
information. With these programs you can total up, say, sales in
the Midwest or every book in your collection written by Kurt
Vonnegut.
</P>
<P>
   FileMaker Pro is considered an entry-level database for small
businesses, home users and work groups within a bigger company.
It's designed to be easy-to-use and understand without any
background in programming.
</P>
<P>
   No program meets this standard, but FileMaker Pro is pretty easy
to use and learn compared with most database programs.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes with lots of templates that you can adopt as your
own. Better yet, the Internet and local bulletin boards are full of
templates users have built into FileMaker Pro and distributed for
others to use.
</P>
<P>
   While this program has been around for years, the latest version
includes several new features. For one, FileMaker Pro has been
redesigned to look and act more like the programs in Microsoft's
Office suite of software. You'll find menu toolbars and pop-up
context menus that resemble those in Office.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind this redesign is to make FileMaker Pro familiar
and useful to a larger audience. Does it work? Only in part,
according to most reviewers. They found the mix of FileMaker Pro
styles and those of Microsoft confusing in spots.
</P>
<P>
   The program also goes too far at times in simplicity, crossing
over into ``dumbed-down.'' In the name of simplicity, for example,
FileMaker Pro includes only six fonts. It's a laborious procedure
to load in more.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any built-in programming language for power users.
That limits FileMaker Pro's appeal for bigger tasks such as running
a company's human resources department, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the program is receiving high marks for many of its
easy-to-use features. It's easy, for example, to create reports and
different ways to analyze and view information. The program walks
users through these things step-by-step through ``assistants,'' a
feature much like Microsoft's Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Another big plus is that, like Microsoft products, FileMaker Pro
works on both the Mac and PC platforms. That means databases
created in one platform will work in the other.
</P>
<P>
   FileMaker Pro retails for about $240, with the upgrade selling
for about $100 less.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
