<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Need for food is growing
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite a booming economy, more families will line up
at soup kitchens this year to celebrate Thanksgiving, according to
food banks around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our requests for help are at an unprecedented level,'' said
Nancy Carrington, executive director of the Connecticut Food Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, food donations are down 15 percent this year. But
the demand for food has increased 30 percent during the last 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   Food banks say more families are in need because they have been
removed from welfare rolls. During the last three years, 1.7
million families have stopped receiving financial support from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The government doesn't agree welfare reform has caused problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any real hard evidence that the changes in
welfare have resulted in a greater hunger or greater need for food
banks,'' said Michael Kharfen, a spokesman for the U.S. Department
of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURE VOTERS DON'T KNOW MUCH ABOUT GOVERNMENT
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government doesn't think you know enough about how it
works.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of students tested nationwide scored below ``basic''
knowledge about the government and the responsibilities of being a
citizen. Twenty-two thousand students in the fourth, eighth and
12th grades were tested last winter. The U.S. Department of
Education released the results last week.
</P>
<P>
   Only one-fourth of the test takers scored ``proficient'' or
``advanced'' in their understanding of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION HIGH-FLYING FUN
</P>
<P>
   Look! Up in the sky _ it's a bird! It's a plane! It's a ride
that flies you around like Superman!
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest trend in amusement parks _ to be flown face-down
as though you were the Man of Steel. Two of these type rides, along
with many others, were on display at the International Association
of Amusement Parks and Attractions convention in Atlanta last week.
</P>
<P>
   On the ``flying'' rides, people are hoisted into the air and
zoom around in a circle, while they're fastened in face-down with
their feet dangling. The ride ``Fly Away,'' is made by a German
company; ``The Kite'' is made by an Italian company.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
