<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7605 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-WEAR     11-22 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-WEARPC23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putting on your PC
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thad Starner, one of the stars in the Georgia Tech
College of Computing, is easily recognized wherever he goes _ on
the campus or around the country.
</P>
<P>
   He is, depending on his operating base that day, the cool dude
in the computer glasses, or that nerd who wears his computer and
thinks everybody should. Either way, it's fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   Starner, 30, has worn his computer virtually 24/7 since Dec. 11,
1996, when he was a student in the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology media lab. He has become a national, yea, even an
international guru on wearable computers.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is not the only apostle, he is dubbed the pioneer by
the Financial Times of London and by other observers far and near.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to wear it, mostly because it makes more sense than a
desk computer,'' says Starner.
</P>
<P>
   You get his point when you learn that his wearable computer with
the viewing screen just an inch from his left eye allows him to
send and receive e-mail, browse the Internet or just read _ while
at the same time doing other duties, or just lying in the grass in
a park. He used the wearable computer to write his 250-page
doctoral thesis, astonishing when you consider the complex format,
footnotes, cross-references and minutiae that accompany such a
formal text.
</P>
<P>
   The viewing screen has remarkable clarity.
</P>
<P>
   With his computer in a pocket or in a shoulder bag, and sending
messages via his Twiddler, a nine-button, one-hand keyboard that
looks like an ocarina, Starner is in touch with a bottomless pool
of knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview the other day, he startled me by addressing me
as if my life were an open book: ``Congratulations on your award
announced the other day ... that's nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to me, my life WAS an open book. Even though he was
looking at me, he was also perusing a file of information about me
by way of his eye-level computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   You get the idea Thad Starner is at one with his apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   His mission in life, Starner said, is to see the day a billion
people may be online, connected in wireless communication as he is
with his community of cyborg friends, as well as the rest of us on
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be made possible by common, inexpensive pocket
computers, sophisticated enough to combine in one device all our
familiar things _ the calendar, the watch, the computer, the cell
phone and the word processor, all with wireless communication
capability,'' Starner said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it will be so basic that it can connect to
peripherals of your choice _ music player, video cameras or
whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to Starner, the evangelist, talk about his wireless
wearable computer:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is already much more than a computer as we usually
understand it. For instance, I read better on this computer than I
do using books. You know how reading in bed can be difficult,
trying to wrestle your way into a comfortable position with five
pounds of pages?
</P>
<P>
   ``With my computer, I read electronic versions of books lying in
bed at night, after my wife is asleep, there quietly in the
darkness. ... I format the pages so the lines are equal to my
reading style, which helps me to read fast and comfortably. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to bend down the pages to mark a favorite
passage. You do that electronically, or copy it and file it or
share it with somebody in an e-mail, all right there in the quiet
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have academic meetings, they like to make me the
secretary. I take notes as we go, highlighting what is important,
and when the meeting is over I offer everybody a copy of the
minutes, which I download to the printer in the room. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``No, my wife does not wear a computer, but in me she has a good
executive assistant. ... When she runs across something, a passage
in a book or whatever, she asks me to `file it,' and I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The family that computes together ...
</P>
<P>
   Actually, his wearable computer is like a member of the family,
with special needs, all of which Starner has learned to
accommodate.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of us 'borgs, the battery is a main concern,'' Starner
said. ``This is my approach. When I sleep, my battery sleeps; when
I eat, my battery eats (gets a charge). And that way we are both
ready at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideal wearable computer, which Starner said could be as much
as two decades away, will be a machine that understands commands in
context, probably by voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will be able to say `remind me about my meeting with Jonas
Tuesday at 3:30 at the office ... and let's include Fran and
Jennifer and Mark,' and the machine will know which Tuesday and the
place and the identity of Fran and Jennifer and Mark and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   In another example, someone may place a call via the Internet,
only to have the machine say, ``Sorry, Thad is teaching right now,
but he has been waiting to talk to you. ... Please call back at
3:30, when he should have some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today Starner says he often boards a plane to keep an
appointment in another city with no record of specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I can access a file at any time, either my
calendar or an e-mail message, that tells me exactly the time and
place and who will meet me or whatever,'' Starner said.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of steps between today's equipment and the point
where computers understand us and what we want in context, Starner
said, but that system will take shape, bit by bit.
</P>
<P>
   He did not add that even though he foresees 20 years in the
development, these things occur at an accelerating pace.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how it ever occurred to him to wear a computer, Starner
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in ninth grade when I asked my father for an answer to
a trigonometry question. He said that, even though he used trig
every day, he had forgotten much of the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that age, I couldn't understand how my father could have
forgotten such useful training. I learned the value of staying in
touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first idea that the interface might be interesting was when
watching a science fiction movie.''
</P>
<P>
   And now Starner is operating personally on the edge of science
fiction, and always in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
