</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Career changers profiled in magazine
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Looking for a dramatic career change, perhaps from
prosecutor to video game developer? Then check out the November
issue of Fast Company magazine. An article profiles people who have
made remarkable career changes. There's a jazz musician who became
a successful business consultant and a prosecutor who did become a
video game producer.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping magazines are in season, and the publishers of Yahoo
Internet Life have issued the premiere issue of eShopper. The
magazine advertises itself as a ``guide to the click-and-buy
lifestyle,'' whatever that is.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, dated for December, features articles about how to
avoid Internet scams and how to search the Web for great bargains.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   The makers of ``SimCity'' and ``Theme Park'' have teamed up for
a new computer CD called ``SimTheme Park.'' It's an interactive
simulation that lets you create rides and then group them into an
amusement park. Published by Electronic Arts, ``SimTheme Park''
retails for about $40. It's available only for PCs with Windows 95
or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Jones lives on in the latest computer game about the
fictional hero from LucasArts. In this sequel, ``Indiana Jones and
the Infernal Machine,'' our hero battles Soviet agents in 1947. The
game is set in the Middle East and explores the Tower of Babel.
Like all the titles in this series, ``Infernal Machine'' is a 3-D
role-playing game. ``Infernal Machine'' is available only for PCs
running Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to learn something is through practice,
playing and experimenting with what you have learned. The Internet
is a wonderful playground for students of all ages. Take math, for
example. ``Absurd Math'' is a collection of puzzles and games that
test pre-algebra math skills. There are hidden clues and mysteries
to be solved through cracking math problems. You'll find this site
at www.hrmvideo.com/abmath.
</P>
