r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A23-COX     11-22 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: In a recent paper there is a picture of a
sprinkler made of copper pipe which becomes a swirling, functional
sculpture when the water is turned on. Would you please find out
how and where I can purchase one? _ Cynthia Ann Leach
</P>
<P>
   A: That copper sprinkler was created from a custom kit by Dream
Sprayer. The company produces several styles of sprayers with
spirals as well as the kit to design your own. Kits are $79 and
include all the components a creative gardener needs. All thumbs?
Ready-made copper sprinklers are $189-$249 and arrive with the
three-prong base you need to support the water art work. Contact
Dream Sprayer at (920) 494-3430 or check out the company's Web page
at dreamsprayer.home.att.net.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My sister plans to be married in Italy. She wants my children
to be in her wedding. At the time of the wedding one will be 7, the
other, 21 months. What are the rules concerning passports? I have
seen passport pictures with a mother and child together. At what
age should a child receive his own? _ J. Little
</P>
<P>
   A: Break out the forms, Mom, you are applying for passports for
these kiddos. ``All persons including newborn infants are required
to obtain passports in their own names,'' according to U.S. Postal
Service spokeswoman Barbara Pokorny. Postal stations provide
passport services. For those 15 years and younger, passports are
valid for five years; for 16 years and older, 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell me why Matthew McConaughey seems to have a
sideline pass to every UT home football game? He was even on the
sidelines at the Texas-OU game in the Cotton Bowl. It's true that
he's not bad to look at down there, and since he stands right in
front of our section most of the time, we do get a pretty good
view. But how does he rate such special treatment? _ Dianne Brode
</P>
<P>
   A: McConaughey falls into the special guests category along with
other University of Texas Longhorn fans such as Ben Crenshaw, Lance
Armstrong, Darrell Royal and Earl Campbell, according to sports
department spokesman Bill Little. You may have seen them pacing the
sidelines also. All-access passes are issued by the UT Athletic
Department football office. Perhaps your son will be down there
among the glitterati one day. Q: My son is getting married in the
spring and I have purchased a double wedding-ring quilt for their
wedding gift. I would like to include the history of the quilt as
part of the gift. Could you help me find the history?
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathy Holland
</P>
<P>
   A: The double wedding-ring quilt appeared as early as 1870 but
did not come into popularity until 1925-30, says third-generation
Texas quilt-maker Kathleen McCrady. This is a difficult pattern _
not for the novice quilter. In the late 1920s, patterns were
published making such patterns easier to execute. Other popular
patterns of this era are Sunbonnet Sue, Dresden Plate and
Grandmother's Flower Garden. No one knows the exact origin of the
double wedding-ring quilt, but it is a traditional newlywed
present. The interlocking rings are reminders of new connections
and promises.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which is correct: ``Fleshed out'' or ``Flushed out,'' as in
an issue? I hear both terms used. (Flushed out makes more sense to
me.) And while I am at it, where did ``early on'' come from and
what in the world does ``arguably'' mean? _ David Beard
</P>
<P>
   A: You've been reading too many William Safire ``On Language''
columns. Grammar guru John Mark Rogers at the University of Texas
Writing Center tackled your query. ``Flesh out,'' as in an issue,
is correct. The phrase conjures putting meat on a skeleton, or
filling in an outline for a topic. ``Early on'' is an informal
usage in which ``on'' is superfluous. Use it in conversation _ if
you must _ in lieu of ``early'' or ``earlier.'' For the adverb
``arguably,'' Rogers suggests this meaning, ``openly debatable
among experts.''
</P>
<P>
   UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROAR
</P>
<P>
   _ Reader Jamie R. Oliver, vice president of the Central Texas
Chapter, Employee Assistance Professional's Association, offers
details on dealing with workplace violence. ``Any organization of
size should have a 'Zero Tolerance' policy on threats of violence
in the workplace to go along with similar policies on alcohol/drug
abuse and sexual harassment/discrimination,'' notes Oliver. The
policy should include who receives the report (e.g. supervisor,
human resources, security) and what form the report should take.
Procedures should be in place for investigation and documentation
of threats as well as subsequent discipline if warranted.
</P>
<P>
   _ Need to go that extra geek mile this holiday season? Choose
gifts from a selection of Geek Wear white pocket protectors bearing
geek mottoes such as Code Warrior, Get Down! Get Geeky! or Geek
Wear. Each is $1.90 plus shipping. Perfect for that special nerd in
your life. Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at
P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
