<HEADER>
A7616 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-FEATURE-INDIANS23     11-22 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-INDIANS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meet the people who lived in Georgia long before us
 &HT;    By Jill Young Miller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thanksgiving week is when many Americans think about
the Indians who helped Pilgrims from England through those first
harsh winters. But it's not the only time we can appreciate Native
American culture and history.
</P>
<P>
   A new exhibit at the Atlanta History Center celebrates those
first inhabitants of America and focuses on the tribes of Georgia.
It will be at the center for a year.
</P>
<P>
   NFK visited the exhibit, which is called ``Native Lands: Indians
and Georgia.'' Here's some of the cool stuff we learned:
</P>
<P>
   WHO LIVED HERE?
</P>
<P>
   The Native Americans who lived in Georgia were the
Mississippians, and later the Creeks and Cherokees. The
Mississippians were here from the years 900 to 1600. They built
great Indian mounds and surrounded them with their towns. Some
towns had populations in the thousands. By the early 1700s, many of
their descendants had become members of the Creek Confederacy and
lived throughout most of what is now Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, another group of descendants, the Cherokees,
lived in the southern Appalachian Mountains, which are in northern
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT LANGUAGES DID THEY SPEAK?
</P>
<P>
   The Creeks spoke many languages and dialects, including
Muscogee, Hitchitii, Yuchee and Shawnee. The Cherokees spoke one
language: Iroquoian. Their ancestors, the Mississippians, spoke
many languages, but the names aren't recorded in history.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DID THEY CELEBRATE?
</P>
<P>
   The Green Corn Festival was the Creeks' and Cherokees' most
important religious tradition. They held the sacred festival every
year at harvest time, and it lasted for days.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time for prayers, dances, songs, telling stories and
predicting the future. People forgave each other for wrongdoings,
and they destroyed things used in the previous year, such as
pottery, food and clothing. Women harvested corn and vegetables,
and hunters brought game for a feast.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SPORTS DID THEY PLAY?
</P>
<P>
   A ballgame called ``Little Brother of War'' trained young men to
be warriors. Players used two sticks with pockets at the ends to
carry and throw a deer-hide-covered ball as they ran down a field.
They could not touch the ball with their hands. A team scored when
a player hurled the ball between the other team's goal posts.
</P>
<P>
   The game was rough. The players could hit each other with their
sticks and do just about anything else to stop the other team. The
game helped settle disputes.
</P>
<P>
   WHO WAS PART OF THE FAMILY?
</P>
<P>
   Every Creek and Cherokee belonged to a ``clan,'' a large
extended family. Children inherited their clan from their mother _
and with it certain traditions, dances, prayers and jobs. If
someone was sick or old or lost their home, the clan took care of
them. Everyone in the clan helped raise the children. By the early
1800s, seven clans existed among the Cherokee: Blue, Long Hair,
Bird, Paint, Deer, Wild Potato and Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HAPPENED TO THE TRIBES?
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippians suffered from epidemics, warfare and
enslavement by Europeans and other Native Americans. Their first
contact with the Europeans was in the 1500s, and because they had
no immunity to European diseases, whole towns and villages died.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Creeks and Cherokees were pressured to leave their
native lands and move west. By 1826, Georgia had evicted the Creek
Nation. In 1838, U.S. troops rounded up the Cherokees and forced
them to go west. The Trail of Tears was a forced march that lasted
116 days and took the Cherokees to Oklahoma. By 1840, almost no
Creek or Cherokee people remained in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE ARE THEY TODAY?
</P>
<P>
   The descendants of the Creeks and Cherokees who had to leave
Georgia live in North Carolina, Oklahoma and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern Band of the Cherokee Nation, numbering about 9,000,
lives on 50,000 acres in western North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Cherokee Nation of Oklahoma has more than 150,000 members.
In 1907, the federal government dissolved the Cherokee reservation
to establish the state of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The Poarch Band of Creek Indians lives on 1,700 acres near
Atmore, Ala. The tribe includes more than 2,000 descendants of the
Creeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Muscogee (Creek) Nation of Oklahoma has about 47,000
members.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Native Lands: Indians and Georgia'' study guide;
``Native Lands: Indians and Georgia'' exhibition catalog; Sarah
Hill, guest curator, Atlanta History Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
