<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7618 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN23-C     11-22 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glued to the tube with thanks By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ In this holiday season,
<TEXT>
let us pause and consider the tuber that is neither mashed nor
sweet. Let us consider the faithful boob tuber, which has no
calories but still makes us fat ...
<P>
   TV TO BE THANKFUL FOR
</P>
<P>
   1. Aaron Sorkin _ Enough already about David E. Kelley. The
smartest shows on the networks this season belong to Sorkin, who
came to TV from big-screen scripting (``A Few Good Men,'' ``The
American President'') to concoct last year's ``Sports Night'' for
ABC and this fall's ``The West Wing'' on NBC. The ambivalent
romance between Casey and Dana on ``Sports Night'' is the hot
button this season, but the
</P>
<P>
   real love affair is the deep friendship between Casey and Dan.
An episode of ``The West Wing'' dealing with the politics swirling
around a gun-control bill showed the agony and the reality of
turning ideals into law. Unlike the creations of another famous
Aaron (that would be Spelling), these programs are not cotton
candy. They're Power Bars. ``Sports Night,'' by the way, returns
Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``The Simpsons'' _ For nearly a decade, Matt Groening has
made us groan, wince and howl _ but we've never been bored. In a
recent inspired moment, Homer, who never met a fat gram or a
calorie he didn't like, asks to have hot butter poured on his Milk
Duds at the movies. Still surprising after all these years, a
rarity on TV.
</P>
<P>
   3. Original movies on HBO and TNT _ While the broadcast networks
have sunk to endless rape and murder flicks, the cable channels are
turning out thoughtful movies. ``The Sopranos'' has gotten all the
press this season for HBO, but let's not forget the quality of the
network's original movies. The latest is ``RKO 281,'' a fascinating
look at the making of ``Citizen Kane'' and the strange convergence
of two legendary titans, Orson Welles and publisher William
Randolph Hearst, on whose life Kane was based. James Cromwell is an
against-type choice to play Hearst _ a risk the Big Three would
never take.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bill Moyers _ Ignore the bogus flap over the funding of
Moyers' projects. He is incapable of selling out to anybody. The
commercial networks aren't going to devote an hour or two to
campaign finance reform, the Constitution or ``Amazing Grace.''
This season's ``Fooling With Words,'' about the art of poetry, was
an offbeat look at literary creation. Let Peter, Dan and Tom handle
the plane crash headlines. Moyers is a master at making us think
deeper.
</P>
<P>
   TV TURKEYS
</P>
<P>
   1. Newsmagazines _ Why is it that every newsmagazine except ``60
Minutes'' feels compelled to run stories on murders, bigamists and
mothers who cause horrible illnesses in their children? ``Dateline
NBC'' seems to run the same murder story five times a week,
distinguishing a few by calling them ``interactive'' and asking
viewers to vote guilty or not guilty online. With a dozen hours of
these shows a week, we're stuffed to the hurling point with these
tasteless turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whiny, sex-obsessed twentysomethings _ These folks are
annoying in real life and they're annoying on TV. The good news is
ABC's ``Wasteland'' is gone; the bad news is a bunch of new ones
are scheduled to arrive midseason. The WB has an hourlong drama,
``DC,'' and the sitcom ``Zoe'' in the works; and CBS is grasping
for youth with a Miami-based comedy called ``Grapevine.'' Maybe the
newcomers won't whine, but I wouldn't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wrestling _ I don't care if it is just campy theater, it's
grotesque. And after years of being banished to cable, wrestling
has crept onto a broadcast network this fall in the ugly form of
``WWF Smackdown.'' These pumped up, greased down growlers appeal to
something lower than the lowest common denominator, and in an
effort to out-do each other, they've become more violent. This fall
alone there were two paralyzing accidents in the ring. Put on some
clothes and get a real job, guys.
</P>
<P>
   4. E! Entertainment Television _ Farm out ``Talk Soup,'' the
only decent program on the network, to Comedy Central and close
this operation down. Just because ``Entertainment Tonight'' is a
hit in syndication doesn't mean this stuff should be on 24 hours a
day. A typical day's lineup includes ``Scandals,'' ``Celebrity
Profile'' (featuring such A-listers as Melissa Gilbert and Charlie
Sheen) and the ultra-crude ``Howard Stern.'' Eeeee-yow!
</P>
<P>
   5. The new game shows _ OK, everybody's watching ``Who Wants To
Be A Millionaire.'' Four of the latest episodes were in the top 10
and all seven were in the top 20. But this is really hokey stuff.
Regis Philbin's breathless excitement, the pulsating music, the
hand-flapping-lip-sweating contestants, the squealing studio
audience. It's all just too much. And those questions: How many
teaspoons in a tablespoon? Which state capital is at the highest
altitude? Not that the questions are all easy. They're just random
trivia. It's a testimony to how tired viewers are of regular fare
that this show is such a hit.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Diane Holloway at dholloway(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
