<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Tuesday, November
23, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is available Tuesday after 2 p.m. EST
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 1120 PUTTING ON YOUR PC _ The future of personal
computing can be found today and its in the eyewear of a Georgia
Tech computer guru. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution )
Art includes one 4-column color photo of man wearing computer
glasses and a 1-column photo of complete personal computer system.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS _ A company is producing high-tech toys with girls in
mind. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) Art includes 1-column color
photo of Lady Bug listening device.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ Better products are created by the marketplace,
not the courts. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art
includes 1 column color sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS _ Analyze baseball's case against Pete Rose while
surfing the Internet (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art
includes 1-column color photo of Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   GAME CORNER _ Fishing for a new game? This video game features
everything but the smell of the trout. (Staff, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MARS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Mars is just a bright dot in the sky on a
starry night, but personal computers and the Internet have brought
the Red Planet as close as your keyboard. Most space missions now
have at least one, and sometimes many, Internet sites, and the
large number of missions aimed at Mars in recent years has caused a
proliferation of sites for the fourth rock from the sun. (Gaffney,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DELLHOUSE _ LAS VEGAS _ Christmas is closing in, and
``Dellbert,'' an imaginary teen-age inhabitant of Dell Computer
Inc.'s ``Holiday House,'' suspects that his parents forgot his
Christmas wish list. Better to put it on paper, he decides, using a
festive font and full color, with photos downloaded from the
Internet. He sends it from his bedroom personal computer to his
parents' printer and then e-mails it to his mother _ who can read
it in the kitchen on her notebook PC. It can't escape his mother's
attention, Dellbert figures, because she is always surfing the Web
wirelessly for new recipes. These were a few of the visions evoked
last week during a tour of Dell Computer Corp.'s Holiday House, set
up in a quiet red-brick townhome at the Las Vegas Country Club, a
mile or so from the din of Comdex. (Mahoney, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-FAILURE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Todd Rogers' story is one you
don't hear very often in a town like Austin. In 1996, he quit his
job and became a high-tech entrepreneur. But he didn't become a
member of one of Central Texas' growing league of overnight
high-tech millionaires. Rogers' company, which developed software
for veterinary clinics, failed. Today, nearly a year later, he's
still paying off debts. He drives a Honda Accord, not a Porsche. He
doesn't live in a mansion. And he's back working for somebody else.
(Hawkins, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GADGETS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ VTech Industries of Wheeling,
Ill., sells several e-mail products that it says can be used
anywhere by simply plugging them into a telephone jack. Two of the
products, e-Mail PostBox and e-Mail Express, sell for less than
$100. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDGEAR _ AUSTIN, Texas _ It's amazing that anything with
Barney's mug on it still exists. There was a time where the purple
dinosaur inspired rage and social backlash. Now, it's the opposite.
Barney is back in favor, in part because of cool toys such as
Barney's Song Magic Bongos ($30). (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GAMER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Say what you will about Microsoft _
it continues to revolutionize gaming with its quality peripherals
and great games. Its latest, Age of Empires II ($50 for the PC), is
yet another in a long line of great real-time strategy games.
(Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-SITES _ A look at sites covering turkey preparation.
(Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE-WEARPC _ Weekly centerpiece on personal
technology, from products to trends to advancements. This week:
Wearable computers. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: Retrace your steps when something goes
wrong with your PC. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Adobe's Web Collection
package. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: Opting to receive
online retailer's e-mails can sometimes save you money. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: Reference Web
sites. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ News on Apple and its products. This week:
FileMaker Pro. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Tech briefs on new products and developments.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POWERUSER-COLUMN _ This column will not move this week. (Yandel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   DIGESTION-MAIN _ Thanksgiving's two days away, and for most
people it's a guaranteed bout with indigestion _ too much food, too
much high-fat food, too many sweets, sometimes too much alcohol _
it's enough to make anyone turn green. With a little moderation, it
doesn't have to be that way; and if you can't do what's good for
you, some remedies work better than others. (McKenna, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DIGESTION-GRAPHIC
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The following budget line is for a graphic which will be
available via the Budget Tool: Graphic on how the digestive system
works and what causes indigestion; what you can do besides
medicines to lessen the effects of overeating (will exercise and
drinking water after the Thanksgiving meal help head it off; what
are the alternative medicine remedies for it _ will ginger help,
for instance?) (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DIGESTION-GLOSSARY _ A glossary of digestive disorders.
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   CELULITE _ The skinny on Cellasene. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-KIDPROOF _ Five things you should know about
child-proofing a house before you take your young child to
grandma's for the holidays, or other homes that don't have kids.
(Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MOON-MAIN _ When members of R.E.M. wrote the pop-hit tribute to
the late comic Andy Kaufman, ``Man on the Moon,'' they had no idea
that, more than a decade later, the song would inspire a feature
film of the same name. Today, the soundtrack to the Jim Carrey film
arrives in stores, scored by Mike Mills, Peter Buck and Michael
Stipe. We talk with Mills about putting the music together, his
thoughts on the film and on the legacy of Andy Kaufman. (MLongino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MOON-CDREVIEW _ A review of the soundtrack (by R.E.M.) of the
Jim Carrey-as-Andy Kaufman movie ``Man in the Moon.'' (Dolar,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFY-ANGEL _ Review of the ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and
``Angel'' crossover night tonight - where characters from each
visit theother. Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CASSIDY 0 A conversation with Carol Cassidy, director of the
documentary ``''Run Like a Girl,'' which airs tonight on WPBA at 11
p.m. Her other documentary, ``Smile Pretty,'' also a part of her
five-year nationwide project that looks at gender and identity in
adolescent American girls, airs next Tuesday on WPBA. (Kloer,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN _ Observations on the television industry from
a leading commentator. This week: Tuning in for Thanksgiving.
(Holloway, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NEWS FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   NFK-CHECKITOUT _ A brief on a new web site, TV show or event for
kids. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NFK-NEWSFLASH _ Three or four briefs of world and national news,
written for kids to understand. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
