<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7630 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEW-STROKE-TREATMENTS     11-22 1504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-STROKE-TREATMENTS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TREATMENTS HELP STROKE VICTIMS REGAIN LIVES
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color graphic of a brain showing the four types of
stroke) 
 By BEN STEELMAN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shirley Pritchard doesn't remember much about what happened on
Jan. 19, but she'll never forget the date. The Carolina Beach,
N.C., resident suddenly became disoriented. She couldn't recognize
her husband, Herman, or her surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband quickly dialed 911 for an ambulance. It was a wise
move. Pritchard was having a cerebral infarction, more commonly
called a stroke. Part of her brain was starving for oxygen and
rapidly dying.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 600,000 Americans experience a stroke each year, an
average of one every 53 seconds. About a fourth of these will die.
</P>
<P>
   Of those who survive, thousands will be left crippled, with
paralyzed limbs, dimmed eyes, slowed or slurred speech or an
inability to chew or swallow properly.
</P>
<P>
   The costs of treating strokes _ including nursing home care,
home health care and lost wages _ is estimated at more than $45
billion per year. Strokes, sometimes called ''brain attacks,'' are
the leading cause of long-term disability in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, an array of new drugs can make it less likely that
patients will suffer severely or that their disabilities will be
long-lasting. Moreover, rehabilitation and treatment can offer many
patients the hope of a near-complete recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard has been relatively lucky. ''I still am not back 100
percent,'' she said. ''I had a hard time getting my speech back.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been taking outpatient therapy sessions, and her
pronunciation is clear. Yet she hesitates briefly before
pronouncing each syllable.
</P>
<P>
   ''My grandsons say they can't understand me,'' she said.
''Sometimes, I don't understand myself.''
</P>
<P>
   More embarrassing for Pritchard has been a rare side effect of a
stroke called ''alien hand syndrome.'' One of her hands
occasionally does things without her control.
</P>
<P>
   ''It kind of takes off on its own,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, unexpectedly, the hand will sometimes grab
inappropriately at other people nearby. Pritchard knows another
patient with the same condition who was nearly strangled by her own
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, alien hand syndrome generally disappears within six
to 12 months after the stroke, according to medical journals.
</P>
<P>
   Other stroke damage, however, can last for the rest of a
patient's life. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; STARVED FOR OXYGEN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A stroke occurs when parts of the brain are suddenly deprived of
oxygen. This happens when oxygen-rich red blood cells can no longer
reach these areas.
</P>
<P>
   A blood clot or some other particle of matter can block a key
artery or blood vessel that feeds the brain. Such blockages, known
as thrombosis or embolisms, account for 70-80 percent of strokes,
according to the American Heart Association. In some cases, surgery
might be needed to clear the blockage.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, a temporary blockage can lead to what doctors call
a transient ischemic attack, which are often _ and inappropriately
_ called a ''mini-stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   The symptoms almost never last more than a day and generally
disappear within a few minutes or hours. But that doesn't mean the
symptoms should be ignored. Patients who have had a transient
ischemic attack are about 10 times more likely to suffer a
full-blown stroke than other people of the same age and sex.
Moreover, roughly 10 percent of strokes are preceded by these
attacks, according to the American Stroke Association.
</P>
<P>
   Once a patient reaches a hospital, physicians have many new
techniques to treat a stroke. One of the most exciting is called
tissue plasminogen activator (TPA), also called a ''clot-buster.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally used to treat heart attacks, TPA was found to
minimize or prevent damage in roughly 11 percent of stroke
patients.
</P>
<P>
   TPA must be used with care, however, as it could endanger a
patient's life if the stroke is caused by bleeding rather than a
clot. Emergency room teams must move fast, using CAT scans and
other diagnostic tools, to determine which is which. Unless TPA is
used within three hours after stroke symptoms appear, it could
increase the risk of fatal bleeding. The drug also can be dangerous
to patients who take blood-thinners or who recently had major
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Studies are being made on neuroprotective agents, drugs that
could stop the chemical chain-reactions that lead to brain damage
after a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   At a medical conference in Nashville earlier this year, doctors
reported on promising studies of one drug, prourokinase, which
could help patients up to six hours after stroke symptoms appear.
Unlike TPA, which is given intravenously, prourokinase must be
released directly into the brain, by way of a catheter threaded
through an artery _ a hazardous procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Another promising drug, now being tested, has been derived from
snake venom. At the University of Pittsburgh, researchers are
experimenting with transplants of laboratory-grown brain cells in
an effort to help patients regain speech or motor skills more
rapidly. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; HOPE OF REHABILITATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, the damage cannot be repaired. Once the
oxygen is cut off to parts of the brain, brain cells and nerve
cells begin to die within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The death of brain cells may deprive a patient of certain
functions.
</P>
<P>
   Stroke patients may recognize common objects, but may not be
able to recall their names. Or they may develop aphasia, where they
know the words, but cannot remember what they mean.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, with appropriate therapies, patients' outlooks need
not be bleak.
</P>
<P>
   ''In rehabilitation medicine, the focus is always on function,''
said Dr. John Liguori, medical director for Coastal Rehabilitation
Hospital in Wilmington, N.C. ''We cannot cure strokes, but we can
treat the disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   If patients' arms and legs are weakened on one side of their
bodies, for example, therapists teach them how to use their
''good'' side for such skills as dressing, brushing their teeth or
operating a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, a leg brace or walker can help patients get
around almost normally.
</P>
<P>
   Recovering stroke patients may need help eating and drinking and
may even need to change their diets. If the nerve cells controlling
the throat muscles are affected, patients can have trouble
swallowing; liquids might pour straight into the lungs, leading to
pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Speech therapists try to restimulate patients' brains. For
example, using pictures of a horse, a table or a dollar bill, the
therapist would ask, simply, ''What is that?'' If patients can't
name the object, the therapist might prompt them: ''It starts with
'tuh-'...'' Or: ''It's what you eat supper on.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The words are up there,'' says Sharon Roberts, a speech
pathologist at Coastal Rehabilitation Hospital. ''The problem is
regaining access to them.''
</P>
<P>
   She likened the effects of a stroke to a hurricane or a
landslide closing a highway. Patients must gradually discover a new
way to their old memories, either by finding an alternate route or
rebuilding the path.
</P>
<P>
   Many patients, like Pritchard, can make considerable progress
with just a few months of therapy.
</P>
<P>
   But the decades-long Framingham, Mass., heart study found that
31 percent of stroke survivors needed help caring for themselves
and that 16 percent needed to be institutionalized.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some doctors think rehabilitation medicine is boring and slow
and that it's kind of depressing,'' Liguori said. ''But to me,
there's nothing more exciting than helping people regain their
independence.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as one-third to one-half of stroke survivors suffer
clinical depression in the first two years after a stroke, the
American Heart Association reports.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this depression may result from physical damage to the
brain; it seems to be especially common when the front of the
brain's left hemisphere is the damaged area.
</P>
<P>
   Depression also may result from frustration or sorrow at one's
condition, at the loss of abilities once taken for granted or the
inability to enjoy once-favorite hobbies or pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association publishes a bimonthly magazine
for the lay reader, Stroke Connection, with news on new treatments
and therapies and encouraging success stories. Subscriptions are
$12 per year. To subscribe, call (800)553-6321. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ben Steelman writes for the Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
