<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7632 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-FAMILY-HISTORY-PROJEC     11-22 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-HISTORY-PROJECT-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARING FAMILY HISTORY: A GOOD HOLIDAY PROJECT
</HEADLINE>
  By LAURA TAXEL 
 c.1999 Laura Taxel 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my son Simon's teacher asked the children to make family
trees, he came to us for help and my husband and I were shocked at
how little we knew about our own pasts. We called our parents and
asked them for names, dates of birth, countries of origin, and
anything else they could recall about their parents, grandparents,
and other relations.
</P>
<P>
   We were lucky; we had living relatives who could give us this
information _ information that we might have absorbed by osmosis in
times gone by. It was once common for family members of different
generations to spend time together talking.
</P>
<P>
   Now members of extended families don't necessarily live close to
one another. And even when together, listening to stories about
dead relatives is often less appealing than watching television and
videos, playing computer games, or chatting online.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to know who they are, children need to know where
they come from. For many of us, the holiday season is a time to
gather together with relatives, some of whom we may not see on any
other days of the year. And that makes the holidays an ideal time
to collect family memories and share family history with children.
</P>
<P>
   ''Children have a natural curiosity about the past and a hunger
to know about their family's history,'' said Dr. Alan Entin, a
psychologist and family therapist in Richmond, Va. ''It gives them
a satisfying feeling of connectedness and continuity. They take
great pride and pleasure in that sense of belonging.''
</P>
<P>
   Going back just three generations relates each of us to at least
14 people. Go back six more generations, and we're connected to a
minimum of a thousand other people. This notion of being part of a
larger clan is especially important for today's children, many of
whom have little regular contact with grandparents and relatives
beyond their immediate family.
</P>
<P>
   In our world of rapid change, family upheaval, and geographic
mobility, children may feel isolated and separate. Stories,
pictures, and information about the family tree offsets those
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our children always think of parents and grandparents as
having always been old,'' said Entin. ''Through stories and
photographs, they see us in new ways, get to know us. Discovering
who they resemble in the family and things they have in common
builds essential relationships with those who came before. It can
provide the support of an extended family even if that family
doesn't actually exist in day-to-day life.''
</P>
<P>
   You may feel there's nothing interesting to share. But you don't
need pedigree charts, larger than life heroes, or Indiana Jones
adventures in order to have a personal past that will be meaningful
to your children.
</P>
<P>
   History is more than great events _ it's also ordinary people
leading regular lives filled with simple pleasures and small
calamities. What seems dull to adults can be compelling to
children.
</P>
<P>
   ''These stories are entertaining because they come from a world
that has gone away forever,'' said John Bellamy, a genealogy
specialist. ''No matter how average you think your family is, you
have stories to share that children will love.''
</P>
<P>
   We all have ancestors who came from some place, and each of us
has lived a life rich in experiences. Sharing those experiences
teaches children essential life lessons and nurtures compassion,
empathy, and the idea that they too can survive adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stories about hard, sad times can give adults a way to talk
about things like illness, death, and failure without it being too
overwhelming for children,'' said Entin. ''It helps kids to know
that everybody, including parents and older siblings who seem so
infallible, goes through hard times and makes mistakes. The most
beloved stories are usually about things that went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories sometimes have a dark side, and can evoke painful
emotions. But it's important not to deny children the gift of a
link to their past by your silence. Their grandpa may have been the
meanest, most good-for-nothing, wife-beating alcoholic that ever
lived, but he was also your father and there's something of value
you can pass on about his life to your children, even if it's only
about what not to do. In the sharing, you may begin to get a better
understanding of him and the forces that shaped your life, find
peace with what has happened to you, and let a kind of healing
begin.
</P>
<P>
   In her book ''Keeping Family Stories Alive,'' Vera Rosenbluth
writes that learning about her family's history gave her a feeling
of ''being a somebody'' and a comforting sensation of permanence.
''The stories of my grandmother's life weren't especially unusual;
every family has similar stories. But for me, they were the most
special stories in the world because they were the stories of MY
family. They laminated me into my own and my family's past and were
an important part of my sense of identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Family history is documented in simple things like birth
announcements and old letters; in a piece of furniture or jewelry
that has been passed from one generation to another; in family
recipes and holiday traditions, in wedding dresses, medals, or
trophies stored away in boxes. Recalling where these objects came
from, when they were used, or to whom they first belonged can open
up a treasure chest of memories.
</P>
<P>
   There are stories hidden in names. The origin of your last name
can lead you into exploring your families geographic roots with
your kids. Nicknames and how they came about can evoke great
anecdotes, and if you, a relative, or your child is named after
someone else, there's a piece of the past in that too.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing your history can be as easy as saying, ''This is a song
my grandma always sang to me,'' or as elaborate as researching your
lineage. You can make a story out of all the different places
you've lived, or create a map that shows the travels and migrations
of your ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Let other family members help. People of another generation can
paint vivid, intimate pictures of the past for children with the
details of their daily lives _ what they wore, how food was
prepared, games they played, and how they earned a living. It's as
much history as what's in the social studies books. Children need
this kind of information so they can place people in real time.
Otherwise it's hard for them to know the difference between 1950
and 1850. This fact became obvious when one of my boys wanted to
know if my mother churned butter when I was a kid or if telephones
had been invented yet.
</P>
<P>
   Encourage children to ask questions and interview relatives at
family gatherings. ''It's a great way to bridge the generation gap,
to find out what parents and grandparents have been through,'' said
Ann Sindelar, a librarian for an Ohio Historical Society. ''It
personalizes the past, draws children and elders closer, helps kids
learn about events that have affected 'their' people, and see that
'their' people had an impact on events too.''
</P>
<P>
   It also teaches them to honor and respect elders and realize
they have something valuable to share.
</P>
<P>
   So start a new tradition this holiday season; make time to talk
with older relatives about the family's past.
</P>
<P>
   Be intentional about it. Ask where and when they were born, who
their parents were, and how they're related to you. Ask about their
lives, their work, they ways they enjoyed themselves. Write it
down. It will be an invaluable treasure for your children.
</P>
<P>
   ''Giving children the history of their family lets them know
they're a product of the past,'' explained Bellamy. ''And like
those people, they have a stake in the future. I really believe
that if you don't understand where you came from, you won't know
where you're going.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ( Laura Taxel is a Ohio-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
