<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7658 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CULTURE-OF-COPYCATS-A     11-22 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-OF-COPYCATS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CULTURE OF COPYCATS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO B&AMP;W PHOTOS are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ERIC WILSON 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``There's nothing else like it in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   There is probably no sentence more frequently uttered along
Seventh Avenue, one used liberally by eager salesmen seeking to
describe a garment, a fabric or design as truly distinct.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there a sentence less likely to be true in an industry
dominated by a culture of copycats.
</P>
<P>
   Knockoffs, it is said, have been part of fashion ever since Eve
saw Adam's fig leaf and designed one of her own. They have a
storied history, from the legitimized couture copies sold by some
of the leading U.S. department stores in the '50s and '60s right up
to today's phenomenon of dress adaptations made by ABS and Victor
Costa that mimic clothes worn during the Academy Award
presentations.
</P>
<P>
   It is a practice so commonplace, and one not clearly prohibited
by law, that most designers who have been copied have felt helpless
to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been several recent legal challenges, and now
that the Supreme Court has taken up a case with the potential to
define what constitutes a violation of existing trade dress law,
the practice of knockoffs is under the spotlight, raising questions
among manufacturers of what the ramifications of such a decision
could be.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court got into the design business in October when
it took up an appeal by Wal-Mart Inc., which lost a $1.25 million
judgment to a children's playsuit maker in 1996. In the case, to be
decided sometime next year, the justices will define what makes a
product's look or image so distinctive it can't be legally copied.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have made their names by aping others' designs,
it's a tricky issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there has been a garment business, people have
always been inspired by others,'' said Allen B. Schwartz, design
director of ABS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about who puts what spin on it,'' he said. ``Gaultier
or Galliano will put their spin on it, I'll put my spin on it, but
fashion isn't anything unless everyone is buying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz is the self-anointed King of Copycats and promotes the
practice proudly _ he says he can turn out a designer adaptation
nearly overnight and have it in stores within a few weeks. He's
appeared on numerous television programs displaying this talent,
and even paid his own airfare to Chicago this year to show his
Academy Awards-inspired collection on ``Oprah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `original' does not exist in fashion,'' Schwartz
said. ``Everything starts from some sort of inspiration. If Calvin
or Ralph or Burberry think they invented plaid, a slip dress or a
bias cut, they need to get to a couch. They are just reinventing it
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers like Schwartz and Victor Costa, who also claims to be
the fastest at getting Oscar looks into stores, argue that they are
performing a service to customers who want, but can't afford, to
look like celebrities in custom-made designer gowns. The designers
they imitate, however, rarely appreciate the flattery.
</P>
<P>
   Miuccia Prada, in a 1996 profile, decried the mass adaptations
of her designs, calling the knockoff artists ``vultures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are experiencing an incredible attack from people who want
to know what we are doing,'' she said. ``They hang around our
fabric mills, they want to see our prototypes _ it's really
becoming unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so aggravating,'' said Vera Wang. ``If I were Miuccia
Prada, I'd take a gun and shoot everyone in the shoe industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang has seen her bridal designs knocked off throughout the
industry, and looks she created for celebrities at the Academy
Awards copied within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that most consumers know the difference, so
therein lies the problem,'' she said. ``Most of the real design
houses end up becoming design studios.''
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Lang said since his firm has been frequently quoted as
one of the most influential fashion houses of the '90s, ``for this
award we take obviously the good and the bad which goes with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oscar de la Renta called it the ``highest form of flattery,''
but added, ``What would really upset me is if no one copied me.
Today you deal with a consumer who is highly sophisticated. She
knows that what I'm selling not only has a certain look, it also
has a certain quality of manufacturing. That cannot be knocked
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Nova USA designer Tony Melillo said, ``At first, you feel like
somebody is making money off what you did, but in the end, you feel
at least you're doing something right. It came up recently with the
Gap photographing everything with judo pants, which I've been doing
since I started. In the end, I actually feel a little bit weird
about it, but it's life.''
</P>
<P>
   And in 1994, Jean-Jacques Picart _ Christian Lacroix's former
partner _ said, ``In the old days, there was copying; now people
are hijacking the very identity of designers. It's turned into a
real handicap for us. Copies are like mosquitoes. One bite doesn't
matter _ just an irritation _ but 100 bites give you a fever that
can kill.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement was made in reaction to Yves Saint Laurent's
successful lawsuit against Ralph Lauren, in which YSL charged in
Paris courts that his couture tuxedo dress had been knocked off by
Lauren. He demanded damages of close to $1 million at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren counterattacked, and demanded $174,000 in damages for
defamation of character for statements in Women's Wear Daily by YSL
president Pierre Berge, who accused the American of ripping off
YSL.
</P>
<P>
   The Lauren and YSL dresses were modeled in court before Judge
Madelaine Cotelle, who pointed out the differences in fabric, how
YSL's version had pockets and how one had gold buttons and the
other did not. Lauren was found guilty and both were fined _
Lauren, $393,000 for copying the dress; Berge, $89,295 for
``denigration'' of Lauren's character.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch also lost a high-profile case against
American Eagle Outfitters in which it said American Eagle had
unfairly copied the look and the printed wording on some of its
garments. That suit was dismissed in July in U.S. District Court in
Cincinnati, although A&AMP;F has vowed further appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Whether apparel firms can do anything about it, though,has
garment industry executives talking about the potential
ramifications of the case before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   While many demand stronger legal protection from piracy, they
also fear a storm of litigation would arise if the High Court
upholds the case, opening the way for suits against anything
perceived as a knockoff, even something as basic as a cargo pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would really help the industry if they could get something
like this (a specific law) done, because you would end up with more
diversity of product,'' Konheim said. ``But the thing is, if you do
a cargo pant and somebody else does a cargo pant, is that
copying?''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Miller copyrights each of the prints she designs, and the
firm has successfully filed more than 1,500 infringement cases
since 1986 related to firms that copy the designs. While prints are
clearly protected under law, silhouettes are a tricky issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a copy,'' Konheim said. ``That's a trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Azria, president of BCBG, who has frequently been accused of
copying top designer lines, blasted the practice of knocking off
other designers, and said his line is as subject to knockoffs as
anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   ``People from the mass market copy you and can put you out of
business,'' he said. ``I spend $10 million to $20 million in
product development a year, only to be knocked off by a contractor.
The question is not what is right or wrong, the question is why
America does not have any law that would protect us from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Schwartz added that all designers look to others for
inspiration. ``I eat, live and breathe fashion. I watch CNN every
morning. I read every magazine,'' he said. ``Nobody has a lock on
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schwartz stressed that even though he has a reputation as a
copycat, he's really a kitten. His Academy Award group accounts for
about 5 percent of his business, ``and 5,000 percent of my
publicity,'' but the rest of the ABS line is made up of
``original'' interpretations of what is happening in fashion, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Where a designer could really get into trouble, he said, is by
copying a print, since that is protected by law.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the version of the John Galliano gown that Cate Blanchett
wore to the Academy Awards in March seemed a little daring,
considering it was copied right down to the fluttering hummingbird
embroidered on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Schwartz said. ``Mine was a seagull.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Eric Wilson is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CULTURE-OF-COPYCATS-A     11-22 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-OF-COPYCATS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CULTURE OF COPYCATS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO B&AMP;W PHOTOS are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ERIC WILSON 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
