<P>
   And in 1994, Jean-Jacques Picart _ Christian Lacroix's former
partner _ said, ``In the old days, there was copying; now people
are hijacking the very identity of designers. It's turned into a
real handicap for us. Copies are like mosquitoes. One bite doesn't
matter _ just an irritation _ but 100 bites give you a fever that
can kill.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement was made in reaction to Yves Saint Laurent's
successful lawsuit against Ralph Lauren, in which YSL charged in
Paris courts that his couture tuxedo dress had been knocked off by
Lauren. He demanded damages of close to $1 million at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren counterattacked, and demanded $174,000 in damages for
defamation of character for statements in Women's Wear Daily by YSL
president Pierre Berge, who accused the American of ripping off
YSL.
</P>
<P>
   The Lauren and YSL dresses were modeled in court before Judge
Madelaine Cotelle, who pointed out the differences in fabric, how
YSL's version had pockets and how one had gold buttons and the
other did not. Lauren was found guilty and both were fined _
Lauren, $393,000 for copying the dress; Berge, $89,295 for
``denigration'' of Lauren's character.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch also lost a high-profile case against
American Eagle Outfitters in which it said American Eagle had
unfairly copied the look and the printed wording on some of its
garments. That suit was dismissed in July in U.S. District Court in
Cincinnati, although A&AMP;F has vowed further appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Whether apparel firms can do anything about it, though, has
garment industry executives talking about the potential
ramifications of the case before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   While many demand stronger legal protection from piracy, they
also fear a storm of litigation would arise if the High Court
upholds the case, opening the way for suits against anything
perceived as a knockoff, even something as basic as a cargo pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would really help the industry if they could get something
like this (a specific law) done, because you would end up with more
diversity of product,'' Konheim said. ``But the thing is, if you do
a cargo pant and somebody else does a cargo pant, is that
copying?''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Miller copyrights each of the prints she designs, and the
firm has successfully filed more than 1,500 infringement cases
since 1986 related to firms that copy the designs. While prints are
clearly protected under law, silhouettes are a tricky issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a copy,'' Konheim said. ``That's a trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Azria, president of BCBG, who has frequently been accused of
copying top designer lines, blasted the practice of knocking off
other designers, and said his line is as subject to knockoffs as
anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   ``People from the mass market copy you and can put you out of
business,'' he said. ``I spend $10 million to $20 million in
product development a year, only to be knocked off by a contractor.
The question is not what is right or wrong, the question is why
America does not have any law that would protect us from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Schwartz added that all designers look to others for
inspiration. ``I eat, live and breathe fashion. I watch CNN every
morning. I read every magazine,'' he said. ``Nobody has a lock on
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schwartz stressed that even though he has a reputation as a
copycat, he's really a kitten. His Academy Award group accounts for
about 5 percent of his business, ``and 5,000 percent of my
publicity,'' but the rest of the ABS line is made up of
``original'' interpretations of what is happening in fashion, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Where a designer could really get into trouble, he said, is by
copying a print, since that is protected by law.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the version of the John Galliano gown that Cate Blanchett
wore to the Academy Awards in March seemed a little daring,
considering it was copied right down to the fluttering hummingbird
embroidered on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Schwartz said. ``Mine was a seagull.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Eric Wilson is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
