<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7660 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-DOT-COM-PHENOM-NYTSF &LR;      11-22 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT-COM-PHENOM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DOT-COM PHENOM  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' business news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GEORGIA LEE 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The great Internet land grab continues.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce pioneers, some with huge advertising budgets, are out
to generate sales, surely, but they're also looking to build brand
loyalty, capture ``mindshare'' and squash the competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has in effect become advertising's newest category.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion of Web sites and Internet services is invading
every media vehicle, from prime time TV to local newspapers, as
well as a host of creative new venues, from store kiosks to
18-wheelers. And it's growing more pervasive every day.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet fashion frontier, where a dominant player such
as Amazon.com has yet to emerge, competition is intense. The
medium's exponential sales growth and potential are adding fuel to
the flame, making advertising more crucial than ever, say experts.
</P>
<P>
   New online business is indeed up for grabs in fashion and
related categories. Total Internet retail sales are projected at
$14.9 billion for 1999 and $23.1 billion for 2000, up from $7.8
billion in 1998. Fashion, footwear, health and personal care areas
should generate around $1 billion in 1999, and $1.9 billion for
2000, according to Jupiter Communications, a New York consulting
firm that tracks the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With an infusion of new investment money from recent IPOs and
venture capital, young online companies are stepping up to the
plate with multi-million-dollar advertising budgets that in some
cases rival total company sales.
</P>
<P>
   Bluefly.com, a designer outlet with 200 brands at discount
prices, had a second-quarter 1999 marketing budget of $2.48
million, compared with sales of $1.14 million for the same period.
And with a $10 million capital infusion from financier George
Soros, the company is expected to spend heavily over the next three
years to build business, with advertising an important priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to gain share of mind, to dominate, and it's something
we intend to do with a big commitment over the next few years, not
over the next few generations,'' said Ken Seiff, chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Bluefly.com's campaign _ a stylized woman in a lounge chair with
a martini and Chinese takeout food _ includes the copy ``Tuesday,
11:15 p.m. _ buying a new dress.'' Rather than touting discount
prices, the message stresses the benefits and convenience of
Internet shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Camdens, a Web site focusing on upscale corporate
gifts, uses advertising to promote a message of luxury,
personalization and customization, one that sharply contrasts with
much of today's offbeat Internet ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the avalanche of dot-com advertising, many companies use
shock value, such as shooting gerbils out of a cannon, to get
attention,'' said Fred Reffsin, ceo of Camdens. ``We're trying to
emphasize services, image and what the Internet can do for
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Reffsin said the money and time it takes to acquire new
customers is justified by the enormous potential of the gift
category.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our area, we can be a first mover, so we have to get out a
strong, compelling message,'' he said. ``It takes money and time to
convince people to change shopping behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Camdens' annual advertising budget of over $20 million includes
a combination of broadcast and print media to build its brand
image.
</P>
<P>
   Camdens' target customer represents a ``new luxury buyer,''
Reffsin said. The new luxury customer, who may come from
middle-class origins, buys for personal rewards, rather than
status, he continued. ``Unique product, such as a teak mousepad and
matching monitor, stands for individualized expression for the
sender as well as the receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the name out, in any way possible, is the first step in
brand building, a challenge that can be especially daunting and
expensive to new, relatively unknown companies.
</P>
<P>
   Sephora.com, which launched a beauty Web site this month, has a
leg up by having established stores first, said Jim Kenney, ceo.
With 33 U.S. stores, and 50 scheduled by yearend, the two channels
are designed to complement each other. Customers can reorder store
items online and return online items at stores.
</P>
<P>
   A $25 million ad campaign features a strong fourth-quarter push
that integrates the store and web site messages, which both stress
ease of shopping and elegant presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond traditional offline media, online advertising is evolving
from simple banners to partnerships, such as portal agreements.
That alone can cost millions. Online advertising, which totaled
$2.8 billion in 1999, allows focused, targeted messages that reach
potential shoppers and result in sales conversions, say experts.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies, such as Fashionmall.com, seek a smart strategy
through a combination of offline and online advertising that pays
off in measurable costs and sales results.
</P>
<P>
   In business since 1994, Fashionmall.com is ancient compared with
many Internet players. The company's ad budget grew from $500,000
last year to $8 million this year, following an IPO and a total
redesign of the site last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to just throw money at advertising; you have
spend money smartly,'' said Ben Narasin, ceo. ``We've learned
through mistakes over the past few years what works best.''
</P>
<P>
   Offline spending includes traditional print and television, as
well as telephone kiosks, a Times Square wall, the ``7th on Sixth''
fashion show and even sandwich boards. A ``tease and reveal''
campaign featured a man and woman staring at a black dot with no
copy, with the company name and logo added later.
</P>
<P>
   The company's online investment went beyond banner advertising,
which has proven ineffective, to partnerships that really generate
traffic and acquire customers, said Narasin.
</P>
<P>
   Online partnerships are key for Ashford.com, a luxury goods
retail website launched in April 1998. With sales of $30 million
for fiscal 1999, the company's annual advertising budget is $17
million, with $10 million for fourth quarter alone, in anticipation
of big holiday demand.
</P>
<P>
   With 40 percent budgeted for online advertising, Ashford.com has
established multi-million dollar partnerships with AOL and Yahoo to
drive traffic to the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game is cost of customer acquisition,'' said
Kenny Kurtzman, ceo. ``Online advertising is efficient and highly
measurable in cost terms, while offline advertising is harder to
measure.''
</P>
<P>
   For offline spending, Ashford.com will use TV, radio and print.
For holiday, magazines include both fashion, food and financial
publications, such as Bon Appetit, Harpers, Fortune, Vanity Fair,
Vogue and Money.
</P>
<P>
   Beauty and fragrance sites, such as Jasmin.com, launched in
August, are finding direct mail and sampling to be as effective as
traditional media in promoting product. With an $8 million
marketing budget, Jasmin.com will promote its exclusive
distribution of the Hugo Boss fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   Jasmin.com's all-offline strategy includes over 30 million
on-page samples with fragrance on a gauze strip and a Jasmin.com ad
on the flip side. The Jasmin.com ad _ a woman surrounded by a green
veil _ conveys a sensual, emotional message meant to resonate with
fragrance buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the Internet clutter, the crazy spending, and many of
the dot com companies not being marketing experts, brand building
can still be hard,'' said Dale Dewey, president and ceo. ``But even
with the Internet, the normal ad rules still apply, and a good,
creative ad campaign can take you a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Georgia Lee is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
