<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-GENERAL-PRACTICE-STAR     11-22 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-PRACTICE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL MELODRAMA DOWN UNDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Steve Bisley and Zoe Carides in a scene
from ``General Practice.'') 
 By JUDITH ANDERSON  
 c.1999 The New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before there was ``E.R.,'' there was ``G.P.''
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Chicago Hope,'' ``L.A. Doctors'' or ``Providence,'' in
fact, while the doctor shows in this country consisted largely of
reruns of ``Marcus Welby'' or even ``Ben Casey,'' ``General
Practice'' was racking up every major television award in
Australia. From 1989 to 1996 it topped the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to suggest that it was a progenitor of the recent
barrage of American medical dramas, but now that it's being shown
in the United States on various syndication outlets, comparisons
are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the big difference: In the Australian series, neither
the physicians nor the patients think the doctor is God.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Practice'' is low-key and low-tech. No adrenaline
overdrive. No closeups of throbbing, bloody things on the operating
table. No arrogance. These docs make house calls, and they bring
their personal lives to work just like the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Practice'' focuses on the staff of the Ross Street
Surgery, a busy suburban medical practice. The central characters
include three doctors: The crusty, orthodox senior partner (Michael
Craig), an intense young woman (Zoe Carides) and a 40-something
army doctor (Steve Bisley) who has retired and taken up a civilian
practice in a final attempt to salvage his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   We see them in the round, so to speak, not only at times of
crisis. They're not specialists, so they routinely treat the whole
patient rather than merely his or her symptoms, and they seldom
rely on modern medicine's most sophisticated technology or its
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a cultural difference rather than a creative
one,'' Bisley says. ``In Australia, now as in the past, a general
practitioner usually operates in the suburbs and is very much a
part of his community _ a well-known part. He treats entire
families. If he lives long enough, he treats entire generations.
His reputation rests on good will and his ability to integrate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the episode that introduced Bisley's character, Dr. Henry
King, to the Ross Street practice, his ability to ``integrate'' was
tested by his new job and his new status as a recently separated
spouse and parent. His patients and colleagues were wary, and his
furious wife dumped a truckload of fill dirt across his gate _ a
perfect example of the show's trademark blend of medical and
personal drama with a touch of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the 13 episodes being broadcast in the show's
first American airing, Dr. King faces divorce, struggles with the
challenges of weekend parenting, copes with being single again, has
to change his military bedside manner to suit a civilian practice
and, eventually, develops a romance with Carides' character, Dr.
Sonia Kapek.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are questions and conditions men his age universally
face,'' says Bisley, who himself is close to Dr. King's age.
``There's confusion about roles, the disintegration of the family,
the pressures put on men without adequate support. They were
questions that interested me as a person as well as an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Bisley is one of Australia's big stars _ probably best
known to American audiences as Jim Goose in the film ``Mad Max''
(1979) _ Henry King is not at the center of each story. In fact,
the viewpoint frequently shifts away from any of the principal
characters.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one recent episode explores the ethics of a
couple's having a baby in order to use its umbilical-cord blood to
treat their daughter, who has leukemia. Sonia Kapek is their
general practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings between parents and doctor, the viewer picks up
information about the use of cord blood instead of a bone-marrow
transplant. Dr. Kapek moves the plot along, learning from
11-year-old Emily that she is no longer in remission, informing the
parents that the fetal blood does not match Emily's and urging the
mother to reconsider her decision to abort the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kapek acts as a catalyst and voices the moral concerns, but
in the hour-long episode she is on screen for less than 15 minutes.
Script and camera stay with the parties concerned, and when Emily
claps on headphones to block out her parents' angry, anguished
debate, we hear the argument as she does, through a barrage of hard
rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Practice'' isn't always about life and death. Mostly
it's just about life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Judith Anderson is a Tucson, Ariz.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
