<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARNOLD-SCHWARZENEGGER-IN-END-OF-DAYS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIAL MUSCLE: ARNOLD SCHWARZENEGGER BATTLES HELL ITSELF IN
`END OF DAYS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Arnold Schwarzenegger in a scene from
``End of Days.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Arnold is back.
 &HT;    After a two-year absence from the big screen, including time
spent recovering from heart surgery, Arnold Schwarzenegger, the
king of action films, is out to reclaim his crown. And the fight
commences with the millennial thriller ``End of Days.''
 &HT;    But this isn't quite the Arnold we used to know. The new film
offers up a more sensitive, less invincible Schwarzenegger, with
the 52-year-old uberstar cast as a suicidal security specialist who
finds himself trying to save a young woman (Robin Tunney) _ not to
mention the world _ from the Devil himself (Gabriel Byrne).
Naturally, Schwarzenegger must accomplish his task before the clock
strikes midnight on New Year's Eve, 1999.
 &HT;    How different is ``End of Days'' from, say, ``The Terminator''
(1984) or ``Eraser'' (1996)? Well, the big guy mopes. He cries. He
even gets beaten up by a little old lady.
 &HT;    ``It was very important to do the film in such a way that it
causes surprises all the way through,'' Schwarzenegger says,
looking hale and hearty during a press conference at New York's
Essex House hotel. ``Therefore we did not want to go in the
traditional way, which is that you come in as the hero, the knight
in shining armor, and the audience knows right away, `Ah, he's the
hero, he's perfect. He's going to kick some butt over here and he's
going to wipe out the enemy.'
 &HT;    ``That worked in the '80s and in the early '90s, but that
doesn't work today,'' the actor says. ``That's why I chose `End of
Days.' First of all, it shows the character as very vulnerable,
which is quite important. No. 2, it had all the twists and turns.
 &HT;    ``People never really know what's going to happen,'' he says.
``Here I start out for the first time with a gun to my head,
wanting to take my life. It's also the first time I'm on drugs, on
alcohol. I've lost my family. I've lost my job, my friends. This is
the end of the rope, and it's something I've never played.''
 &HT;    Schwarzenegger is on a roll.
 &HT;    ``People don't know, with this vulnerability, will the Devil
have success in seducing me?'' the actor says. ``Will I eventually
become possessed by the Devil? So the vulnerability factor was very
important in what I'd do to make the story work.
 &HT;    ``At the same time,'' he adds, ``on the other side of the coin,
we had to show the power of the Devil, what influence he has over
people. That made the stepmother/nanny, even though she's maybe a
65-year-old woman, extremely powerful internally and externally.
 &HT;    ``She threw me around like a doll,'' Schwarzenegger says,
chuckling heartily. ``When I read that, it was one of my favorite
scenes in the movie, because it's one of those you've never seen
before.
 &HT;    ``It's normally me always kicking butt,'' he says. ``For me to
get the beating, for me to go down and down and down in this movie,
and then have an arc where I can come back ...
 &HT;    ``Also,'' he adds, ``you realize that the gun power is not
really the ultimate power. It is something else, and that's the
basic message.''
 &HT;    Big news for a guy whose movies used to throw guns around the
way the Three Stooges threw pies. But the former Terminator insists
that the movie is all the more powerful for its greater emotional
range.
 &HT;    ``I didn't act the crying,'' says Schwarzenegger, who is married
to television personality Maria Shriver and has four children.
``You have to dig down deep inside and find the moments that are
very upsetting and do make you cry. Anybody who has a family, who
has children, very quickly thoughts can come to your mind that make
you cry.
 &HT;    ``At this point in my life, that was not the most difficult
thing to do,'' he says. ``I think the most challenging thing was
the acting and to always act out the vulnerability, the
helplessness.
 &HT;    ``Even though I pull myself together as a character and go, `OK,
now we're going to get some answers. Now we're going to do this,'
the fact of the matter is there was nowhere to go unless the
character changes as a person and I get rid of my hostilities and
my anger, and unless I look at faith as an option, look at inner
strength as an option.''
 &HT;    Born and raised a Catholic, Schwarzenegger says that he remains
committed to the Church.
 &HT;    ``I do have more faith now than I did when I was younger,'' he
adds, ``because my mother took me to church every Sunday, and to me
it was just an obligation so I didn't get smacked across the
face!''
 &HT;    The actor laughs loudly.
 &HT;    ``And then, later on, when I had a chance to rebel when I was 18
or 19 and I came to the United States and was riding high, being
the bodybuilding champion and all of that, I never went to
church,'' he recalls. ``I thought the whole thing was absolutely
absurd.
 &HT;    ``Then, when you get older _ and especially when you start
having children _ the whole thing comes back without anybody even
telling you.
 &HT;    ``The circle comes around again,'' Schwarzenegger says. ``You
start thinking about all the things your parents did and the things
that you rebelled against. It all of a sudden makes sense now, and
you're doing the teaching to your kids.
 &HT;    ``Then they'll rebel, and it's a continuous cycle.''
 &HT;    Schwarzenegger may have been off the screen for a while, but
he's making up for lost time. In early December he'll head up to
Vancouver, B.C., to shoot ``The Sixth Day,'' a cloning thriller.
After that he'll pick a new project from among ``Doc Savage,''
based on the classic pulp-novel character, and possible sequels to
``Total Recall'' (1990) and ``True Lies'' (1994).
 &HT;    He'd consider a ``Terminator 3,'' he adds, but only if director
James Cameron agreed to join him in making the film.
 &HT;    Not on his list, despite much-talked-about comments he made in a
recent magazine interview, is a run for public office.
 &HT;    ``I don't have anything planned,'' says Schwarzenegger, a
longtime Republican. ``I have thought about it several times ...
but right now I'm too heavily in show business.
 &HT;    ``I enjoy making movies,'' he says, ``and there are many more I
want to do. I don't see myself jumping ship and doing something
else yet.
 &HT;    ``Will it happen down the line? Could it happen?'' He pauses.
``Yes, it's possible.''
 &HT;    What's not possible, Schwarzenegger says, is his ever being won
over by the Devil.
 &HT;    ``There is no offer that he can make me, because I know _ from
all the research I've done and all my personal experience _
everything he has to offer me is a temporary pleasure,'' he says.
``That includes what you see in the movie ... That's the way it is
with the Devil, and you have to know that.
 &HT;    ``All the things that are easy to come by, that taste good, that
are good, that bring pleasure, could potentially backfire on you,''
he concludes. ``So you should not look at the easy way out, but
should set your goal, go for that and not get distracted by
anything else.''
 &HT;    Amen, Arnold.
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``End of Days,'' consult the
official Website at www.end-of-days.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
