<SLUG> BC-TIM-ROBBINS-DIRECTS-CRADLE-WILL-ROCK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIM ROBBINS: FILLING THE `CRADLE' WITH THE POLITICS OF ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Tim Robbins directing a scene from
``Cradle Will Rock.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He starred in ``The Player,'' but Tim Robbins refuses to play
the Hollywood game.
 &HT;    He avoids power lunches. He takes two years off to regroup
between films. And, oh yes, he makes strange movies about the
production of real-life plays back in the 1930s.
 &HT;    Tom Cruise he ain't. Brad Pitt he ain't.
 &HT;    ``Those guys are major players,'' Robbins says cheerfully.
``They have to deal with all the Hollywood hoopla.''
 &HT;    Well, now, of course Robbins has starred in some major studio
productions himself _ think ``Bull Durham'' (1988) and ``The
Shawshank Redemption'' (1994) _ and, for that matter, teams with
Susan Sarandon as one of Hollywood's favorite offscreen couples.
She even won an Oscar for her role as a Death Row nun in ``Dead Man
Walking'' (1994), a major-studio production directed by ... Robbins
himself.
 &HT;    ``Oh no, I'm not a player. I'm not in the inner club,'' the
41-year-old actor/director insists, widening his eyes and
contorting his round, practically ageless baby face into a smile.
``And I don't think I would like to be a player, because that's a
lot of fussability.''
 &HT;    Dressed casually in a white tank top, a gauzy beige shirt and
khaki pants, Robbins is at Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel for a
breakfast interview to promote ``Cradle Will Rock.''
 &HT;    That's his latest film as a director, opening Dec. 3. And, yes,
it's a $25 million film about the real-life production of a play _
the controversial 1937 musical drama ``The Cradle Will Rock'' by
Marc Blitzstein (Hank Azaria) _ more than 60 years ago.
 &HT;    When the play was dubbed an ``attack on capitalism,'' the WPA
Theatre canceled it. But the producers, including director Orson
Welles (Angus Macfayden) and actor/director John Houseman (Cary
Elwes) moved the show to another theater nearby, where it was
performed without scenery, props or costumes.
 &HT;    It became a hit and landed on Broadway.
 &HT;    ``To me,'' Robbins says, ``it's really about censorship and how
far an artist will go to have his or her voice heard by the
masses.''
 &HT;    Sarandon appears in the film, but it took a bit of negotiation,
Robbins adds.
 &HT;    ``After `Dead Man Walking,''' he says, ``Susan said she would
only work with me again if she could wear mascara and wear nice
clothes.''
 &HT;    Actually, given its political theme, ``Cradle Will Rock'' was a
natural for Sarandon, who _ like Robbins _ is a longtime liberal
advocate.
 &HT;    ``Please don't call this a political film,'' Robbins implores.
``I'm not interested in politics or political statements _ I'm
interested in telling stories about individuals and human
courage.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, he's quick to note that he strongly opposes
censorship and favors government funding of the arts _ with,
naturally, a spin of his own.
 &HT;    ``I can argue it either way,'' he says. ``Too much support is
bad. If there's not enough for an artist to be angry about and
overcome, I think it limits what that person is willing to say. I
think great art often comes out of deprivation and struggle.
 &HT;    ``At the same time,'' he continues, ``if I'm going to give $10
to the government, I'd like to see $9 spent on culture. That's only
my personal opinion.''
 &HT;    He laughs.
 &HT;    ``I don't know if we could run the country on that budget,'' he
says. ``But it would be a heck of a lot of fun.''
 &HT;    His latest directing effort talks about the idea of ``selling
out'' as an artist.
 &HT;    ``I've been there,'' he admits. ``I've done some cheesy
movies.''
 &HT;    Still, he says, he tries to retain some integrity.
 &HT;    ``You know what? I turned down $6 million the other day,'' he
says. ``It was a pretty good script, but I didn't want to do that
particular role.''
 &HT;    And, no, it wasn't easy.
 &HT;    ``Yeah, it hurts,'' Robbins says. ``But I've turned down money a
lot. I've said no to violent movies, I've said no to movies that
exploit women. I will not do a movie where there's a female
character who is simply there to be nude and have sex.
 &HT;    ``If I'm killing somebody in a script just to satisfy the most
basic needs of the audience, I will not be in that movie.''
 &HT;    He shrugs.
 &HT;    ``Then I go out and I see the actors who took those roles become
big stars,'' he says. ``I see them making even bigger money. And
sometimes I do wince a little bit.''
 &HT;    But that's the price you pay when you're a politically sensitive
actor/director who'd rather do a controversial money-loser like
``Bob Roberts'' (1992) than ``Mission Impossible XII.''
 &HT;    ``A politically sensitive actor,'' Robbins snorts. ``That's an
oxymoron!
 &HT;    ``Anyway, I hate the word `political,''' he adds. ``It implies
you're doing something for a beneficial reason for yourself _ if
you think about a politician making a political decision, they're
thinking about what's best for them.
 &HT;    ``And I don't have anything to do with politics,'' Robbins says
cheerfully. ``I hate politics. I hate politicians.''
 &HT;    The words he prefers are ``socially conscious,'' which covers a
range of concerns from feminism and the death penalty to
environmentalism and foreign arms sales.
 &HT;    It all began when he was growing up in New York's bohemian
Greenwich Village, he says.
 &HT;    ``Right now, I have an image of myself as a kid walking down the
street with my baseball glove,'' he recalls. ``And I'm walking past
some of the most exciting and strange people of the generation, and
not knowing I'm walking past them.
 &HT;    ``For instance, Bob Dylan lived right around the corner from
me,'' he says. ``I can actually dream a movie about it.''
 &HT;    Acting was a happy accident.
 &HT;    ``My sisters were involved in a theater company,'' he says,
``and I joined that at 12 years old. Basically, I was interested in
stealing some attention from my sisters. And it worked.
 &HT;    ``I think also I was at a stage where it was also about girls,''
Robbins says. ``And I think girls did like me better as an actor _
I remember the first time I did a play, all of a sudden I had a
girlfriend.''
 &HT;    He studied theater at UCLA, and in 1981 founded a theatrical
group, The Actor's Gang.
 &HT;    He met Sarandon on the set of ``Bull Durham,'' and the two have
been together for 12 years. They have two children together, as
well as her teen-age daughter, but have never married.
 &HT;    You'd think they would have, simply to avoid having to answer
the same questions, over and over again, about why they haven't
tied the knot.
 &HT;    ``I'm a supporter of the institution of marriage,'' Robbins says
patiently, ``and wholeheartedly stand by other people's right to
get married. It's just that I have no desire to get married, which
is a personal choice.''
 &HT;    Meanwhile, the two continue to live a very married life, somehow
juggling child-rearing and two busy Hollywood careers. Plus, of
course, a little political activism.
 &HT;    Not that Robbins would ever pull a Warren Beatty and flirt with
running for high office.
 &HT;    ``Me as president?'' he says, laughing hard. ``Maybe in another
`Austin Powers' movie.
 &HT;    ``But in real life? That would be a disaster!''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Cradle Will Rock,'' consult
the official Website at www.movies.go.com/cradlewillrock. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
