<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7691 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-PATRICK-STEWART-IN-A-     11-22 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRICK-STEWART-IN-A-CHRISTMAS-CAROL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRICK STEWART AND THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING SCROOGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Patrick Stewart in a scene from ``A
Christmas Carol.'') 
 By JEAN OPPENHEIMER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Only 12 years ago, Patrick Stewart had never even read ``A
Christmas Carol.''
 &HT;    He'd spent his whole life reading Shakespeare, Marlowe, Dickens
and the rest of the great-British-authors canon, but it was one of
those books that he sort of felt like he already knew without
bothering to read.
 &HT;    That changed when he finally did read it, in preparation for a
public reading he'd agreed to do at a benefit for the
organ-restoration fund at the Yorkshire church he had attended as a
child.
 &HT;    It's not too much to say that it changed his life. Three years
later, the English actor _ still best known as Capt. Picard in
television's long-running ``Star Trek: The Next Generation'' and
its big-screen sequels _ opened on Broadway in a one-man show.
Alone on stage, without sets, makeup or props, he performed ``A
Christmas Carol,'' playing 40 different characters to glowing
reviews and packed houses.
 &HT;    Every Christmas season since 1991, Stewart has performed the
show either in the United States or Britain. Despite numerous
offers, however, he has never mounted a fully dramatized version of
the story.
 &HT;    That ends Dec. 5, when Turner Network Television presents ``A
Christmas Carol,'' starring Stewart as Ebenezer Scrooge. Speaking
by telephone from Canada, where he is playing teen-mutant-mentor
Charles Xavier in the big-budget ``The X-Men,'' Stewart admits that
he'd had his reservations.
 &HT;    ``You might ask, why another `Christmas Carol?''' Stewart says.
``It's probably the most adapted work in the world, after the
Bible. Do we really need another one?''
 &HT;    His answer was an emphatic yes, as long as the television
version retained the key aspects of the original novel, which have
been softened in many of the adaptations.
 &HT;    ``Dickens the social critic was so present in `A Christmas
Carol,''' says the actor, a lifelong Socialist who heartily
endorses the story's underlying humanistic, anti-capitalist
message. ``Dickens was illustrating the impact of the economic
philosophy of someone like Scrooge on society. And after living
through Thatcherism and Reaganism, we are certainly familiar with
that in the West.
 &HT;    ``Scrooge is a proponent of market forces _ the strong must
prosper, and the weak will just have to do the best they can. And
if they have to go, well, they just have to go.''
 &HT;    Stewart also responds to the story on a personal level.
 &HT;    ``All of us are affected by the concept of a second chance,'' he
says. ``We have all thought, `If only I had this to do over again.'
And Ebenezer is given that chance.
 &HT;    ``Scrooge's experience was such that it led him to believe that
he couldn't rely on happiness, he couldn't depend on love, he
couldn't rely on something pleasant being forever,'' the actor
says. ``And therefore he cut himself off from being vulnerable to
that ever again.''
 &HT;    One of Stewart's closest friends, Bernard Lloyd, plays Marley in
the television movie. He told him that he thought Stewart would go
on playing Scrooge ``until I finally exorcised the Scrooge in
myself.''
 &HT;    It rang a bell, Stewart admits.
 &HT;    ``It's really just a question of withholding when you could be
more generous,'' he says thoughtfully. ``We run for cover so often.
It can be frightening to live openly in this world. In many
respects many of us are tortoises _ we pull our heads in.''
 &HT;    Stewart was born in northern England, the youngest of three
brothers. He discovered acting at 12, when a teacher asked him to
play the role of a schoolboy in a local amateur production. The
young Stewart felt immediately at home on stage, he recalls,
finding it an inexplicably comfortable, safe and familiar place to
be.
 &HT;    Acting soon became his passion, almost his obsession _ Stewart
recalls that, at 16, he found himself rehearsing for six different
plays at one time. After graduating from secondary school he
performed in the provinces, then was accepted into London's
prestigious Royal Shakespeare Company, where he spent 12 years
working with such esteemed directors as Peter Hall, Peter Brook and
Trevor Nunn.
 &HT;    They were only the latest in a series of mentors who had
inculcated the traditions of the British theater into the young
actor.
 &HT;    ``Certain standards were set that had to do with
professionalism, but they also influence how you live,'' he
recalls. ``The company you keep makes a difference. Things begin to
rub off.''
 &HT;    Bloodlines help, too. His mother had enjoyed acting, Stewart
says, frequently performing with an all-female theater group at the
local Methodist church. On his father's side, he later learned, his
grandfather had actually been a professional actor.
 &HT;    ``He was never spoken of, because he was the black sheep of the
family,'' Stewart says. ``He had deserted my grandmother and their
four small children. His name was William Stewart, and reportedly
he came to America and established a career here.''
 &HT;    Although Stewart maintains a home in the English countryside,
not far from where he grew up, he spends most of his working time
in the United States. In addition to his ``Star Trek'' credits, he
has also appeared in a number of feature films, among them
``Jeffrey'' (1996) and ``Conspiracy Theory'' (1996), as well as
such television programs as ``The Canterville Ghost'' (1995) and
``Animal Farm'' (1999), as the voice of Napoleon the pig. He has
done a great deal of Shakespeare throughout his career, including a
stint on Broadway two years ago in ``The Tempest.''
 &HT;    Just as writers are frequently accused of writing basically the
same story over and over again, Stewart says, actors have a
tendency to keep returning to similar themes.
 &HT;    ``I have certainly seen a pattern in my choices over the past 10
or 15 years, and it doesn't make a very rosy picture,'' he admits
with a rueful laugh. ``Prospero, Captain Ahab, Othello, a role I
did in an Arthur Miller play last year _ they are all people
possessed by different things and trying to free themselves from
that obsession.''
 &HT;    Many of his characters also are noteworthy for their
self-destructive streaks.
 &HT;    ``That connects them, too, and it's not accidental,'' he says,
``although I often don't realize it until after I take the part.
That's one of the wonderful things about being an actor _ we get a
chance, as in the most effective therapy, to play out the themes.
 &HT;    ``I hope I can exorcise the Scrooge in myself without doing `A
Christmas Carol' forever and ever.''
 &HT;    But ``A Christmas Carol'' has been a constant in Stewart's life
for many years now, and he admits that the book which took him so
long to get to still fascinates him.
 &HT;    ``Here's this little Victorian novelette, easily overlooked,
frequently written off as a minor Dickens, a Victorian sentiment,''
he says. ``And yet it proves to be one of the most potent morality
tales in the English language.''
 c.1999 Jean Oppenheimer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jean Oppenheimer is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``A Christmas Carol,'' consult
the TNT Website at tnt.turner.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
