<HEADER>
A7694 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MOVIE-RIDE-DEVIL-REVI     11-22 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RIDE-DEVIL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RIDE' CAPTURES A NATION IN CULTURAL AND PHYSICAL COMBAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:  3 stars  
(Eds: Not for use before Wednesday, Nov. 24) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less a combat movie than an acutely observed look at America on
the brink of change, Ang Lee's ``Ride With the Devil'' is a Civil
War film loaded with subtext. Lee isn't so much interested in
battles or bloodshed _ although there is plenty of both _ as he is
in the passing of the cultural torch. And he captures that moment
rather well.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has always displayed an expert ability for presenting slices
of societal flux. He did it most impressively with his last film,
``The Ice Storm,'' a movie that hit on feelings of isolation and
angst in '70s suburbia. With ``Devil,'' Lee is preoccupied with
examining the death of the Southern way of life and how the Union's
victory emancipated not only the slaves, but other outsiders as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The film takes place on the Missouri-Kansas border, where
Southern Bushwackers and Union Jayhawkers chaotically roam the
countryside, dispensing guerrilla justice as they see fit. In the
movie's opening moments, Lee introduces us to the Confederates and
their families, whose lives are about to be brutally changed by the
encroaching Union army.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing their enemy, the gentlemanly Jack Bull Chiles (Skeet
Ulrich) and his best friend, a quiet German immigrant Jake
``Dutchy'' Roedel (Tobey Maguire) join a group of Bushwackers that,
apart from all the killing, exhibit a courtly grace peculiar to the
horrors of war. One of them even brings along his slave, Daniel
Holt (Jeffrey Wright), who loyally fights on the side of the South
while quietly looking to make his own path.
</P>
<P>
   During the winter, Jack and Jake hole up outside a
Confederate-friendly home where they meet a young, self-possessed
widow, Sue Lee (pop singer Jewel). As the conflict (and savagery)
intensifies, the film shifts its focus to the three principal
outsiders _ immigrant, slave and young woman _ as they confront the
notion of freedom and its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   In adapting Daniel Woodrell's 1987 novel ``Woe to Live On,''
Lee's writing and producing partner James Schamus paints the period
in appropriate shades of gray. Lee continues to amaze with his
ability to deliver small, telling details, a marvelous gift that
makes it easy to overlook some of the film's failings.
</P>
<P>
   Wright is the real find in the ensemble cast, powerfully playing
a character who remains silent (out of necessity) for much of the
film. Jewel, making her film debut, acquits herself nicely, giving
Sue Lee a calm conviction. James Caviezel, Jonathan Rhys Meyers and
Simon Baker round out the Bushwackers with impressive style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Devil'' isn't always successful in defining its characters,
but its message never wavers: Freedom comes with a price, and
sometimes that means changing a culture. It's a point well taken in
a moment of history where America still struggles to do the right
thing for all of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The film: &LR;  ``Ride With the Devil'' (R; graphic war violence). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Skeet Ulrich, Tobey Maguire, Jewel, Jeffrey Wright. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Ang Lee. Screenplay by James
Schamus, based on the novel ``Woe to Live On'' by Daniel Woodrell.
Released by USA Films. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  Two hours, 14 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Playing: &LR;  Mann's Criterion in Santa Monica; GCC Beverly Connection
in Los Angeles; Cineplex Odeon Century Plaza Cinemas in Century
City. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
