 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``l''
lifestyle news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABILENE, KANSAS _ Around the corner from the Dwight D.
Eisenhower presidential library in Abilene, Kan., is the Museum of
Independent Telephony.
</P>
<P>
   Its 20,000 visitors a year see a bewildering collection, ranging
from wooden wall phones, ``candlestick'' phones and old pay phones,
to switchboards and a reconstructed operator's lair.
</P>
