<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECKLESS-RUMORS-EGYPTAIR-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS FBI LEAKING IRRESPONSIBLE THEORIES ON EGYPTAIR CRASH?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Note last graf)   (RESENDING from Nov. 18 for those needing)  
  
 (This excellent 1,000-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The mystery of what happened to the Egyptair Boeing
767 which crashed off the U.S. coast two weeks ago may finally be
solved this week, as the tape from the cockpit voice recorder is
painstakingly transcribed and analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation in British and American media has so far blamed
mechanical failure, a struggle between the crew, a bomb, a hijack
and a suicidal crew member, without any evidence whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators from America's National Transportation and
Safety Board have been extremely careful not to speculate, and the
lack of any ``steer'' has to some extent encouraged the media to
make up theories.
</P>
<P>
   But the nationality of the crew and the plane have also
apparently encouraged reporters to make irresponsible guesses at
what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In previous crashes, infighting between the U.S. agencies
investigating the incident has contributed to a welter of
conflicting stories about the cause. This time, the authorities
have sought to stop speculation by focusing on the facts.
</P>
<P>
   But anonymous sources from one U.S. agency have repeatedly
leaked their views to the press.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest indications from the cockpit voice recorder are
that there was a problem with the aircraft, the crew tried to deal
with it, but that things went rapidly from bad to worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something happens. Alarms go off. Both work to try to fix
it,'' an unnamed source told the Associated Press after the
investigators listened to the tape for the first time. ``There is
some kind of problem that they're dealing with. It gets
progressively worse. And the tape stops.''
</P>
<P>
   The source, however, apparently did not speak Arabic and had not
understood anything on the tape, which tends to undermine his
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   From the aircraft's flight data recorder, it is known that for
some reason the crew disengaged the autopilot. The aircraft began
dropping from 33,000 feet at a 40-degree angle, reaching a speed
just short of the sound barrier, and reaching zero gravity.
</P>
<P>
   The engines were apparently manually shut down during the dive.
It reached 16,000 feet and then climbed back up to 24,000 feet
before falling rapidly again and breaking up. This pattern of
events does not fit readily with any known course of action in
response to a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The first reports from the voice recorder did seem to lessen the
probability of one of the many competing, and contradictory,
accounts made up in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication of a fight between the crew, who were
speaking ``like pals,'' said AP. Nor was there any sign that
someone had entered the cockpit. Indeed, there was never any
evidence whatsoever for this theory.
</P>
<P>
   A government official told Newsweek magazine that Boeing was
``pushing'' the theory that a cockpit struggle was responsible for
the crash. Boeing denied this. If mechanical failure is the cause,
then there might be serious implications for Boeing, including
legal action.
</P>
<P>
   The supposition of a cockpit fight was based on the fact that
the flight elevators had been moved in opposite directions moments
before the aircraft crashed, and from this the inference was drawn
that the pilot and co-pilot were acting against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Equally, it assumed that the decision to shut off the autopilot
and the engines were irrational, something that cannot be known
until the causes of the aircraft's initial problem are known.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation that one of the crew might have tried to kill
himself, or have fought with his colleagues, was based on no
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It seems highly unlikely that U.S. newspapers would have made
these accusations against an America pilot who had died in similar
circumstances, and the families and friends of the crew have
understandably responded angrily to these libels.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Ahmed al Habashy, the lead pilot, was stable and happy,
his wife and brother have said. He was close to retirement. ``He
never smoked or drank alcohol,'' his brother told Agence France
Presse. ``He had no bad habits. He was very religious and prayed
and was always reading the Koran,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Herald felt it necessary to add that he was ``not an
extremist.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-pilot Adel Anwar was due to be married five days after the
flight and had exchanged slots with another flight officer to
return home sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Other theories with equally little evidence have also surfaced.
The first was that the reverse thrusters might have malfunctioned,
based on a similiar crash of a Boeing 767 in Thailand _ an aircraft
that was made at the same time as the Egyptair plane. The data
recorders seemed to rule this out.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Herald reported that a flight attendant called Hassan
Sherif telephoned his wife, Rania, from New York to say ``there was
something wrong with the plane'' and that he was ``very worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Egyptair said that there was a flight attendant on the aircraft
called Hassan Farouk, not Hassan Sherif. Rania Reda is his fiancee,
not his wife. ``He just told me that the plane was delayed at Los
Angeles and he is waiting for the plane,'' Reda told Associated
Press Television News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   More than one newspaper has blamed terrorism, citing the
aircraft's flight profile, the suddenness of the problem and the
lack of a distress call. It has also been noted that the aircraft
had a large number of Egyptian military personnel on it.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI have given no signs that they are actively looking at
terrorism as a likely cause, though some kind of sudden incident
might have led the aircraft to depressurize rapidly, and the crew
might then have taken it lower.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaks from the inquiry may come from the FBI, which
would take over the investigation if there was a strong presumption
of criminal activity. The FBI has been heavily criticized for a
number of investigations recently, and is seeking extra funds for
an expansion and reorganization of its activities _ including a new
counter-terrorism unit. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 1,000-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper
in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
