<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Beware of Greeks bearing flags
 &HT;    For release Nov. 24, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The demonstrators have been described both as anarchists and
communists; an awkward alignment of contrasting beliefs. They tore
through the streets of downtown Athens, torching businesses,
looting and, of course, burning the American flag practically under
the nose of visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many amendments the Congress tries to shove into
our Constitution, one banning flag burning will have no consequence
in Athens, or Baghdad, even Belgrade. They're beyond our
Constitutional reach. Where they get all those flags to burn is of
interest to me, as I would like to buy into what must be a
profitable business of supplying particularly incendiary American
flags to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, 10,000 Greeks torched their own capital _ and some
American flags _ to protest U.S. policy in Yugoslavia, Kosovo and
Bosnia, all of which shows you how stupid they are. ``We've Burned
Ourselves,'' Reuters News Service quoted a leading Athens newspaper
headline.
</P>
<P>
   It always has impressed me that American flags are game for
flame for any of our diverse worldwide foreign policies but when
the Soviets and, now, the Russians are involved in controversial
conduct, it doesn't seem to happen.
</P>
<P>
   This likely is because no one is producing Russian flags as
quickly as they are American flags. Availability is critical to
flag burners.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Russians slaughtering Chechnyans and, several years
earlier, Afghans, there seems to be a noticeable need for Russian
flags to burn. As we mass produce American flags for foreign
conflagration, we ought to think of doing the same with Russian
flags. We could be well into a thriving export business which would
go toward helping us repay some of the money we either loan or
otherwise allow to sift into foreign hands.
</P>
<P>
   With the anarchist/communist underbelly of Greece evident and
with Clinton, in one of his Jimmy Carter-like moments of contrition
over the U.S. supporting a Greek military junta in 1967, I was
wondering if anyone in Greece was considering thanking us for other
measures we took on behalf of the Greek people?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps memories do not go back as far as 1947 when Harry Truman
and the U.S. Congress rushed to support the Greek people who were
threatened by advancing Soviet communism. Hundreds of millions of
dollars were shipped to Athens so the nation could remain
independent of Soviet control.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, things did go bad with the junta we supported in
1967, especially the deadly crackdown it committed on student
demonstrators in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a Cold War thing, us supporting the military right
against a rebellious left that was tied to the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   That left apparently has not forgotten the U.S. and the junta,
and never wanted to remember the U.S. saving Greece from communism
in 1947. Each year at this time, much of the same group stages
anti-American protests for our support of the junta. Usually, it
goes unnoticed by the world media. But when the president of the
United States happens to be in Greece at the same time, followed by
a press corps the size of Texas, it becomes more of a launching pad
for violence and grievance.
</P>
<P>
   This is the cost of being a world policeman. I don't believe
that the U.S. so much wants to be the global cop as it has been
kept in that position by a world that cannot get along, either
internally or across borders.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of that assignment, mistakes certainly can be
made. They subsequently result in flag burning and other
interruptions to normal relations. The Chinese went on a nifty
flag-burning bent after we mistakenly and stupidly bombed their
embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-American protest in Athens had to do more with ethnic
bonding than anything else. The Greeks are close to the Serbians,
just as are the Russians. No matter the ritual slaughter of
Albanian Kosovars at the hands of the Serbians, which brought the
U.S. into the melee, the Serbians could do no wrong in the minds of
the protesting Athenians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit simply inflamed the fringe of Greek politics.
</P>
<P>
   And it did wonders for the flag salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com(.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
