<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THRILLERS ON TAPE SHOWCASE WOMEN AUTHORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cold Hit,'' by Linda Fairstein. Read by Allison Janney.
Abridged, approximately 4.5 hours. Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio. $24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death Du Jour,'' by Kathy Reichs. Read by Katherine Borowitz.
Abridged, approximately 4.5 hours. Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio. $24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gravity,'' by Tess Gerritsen. Read by Campbell Scott.
Abridged, approximately 4.5 hours. Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio. $25.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery-thriller genre long ago stopped being a men's club.
For almost two decades Sue Grafton and other women have
demonstrated that either gender is capable of capturing the
public's fancy with well-conceived characters, fresh plots and a
fine eye for detail.
</P>
<P>
   What is relatively new, however, is the growing number of
successful, professional women who are turning to writing in their
spare time, crafting thrillers out of their chosen careers.
Patricia Cornwall, the forensic pathologist, probably opened the
door farther than anyone else, but others are quickly following,
crossing the threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes Fairstein, Reichs and Gerritsen interesting to
contrast. Read with flawless style by screen and stage veterans
Janney, Borowitz and Scott, respectively, these three authors'
books on tape can best be separated by how well they adhere to the
basics of the mystery genre, as well as their own careers.
</P>
<P>
   Fairstein, a sex crimes prosecutor in the Manhattan district
attorney's office, and Reichs, a professor and forensic
anthropologist for North Carolina's chief medical examiner, have
each started a series based on what each woman knows best.
Fairstein has created Alexandra Cooper, an assistant DA, while
Reichs' alter-ego is Dr. Temperance Brennan, a forensic
anthropologist based in Montreal, where Reichs spends parts of each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Both have mastered the genre, sharing the drama of their working
worlds through fictional characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Hit,'' Fairstein's third, may be her best yet. She has
Cooper navigating the slippery sanctums of art galleries and forged
masterpieces while being stalked herself. ``Death Du Jour'' is
Reichs' second, and it is every bit as good as her debut, ``Deja
Dead.'' She has Brennan unraveling a case that takes her back and
forth between Montreal and the Carolinas, mining the physical
worlds she knows best, too.
</P>
<P>
   Neither woman has quit her so-called day job, though it would
seem they could if they so desired. Both have enjoyed best-seller
status right out of the box. Money must be a non-issue. Maybe
neither is sure if writing is what she really wants to do, though
each has demonstrated that she can handle this craft just as deftly
as the high-powered jobs they have both thrived in.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to Gerritsen, who has abandoned a successful
practice as an internist to devote all her attention to writing
thrillers. She also has seen her books reach the best-seller lists,
but it's almost impossible to understand why.
</P>
<P>
   With each story _ ``Gravity'' is her fourth _ Gerritsen goes
farther over the top, taking medical mysteries into the terrain of
science fiction. She knows about intubating and other procedures,
to be sure, but she appears to be way out of her element writing
about a NASA space station that has been infected by deadly,
contagious cells.
</P>
<P>
   Masters of this genre don't necessarily have to create a central
character around whom they anchor their tales, but such a device
gives the writer a focal point and can keep her centered. It's
working well for Fairstein and Reichs, and I suspect Gerritsen
would benefit in a big way if she found a heroine for her harrowing
stories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1323EST &QL; 
