<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO IT'S COME TO THIS POINT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did you notice the scores? Virginia Tech 62, Temple 7. Kansas
State 66, Missouri 0.
</P>
<P>
   Mismatches for sure. But no matter what anyone tells you, the
totality of the routs was not an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of the Bowl Championship Series rankings,
where it's not so much whether you win, but by how much.
</P>
<P>
   We are at the stage of the season when the computers and their
printouts will crunch the numbers to determine who plays Florida
State in the Sugar Bowl for the national championship Jan. 4 in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech, ranked No. 2 but feeling the breath of Nebraska
on its back, is lobbying hard for a spot in the game, and knows
that victory margin is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Saddled with a weak schedule _ according to the computers _ the
Hokies are not a slam dunk to make it to New Orleans even if they
beat Boston College Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska maintains it still has a chance if it beats Colorado
Friday, then wins the Big 12 title game against Texas in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State also believes it has a chance if Nebraska is beaten
and BC can upset Virginia Tech. But the Wildcats know they have to
make some points, so to speak, with their margins of victory. Thus
the destruction of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that what the BCS wanted when they set up this thing?''
asked one coach Sunday. ``People running up the scores, creating
bad feelings. That doesn't seem like the best system.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't, but it's the only system that is in place right now.
Saturday's games cleared up the picture somewhat. Florida State is
11-0 and has one slot clinched.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech and Nebraska seem the leading contenders to fill
the other slot.
</P>
<P>
   And with it all a numbers game, look for Virginia Tech to show
no mercy from the opening kickoff against BC. This will not be a
casual game, where winning is the only thing that matters.
</P>
<P>
   That will put BC in an interesting situation. The Eagles are
flying after their 31-29 win over Notre Dame. At worst they're
going to Tucson to play a Big 12 team in the New Year's Eve
Insight.com Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   There is still an outside possibility of the Eagles going to
Jacksonville for the Gator Bowl Jan. 1. But that would require a
win over Virginia Tech and a Miami loss to either Syracuse or
Temple the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling among the people running the bowls is that Miami
would bring no one to Tucson but might bring some fans to
Jacksonville, while BC has a better chance of attracting fans to
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   So why not take care of both bowls and both teams by sending the
Eagles to Tucson and the Hurricanes to Jacksonville?
</P>
<P>
   As for the other BCS bowls, this is the way the situation looks
right now, projecting Virginia Tech and Florida State in the Sugar
Bowl: Fiesta Bowl _ Nebraska vs. Tennessee; Orange Bowl _
Florida-Alabama winner vs. Michigan; Rose Bowl _ Stanford vs.
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a roll
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UMass, fresh off a 62-20 win over UConn, will face Furman in
Saturday's Division 1-AA opening-round playoff game. ``We're
playing pretty good now,'' said UMass coach Mark Whipple. ``Better
than we were at this time last year.'' Which, of course, turned
into a national championship season . . . The situation at North
Carolina has turned ugly now that it appears coach Carl Torbush
will be fired. Torbush got only two years out of a five-year
contract to prove he could run the Tar Heels program. Last year he
went 7-5 and reached a bowl game. This year he was 3-8 with an
injury-riddled team, finishing the season with a 38-0 win over Duke
Saturday. ``It's not fair. It's not right,'' said Tar Heels punter
Brian Schmitz. ``For a school as classy as North Carolina to be so
classless is mind-boggling.'' Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tame Lions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nice finish for Penn State, which went from the BCS title game
to maybe the Outback Bowl with three consecutive losses, including
a 35-28 setback to Michigan State Saturday. An interesting bowl
matchup would be Penn State-Mississippi State, pitting Paterno vs.
old nemesis Jackie Sherrill. This is the first time Penn State
ended the regular season with three straight losses since 1914 . .
. It looks like Michigan State, which had the same record and won
the head-to-head meeting against Michigan, will be relegated to the
Citrus Bowl, while the Wolverines get a BCS at-large berth. The
reason? Michigan has more appeal for television . . . Another
intriguing matchup would be Hawaii vs. Oregon State in Honolulu on
Christmas Day, matching two coaches who were in the NFL last
season. June Jones was in San Diego and Dennis Erickson was in
Seattle. Both have made the smooth transition back to the college
game. Oregon State is playing in its first bowl game since 1964,
while Hawaii went from a winless season to a share of the WAC
championship in one year . . . Georgia Tech's stunning loss to Wake
Forest wiped out the slim chance that quarterback Joe Hamilton had
of catching Wisconsin running back Ron Dayne in the Heisman Trophy
race . . . Star of the year has to be Texas Christian running back
LaDainian Tomlinson, who broke the NCAA Division 1-A rushing record
for a game by picking up 406 yards (and scoring six touchdowns) in
a 52-24 win over Texas-El Paso . . . More bad news for South
Carolina, which finished an 0-11 season with a 31-21 loss to
Clemson. The Gamecocks became the first team in SEC history to
finish 0-11 without forfeits . . . With Notre Dame no longer
eligible, the Big East is set to place four teams in bowl games.
The conference could have five teams eligible if Pittsburgh beats
West Virginia Saturday. But if Syracuse loses to Miami, count on
the Orangemen being the odd-team out, with Pitt getting the Big
East's Music City Bowl slot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
