<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY RETIREMENT REQUIRES SAVING EVEN MORE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I would like your opinion on whether I am on the right track.
I am 39 and have the following investments: A Putnam IRA account of
$200,000, divided evenly between Putnam Growth Equity Investors and
Putnam Voyager, to which I add $500 a month; a variable annuity
account of $45,000 divided evenly among Fidelity Contrafund, Janus
Balanced, Janus Worldwide, MFS Research, and T. Rowe Price Equity
Income funds, to which I add $1,000 a month; a holding in Mainstay
Capital Appreciation fund of $30,000, to which I add $1,000 a
month; and $15,000 in a checking account bearing a high interest
level. I am in software sales and earn about $120,000 a year. Am I
saving enough for retirement in 16 years? Would you recommend
changing any of my positions?
</P>
<P>
   S.A., Falmouth, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You'd be close to a comfortable position, depending on how
much you think you will need.
</P>
<P>
   If your entire portfolio (including your bank savings) grew at
an average 10 percent rate, and if you continue contributions at
the current $2,500 a month rate, you would amass $2,460,625.
</P>
<P>
   After deducting the amount you are saving, you are currently
living on $90,000 a year. To get the same buying power as $90,000
brings today, you would need $156,058 after 16 years if inflation
averaged 3.5 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought you could live on the equivalent of $72,000 _ 80
percent of your current after-savings income _ you would need
$124,864. If you thought you could reduce your living expenses to
60 percent of their current level, you would need $93,635 income in
your first year of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   When you retire at a fairly early age, its important that you
have a sizable amount of savings in excess of what you need to
provide your income stream.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, when you retire at age 55, it's possible your
retirement could last 40 years or so, and you will need to be able
to protect yourself against the inflation that's likely during
those later years.
</P>
<P>
   A comfortable margin might be to have two-thirds of your savings
providing your income stream, with the rest in reserve, invested in
growth securities to deal with that inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to that original projection, this means that you
might draw on $1,640,416 to provide income. If fixed-income yields
are in the neighborhood of 6.5 percent, that would mean you would
have $106,6276 to live on _ the equivalent of $61,500 in today's
money.
</P>
<P>
   But there are several positive factors that I am overlooking.
One is that if you increase your savings rate proportionally to any
increases in income, the projected accumulation would likely be
higher. Second, at some point you can probably count on some
benefits from Social Security, which will allow you to reduce your
reliance on your savings for an income stream. And third, the model
I have devised basically presumes that you want to live through
retirement in the happy position of seeing very little or no loss
of your capital.
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, you have limited interest in leaving an
estate, you can certainly draw much higher amounts from the savings
pool, seeking to manage things so that you will live comfortably
and will have sufficient funds to last out your life, but not
necessarily to make your heirs ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   As for your portfolio, I tally more that 87 percent of your
holdings in large-cap domestic stocks, which is far too much. Only
your cash savings, MFS Research, and portions of the holdings in
Janus Worldwide and Janus Balanced represent diversifications away
from that segment.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you limit the large-cap domestic segment of the total
portfolio to about 60 percent, building positions in small- and
mid-cap funds and increasing your overseas investments.
</P>
<P>
   A quick way to begin with the latter is to swap Janus Worldwide
(which holds about 35 percent of its portfolio in domestic issues)
for Janus Overseas, which holds a portfolio entirely devoted to
foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are 32 and 31, respectively. We have a
3-year-old son and a 7-month-old daughter. Our savings are these:
$4,500 in US Savings bonds; $11,683 in traditional IRAs, of which
$7,300 is in a CD and the rest in stock funds; $10,600 in Roth
IRAs; 9,000 in taxable mutual fund accounts; $2,000 in credit union
savings; and $6,000 in individual stocks. We fully fund both IRAs
each year, and add a total of $550 a month to the other accounts.
We would like to retire at age 60 and to have a comfortable fixed
income, which I would guess to be $2,500 a month at today's values.
In addition to the assets above, I plan to have a military
retirement, plus a retirement from a future occupation. However, I
would like to find the road to a comfortable retirement without
counting on these retirement benefits. I feel we are way behind.
Can we get there from here?
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Cape Cod, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Although your total savings of $42,238 doesn't seem like a
huge nest egg, you have a lot of time to work on it. If you
maintain savings at the current level, and if your portfolio grows
at an average 10 percent rate for the next 28 years, you would
accumulate $1,929,323.
</P>
<P>
   You would require $78,605 a year to give you the same buying
power as $30,000 provides now, presuming inflation averages 3.5
percent. If a fixed-income portfolio could bring you an average 6.5
yield in 28 years, you would need only a little more than $1.2
million to fulfill your target.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of your accumulation could then be left in growth
vehicles to protect you against inflation. And any military and
civilian employment pension benefits you may earn would simply be
gravy. In short, far from being way behind, you are nicely on
schedule, and way ahead of many, many people who write to me.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all of that pleasant news is based on the idea that you
achieve 10 percent average portfolio returns on your retirement
portfolio. You suggested a few changes in a part of your letter I
edited out, involving the savings bonds and the CD account among
your traditional IRA holdings.
</P>
<P>
   I agree that both of these are likely to provide a long-term
drag on your portfolio, and would move the CD money into the USAA
S&AMP;P 500 fund that is currently among your traditional IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the savings bonds, I would move both that money and the
ongoing contributions to a health care fund that concentrates on
medical equipment and pharmaceutical companies, such as Fidelity
Select Health Care fund.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I suggest you set a target dollar amount to accumulate
in your credit union account as emergency savings, and once that
target is reached, divert the $200 monthly contribution that is now
going into that account to investments with greater long-term
potential. The two fund categories that you might focus upon at
that point are international and small-cap funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm 85 and no longer have any money in stocks; all my money
is in CDs. Lately I've noticed that banks are offering CDs for
periods of six or seven or 11 months. I'm thinking that something
is fishy in Denmark. Please enlighten us.
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Chula Vista, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think what you're seeing is the vehicles that banks are
promoting.
</P>
<P>
   You can still find CDs at the traditional durations, but given
the current uncertain interest rate climate, they aren't
particularly attractive, and they aren't being promoted very much.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure you've noticed that in normal markets the longer you
put your money in a CD, the higher the rate you will be paid.
</P>
<P>
   But entering this week in the Boston market, three of nine banks
reporting CD rates are offering a lower rate for a 30-month CD than
for a 12-month certificate. A fourth offers 30- and 12-month CDs at
the same rate.
</P>
<P>
   The same uneven situation prevails, to a lesser extent,
nationally. As this is written, according to bankrate.com, the
national average for a 48-month CD is 5.46 percent _ lower than the
5.65 percent average for a 36-month CD and identical to the rate
for both 24- and 30-month CDs.
</P>
<P>
   So my take on this is that bankers are unenthusiastic about
writing some of the longer-term CDs, and thus have focused their
promotions on shorter issues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
