<HEADLINE>
DOMINANT DAVENPORT A TALL ORDER FOR HINGIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Martina Hingis's mother undoubtedly told her there'd
be days like this. That's what mothers are for: to warn their
offspring that no matter how well things are going, somebody might
just step up and flatten you.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was one of those very rare days for Martina Hingis, the
No. 1 tennis player in the universe, who was knocked flatter than
the world before Columbus by Lindsay Davenport. Martina could have
masqueraded as a tortilla after Davenport worked her over, 6-4,
6-2, using a racket as a rolling pin.
</P>
<P>
   Bygone fight manager Joe Jacobs had an expression for what
happened on the blue carpeted rectangle of Madison Square Garden.
``We shoulda stood in bed!'' he would lament after one of his pugs
``got ruint.''
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis's mother/mentor/coach, Melanie Molitor, looked
like she was taking it on the chin, too. She sat in the first row,
among 14,653 patrons of the Chase Championships, the last roundup
of the century for the young brilliants of the game, with her eyes
popping at what Davenport was doing to her kid.
</P>
<P>
   Every time 6-foot-3-inch Davenport erupted with an ace or a
torrid, winning blast, Mom Molitor flinched sympathetically. She
resembled the venerable Boston pugilistic trainer, Al Lacy, whose
head jerked every time his middleweight champ, Paul Pender, got
hit.
</P>
<P>
   Martina got hit with winners so many times that she could have
modeled as a cheese from her homeland, Switzerland. This was not
Hingis bringing ruin on herself with errors; she committed but
seven. No, this was Davenport _ her left wrist aching and left
thigh tightly strapped _ crunching everything in sight, slugging
.726 with the stupendous total of nine aces and 36 winners of 62
points in 61 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Martina could run, but there was no shelter within the rectangle
as the ever-increasingly nimble Lindsay arrived everywhere the
Swiss kid figured she couldn't. Lindsay crushed the rubber lemons
so resoundingly you thought they would spurt juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't give me a chance,'' Hingis said accurately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best match I've played, especially when you
consider the opposition,'' Davenport said accurately.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay's was a tour de force of baselining, scampering,
serving, and volleying such as this climactic tourney has seldom
witnessed. Almost a quarter-century had passed since a similar
one-sided score was registered in a title bout: Chris Evert over
Martina Navratilova, 6-4, 6-2, at Los Angeles in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Jean King, the champ who launched the Long Way Babies of
female tennis in 1972, calls Hingis ``a tennis genius,'' and she is
right. But even Einstein probably had days like this when his
theory of relativity seemed relatively irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport was irreverent in her treatment of the genius. But
that doesn't mean 19-year-old Martina's wizardry won't continue to
drive most of her foes wrong-footedly mad as she weaves her
shotmaking webs, such as the one in which Venus Williams was
trapped in the semis, 6-4, 7-6 (7-2).
</P>
<P>
   However, Little Miss No. 1 is ever at risk in the land of the
sinewy, power-dealing giants: the Sisters Sledgehammer (Venus and
Serena Williams), Davenport, 6-foot Mary Pierce, and sizeable
Barbara Schett and Amelie Mauresmo. Taking them on,
back-to-brawny-back, as she did at the US Open (beating Venus,
losing the title to Serena) may make her wish she was Atlas in
drag. The Venus-Lindsay combo within 24 hours proved too much.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Jean, gold medalist Davenport's Olympic coach and
Federation Cup captain, grins, ``Lindsay fully believes in herself
these days. It took a while to believe that she could lose the
excess weight and be a genuine champ. She is the finest striker of
the ball in the game _ and will get better.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Medusa, the Women's Tennis Association computer,
Hingis and Davenport are 1-2 for the year. But the public
perception must be that Lindsay, with her Wimbledon and Chase
triumphs and five other titles, is the player of the year _
finishing driving, as they say at the track.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the genius in her family was sitting in the fourth row,
mom Anne Davenport, who says, ``I just thought Lindsay should have
her own game.'' She meant that the family was immersed in
volleyball, papa an Olympian, mom and two other daughters
first-class players. ``When Lindsay showed an aptitude for tennis,
I encouraged her'' _ although the rest of her family was pushing
volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   The twine barrier between them must have seemed as high as a
volleyball net to Hingis, and Mt. Davenport as formidable as Etna.
</P>
<P>
   They will meet again, often. ``They're two of the reasons the
women's game has never been better,'' applauds their spiritual
mother, Billie Jean.
</P>
<P>
   Closing her thundering recital with three of her nine aces _ ``I
never did that before'' _ Lindsay actually rolled an 11. ``Really?
I won the last 11 points?''
</P>
<P>
   She did. With her hot hands, and 11s up her short sleeve, maybe
Long Lindsay should visit another sporting rectangle _ a Vegas
craps table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COPELAND-2000-2NDTAKE     11-22 1790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPELAND-2000-2NDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: with Bernstein. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one prelude concert the Sextet for Clarinet, Piano and String
Quartet will be performed. This is actually a 1937 arrangement of
Copland's Short Symphony (1933), an orchestral work renowned for
its difficulties: relentless syncopations, crisscrossing rhythms
and almost constantly changing meters. Stravinsky wrote few pieces
stronger than this sextet. Yet it seldom turns up in chamber music
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Another inexplicable rarity is the Piano Fantasy, which the
pianist Michael Boriskin will perform in the festival. Completed in
1957 after several years of labor, this is a monumental, gritty,
technically arduous half-hour composition, freely adapted from
12-tone techniques and true to its name. It holds up to any
20th-century piano piece, by Schoenberg, Messiaen or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Here the use of dissonance is bracing in a way that somehow
seems, well, American. There is no sense of European angst about
it. Rather, the astringent harmonies are ecstatic, energizing. It's
as if Copland were saying: ``Just listen to that dissonance. Isn't
it wonderful?'' The Fantasy is inexorable yet elusive in design,
like an adventure trip with ``few familiar landmarks,'' in the
words of the composer Arthur Berger.
</P>
<P>
   In many years of concertgoing I have come across only one
performance of the piece, during a Copland tribute presented by the
ensemble Boston Musica Viva at Jordan Hall in 1979. Copland, who
was present, had not heard the Fantasy performed for some time, he
said, and was awe-struck by the playing of the pianist, Randall
Hodgkinson. ``It's like you're reading my mind,'' Copland, clearly
moved, told the pianist.
</P>
<P>
   The Philharmonic programs draw from all periods of Copland's
work, which are more diverse than is generally realized, especially
the period during the 1920s when Copland, trying to shake up his
language and make it American, borrowed from jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Incorporating jazz into his symphonic music ``signified a
defiant badge of contemporary urban America,'' Howard Pollack
writes in his new biography, ``Aaron Copland: The Life and Work of
an Uncommon Man.'' Thomson later referred to Copland's venture into
jazz as his friend's ``one wild oat.''
</P>
<P>
   Though witty, the remark is a bit unfair. Works like the Piano
Concerto and ``Music for the Theater,'' which will be performed by
the Philharmonic, are raucous, rude and vibrant.
</P>
<P>
   Copland eventually felt he had come to a dead end. Jazz was too
powerful; it resisted getting dressed up for the concert hall.
Copland's jazz works started sounding like stiff, self-conscious
imitations of the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s he simplified his harmonic language. But by the
1950s he was already experimenting with 12-tone music. Pollack, in
his book, convincingly challenges an existing assumption, that
Copland, following Stravinsky's example, started writing 12-tone
music out of a fear of being considered obsolete by younger
composers.
</P>
<P>
   Copland was always curious about new developments. By this time
he felt that his harmonic language was becoming stale. Why did he
turn to dodecaphonic techniques, Bernstein once asked him?
``Because I need more chords,'' Copland replied. ``I've run out of
chords.''
</P>
<P>
   That Copland's music was so stylistically diverse would seem to
complicate the question of its American character. Isn't it futile
to specify what makes his music, or any music, American? What makes
German music German? Copland's bare, widely spaced modal harmonies
may conjure up the spacious American plains. But Palestrina wrote
similar chords in 16th-century Italy. Sturdy, simple hymns may
evoke plain-spoken American pioneers. But Martin Luther's chorale
tunes are just as simple and sturdy.
</P>
<P>
   There is a disarming quality in all of Copland's music that
comes from its shifting moods, by turns joyful and ecstatic,
brusque and riotous, pensive and reserved. Somehow, the shifts
never seem tortured or neurotic; rather, just two sides of the same
identity, expressed clearly, without apology or fuss. But is this
American?
</P>
<P>
   Surely, that quality comes more from Copland's personality than
from any general character trait of the American people. For a
homosexual man coming of age in the America of the 1910s, Copland
was remarkably well adjusted. He accepted his difference, and the
resultant isolation, with inner calm and little self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he cultivated privacy. In public he was avuncular and
discreet about his personal life. With friends he was open and
easy. But the public reserve, the public face, was always there,
not least in his music.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable document movingly captures Copland's sense of
reserve as it relates to his music and illuminates the question of
his Americanness. In 1974 he conducted the chamber ensemble version
of ``Appalachian Spring'' for a Columbia recording. Included with
that album was a six-inch bonus record of excerpts from the
rehearsal session, and it is a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-COPELAND-2000-3RDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: a revelation. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The players are top-rank, and as Copland greets them, he wryly
says, ``I assume you all know the piece.'' Someone answers back,
just as wryly, ``Only by reputation.'' A collegial mood thus
established, the musicians set to work. Before hearing a note,
Copland issues directions for the tranquil opening episode of the
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``A warm, soft sound without any sense of effort,'' he requests.
To the clarinetist, who will play the simple triadic opening motif,
which is the germ of the entire piece, Copland asks for a ``sort of
noncommittal sound.'' The musicians start to play, but Copland soon
stops them. ``Do it without any sense of diminuendo on each note,''
he tells the string players.
</P>
<P>
   At the first breakout section of the score, the Allegro dance,
he asks for the music to be bouncy, playful. ``This is a barnyard
dance,'' he says. ``It's not symphonic.'' When the dance fades
away, except for a recalcitrant jumpy flute, and a string chorale
tries to change the mood, he warns the musicians, ``Watch out, this
is getting too sweetly sentimental, a little too on the Massenet
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The most telling moment comes at No. 16 in the score, when the
music seems to want to settle into a simple little oompahpah dance,
but the rhythms become irregular instead, and a solo clarinet plays
a wistful elongation of the triadic opening motif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make it more American in spirit, in that the sentiment isn't
shown on the face,'' Copland says. ``More cool. The music by itself
is warm. You don't have to help it.''
</P>
<P>
   Copland never gave a more succinct summary of what being
American meant to him as a composer and a man. Maybe there is no
such thing as an essential American character. But in his work
Copland convinces us that there is. And if in pursuing this
American idiom, Copland limited his scope, he certainly humanized
his voice. That's what people respond to.
</P>
<P>
   To whatever degree Copland's call to find a collective national
voice resonated among his colleagues, his role in organizing
composers was pivotal. His work in this regard will be a recurring
topic in panels and lectures during the retrospective.
</P>
<P>
   Copland conscripted a little commando unit of American
composers. Thomson, Sessions, Roy Harris and Walter Piston were the
soldiers; Copland was the officer in charge.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it was a loose-knit group. Harris spent most his time
out West teaching, taking it easy and writing neo-Romantic
symphonies that won him an enviable popularity, which has not
lasted. Piston was a conservative type, comfortably ensconced on
the Harvard faculty and not especially interested in shaking up the
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions was essentially opposed to collective action on behalf
of American composers. He believed to his core that music was
either good or bad: something vastly more important, and
discernible, than whether it was French or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   In 1926, after hearing Boulanger play through Copland's Symphony
for Organ and Orchestra (1924), on the piano, Sessions wrote his
friend a chastising letter. You ``deserve hell,'' Sessions wrote,
for ``allowing yourself, when you can write music of your own like
that, to take any interest whatever in other people's music, and
especially in the music of other young Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you see,'' he continued, ``that any two pages of your
symphony are worth all the collected works of the `jeunes
americains' that you so generously allow yourself to be interested
in, and who have got to stand or fall on their own strength?''
</P>
<P>
   Thomson, though primarily based in Paris from 1925 to 1940,
shared Copland's belief in the importance of organization.
Collectivism was in the air, and both Copland and Thomson felt that
composers had more to gain by cooperating than by competing. The
real competition, as Thomson later described it in his
autobiography, was the ``German-Austrian musical complex,'' which
he likened to an ``international cartel operating through the
familiar techniques of price-fixing, dumping and pressures on the
performing agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, they believed, was to form American composer-run
organizations, professional guilds to assure fair payment of
royalties, promote performances and subsidize publication. They
encouraged their colleagues to follow their example and get
involved in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Composing music for theater, film, high school bands and the
like was admirable professional work. Copland was immensely pleased
when, after four prior nominations, he won an Oscar in 1949 for his
music for ``The Heiress.''
</P>
<P>
   This score and others will be discussed by two composers who
know the business from the inside out, Andre Previn and David
Raksin, in the final event of the festival, ``Copland and Film
Music,'' a program at the Museum of Modern Art on Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   That the festival will end in a museum is fitting. Copland's
work has been felt well beyond the confines of the concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the filmmaker Spike Lee, who used Copland's music in
the soundtrack for ``He Got Game,'' which tells the story of the
bitter relationship between a young inner-city basketball star,
played by Ray Allen of the Milwaukee Bucks, and his father, a
convict, played by Denzel Washington. Why Copland?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I listen to his music, I hear America, and basketball is
American,'' Lee writes in liner notes to ``Spike Lee Presents: The
Music of Aaron Copland,'' a Sony Classical recording.
</P>
<P>
   So Aaron Copland is now as American as basketball. He could not
have asked for better validation of his ``vague and dubious'' goal
of fostering a recognizable American musical voice. It was not
futile after all.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
