<HEADER>
A7791 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CATHOLIC-COLLEGES-BOS     11-22 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-COLLEGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOPS' DOCUMENT STRIKES AT US CATHOLIC CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle over control of Catholic colleges, which reached a
determining point last week, is one of the most significant events
in the liberal-conservative conflict that has been raging in the
Roman Catholic Church in America for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The hue and cry over ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae,'' a watershed
document establishing bishops' authority over what is taught in
Catholic universities, is not unrelated to the response to
``Humanae Vitae,'' the papal encyclical issued in 1968 that, most
famously, opposed artificial birth control.
</P>
<P>
   That document started the long-running controversy that has
defined Catholicism in this country _ whether Catholics can dissent
from the teachings of Rome and still remain true to their faith.
</P>
<P>
   And it has been Catholic theologians who have helped to provide
the intellectual framework for the debate, promoting the idea that
freedom of conscience should take precedence when Catholics
disagree with the Vatican on issues that are not central tenets of
the faith _ for example, priestly celibacy.
</P>
<P>
   Their pivotal role has not been lost on Rome.
</P>
<P>
   So Pope John Paul II played a pivotal role in ensuring that ``Ex
Corde Ecclesiae,'' which gives bishops the authority to decide who
is fit to teach Catholic theology, was adopted, much to the dismay
of many university administrators and faculty.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops gave many impassioned speeches while meeting last
week in Washington, D.C., about adopting the new guidelines as a
way to preserve the Catholic identity of Catholic colleges. But as
much as anything, it seemed, they wanted to make the Vatican happy.
</P>
<P>
   And for John Paul II, the long-discussed ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae''
is crucial to his unyielding campaign _ aided by powerful
conservative allies in the United States _ to rein in an American
Catholic establishment he says has fallen victim to liberal and
democratic notions that threaten Rome's authority.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has made it clear in speeches and writings that the
Roman Catholic Church is not a democracy. Observers say John Paul
cannot comprehend why, in the United States, church teachings on
everything from abortion to women priests are open to public debate
and the subject of opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US bishops are the ones who understand American culture,
who understand American society, and yet they essentially allowed
the Vatican bureaucracy to decide what's best for America,'' said
Peter Beisheim, professor of religious studies at Stonehill
College, a Catholic college in Easton. ``And John Paul II is
someone who seems to have problems with American society.''
</P>
<P>
   That Catholic theologians are singled out by ``Ex Corde
Ecclesiae'' (Latin for ``from the heart of the church''), is a
deliberate move, according to some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative bishops and lay groups, such as Catholics United
for the Faith, say many theologians are given too much leash to
promote dissent from church teaching on topics such as celibacy for
priests and homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, critics say, theologians are promoting a liberal
line and helping stoke the conflict between a majority of
rank-and-file American Catholics and church fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's at stake here is the truth about what the church
teaches,'' said Philip Gray, vice president of Catholics United for
the Faith in Steubenville, Ohio. ``It's not up to a theologian to
determine what he believes Christ taught. It's up to the theologian
to be faithful to what the church's teaching authority says Christ
taught. If he doesn't, then the faithful can be led into error.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, groups like Catholics United and the Cardinal Newman
Society have been complaining _ sometimes directly to the Vatican _
about theologians who they said were being disloyal to the church.
</P>
<P>
   One particular fear among university administrators, many
theologians, and some bishops is that conservative groups will use
``Ex Corde Ecclesiae'' to target theologians with whom they
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal Newman Society cited ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae'' when it
issued a report criticizing 21 Catholic colleges for inviting
commencement speakers who opposed the church's antiabortion
position.
</P>
<P>
   The Newman Society's reaction to the bishops' vote last week
seemed to suggest that it was prepared to take up the banner of
defending the Vatican against wayward teachers of Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can move forward with the hard work of building truly
Catholic campuses . . . and hiring faculty and staff who fully
support the Catholic educational mission,'' said Manuel A. Miranda,
the society's president.
</P>
<P>
   The influence Catholic theologians have over shaping the
Catholic community in the United States is something of which the
Vatican is keenly aware. Since World War II, the US Roman Catholic
population has become better educated, and Catholic colleges have
played a central role in opening academic doors to Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   So Rome has a vested interest in trying, to the extent it can,
to have a say in who teaches theology at the 236 Catholic colleges
in the United States. It is more than a struggle for the soul of US
Catholic higher education, analysts say. It is a struggle for the
soul of Catholicism in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, it is a battle the Vatican may have a hard
time winning. Few bishops, even those who agree with the Vatican's
views on the rise of liberal Catholicism in the United States,
would probably be interested in taking on theologians or university
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Not just because doing so would raise questions of academic
freedom, the legal requirements of faculty contracts, and the
weight of tenure. But also because the idea spawned by the fallout
from ``Humanae Vitae'' _ that you can disagree with the church's
fathers and still be a good Catholic _ is now firmly planted in
this country's Catholic landscape.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing the Vatican does, including pressuring the bishops
to embrace ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae,'' may be able to uproot it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
