<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-WHALEY-BOS &LR;      11-22 1602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-WHALEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STORY OF `JOE THE KING' IS REALLY FRANK WHALEY'S OWN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Whaley, writer and director of ``Joe the King,'' is at the
Lenox Hotel during the recent Boston Film Festival, about to
discuss his directorial debut. After shaking hands, a visitor
comments that with ``Joe the King,'' Whaley has made the feel-good
movie of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Set in hell, yeah,'' he says, with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   All right, ``Joe the King'' is not the feel-good movie of the
year. It is a youth movie unlike any other, although it bears a
resemblance to the grittier aspects of ``Outside Providence.'' But
it is not a sweet coming-of-age movie. There is no hot teen sex, no
gross bodily fluids, no cheap yuks. There are no ``Dawson's Creek''
or ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' stars making the leap to movies. No
sentimentality. The young actors _ including Joe, played by Noah
Fleiss _ are relative unknowns. The name adult actors _ Val Kilmer,
Ethan Hawke, John Leguizamo _ are supporting characters.
</P>
<P>
   While the movie was not made for kids, Whaley says, ``I thnk
it's good for kids to see a movie like this. A lot of movies are
really frivolous. They don't show kids in an intelligent way. This
guy, Joe, is heroic in that he's able to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is highly autobiographical. Set in the 1970s, it
concerns the difficult life and trying times of Joe, a frequent
truant and budding juvenile delinquent who is on the path to a
career in crime and a life spent mostly in jail. The son of an
alcoholic father and a wayward mother, Joe is not necessarily an
evil kid. In doing what he thinks needs to be done to get by, he
makes some bad choices.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Whaley was at the Sundance Film Festival,
nervously anticipating the screening of his film. ``I didn't show
any (advance) footage, so no one knew what the movie was about. (I
thought) the only way to sell it was to keep it quiet and make an
event out of it at Sundance,'' Whaley recalled. ``Before the
screening started, it was like Elvis was in there. They were
pushing and shoving to get in; every agent in town wanted to talk
to me; everybody wanted to have dinner with me. And then, once the
screening started, within the first 15 minutes, about 40 people
walked out. I was so distraught. A good friend of my brother's
(Robert, who has a role in the movie) was there and I was crying,
because it was my whole life'' up on screen ``and he said, `You
have got to stand behind your work and think about the people who
stayed, not the people who left. There are people in the audience
who were really affected by it, and those are the people you made
it for. So why are you being a baby?' But you don't see that. You
always remember the bad reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he says he realized that ``no matter what kind of movie
you make, what kind of painting you make, what kind of book you
make, not everybody's going to like it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Whaley may have gotten the last laugh, because ``Joe the
King'' was nominated for the Grand Jury Prize and shared the Waldo
Salt Screenwriting Award at Sundance. But the movie wasn't released
until this fall.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a movie of high dramatic conflict. ``I took a very
pure approach to writing,'' says Whaley. ``I did not think of plot.
I told the story from one point of view, where he travels down this
path. People come in here and there, but he keeps going.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for laughs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The film begins in a classroom where it's
tell-your-peers-what-your-dad-does day. Young Joe (played by Peter
Tambakis) is paddled bare-bottom by his teacher because he doesn't
want to reveal that his father is the school janitor. You might be
thinking this movie will evolve into a dark comedy, but shortly you
realize this isn't a story to be played for laughs. It hits you _
``like a ton of bricks,'' finishes Whaley. ``Although I tried to
infuse it it with several humor sprinkles throughout to mitigate
the darkness. I know just from watching a film that if it gets too
heavy, then the audience starts to go `Nahhhhh.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The characters all come from my childhood. I was Joe. Those
other two guys were my friends. We were loser kids but we kind of
found each other. I don't know what happened to them; they were
ghosts of my past. The father (in the movie) is actually a Disney
version. My father was a tough guy, a drunk. That was our home
life, pretty decrepit, pretty impoverished, to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley's father is dead. His mother is alive, but Whaley says he
doesn't expect or want her to see ``Joe the King'' even though,
somewhat parodoxically, ``it is sort of a love letter to her,
because I look at her now and, as I get older I see this even more,
she is almost really heroic in that she kept a roof over our heads.
I have two sisters and a brother, and we are all adults, we are
working, we are happy, and so if not for her, we would all be dead
or in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley, who had many run-ins with the law before he was 18, says
he never ended up in reform school or jail. ``I just always talked
my way out of it. It was mostly shoplifting and there was a moment
where I sort of began the process of graduating to higher crimes. I
got in with a crowd that was into body parts, cars, and chop shops.
Easy, quick money. I learned to hot-wire, stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fate took a curious twist. ``At the same moment, I found my
brother had joined the drama club in school because there was a
girl that he liked, and in those days I did everything that he did.
So I said, `I'm joining drama club too,' and I joined the drama
club, as I had a crush on a girl in there. It wasn't because of
acting; I didn't understand acting. I'd never seen a play, but for
the first time in my life, at 16-17, I didn't feel alienated. There
were people there whom I related to. I got a lot of attention. I
was such a shy, introspective, quiet kid and I finally found
expression.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman who headed the drama club challenged him to think
about his future. She had him look into an Education Opportunity
Program, a program for inner-city kids championed by President
Jimmy Carter, and Whaley was selected for it. He got a stipend,
books, and an education, studying theater at Albany State
University and graduating in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``It,'' he says, of the educational experience, ``saved my life.
If it wasn't given to me, I wouldn't have gone. I was on a
collision course. The judge in a family court said, `I'm not
kidding you, I'll give you one last chance and if doesn't work out,
I'm sorry.' I didn't want to go to jail because a friend of mine
did go to jail and got beaten up and raped.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Flawed but likable &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This, more or less, is Joe's life in the movie _ without the
going-to-college happy ending. Joe is sometimes likable, sometimes
not, but Whaley says ``for all his flaws'' he is sympathetic. ``The
only way the film works is, on one level, they must want to stay
with this guy. And I think because of what he looks like and
conveys in his eyes, they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Joe's criminal behavior morally justifiable?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not morally,'' says Whaley, ``because it is wrong to
steal. There are consequences to be paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley adds, ``I got lucky (finding Fleiss) and in that I saw a
lot of actors and Noah wasn't what I was looking for physically _ I
wanted somebody not so handsome and he was a good-looking kid _ but
he was very well behaved and memorized his script in a limited
amount of time. We needed an actor who was prepared and disciplined
who could also work with these other adult actors.'' And, he adds,
who could handle some pretty rough and gritty scenes.
</P>
<P>
   What, exactly, is Joe the king of? ``As I was shooting, I was
looking for a beautiful title and somewhere along the line `Joe the
King' came to me, it wasn't referenced to anything, although we did
throw a line in later about it,'' Whaley says. ``If I was to use a
metaphor, I would say Joe is the king of this little domain
underneath his house.'' (Joe stashes his prime treasure there,
recordings that he bought with stolen money to give to his mother.)
</P>
<P>
   A Syracuse native, Whaley, 36, has acted professionally for 15
years and has been in ``The Doors,'' ``Hoffa,'' ``Swimming With
Sharks,'' ``Reservoir Dogs,'' and ``Born on the Fourth of July.''
He also appeared in the recent TV miniseries ``Shake, Rattle, and
Roll.'' But ``Joe the King'' was germinating for years. Whaley says
as an actor, writer, and director he's drawn to ``dead-end guys,
blue-collar guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley met Kilmer on the set of ``The Doors'' _ Kilmer played
Jim Morrison, Whaley played guitarist Robby Krieger, and the two
remained pals. He and Hawke, who plays Joe's guidance counselor,
are friends who met on the set of ``A Midnight Clear'' in 1991.
John Leguizamo, co-executive producer, plays Jorge, a busboy at the
restaurant where Joe works. Kilmer plays Joe's semi-bloated,
disheveled father. Whaley says Kilmer shed his glam image, put on
some pounds, and transformed himself into someone who ``destroyed
his life, destroyed his body, even if at one time he was a
striking, charismatic guy.'' The film, which cost $1.2 million, was
shot in 28 days on location on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   How does Whaley define success for the movie? ``If it plays in
(a small New York theater) for a couple of months, long enough for
all my friends to see it,'' says Whaley.
</P>
<P>
   Will it play in the malls and multiplexes? ``I doubt it,'' he
says, ``though I would love it to. `American Beauty' is playing in
malls . . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
