<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIV MAY BE WITHIN IMMUNE SYSTEM'S CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A small but remarkable experiment is showing that some
AIDS patients may be able to control the disease on their own when
treatment with potent drugs is halted intermittently.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment represents the next conceptual push in AIDS
research, now that specialists are convinced it won't be possible
to eradicate the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) from patients'
cells with forseeable treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Massachusetts General Hospital say they were
highly encouraged by the results when they repeatedly stopped
triple-drug therapy in HIV-infected volunteers. They described
preliminary findings from two such patients Friday at a scientific
meeting in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS virus came back each time the drugs were stopped, but
in both cases, there were clear signs that the patients' immune
systems were battling to control the emergent virus, with
increasing success. In effect, unleashing the virus in a controlled
fashion may act like a vaccine booster shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that patients' reexposure to their own virus has
potentially the same effect that a vaccine would have,'' Dr. Eric
Rosenberg, who presented the new data, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuver is called ``structured interrupted therapy,'' and
the ultimate hope is that it will allow at least some HIV-infected
patients _ those treated very early in the course of their
infection _ to be weaned permanently from antiviral drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also expect the experiment will teach them what it
takes, immunologically speaking, to keep HIV in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're optimistic _ in fact, quite certain _ that we will get a
much better understanding of what's needed for viral control,''
said Dr. Bruce Walker, director of the MGH's AIDS Research Center.
``That will guide vaccine development.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to know if any AIDS patients will be able to throw
away their antiviral drugs. Still, the signs are encouraging enough
that other leading AIDS laboratories have embarked on similar
experiments or are gearing up to do them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Structured interrupted therapy is what everybody's excited
about and working on,'' said Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, the federal
government's leading AIDS researcher. ``We and a number of labs
have protocols to put people deliberately on intermittent
therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fauci cautioned, ``we need to be really careful not to
make definitive statements until we see a trend. We need a lot more
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The MGH doctors have another 18 volunteers lined up to do
interrupted therapy. They stressed that HIV-infected patients
should not stop treatment outside of studies, because close
monitoring of viral loads and immune responses are crucial to keep
the virus within safe bounds and avoid the emergence of
drug-resistant viral strains.
</P>
<P>
   The new experiments were inspired by the striking observation
that some HIV-infected patients have controlled the virus all on
their own. One such patient, Robert Massie, is an Episcopal priest,
environmentalist, and former candidate for lieutenant governor of
Massachusetts who acquired the AIDS virus in 1978 from an infusion
of anti-hemophilia factor. Massie has been intensely studied by the
MGH researchers; his HIV-specific immune response ``is the
strongest we've ever seen,'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Another inspiration is the so-called Berlin patient, a
30-year-old German man who has become an icon of hope in the AIDS
community. He took himself off anti-AIDS drugs in December, 1996,
after several on-and-off cycles of therapy, and has remained well
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him today and he's in perfect health,'' his physician,
Dr. Heako Jessen, said in a telephone interview last Thursday.
``His virus is controlled and his immune system is normal, perhaps
because this on-and-off therapy boosted his HIV-specific
immunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessen, an independent practitioner who collaborates with the
MGH researchers, has interrupted drug therapy in 10 patients this
year. He reports longer and longer intervals before the virus
returns, some reaching three months so far.
</P>
<P>
   At the MGH, seven patients in all have stopped taking their
anti-HIV therapy for varying lengths of time, although Rosenberg
presented data Friday from only the first two at a meeting of the
Infectious Disease Society of America. To qualify, all such
patients must have been diagnosed very early _ during the flu-like
acute illness that usually occurs within weeks of HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
   Walker and Rosenberg have found that such acutely treated
patients retain strong immune responses directed at HIV, especially
among so-called T-helper cells that orchestrate the entire immune
response symphony. Once patients have been infected for months or
years, they almost always have lost such potent HIV-specific immune
responses, even if they regain responses against tuberculosis,
tetanus, cytomegalovirus, and other bugs.
</P>
<P>
   So far the results of the MGH experiments are tantalizing.
</P>
<P>
   Patient 1, a 32-year-old Boston man, initially went off therapy
last July after 17 months on antiviral drugs that had suppressed
blood levels of HIV below the limits of detection.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later HIV began to show itself, rising slowly to
about 17,000 viral copies per milliliter of blood (a thousandth of
a liter). This was only a fraction of the 280,000 virus particles
that this patient had when he was first diagnosed, but Rosenberg
and Walker decided to start drug therapy again lest the virus get
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they were encouraged by the fact that the virus had
returned slowly. When most AIDS patients stop multidrug treatments
(for instance, because of another illness or intolerance to the
drugs), the virus comes roaring back to pretreatment levels within
days or weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Patient 1 again stopped therapy in early January of this year
because of a liver ailment. This time something interesting
happened. After three weeks without drugs, HIV showed itself in the
patient's bloodstream, steadily mounting until there were 38,000
viral copies per milliliter. But just as the doctors were preparing
to start therapy again, his viral ``load'' began to fall
dramatically _ to 6,000 copies, then 400 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was doing it all on his own,'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Patient 1 started taking antiviral drugs again when he was able.
Eight weeks later, he interrupted treatment again _ and this time,
his immune system kept the virus at low levels for four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a gray zone of good but not perfect control,''
Rosenberg said. For now, Patient 1 is back on triple-drug therapy,
but he and Rosenberg plan another drug ``holiday'' soon to see if
his anti-HIV immune response is even more effective the next time.
</P>
<P>
   Patient 2, a 40-year-old man, also seems to show that the immune
system can be spurred into an effective attack against HIV by early
treatment and on-and-off drug cycling.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed with acute HIV syndrome in April, 1997, Patient 2 had
an initial viral load of more than 1 million copies. Drug treatment
quickly brought that down to undetectable levels, or less than 50
copies, where it remained for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment was interrupted last January 28, but within three
weeks Patient 2's viral levels had spiked to more than 100,000
copies. Drugs again brought that back down below detectable levels.
</P>
<P>
   When Patient 2 stopped taking drugs the second time, on June 2,
the virus remained hidden for two weeks but then crept back into
his blood at a low level _ about 200 copies. Over the ensuing
months, the viral level fluctuated in the hundreds to low
thousands, never rising above 6,500 copies.
</P>
<P>
   For four months, Walker noted, ``this fellow was at a viral
level which the US Public Health Service guidelines say would not
need to be treated.''
</P>
<P>
   The MGH researchers are encouraged not only by the viral levels
in these patients, but by their rebounding immune responses to HIV.
Despite his good response, Patient 2, like Patient 1, decided to do
another eight-week round of drug treatment in the hope that a third
``booster shot'' of HIV ``will be the charm,'' as Walker put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four months off drugs was really liberating,'' Patient 2 said
in an interview. ``But I decided to go back on to see if at one of
these points my natural immunity will keep it in check and I won't
have to take drugs at all. But I know I'm in uncharted territory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
