<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY MOMENTS TO DIGEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pie-eating contest starts as soon as the ravaged turkey is
cleared away. You know the pie- eating contest. It's a Thanksgiving
moment, not a Kodak moment, unless a disciple of Diane Arbus
happens to be behind the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to try a piece of my pie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't eat another bite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to try my pie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, maybe just a tiny slice.''
</P>
<P>
   So you try her pie, and then you have to try somebody else's
pie, and then somebody else's, and they all want to know what you
think of their pies. You have to lie because you can't tell them
the truth, i.e., ``I think I may be sick.'' It would ruin the
Thanksgiving moment.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Rockwell has a lot to answer for. He enshrined the myth
of Thanksgiving in that famous Saturday Evening Post cover, the
happy family gathered around a turkey the size of Mount Rushmore.
Before he created that scene, people used to feel lucky to have a
chicken on Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Now the stakes have escalated to the point where everybody wants
a bird that will feed the starving millions. Which means that
somebody (guess who?) has to get up at 5 a.m. and wrestle the thing
into the oven. There is nothing that will get your holiday,
so-called, off to a more festive start than rising before dawn and
trying to get a grip on a cold, slippery 23-pound turkey. Talk
about a Thanksgiving moment.
</P>
<P>
   It is a rare man who will find himself dealing with a giant raw
turkey in the hours before sunrise on Thanksgiving morning. That's
because Thanksgiving is for men, the way Christmas and Halloween
are for children. It's a sexual stereotype, I know, and I should be
ashamed of myself. But it's a stereotype because it's true.
</P>
<P>
   It's a day when men gather and do what men do, all the
traditional male Thanksgiving things. They go to high school
football games. They watch football on TV. They play touch
football. They talk about football. They drink beer. They smoke
cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Men want to help on Thanksgiving, but their timing is off. ``Can
I help?'' they ask, just as you've finished doing whatever it is
they might have helped you do if you'd known where to find them.
</P>
<P>
   But men do carve, and everybody knows that carving is the most
important job on Thanksgiving. It's a lost art, really. And if it
goes wrong, and the turkey ends up all crumbly, looking like
something that belongs in the cat's dish, it's not his fault. It's
your fault because you didn't cook it right. It makes for another
Thanksgiving moment to treasure for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Like the year your sister-in-law microwaved the turkey.
</P>
<P>
   And the annual unveiling of your aunt's Jell-O mold. You can't
avoid it. No use protesting that you're allergic to molds.
</P>
<P>
   Or the first _ and last _ time your brother-in-law insisted that
you deep-fry the turkey whole, outdoors, in a vat of boiling fat,
the way they do it back home in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Who could forget the Martha Stewart-inspired Thanksgiving at
your cousin's house? How many miniature pumpkins are one too many?
</P>
<P>
   Or the year of the tofurkey _ when your kids suddenly decided
they were vegetarians?
</P>
<P>
   And there was that Thanksgiving you tried a recipe from The New
York Times, an easy way to cook a turkey in no time at all, in a
500-degree oven. All the smoke alarms went off, and the fire
department came and carried the smoldering turkey out of the house.
Later, you went out for Chinese food. What a good idea. The Chinese
food, that is. And the burning turkey, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnit.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
