<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OPEN HOUSE' PITCH OMITS 2 KEY WORDS: TIME SHARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've all heard the pitch: For just a little bit of your time,
you'll receive an assortment of fabulous gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Charves got the pitch recently from a woman named Holly at
the Colonial Acres Resort in West Yarmouth, Mass., a time-share
operation, although no mention of that was made in the pitch. In
return for coming to an ``open house,'' Charves was promised two
free roundtrip airline tickets to a destination of her choice from
a list including Florida, California, Hawaii, and the Caribbean; a
free three-day, two-night getaway to any of 45 US cities; and gift
certificates to the Red Lobster or Olive Garden restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Charves was skeptical _ ``I'm no idiot,'' she said _ but she
thought a trip with her children to Cape Cod and two free airline
tickets would be a productive outing.
</P>
<P>
   One of Charves's daughters has ataxia telangiectasia, a deadly
genetic disease that afflicts only about 650 children in the United
States. Charves wants to raise awareness of the disease, and
planned to donate the airline tickets to raise money for research.
</P>
<P>
   Charves said she asked Holly repeatedly whether the tickets were
really free and whether she had to buy anything to get them. She
even asked for assurances in writing and Holly sent her the script
of her pitch. ``It says flat out, two free airline tickets,''
Charves said.
</P>
<P>
   But the tickets weren't really free. The time-share industry may
be gaining respectability with the entry of big-name companies such
as Marriott, Hyatt, and Disney, but many resorts continue to
deceive would-be customers into thinking they are getting something
valuable for their time.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's trade group admits that the No. 1 consumer
complaint about time shares is deceptive marketing practices
(including promotional sweepstakes contests, as we wrote about last
week). And the Massachusetts attorney general has received several
dozen complaints about time-share resorts since 1996, including
four involving Colonial Acres.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis McCauley, director of marketing for Colonial Acres, said
he goes to great lengths to treat would-be customers fairly. He
said the gifts he offers consumers have a retail value of about
$550. And to make sure his telephone solicitors don't mislead
people (they get paid based on how many people they bring to the
resort), he has a manager follow up with each person who agrees to
a visit. A letter is also sent to the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is spelled out for them,'' McCauley said. ``We try
to do everything the proper way.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charves said she never received a follow-up letter or phone
call. What was sent _ the script that Holly had read _ showed how
deceptive the pitch is.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention of a time-share presentation. ``All we are
going to do is walk you around the facilities and show you our
beach and models in the hopes that if you like what you see, you'll
come back and stay with us in the future,'' the pitch said.
</P>
<P>
   McCauley said ``time share'' is not mentioned because consumers
have the wrong idea about it. ``The words have the connotation of a
skull and crossbones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   We wonder why.
</P>
<P>
   The two free roundtrip airline tickets, offered by a company
called Fly Free America, are an homage to semantics. They are free
only if you spend a certain number of days at a resort in the
destination city and pay the resort's top room rate. But at those
prices, the tickets are hardly free.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you want to fly to Hawaii and stay at the Waikiki Joy.
Using Fly Free America, two people could fly to Hawaii for free in
March as long as they stay a minimum of 13 nights at the Waikiki
Joy at $280 a night. That works out to $3,640, not including room
or departure taxes and transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Jo-Ann Bellanti at Colpitts Travel in Dedham, Mass. was able to
book the same trip on American Airlines and a suite at the Joy for
$2,885, with transfers and taxes included, for a savings of more
than 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Trips closer to home and of shorter duration are more
cost-effective, but still no bargain. Using Fly Free America, a
four-night stay at the Hyatt Regency Grand Cypress in Orlando in
February would cost $1,400, not including taxes and transfers.
Bellanti was able to book the same trip on Delta for $1,323 with
taxes, transfers, and a free shuttle to Disney World included.
</P>
<P>
   The free three-day, two-night getaway to any of 45 destinations
doesn't include transportation and it hinges on a second time-share
solicitation. According to Mini-Vacations Inc., the company running
the program, guests select a destination and then are booked at a
motel there. The motel bill is paid for by a nearby time-share
resort, which then targets the travelers for another time-share
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   The one gift with no strings attached was the $30 gift
certificate to the Red Lobster or Olive Garden restaurants. Charves
used her certificate at Olive Garden.
</P>
<P>
   For Colonial Acres, the restaurant certificate was probably the
most expensive gift offered. The company that owns Red Lobster and
Olive Garden sells the certificates to companies like Colonial
Acres at a 10 to 15 percent discount. Mini-Vacations Inc. said it
charges $3 for its getaway packages and Fly Free America charges
$7.50 to $10, depending on how many trips are purchased. The
estimated cost of the Colonial Acres pitch to the time-share
resort: About $40.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phone bill aggravation
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's incredible to us that a long-distance phone company called
International Plus, which targets Asian immigrants, has a slogan
with the words ``simple solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   In at least one case involving a Somerville couple who moved
here from Taiwan, this company refused the most simple solution to
a complicated problem that it created.
</P>
<P>
   Before contacting us, Hong Wang, 37, a hospital researcher,
tried for several weeks to resolve a $50 billing problem he had
with International Plus, also known as NOS Communications. After
canceling the carrier because of bad phone connections, he was hit
with an array of unannounced extra fees.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Las Vegas, told him the extra fees were
imposed because low calling rates are promised on the condition
that he stay with the company for six months and meet minimum
monthly usage requirements. Wang said he and his wife were never
told about these rules when a Chinese-speaking telemarketer sold
them on the plan earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest bill, a 24-minute call to Taiwan, for example, was
recalculated at a rate of $1.74 a minute, instead of 29 cents a
minute. He was also hit with a $10 monthly management fee.
</P>
<P>
   When Wang declined to pay, the company threatened to take his
case to a collections agency that could begin legal action.
</P>
<P>
   When Wang asked for our help, we agreed to step in, largely
because we have long suspected that firms specializing in ethnic
marketing may take advantage of these new-to-America consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, we didn't have much luck either. After placing
numerous phone calls to the company's 800 phone number, it declined
to address the Wang case with a reporter and refused to give out
the phone number of company headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Tuesday, after obtaining the headquarters phone
number through an Internet site, we reached a company attorney who
intervened. Wang was told later by the company he would get about
$50 in credit for the disputed fees. In the future, Wang said he
will be far more suspicious of telemarketing calls and demand all
rules in writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we learned our lesson the hard way,'' Wang said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
