<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE BEING HUNG OUT TO DRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ They may as well take the No. 11 off his jersey and put
a big bull's-eye on his back.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe is now the No. 1 target in the National Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a coincidence that the Miami Dolphins' defense
pummeled the Patriots' Pro Bowl quarterback, taking control of
their important AFC East game Sunday and going on to a 27-17
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami coaching staff spent last week looking at the film of
the New York Jets banging Bledsoe around last Monday night, and
decided to do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked up some things from the Jets and put them into our
package,'' said assistant coach Dave Wannstedt. ``If you want to
beat these guys, you have to pressure Bledsoe and make some plays
downfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we told our guys. We have to make some plays
downfield, and we can do that if we can make him force the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened. Bledsoe threw five interceptions, and it
could have been eight.
</P>
<P>
   Once again he repeatedly was knocked to the ground. He has been
knocked down more than any quarterback in the league this season,
because opponents realize that if you stop Bledsoe, you stop the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins defense was magnificent. It gave up just 10 points
and was stung just twice (Miami quarterback Damon Huard gave the
Patriots their first 7 points by tossing a bad lateral that turned
into a fumble inside his 10).
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's 68-yard scoring bomb to Shawn Jefferson in the third
quarter, and Kevin Faulk's 43-yard run that set up a field goal in
the second were the only New England offensive plays of any
consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe had just 60 yards passing deep into the third quarter.
At the start of the fourth quarter Monday night against the Jets,
he had just 88 passing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Two teams in a row now have taken the Patriots' regular offense
apart. They didn't do anything against the Jets until they went
into a no-huddle, shotgun formation last week, and they went into
that mode out of their regular T formation by the third period
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's defensive backs did a great job of covering the
Patriots' receivers. In certain passing situations they did
something novel, having a speed cornerback run with tight end Ben
Coates, who usually has a bigger safety or linebacker assigned to
him. Twice under pressure Bledsoe tried to force the ball into
Coates and was intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   This game followed a similar pattern to the Jets loss. New York
vowed to take it to the Patriots physically, and the Dolphins were
urged by coach Jimmy Johnson to do the same thing. Johnson
predicted that if they beat up the Patriots for three quarters, New
England would be worn down by the fourth. He was correct.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling last week in Buffalo with one of the worst
offensive outputs in team history, the Miami coaches decided to cut
down the number of plays in their game plan to help Huard. At times
against the Bills he seemed confused and uncertain. They thought by
giving him less to do, they might get more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we need 21 points to win this one,'' Wannstedt said
before the game. ``Our offense has to do something early to give
our defense something positive. It's tough to play defense if you
don't think your offense can score any points.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami also believed it couldn't win if it turned the ball over.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Bledsoe was the focal point of their plan. They
wanted to knock him down as often as possible and make him move,
believing he doesn't throw as well when he's on the run. They also
wanted to be careful not to let Bledsoe step up in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, the Patriots' offense had a couple of new
wrinkles designed to shake the Dolphins' confidence on defense.
Early on they came out in a no-back backfield on first down, but
the Dolphins sacked Bledsoe before he got the ball away. A couple
of plays later, they tried to throw a halfback option pass from
Lamont Warren back to Bledsoe. But Warren got hit and couldn't get
the ball away cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Patriots did well in the early going was run to
the right more than they usually have this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have tended to run to the left. Against the Jets,
on a key fourth and 1 in the first quarter, New York guessed left,
shot two linebackers into the hole, and stopped Terry Allen short
of the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, after recovering a fumble at the Miami 7 in the first
period, the Patriots used this tendency to score their first
touchdown. Fullback Tony Carter ran at the left guard, then Allen,
after a fake jab step left, got the ball and slashed over right
guard for 6 yards and the score. Inside linebacker Zach Thomas had
vacated the area after going for the fake.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the first quarter, Faulk used the same kind of
move on his 43-yard run. He started left, then darted over right
tackle. Again Thomas took the fake and was out of position. He
lunged and missed the tackle, and Faulk ran over safety Brock
Marion before being taken down deep in Miami territory, setting up
a 27-yard field goal by Adam Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Bledsoe didn't have much time to set his feet
and throw because of the Dolphins' excellent pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Huard was shaky starting out. He completed just two of his first
six passes for 7 yards. But in the second quarter, he started to
gain confidence, and finished the half 13 of 22, twice running for
first downs.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Patriots have to go to Buffalo, where the Bills play
some of the toughest defense in the league. There is no tougher
place to play than Buffalo if you are a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   While the Jets and Dolphins blitzed linebackers and defensive
backs to get after Bledsoe, the Bills can do it with just down
linemen. It's not going to get any easier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
