<HEADLINE>
VILLAGE SHELTERS FAMILIES EVADING THE REACH OF GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JINBIAN, China _ This tiny cluster of caves perched on a
hillside in northern Shaanxi province can barely be called a
village. But in its own way, it is a community for those who have
no other home.
</P>
<P>
   Jinbian has become something of a revolving-door refuge for
families who have violated China's one-child policy and are on the
run from government fines or sterilization; for societal misfits;
and for families whose disabled members were ostracized elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Kong Baoqing, 27, came to Jinbian partly because her elderly
parents wanted to return home from the bitter cold of northern
Heilongjiang province and to escape the discrimination against her
mother, who is a dwarf. But Kong also wanted to have a second child
out of sight of local authorities there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are transients, so the government can't control us,'' she
had thought. But local authorities soon got wind of it and slapped
her with a $300 fine _ nearly half the average annual salary in
China _ and forced her to undergo sterilization surgery. Like other
flouters of the one-child policy instituted in 1979, she learned
that because of routine police checks, ``if you move here to an
abandoned cave, the government finds out within a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Kong's mother also violated family-planning rules by having four
children. But Kong says officials tacitly allow disabled people to
break the one-child rule _ partly out of compassion, and partly
because they believe disabled people need more help in old age.
</P>
<P>
   Kong has been allowed to stay in the village since her parents
originate from the region. But authorities refuse to give a
residency permit to Kong's husband and two children. It costs $25 a
term to send each child to school _ almost three times higher than
if they were legal local residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought of building a real house last year but decided not
to, because then we'd be committed to stay,'' she said. ``If we
find a place to make more money, we will move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
