<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS BYPASSES CHINA'S CAVE DWELLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YAN'AN, China _ But for some smoky coal mines and petroleum
refineries, the dry, barren landscape that stretches for hundreds
of miles through north-central China looks much as it has for
centuries: rolling hills bereft of trees, rocky outcroppings from
yellow earth, and a mysterious motif _ thousands upon thousands of
arches carved into hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance, the curious pattern resembles a giant beehive.
But then the rustic wooden doors and colored quilts covering the
arches come into focus, and it becomes clear that peasants are
surviving in this harsh terrain just as their ancestors have since
prehistoric times: by digging a cave and calling it home.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five decades, China has hurtled from a feudal,
agrarian society to a communist, industrial model, and finally to
an increasingly market-oriented economy. Last week, China and the
United States signed a historic deal paving the way for Beijing to
enter the World Trade Organization, which in turn is expected to
further integrate China into the global economy. But a sizable
percentage of China's 1.3 billion people live in such isolated and
backward conditions that they are unlikely ever to benefit from the
fruits of freer trade and the boom along China's commercial
seaboard. There are no official figures, but some estimate that 40
million to 70 million Chinese peasants still live in earthen or
stone-front caves, mostly in the three neighboring provinces of
Shaanxi, Henan, and Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
   As China's economy marches forward, these present-day cave
dwellers don't even realize they have been left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Huo Laiyin, a 70-year-old peasant who lives in a cave in
Fanzhang village in northern Shaanxi, has heard of former leader
Deng Xiaoping, but never of his Open Door policy that began
expanding economic markets 20 years ago, fueling spectacular
growth. The prosperity that blessed China's cities in the past two
decades hasn't affected Huo; in fact, bad weather and soil erosion
mean her life has gotten worse. Her dry land became infertile and
her old cave started to crumble. She had to sell her only donkey
for money to buy food, and last year she moved into her brother's
cave.
</P>
<P>
   She gave up farming rather than pay taxes on land that yields no
crops. Her son cannot work because of a mysterious illness, and the
family cannot afford the $25 per term to send her 7-year-old
grandson to school.
</P>
<P>
   The farthest distance Huo has ever traveled is less than 20
miles to Yan'an, a city of fewer than 50,000 people. Unlike the
striving masses who fill China's major cities, she can't even dream
of a better life.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could I even think of moving to Yan'an or living in an
apartment? I have no money, and I never will,'' she said, without a
hint of bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Yan'an has a proud history as the mountainous redoubt of China's
communist revolutionaries while they were fighting the nationalist
rulers from 1936 to 1947. Mao Zedong slept in the hills in a cave
dug out of the clay-like loess, and his onetime base camp is now a
neatly swept tourist pilgrimage site. But while revolutionaries
lived in caves as a hideaway, families like Huo's have been living
here since Neolithic times _ out of topographical and economic
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   With few trees and not much building stone available, caves dug
out of the soil are the cheapest and most practical form of housing
here, costing $125 for skilled laborers to make the door and shape
the arch, and about $12.50 in taxes for the use of the land.
Sometimes a family will sell its cave before moving; but more
often, families abandon it when it is collapsing and dig a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Caves are also good for the changeable climate; the insulation
of the earth keeps dwellers cool in summer and warm in winter. They
are dark and poorly ventilated, but that doesn't seem to bother the
residents.
</P>
<P>
   So natural is a cave home to local people that even those who
build a freestanding dwelling have echoed the architecture of
caves, yielding the striking sight of arched, single-room,
earth-and-stone rowhouses that look like stables.
</P>
<P>
   The average earth cave is home to a multigenerational family and
consists of a single room about 10 feet wide and 20 feet deep into
the hillside. A ``kang'' _ a hard earthen platform carved out of
the back wall of a cave _ serves as bed, sofa, and dining area, and
is warmed by heat from an attached mud stove. Tureens balance over
the open fire, scenting the air with the smell of porridge. The
cooking utensils resemble ancient bowls and ladles. The massive,
circular grain-grinding stones outside each cave appear unchanged
since prehistoric times.
</P>
<P>
   The caves have no running water or bathrooms, and the brown mud
walls are decorated with newspaper or colored posters. Many caves
are electrified, with a single naked bulb hanging from a wire and a
cheap television set _ creating a bizarre juxtaposition of cave
dwellers watching historical costume dramas and soap operas
broadcast from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the government in Ningxia province launched a
five-year, $365 million program to voluntarily relocate one million
cave dwellers to new irrigated villages in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   But many cave people who had moved during an earlier pilot
project found the pioneer life too hard and moved back to their old
caves. The government says the new villages eventually prospered,
and there is a waiting list for people wanting to move.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Shaanxi cave villages, where the only sounds are of
roosters crowing, pigs squealing, and people chopping wood, no one
knows of any plans to move them. But they are counting on a
government vow to plant fruit trees to reforest the windswept soil
and yield a new harvest. Premier Zhu Rongji visited recently and
was struck by the barrenness of the land.
</P>
<P>
   Many older people here seem to have no sense of how hard their
living conditions are and have no particular interest in moving to
city dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In wintertime, a regular house is colder than this, and in
summer, our caves are cooler,'' said Yan Zhifa, 63, who has lived
in caves all his life. ``If you build a good, strong cave, you can
have several generations living there, maybe for 200 years. A
regular house needs repairs after five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Yan, who wears the blue Mao cap and plain navy buttoned shirt
still favored by older peasants, cannot grow crops on his eroded
parcel. He has to give the government $8 a year in cash for the use
of the land since he can't pay the tax in grain.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because he has never seen anyone living any other way,
he has never thought to take advantage of the boom in China's
cities. ``We'd never dare to think like that,'' he said solemnly.
Nor does he blame the government for his condition; he just figures
this is the hand that life has dealt him.
</P>
<P>
   Yan says his life is unhappy not for a lack of material comforts
but because of loneliness. One of the downsides of modernization,
he said, is the desire among some young people, including his sons,
to live in their own caves, leaving widowers like Yan sleeping and
eating alone. And perhaps because of the influence of television,
the younger generation may be the first in centuries to try moving
out of caves entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city represents modernization, and of course we want to
develop,'' said Li Gaiqing, 36, cooking under a poster of Deng, the
leader whose modernization drive not only opened trade, but also
put a television in nearly every cave. ``It's just like food; once
you have enough to eat, you can think about eating good food. Once
you can live comfortably, you can think about a beautiful house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
