u k BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-22 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VOICE OF FAIRNESS AMID THE DECATUR DIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has been accused of meddling in a community's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   He has been criticized as a publicity-seeker searching for an
issue to enhance his national image.
</P>
<P>
   But from the moment he arrived in the central Illinois farming
town of Decatur, the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson was in the right place
for the right reason. He was there to expose an injustice delivered
to seven students who were initially expelled from school for two
years for brawling during a football game.
</P>
<P>
   Only after pressure from Jackson and Governor George Ryan did
the School Board agree to cut the expulsion from two years to one,
and allow the students to immediately enroll in an alternative
school. Yet Jackson knew that even a one-year expulsion is still
too severe a punishment for the brawl. There were no guns, no
knives, no drugs, and no serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A 17-second videotape of the fight, captured by a nearby
spectator, has been on virtually every newscast in the country. The
videotape, however, did not expose the true wrong: the School
Board's ``zero tolerance'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the expelled students were wrong to fight at the game,
and deserved a fitting punishment after due process. But there was
no fitting punishment, and no due process. The board's action
precluded both.
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson said, rather than expell them and enhance their
chances of being dropouts or worse, a smarter punishment would be
to force them to stay in school under stricter conditions. ``If
there's hell in them,'' Jackson said, ``let's educate the hell out
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's arrival in Decatur did as much to bring a local
injustice to the nation's attention as did public airing of the
videotape of Los Angeles police beating Rodney King. In both cases,
those in power were caught delivering an injustice upon those
without power.
</P>
<P>
   Although the expelled students in Decatur were African-American,
Jackson was pragmatic and wise in stressing that the issue was
about fairness, not race. He reminded the School Board, and the
media, that in other, more serious incidents, the students involved
had received less harsh discipline.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he noted that a Decatur student, who is white, made
a bomb threat to the school, which is far more serious than the
highly publicized brawl. That student was expelled for one year.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, however, knows that if he labeled this as strictly a
racial issue, he would set himself against conservatives who might
suggest that he is trying to use the ``race card'' to get the
students a lesser punishment. He could also lose credibility with
many African-Americans, who might accuse him of using racial
demagoguery to protect students who are guilty of starting a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Jackson is stressing the unfairness of the discipline
given the brawlers compared with punishments given other students.
He is letting the news media and television watchers see the
obvious: that it is about unfair treatment of individuals who
happen to be black. As Jackson puts it, ``This isn't about black or
white, it's about wrong or right.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's ongoing presence in Decatur _ a town in which blacks
make up 17 percent of the population, and 40 percent of public
school enrollment _ also has helped reveal other injustices against
the expelled students. None was given a chance to present his side
of the story. And the school reportedly released the offending
students' attendance and grades, in an apparent effort to show that
they were bad students as well as troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's filing of a lawsuit against the school administrators,
which seeks $5 million in damages for each of the six involved
students (one of the brawlers dropped out), will help assure that
the board's wrongful action will ultimately be more embarassing to
it than the release of their private records was to the students.
And attempts to justify the School Board's action by seeing four of
the students charged with felony counts of ``mob action'' will
prove futile.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson accompanied the students to alternative schools
last week, he is not giving up his fight to get them back into
regular classes in the Decatur school system. He wants them to be
eligible for reinstatement as early as January if they do well in
the alternative schools _ a compromise from his earlier position of
immediated reenrollment.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackie Goetter, president of the School Board, insists there
is no possibility of reinstatement before next spring. She said,
``There is nothing that the Rev. Jackson can say or do during his
visit to Decatur that would make me change my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   If, however, the School Board continues to dig in its heels,
Decatur, Ill., in 1999 may become what Selma, Ala., was in the
1960s. Because while much progress against racial injustice has
been made since Selma, the events in Decatur suggest we still have
a way to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
