<HEADLINE>
FILMS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
!! ``Felicia's Journey'' Bob Hoskins is creepily compelling as a
bachelor chef in grimy Birmingham who offers refuge to Elaine
Cassidy's pregnant Irish girl looking for her boyfriend. But the
pieces never come together satisfyingly, making Atom Egoyan's film
of William Trevor's novel seem over-stylized and too detached.
(PG-13) 
 
!!! ``Joe the King'' Less is more in Frank Whaley's
autobiographical coming-of-age film. The title character is a child
of the underclass who is anything but a king and can't even escape
into anonymity in his small upstate New York town. Noah Fleiss is
appealingly gallant as young Joe, and Val Kilmer delivers a bravely
self-abnegating performance as his alcoholic father. (R) 
 
!!! ``Last Night'' Don McKellar proves a simpatico director in this
film that drolly _ and then movingly _ goofs on Canadian politeness
and reasonableness, even when the characters are faced with the
knowledge that the world will end in six hours. McKellar, as a man
who just wants to end it all quietly and alone, projects disarming
modesty. Sandra Oh, as a woman stranded in the wrong part of
Toronto, unable to get home for a final dinner with her husband, is
affecting, too. (R) 
 
(FR) !! 1/2 ``The Legend of 1900'' Giuseppe Tornatore's gorgeous
fable about a foundling boy discovered on an ocean liner at the
turn of the century. As played by Tim Roth, he becomes a legendary
pianist who never leaves the ship, sailing through the ragtime and
jazz eras. There's a terrific keyboard duel with Jelly Roll Morton,
but the film is too long and too slack not to go adrift. (R) 
 
!! ``Sleepy Hollow'' Tim Burton's take on Washington Irving country
and the Headless Horseman legend is visually stunning, even if he
rips off his own ``Nightmare Before Christmas'' blatantly. Johnny
Depp and Christina Ricci are good-looking romantic leads, but the
motive behind a series of seemingly ghostly decapitations in 1799
is transparent, and the film seems pretty empty, despite the juicy
atmosphere. (R) 
 
!!! ``West Beirut'' Ziad Doueiri's engaging autobiographical film
about growing up during the chaos of the Lebanese civil war of the
1970s. With school shut down, he and his pals turned filmmakers get
into sweet trouble in this lovingly detailed chronicle. The movie
faces up to the danger that never lets them forget that their
neighborhood is not the playground it sometimes appears to be.
(Unrated) 
 
!! 1/2 ``The World Is Not Enough'' This 19th James Bond caper looks
snazzy, but barely gets by on the strength of its stylistic
flourishes, including a pileup of over-the-top wordplay. Pierce
Brosnan musters the necessary deadpan aplomb, but the plot,
involving Robert Carlyle's Russian terrorist trying to nuke Sophie
Marceau's oil pipeline, has a been-there, done-that quality. The
script is not enough. (PG-13)
