<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Disgrace'' by J. M. Coetzee (Viking, $23.95). A small but
bracing novel by one of South Africa's finest writers, winner of
this year's Booker Prize. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue at the Mizzen'' by Patrick O'Brian (Norton, $24). The
20th Aubrey-Maturin novel is not up to the early books in the
series, but O'Brian's prose is as exhilarating as ever. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Voyage'' by Philip Caputo (Knopf, $26). Three boys from
Maine on a sailing ship, bound for the Caribbean. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Test: The Secret History of the American Meritocracy''
by Nicholas Lemann (Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux, $27). How the SAT
became the preeminent standard for college admission. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nabokov's Blues: The Scientific Odyssey of a Literary Genius''
by Kurt Johnson and Steve Coates (Zoland Books, $27). The
scientific adventures of the most famous amateur lepidopterist. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainsong'' by Kent Haruf (Knopf, $24). An outcast girl in a
Colorado town finds love and care on the farm of two eccentric
brothers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``More Matter: Essays and Criticism'' by John Updike (Knopf,
$35). A new collection from a busy pen. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Stiffed: The Betrayal of the American Man'' by Susan Faludi
(Morrow, $26). A feminist approach to the woes of the guys. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
