<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7826 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-STEIGERE-BOS &LR;      11-22 1661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-STEIGERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING UP FOR LOST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ At 74, Rod Steiger has segued into an ongoing
string of paternal authority figure roles. Already this year, he
has been seen as a grandfather in ``Shiloh 2'' and a judge in
``Crazy in Alabama.'' On Wednesday, he'll be seen as a priest
aiding Arnold Schwarzenegger in the millennial devil movie, ``End
of Days.'' (Steiger mischievously offered to do a fight scene with
Schwarzenegger, but only if he won. It didn't happen.) Before the
year is out, Steiger will play a judge again, in ``Hurricane,''
opposite Denzel Washington's Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, the
middleweight boxer imprisoned for nearly three decades before his
murder conviction was overturned.
</P>
<P>
   With his shaved head, sharp nose, and aviator glasses, the burly
Steiger, at the Palm Beach Film Festival earlier this year for a
career award, is a caricaturist's delight. He made his reputation
playing heavies or, at the very least, emphatic characters in ``On
the Waterfront'' (1954), ``The Big Knife'' (1955), ``Oklahoma!''
(1955), ``The Pawnbroker'' (1965), ``Doctor Zhivago'' (1965), and
``In the Heat of the Night'' (1967). In that film, his performance
as a Southern cop reluctantly partnered with Sidney Poitier's
Philadelphia detective won him an Oscar. His director in that film,
Norman Jewison, directed him in ``Hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the only instance of things coming full circle for
Steiger. For decades, he was angry at Marlon Brando. The reason?
Brando wasn't there when Steiger shot his close-ups in ``On the
Waterfront.'' ``Because acting is reacting, I didn't get over it,''
Steiger recalls. ``Then last year in Montreal (where Steiger was
accepting another career award and Brando was filming), who sends
me this wonderful telegram but Brando? Then I get this note. I go
to a Chinese restaurant and sitting at a table is Mr. Brando. I
said to myself, `I guess I gotta thank him.' So we give big hugs
and I rub my bald head against his bald head, and I said, `I'm
really sorry you sent me the telegram because now I can't say any
more rotten things about you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Physically imposing though he still may be, Steiger allows his
face to soften more readily these days. He wears a gold medallion
into which is sculpted an image from Saint-Exupery's ``The Little
Prince,'' a favorite book that gave him hope. The medallion is also
engraved with the names of his grown daughter, his 7-year-old son,
and the date of his Oscar win. He speaks wistfully of hoping to
watch his son grow up. He writes poetry. Like another fabled movie
tough guy, Edward G. Robinson, he collects art, and has studied it.
Pushed to choose a favorite role, he cites the guilty Jewish
survivor he played in ``The Pawnbroker,'' adding that he stole his
unforgettable silent scream in that film from memories of Picasso's
``Guernica.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Steiger is making up for lost time _ eight years of
virtual immobilization from clinical depression. It got to a point,
he recalls, where he sat trying to figure out which method of
suicide would be the least messy. Eventually, he was led to
medication that corrected the chemical imbalance causing the
depression. His comeback film was ``The Specialist'' (1994),
opposite Sylvester Stallone and Sharon Stone. Steiger played a
Cuban criminal godfather in Miami. He has no illusions about the
quality of the film. ``It was like a $60 million commercial for
me,'' he says, chuckling. ``It said I was still alive.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Absent father &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steiger is also old enough to savor the irony in his current
string of father figures. ``My mother and father were a
song-and-dance team. I've never known my father. They split up in
my first year as a child. When I was on Broadway, in `Rashomon,'
somebody asked me what I would do if a man walked into my dressing
room and said he was my father. I said I didn't know. I probably
would go to pieces or (beat him up). I couldn't figure that one
out. Looking back, I lucked out. I was born on Long Island, in
Westhampton, but my mother moved to Newark. I was kind of on my own
since I was 10. My family was destroyed by alcohol. I grew up in
the Navy. I had one year of high school. I remember getting my
mother to sign a paper and lying about my age so I could enlist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I served in the Pacific. I was on a destroyer. We escorted the
carriers. The Japanese would come in and spray us with bullets, but
they mostly would try to kamikaze the carriers. In the Philippines
we had a tornado that made the war look ridiculous. Waves 40 feet
high for three days. I learned that the wave doesn't go up. You go
down. Anyway, I survived the war. I fell into acting. I never
dreamed of being an actor. When I got out, my generation believed
you should make your own living if you're any kind of a man, find a
place you could sleep in that was fairly clean and you could pay
for. Somebody said civil service, they take veterans first. If you
have the IQ of a decimal point and you were a veteran, you were in.
I operated the check machine that sorted the canceled benefits
checks. Well, they had a theater group with all the pretty girls.
I'm talking a building that takes up a whole city block with about
8,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you'd ask one of the attractive women for a date,
they'd say, `I'm busy. I'm rehearsing.' Well, we found out about
the theater group and, needless to say, we descended like vultures.
We wanted to get lucky with the girls. So here we are, we're six
fiends, and somebody says, `What do you do?' And I said, look at
her, she's gorgeous, and I said, `I'm an actor.' So I started from
there and somebody told me to take it serious, and I did. I
realized I could get $85 a month and go to school, so I moved to
Manhattan and went to three different schools, the Actors Studio
included. I was in a play before I saw one. I gave myself two years
to just study and rehearse.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Steiger began appearing in plays, and on TV in that
medium's golden age, when live drama was shot on camera. The
live-TV experience was invaluable, he says, and became diluted when
TV went to tape. He was TV's original ``Marty'' and also played
Rasputin, Rudolf Hess, and Dutch Schultz for Walter Cronkite's
``You Are There.'' ``I love biography,'' Steiger says, ``studying
about all those people and their social settings. It's the best
possible education for an actor.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A pass on `Patton' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steiger counts Al Capone, W. C. Fields, Napoleon, Hemingway, and
Mussolini among his favorite roles. ``I made many mistakes along
the way,'' he says, ``but the big one was after I had just gotten
the Academy Award and they sent me this script called `Patton.' And
I was this . . . pacifist (of sorts), and I said, `I'm not going to
do anything to glorify war.' I was a schmuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm fairly content. I got no complaints. Looking back, I
realize I had an incredible amount of rage. Because I felt my
family disappointed me. My mother! God help her. I learned later
that alcoholism was a disease. So the neighborhood used to laugh
and make jokes. I used to take her out of the bar and stuff like
that. But the last 12 years of her life, she went into AA and she
was one of the great sponsors they ever had. Anyway, I realize now,
somebody said to me, `Jesus! When you work, you're so intense. It's
abnormal. It's like your life or something.' And I realized only
two years ago that I'm trying to make sure the neighborhood never
laughs at the name of Steiger again. And I gotta tell you, I'll (do
anything) to make sure that doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rage came out, I'm happy to say, in a safe place. Had I
not been so fortunate to become an actor, I would have been one of
those people when they come into the bar, you try to get out
without him seeing you. And when he says, `What are you doing,
buddy?' you freeze and say, `Holy Christ, how am I going to get out
of this?' Somebody would have stuck a knife in my stomach when I
was 35 and that would be it.'' Not that Steiger's battles are
exactly over. Take, for example, his longstanding wish to direct.
It finally looks as if it's going to happen, with a film called
``Thanksgiving,'' about three aging lifelong friends. Steiger, who
wrote the film, will be one of its stars.
</P>
<P>
   Why so long? ``I've been asked to direct for 30 years. I mean,
I've had so many lunches, I felt I owned restaurants. Finally, the
last time a guy called, I said, `Look, let me save you the price of
a shrimp cocktail. I'll give you my whole theory of directing in
two words _ final cut.' Elizabeth Taylor said she'd like to do a
picture about Dorothy in Oz many years later. She said I saved her
life. That's an exaggeration, but a pleasant one. When I went to
see her about Oz, she was in bed, she hurt her back. I came back
two years later, she was in bed, resting. The third time, too.
Since my depression experience, I could tell isolation was
happening. So I said, `Would you like to go to lunch?' She said,
`I'd love to.' We went, we came back, and as I was leaving, the
staff said that except for AIDS benefits, that was the first time
she'd been out of the house in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope she does the Dorothy-in-Oz picture. She's one of the
most courageous, naive in the best sense, romantic people I've met.
And intelligent. And funny. You can't be funny without
intelligence. People have written that we have a romance. We don't
have a romance,'' says Steiger, a veteran of four marriages and
four divorces. ``I don't plan on retiring, ever,'' he adds, not
that anyone was thinking he would. Like any good actor, especially
one who never does things in a small way, he has a vision of his
swan song. ``I want to just keel over and die while filming a
scene,'' he says. However it happens, he intends to have the last
word. His self-composed epitaph? ``See ya later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
