<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Nov. 23:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BULGARIA-CLINTON (Sofia) _ President Clinton, first U.S.
president to visit here, thanks Bulgaria for its help in the Kosovo
conflict. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-GENOCIDE (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Rwanda, angered over the
release of a genocide suspect, refuses to grant a visa to the head
of the genocide tribunal. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-HOLBROOKE (United Nations) _ On a visit to West and East
Timor, Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy to the U.N., says that
militias are using intimidation to prevent most refugees from
returning to East Timor. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SOLDIER (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli Defense Forces moved to
discharge a lieutenant who, as an instructor in an army classroom,
said that Reform and Conservative Judaism, by fostering
assimilation, had done more damage to Jews that the Nazi Holocaust.
By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
