international family planning groups work on the ground: Over the
past decade, these organizations have worked to limit their
dependence on official U.S. financing. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BLIND (Washington) _ The FCC is taking the first steps toward
requiring television to carry narrative descriptions of the action
in TV shows, so that blind people can enjoy TV dramas.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH (Washington) _ Developments in the crash of EgyptAir
990. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-ART-EXHIBIT (Detroit) _ The new director of the Detroit
Institute of Arts cancels an exhibit that had been planned for two
years, one including displays of artwork combining religious and
sexual themes. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   NY-REMEDIAL-EDUC (New York) _ The state board of Regents is
expected to clear the way for the City University of New York to
begin to exclude students from its degree programs who cannot
demonstrate that they are ready to begin ``college level work'' in
both mathematics and English. Although public universities from
Florida to California have been trying to raise admission
requirements, CUNY is unusual in saying that students who have
otherwise met their college admissions requirements may not enroll
if they need any remedial work. By Karen Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-NH (Manchester, N.H.) _ Bill Bradley gives a speech on
campaign finance reform. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-GORE (Washington) _ Republicans plan a billboard campaign
against Al Gore with a special billboard located across the street
from Gore campaign headquarters. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-CHARGE (Tokyo) _ Nissan Motor forecasts a $5.57 billion
group net loss for the year as it takes bigger-than-expected
write-offs to pay for years of losses. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MOROCCO-BOURSE (Casablanca) _ Early next year, the trading floor
of the Casablanca Stock Exchange is shutting down, thrusting the
small, young exchange into the growing ranks of virtual markets. As
in London, Paris, Brussels, Toronto, Sao Paulo and elsewhere,
brokers here will be trading directly from their own offices in a
kind of miniature Nasdaq. It is an impressive step, and one that
several Middle East stock markets are also expected to emulate in
the coming year. After long, sleepy histories, these stock
exchanges have caught the attention of government officials as
vital tools for selling state-owned companies and attracting
foreign investors as they move from centrally planned economies to
free enterprise. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-TRADING (Undated) _ A Securities and Exchange Commission
report suggests that online trading firms may have a legal
responsibility, in some cases to make sure investments made by
their customers are ``suitable'' for them.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are mixed in mid-afternoon trading.
The Dow Jones industrial average was up 53 points, the S&AMP;P 500 down
3 points and the Nasdaq composite up 10 points. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-PRODIGY (Undated) _ SBC Communications and Prodigy
Communications will combine their consumer and small business
Internet operations in a deal that will give SBC a 43 percent
equity stake in Prodigy. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   HOLZMANN-BANKRUPTCY (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Philipp Holzmann,
Germany's biggest builder, is facing bankruptcy after creditors
fail to agree on a $1.6 billion rescue plan for the 150-year-old
company. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-MANNESMANN (London) _ Developments on the Vodafone
Airtouch takeover bid for Germany's Mannesmann. By Andrew Ross
Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
