<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7828 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-MURRAY-BOS &LR;      11-22 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MURRAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECONNECTING WITH DAVID MURRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When David Murray gets on a roll, his tenor saxophone
locks on to the rhythms of the earth. His notes cascade with an
unerring yet unpredictable flow, first with a volcanic fury, then
with a breeze, a sigh. He blows in phrases, each sentence complete.
Yet before marking that punctuation, his lines follow so jangled a
path, radiate in so many directions, they seem impossible to
resolve _ until, somehow, they are resolved, at which point, with
scarcely a breath, a new sentence, a new mystery, begins.
</P>
<P>
   The question puzzling many jazz fans in recent years: Whatever
happened to this guy?
</P>
<P>
   From the mid-1980s to the mid-'90s, Murray staged his
musical-fireworks shows on a regular basis. He put out what seemed
like an album a month, led a half-dozen bands (duos, trios,
quartets, octets, big bands, funk groups), played sideman in
several more (most notably the World Saxophone Quartet). In New
York, you could see him play every Monday night at the Knitting
Factory, and only slightly less often at other clubs around town.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, he disappeared, flew off to Paris and Dakar,
joined up with Guadeloupean ka drummers, Djembe percussionists,
African rappers. A flurry of rumors circulated: He was fed up with
the Wynton-ized New York scene, he had tax troubles, he was fleeing
former wives or girlfriends. Whatever his reasons, went the
widespread whisper, Murray _ barely past 40 _ had given up the
ship, had abandoned not only America but jazz.
</P>
<P>
   He would still toss out the occasional tease. Last fall, he led
a big band and strings through some riveting arrangements of Duke
Ellington and Billy Strayhorn compositions. Now and then, with no
fanfare (who even knew he was in town?), he sat in on late-night
jam sessions at St. Nick's Pub in Harlem. Last month, he brought
his octet to the Iridium, one of Manhattan's most upscale jazz
clubs, to play his arrangements of John Coltrane's music (a CD of
which will be issued, on the Justin Time label, early next year).
</P>
<P>
   Some fans wondered: Could this be the start of a comeback, a
return to roots?
</P>
<P>
   Murray laughs at the question. As far as he's concerned, he
never left.
</P>
<P>
   He is sitting in his favorite Japanese restaurant in midtown
Manhattan a few hours before his Iridium gig begins. ``There's this
whole New York-centric thing,'' he says, shaking his head, ``this
idea that if it's not happening here, it's not happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may not see me here, but I play someplace, with one of
my bands or another, every weekend. All summer, we did this
Ellington thing. I flew the big band across the Atlantic at least
12 times. If they couldn't make it, the octet did it. I talk with
people every day on the telephone. I know what's going on in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   So, why did he leave the country? ``Because I met a woman, fell
in love, and we had a baby,'' Murray says. ``She lives in Paris, so
that's where I live.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Valerie Malet, was the chief assistant for the
biggest jazz organization in France, a government-subsidized group
that works with young people _ mostly African immigrants _ in the
impoverished suburbs of Paris. &QL; 
 &QL; 
His own kind of fusion &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Murray met her on one of his bands' European tours. He
frequently conducts seminars when he tours, and in Paris, he got
particularly involved in Malet's group, organizing workshops,
combining the African pop music they knew with jazz standards and
some of his own compositions. He took the best dozen students to
Guadeloupe, Martinique, and Senegal, and linked them with young
musicians he had organized in similar workshops there.
</P>
<P>
   That link led to the Fo Deuk Revue, Murray's
Afro-Caribbean-funk-pop fusion band, which has toured widely, put
out two albums, and _ coinciding as it did with his romance and
subsequent move to Paris _ led many of his stateside followers to
conclude he'd left the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray insists, ``I'm just branching out. People try to keep
you in their box, they don't want you to branch out. But I don't
want to play with'' _ here he goes into a singsong speech pattern _
``this same quartet, these same three guys, that same riff, we're
going to make that same turnaround that same way. I don't want to
do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never stopped doing what I'm doing. I'm a jazz musician.
How can I stop playing jazz?''
</P>
<P>
   As Murray sees it, the change in scenery has done him nothing
but good. ``In New York, the phone is always ringing. . . . I have
more time in Paris to do research, read books. I have more time to
practice, too. I rarely practice less than two hours a day. I write
arrangements every day for a couple of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also currently organizing his next African project, in
Cameroon. ``They have a history of brass bands,'' he says. ``I'll
arrange traditional songs they know, with a jazz influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, I'm not sitting in a bar trying to learn French
and talking to everybody passing by. I'm over there working, every
day. I have problems sleeping because my brain keeps going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coltrane tribute is not a project he would have undertaken a
few years ago, for a variety of reasons. When Murray came of age on
the horn, in Oakland in the 1970s, tenor saxophone players tended
to model themselves after Coltrane or the other modern titan, Sonny
Rollins _ but rarely both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I knew was Coltrane-crazy, but I went the other way,
with Sonny,'' Murray recalls. ``I refused even to study Coltrane.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of this split stemmed from the clash in loyalties that
erupts whenever two players compete for the crown, whether in jazz
or baseball. Part of it involved a radically different approach to
the main business of jazz _ improvisation. Coltrane elaborated on
the harmony of a tune, twisting and extending its chords to their
ultimate limits and building new chords, and variations on those
chords, on top of that. Rollins explored the melody, taking it
apart and piecing it back together in endless combinations, probing
the essence of a song. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Intent on melody &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``avant-garde'' musicians of his generation, Murray is
distinctive for how deeply he burrows into song forms. Few horn
players since Ben Webster blow a ballad more soulfully; even
Murray's more out-there excursions remain anchored to a melodic
base.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, melody is everything,'' he says. ``Lots of time, you
have guys play squeaks and squawks _ it's not connected to
anything. Everything I play is inside the structure. Every note has
to mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   There was another reason for Murray's hesitation at approaching
Coltrane. ``I always felt a lot of people hit the wall because of
Trane,'' he says. ``It was clear why they got into it. Coltrane
created his own lexicon, he was the future. Here you are, sounding
like an automobile _ he's got a spaceship going on.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you're flying a spaceship, navigation becomes a
different sort of art and, if you lose your grip for a second, you
get stuck in a rut's orbit or crash and burn into the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken me this long _ I'm 44 years old _ to feel confident
enough to take on his music without its obliterating me as a
player,'' Murray says.
</P>
<P>
   He started by studying transcripts of ``Giant Steps'' and
``Countdown,'' Coltrane's toughest solos, and playing along with
the records. ``Listening to him is one thing,'' Murray says,
``playing it is another. Getting into Trane's mind _ that man's
computer was wired different from anybody's I'd ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he arranged harmonies, counterpoints, call-and-response
riffs for the rest of the octet. Then they rehearsed, improvising
further as their grasp of the material tightened.
</P>
<P>
   One night at the Iridium, as the octet plowed into the ethereal
first movement of ``A Love Supreme,'' Murray slipped into the zone
_ the one that modern jazz often aims for but rarely occupies _
where melody and harmony merge, the notes off the horn vaporize
into pure passion, pure velocity, and the band's staggered cadences
meld into the form of pure rhythm. It was Rollins transposed over
Coltrane. It was David Murray _ it was jazz _ at their most
electrifying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
