<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-WILLS-BOS &LR;      11-22 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS GOVERNMENT GOOD FOR THE COUNTRY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT L. TURNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A NECESSARY EVIL 
A History of American Distrust of Government 
By Garry Wills 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 366 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randy Weaver and David Koresh believed in armed
self-sufficiency. Among the materials found in Timothy McVeigh's
car after the bombing of the federal building in Oklahoma City was
a note containing the following sentence: ``Obey the Constitution
of the United States and we will not shoot you.''
</P>
<P>
   All through American history since the signing of the
Declaration of Independence, and even before that, opponents of a
strong central government have often sought to justify their
opposition by suggesting that the philosophical underpinnings of
the nation harbor within them an antigovernment strain that is an
essential and healthy part of the national character.
</P>
<P>
   Garry Wills has taken upon himself the task of demolishing that
argument, and in ``A Necessary Evil: A History of American Distrust
of Government'' he generally succeeds. The Founding Fathers did not
design the federal government to be either weak or inefficient, and
did not plant in the Constitution the seeds of its own destruction,
Wills argues persuasively.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, James Madison is portrayed by Wills as fashioning
a constitution as strong as politically possible. He was trying,
Wills writes, ``to cut back on states' rights, offering palliatives
to the Antifederalists as a way of bringing back his own favorite
plan of federal power.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when modern insurrectionists, nullifiers, vigilantes,
and other opponents of the federal government point to the
Constitution itself for justification, Wills says, they usually
rely on the interpretations of the Antifederalists, who lost the
argument.
</P>
<P>
   An insightful historian and potent polemicist, and winner of the
1993 Pulitzer Prize for ``Lincoln at Gettysburg,'' Wills in this
book rolls out artillery that at times seems trained on a target
too small. McVeigh's act in Oklahoma City was horrible and
demented; how important is it to invalidate some of its rhetorical
trappings?
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Wills draws on sources ranging from Plato to Jefferson
to Mencken to antiabortion zealot Randall Terry _ a canvas that may
be viewed as impressively broad or as oddly scattered. Certainly
there are passages in which Wills bounds down a tangent to make a
point he is eager to get on paper. Reporters call this emptying the
notebook. Wills goes out of his way to attack columnist George Will
and several academicians, including Bruce Ackerman and Akhil Reed
Amar of Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a section on gun control, he wanders back to Tombstone
and Dodge City to counter Hollywood history, saying most cowboys
either had a rifle or were unarmed. ``Handguns were banned in the
cattle towns,'' he says. ``The `Wild West' was the birthplace of
strict gun control laws.'' After portraying a domesticated Wyatt
Earp who ``repaired boardwalks in the offseason,'' Wills goes on to
a scholarly examination of the Second Amendment, which he says is
regularly misinterpreted by the National Rifle Association and its
partisans. ``History, philology, and logic furnish no solid basis
for thinking the Second Amendment has anything to do with the
private ownership of guns,'' he says. This is not new. Robert Bork
has cited consistent Supreme Court rulings that ``there is no
individual right to own a firearm.'' But it is one of Wills's most
vigorous forays.
</P>
<P>
   A few others limp noticeably. One is Wills's fatuous suggestion
that the Vietnam War was actually lengthened by leftist protests,
based partly on the reflection that they hardened the editorial
opinion of the National Review. Another is the tortured logic
advanced by Wills to say that the Supreme Court, when it nullifies
a law passed by Congress, is not exercising a judicial prerogative
but a legislative one, because the Court was created by the
Constitution, a legislative document.
</P>
<P>
   Wills's own argument is that a strong federal government is a
necessary good, and that antigovernment values have victimized
``millions of poor or shelterless or medically indigent who have
been told, over the years, that they must lack care or life support
in the name of their very own freedom. Better for them to starve
than to be enslaved by `big government.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As we approach another presidential year, and the turn of the
calendar, Wills's is a worthwhile contribution to the national
debate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
