<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7834 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-LERNER-ART-BOS     11-22 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-LERNER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RABBI WITH ADVICE FOR JEWS WHO MARRY OUTSIDE THEIR RELIGION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Mass. _ Given the title of Rabbi Devon Lerner's new
book _ ``Celebrating Interfaith Marriages'' _ you just know she is
going to rattle a few cages.
</P>
<P>
   For the average traditional Jewish parent, the prospect of an
interfaith marriage in the family is hardly cause to celebrate. The
Arlington rabbi has herself presided over a couple of interfaith
weddings in which the Jewish parents were so opposed to the
marriage that they refused to come to the ceremony. Rabbi Irwin
Fishbein showed up at one interfaith ceremony and discovered that
the groom, who was Jewish, had been kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``His family had held him in a motel till the ceremony was
over,'' says Fishbein, director of the Rabbinic Center for Research
and Counseling in Westfield, N.J., which collects data on
intermarrying couples.
</P>
<P>
   The examples, of course, are extreme cases. But the fact is that
the Jewish community generally has discouraged interfaith
marriages, and most rabbis refuse to officiate at them, either for
theological reasons or out of a belief that such marriages will
contribute to an erosion of the Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Lerner approaches the matter from a different, less
emotional perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interfaith marriages are a fact of life,'' she states
matter-of-factly in the introduction to her book, a practical
manual for creating a Jewish/Christian wedding ceremony. ``Today
more than 50 percent of Jewish men and women are marrying
non-Jewish, mostly Christian partners. . . . I wrote this book to
help meet this growing demand and need.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerner's book deftly sidesteps the debate among religious
leaders about the propriety, or validity, of such marriages,
although she does suggest that, in general, Jewish clergy are more
opposed to or conflicted about them than Christian clergy are,
particularly Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the book is full of utilitarian advice about
nuts-and-bolts matters such as how to choose an officiant, types of
interfaith ceremonies, how to handle conflicting Jewish and
Christian traditions, suggested blessings and prayers, and small
details for planning an interfaith wedding, ranging from
``placement of the ritual items'' to ``who wears yarmulkes'' and
``lighting the unity candle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so few resources out there for couples who want to
honor both traditions in their weddings,'' says Lerner, who is both
a social worker and a rabbi ordained in the Reform branch of
Judaism. She has served congregations in Atlanta, Richmond, Va.,
and in Lexington. She has been officiating at interfaith ceremonies
since her ordination in 1979. ``It's too much to ask (interfaith)
couples to create their own ceremonies. They don't know where to
begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerner says she first confronted the issue more than 20 years
ago when her brother married a Christian and ``I realized I needed
to develop an understanding of this matter that felt important and
authentic to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has officiated at more than 200 interfaith
marriages, among them those in which one partner is Jewish and the
other is Catholic, Protestant, or Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Lerner does place stipulations on the weddings she
performs. One is that she will co-officiate with Christian clergy
only if ``there are no prayers said in Jesus's name. Some Jewish
people are uncomfortable with the name of Jesus and the presence of
the cross,'' she says, ``since historically many Jews have been
killed in Jesus's name.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor will she marry every interfaith couple who knocks on her
door. ``One of my requirements is that the couple has to make a
decision about how they are raising their children,'' she says.
``It has to be one faith or the other, but not both. My experience
tells me that if you raise children in both religions, they will
grow up to be very tolerant of different religions, but they won't
have the traditions of either parent.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not shy about stating her preference that the kids be
brought up Jewish. ``I say to them, `Of course, I'm biased.' But I
honor their decision. My concern is that children will have a
religious grounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she knows that her stipulations would fail to appease
most other rabbis. Orthodox and Conservative rabbis refuse to
participate in interfaith ceremonies because they believe that
Jewish law forbids their involvement. And while 43 percent of
Reform and Reconstructionist rabbis (the liberal branches of
Judaism) do officiate at such weddings, according to a 1999 survey
of 1,929 rabbis conducted by the Rabbinic Center for Research and
Counseling, only about 10 such rabbis are in Greater Boston,
according to Rabbi Fishbein. ``New England happens to be very
conservative,'' he says. ``It just doesn't have a very strong
reform tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since most interfaith couples do not raise their children as
Jews, Reform rabbis often see each interfaith marriage as one less
Jewish family for the next generation,'' Lerner writes in the book.
It is a realistic concern, she notes, given that less than 3
percent of the American population is Jewish, and given that the
sting _ and the impact _ of the Holocaust is still very fresh for
Jews. ``Often,'' she says, ``I hear people say, `I don't want to
finish what Hitler was trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But while she understands these concerns, she doesn't share them
all. ``I'm not as worried as a lot of people are,'' she says. ``I
feel that if we have something to offer _ something precious _
Judaism will always be there. I've seen how interfaith marriages
really bring a lot of important insights into the Jewish community,
and revitalize us. I can't tell you the number of times I've heard
Jewish couples say that the Christian partner has gotten them more
involved in their Judaism, and made them think about their
traditions in new and positive ways.''
</P>
<P>
   She allows that her position on such marriages has placed her
``a little bit on the fringe'' of mainstream Jewish clergy,
``although not because I've gotten that feeling from my
colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucking tradition ``has been scary at times, but I get wonderful
feedback. I feel so strongly that this is the right thing to do. I
think it is important to be welcoming to people of different faiths
within the Jewish community. And the Jewish partners often feel
rejected if they can't find a rabbi to perform the ceremony. In any
wedding, the number one priority is the couple's relationship. If
they truly love one another and respond to each other's traditions,
they can have a wonderful life together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
