<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-KINGSTON-CLINTON-1123     11-22 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGSTON-CLINTON-1123-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GEORGIA REPUBLICAN TRAVELING WITH CLINTON FIND HIMSELF IN
STRANGE, FRIENDLY WATERS
 &HT;    (350&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With CLINTON-1123.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria _ Georgia Republican Jack Kingston had his
doubts about touring southern Europe with President Clinton and
several hundred of the Democratic Party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   But the congressman has found his comfort zone expanding on a
trip that has taken him from Athens to Florence to Sofia since
Friday, as one of a handful of congressional guests of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Being whisked through the wonders of the ancient world aboard
the modern magic carpet of Air Force One, after all, has its
pluses.
</P>
<P>
   When Kingston got off the world's most famous Carolina blue and
white jumbo jet Sunday night in Sofia, he was welcomed by an honor
guard, dressed in high boots and ceremonial caps with long
feathers, rolling out the red carpet _ literally _ to the stirring
music of a military band.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from the commercial flight Kingston took a few
days earlier _ the airline lost his luggage, Kingston said _ en
route to Athens, where he linked up Friday with Clinton's
entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Kingston wound up at a dinner with Clinton, his
National Security Advisor Samuel Berger, Chief of Staff John
Podesta and a dozen other Clinton confidantes at the Tzar Ivan
Assen II National Rotisserie Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dined on goose livers _ ``to prove I'm a real
Bulgarian,'' he said _ but Kingston was more impressed with the
ambience than the local cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder. He was seated beside Clinton's daughter, Chelsea, and
the two passed a memorable evening, he recalled, warmed by a
hickory fire and the soothing strains of a Strauss waltz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great conversation,'' said Kingston, a father of
four. ``She's a bright young lady and very balanced, and loves her
mom and dad.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he stopped by an upscale crafts arcade in downtown
Sofia top pick up some trinkets for the folks back home _ some
silver filigree butterflies and crosses, and a brightly colored
lacquered box.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no time for shopping,'' said Kingston, who represents
constituents along the Georgia coast, ``so I'm just clearing the
shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, a guy could get used to this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disturbing,'' confided Kingston, who voted a year ago to
throw Clinton out of office. ``I never met so many nice Democrats.
It's scaring me.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   He even had kind words to say about his one-time political
nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference Sunday in Florence to discuss progressive
governance with several of his European counterparts, Clinton stole
the show, Kingston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no question that the president was center stage,''
said Kingston, who is on the trip representing House Speaker J.
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. Kingston sits on three Appropriations
subcommittees, including Foreign Operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just no question that when the president spoke,''
Kingston said, ``his vision, which is worldwide, was respected.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been all glamour.
</P>
<P>
   Ten thousand demonstrators turned out to protest Clinton's visit
to Athens _ none came near Kingston or Clinton _ where Kingston met
with Greek opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed, among other things, Greek-Turkish tensions on
the divided island of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cyprus question is a tough one,'' Kingston said. ``But the
Greek people were appreciative of the fact that the president was
there, despite the demonstrations.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spent last week in Istanbul and Ankara, is trying
to broker peace between long-term rivals Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has a remarkable rapport with both countries,''
Kingston said.
</P>
<P>
   He'll get one more glimpse of the Clinton charm abroad when he
travels with the president on Tuesday to neighboring Kosovo.
Clinton led his NATO allies in a 78-day air war last spring to
drive out Serb troops and paramilitary thugs who were raping,
killing and otherwise terrorizing the ethnic Albanian majority
there.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to give a speech to citizens of Kosovo then host a
Thanksgiving week meal for some of the 6,300 U.S. peacekeeping
troops stationed in the cold and bleak Yugoslav province. He's
almost certain to get a hero's welcome _ more good news for
Kingston to report back home to Speaker Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
