<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-MOSQUE-1123-CO     11-22 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MOSQUE-1123-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SORRY PILGRIM, TOURIST; HOLY LAND CHURCHES CLOSE IN PROTEST OVER
MOSQUE
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The doors of the Holy Land's most revered churches
were closed Monday in a historic protest that left pilgrims caught
in the middle of a religious dispute.
</P>
<P>
   On the stone streets of Jerusalem's Old City, monks stood in
their doorways and told inquiring visitors they were ``on strike.''
Church workers shouted down foreigners trying to pray in the
courtyard of the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, believed to the site
of Christ's crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to the Old City at Dormition Abbey, the site of the
Virgin Mary's eternal sleep, a flyer on the closed iron gates
stated, ``Thank You for Understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   And, while the holy family found shelter in a Bethlehem manger
2,000 years ago, the iron door to the church now at that site was
shut Monday. Regular worshippers were allowed in most sites but
foreign pilgrims and tourists, despite having traveled thousands of
miles, were not.
</P>
<P>
   Father Claudius Baratto, spokesman for the Franciscan Custody of
the Holy Land, said it was likely the first time in history that
the approximately 30 shrines of his order were voluntarily closed.
Some of the sites, mainly in Jerusalem, Bethlehem and Nazareth,
date back to the Fourth Century.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Roman Catholic, Greek Orthodox and Armenian
churches called the two-day strike. It was to protest the proposed
construction of a mosque near the principle church in Nazareth, the
biblical town of Christ's youth. Muslims in the largely Arab city
demand that a large mosque be built close to the Roman Catholic
Basilica of the Annunciation.
</P>
<P>
   The closure comes at a tense time, when local authorities and
churches are starting to see the arrival of millions of pilgrims
and tourists expected in the millennial year.
</P>
<P>
   Christian denominations have long squabbled among each other at
the holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have so far failed to persuade the
denominations at the Church of the Holy Sepulcher to install an
emergency exit, even though severe crowding already occurs. Many
roads and buildings are still under construction in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of Jewish-Christian friction have surfaced as well. The
government's Chief Rabbinate recently warned hotels they could lose
their Kosher certification if they display Christmas trees in
public places. Many Jewish Israelis opposed the Christmas tree
decree. But, a Rabbinate official, Yaakov Sabag, said the trees
could insult some Jews ``like the Swastika hurts peoples'
feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   While Catholic and orthodox churches were closed Monday,
Protestant holy sites, visited mainly by foreigners, stayed open.
There are relatively few local Protestants and they have not been
heavily involved in the Nazareth dispute. But, some foreign
evangelical Protestants openly blame the Muslims for the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The church closings signaled the increased pressures of the
millennium. The debate over Nazareth has been going on for two
years, with Muslims constructing a prayer tent near the proposed
mosque site and staging protests. On Easter, riots broke out in
which stores and homes of Christian Arabs were attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Local Catholic leaders, meanwhile, have threatened to try to
cancel the expected March visit to Israel of Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   The approximately 100,000 Christian Arabs in Israel, mostly
Greek Orthodox and Catholic, find themselves outnumbered 9 to 1 by
Muslims and often find the growing number of mosques intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed mosque is planned to be taller than the large
Basilica of the Annunciation. Catholics fear that it will
overshadow the church and disrupt it with loud-speakers sounding
the call to prayer. They planned to use the area, which a court
ruled was state land, as a visitors plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to mediate the dispute, the Israeli government
proposed that the mosque be built on a third of the land, but after
the millennial year 2000. Also, the Muslims were required to take
down their prayer tent. On Tuesday, the Israeli government is
allowing the Muslims to lay a cornerstone for the new mosque.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Interior Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami has promised, also, to
build a police station on the plaza to provide safety.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   He has repeatedly pledged to work with both sides on finding a
solution. But, the current compromise does not satisfy the concerns
of the Catholic leaders, supported by Greek Orthodox and Armenian
churches.
</P>
<P>
   They accuse Israeli officials of trying to divide the Arab
community and use the church dispute to win over Muslim voters.
They say relations have been good between most Muslims and
Christians, but that Israeli officials have encouraged extremists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government supported a small group of fundamentalists who
are intent on building a mosque only a few meters away from the
historic church,'' the church leaders wrote in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is it clear discrimination against the Christian
community,'' they wrote. ``It is equally an abandonment of the rule
of the law by the government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very sad, very sad,'' said Metropolitan Timothy(cq no
family name), a leading bishop in the Greek Orthodox Church. ``I
don't know what will be the effect, but this is the only way the
community found to express our sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists and pilgrims were both disappointed and puzzled by the
closed doors. Outside the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, where
Catholics believe Christ was crucified, groups stood before the
massive metal doors.
</P>
<P>
   Some tried to pray in the courtyard, which is only allowed on
Good Friday. No exceptions were made today, as church workers
threatened to remove anyone praying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion should unite people, not keep them apart,'' Merlin
St. Martin, visiting from London, England.
</P>
<P>
   At Protestant sites, the traffic was heavy as usual. The Garden
Tomb, where Protestants believe Christ was crucified, was crowded
with the usual busloads of pilgrims, including a group from Hobe
Sound, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``The different faiths should have the freedom to visit the
sites they wish,'' said Cliff Churchill, 47, the academic dean at
the Hobe Sound Bible College.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
