<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-CAYMANS-3TAKES     11-22 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAYMANS-3TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-TO-Z LOOK AT GRAND CAYMAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGE TOWN, Grand Cayman _ The jingle rattles in your head:
``The Cayman Islands. ... Those who know us love us. ... The Cayman
Islands.''
</P>
<P>
   But just what do you know of these three little islands about
150 miles south of Cuba?
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, the Caymans consist of 76-square-mile Grand
Cayman, home to George Town, the country's capital; 15-square-mile
Cayman Brac; and 11-square-mile Little Cayman. Total population is
about 35,000, most of whom embrace their continuing status as a
British colony.
</P>
<P>
   Though small, the islands boast some of the world's best
snorkeling and diving, a standard of living and a literacy rate
that are among the highest in the Caribbean, and a refreshingly
friendly approach to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   To jump-start your love affair, we offer an A-to-Z look at Grand
Cayman, the most frequently visited island.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A _ ACCESSIBLE
</P>
<P>
   Cayman Airways flies Boeing 737s and prepares passengers for an
island holiday by serving complimentary rum punch and other fruity
concoctions. Call 800-422-9626; access www.caymanairways.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B _ BEACHES
</P>
<P>
   Miles and miles of platinum-colored shores make Grand Cayman a
beachcomber's paradise. The most popular is Seven Mile Beach, a
striking mix of fine hotels, festive dining and nonstop water
sports _ with nary a bothersome vendor in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Its name is a bit of a stretch, as the beach is only 5 1/2 miles
long. If you are not staying at one of the condominium or resort
hotels along this area, a lovely public beach has ample parking, a
picnic area, a playground and restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C _ CONCH RULES
</P>
<P>
   You can fritter away hours of your vacation sampling the many
versions of the popular fried dumplings known as conch fritters. Or
try conch chowder, marinated conch, conch cocktail, cracked conch,
conch stew and conch ceviche.
</P>
<P>
   Conked by conch? Other traditional Caribbean fare here includes
turtle, oxtail, johnnycakes and meat pies.
</P>
<P>
   And don't skip breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   As a British colony, the Caymans enjoy the traditional English
breakfast. Stop by one of the island's many pubs for a ``fry-up,''
with its heart-stopping portions of sausage, bacon, fried eggs,
black pudding, mushrooms, baked beans and baked tomatoes. At the
Landmark, a second-floor pub serves breakfast to soccer fans who
gather around big-screen TVs. Call 345-949-2582.
</P>
<P>
   For an even more exotic experience, stop by the Champion House,
where locals line up for ladles of traditional Caymanian breakfast
fare such as boiled dumplings, braised kidneys, chicken gizzards,
boiled green bananas, rice and beans, fried plantains and pastries
_ all served buffet-style.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss the habit-forming hominy and corn-meal porridge; the
callalou, resembling spinach in taste and texture; and the ackee
and codfish, a pungent saute of salty codfish, peppers, garlic,
onion and ackee, a red fruit native to Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   And don't be surprised that, despite the bustle, the dining room
is empty. Islanders prefer their breakfast to go. Call
345-949-7882.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   D _ DIVE IN
</P>
<P>
   About a third of Cayman Islands visitors report that they come
for the crystal-clear waters, healthy coral reefs and diverse
marine life that create ideal diving and snorkeling conditions.
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder: Grand Cayman is the birthplace of Caribbean
diving, which began with a single dive shop in 1957. Today, more
than 40 companies provide services here. Divers can select from
more than 130 sites, many less than a half mile from shore. Most
dives concentrate on undersea cliffs where marine life flourishes
and visibility ranges up to 200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   A recommended reference is ``Lonely Planet's Pisces Diving and
Snorkeling Guide to the Cayman Islands'' (Lonely Planet, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E _ Eeeeee!
</P>
<P>
   That's the sound snorkelers make when they brush up against
their first stingray.
</P>
<P>
   The Caymans offer an opportunity to see exotic sea creatures
such as eels, sharks, stingrays and sea turtles without wandering
too deep or too far from shore.
</P>
<P>
   In the shallows of Grand Cayman's North Sound is a remarkable
place called Stingray City. Here dozens of Atlantic Southern
stingrays swarm, looking for handouts as delighted snorkelers
squeal with excitement. The rays, some as wide as 5 feet, are
harmless unless you step on them or grab them by their whiplike
tails.
</P>
<P>
   A Stingray City sandbar provides a spot for nonswimmers to
``play'' with the stingrays.
</P>
<P>
   Several snorkeling/diving tour operators offer excursions to
Stingray City, varying in price according to the number of snorkel
sites. A half-day tour with three stops starts at about $25. We
used Capt. Marvin's Watersports (345-945-4590).
</P>
<P>
   The Cayman Islands Department of Tourism publishes an excellent
full-color guide that describes dozens of sites for snorkelers of
all abilities. Call 800-346-3313.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F _ FISHING
</P>
<P>
   Anglers are attracted to the Cayman Islands by their abundance
of gamefish such as wahoo, dolphin, blue marlin and tuna, many of
which can be found as little as a quarter-mile offshore. More than
a dozen outfitters specialize in shore, reef and deep-sea fishing
excursions.
</P>
<P>
   While local fishing tournaments are popular, the big event is
the Cayman Islands International Fishing Tournament each spring.
The 2000 event is scheduled April 29-May 7, and a $250,000 cash
award awaits the angler who can top the tournament's 584-pound
record for blue marlin.
</P>
<P>
   For information, write the Cayman Islands Angling Club, P.O. Box
30280 SMB, Grand Cayman, Cayman Islands, British West Indies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G - GOLF RELIEVES GREEN ENVY
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean World magazine's readers have voted the Links at Safe
Haven the best golf course in the Caribbean for two consecutive
years. Designed by Roy Case, the 18-hole, par-71 championship
course may be more blue than green, with water hazards dominating
all but two holes. For a tee time, call 345-949-5988.
</P>
<P>
   After a round of golf, retire to the Links' restaurant, where
panoramic views and a French-Asian fusion of flavors make for a
memorable meal. Keep it light _ perhaps chilled tropical gazpacho
and a Caesar salad topped with blackened chicken _ so you'll have
room for the raspberry sorbet. Dinner specialties include roasted
duck and grilled ostrich sausage.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyatt Regency's Britannia Golf Course can be played as a
nine-hole regulation course or as an 18-hole course using a Cayman
ball. A Cayman ball is designed to travel half as far as a regular
golf ball. The Brittania course is the Caribbean's only course
designed by Jack Nicklaus. Call 345-949-8020.
</P>
<P>
   On the horizon is the island's second nine-hole course. Designed
by Greg Norman, the private course will be for guests of the
Ritz-Carlton resort, expected to open in mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H _ HELL, IT'S HERE
</P>
<P>
   Some tourist traps pretend to be paradise. This place is Hell.
Yes, that's the official name of a pit stop on van tours. A
devilish rock formation is the reason some guidebooks recommend a
visit, but it's actually nothing more than a collection of T-shirt
shops brimming with postcards.
</P>
<P>
   And what's this?
</P>
<P>
   A post office in Hell.
</P>
<P>
   How convenient.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I _ INTERNATIONAL BANKING CENTER
</P>
<P>
   London, Tokyo and New York have long been known as banking
capitals. But did you know Grand Cayman ranks fifth in size among
international financial centers? That's thanks to the country's
tax-free policies and 1960s-era legislation that approved banking
secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Today 550 banks, more than 400 insurance companies and nearly
900 regulated mutual funds are among the 31,000 registered
companies doing business in the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   This explains why business suits outnumber swimsuits in George
Town.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   J _ JUST LOOKING
</P>
<P>
   Duty-free shopping is appealing, but you should know going in
that the Caymans are expensive when compared to other islands.
</P>
<P>
   The country's strong economy and the Cayman Islands dollar's
fixed exchange rate with the U.S. dollar (CI $1 equals U.S. $1.25)
mean you won't find the bargains of, say, the Bahamas or Mexico.
What you will find are some choice goods at a choice price. So be
choosy.
</P>
<P>
   Consider jewelry featuring Caymanite, a unique-looking
semiprecious stone found only in the Cayman Islands. The Cayman
Islands National Museum has a nice, well-priced selection.
</P>
<P>
   Seek out locally produced treasures such as folk art, thatch
brooms and waurie boards, which are used in a West Indies game
similar to backgammon. Another popular purchase is jewelry made
with antique coins and other items recovered from shipwrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's way off the beaten path, don't miss Caribbean
Charlie. This wonderful shop on the north side of Grand Cayman
sells whimsical hand-carved birdhouses.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Charlie Ebanks, the birdhouses pay tribute to local
landmarks. The creations are painted by Ebanks' wife, Elaine. Her
palette is vivid and reflects the islands: Pink is for the conch,
green for the sea, blue for the sky, and yellow for the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the Ebankses add another birdhouse to their
repertoire. Charlie also creates custom tables, beds, chairs and
other furnishings. Call 345-947-9452.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware as you shop that some items for sale won't make it past
U.S. customs. Any goods made from turtles (including shells, food
products and jewelry) are banned.
</P>
<P>
   And before buying black coral, make sure the seller is licensed
to harvest it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   K _ KAYAKING AND OTHER ADVENTURES
</P>
<P>
   Activities on Grand Cayman are not limited to snorkeling and
diving. Kayaking, water-skiing, parasailing and windsurfing are
among recreational possibilities. Other options include horseback
riding, golf, tennis, hiking and bird-watching.
</P>
<P>
   Your hotel's concierge or tour desk can suggest places to rent
gear and hire guides. And if you tire of fun in the sun, the
Stingray Bowling Centre &AMP; Arcade offers indoor distractions. Call
345-945-4444.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L _ LOADS OF LODGING
</P>
<P>
   Island accommodations run the gamut from four-diamond luxury
digs to self-service condominiums. But budget-minded travelers will
be hard pressed to find lodgings for less than $100. Even a
normally bargain-priced chain such as Sleep Inn charges rates
starting in the off-season at $120 for a double. The Cayman tourism
office has an extensive lodging guide that lists rates.
</P>
<P>
   When comparing rates, be sure to inquire about added taxes and
surcharges. A government tax adds 10 percent to all room rates, and
most hotels add a 10 percent to 15 percent gratuity.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to films such as ``The Firm,'' the Hyatt Regency is the
hotel that comes to mind when most people think of Grand Cayman.
You'll need a map to find your way around the sprawling Hyatt
resort, which boasts five restaurants, a fitness center and spa,
several boutiques, a dive shop and an extensive children's program.
Call 345-949-1234 or access www.hyatt.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Another highly regarded Seven Mile Beach hotel is the Westin
Casuarina Resort. The hotel is noted for its beach-front location,
friendly staff, full-service spa and Casa Havana, a Cuban-flavored,
open-air restaurant. Call 345-945-3800; access www.westin.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a more intimate experience, consider Annie's B&AMP;B,
one of a handful of guest houses on Grand Cayman. Annie Moulton's
place is in the Snug Harbor neighborhood, a few blocks from Seven
Mile Beach. It provides guests with a full breakfast, towels and
folding chairs for beach outings, and use of a washer and dryer.
Its spotless rooms have private baths, and two sitting rooms are
available for guests' use. Call 345-945-5505; access
www.anniesplace.ky.
</P>
<P>
   All-inclusives are just beginning to gain momentum on Grand
Cayman. Two sister properties are the Beach Club on Seven Mile
Beach and Spanish Bay Reef at the island's northwestern tip. The
resorts' packages include lodging, all meals and beverages
(including alcohol), use of snorkeling and diving equipment,
introductory diving and snorkeling lessons, unlimited daytime shore
diving for certified divers, use of nonmotorized sport equipment
and airport transportation. Call 800-482-3483; access
caymanresorthotels.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   M _ MASTIC TRAIL
</P>
<P>
   The island's natural wonders aren't limited to the water. The
Mastic Trail takes adventurous visitors into a dense forest and
through a mangrove swamp that recalls a time before tourists and
mass logging. Along the two-mile trail, you are likely to see
parrots, frogs, lizards and the West Indian woodpecker, as well as
mango, papaya and royal palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   You can hike the trail on your own, but you'll get a better
understanding of local flora and fauna by taking a guided tour.
Silver Thatch Excursions, founded by biologist Geddes Hislop,
offers a three-hour tour for $50; participants should be reasonably
fit and wear sturdy walking shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Walks are offered daily except Sundays. Call 345-945-6588;
access www.silverthatch.ky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   N _ NATIONAL MUSEUM
</P>
<P>
   The Cayman Islands National Museum focuses on the islands'
residents and their seafaring tradition. One exhibit introduces the
``catboat,'' a vessel that was painted blue to allow anglers to
sneak up, catlike, on turtles.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in the Old Courts Building, the museum pays tribute to
``founder'' Ira Thompson, a cabdriver who began gathering Caymanian
artifacts as a hobby in the 1930s. The Cayman government bought his
collection in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $5, $2.50 for children. The museum is closed on
Sundays. Call 345-949-8368.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O _ OUT AND ABOUT
</P>
<P>
   You'll find plenty of variety in the local dining scene, where
menus offer everything from burgers to racks of lamb. Indulge in
the local cuisine, but be prepared for sticker shock: With the
exchange rate, the $12 entree really costs $15, and most
restaurants add a gratuity to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of our favorite restaurants:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Lighthouse at Breakers is a 25-minute drive down the
southern coast from George Town. The atmosphere is far more casual
than the fare, which includes Chicken &AMP; Shrimp Stir Fry, Lobster
Gnocchi and Lobster Quesadillas.
</P>
<P>
   The charming ocean-side restaurant earns kudos for its
vegetarian selections and freshly baked bread and is widely known
for its extensive wine selection.
</P>
<P>
   It's open daily. Call 345-947-2047.
</P>
<P>
   _ While fresh seafood specialties such as Lobster Bisque and
Basil and Pistachio Crusted Sea Bass are tempting, we have to
wonder whether it isn't the floor show that keeps the Wharf packed.
Floor show is a misnomer; this is a sea show. In the evening, huge
tarpons begin circling the outdoor dining area, which juts over the
ocean. They come to be fed, and their feeding is the show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant employee throws out freshly cut fish, and the
tarpons react with lightning-quick speed. The Wharf also allows
young diners to feed the tarpons.
</P>
<P>
   It's open for dinner daily. Call 345-949-2231.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey Bogart rules the roost at the romantic Ristorante
Pappagallo. Bogart is an African gray parrot who greets diners at
the door; he is joined by a feathered menagerie that includes
colorful macaws and comical cockatoos.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a natural lagoon and topped with a dramatic thatched
roof, the restaurant is stunning. Its menu focuses on northern
Italian specialties and fresh seafood, and its wine list is
extensive.
</P>
<P>
   It's open daily. Call 345-949-1119.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   P _ PEDRO ST. JAMES CASTLE
</P>
<P>
   Another misnomer, Pedro St. James is not a castle. Built in 1780
as a private home, it is the country's oldest stone building. On
Dec. 5, 1831, Caymanian democracy was born when a group meeting
here decided to form the islands' first elected parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can explore the three-story coral-stone house, which
has wide verandas, mahogany floors and a first-floor jail. A
well-done multimedia production shares 200 years of history in 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Spend some time on the Pedro St. James ocean-front grounds,
landscaped with native cacti and trees. Purple bougainvillea and
yellow allemanda offer tropical splashes of color.
</P>
<P>
   It's open daily. Admission is $8, $4 for children. Call
345-947-3329.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q _ QUEEN ELIZABETH II BOTANIC PARK
</P>
<P>
   We discovered the beauty of the traditional Caymanian sand yard
during a visit to this spectacular 65-acre nature preserve. The
park features several habitats, including a Floral Colour Garden, a
woodland trail and a wetland area that attracts many bird species.
</P>
<P>
   The sand yard's collection of conch shells, vines and palms
creates fantastic shadows that rival any showy blooms. It fronts a
colorful and carefully restored Caymanian house, focal point of the
park's Heritage Garden, which explores island life through displays
of fruit trees and medicinal plants.
</P>
<P>
   Another park highlight is its iguana habitat, which showcases
the endangered blue iguana. Although the iguana looks scary, the
park's most threatening inhabitants are a trio of poisonous plants
that visitors would be wise to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The park is open daily. Admission is $7.50, $5 for children.
Call 345-947-9462.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R _ RUM CAKES
</P>
<P>
   You can almost wring liquid from these super-moist cakes, which
are made with specially blended Tortuga Rum. At the ``factory'' and
a satellite mini-bakery, picture windows allow visitors to watch as
the batter is poured into tiny bundt pans. Skip that and head for
the free samples.
</P>
<P>
   Here and at a dozen other Tortuga Rum Co. stores, you'll find
several flavors of Cayman Island Rum Cake, the island's
biggest-selling export. Besides the original-, chocolate- and
coffee-flavored cakes, Tortuga Rum also produces truffles,
rum-flavored coffees, fudge and barbecue sauce.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get to Grand Cayman soon, go online to order a rum
cake at www.caribplace.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   S _ STINGRAY BEER
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the Cayman Islands' first micro-brewery provides a
quick lesson in beer production. Watch as brewers add a bit of
barley, a dose of wheat, a dash of hops and a hint of yeast to
water to produce a heady beer. Stingray is served in many
restaurants and bars. The brewery is closed on Sundays. Call
345-947-6699.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   T _ TURTLE FARMING
</P>
<P>
   The government-owned Cayman Turtle Farm is the only one of its
kind in the world. Started in 1968, the farm is home to 18,500
green sea turtles, the largest weighing more than 600 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to producing turtle meat, a staple of the Caymanian
diet, the farm releases 25 percent of its hatchlings to the wild.
It also is involved in research and conservation, working with
other countries to protect endangered turtles such as the Kemp's
ridley.
</P>
<P>
   The farm's collection of native wildlife includes Cayman green
parrots, iguanas, agoutis and hickatees.
</P>
<P>
   The farm is open daily. Admission is $6, $3 for children. Call
345-949-3893; access www.turtle.ky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U _ UNDERSEA TOURS
</P>
<P>
   Don't dive or snorkel? That doesn't mean you have to miss the
underwater wonders of Grand Cayman. Three companies offer views of
marine life that aren't all wet.
</P>
<P>
   The Nautilus is the world's largest semi-submersible and the
latest arrival on the undersea-tour scene. Its design allows for
above-water viewing on deck and underwater discovery in a spacious
cabin six feet below the waterline.
</P>
<P>
   Nautilus offers several types of excursions, ranging from a
one-hour tour to a dinner cruise. It also hosts a weekly comedy
show featuring the island's Big Kahuna. Call 345-945-1355.
</P>
<P>
   _ A similar experience is provided by the Seaworld Explorer,
which has an underwater observatory and a covered deck and offers
one-hour tours. Call 345-949-8534.
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlantis Submarines operates a 48-passenger submarine that
takes tourists to depths of 100 feet. Night dives focus on corals,
sponges and other nocturnal marine life.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis offers a terrific experience, but some passengers may
be uncomfortable with the tight quarters. Children must be at least
3 feet tall to be allowed on the sub. The company also has a
three-person submarine that takes guests to depths of 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Call 345-949-7700.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   V _ VISIT CAYMAN BRAC AND LITTLE CAYMAN
</P>
<P>
   These two islands _ separated by just five miles, but 90 miles
from Grand Cayman _ appeal to travelers looking for a peaceful
playground.
</P>
<P>
   Like Grand Cayman, they beckon to divers. Just off the north
coast of Cayman Brac, you can explore the cannons, missile launcher
and decks of a sunken 330-foot Russian frigate. Little Cayman
boasts the Bloody Bay Wall, a 1,200-foot vertical wall that teems
with marine life.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Cayman Brac should not miss its parrot reserve,
which opened in 1996. Brimming with silver thatch palms, cacti,
wild banana orchids and agaves, the park is home to about 400
parrots.
</P>
<P>
   Island Air offers daily flights between Grand Cayman and its
sister islands. Call 345-949-5252.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   W _ www.caymanislands.ky
</P>
<P>
   The Cayman Islands' Web site is a good starting place for
vacation planners. It provides information on lodging, dining, tour
operators and more.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not online, contact the Cayman Islands Department of
Tourism's Houston office by calling 713-461-1317.
</P>
<P>
   Another terrific resource is ``Cayman Islands Alive!'' (Hunter,
$16.95). Texans Paris Permenter and John Bigley cover all the
bases, from climate and culture to night life and diving sites.
Maps and lists of Web sites and books enhance this thorough but
compact guide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   X _ X MARKS THE SITE OF PIRATES' PLUNDER
</P>
<P>
   During the 1700s, the islands were known as a pirates' paradise
because of their remoteness. Grand Cayman celebrates its
swashbuckling history with the annual Pirates Week National
Festival, a raucous 10-day extravaganza that includes parades,
street dances, heritage festivities and sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too early to begin planning for next year's festival,
Oct. 27-Nov. 5. For information, write to Pirates Week National
Festival, Box 51 GT, Grand Cayman, Cayman Islands, British West
Indies.
</P>
<P>
   Other annual events on Grand Cayman include the Orchid Show
(345-947-9462) in February; Cayfest 2000 (345-949-5477) in April;
International Aviation Week (800-346-3313) in June; and Taste of
Cayman (345-949-8522) in July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Y _ YIELD TO CRUISERS
</P>
<P>
   While the Cayman Islands limit the number of cruise-ship
passengers to 6,000 per day, George Town can get a little crowded
on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Thursdays. Just avoid downtown during
midmorning and late afternoon, when the day-trippers are in
transit.
</P>
<P>
   Among cruise lines calling regularly on Grand Cayman are
Carnival, Celebrity, Crystal, Holland American, Norwegian, Premier,
Princess and Royal Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Z _ Zzzzzz
</P>
<P>
   As in catching some after a long day of activities on Grand
Cayman. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
