<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON SEPARATED HANDS AND HOOKED PINKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 28)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am not in the least superstitious, but I know enough not to
open an umbrella indoors, leave shoes on a table or a hat on a bed,
touch somebody with a broom or rock an empty rocking chair. When
any of these sure-fire invitations to misfortune occur, I _ like
anyone who hears a sneeze _ say, ``Bless you!'' The latest medieval
research tells us that this phrase _ in German,  &UR; Gesundheit &LR; , ``a
state of good health'' _ keeps the Devil from possessing your soul.
</P>
<P>
   But folklorists know there are more specific expressions that
are used to ward off evil in special situations. At a gathering of
media biggies, I posed this query to Corinne Boggs Roberts: When
you are walking along hand in hand with a friend, and an obstacle
like a tree or a lamppost forces you to break your handclasp
momentarily, what expression do you use to ward off a quarrel or,
worse, permanent separation? Without hesitation, Cokie, as she is
known to intimates, replied, `` &UR; Bread and butter &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bartis, at the American Folklife Center of the Library of
Congress, explains, `` &UR; Bread and butter &LR;  go together, a sign of
unity.'' He finds a citation in the seven-volume Frank C. Brown
Collection of North Carolina Folklore: ``If two persons are walking
and they come to an object (high object) in their path, and one
goes on one side and one on the opposite side, they will have a
fuss.''
</P>
<P>
   A California source shows the expression to be national: ``When
something goes between two people while walking, and nothing is
said afterward, the two will quarrel.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of bytes of e-mailed expostulations will be onloaded
to my head from folklorists certain that the only expression to be
used in that case is  &UR; needles and pins &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Hold your ire. According to a 1920s usage cited in the
Dictionary of American Regional English (DARE), when two people
accidentally said the same thing in unison, ``one would then say
`needles' and the other `pins,' then hook little fingers and make a
silent wish.'' (I used to say ``Snap!'' before hooking pinkies.
Today I say, ``Great minds think alike,'' and eschew the digital
signals.) ``When walkers were separated and did not use this phrase
or  &UR; bread and butter &LR; ,'' DARE adds, ``it was believed they would
have a quarrel.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDS WITH
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. John Kerry has an affinity for the vice president's
positions,'' writes Carey Goldberg in The New York Times, ``and is
friends with him.''
</P>
<P>
   That locution grates on the ears of Kenneth Smith of Newark,
Del. ``Since we have never met,'' he writes, ``it follows that I am
not  &UR; friends with &LR;  you.'' He finds his singular  &UR; I &LR;  ill fits the
plural  &UR; friends &LR;  and prefers to put that as the all-plural ``we are
not friends'' or the all-singular ``you are not a friend of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   I checked with the usagist Jacques Barzun, who is a friend. He
is untroubled by the number disagreement of this spreading idiom
but finds a shade of difference in meaning: `` &UR; Friend of &LR;  refers to
an established relationship.  &UR; Friends with &LR;  gives the connotation
of `friendly toward,' referring to the attitude rather than the
firm relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the element of abstraction.  &UR; Friends with &LR;  is an
outgrowth of  &UR; friendly with &LR; , implying interaction between people.
You can be a  &UR; friend of &LR;  the Constitution or a  &UR; friend to &LR;  man, but
you cannot be  &UR; friends with &LR;  either abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm  &UR; friends with &LR;  her,'' in my book, is not incorrect, but is
informal. ``We're friends'' or ``she's a  &UR; friend of &LR;  mine'' is
unassailable in any company.
</P>
<P>
   REVELATION DISCLOSURE
</P>
<P>
   In a reminiscence of the late Judith Campbell Exner, a put-upon
paramour of President Kennedy, I wrote that ``responsible
newspapers subsequently revealed that ((Sam)) Giancana, the woman's
Chicago lover, was also the Mafia don who took a contract from the
CIA to assassinate Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   A careful reader questions my use of the verb  &UR; reveal &LR; . Wouldn't
a better choice have been  &UR; disclose &LR;  or  &UR; divulge &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   The root of  &UR; reveal &LR;  is the Latin  &UR; velum &LR; , ``veil''; to  &UR; reveal &LR; 
is to strip away the veil. The early use of  &UR; revelation &LR;  had to do
with the unfolding of divine will or the making-known by some
supernatural agency. That meaning still clings to the central sense
of the word today; to  &UR; reveal &LR;  is to allow a vision of what is
beyond the range of ordinary human reason or sight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Disclose &LR;  is its workaday synonym; no heavenly choir is singing
in the background. The root meaning is ``to unclose,'' which means
``to open''; the most common sense is ``to make known what was
previously unpublished, deliberately held back or kept secret.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Divulge &LR;  can be tracked back to the Latin  &UR; vulgus &LR; , ``mob''; it
means ``to make known to the multitude,'' with the whiff of a
suggestion that the informant should have kept his information to
himself. It implies either a breach of confidence or other
impropriety in the communication. (I like Merriam-Webster's New
Dictionary of Synonyms, but will not  &UR; divulge &LR;  my source.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a writer (called `contributing editor') on Time
magazine,'' notes Allan Ecker of New York, ``the managing editor
was T.S. Mathews, a brilliant man. He always struck out  &UR; revealed &LR; 
(`The sergeant  &UR; revealed &LR;  that no gun had been found on the scene')
and substituted  &UR; disclosed &LR;  or just plain  &UR; said &LR; . According to
Mathews,  &UR; revealed &LR;  was `reserved for the five books of Moses and
the poetry of William Blake.'''
</P>
<P>
   I'll go with that. Not every full disclosure is a full
revelation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
