<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A Pesticide Filter &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A car's air filter is a simple device, usually just a ring of
paper through which all of the air entering the engine must pass.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at Ohio State University have studied what amounts to
a similar filter for farmland. But it is one that treats exiting,
not entering, air, and is made not of paper but of evergreen trees.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists studied how effective rows of evergreens were in
reducing the movement of pesticides beyond fields where they were
sprayed. Using droplets of dye in wind tunnel experiments, they
found that pine trees and other evergreens collected two to four
times more droplets than deciduous trees like maples.
</P>
<P>
   Evergreen needles, the researchers noted, have more surface area
than flat leaves, and create swirling air patterns that lead to
more droplets' being deposited. (Evergreens have another advantage
as well; they never lose all their needles.)
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who plan to build a longer wind tunnel for more
studies, suggest that windbreaks made of evergreens could be useful
in limiting the drift of pesticides off agricultural land.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Is Anyone Out There? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that if aliens were to somehow pick up the
jumble of radio and television signals that emanate from Earth,
they would learn much about civilization. But they might get the
wrong idea _ that all humans sound like Rush Limbaugh, say, or look
like Fred and Ethel Mertz.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago this month, scientists sent a deliberate
and much more powerful message, aimed at a specific location in the
sky. It wasn't nearly as funny as an ``I Love Lucy'' rerun, but
after all, it was meant to inform aliens, not entertain them.
</P>
<P>
   The three-minute message, which was sent from the Arecibo radio
telescope in Puerto Rico on the occasion of a ceremony marking a
major upgrade to the instrument, included in simple binary form the
formula for DNA, a diagram of the solar system, a human stick
figure and other information. It was aimed at a cluster of about
300,000 stars near the edge of the Milky Way, more than 20,000
light-years from Earth. The idea was that any civilization with an
Arecibo-size dish or better should be able to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the signal still has a way to go. And even when it
gets to that part of the galaxy in 200 centuries, the cluster will
have moved. The transmission was more a demonstration of the power
of the telescope and less a serious effort to communicate with
other worlds. But that did not stop many scientists from leaving
the tent at the ceremony and gazing up at the telescope as the
message left Earth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Good Show &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Leonid meteor shower last week lived up to expectations,
with some observers reporting peak rates that exceeded the
predicted range of 1,000 to 1,500 meteors per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The show was particularly impressive in parts of the Middle East
and southern Europe, where rates of 1,600 to 1,800 meteors per hour
were reported early Thursday morning. In North America, the highest
counts were 40 to 50 meteors an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Some predictions as to when the peak would occur were highly
accurate, including those by astronomers at Armagh Observatory in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1553EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7960 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ALTERNATIVE-MEDIC     11-22 0786
