<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7975 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-HEALTHY-GUY-2000(2TAK     11-22 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHY-GUY-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A HARDWORKING MAN LEARNED _ THE HARD WAY _ TO PUT HIS HEALTH
FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year after my chest was split open for heart bypass surgery, I
think I understand a little how women must feel after a mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning when I take a shower, I see my reflection in the
bathroom mirror. My eyes invariably lock onto the thick, wrinkly
scar that runs from just below my throat to a spot 2 inches above
my navel. Bypass scarring is minimal compared with the loss of a
breast, but it's still my body I see in the mirror, damaged and
different and never to be the same again. I swallow hard; I guess I
will for the rest of my life.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath of heart surgery is as traumatic as heart illness
itself, maybe more so. The emotional distress before the operation
is different from adjusting to a new lifestyle with physical
limitations afterward. Heart disease can take us by surprise,
especially when we don't know how to recognize the warning signs
or, worse, ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to me should interest you if you are making the
same mistakes or care about someone who is. The consequences can be
awful.
</P>
<P>
   THE MAKING OF A WORKAHOLIC
</P>
<P>
   Compulsive overachievers like me are usually born not quite as
good-looking, intelligent, coordinated or glib as some of our
peers. As children in the 1950s to mid-'60s, we were raised to
believe that, despite our limitations, anything was possible if we
worked as hard as we could. Talent could be secondary to
determination. Parents and teachers repeated the message, and we
believed it.
</P>
<P>
   For us, ``no excuses'' became a philosophy, not a brand of
jeans. Co-workers who called in sick handed us the advantage
genetics hadn't. Self-esteem was measured by how much physical
and/or emotional pain we ignored while we worked harder than the
next guy, which is why some of us die or come close to it when
we're in our late 40s and early 50s.
</P>
<P>
   In my first 16 years at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram, I believe
I missed four scheduled workdays, two when relatives died. I always
arrived around 7 a.m. so I could get in an extra few hours' work
before the office phones started ringing. At night, I wrote books
at home, six between 1992 and 1998. I averaged three speeches a
month, to church or civic groups. I also tried not to neglect my
family, which meant I often did my writing between 10 p.m. and 1
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   With so much time devoted to work, there wasn't enough for
regular exercise. Maybe two Saturday mornings a month, I played
tennis with a friend. Otherwise, my main physical exertion was
opening the refrigerator. I was addicted to unhealthy food _
barbecue and enchiladas, ice cream, pastry and mashed potatoes
swimming in gravy and dotted with thick hunks of butter.
</P>
<P>
   I believed that I deserved those treats because I worked so
hard. My weight increased, from 200 pounds to 220, then 230,
finally reaching a point at which I avoided scales.
</P>
<P>
   Middle age only increased my frantic pace. Journalism is a
profession in which, in the words of the late, great writer Jerry
Flemmons, ``The young eat the old.'' In my early years at the
Star-Telegram, I'd gleefully shouldered older writers aside. Now I
was obsessed with not letting that happen to me. I began
volunteering to write stories no one else on the staff would dare
to do, such as living on the streets of Fort Worth for a week as a
homeless person. My objective was to give readers an insight into
social problems that needed to be addressed. But it was also
self-serving; I was hopeful that Star-Telegram management would
consider me irreplaceable.
</P>
<P>
   I was 46 years old when I spent a week on the streets in 1997.
At the end of that week, my feet were sore (I walked an average of
18 miles a day); I lost 17 pounds (weight I quickly regained); and
had a dislocated shoulder suffered in an attack by a drug addict
outside a homeless shelter. Because my wife had ordered me not to
go _ Nora predicted I would get hurt during the course of the week
_ I never told her about the injury, and wrote around the incident
in the Star-Telegram story.
</P>
<P>
   The shoulder popped back into place, but there was muscle damage
that a doctor told me required surgery. I just ignored the pain
instead, and it prevented me from playing tennis. I became a total
couch potato.
</P>
<P>
   By the spring of 1998, I could play tennis again. But now, there
was a new problem. During my matches, I felt pressure against the
base of my throat, like someone pushing a thumb against my
windpipe. I could still breathe and wasn't feeling faint, but the
sensation was constant and annoying. Occasionally, I noticed the
same pressure when I wasn't exercising.
</P>
<P>
   AND THEN, AGONY
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, Nov. 21, 1998, I went out to play tennis
with my friend. As we began knocking balls around the court, I felt
the pressure on my throat, and this time it was so intense, it made
me dizzy. I said I didn't feel good, and that we'd have to quit.
Inside, I fumed. Enough was enough. I was going to get in shape!
</P>
<P>
   But I had already run out of time.
</P>
<P>
   I got up at 6 a.m. Sunday. Too heavy to jog comfortably, I
decided to walk two or three brisk miles. I was quiet leaving the
house, so I wouldn't wake my wife.
</P>
<P>
   The throat pressure was there from my first step. I kept going,
but about three-quarters of a mile from my house, I was brought to
my knees by a sudden, searing pain that erupted behind my left
shoulder blade. It was agony like I'd never felt before. I thought
I was dying.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't black out, although I came close. The pain didn't go
away, but it diminished. It was still dark; nobody else was around.
I staggered to my feet. Step by step, stopping every time the
pressure in my throat increased, I lurched home and collapsed on
the porch.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   I went inside. Nora and the boys were still in bed. The pain was
now a dull ache. I decided not to tell my family what had happened.
They'd only worry, and I was convinced I hadn't had a heart attack,
because the pain wasn't in my chest.
</P>
<P>
   The next day I saw my doctor. I told him what happened _ sort
of. I'd been walking, had a little discomfort, decided to come
home. He examined me, told me to lose weight, gave me an
electrocardiogram, and suggested that, just to be on the safe side,
I should see a cardiologist. He made an appointment for me for that
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he sent the results of the electrocardiogram to the
cardiologist's office. The cardiologist's nurse called me to say I
had to come in now.
</P>
<P>
   The cardiologist was blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either had a heart attack or tried hard to have one,'' he
said. ``We've got to do tests right away to see how much (coronary)
blockage there is. Then we'll either do an angiogram or a bypass,
depending what we find.'' For every day I put off surgery, he
added, odds dramatically increased that I'd have a fatal heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   I felt like I'd been dropped down a well. I heard a voice I
barely recognized as my own, asking if there was a way I could have
the surgery without my family knowing about it.
</P>
<P>
   He said no.
</P>
<P>
   ATTITUDE ADJUSTMENT
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Nov. 30, 1998, I had triple bypass surgery at Harris
Methodist Fort Worth hospital. I was told I'd have to stay home for
a month, then gradually build to a full day back at work. My diet
would now be sensible, with vegetables replacing grease. I would
exercise regularly, with ``regularly'' defined as ``every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, I would have to change my attitude. That sounded
like the hard part. It was and still is.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy food took some adjusting to, but now it tastes pretty
good. Since my surgery, I have not eaten barbecue or a steak or ice
cream or a doughnut. Not once.
</P>
<P>
   My tennis-playing is still sporadic, but I exercise a minimum of
four hours a week, mostly half-hour daily walks. I've figured out a
hilly three-mile route around my neighborhood, and so far have worn
out a pair of cross-trainers. Sometimes I jog part or most of the
way. I let my body dictate the pace. But I walk when it's cold,
very hot or raining. I often walk right after I get home from work,
to alleviate job-related stress.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep habits are different, too. I try to get seven hours a
night, and I go to bed whenever I feel tired. If that's
occasionally before 10 p.m., so what?
</P>
<P>
   At work, I'm trying to be more sensible. I still get in around 7
a.m., and get a lot of the day's writing done before the phones
start ringing. But I go home by 4 p.m. whenever possible. As books
editor, I can take reading home with me. Ten hours of work a day is
about my limit. When I start feeling tired, I quit whatever I'm
doing. I wonder whether I used to get just as tired and simply
ignored it.
</P>
<P>
   After his bypass, author Larry McMurtry wrote eloquently about
his belief that whoever he was died on the operating table, leaving
a shell behind, a new, although somehow lesser, person. I don't
think anything quite that dramatic happened with me, but I know
what he means. The differences manifest themselves in little
things, like having to remember to button my shirts all the way up
to the collar so the top of my scar doesn't peep out. But I've also
changed in other, more significant ways.
</P>
<P>
   Having come close to dying, I am obsessed for the first time
with not having THAT happen again for as long as possible. I
hesitate now when I never would have before. By coincidence, I was
in Oklahoma City the afternoon those terrible tornadoes struck, but
instead of racing into the middle of the chaos so I could write an
on-the-scene story, I stayed in my motel room.
</P>
<P>
   Recuperation itself has become uncertain. Although I have lost
about 30 pounds, 25 of them disappeared within a couple months of
giving up barbecued brisket. It's frustrating how little weight
I've lost since. I ought to be as skinny as Calista Flockhart (Ally
McBeal) by now. I'm told I have to try harder.
</P>
<P>
   I've had to go through some medication changes, and, in one
case, it wasn't easy. Just after I got back from Oklahoma City, my
cardiologist put me on a new drug he warned might take me a few
weeks to get used to. In fact, I spent almost a month in a haze. At
one point, I couldn't remember which of my two sons was older. But
because the doctor said they would be better for me, I didn't tell
him or my editors about the side effects, and, finally, the side
effects went away.
</P>
<P>
   But the uncertainty hasn't. You never stop being afraid it's
going to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   I might be sitting in front of my computer, hiking up a hill
near TCU, or driving to the grocery store. I feel the tiniest
twinge anywhere in my body above the waist, and I think I'm having
a heart attack. After a moment or two I know that isn't true, that
I'm being stupid. But the next time, I panic again. I guess it's
fair to say I'm always a little afraid now, and that mental scar is
worse than the surgical one down my chest. For me, as for many
other coronary patients, this is the legacy of pushing too hard and
eating too much and exercising too little. All we can do now is try
to minimize the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand me. I'm happy and grateful to still be
alive. I should be around to see my sons finish growing up. I have
every intention of not just seeing my grandchildren someday, but
attending their weddings. But the days in between will have
difficult moments. I brought them on myself.
</P>
<P>
   If you've long been promising to take better care of yourself,
start now. Just imagine seeing your own scarred chest every morning
in the bathroom mirror. Be smarter than I was. You don't want to
learn the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
