<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ENVIRONMENT-1500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER POLLUTION PENALTIES COLLECTED IN TEXAS UNDER BUSH WATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At a time when Texas is gaining notoriety for
leading the nation in toxic emissions, state regulators are
collecting fewer and fewer environmental fines, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Fines collected from polluters during fiscal 1999 have hit a
seven-year low, figures from the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission show.
</P>
<P>
   Many environmentalists say the downward trend reflects lax
enforcement by the administration of Gov. George W. Bush and a
disturbing coziness with the industries that the commission
regulates, an allegation that state officials dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in penalties comes as an increasingly harsh spotlight
focuses attention on the state's environmental problems. As
Dallas-Fort Worth struggles to meet federal air standards and
Austin edges closer to violating them, Houston recently passed Los
Angeles as the smog capital of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing some things that otherwise might have been caught
by inspectors going unpenalized,'' said Ken Kramer, director of the
Texas branch of the Sierra Club, a national environmental
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said Bush's ``whole approach to regulation has been
primarily one of laissez faire, in which business and industry is
allowed to call the shots. In that type of atmosphere, there's not
going to be any tough enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides and commission officials see the enforcement trend
differently. For one thing, the commission _ controlled by Bush
appointees _ says the number of enforcement actions being taken to
court has risen, so getting a final resolution has taken longer in
some cases.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, orders requiring companies to take some type of
corrective action dramatically increased during the past 10 years _
from a little over 200 in 1990 to more than 600 in 1999 _ even
though penalties have gone down.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said an ``all-time record high''
of about $27 million in fines was levied in 1998. That figure
included court-imposed fines generated by legal action taken by the
Texas attorney general's office in addition to fines imposed by the
natural resource commission. She was unable to provide a breakdown
of how much was assessed by the commission or generated by legal
action, although she said most of the fines were the result of
action by the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enforcement of environmental protection has been strong during
Governor Bush's tenure,'' she said, pointing to the spike in
enforcement orders issued by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say one reason that penalties have dropped is that the
agency has gotten better at catching violations early, in part
through voluntary programs, thus avoiding the necessity of
assessing penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are addressing violations earlier in the process,
and as a result you are having fewer penalty events,'' said Paul
Sarahan, the commission's director of litigation. ``People are
getting into compliance sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   According to agency figures, the total amount of fines collected
in fiscal 1999 (which ended Aug. 31) was $4 million. The most
recent year in which regulators collected a lower amount was 1992,
when $3.5 million in penalties was collected, figures show.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with $4.6 million in 1998, $4.1 million in 1997
and $6.9 million in 1996. The highest penalty level in the past 10
years occurred in 1993, when $9.1 million was collected.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from fines, the commission also requires companies under
enforcement orders to engage in ``supplemental environmental
projects,'' in which companies agree to fund local ecological
improvements in lieu of penalties.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, for example, more than $4 million in such projects were
required, meaning that, when combined with penalties, companies
were required to spend more than $11 million to comply with
enforcement orders.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even after adding in the amounts for supplemental
projects, the total dollar amount that companies were required to
spend as a result of enforcement activity is at a seven-year low.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, a Democratic presidential candidate and
possible Bush rival for the White House, has repeatedly hammered
Texas for its environmental problems, recently noting that the
state was ``No. 1 in the pollution of water, air and ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The figures that Gore is using come from the Toxic Release
Inventory compiled by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. The
data show that Texas led the nation in 1997 in total toxic
emissions, which include releases on land and in the air and water.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has led the nation in toxic air releases since 1988,
according to Ramon Alvarez, staff scientist at the Environmental
Defense Fund in Austin, which has analyzed the EPA data.
</P>
<P>
   In total releases of all toxic emissions, Texas has had the
worst record in the nation since 1994, with Louisiana close behind,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and state officials say one factor driving the
downturn in penalties is a controversial state program that
encourages voluntary compliance with environmental laws:
self-audits.
</P>
<P>
   By conducting internal audits, companies can confidentially
divulge violations and receive immunity from penalties.
Participation in the program has steadily grown since it was
introduced in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 260 notices that violations _ and multiple
violations _ have been discovered during self-audits since the
program began in 1995, commission figures show.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were unable to say how many violations have been
discovered altogether, although former commission Chairman Barry
McBee testified before Congress in 1997 that there were, on
average, 4.3 violations per disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   If that rate held constant, that would mean that about 1,000
violations have been disclosed to the commission under the
self-audit program.
</P>
<P>
   Although companies can still receive penalties even after
disclosing violations if the infraction involves willful
noncompliance, the commission's audit coordinator, Scottie Aplin,
said she knew of no such penalties ever being imposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is not to avoid or prevent them from getting
penalties,'' she said. ``The idea is to get them into their
facilities and getting them into compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists criticize the law because the detailed
information about the violations is kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has come to accept it as their right to know what
violations of environmental laws have happened in their
communities,'' said Robin Schneider, director of Public Research
Works, a Texas environmental group. ``You're going to see a lot
fewer violations being punished.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that watchdog groups cite in explaining the
penalty downturn is a relatively new policy, drafted in 1995,
against unannounced inspections. Environmentalists say the policy
allows polluters to cover up dirty practices before the inspectors
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators dispute that characterization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard practice is to announce the inspection, to give
notice,'' said Sarahan, the commission's litigation chief. ``The
exception is where we have a complaint or where there is a belief
that giving notice would allow time for the violations to be
covered up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarahan said notifying the companies ahead of time allows for
``both an effective and an efficient inspection.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas is not alone in experiencing a decline in assessing
penalties for environmental violations.
</P>
<P>
   A story in the November issue of Washington Monthly documents an
enforcement decline on the federal level and in most states.
Although most enforcement activity occurs at the state level, the
article called the EPA ``remarkably lax in its oversight role.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston environmental lawyer Jim Blackburn said there has been a
decline in enforcement statewide for years, a factor he attributes
to the notion that regulated industries should be treated like
``clients'' of the regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like a little more distance, a little more of the old-time
regulator,'' Blackburn said. ``I'm just a pretty firm believer in
that if someone is not in compliance with the law, it ought to be
flagged and they ought to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackburn said the cooperative trend ``was well under way'' when
Bush took office in 1995, but worsened since. He said the
Legislature has not been very friendly to the environment, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, it is hard to get a strong environmental agency,
whether's it's Democrat or Republican,'' Blackburn said. ``I think
it's worse under Bush ... but I think the Texas Legislature is a
huge problem.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1619EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
