<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7979 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-A&AMP;M-TRAGEDIES-1500(2T     11-22 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-A&AMP;M-TRAGEDIES-1500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONFIRE TOLL ADDS TO PALL OVER A&AMP;M
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ All too regularly this year, volleys of
gunfire have rung out over the Texas A&AMP;M campus, blacked out and
eerily silent during the salutes to the recent dead.
</P>
<P>
   In the shadow of the stately Academic Building, where a bronze
statue of Lawrence Sullivan Ross, a Texas governor and A&AMP;M
president, watches over the lawn, buglers sound taps. The doleful
refrain is repeated for each A&AMP;M student who died during the
previous four weeks. This year, it has become painfully familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Death has come calling here often of late, too often for a
campus crowded with teen-agers and 20-somethings. The extraordinary
number of deaths _ by car wreck, suicide, drug overdose, homicide,
plane crash _ had already taken a toll on the Aggie family before
Thursday's collapse of a huge log pyramid being erected for the
annual bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   But the deaths of 12 more young people celebrating a beloved
ritual the week before Thanksgiving compounded an already growing
sense of melancholy at this university.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else could happen this year? What else could go wrong?''
asked Travis Rubelee, a senior in the Corps of Cadets, whose face
registered a tired resignation that, indeed, very little else could
go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   This is a university that takes death very seriously. There are
solemn ceremonies, such as Silver Taps and Muster, and buildings
where hats are removed in honor of A&AMP;M's war dead, and a graveyard
and eternal flame honoring the succession of mascots named
Reveille.
</P>
<P>
   But this reverence is not just part of A&AMP;M. It is embedded into
the culture of Bryan-College Station and the twin cities'
population of about 123,000, and even some of the area's smaller
towns, such as Hearne, where businesses and schools lowered their
flags to half-staff last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to a lot of people over the last two days who feel
the same way I do,'' said Hugh Walker, an assistant city manager in
Bryan. ``They say, `I didn't go to A&AMP;M. I've got no ties to A&AMP;M. I
don't know anybody at A&AMP;M. But this hurts.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M University is a big place, with more than 40,000
students, almost all of them young, some of them from places hours
away by car, some of them overtired, some of them who drink.
</P>
<P>
   A few of them die every semester. But 12 in the spring? And 19
so far this fall?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of students have talked again and again about what a bad
semester this has been,'' said Sean Miller, a 1998 graduate who
works at the Association of Former Students. ``When we lose one or
two, it hurts. But this year has been extremely difficult to deal
with. It's certainly tested our faith. And a lot of us just want
this one to be over with.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's student newspaper, ``The Battalion,'' ran a news story
Nov. 4, two weeks before the bonfire accident, about the rising
death toll.
</P>
<P>
   Four students died in auto accidents during a three-week period
in late February and March.
</P>
<P>
   A student overdosed on cocaine in March.
</P>
<P>
   A freshman leaped to his death in March from a campus parking
garage in the middle of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Also in March, a 21-year-old woman who was taking a semester off
from A&AMP;M was found bludgeoned to death in Brazos County.
</P>
<P>
   In April, an A&AMP;M student was killed in an accident on Interstate
30 in Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   A plane, owned by Ags Over Texas, carrying five skydivers from
A&AMP;M, crashed in September after taking off from a Bryan airfield,
killing all aboard.
</P>
<P>
   An A&AMP;M freshman fell asleep at the wheel of his car and plowed
into a crowd outside a fraternity party in October, killing six
students, one of them from A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``With any of these incidents, it has amazed me how many
students are impacted,'' the paper quoted the student counseling
director as saying. ``It is almost like dropping a stone and the
concentric circles going out.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at Silver Taps, which seldom attracted more than a
couple of hundred students, has been going up too. The next one,
Dec. 7, right before finals, may set a record when taps is played
12 times.
</P>
<P>
   Taken individually as deaths, though, a number of students and
professors said they could rationalize this year, as bad as it has
been. Car accidents happen all the time. Skydivers take risks. Drug
and alcohol abuse leads to bad decisions.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been the case since Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unthinkable happened,'' said Drunay Collins, a junior from
San Antonio. ``It was like Bryan-College Station had an earthquake.
That's how I felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, and friend Donna Trevino, also a junior, said the
bonfire deaths struck the campus so much harder because they
happened on campus, because the victims died during construction of
the bonfire, because the hearses sat parked on the polo fields all
day for everyone to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affects everyone who goes to school here,'' Trevino said.
``It's been very hard to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the university hasn't tried. Classes went on as
scheduled, the administration believing that the students might be
better off distracted with math and science.
</P>
<P>
   But a great many of the professors postponed tests or just gave
``walks.'' A few classes prayed together, some just talked about
their feelings. Texas A&AMP;M has never been quieter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My math prof is an adviser to the Corps and she came into
class (Friday) and just lost it,'' Trevino said. ``She's a pretty
cocky kind of math prof, so it was difficult for all of us to see
that. This just isn't going to go away for us.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Bryan-College Station is unquestionably a college town. Although
the two cities have their own personalities and have been known to
compete with each other, they're forever linked, really, as one
place. The unifying element is A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``No A&AMP;M, no Bryan-College Station,'' explained Don Ganter,
owner of the area's legendary watering hole, the Dixie Chicken.
``Without that university, there wouldn't be enough people around
here for a volunteer fire department.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganter figures that 95 percent of the people in Bryan-College
Station are economically tied to A&AMP;M, but probably more than that
are emotionally tied to it.
</P>
<P>
   College Station has the newer homes, most of the students, a
majority of the professors. Bryan is older, less expensive, more
working class. Around them are rural towns like Calvert and Iola
and Wellborn.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mayfield, director of the Baptist Student Ministry and a
resident of the area for only about three years, said the mixture
revolves around A&AMP;M's students, transient as they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a noon Bible study every week and the local churches
bring food for the students to eat,'' Mayfield said. ``But you know
who brings most of the food? It's the churches in Navasota and
Roans Prairie and Madisonville, none of whom really have a personal
tie to A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a strange, and really strong, friendship and bond
between the local folks and the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   That bond is seen in the flags at banks, hotels, car
dealerships, fast food joints all flying at half-staff. It is seen
in the words of encouragement on signs along the street, and in the
eyes of an Asian convenience store clerk who apologized for crying
in front of a customer. ``It's the bonfire,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freshmen in school for two weeks come by here to make sure
they get their senior boots from us,'' said Kathi Holick,
granddaughter of the Czech cobbler who built a boot business on A&AMP;M
cadets. A few minutes after she said it, two underclassmen came in,
just to sit there quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get to know them over the years,'' she said, biting her
lip. ``It's been a very weird two days.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Don Self, a 20-year-old from Arlington killed in the
bonfire accident, was supposed to pick up his senior boots in a few
days. Tim Kerlee Jr., a freshman who died late Friday, asked to
hold a pair of senior boots before he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you supposed to do with that, when a boy's friends
come running in here saying all he wants to do is hold a pair of
boots before he dies?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not many people expect A&AMP;M or the communities to return to
anything close to normal until after the Thanksgiving break. This
week's yell practice and football game, several students said, will
only serve as painful reminders.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Oliver, an associate dean in the College of Liberal
Arts and an English professor, hopes that by early December the
campus won't still be so obviously grieving. Although Oliver isn't
sure things will turn around until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we talk about on a college campus is the future _ the
future of the students, the future of the world, the future of the
university,'' Oliver said. ``When events like this happen, you
can't talk about futures.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
