<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-KUNGFU-FITNESS-NY     11-22 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-KUNGFU-FITNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KUNG FU, ONLY THE MUSCLES SCREAM 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By ANDREA HIGBIE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kung fu is the martial art with the silliest song _ Carl
Douglas' ``Kung Fu Fighting'' of 1974 _ and most revered
practitioner: Bruce Lee, whose fans became even more cultlike after
he died of a brain edema in 1973 at the age of 32.
</P>
<P>
   So with the song dancing in my head (``Everybody was kung fu
fighting/Those cats were fast as lightning/In fact it was a little
bit frightening/But they fought with expert timing'') and in
observance of what would have been Lee's 59th birthday (Nov. 27),
off I went to the nearest kung fu parlor, Al Bender's Kung Fu
Academy of New Jersey, in Bloomfield.
</P>
<P>
   If you were thinking that a man named Al Bender might not be the
most apt instructor of the ancient art of kung fu, you would be
wrong. Bender is a man Bruce Lee would have had to admire. Strong
and fairly silent like Lee (his early idol, by the way, no surprise
that), he talks philosophy before practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The philosophy is in the movement,'' said Bender, 43, who
began his training in 1977 and studied with Peter Kwok, a martial
arts grandmaster, and Bow Sim Mark, a master. ``You can overcome
your opponent with basic technique but you must overcome yourself
with advanced technique. That means: always strive for higher
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Kung fu is proclaimed to be the most holistic of the martial
arts, with its practice of self-defense, exercise, precision and
spiritual achievement. The Chinese say it can be done in the space
of a lying cow: One needs nothing but concentration and desire.
</P>
<P>
   The academy's classes in the large second-floor studio decorated
with trophies and yin-yang posters are much like the Douglas song
(minus the cats). About 25 men, teen-age boys and young boys along
with a smattering of women meet every Saturday morning for two
hours. For most exercises, each student is paired with a partner of
similar strength. For punching and kicking, one student holds small
padded targets, moving them quickly so the other must adjust his
eye, hand and foot coordination to hit them.
</P>
<P>
   My partner was Sarah, an enthusiastic student in her 30s who was
graceful in her loose black tunic and pants. She promised not to
punch or kick me and, I'm happy to report, kept her word. Students
do get bonked every now and then; I've seen the bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Three teachers _ sifus _ roam and instruct, prod and encourage
as the class works offensively and defensively. Kung fu is a
``special kind of skill, a fine art rather than just a physical
exercise,'' Lee wrote, and I found myself being turned into ... an
artist. The instruction to this end is exacting, to a fault: By the
50th pivot kick at a standing padded target, I was not so inclined
to continue perfecting my form as I had been 40 kicks earlier, but
under the gaze of my sifus, continue I did.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone cheers everyone else on, even grinning as the little
boys romp through their exercises. ``We're like a family,'' Edelyn,
a student who said she gave up aerobics classes for kung fu, told
me, and I took this to mean a happy family, despite the punching
and kicking. John, another student, assured me that in a couple of
weeks I'd be able to do the moves in my sleep. Not sure my husband
would appreciate that, I still pressed on, feeling the beginnings
of what would become 72 hours of assertively throbbing muscles,
with pain spreading like a rumor in my forearms, upper back and
inner thighs.
</P>
<P>
   Sifu Al took Justin, the other new student, and me aside, and
called to Sifu Rafael to ``teach them a lesson.'' Uh-oh. But the
lesson, fortunately, involved kicking a big inanimate target as
well as defending myself, hypothetically, against Justin's punches.
Defense is crucial to kung fu, which also means having the smarts
to retreat when your opponent is bigger and stronger, which for me
at 5-foot-5 would be pretty much all of the time and was definitely
the case with Justin, who crowded 6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Though this was Justin's first lesson, it was clear that he had
done some serious time practicing in front of the mirror. He was at
most 18, but he moved like a person who had watched a lot of kung
fu movies, Bruce Lee's ``Enter the Dragon'' and ``Fists of Fury''
among them. Symbolism is important here: dragon connotes wisdom.
(Fists, the obvious.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The opponent is but the other complementary (not opposite)
part,'' Lee is quoted in John Little's new book, ``Bruce Lee:
Artist of Life'' (Tuttle, $24.95). Justin and I were perfectly
complementary; he punched, I ducked.
</P>
<P>
   Kung fu is quiet; no one is screaming or breaking boards with
bare hands and feet, as in karate. Concentration is essential.
There are hundreds of styles of kung fu, derived from northern and
southern China as well as Vietnam, India and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the arts practiced today are less than 150 years old,
whereas traditional kung fu can trace its lineage back 4,000 years
and possibly 6,000 years,'' said Michael J. Formica, assistant
instructor at the Chinese Kung Fu Wu Su Association in Manhattan,
adding that humor was long a part of the martial arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Christian missionaries were first in China, they saw
people doing t'ai chi and chi kung and asked, `What's that?' They
were told `kung fu,' or `hard work,''' said Formica (pronounced
for-MEEKA). ``Not understanding the joke, they began referring to
wu su martial arts as `kung fu,' and it stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard work'' is right. ``Rife with paradox'' is also a true
description, as is ``obsessively complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person grabs you, he is in control, right?'' said
Formica. ``Wrong. You are in control, because that person has made
a commitment to action, while your options are all still available
to you. By virtue of his offensive act, your defensive act becomes
offensive. Personally, that took me about 20 years to grasp.''
</P>
<P>
   A subtle spirituality, over time, is of the essence. ``A  &UR; real &LR; 
martial artist, not these punch-kick-punch-kick guys, will tell you
that fighting is ancillary to practice and just a happy benefit,''
Formica added.
</P>
<P>
   If pain was gain, then I'd accumulated a ton of it. But four
days later, in time for the Wednesday night hourlong class devoted
to form, my muscles were beginning to feel like themselves again.
Good thing, too, because it was time to stretch them past all
recognition. Now I know, should I ever need to do this again, that
I can squat, bend my left knee to the floor and stretch my right
leg all the way out to the right. In striving for higher
achievement, I also know that I can hop back up and stand straight,
bend down and swing my head past my knees _ without fainting!
</P>
<P>
   The forms necessary to set into action the punches and kicks are
intricate and precise. Let us just say that if your feet are not at
perfect 45-degree angles in the first position, a sifu will let you
know about it. And watch while you correct it. The type of kung fu
practiced here _ Chuan Su Er Shur Fa _ has 20 forms; we focused on
the first two, and tried the first 10. No. 9 _ ``Hidden Punch'' _
involves striking the opponent while deflecting his force; trust
me, it's impressive.
</P>
<P>
   The high kicks were fun and allowed me to indulge in my favorite
fantasy career, Rockette. (With sneakers.) I was advised to add my
punches to the kicking and told that I would ``feel it'' the next
day. I'm not an exercise neophyte but as punching and kicking are
not normally activities I do every day (though I know I could get
used to this, especially with the right targets), that promise came
true.
</P>
<P>
   So kick and punch I did, over and over, the words of ``Kung Fu
Fighting'' urging me on. If I was not fast as lightning, at least I
can say I was, to the little boys in the class perhaps, a little
bit frightening. The expert timing is another story.
</P>
</TEXT>
