<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7985 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BREAST-CANCER-ART     11-22 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAST-CANCER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESBIANS FIND CANCER SUPPORT WITHOUT EXCUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What happens to a couple when one partner suddenly
becomes ill and dependent? How will a lover react to a scarred or
missing breast, a bald head, a woman who wakes up crying in the
middle of the night, wondering how much time she has left?
</P>
<P>
   Those issues may come up at any support group for women with
breast cancer, and the five couples who discussed them at Beth
Israel Medical Center in Manhattan on a recent evening were no
different from most, except in one essential way.
</P>
<P>
   Both the patients and their partners were women: the group had
been created specifically for lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that lesbians need or want a separate support group
may seem puzzling to the larger heterosexual world. Of all
diseases, breast cancer would seem to be the one that should unite
women from every walk of life.
</P>
<P>
   But even in a supposedly enlightened era and a smugly
sophisticated city, gay and straight do not always mix. The women
who met at Beth Israel said they needed their own group not because
they were uncomfortable with straight women, but because straight
women were uncomfortable with lesbians. And they said that as much
as they wanted to talk about breast cancer with other women, if the
lesbian group had not been formed, they would not have joined a
support group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is safe,'' said one of the group's members, Cheryl
Dessin, whose partner, Barbara Slatos, was treated for breast
cancer last year. ``It's a very comfortable atmosphere. We can say
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Slatos said it was bad enough to have breast cancer without
having to worry about being judged or looked down on by
heterosexual women in a support group, or having to masquerade as
straight to avoid their disapproval. ``That would be unendurable,''
she said. ``There are many, many homophobics out there, even in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Crespi, a therapist who acts as facilitator for the group,
said, ``You don't want to have to think about being gay when you're
dealing with something that is life and death.'' In a group where
everyone is gay, she said, ``you don't have to justify or explain
your life to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   There are not many groups like the one at Beth Israel, but
people involved with health care problems confronting gay women say
they expect that additional groups will be created, as an outgrowth
of other medical and social services designed especially for
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the increased awareness has resulted from the efforts of
advocacy groups for health care for lesbians. There are now about a
dozen such groups in the United States, according to the Mautner
Project for Lesbians with Cancer, in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors discriminate, researchers discriminate, insurers
discriminate,'' said Kathleen DeBold, executive director of the
Mautner Project. ``Cancer does not discriminate, and that's why
these projects are so important.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesbians in long-term, stable relationships are often denied the
right to make decisions for a severely ill partner, Ms. DeBold
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a client who couldn't get into the intensive care unit
to see her lover except by posing as her sister,'' Ms. DeBold said.
``When the woman's family came, they said, `That's not her sister,'
and the hospital threw her out. This is the kind of thing people go
through all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeBold said that when her own partner of more than 20 years
was being treated in an emergency room, a doctor determined that
she was not a blood relative and told her that if she did not leave
he would have her removed by a guard.
</P>
<P>
   The same insensitivity can come out even in support groups.
</P>
<P>
   Terri O'Hara, director of Lesbian Cancer Support Services in
Denver, said, ``The ideal is that it shouldn't matter. We should be
able to walk into a room and feel completely comfortable exposing
our lifestyles. But we hear hurtful and hateful things every day.
I've had lesbians say they went to support groups and other women
left if they brought or even mentioned their female partners.''
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, Ms. O'Hara said, women who join mainstream
groups decide to stay in the closet, avoiding mention of their
partners or referring to them in a vague way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cover up,'' Ms. O'Hara said. ``It's a lot of work. It can
be exhausting. You're not feeling well, you're emotionally in
turmoil, you have financial concerns. It's a vulnerable time to
worry about outing yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   A particular concern among gay women who have partners is that
the partners be able to attend the support group. Several lesbians
said they thought gay partners were probably more interested in
participating than husbands were. But even if husbands did want to
attend, the idea of the gay partners sharing their feelings with
the straight husbands somehow was not a comfortable scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``With breast cancer, so many women I've talked to who have
tried going to a regular support group find that the women spend a
lot of time talking about husbands and how husbands can't accept
their body image,'' Ms. DeBold said. ``Most lesbians do not have
that kind of problem in their relationships. The perception of the
female body is different. Lesbians tend to be much more loving and
supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Siegel, a member of the Beth Israel group, was treated
for breast cancer in 1991 and joined a mainstream support group.
She was 57 then but had not told her doctors or the other women in
the group she was a lesbian, or mentioned that she had a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why I didn't say it, I can't even tell you,'' she said. ``I
don't know why. I knew I was the only lesbian in the group.
Everybody else spoke about a boyfriend or a husband. I didn't mind
being there as long as we stuck to the matter of cancer, but there
were times when some of these women had to refer to their mates. I
felt a kind of lack. I would have liked to have said something
also. Maybe I should have. It probably wouldn't have made a
difference, but maybe I thought they wouldn't welcome me as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, she said, her attitude is different: ``I think it took
the cancer and possibly living in New York for a while for me to
say, I'm a person, I live in New York, I pay my taxes, I have a
right to be a lesbian. I came through the cancer, I met my maker
and I am what I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crespi said that many gay women, particularly older ones who
grew up when there was far less acceptance, cannot help but expect
straight people to disparage them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's internalized homophobia,'' Ms. Crespi said. ``As gay
people, it's difficult to escape your own feelings of, `I'm not
going to be treated well or valued, people are going to be
prejudiced.' We grow up with a history of a lot of very negative
feelings, and the fear is really there all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   A mixed group might be successful if it were identified from the
outset as open to both gay and straight women, so that members
would by definition be people who were willing to accept each
other's lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be wonderful,'' Ms. DeBold said. ``A cancer support
group is not the place to deal with issues about sexual
orientation. That's the goal, that one day the barriers will be
removed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
