<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME IS NOT BOWLING ANYONE OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Palm Beach and all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're tired. They're frustrated. They're hurt. At best, they
will finish with a mediocre 7-5 record and get a bid to a mid-major
bowl like the Insight.Com in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the thought of accepting a bowl bid with
those credentials would have been denied without a second thought.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, when Notre Dame football was a religious
experience on Saturday afternoons in the fall. When College
Football America took its cue from what happened under the Golden
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   This is now. And it's not pretty for longtime followers of the
Irish to accept. Notre Dame football has become . . . ordinary,
which is the harshest thing you can say about the program.
</P>
<P>
   That the team is even considering a bowl bid with such a record
shows you how low the bar has been dropped in South Bend.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, coach Bob Davie said earlier this week that no decision
on any bowl has been made.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can any be made until after Thanksgiving, even if the Irish
beat Boston College Saturday, since Notre Dame must beat BC then
Stanford next week to become bowl eligible at 7-5, which is the
minimum number of wins for a team that plays a 12-game schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: What has happened in South Bend? How did Notre
Dame become Indiana or North Carolina State all of a sudden, a
major program that flirts with .500 and is among the also-rans
sooner rather than later in a season?
</P>
<P>
   Most of it has to do with recruiting and the diffusion of talent
across the country with scholarship reductions. Going to Notre Dame
is not that big a deal anymore to the scholar-athletes the Irish
target.
</P>
<P>
   There are other choices. Almost every school and league has some
kind of television package. As an independent, the Irish have no
parachute offered by members of the major conferences, which
guarantee the coveted Bowl Championship Series slots to conference
winners.
</P>
<P>
   As an independent, Notre Dame's schedule is almost suicidal.
Michigan, Michigan State, Purdue, Southern Cal, Arizona State,
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   It all looks nice for television ratings, but for a coach, it
looks like a season of misery unless everyone stays healthy and
everyone plays up to their potential.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't happened this season for the Irish, who are missing
16 players because of injuries and have had five others leave the
team for various reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Who puts Notre Dame No. 1 on their wish list right now? The
blue-chip quarterback? Sorry. He can go to Miami or Georgia Tech or
Florida or Purdue. The big-time running back? He can go to Virginia
or Wisconsin. The wide receiver? He can go to Florida State or
Arizona State. The linemen? They can go to Nebraska or Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And if education is the sole purpose, Duke and Stanford offer a
collegiate experience and big-time football, while Ovy League
schools provide a great edcuation and decent football.
</P>
<P>
   During Lou Holtz's tenure in South Bend, the Irish won a
national championship and 100 games in 11 years, probably as good
as it gets. But Holtz also fiddled with the recruiting classes,
pushing the envelope on who could get in and who could not. The gap
between the football team and the student body widened, was closed,
and widened again as Holtz struggled with the dilemma of all
coaches who have come to the Golden Dome _ find students who are
athletes, who are good enough to win at the heighest level, and
maintain the academic integrity of the university.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of his predecessors, Holtz burned out under the harsh
scrutiny. Now Davie, finishing his third year, is being judged.
Holtz won a national championship in his third season, so did Dan
Devine and Ara Parseghian.
</P>
<P>
   That obviously won't haappen this season. People are questioning
whether Davie has the right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fair question that has yet to be answered. Like those who
came before him, including the ill-fated Gerry Faust, Davie
deserves the full five-year run that Notre Dame gives all its
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule will not get easier next year, when Nebraska is
added to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that few Irish eyes are smiling these days when
Notre Dame football is discussed, if it is discussed at all.
</P>
<P>
   The mood in South Bend this week has been devoid of anger or
resentment over a team that is now 5-5, with a loss to Pittsburgh,
a loss to Tennessee, and a near-loss to Navy as its last three
results.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is anything that can kill a relationship or a
program, it is indifference, which means the flame of passion has
been extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, that seems to be what has happened at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Rhode Island looking for a new football coach, Rams
officals could do worse than looking to Curry College where Steve
Nelson has done a nice job of reviving that Division 3 program.
Nellie would be a natural fit for URI, someone with name
recognition that could get the Rams jump started, as well as a
proven ability as leader and a coach who can turn a program around
. . . The firing of LSU coach Gerry DiNardo last week was not a
surprise, but give athletic director Joe Dean credit for honesty,
if nothing else. ``Basically, he didn't win enough football
games,'' said Dean, referring to last year's 4-7 mark and this
year's 2-8 record. Dean wants to have a replacement by the first
week of December. Reportedly, the Tigers are looking at Texas A&AMP;M
coach R.C. Slocum, who was under consideration five years ago when
DiNardo was hired. Slocum, who has strong Louisiana ties _ he went
to McNeese State _ did nothing to diffuse the rumors this week. ``I
have a lot of respect for that school,'' he said, ``but that has
nothing to do with getting our team ready to play Texas.'' Slocum
is in the first year of a new seven-year deal and it will require a
payment of $1.8 million . . . The NCAA slapped Division 3 St.
John's with a three-year probation last week. The crime? The school
practiced in pads a few days earlier than rules permitted. Hmm.
What does that mean for Minnesota, which had a major case of
academic fraud? . . . Watch out for UMass. The Minutemen seem
poised for another national chanmpionship run. All they have to do
to clinch a 1-AA playoff berth is beat UConn, something they didn't
do in two tries last season . . . If the Minutemen do get the berth
and win at least a couple of playoff games, consider coach Mark
Whipple on the endangered species list for a move to Division 1-A .
. . Everyone thinks Florida-Florida State is a big deal, which it
is. But in Idaho, nothing is bigger than Saturday's Idaho-Boise
State battle, which will decide the Big West title and give the
winner a berth in the Humanitarian Bowl. In Conference USA,
Southern Miss. and Louisville will battle for a Liberty Bowl berth
Saturday. Want a Coach of the Year candidate? Try Hawaii's June
Jones, who has taken the Rainbows from a winless season last year
and a 19-game losing streak to a share of the WAC title. If Fresno
loses to San Jose State Saturday the Rainbows will earn the title
outright . . . How's this for bad timing. At last week's
Rutgers-Syracuse game, Scarlet Knights radio announcer Bruce
Johnson had to leave early because of a commitment to broadcast the
No. 4 fourth-ranked Rutgers women's basketball team playing a game
in Tennessee against North Carolina State. Naturally, the football
team wins in overtime and Johnson's backup, Neal Solondz, has
soundbites of the finish on all the highlight shows. Oh yeah, the
women's basketball team lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
