<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORTHY BIO OF A SENATE LION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- &UR;  &LR; To understand the importance of the best book
written about a significant legislator in ages _ Adam Clymer's
``Edward M. Kennedy'' _ here's a short tale about what the senator
does for a living that occurred too late for inclusion in Clymer's
definitive work.
</P>
<P>
   By semiofficial account, the latest Kennedy caper began in
January and ended last week. It began with a letter to the
bipartisan Medicare Commission (naturally, he arranged for
Republican co-writers) and ended in the last of the late-night
talks on Capitol Hill over a budget package.
</P>
<P>
   In between, you don't want to know how many meetings and
briefings Kennedy arranged between leading congressional figures
and leaders of hospitals, nursing homes, and other health care
front-liners. It is, however, worth noting that he had three
face-to-face meetings with President Clinton on the issue _ one in
late September, one in late October, and the last just three weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   At stake was literally the health of the basic elements of the
health-care infrastructure, severely put at risk by the unexpected
impact on providers of cutbacks made two years ago in order to
produce the balanced budget deal. That impact was doubly severe in
states with disproportionately large health-care institutions that
serve national needs, not merely local ones _ as in Massachusetts,
which first elected Kennedy 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the senator started 10 months ago with just a few natural
allies, he had neither the ear of Congress's big shots nor the
initial sympathy of the Clinton administration. But by the time he
was finished, it was as if the two official ends of Pennsylvania
Avenue were competing to meet his exquisitely documented concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative package _ to improve the dangerously weakened
financial position of major teaching hospitals, nursing homes, home
health-care providers, and major pediatric facilities _ was worth
about $20 billion over 10 years when introduced in October by
Kennedy and Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota. When the
last negotiating session concluded a week ago, the experts were
still figuring out details, but the figure I got was a cool $27
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in the health-care infrastructure remains, but its
truly threatening severity has been significantly ameliorated. And
Kennedy will be back in the trenches next year.
</P>
<P>
   In his just-published book, Adam Clymer tells dozens of these
kinds of stories, many with warts attached, but most the kinds of
insight-loaded yarns that cause you to shake your head in
near-wonder. No one has ever bothered to do the hard work to piece
together a serious examination of the Kennedy's career and life _
yet he makes any short list of the most important legislative
figures in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Clymer, a New York Times reporter, is one of those relentless
journalists who understands that the hard way, the inductive way,
is the best way. He loves the game with a passion but is one of the
few who can operate effortlessly in that critical area where
politics and policy mysteriously meet.
</P>
<P>
   In a silly age of buzz, hype, gossip, and garbage, Clymer's book
supplies an uplifting end to a somewhat shabby decade of American
biography. The triumphs, tragedies, successes, flops, and misdeeds
are all there in profound perspective. Clymer breaks enough new
ground to build a small city on. But one story, involving health
care, illustrates both Kennedy's most recent success and the roots
of his involvement.
</P>
<P>
   It involves Columbia Point, the failed public housing project in
Boston's Dorchester neighborhood that back in 1966 produced at
least one huge success _ a health clinic. Simply by existing, the
clinic meant that mothers with kids had ready access to basic
services, instead of spending hours on buses and the subway getting
to facilities downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was there in August and in December, back when Medicare
and Medicaid were in their infancy. But he also had gotten a $51
million appropriation through Congress to help establish another 30
such neighborhood centers around the country. As Clymer tells it,
Kennedy carefully nurtured the effort until by 1995 there were some
850 clinics in urban and rural areas serving 9 million people.
</P>
<P>
   And for good measure, when Reagan tried to end it all, Kennedy
took him on (with carefully recruited Republican support as usual)
and clobbered him.
</P>
<P>
   Health care is a good for-instance, because the failure to
obtain national insurance is an enduring Kennedy frustration (his
first bill was introduced nearly 30 years ago). But he never gives
in, and he toils with the same grass roots mania he first displayed
organizing the West for his brother in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing only accomplishment and not longevity, and spanning
an incredible range of huge domestic and foreign policy concerns,
his full career is without parallel. In actual, measurable impact
on the lives of tens of millions of working familes, the elderly,
and the needy, Kennedy belongs in the same sentence with Franklin
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
