<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS BUSH, GORE LEAD RIVALS IN CALIFORNIA PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush have comfortable leads over their party rivals with four
months to go before the primary in voter-rich California, according
to a new survey.
</P>
<P>
   Gore attracted more than double the support won by former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, his main Democratic rival. And nearly
twice as many voters said they would pick Bush over his chief
Republican opponent, Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, commissioned by the San Francisco Examiner and
KTVU-TV, also found that Bush may be vulnerable to Gore and Bradley
in head-to-head matchups. The survey showed Gore leading Bush by 2
percentage points. It also showed Bradley leading Bush by a single
point when paired in a hypothetical November election.
</P>
<P>
   This statistical dead heat comes despite Bradley's fourth-place
showing when all the candidates are lumped together in the survey,
as they will be in California's March 7 open primary. The open
primary allows Democrats and Republicans to cross party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that if Bush emerges as the Republican nominee, he
will have to overcome several factors to win the state's 54
electoral votes in November 2000. Those factors include his
conservative record as governor of Texas, a lingering anger with
the Republican Party among the state's growing numbers of Hispanic
voters and the lack of a powerful force motivating change.
</P>
<P>
   If California voters continue down the same political path they
took in the state in recent election, Democrats may have the edge
in 2000. President Clinton won here over former President George
Bush in 1992 and again against former Sen. Bob Dole in 1996. Last
year, Democrats swept statewide elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a very tough state for Bush to win,'' said
Del Ali, of Research 2000 of Rockville, Md., which conducted the
poll of 802 registered California voters. The survey was done Nov.
16-18 and has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed Bradley and Gore getting more support
than Bush among women. Bush, who opposes abortion, is viewed as a
moderate, in part because of his message of ``compassionate
conservatism.'' He also appears to have picked up a significant
number of women voters since former Red Cross President Elizabeth
Dole dropped out of the GOP presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``I don't think women voters have been in play for
them, and I think that's a big problem,'' Ali said of the Bush
campaign. ``I think the soccer moms, the women voters are starting
to take a look, and if Bush stays moderate, he can fulfill the
challenge. But if he moves rightward, I think it's a matter of time
before the gender gap comes into play like it did in the last
election.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey is a brief snapshot of the campaign. The political
scene could change dramatically over the next few months as
candidates begin advertising and campaign in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner/KTVU random telephone survey was conducted of
people who said they vote regularly. The party affiliation mirrored
registration figures in California: 46 percent of those polled were
Democrats, 36 percent were Republican, and 18 percent either
belonged to third parties or declined to state which party they
support.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other findings of the survey:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gore was viewed the most favorably, but he also has the
highest unfavorable rating among the major candidates, 42 percent.
Bush's unfavorable rating was lower, 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pat Buchanan, who left the GOP to seek the Reform Party's
nomination for the presidency, was disliked more than any other
candidate _ by 58 percent of those surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buchanan would take away votes from Bush in a three-way race.
The survey showed Gore with 47 percent support and Bush dropping to
42 percent support when Buchanan is entered into the race. Buchanan
picked up only 5 percent of those surveyed, but he took all his
votes from Bush. The same scenario occurs in a
Bradley-Bush-Buchanan race.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush and Gore split the Asian vote, but Gore leads
overwhelmingly among African-American and Hispanics. White voters
tend to favor Bush by a slight margin of 5 percentage points. Bush,
however, had a surprisingly high 37 percent of the Hispanic vote
compared to Gore's 57 percent. That shows Bush appears to have
dissolved some of the animosity the Republican Party in California
collected with its support of the anti-immigration measure
Proposition 187.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanics are still with Democrats,'' Ali said. ``I'm not
surprised. There was big talk with Bush doing so well with
Hispanics in Texas. That's the governor's race. That's Texas. Now
we're talking about an ethnic group still upset. This is a
tremendous gap among voters. The glass may be half-empty more than
half-full for Bush on this issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
