<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CRIMES-PONZI-ART-BOS &LR;      11-22 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIMES-PONZI-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1920 SWINDLER LEFT VICTIMS, IMITATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A file photo is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and f codig)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Charles Ponzi did something few other criminals _ not
Al Capone or Jesse James _ could manage: He got his name attached
to his crime.
</P>
<P>
   Ponzi, who fleeced Bostonians out of millions in 1920, did not
invent what has come to be known as a Ponzi scheme, a scam in which
early investors are paid with money from new investors. The con had
been around for years, maybe centuries. But Ponzi did it on such a
grand scale, with such flair and in such full view of the world and
the media, that he earned his place in criminal history. ``He was a
celebrity and that only enticed more people into his scheme,'' says
William Galvin, Massachusetts secretary of state, who spends part
of his time trying to protect investors from modern-day Ponzi
imitators.
</P>
<P>
   Ponzi may have already been a crook when he left Italy in 1903
at age 20 for America. He participated in scams everywhere from
Providence to Montreal, where he wound up in prison for his
efforts. But Ponzi's ambition was as big as his adopted country. He
knew he was destined to be rich. He just needed the right idea.
</P>
<P>
   For Ponzi, the right idea turned out to be stamps, actually a
type of foreign stamps called International Reply Coupons. Through
some quirk in the laws, the coupons could be purchased overseas for
a penny or two and redeemed in the United States for 6 cents. In
theory, you could buy enough of the stamps to make huge profits. In
practice, Ponzi only needed the stamps for a cover story.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was enough truth in the story to bring in the
gullible,'' says Galvin.
</P>
<P>
   Ponzi set up an office at 27 School St. and created a firm
called the Securities and Exchange Company, a name meant to instill
confidence in potential investors. Then he made his offer:
Investors who bought into the company would get a 50 percent return
on their money in 45 days; a 100 percent return in 90 days. Banks
at the time paid 5 percent interest annually.
</P>
<P>
   Sales were slow at first, but Ponzi had the gift of gab and the
ability to tell people what they wanted to hear. If they were
skeptical, and some were, he could recount in great detail the
story of the stamps and assuage their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   As time went on, Ponzi didn't need to do much selling: his
investors became his best sellers. They told friends, relatives,
and co-workers about the investment. If people actually wanted to
get their money back after 45 days, Ponzi was happy to oblige. He
had plenty on hand. In fact, most people chose to reinvest for
another 45 days, hoping for an even bigger score.
</P>
<P>
   Ponzi started selling in December of 1919. By the spring he was
rich. He bought fancy suits and took to carrying a cane and a
gold-tipped cigarette holder. He bought an expensive car and hired
a chauffeur. He brought his mother over from Italy and purchased a
huge house in suburban Lexington for his wife, Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there was more money than he could spend. In May 1920,
he took in $442,000, according to biographer Donald Dunn, author of
``Ponzi: The Boston Swindler.'' By the summer he was taking in
$250,000 a day. He stuffed the money into closets and desk drawers.
Who said the streets of America weren't paved with gold? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity was a mixed blessing &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ponzi's wealth brought fame and attention from the newspapers,
which wanted to know more about the man with the Midas touch. The
celebrity was a mixed blessing: It attracted new investors but it
also brought scrutiny from law enforcement and hard-nosed
reporters. The Boston Post, smelling a rat, began publishing
skeptical stories about Ponzi, questioning how he could afford to
pay out such outlandish sums.
</P>
<P>
   A Post reporter interviewed Clarence Barron, the founder of the
financial publication, Barron's, who all but declared the Ponzi
plan a fraud. Barron checked with the Boston post office and found
out that hardly any of the International Reply Coupons were
actually being redeemed. ``Why don't the postal operations reflect
Ponzi's, if he truly is dealing in millions of coupons?'' Barron
asked.
</P>
<P>
   But the press wasn't Ponzi's only problem. As he knew better
than anyone, Ponzi schemes start well but end badly. You can rob
Peter to pay Paul, but eventually you run out of Pauls and the
whole thing collapses.
</P>
<P>
   Ponzi needed an exit strategy. At one point, in a very 1990s bit
of thinking, he considered taking his company public and using the
proceeds from the stock sale to pay off his debts. He also
contemplated taking over some local banks and using their money to
pay his creditors.
</P>
<P>
   He never got the chance. The Post, which won a Pulitzer Prize
for its Ponzi coverage, kept after him. Eventually the paper dug up
a prison photograph of Ponzi from Montreal. To add insult to
injury, Ponzi's public relations man deserted him and wrote an
article for the Post that said Ponzi was broke.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal with the state, Ponzi began giving back money to
investors. He gave back more than $3 million. Naturally there
wasn't enough to meet his obligations. When an auditor for the
state tallied up the figures he found that Ponzi had $3 million in
assets and $7 million in liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means you are $4 million short,'' the auditor told Ponzi,
who reportedly replied, ``Gee. Then I guess I am not solvent.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview just before he surrendered to police, Ponzi was
asked if he wanted to make a statement. The public deserves it,
don't you think? the reporter said. ``The public deserves exactly
what it gets, no more, no less,'' said Ponzi. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Suckers in all shapes and sizes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Spooner agrees. The well-known Boston stockbroker and
author says as long as there are people looking to get rich quick,
Ponzi schemes will thrive. ``P. T. Barnum was right,'' says
Spooner. ``There is a sucker born every minute.''
</P>
<P>
   The suckers come in all shapes and sizes and from every social
class. In the 1970s a group of famous entertainers including Liza
Minelli, Andy Williams and Jack Benny lost millions when they
invested in a tax shelter plan that purported to invest in oil. It
turned out there were no oil wells.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s the Foundation for New Era Philanthropy got a
number of financial heavyweights, including John Whitehead, the
chairman of Goldman Sachs and former US Treasury Secretary William
Simon, to contribute $100 million to a charity that promised it
would double donors' donations in six months. The money wound up in
the pocket of the foundation's creator, John Bennett Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Gullibility isn't strictly an American vice. In the mid-1990s
practically everyone in Albania poured money into a series of
Ponzi-style investment plans. By one estimate, $1 billion or 25
percent of the poor nation's gross national product was funneled
into the plans that promised high rates of interest and used new
money to pay off early investors. When angry Albanians found out
they had been duped, they rioted in the streets and threatened to
bring down the government.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Nestor, one of Galvin's deputies, says there are some
common themes to all Ponzi schemes. They all sound too good to be
true, and they all guarantee high rates of return. In the real
world, says Nestor, there are no guarantees and high rewards only
come with high risk. ``We can regulate until we are blue in the
face,'' says Nestor, ``but if people are not careful they can be
ripped off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponzi schemes have precious few winners. The list of losers
often includes the creator. ``Unless you have Whitey Bulger's
travel agent there is no way to get away with one,'' Galvin says.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ponzi didn't get away. He spent more than a decade in
jail. While he was in prison his mother died. When he got out his
wife divorced him and the government deported him to Italy. He died
in the charity ward of a Brazilian hospital in 1949. The last
picture of Ponzi, taken in the hospital, showed him with a big
smile on his face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1639EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8023 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     11-22 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Nov. 23. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Henry Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BULGARIA-CLINTON (Sofia, Bulgaria) _ President Clinton offered a
rousing pep talk to the people of Bulgaria Monday night at an
outdoor rally in the same downtown square where democracy advocates
helped overthrow a brutal Communist dictatorship almost exactly 10
years ago. Never before has an American president come to this
ancient land, and the crowd of 10,000 flag-waving people roared
with approval in a celebration that showed just how much has
changed since the Berlin Wall came down in 1989. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-CORRUPTION (Kano, Nigeria) _ After Friday Prayers,
townsfolk say, Maryam Abacha, the widow of the dictator who ruled
and looted this country for five years, has begun opening the gates
of the family compound to the city's poor, who fill her courtyard
to receive free bags of rice, millet and sorghum. The practice is
regarded here as a crude attempt to burnish the image of the
Abachas, who have become the poster-family of an unexpected and
ambitious drive by the county's new president, Olusegun Obasanjo,
to root out corruption. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RSI-INJURIES (Washington) _ Labor unions said Monday that they
would train their members to recognize and report violations of new
workplace rules intended to prevent injuries resulting from
repetitive motion, heavy lifting, bending twisting, pushing and
pulling. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-NH (Manchester, N.H.) _ Bill Bradley gives a speech on
campaign finance reform. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GOVERNORS (Carlsbad, Calif.) _ More than one Republican
governor looked at making a presidential race this year, and there
is a lingering touch of envy over the one who did. But one thought
was implicit in conversations the Republican governors had
stretching back to last year: The time had come to nominate one of
their own for president. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ABUSE-WOMEN (Boston) _ Defenders of battered women long
struggled to persuade authorities to crack down on brutal men who
reigned by the fist at home, and in recent years have largely won.
But as laws and police have gotten more aggressive, they have
produced a startling side effect: In spots around the country, as
much as one quarter or more of arrests for domestic assault are not
of men but women. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-SCHOOL-PRIMER (Undated) _ In a move likely to incite
renewed debate over how secondary schools should handle the topic
of homosexuality, a coalition of medical, mental health,
educational and religious organizations announced Monday that it
would send superintendents of each of the nation's 14,700 school
districts as primer on the issue, saying that there is nothing
abnormal or unhealthy about being gay. By Erica Goode.
</P>
