<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8025 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DIGESTION-GLOSSARY23-     11-22 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGESTION-GLOSSARY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Common digestive disorders: A glossary
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Common digestive woes usually are short-term problems, such as
indigestion, constipation and diarrhea. Chronic symptoms can be a
sign of a more serious disorder. Here are some of the more common
ways your digestive system can leave you singing the tummy blues.
</P>
<P>
   Celiac disease: Also called sprue, it's caused by the protein
gluten, which is found in wheat, rye, barley, and sometimes oats.
People with it cannot properly absorb food because the lining of
the small intestine is damaged. Often occurs in the first year of
life but can occur at any age. Gas, weight loss, weakness and
fatigue are symptoms in adults.
</P>
<P>
   Constipation: Eat more fiber, drink more water and eat less
highly refined and processed food, such as cheese, doughnuts, and
vending machine food if you want to avoid bouts of constipation.
Wholegrain bread, cereals, fruit, leafy vegetables, beans and
water, water, water will get bowels moving. Too little exercise and
long periods of immobility also affects bowel habits. It can also
be a sign of of a metabolic disorder or trouble with your large
intestine.
</P>
<P>
   Diarrhea: Can be a symptom of many disorders, including food
poisoning. Can also be caused by a viral infection, called
gastroenteritis, spread from another person commonly to babies and
young children. Persistent diarrhea and/or bloody stools are signs
of a more serious disorder needing medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Food intolerance: Developing a stomachache each time you eat a
certain kind of food may indicate an intolerance to it. Often it's
an enzyme deficiency, so your body can't properly digest the food.
Lactose intolerance is an example. Inability to digest lactose, the
natural sugar found in milk and dairy products, is a common dietary
problem worldwide and is linked to certain ethnic groups, such as
African-Americans, Native Americans, Asians and Jewish people.
People with lactose intolerance experience stomach bloating,
cramping and diarrhea within a few hours after drinking or eating
milk or dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   Food poisoning: Eating food or water that's been contaminated
from various kinds of bacteria is the most common cause of sudden
onset of diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   It can start within hours or days after consumption of the bad
food. There are 250 different kinds of foodborne illnesses that
sicken some 76 million Americans annually, killing 5,000 and and
hospitalizing 325,000 others. People suffering from it often
mistakenly call it stomach flu, but there is no such thing.
Bacterial infections can develop if you eat turkey or other foods
left out on the counter overnight or contaminated vegetables, fruit
or meat. Get to a doctor if diarrhea doesn't stop in 48-72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Gastritis: Inflammation of the stomach lining that is usually
chronic. Causes include long-term use of aspirin and
anti-inflammatory drugs such as ibuprofen, excessive alcohol intake
or infection by H. pylori bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Gastroenteritis: Inflammation of the lining of the stomach and
intestines that's usually due to a bacterial or viral infection.
Symptoms can include diarrhea, vomiting, cramps and fever. It
commonly occurs within families or others in close contact, such as
schoolchildren. If symptoms are severe or prolonged, consult a
doctor. Most people recover rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Gastroesophageal reflux: Also called GER or acid reflux. Most
common cause of indigestion attacks and a burning pain called
heartburn. It's caused by acidic juices from the stomach flowing
back up into the esophagus, which cannot protect itself from the
acid. Acid reflux attacks are usually brief and mild. But if
chronic and persistent, acid reflux can lead to permanent damage
and possible digestive tract bleeding. Pregnancy and obesity are
some GER triggers. Symptoms include heartburn, or burning pain in
the chest behind the breastbone, acidic taste in mouth, persistent
cough, and belching. If the chest pain does not occur after eating,
and spreads up and down an arm, you could be suffering angina or a
heart attack. Seek medical help immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Helicobacter pylori infection: Caused by presence of H. pylori
bacteria, which is found in stomach lining of about half of world's
population. Discovered last decade and replaced the long-time
diagnosis of stomach ulcers being caused by foods and stress. The
bacteria damages the mucus layer that protects the stomach lining
from acidic digestive juices and leads to damage. Causes gastritis,
peptic ulcer and possibly increasing risk of developing stomach
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Hernia: Usually occurs in men when heavy lifting or other
triggers cause a part of the intestine to push through a weakened
stomach muscle. Visible bulge develops that can disappear when
lying flat. Can become twisted, causing severe pain and requiring
immediate surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Indigestion: What you get when you overindulge, either eating
too much of everything, wolfing down your meal over the kitchen
counter or car dashboard, or from too much alcohol, coffee, rich,
fatty or heavily spiced food. Stress, certain drugs and aspirin can
also cause indigestion. Symptoms are pain or discomfort in upper
abdomen and your stomach feeling ``sour.''
</P>
<P>
   Irritable bowl syndrome: Intermittent abdominal pain with
constipation and/or diarrhea. Commonly develops in 20-30 year-old
age group; twice as common among women. Can cause abdominal
bloating, excessive gas, feeling of fullness and feeling bowel has
not completely emptied. Can be distressing but usually doesn't lead
to serious complications. Symptoms can be resolved with avoiding
large meals, spicy and fried food, reducing caffeine intake, eating
at regular times and using relaxation techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Peptic ulcer: Eroded area of the tissue lining of the stomach or
duodenum, the first part of the small intestine. Symptoms include
pain or discomfort in upper abdomen, loss of appetite and weight
loss, feeling of fullness, nausea and sometimes vomiting. Pain
usually worse when stomach is empty. Pain can disappear for weeks
or months and then reappear. Peptic ulcers are either duodenal
ulcers (usually in people in 20-45 age group) or gastric ulcers
(most common in over 50 population.) Gastric ulcers are aggravated
by food. Common complication is bleeding as the ulcer deepens and
strikes nearby blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: American College of Physicians Complete Home Medical
Guide, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention; research by
staff writer Patricia Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
