</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8026 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DIGESTION-MAIN23-COX     11-22 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGESTION-MAIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surviving T-day indegestion
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It will probably start with a cheese straw.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a nibble. Not even a mouthful. So negligible that you'll
follow it up with a ham biscuit. And a sausage ball. And some
spiced pecans, a handful of mixed nuts, a couple of marshmallows
filched from the sweet potatoes, a scrap of turkey skin, some loose
crumbs of stuffing ...
</P>
<P>
   Need we go on?
</P>
<P>
   You know how this ends. Four or five hours of unrestricted
grazing later _ more green-bean casserole? why, thank you! _ you're
horizontal and groaning, stunned with carbohydrates, dimly sensing
that first acrid tickle, that uneasy toasty feeling, that growing
apprehension that your stuffed self is boiling over just below your
chest.
</P>
<P>
   Heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   Take it as some small comfort that you'll have a lot of company:
By one estimate, almost half of adult Americans experience some
digestive trouble at least once a month. Care to guess which day in
November marks heartburn's high-water mark? Too much food, too much
fat, too much alcohol, too much caffeine _ Thanksgiving practically
qualifies as National Indigestion Day.
</P>
<P>
   Of course you already know the easy answer. ``My first advice
would be moderation in the size of the meal and the amount of
alcohol consumed,'' said Dr. J. Patrick Waring, a specialist in
digestive disorders at Emory University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   That's because a big meal sets you up for gastric distress.
First, the extra amount you eat distends your stomach. Sensing a
tough task ahead, the stomach produces extra digestive juices. Then
some of the ingredients of your dinner _ alcohol, chocolate, fatty
foods _ relax the muscles that close off the junction between
stomach and esophagus. Stomach acid splashes through that portal,
searing the delicate tissues on the other side: in medical
terminology, gastroesophageal reflux disease.
</P>
<P>
   Also known as heartburn. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Indigestion isn't only heartburn. Underlying medical conditions
can also provoke digestive trouble:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unrecognized ulcers can cause discomfort in the upper abdomen,
usually linked to eating.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lactose intolerance _ inability to digest a natural sugar in
milk _ produces gas and bloating.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gastritis, an irritation of the stomach lining from
painkillers or bacteria, can cause pain and gastric bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Food poisoning, from bacterial contamination, is distinctive:
sharp cramping, nausea, diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And the early signs of a heart attack _ sweaty discomfort,
restlessness, pain in the chest or high in the abdomen _ can mimic
indigestion as well.
</P>
<P>
   But a significant proportion of the digestive trouble afflicting
the nation on Thursday is likely to be uncomplicated heartburn. The
remedies are uncomplicated as well.
</P>
<P>
   First, don't eat too much.
</P>
<P>
   Second, ``If you have occasional trouble already, and you know
you'll be eating something that will bother you, take an
over-the-counter medication,'' Waring said. ``If you take them
before the meal, they decrease acid production and discomfort after
the meal. They really do work.''
</P>
<P>
   If you skipped a pharmaceutical first course and trouble
develops, the third line of defense is a commercial antacid.
``Maalox, Mylanta, Gaviscon, Tums, Rolaids _ they'll all help
neutralize acid in the stomach,'' Waring said.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you know you have a food allergy, don't hold up the
buffet line deciding what's less risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``People spend a lot of time figuring out which food to avoid,
but if they just avoided overeating that would probably help as
much as figuring out what to stay away from,'' Waring added.
</P>
<P>
   So put down the cheese straw and back away quietly. We don't
want things to get ugly here.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONS APLENTY
</P>
<P>
   A smorgasbord of medical options await those who overindulge on
Thanksgiving. Over-the-counter medications break down into four
categories:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Antacids
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Food enzymes
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Histamine 2 receptor antagonists
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Antiflatulents.
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Pepto-Bismol, have been around for decades and work
by diluting stomach acid. Newer ones , like the histamine 2
receptor antagonists, work by stopping the problem at the
biological source _ Pepcid AC, Tagamet and Zantac work by reducing
the production of stomach acid.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
