<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tips on coping with the glut of leftovers post-feast excess
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taste buds are fickle, easily bored little rascals. What was
anticipated and exciting one day quickly becomes tired and humdrum
to them in no time at all.
</P>
<P>
   Leftovers are, well, they're left over, and as any cook knows,
it takes a bit of effort to get those taste buds' attention in a
meal made from yesterday's feast. Once turkey and ham sandwiches
have made the rounds, recycling an intriguing meal out of leftovers
is indeed a challenge, but it's one that can be met creatively with
a little research time.
</P>
<P>
   The Larousse Gastronomique, which bills itself as the ``World's
Greatest Culinary Encyclopedia,'' says, ``the art of using up
leftovers is not to be considered as the summit of culinary
achievement.'' Still, a host of contributors to the Internet
disagree and provide terrific recipes and ideas that may even rival
the original dish.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some hints, sites and recipes we gathered from the Web
that my help you avoid hearing the dreaded, ``Turkey? Not again!''
</P>
<P>
   SOME HINTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Add an unexpected spice or ingredient that will completely
change the taste and character of the original dish. Seek out
ethnic recipes that use spices like curry, cumin and chili powder
to transform the texture and taste into something new.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Think cheese. Various cheeses used as fondue and in pizzas and
casseroles can do wonders to change the character of a leftover. A
bubbling casserole that alternates layers of leftover meats and
vegetables with Gruyere or another cheese is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Salads. Cube or julienne that turkey, ham or roast and use it
in a salad. Don't be afraid to use fruit and try a dressing you've
never used before for something new.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stir-fry. This is a good way to use a multitude of leftovers.
Don't forget to add something new and serve over pasta or rice.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Breakfast. Think omelets.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fritters and cakes. Dip broccoli or cauliflower florets into
batter and then deep-fry. Add minced onion and other ingredients to
leftover mashed potatoes and fry until golden.
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mr. Food at www.homearts.com/mrfood/articles/c8left11.htm
offers more than 50 inventive ways to redesign all the holiday
leftovers crowding your refrigerator. A pull-down menu lets you
restyle turkey, ham, roast beef, mashed potatoes, sweet potatoes,
stuffing and even goose.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hearty Navaho Chili and creamy Turkey Fettuccine are two of
the recipes for leftovers offered by the Canadian Press at
www.canoe.ca
</P>
<P>
   /CNEWSLifeArchive/981229dollar2.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shopper News at www.shoppernews.com/c040694.html offers
recipes that transform leftover turkey, ham and lamb into rivals of
the originals, such as Asparagus Ham Lasagna.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At the ``Land of Leftovers,'' www.seasoned.com/issues/199903
</P>
<P>
   /c.ll.p1.html, you'll find new twists using all kinds of
leftovers from fish to fowl and all kinds of vegetables in that
trusty old standard for leftovers, the potpie. Recipes include
Simple Fish Pie; Chicken, Leek and Parsley Pie; Farmhouse Pie; and
Corn and Bean Tamale Pie. To avoid monotony, use crusts ranging
from traditional pie pastry to bread crumbs to potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you are interested in making a turkey pizza, check the
recipe at
</P>
<P>
   www.wral-tv.com/features/remakes/1998
</P>
<P>
   /0303-turkey-pizza/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If it's back to work the day after and you're looking for
quick and simple ways to recycle turkey, see the six easy recipes
at www.canturkey.ca/lefovers.htm. The list includes Turkey
Bruschetta, where you brush slices of Italian bread with olive oil,
top with minced garlic and toast in the oven, then spoon on a
combination of turkey, shredded mozzarella cheese and chopped fresh
basil and broil just until the cheese melts.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Turkey Grape Salad, combining halved green grapes,
toasted sliced almonds, sliced green onions, orange zest and light
mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   Others include Turkey Stir Fry, Turkey and Spinach Tetrazzini
and others to make in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Butterball site doesn't leave you stranded after the feast
is over. See Butterball's Lipsmacking Leftover recipes at
www.butterball
</P>
<P>
   .com/bbrecipes.cfm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Peggy Trowbridge, about.com's Home Cooking Guide, offers a
wide variety of leftover turkey recipes that are guaranteed to make
you forget the great feast. Her offerings include Sweet Potato and
Turkey Croquettes; Thanksgiving Turkey-Pomegranate Salad; Chinese
Turkey and Vegetable Casserole; Curried Turkey Salad in Brioche;
and Turkey, Ham, and Vegetable Hash With Fried Eggs. You can go to
about.com and search Peggy Trowbridge and leftovers or go direct to 
homecooking.about.com/home/food/homecooking/library/weekly/bl111797a
.htm?terms &QC; leftovers&AMP;PM &QC; 113300T.
</P>
<P>
   STORING LEFTOVERS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Important information that will keep you from developing an
unwanted science project in your fridge can be found at
www.healthyideas.com/cooking/chef/980723.chef.html
</P>
<P>
   and foodsci.rutgers.edu/schaffner/factsheets/fs588.htm
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Apricot-Turkey Couscous
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 8-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Sunny yellow couscous brightens the prospect for creative turkey
leftovers. It is comforting, quick-cooking and delicious when
combined with turkey, tangy apricots and crunchy almonds. Serve as
a main-course luncheon salad or light day-after-Thanksgiving dinner
salad.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, cored, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely chopped cooked turkey
</P>
<P>
   1 cup slivered dried apricots
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup lightly toasted slivered almonds (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch trimmed and thinly sliced fresh green onions
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken or turkey broth
</P>
<P>
   2 cups plain couscous
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a medium skillet over mediumhigh heat. Add pepper
and saute until softened, about 5 minutes. Stir in turkey,
apricots, almonds and green onions and keep mixture warm over low
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Bring chicken broth to a boil in a medium saucepan. Slowly stir
in couscous. Remove pan from heat, cover and let stand for 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Uncover and stir in turkey mixture until evenly distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Season with salt and pepper. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To toast almonds, place in shallow baking pan and roast
uncovered in 300-degree oven about 20 minutes, stirring often,
until lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 420 calories, 19 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 23), 61 grams carbohydrates, 23
milligrams cholesterol, 209 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
