<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rest assured there's still time to shine
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The time-crunched Pilgrims among us still have time to prepare a
nice Thanksgiving meal. Just take a tour of the grocery freezer
case, the deli or the local bakery for a few shortcuts.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to cook but won't have much time, we offer
the No-Stress Thanksgiving Menu _ simple recipes you prepare but
that take advantage of the best convenience products.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't want to cook (but you forgot to make a
restaurant reservation) look at our suggestions for a Heat-and-Eat
Thanksgiving. We sampled a few prepared products that together
would make a simple, satisfying traditional meal. Or you may want
to pluck a couple of the products to round out your menu or take
care of any last-minute cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   NO-STRESS THANKSGIVING
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Turkey Breast With Apricot Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Sausage and Wild Rice Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Marshmallow-topped Roasted Sweet Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Red-skin Mashed Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Herbed Creamed Spinach
</P>
<P>
   Maple Glazed Onions
</P>
<P>
   Quick Cranberry Salad
</P>
<P>
   Carrot and Orange Salad
</P>
<P>
   Smith House Quick Rolls
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry Mincemeat Pie
</P>
<P>
   Streusel Pumpkin Pie
</P>
<P>
   COUNTDOWN
</P>
<P>
   While others may have slaved for weeks, you'll be able to put a
nice meal on the table in a matter of hours. And the beauty of it _
the only chopping here is quartering potatoes. Here's a general
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   (Monday)Today: Order turkey or any other deli items, such as
dressing or pie.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday/Wednesday: Pick up groceries and pre-ordered items.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night: Marinate turkey breast. If desired, make the
cranberry salad and the carrot and orange salad and keep
refrigerated. You could also bake the pies this evening or bake
them while the meal is being served on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: The best way to break down the cooking duties is by
source of heat.
</P>
<P>
   In the oven: the turkey breast, the sweet potatoes, the rolls
and the pie. Total oven time is 5 to 5 1/2 hours (which can be cut
by 1 to 1 1/2 hours by cooking the pies the night before). Start
with the turkey. You can probably get by with putting the sweet
potatoes in at the same time, but that will increase cooking time
for both dishes. Once they are done, the rolls go in. Then bake (or
reheat pies if desired) while dinner is being served, but remember
to set a timer.
</P>
<P>
   On the stovetop: the sausage and wild rice dressing, the
red-skin mashed potatoes and the maple glazed pearl onions. I'd
start with cooking the sausage and rice (some rice boxes give
microwave directions), and then combining to make the dressing.
Then make the pearl onions. Do the mashed potatoes last.
</P>
<P>
   In the microwave: the spinach for the creamed herbed spinach.
Once cooked, simply blend with the cheeses. Good for reheating
dishes made early, such as the wild rice dressing.
</P>
<P>
   No cook: the cranberry salad and the carrot and orange salad.
You can simplify things by making these the night before, but there
should be plenty of time to throw them together on Thursday as
well.
</P>
<P>
   INGREDIENT CHECK LIST MEAT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whole boneless
</P>
<P>
   turkey breast, skin on _ 3 pounds
</P>
<P>
