<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Boneless Turkey Breast With Apricot Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Marinating time: 2 hours to overnight
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Even boneless turkey breast takes time to thaw, so be sure to
buy yours a day and a half in advance. We think you'll find this so
simple and delicious it will visit your table again before next
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   1 whole boneless turkey breast, with skin on (about 3 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   Ground ginger; fresh minced garlic, or granulated garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup apricot preserves
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup light soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   The night before (or at least 2 hours before roasting): Season
both sides of the turkey breast well with ground ginger and garlic.
Put in a roasting pan. Combine the apricot preserves, mustard and
soy sauce. Blend well; cover breast, top and bottom of turkey with
the sauce. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate until ready to
roast.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Remove turkey from refrigerator and
add 1/4 cup water to the roasting pan. Bake uncovered for 2 1/2
hours (or until a meat thermometer registers 170 degrees), basting
occasionally with gravy in pan. Allow to stand for at least 10
minutes before slicing. _ Adapted from: ``Grandma Doralee
Patinkin's Jewish Family Cookbook'' (St. Martin's Griffin, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 324 calories, 33 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 32), 21 grams carbohydrates, 93
milligrams cholesterol, 662 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Sausage and
</P>
<P>
   Wild Rice Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   If you find yourself without time to crumble and chop a
traditional Southern corn bread dressing, try this alternative. The
sausage makes this a spicy, savory sidekick for a bird.
</P>
<P>
   2 (6-ounce) packages wild rice mix
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces bulk sausage (spicy or mild)
</P>
<P>
   1 (5- to 6-ounce) can sliced water chestnuts, slivered
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried sour cherries or cranberries
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the rice according to package directions, adding 1
tablespoon butter during the cooking. Meanwhile, fry the sausage in
a skillet until cooked through; drain. To the cooked rice, add the
sausage, water chestnuts and cherries or cranberries. Transfer to
an oven-to-table casserole. This can be prepared in advance and
reheated in the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 261 calories, 10 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 26), 40 grams carbohydrates, 19
milligrams cholesterol, 544 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Marshmallow-
</P>
<P>
   Topped
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Tandy LeBlang, author of the nationally syndicated column
Express Lane Cooking, makes this with fresh sweet potatoes. To
simplify the process we tried it with canned (we used Glory Foods
brand) and thought it was delicious. Undoubtedly, fresh would be
even better if you have the time. Here's how to do it: Peel and
slice 3 pounds sweet potatoes in 1/2-inch rounds; arrange in a
single layer in a roasting pan sprayed with nonstick spray, cover
with apple juice mixture; cover with foil and bake 30 minutes.
Remove foil, turn the potatoes and continue to bake 15-20 minutes
or until potatoes are tender. Transfer mixture to an ovenproof
casserole dish. Add marshmallows and bake 15-20 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   3 (15-ounce) cans sweet potatoes, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) can apple juice concentrate, defrosted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 (10-ounce) bag marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Cut sweet potato chunks in 2-inch
slices; arrange in a shallow ovenproof casserole dish sprayed with
vegetable spray. Stir the ginger into the apple juice concentrate,
then pour over the slices. Cover with foil and bake about 15
minutes. Remove the cover, turn the potatoes and continue to cook
about 15 minutes. (Don't worry if it isn't very attractive; the
marshmallows will hide it.) Top with marshmallows and bake 15-20
minutes longer, until marshmallows are nicely browned.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 260 calories, 3 grams protein, trace fat, 62 grams
carbohydrates, trace cholesterol, 77 milligrams sodium, 4 grams
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Red-skin
</P>
<P>
   Mashed Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   There really is no good substitute for homemade mashed potatoes.
But to save time, go the rustic route. Simply scrub small red
potatoes, quarter, boil and mash, leaving the skins on.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 to 3 pounds small red-skin potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Scrub potatoes thoroughly and quarter them. Put them in a
3-quart saucepan and cover with water. Place pan over medium-high
heat and boil potatoes until fork-tender, about 20 minutes. Drain
and return to pot. Pour in buttermilk and add the butter. Beat on
low speed with a hand-held mixer (or use a potato masher) until
desired consistency. Add salt and pepper to taste and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 213 calories, 5 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 19), 40 grams carbohydrates, 12 milligrams
cholesterol, 92 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Herbed Creamed Spinach
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 3-8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to get any easier than this. The herbed soft cheese
delivers just the right touch. Even the most finicky will find this
spinach delicious. After the holidays, make this a weeknight
standard.
</P>
<P>
   2 boxes (10 ounces each) frozen spinach, or 2 bags (10 ounces
each) cleaned fresh spinach
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soft garlic and herb cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to cook spinach, either frozen or fresh, is in a
microwave. If frozen, place the box right in the microwave and cook
on high power for 5 minutes. If fresh, poke 2 holes in a bag of
spinach and microwave on high power for 4 minutes. (If you don't
have a microwave, cook fresh or frozen spinach in a large saucepan
with about 1/2 inch water until soft. This will take about 8
minutes for frozen and 3 to 4 minutes for fresh.) When the spinach
is cooked, drain in a strainer, pushing out as much water as
possible. Toss the hot spinach with the cream cheese and grated
Parmesan. Season to taste with salt and pepper. _ From: ``Cooking
With Three Ingredients'' by Andrew Schloss (HarperCollins, $17)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 138 calories, 7 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 72), 6 grams carbohydrates, 33
milligrams cholesterol, 221 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Maple-Glazed Onions
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe also comes from LeBlang. No one will ever know you
didn't peel each one of those tiny onions by hand.
</P>
<P>
   2 (16-ounce) bags of frozen pearl onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken broth or water
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine onions, broth, syrup, bay leaf, salt and pepper in a
saucepan. Bring to a boil, reduce heat, cover and cook gently 10
minutes. Remove cover and continue to cook over low heat until
liquid evaporates and onions are glazed, about 10 minutes. Remove
bay leaf and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 58 calories, 1 gram protein, no fat, 14 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 15 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Quick Cranberry
</P>
<P>
   Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   To show a little more effort than opening a can, try this tangy,
crunchy mixture.
</P>
<P>
   1 (16-ounce) can whole cranberry sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) can crushed pineapple
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   In a medium mixing bowl, combine the cranberry sauce, crushed
pineapple and chopped pecans. Chill and serve. _ From: ``The
Thanksgiving Cookbook'' by Holly Garrison (Macmillan, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 148 calories, 1 gram protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 29), 28 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 17
milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Carrot and Orange Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Once you rip open the bag of shredded carrots and open the cans
of mandarin oranges, the most labor-intensive part of this recipe
is done. If you don't want to take an extra couple of minutes to
stir up this tasty dressing, substitute bottled (honey-mustard,
poppy seed or some other flavor with a hint of sweetness).
</P>
<P>
   1 bag (10 ounces) shredded carrots
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (11 ounces each) canned mandarin orange sections, drained
(reserve juice)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey mustard (or 1 tablespoon each honey and
mustard)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons fresh minced tarragon or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine shredded carrots and orange sections.
In another bowl, whisk together 1 tablespoon of the reserved juice,
vinegar, oil, honey mustard and tarragon. (This may be prepared
early in the day and refrigerated until ready to serve.)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 176 calories, 1 gram protein, 14 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 72), 13 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 42
milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Smith House Quick Rolls
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 rolls
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In scarcely more time than it takes to heat brown 'n' serve
rolls, you can make these addictive ones from scratch. You can't
taste the mayonnaise _ it simply serves as a binder and adds the
necessary fat to make them moist and tender.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup mayonnaise (do not substitute)
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a mixing bowl with a wooden
spoon, combine flour with mayonnaise and milk, stirring until
smooth (do not overmix). Divide into 12 rolls and place in greased
muffin tins. Bake for 15 minutes. Serve warm. _ From: ``Boarding
House Reach: Famous Smith House Recipes'' (Dot Gibson Publications,
1986)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 118 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 35), 16 grams carbohydrates, 6 milligrams
cholesterol, 297 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry-Mincemeat Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Mincemeat is one of those holiday traditions that knows no
middle ground; you either love it or you hate it. Before you assume
you fall into the latter category, try this version _ in which the
tartness of cranberries balances the spicy sweetness of the
dried-fruit mixture.
</P>
<P>
   1 (27-ounce) jar of mincemeat (we used Borden's Nonesuch)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups fresh whole cranberries (if frozen, do not thaw)
</P>
<P>
   Pastry for a double-crust pie (we used Pillsbury refrigerated
pie crusts)
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk, mixed with 1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream or vanilla ice cream, optional
</P>
<P>
   Place rack in lower half of oven; preheat oven to 425 degrees.
In a large bowl, stir together the mincemeat and the cranberries.
Set aside. Line a 9-inch pie plate with one crust; add filling and
cover with top crust; cut slits near the center. Seal and flute
edges. Brush surface of pie with egg wash. Bake 30 minutes. (May be
baked early in the day and left at room temperature; or bake the
night before, cover and refrigerate; reheat in 350-degree oven just
until heated through.)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 506 calories, 5 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 27), 87 grams carbohydrates, 27
milligrams cholesterol, 453milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Streusel Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 70 minutes (or according to package directions)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the frozen pumpkin pies like Sara Lee and Mrs. Smith's
are really quite good, and they'll fill your house with a
sweet-and-spicy aroma while baking. You can make one extra special
by adding this topping.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 frozen pumpkin pie, such as Sara Lee or Mrs. Smith's
</P>
<P>
   In a medium mixing bowl, combine the brown sugar, flour,
cinammon, butter and pecans until crumbly. Top the frozen pumpkin
pie with the mixture and bake according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 381 calories, 6 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 48 grams carbohydrates, 63
milligrams cholesterol, 319 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Smith House Quick Rolls
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 rolls
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In scarcely more time than it takes to heat brown 'n' serve
rolls, you can make these addictive ones from scratch. You can't
taste the mayonnaise _ it simply serves as a binder and also adds
the necessary fat to make them moist and tender.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup mayonnaise (do not substitute)
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a mixing bowl with a wooden
spoon, combine flour with mayonnaise and milk, stirring until
smooth (do not overmix). Divide into 12 rolls and place in greased
muffin tins. Bake for 15 minutes. Serve warm. _ From: ``Boarding
House Reach: Famous Smith House Recipes'' (Dot Gibson Publications,
1986)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 118 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 35), 16 grams carbohydrates, 6 milligrams
cholesterol, 297 milligrams sodium, 1 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Maple-Glazed Onions
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe also comes from LeBlang. No one will ever know you
didn't peel each one of those tiny onions by hand.
</P>
<P>
   2 (16-ounce) bags frozen pearl onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken broth or water
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine onions, broth, syrup, bay leaf, salt and pepper in a
saucepan. Bring to a boil, reduce heat, cover and cook gently 10
minutes. Remove cover and continue to cook over low heat until
liquid evaporates and onions are glazed, about 10 minutes. Remove
bay leaf and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 58 calories, 1 grams protein, no fat, 14 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 15 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
