A8033 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ANESTHESIA23-COX     11-22 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANESTHESIA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANESTHESIOLOGISTS CALL FOR CONGRESSIONAL PROBE OF NAVY
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The American Society of Anesthesiologists Monday
called for a congressional investigation of plans to permit
unsupervised nurses to administer anesthesia at the National Naval
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The chief anesthesiologist at the Bethesda, Md., hospital was
relieved of his command two weeks ago for refusing to obey an order
that he authorize certified registered nurse anethetists (CRNAs) to
give patients the sleep-inducing and pain-blocking drugs without
physician supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The removal of Dr. Alvin Manaaysay, a Navy captain, was
announced at a staff meeting Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Bonnie Potter, commander of the hospital, confirmed
that she had issued the order that CRNAs be authorized to
administer the drugs to certain patients. However, she denied that
the substances would be given to high government officials only
under physician supervision, regardless of a patient's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other hospitals, it is a physician who determines if a
patient is fit to undergo surgery,'' said Dr. Ronald MacKenzie, an
anesthesiologist at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., and
president of the anestheologists group. ``It is unconscionable that
they would expect someone with only nursing training to make a
medical decision.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie's request for a congressional inquiry was contained in
a press release.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, aides said Rep. Dave Weldon, R-Fla., had spoken to
members of the House Armed Services Committee about investigating
the policy change at Bethesda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men and women who put their lives on the line each day to
defend our freedom have a right to the best medical care
available,'' Weldon, a former Army physician, was quoted as saying.
``If there is a change of this magnitude, it should be subject to
full congressional review.''
</P>
<P>
   Potter said in a written statement that the Navy medical system
already had a policy under which anesthesia is provided to healthy
adults and children more than 24 months old by unsupervised CRNAs.
</P>
<P>
   The change she directed at Bethesda would bring the hospital,
where presidents and members of Congress often receive medical
care, in line with Navy policy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the American Association of Nurse Anesthetists said
the specially trained nurses are fully qualified to administer the
drugs _ and do so frequently in civilian hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Beauregard, a former Bethesda anesthesiologist now in
private practice in Washington, said his former colleagues at the
hospital told him that when Potter was asked what the policy would
be with dignitaries, she replied they would continue to receive the
drugs only under physician supervision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not condone, nor have I ever directed my staff to deliver
a different level of care based on a patient's so-called VIP
status,'' Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for the Army Medical Command has confirmed that
the Army is considering changing its policy to authorize
unsupervised use of the drugs by CRNAs but added that no decision
has been made.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
