r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP22-COX     11-22 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For many, oysters vital to dressing
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cynthia Montgomery of Tucker, Ga., had some oyster
dressing at a friend's home in Tennessee years ago and wrote to us
this fall seeking a recipe for the holidays. All she could tell us
about it was that it includes bread, not corn bread.
</P>
<P>
   We got a bushel of ideas from readers, including this
traditional recipe from Dorothy Welch of Snellville, Ga. She said
it's a recipe her mother used in Ohio for Thanksgiving and
Christmas dinners, and now she continues the tradition for her
family.
</P>
<P>
   A similar recipe from Liz Bowerman adds 2 tablespoons grated
lemon peel and 1 tablespoon dry sage.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Harper sent a recipe she used to use that includes 1/2
teaspoon nutmeg and some lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very good, but I haven't made it in several years as I
found my love for oysters quite exceeded the rest of the family's
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   If enough folks who will be around your table like oysters, we
expect they'll thank you if you make this one.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Oyster Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40-45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   6 cups dry bread crumbs (10 to 12 slices)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped
</P>
<P>
   parsley
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chopped oysters
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon poultry
</P>
<P>
   seasoning
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups oyster liquor
</P>
<P>
   Milk as needed
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, melt butter over medium heat. Add celery,
onion and bay leaf. Cook, stirring frequently, until tender but not
brown, about 10 minutes. Discard bay leaf. Place vegetables in a
large mixing bowl. Add bread crumbs and parsley. Mix thoroughly.
Add oysters, seasoning and eggs. Add enough of the oyster liquor to
moisten. If it needs more moisture, add milk. Spoon into 2-quart
baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 40 to 45 minutes or until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 224 calories, 12 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 21 grams carbohydrates, 121
milligrams cholesterol, 611 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Irene Mitchell, manager
</P>
<P>
   of Blue Moon Bakery in Asheville, N.C., asks for a
</P>
<P>
   recipe for a layer cake that uses champagne.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  M. Thomas is looking for a muffin recipe made with biscuit
mix, brown sugar, honey, butter and maybe a little cinnamon in the
topping.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
