<HEADER>
A8035 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-LATE-THANKSGIVING22-C     11-22 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATE-THANKSGIVING22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Procrastinators, take heart: You can still put out a magnificent
spread this Thursday even if you haven't yet done a thing
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK. We know you are out there. You think planning is stifling
and looking a week ahead on the calendar a waste of the precious
now.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But peek ahead about three days. That's right, it's
Thanksgiving. Remember? Your parents called from Florida last week
and said they'd be at your place by noon. And they are bringing
Aunt Edna and Cousin Tim with them.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now take a deep breath. It will be OK. The frosty cranberry
mold that needs to freeze for a week is out. So is a 25-pound
frozen turkey. Not enough time to thaw.
</P>
<P>
   But order a fresh or precooked turkey today, hit the grocery
tomorrow or Wednesday and on Thursday you can serve a Thanksgiving
meal that will give the illusion of weeks of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why start a month in advance? It's not brain surgery,'' says
Bonnie Tandy Leblang, co-author of Supermarket Sampler and author
of Express Lane Cooking, two nationally syndicated columns. ``I
don't even think of starting until Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a sudden illness sidelined travel plans one
Thanksgiving, so LeBlang dashed to a grocery store that morning and
pulled off the traditional meal in only 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   She warmed thick slices of turkey bought from the deli section;
made gravy from stock she had in the freezer; created stuffing from
bread crumbs, onions and celery; poured cranberry sauce from a can;
mashed sweet potatoes and sauteed green beans. While she and her
kids were feasting, Leblang popped a Mrs. Smith's apple pie in the
oven.
</P>
<P>
   So you see, there's plenty of time to have a delectable
celebration on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial item of business for today is to locate a turkey.
Whether you are looking for a fresh turkey to roast or a precooked
bird, start with phone detective work. Call grocery stores,
restaurants or caterers to see what might still be available _ at
some places, the deadline for ordering turkey has passed.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Walker, a ``hambassador'' for the Honeybaked Ham Co., said
most stores will have pre-cooked turkey through Wednesday, but it's
better to call ahead than walk in. The same is true for many
grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Once the bird is taken care of, the rest of the meal is waiting
in the local grocery. Really. ``The trick is to take advantage of
what's good in the grocery store,'' says Leblang.
</P>
<P>
   And the other guideline, Leblang said, is ``to do exactly what
you are comfortable with and don't feel guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   For each of the traditional Thanksgiving dishes, there are easy
and easier options. For sweet potatoes, you can buy fresh,
partially cooked or canned and take it from there, whether you are
going for whipped, candied or a casserole, Leblang said.
</P>
<P>
   And while she doesn't make a practice of buying prepared dishes,
we found the Glory Foods candied sweet potatoes (in the frozen
foods section) to be quite good. Bake them, turn them into a bowl,
toss with some chopped pecans and no one will complain. Trust us.
</P>
<P>
   For some popular Thanksgiving fare, frozen foods can be
timesavers. Leblang offers a recipe for maple glazed pearl onions
(see K7) that ``is ideal'' for frozen pearl onions, which saves
peeling-and-blanching time.
</P>
<P>
   And home cooks who are intimidated by baking can easily find
alternatives. ``Mrs. Smith's isn't atrocious and neither is the
corner bakery,'' says Leblang.
</P>
<P>
   All you need to do is add a little touch of love, like topping a
commercial pumpkin pie with a streusel or putting the slices on
dessert plates and drizzling with a little caramel sauce from a
jar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just remember to appeal to all the senses,'' says Hambassador
Walker. Simmer cinnamon and cloves in water on the stovetop to fill
the house with a spicy aroma. Transfer all purchased items to your
own serving dishes and garnish with parsley, sage or whole
cranberries to ``make it visually appealing and appear to be
homemade.''
</P>
<P>
   For a last-minute centerpiece, Walker suggests artfully stacking
fruits such as apples, pears, lemons and limes on a platter and
surrounding with white votive candles.
</P>
<P>
   For touch, use cloth napkins and a nice tablecloth; for hearing,
load up the CD player with holiday tunes. And for taste ``go with
the best'' whether you make it or buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Remember to relax and enjoy every part of the process, from
setting the table to washing the dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really about sitting around the table and giving thanks
for the people in your life,'' says Leblang. ``And as a kid, my
favorite part of the meal was doing the dishes in the kitchen
afterward. That's where you hear the best gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   NO-STRESS THANKSGIVING
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Turkey Breast With Apricot Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Sausage and Wild Rice Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Marshmallow-topped
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Sweet Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Red-skin Mashed Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Herbed Creamed Spinach
</P>
<P>
   Maple Glazed Onions
</P>
<P>
   Quick Cranberry Salad
</P>
<P>
   Carrot and Orange Salad
</P>
<P>
   Smith House Quick Rolls
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry Mincemeat Pie
</P>
<P>
   Streusel Pumpkin Pie
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
