<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8045 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-22 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAD AT MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _The better Arizona Sen. John McCain does with the
voters, the worse he does with several of his Republican Senate
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   A smear campaign against him spread by GOP insiders, many of
whom support his rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, burst into the
open recently when author and political analyst Elizabeth Drew not
only described what they were up to but named names. She fingered
four senators, who promptly denied playing such dirty pool.
</P>
<P>
   This columnist cannot personally confirm who is whispering what
to whom. But it is no secret that many of McCain's fellow
Republicans cannot stand him. That is a matter of public record.
</P>
<P>
   Should it make any difference whether senators who deal with him
daily and know him best have taken a dislike to him? No, no, a
thousand times no. The public, not a small club of wheeler-dealers
on Capitol Hill, has the right to decide who is best qualified to
lead the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, the path to peer group affection is to follow the
basic rule that to get along, you must go along. All for one and
one for all, that sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is too independent to fit that mold.
</P>
<P>
   But is that characteristic a badge of honor or a sign of being
out of step?
</P>
<P>
   The gripes against McCain are many. He has a sharp tongue and an
explosive temper, not cuddly personality traits. His crusade for
campaign finance reform irritates candidates who depend on lavish
contributions for re-election, and his repeated charges that the
money makes politicians corrupt particularly galls them.
</P>
<P>
   But the really appalling aspect of the current underground
anti-McCain campaign is the implication that his temper reflects an
unstable personality, dangerously unbalanced by the years of
torture as a Vietnam prisoner of war. The strategy is deliberately
designed to turn his appealing image as a genuine military hero
into a political liability. To counter the rumors, McCain has
promised to release his medical records.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that politics is a rough sport. But this goes too
far and could easily backfire. Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., also a
Vietnam veteran, struck a sympathetic chord when he denounced the
accusations as ``insulting'' to everyhing McCain stands for in the
public mind.
</P>
<P>
   There is no public evidence that McCain is nutty, and in fact
his successful career indicates just the opposite. He is popular in
most opinion polls, if not with his colleagues, and is now
virtually running even with Bush in New Hampshire, which holds the
first 2000 primary.
</P>
<P>
   His foes will no doubt try to provoke him into getting angry
while the cameras are around. But a flash of temper need not be
politically damaging. Every recent president _ every single one _
has been grouchy from time to time, usually with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Anger, properly controlled, can be an appropriate tool of
leadership. It certainly lets everyone know when the boss feels
strongly about an issue.
</P>
<P>
   And a campaign for president requires skills different from
those most useful in the Senate. Many sitting senators have sought
the White House, but none has succeeded since John F. Kennedy did
narrowly in 1960. Kennedy's campaign was no more popular with his
peers than is McCain's.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democratic senators viewed Kennedy as a lightweight and
preferred the chamber's seasoned majority leader, Lyndon Johnson,
who was masterful at manipulating policy behind the scenes but
never won enough public support to mount a serious presidential
campaign. (As vice president in 1963, he became president on
Kennedy's death and was elected in his own right in 1964.)
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, the potential for trouble in McCain's
strained relations with other Republican senators. If he were to be
elected president, he would have to learn to get along with them if
he expected to pass much legislation. Perhaps everyone would let
bygones be bygones and get on with the nation's business. Perhaps
not.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
