<HEADLINE>
ROCKWELL ON TOUR
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-ROCKWELL-REMINISCENCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Norman Rockwell portrayed small-town life in no small part
because he lived small-town life _ and that means that those
wanting to see the majority of his work have to venture to the
Norman Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge, Mass., near the
Massachusetts-New York border.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why ``Norman Rockwell: Pictures for the American
People'' is touring America for the next several years. The largest
traveling Rockwell exhibit ever, ``Pictures'' is also the first
retrospective of all his major works to hit the road since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know everybody can't get to Stockbridge,'' says Maureen
Hart Hennessey, chief curator of the Rockwell Museum. ``We knew
everybody had their favorites, and we felt it was important to
include them in this collection.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will be at Atlanta's High Museum of Art through
Jan. 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The other stops on the tour include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicago Historical Society, Chicago, Ill., Feb. 26-May 21,
2000
</P>
<P>
   _ The Corcoran Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C., June 17-Sept.
24, 2000
</P>
<P>
   _ San Diego Museum of Art, San Diego, Calif., Oct. 28-Dec. 31,
2000
</P>
<P>
   _ Phoenix Art Museum, Phoenix, Ariz., Feb. 24-May 26, 2001
</P>
<P>
   _ The Norman Rockwell Museum at Stockbridge, Stockbridge, Mass.,
June 9-Oct. 8, 2001
</P>
<P>
   _ Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, New York, N.Y., Nov. 7,
2001-Feb. 11, 2002
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
