<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Nov. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous storm system that brought snow to parts of the
central Rockies and western Plains on Monday will move quickly
northeast toward the western Great Lakes on Tuesday. A swath of
rain will occur from northern Missouri to the central Great Lakes.
A few thunderstorms will be embedded in the rain, particularly from
the central Mississippi Valley to the southwestern Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, several inches of snow may accumulate over extreme
eastern South Dakota and western Minnesota as cold air is drawn
into the circulation of the storm. Rain will mix with snow Tuesday
afternoon from eastern Minnesota to the northwestern Great Lakes
states.
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of thundershowers will precede a cold front as it
sweeps into the Mississippi Valley. A surge of very moist air a few
thousand feet above the ground will contribute to causing isolated
strong storms, especially from eastern Texas to the southern
Mississippi Valley. In the wake of the front, dry, chilly air will
spill south through the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the interior West will be dry and cold as high pressure
drifts over Wyoming. However, clouds and a few snow showers will
linger over some of the higher elevations of the central Rockies.
Unsettled weather with variable clouds, intermittent mountain snow
and a few coastal showers will persist in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The eastern states will stay exceptionally mild. The day will
begin with areas of clouds and dense fog, which will yield to some
sun in most areas, especially away from the Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Will of The Wind
</P>
<P>
   Weather in Denver depends on the will of the wind. On Saturday,
with dry winds from the west warming on descent from the Rockies,
the temperature reached 63 degrees. But as a storm system formed in
the southern Rockies on Sunday, moist winds from the northeast were
cooled as they ascended the sloping terrain. By early Monday, over
6 inches of snow had fallen around metropolitan Denver. Later this
week, a potent storm in southwestern Canada will cause strong winds
from the west to sweep across the Rockies, sending the mercury back
into the 60s by Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
