<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Five ways to make your holiday home safe
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanksgiving's right around the corner, which means the joining
of young and old. But sometimes, family get-togethers can end in
tragedy if relatives and friends don't take basic precautions
around youngsters. Five tips for a safe, child-proof holiday:
</P>
<P>
   1. Keep all hard candies and nuts off of coffee tables or end
tables. Choking is one of the greatest hazards of the holidays for
the little ones.
</P>
<P>
   2. Make a place in high cabinets for any medications for
visitors . Remind them to not keep medications in suitcases on the
floor or next to the bed where children can find them.
</P>
<P>
   3. Lock up all silver cleaners and household products.
</P>
<P>
   4. Post the numbers of local poison center or children's
hospital helpline. (In Atlanta, call 404-616-9000 or
1-800-282-5846)
</P>
<P>
   5. Don't let children eat raw batter because of the possibility
of salmonella in eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Children's Healthcare of Atlanta,
www.yourkidshealth.com; compiled by staff writer Diane Lore
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
