<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's `best of' time in Atlanta magazine
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again, Atlanta ($3.50) has anointed the city's best _ from
Atlanta firefighter Matt Moseley for best show of bravery to Krispy
Kreme doughnuts for best guilty pleasure. Otherwise, if you want to
find the best new place to dance (Deux Plex), the best
five-and-dime (Richards Variety Store) or the best place to seduce
a man (the Supper Club), they're all here. All 299 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Also in this issue, the magazine celebrates 25 events that
shaped the city's soul. Among those: Father Thomas O'Reilly
persuading Gen. William T. Sherman not to burn the Catholic church;
a nervous 17-year-old Martin Luther King Jr. delivering a trial
sermon; the introduction of Coca-Cola; Ivan Allen's efforts to
desegregate the City Hall cafeteria; the debut of CNN; and the 1996
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Millennium mildness: If Time's ($3.50) prediction proves true,
this millennium is likely to go out with a whimper instead of a
bang. Some of us are going to party like it's 1999, but more and
more people are planning a quiet, meaningful New Year's Eve.
``They're staying at home hiding under their beds, playing with
their dogs, playing with their babies and wishing it were 1954,''
says trend watcher Faith Popcorn. Hotels and resorts that were
anticipating record business have had to slash their prices. Most
Britons also plan to stay home, says Nicola Lloyd of Selfridge's
department store, which conducted a recent survey. ``People don't
need to go mad. They just want a night to remember with family and
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what about that pesky Y2K bug? Washington is setting
up a $50 million command center to monitor the situation, but the
biggest problems are expected in China, India and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cyberslacking: Workers who spend an inordinate amount of time
surfing the Internet for fun at work may be in for a surprise.
Newsweek ($3.50) reports that more corporations are cracking down
on the amount of recreational time cubicle dwellers spend online.
New technology gives bosses the power to monitor everything that
workers write online, including personal e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Religious experience: The New Yorker ($3) gets spiritual this
week with an essay by John Updike on the future of faith at the end
of the millennium and a series of stunning photographs of the
faithful by Richard Avedon. Reflecting on a trip through Italy,
Updike describes how his ``feeble faith'' was rejuvenated during a
thunderstorm one night in Florence. The nature of faith may change
with scientific discoveries, he concludes, but the yearning for
``something more'' will persist. Avedon captures that yearning with
his powerful images of the Dalai Lama, flagellants in Spain and a
naked holy man in Calcutta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Step by step: When families get together this Thanksgiving,
the scene is not likely to resemble Norman Rockwell's classic
portrait. According to U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.50),
stepfamilies soon will outnumber traditional families. Getting all
of the various exes and stepchildren to mesh into a new family is
difficult, if not impossible. Experts advise against rushing
things. ``It usually takes up to two years for the stepfamily to
emerge from an initial period of conflict,'' says reporter Wray
Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Norman Rockwell gets more ink this week in People
($2.99), which examines the artist's often turbulent life and the
critical reappraisal of his work. ``The subjects may be
straightforward and simple, but the images are complex,'' says Ned
Rifkin, outgoing director of Atlanta's High Museum. ... The
Advocate ($3.95) talks to Michael Landon's son, Christopher, about
growing up gay and his career as a scriptwriter. One of his latest
scripts is the story of a straight man marooned on an island with a
gay man. A lot of studios were interested, Landon says, ``but they
weren't prepared to make the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
