<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8088 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOON-MAIN23-COX     11-22 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-MAIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New life for an eccentric `Man on the Moon'
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andy, did you hear about this one?
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years after you left our planet on a nose dive into
obscurity, a big-time Hollywood director (Milos Forman) and one of
the country's hottest comedic actors (Jim Carrey) have made a movie
about your life. Yes, your closely guarded and eccentrically weird
life, Andy Kaufman. The soundtrack to the movie, which is being
heavily hyped by a major label with music videos and
celebrity-drenched parties, arrives in stores today. And the talent
behind the CD (sorry, they don't make little vinyl 45s like your
Mighty Mouse record anymore) is one of rock's most respected bands,
R.E.M.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Man on the Moon'' countdown is thanks largely to the
uncharted brain of singer/lyricist Michael Stipe. The movie
biography based on the life of the late comic opens Dec. 22 and is
already the curiosity of the entertainment press, with sneak-peek
photos of Carrey-as-Kaufman leaking out like snapshots of the Loch
Ness monster. Talk of the picture's eerie accuracy has even landed
Carrey on the cover of Vanity Fair. Odds are none of this would
have happened if it weren't for Stipe, who wrote the lyrics for the
band's 1992 hit ``Man on the Moon'' about Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the soundtrack's release, bassist/keyboardist Mike
Mills doesn't hesitate to give R.E.M. credit for the Andy Movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are most definitely responsible for it,'' he says in his
Athens office, pulling an advance copy of the ``Man on the Moon''
soundtrack out of a cardboard box. ``When we put the song out, we
incorporated some footage of Andy doing Elvis into the video. His
family saw that and felt like it was time to give Andy his due. So
they did the (television) documentary, and from it came the idea of
the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when the band was finishing the album ``Automatic for
the People,'' Kaufman had become a distant shadow in pop culture,
vaguely remembered as ``that guy on ``Taxi.''' When Stipe appeared
in the studio late one night with lyrics to an as yet untitled
track of music written by bandmates Mills and Peter Buck, it had
been eight years since the comic died from lung cancer at age 35.
Mills recalls that Stipe had scribbled down a
stream-of-consciousness dialogue with Kaufman, posing this
now-familiar question to the great beyond: ``Andy, are you goofing
on Elvis?'' The tune, ``Man on the Moon,'' became a hit single,
sparking a fascination with Kaufman that eventually made him a
hotter act in death than he was in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that his death probably brought more attention to his
wildness and craziness, and the R.E.M. influence added to that,''
says Ron DiNunzio, co-owner of the Atlanta comedy club the Punch
Line.
</P>
<P>
   The screenwriters apparently knew from the beginning that they
wanted to use the song ``Man on the Moon,'' feeling it was
essential to Kaufman's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they brought in the script, it had the title `Man on the
Moon' on it,'' says producer Stacy Sher. ``The second I finished
reading the script, I whipped out my R.E.M. CD and started
listening to the song again, and it made me cry. I don't know if
Milos had ever heard it, but obviously Danny (DeVito), Andy's
family and the folks close to Andy have always felt that R.E.M.'s
song kind of brought Andy back to people's consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   When Universal executives approached Warner Bros. Records for
permission to use the original track, though, they hit snags.
Eventually, the script got through to R.E.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they read it,'' Sher says, ``they really loved it, and we
all agreed we would try to work it out. We all felt like none of us
would deal with the business issues if the creative issues worked
out. And that's exactly what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   R.E.M. expressed interest in being even more involved in the
project. It wanted to help shape the mood and sound of the movie,
and asked to write the score as well. ``We've wanted to do a score
for a long time, but it had to be the right set of circumstances,''
Mills says.
</P>
<P>
   The band faced several challenges. It had just released the CD
``Up'' and was preparing for a world tour. In March and April, the
only time R.E.M. could work on the project, the movie was still in
production, with few scenes completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, the band would have sat down and started doing this
when there was a locked picture, which would have been the middle
of June,'' says R.E.M. manager and attorney Bertis Downs. ``But we
were on tour in the middle of June, and they knew that.'' So Mills
and guitarist Buck wrote music by watching dailies shipped to them
after a scene was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Background music was written primarily for piano and horns,
although there's an orchestral version of the song ``Man on the
Moon'' in the movie in addition to a portion of the original
single. The band, with Stipe, also penned a new tune for the movie,
``The Great Beyond,'' which was released as a single and video last
week. Bathed in neon, the band appears inside a TV set with Stipe
pressing on the glass like a trapped goldfish until the box falls
off a table onto the floor. Mills says the goal was to capture some
of the Kaufman's quirky lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   The soundtrack is a mix of music that is often as enigmatic and
unpredictable as Kaufman himself. In addition to R.E.M.'s material,
it includes ``Angela (The Theme From `Taxi'),'' a Stipe duet with
Carrey-as-Andy called ``This Friendly World'' and Carrey as Kaufman
alter ego Tony Clifton singing the disco hit ``I Will Survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills says he's seen the movie twice, adding ``Carrey is great.
This guy can act, there's no question. He should have gotten an
Oscar nomination for `The Truman Show.' He'll definitely get one
for this. They said that for nine months he (Carrey) was either
Andy or Tony, but I didn't speak with him enough to notice,'' Mills
says. ``I guess that's method acting.''
</P>
<P>
   As for R.E.M., Stipe, Buck and Mills plan to dedicate two weeks
in December to promote the soundtrack and the movie, including an
appearance at the Los Angeles premiere. Then, Mills says, the band
will take a break and, in spring, begin work on a new album.
Although Stipe has jumped headlong into moviemaking with his own
independent production company (``Being John Malkovich''), it's not
so certain that his bandmates will do another movie project anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is very tough to deal with,'' Mills says. ``While
this was fun, I don't want to be in the business. Hollywood is just
too weird and silly and unpredictable. It's very frustrating,
because when we're making a record, we're only trying to please
three guys and our producer, and make beautiful music. With the
movie, it's not about beautiful music. It's about music that
enhances the scene, stays away from the dialogue. You have to make
everybody happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitutiton.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Russ DeVault contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
