<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-CDREVIEW23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Much more a soundtrack than an R.E.M. release
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't mistake this for a new R.E.M. album. And don't expect to
get too much of an idea of how the band stacks up against full-time
movie music composers. It's much more an artifact of Milos Forman's
biopic of gonzo comedian Andy Kaufman. Included are bits of
dialogue and Kaufman-related tunes (Bob James' theme from ``Taxi,''
a lounge-singer-from-hell's version of ``I Will Survive''), two
versions of the R.E.M. song that inspired the movie's title (the
original ``Man on the Moon,'' and an orchestral take). There's a
sampling of the band's soundtrack contributions, theme music that
can be either bittersweet or bumptious, and betrays an ear familiar
with the distinctive way Burt Bacharach arranged for brass.
</P>
<P>
   The group's one big new number, ``The Great Beyond,'' was
previewed on R.E.M.'s recent U.S. tour and evokes the atmospheric
tone of its best work: emotionally direct, poetic without being
cloying, sweet and wishful. Despite the Middle Eastern swirls of
keyboards and strings that introduce the song, it's less satisfying
in its subdued studio version if you first heard it as a
rip-roaring concert number. Either way, though, it plucks the
heartstrings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music From the Motion Picture `Man on the Moon'''
</P>
<P>
   R.E.M., various artists. Warner Bros. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
