<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-REMBRANDT-BOOK-REVIEW     11-22 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMBRANDT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REMBRANDT'S EYES': STRIPPING AWAY THE MYTHS AND FLESHING OUT THE
LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: publication notes appear at end of review.)  (DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Simon Schama's sumptuous new book on Rembrandt bears about as
much resemblance to traditional biographies of the painter as
``Tristram Shandy'' and ``Moby-Dick'' do to conventional novels.
Impassioned and learned, expansive and discursive, ``Rembrandt's
Eyes'' not only leaves us with a fierce appreciation of the
artist's work but also immerses us inexorably in his world.
</P>
<P>
   Schama _ the author of ``The Embarrassment of Riches,'' an
anthropologically detailed cultural history of the Dutch republic
from 1550-1650 _ fleshes out Rembrandt's story with long
digressions about daily life in Amsterdam, conventions in Flemish
portrait painting, religious tensions in 17th-century Holland and
Catholic and Protestant tastes in art. A large portion of this
volume is devoted to Peter Paul Rubens, Rembrandt's great
predecessor and role model, whom he emulated for a decade with
fierce adoration, and many chapters are filled with chatty asides
about rival artists and the subjects of his paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Schama, however, defiantly refutes recent arguments (set forth
most notably by the scholar Gary Schwartz in a 1986 biography of
the painter) that Rembrandt's art was largely a reflection of his
patrons' tastes and predilections, a kind of barometer of literary,
cultural and social currents of the day. Although Rembrandt was
``an intensely social'' animal, Schama writes, ``it's impossible to
look at his strongest work, either in painting, drawing or etching,
and still not be struck by the simple truth that he achieved things
which, as Durer wrote in another context, `could not, in his day be
found.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he is dismantling the myth of Rembrandt the
Conformist, Schama is also questioning the equally potent myth of
Rembrandt the Rebel. ``He never wished to fly in the face of his
patrons' basic requirements,'' Schama writes, ``but rather sought
to transform them into something impossible to envision from
antecedents.'' As for the popular view of Rembrandt as the
self-obsessed genius (a view fueled by the dozens of remarkable
self-portraits in a variety of poses and costumes), Schama argues,
``The reason for the multiplication of his self-image was not a
relentless, almost monomaniacal assertion of the artistic ego but
something like the exact opposite, Rembrandt's experimental
dissolution of his self into countless other personae: the soldier,
the beggar, the bourgeois, the prince, the Antwerp master.''
</P>
<P>
   The one weakness of this book is that while Schama effectively
debunks both Romantic and revisionist conceptions of Rembrandt, he
does not replace them with a persuasive portrait of his own.
Instead he gives us wordy generalities like, ``Rembrandt was, as we
have already noticed, Everyman.'' Or, Rembrandt ``is Hamlet in
Holland, an inward-outward persona, a poet in heavy metal, the
embodiment of both the active and the contemplative life.'' The
reader finishes the book convinced that all the talk about
Rembrandt's inconstancy and fondness for personas says less about
him than it does about Schama's ambivalence and confusion about his
subject's personality.
</P>
<P>
   In one chapter Schama writes that at the height of Rembrandt's
fame there was ``nothing at all to suggest the foul-tempered
martinet of the posthumous caricatures''; in another he writes that
there is ``no doubt that Rembrandt's fuse was short.''
</P>
<P>
   In one chapter he writes that ``his work would be marked by
intense literary passion''; in another he observes that ``the
indispensability to Rubens of his library and Rembrandt's apparent
lack of interest in a literary collection is something that
genuinely separates their sensibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily for the reader such lapses do not intrude upon the
discussions of Rembrandt's paintings, the heart of this book and a
testament to Schama's gifts as a critic and cultural historian.
Writing with a scholar's knowledge of iconography and technique and
a layman's common sense, Schama does an eloquent job of tracing the
process whereby Rembrandt mastered the lessons of Rubens, emulating
his predecessor's religious and historical canvases and producing a
series of ``big, violent, visceral'' masterpieces packed with
``lurching, lunging, bone-crunching action,'' and then slowly
overcame his anxiety of influence to discover a voice and vision of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Rembrandt's physical feel for the texture of paint; his gift for
mapping character through a fleeting expression or gesture; his
ability to strip away superfluous detail to expose an essential
narrative; his talent for capturing the tension between ``the
glitter of the hard, unforgivingly metallic surface of the world
and the vulnerability of mortal flesh'': all are explicated in
these pages with thoughtful erudition.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing crucial paintings like ``The Supper at Emmaus''
(1628), ``The Anatomy Lesson of Dr. Tulp'' (1632), ``Danae''
(1636), ``The Night Watch'' (1642) and ``The Staalmeesters''
(1662), Schama skillfully shows how Rembrandt managed to invest
historical and mythological figures with the emotional immediacy of
ordinary men and women while learning to infuse humdrum domestic
scenes with a heightened sense of drama. He shows how Rembrandt
routinely breached the barriers between genres of painting, mixing
the high and the low, the classical and colloquial. He shows, too,
how Rembrandt remade the conventions of the portrait painting.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Schama points out, the artist's style underwent
a considerable evolution. After the deaths of his wife, Saskia, and
of Rubens, Rembrandt's grandiose history paintings began to give
way in the 1640's to more meditative works: his palette
increasingly relied on four basic colors (black, white, yellow
ocher and earth reds), and the action in his paintings grew ``less
strenuously physical and more philosophically metaphysical.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade of his career, which produced a series of
luminous, pared-down masterpieces, ``Rembrandt redoubled his
experimental determination in the face of increasing evidence of
its unpopularity,'' adopting a gestural style even as more
fashionable painters ``were working toward a more colorful,
brilliantly lit and smoothly painted manner.''
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters further, the scent of scandal that hovered
over Rembrandt's later life (bankruptcy, a public feud with a
former lover, an illegitimate child) helped galvanize criticism
that he was a painter ``bent on limning ugliness'': an artist who
took ``perverse pleasure in surveying the most unappetizing
features of the human body and the most sordid rustic hovels,'' a
man with a ``peculiar attraction to the decrepit.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as Schama observes at the end of this illuminating book,
Rembrandt saw imperfections as the norm of humanity: ``Which is why
he will always speak across the centuries to those for whom art
might be something other than the quest for ideal forms; to the
unnumbered legions of damaged humanity who recognize, instinctively
and with gratitude, Rembrandt's vision of our fallen race, with all
its flaws and infirmities squarely on view, as a proper subject for
picturing, and, more important, as worthy of love, of saving
grace.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `REMBRANDT'S EYES'
</P>
<P>
   By Simon Schama
</P>
<P>
   750 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
