<HEADLINE>
SEX AND THE SINGLE FOSSIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (Eds: Question may be italicized)  
 (af)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How do scientists tell what sex a fossil is, or was, when
they have only one example?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``You never know for sure, but there are clues in the shape
and size of bony landmarks on the skull,'' said John Krigbaum, an
anthropologist at New York University who is a doctoral candidate.
``The skull is the easiest to sex. You usually can't sex other
bones reliably, except for the pelvis.''
</P>
<P>
   With the skull, what scientists look for is the difference
between what is called robust morphology, meaning typically
heavier, larger shapes and sizes, and gracile morphology, meaning
smaller and more ``graceful'' shapes. Krigbaum explained that males
tend to be more robust in the brow ridge, the mastoid process
behind the ear and the lower jaw.
</P>
<P>
   But with only one fossil example, researchers must rely on what
they know of the species and make an educated guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very real problem,'' Krigbaum said, and it has a name:
the species problem. ``It is unclear whether you are looking at a
species that has a marked difference in size between the sexes,
called sexual dimorphism, or an entirely different species,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer you get to humans in the fossil record,'' he said,
``the better idea you have of how females and males differ in body
shape. But a lot of skulls we know of as isolates, like Homo
erectus fossils in Southeast Asia, you can't be sure if they are
male or female.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York,
N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
