<HEADER>
A8092 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MEREDITH-WINE-ART     11-22 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MEREDITH-WINE-ART-1060(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., France)  
 THE WINE IS VINTAGE; ITS ROOTS ARE ORDINAIRE  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(mk) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIS, Calif. _ It's the New World's Vatican of viticulture, the
oracle of grape-growing, the arbiter of winery practice. The
University of California's department of viticulture and enology
trains most of California's winemakers and provides root stock for
much of the New World.
</P>
<P>
   The department's geneticist, Carole Meredith, has recently been
shaking up a lot of the Old World as well as the New. With a new
method of unraveling the grapevine's tangled family tree, she has
shown that several of the world's best known wine grapes are not
pure strains but hybrids between other varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Her findings, which have in many cases been a surprise for grape
breeders, undermine the theoretical basis for France's quality
control system, the Appellation d'Origine Controlee, which denies
its label to wine made from hybrid varieties on the assumption that
such grapes are inferior to their parents. Dr. Meredith's research
has shown that the Cabernet Sauvignon grape, from which one of the
world's best known red wines is made, and the Chardonnay grape,
source of a leading white wine, are both hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 5,000 varieties of wine grape in the world,
several of which have been grown at least since Roman times. All
are the progeny of the wild grape Vitis vinifera but the puzzle of
how they may be related to each other has long been left to wine
historians and ampelographers, an obscure guild of experts who
pronounce on a vine's ancestry by minutely examining its leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Both the historical and leaf scrutiny methods have been left in
the dust by Dr. Meredith's new method. With John Bowers, then a
graduate student of hers, Dr. Meredith recognized several years ago
that the DNA fingerprinting method used in forensic cases could be
adapted to the vine. Since 1996 she and Bowers have roamed through
the leading Californian and French varieties, conducting paternity
tests and establishing quite unexpected liaisons between grapes of
very different repute.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying a grape variety by its DNA is a matter of commercial
as well as historical interest. Because the department's nursery is
a major source of virus-free root stock, it has become the ultimate
arbiter of vine identity. But many of its varieties were misnamed
because they came originally from Europe in the 19th century before
the importance of accurate provenance was recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naming mistakes in this collection are legion, and have caused
inconvenience for both the California wine industry and importers
of plant material from Davis,'' says a stern entry in the latest
edition of the Oxford Companion to Wine, a leading reference work.
</P>
<P>
   To clear up this confusion, Dr. Meredith tried various kinds of
DNA typing before hitting on the same approach used in forensic DNA
fingerprinting. In collaboration with colleagues in Australia who
had had the same idea, she developed a fingerprinting system for
the grape and used it to sort out the vines in the department's
collection.
</P>
<P>
   With the fingerprinting system in hand, she found she possessed
a powerful tool for slicing through the fog of history and legend
that surrounds the ancestry of most grape varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Though wild grapes come in male and female forms that breed
sexually, those in vineyards are usually propagated by hand from
rootstock, so that in principle each new vine is a clone, meaning
it is genetically identical to its parent. Over the centuries,
however, mutations of various sorts have accumulated, creating
genetic differences between clones that are very slight but still
of interest to growers. Types believed to be very ancient, like
Pinot, have not had sex for some 2,000 years, yet varieties of
Pinot exist, their genetic variation presumably caused just by
mutation.
</P>
<P>
   Other varieties are the result either of deliberate breeding or
accidental cross-fertilization. But the records of most such
crosses have long been lost. Dr. Meredith's first genealogical
success came in 1996 in discovering the ancestry of Cabernet
Sauvignon, the grape from which one of the world's best known red
wines is produced. The variety is known to have been grown in
Bordeaux in the 17th century but its origin has long been a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   As luck would have it, the grape and both of its unacknowledged
parents had already been entered in the small database of 50
varieties that she and Bowers had accumulated. Mulling over the DNA
fingerprint data in bed one Saturday morning, the dedicated Bowers
noticed that Cabernet Sauvignon must be a cross between Cabernet
franc, a well-known red wine grape, and a white grape known as
Sauvignon blanc. The word ``sauvignon,'' meaning ``wild,'' did not
denote any suspected genetic relationship, but merely that both
varieties resembled wild grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Meredith suspects the cross arose accidentally between
Cabernet franc and Sauvignon blanc grapes growing in neighboring
vineyards. This was the first objective scientific data on the
origin of a classic wine grape, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Her biggest triumph came in unraveling the kinship of a large
family of important wine grapes, none of which had been known to be
related to each other. Deliciously, one of the parents of this
large and noble family turned out to be a derided and
long-forgotten grape called gouais blanc, which, despite its
Cinderella-like origins, evidently made a fine breeding partner.
</P>
<P>
   Working with colleagues at the French genetic stock bank, the
National Institute of Agronomic Research at Domaine de Vassal, near
Montpellier, Dr. Meredith selected some 300 varieties that from
appearance or historical records she guessed might be related to
one another.
</P>
<P>
   When the grapes were DNA fingerprinted, a remarkable family
relationship emerged that included some of the best known wine
grapes in the world. The two parents were gouais blanc and Pinot, a
fine red wine grape whose pedigree stretches back to the first
century A.D.
</P>
<P>
   Just as human parents produce children of very different
character, Pinot and gouais turn out to be the progenitors of 16
very different wine grapes. Three are known throughout the world.
Chardonnay is perhaps the leading variety of white wine. Gamay is
the grape from which all Beaujolais is derived. And melon, a third
Pinot-gouais offspring, is the source of all Muscadet. These
findings were reported in the Sept. 3 issue of Science.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, a co-author of the research, now works at the University
of Georgia where, even though his family has strong ties to the
California wine industry, he has switched to studying the genetics
of sorghum.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Meredith too grew up in the San Francisco Bay area and went
to the Davis campus of the University of California, her father
deeming Berkeley too radical. She became the arbiter of grapevine
genealogy by an unusual route. Having skipped a lot of classes as a
college student, she worked selling plants in a nursery and became
fascinated with the rich variety of petunias and marigolds that
passed through her hands.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding she wanted to go back to school and study plant
genetics, she talked her way into graduate school at U.C. Davis and
did a Ph.D. on the genetics of tomatoes. She then worked with two
plant biotechnology companies but found she did not enjoy life in
industry for an understandable reason. ``I really resented having a
boss,'' she says. ``I didn't like telling him what I planned to do
and getting his permission to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 she joined the U.C. Davis department of viticulture and
enology (academese for grape growing and wine making), succeeding
Harold Olmo, a well known grape breeder, as the department's plant
geneticist.
</P>
<P>
   To establish her scientific credentials, she worked on tobacco,
a well-studied plant, until she got tenure. Only then did she focus
on the grape, a difficult plant whose genetics are not nearly as
well understood. Her appreciation of the risks was well founded.
The winemakers who supported the department's research saw no quick
payoff in her work and in 1991 she was almost forced to close her
lab. It was after this crisis that she started work on the problem
of identifying grape varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Grapes, like people, have sites on their DNA where the same few
genetic letters are repeated over and over in a biologically
meaningless stutter. The number of repeats changes quite often from
one generation to another, which makes them useful markers of
identity. The repeat number at any one site may not identify an
individual, but the more sites are considered, the greater the
chances of defining an individual uniquely.
</P>
<P>
   In the population of the United States, the FBI uses the number
of repeats at 13 different sites. To define a grape, some 20 to 30
markers are needed. This is not because grapes are more complicated
than people _ they have only 19, very small, chromosomes _ but
because most grape varieties are close relatives and more markers
are needed to distinguish among them.
</P>
<P>
   With partners in nine other wine-growing countries, Dr. Meredith
has formed the Vitis Microsatellite Consortium to share information
about the diagnostic repeat sites, which are known as
microsatellites to geneticists. So far 154 of these sites have been
identified. They are also helpful to grape breeders because they
serve to locate the position on the DNA of desired genes. Dr.
Meredith hopes the sites will help solve the major mystery of grape
growing, which is why the same variety may produce a great wine in
some environments and a lousy one in others. ``I think we are
really on the threshold of understanding these things,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Recently she unraveled the long-puzzling relationship among
three similarly named wine grapes _ France's Syrah, California's
Petite Sirah and Australia's Shiraz. It turns out that Shiraz is
the same as Syrah, and Petite Sirah is a cross between Syrah and an
obscure French grape called Peloursin.
</P>
<P>
   Further work, which Dr. Meredith has not yet published, has
shown that Syrah itself is a hybrid of Dureza, a dark-berried grape
of the Ardeche region of France, and a white grape known as
mondeuse blanche. Syrah, surmised to be the grape known to the
Romans as Vitis Allobrogica, is Dr. Meredith's favorite. With her
husband, Stephen Lagier, a winemaker, she has started growing Syrah
on a vineyard they own in the Napa Valley. She plans to sell her
Syrah commercially next year and feels the venture has given her a
better understanding of her students, many of whom come to the
department having been out of school for many years and with a
passion to learn winemaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here I couldn't understand that because I
was thinking just as a scientist,'' she says. ``But now I am making
my own wine from our own land, I am living out a dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
