<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROUNDABOUT-THEATER-AR     11-22 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROUNDABOUT-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER FINANCES SPACE BY PUTTING DONOR'S NAMES IN LIGHTS AND OTHER
PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT14, is being sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The VIP lounge is spoken for at $500,000, as is the
box office at $250,000. But the penthouse lobby is still up for
grabs at $1.5 million, along with the orchestra pit ($350,000) and
four restrooms ($75,000 each).
</P>
<P>
   While one mega-donor, et unannounced, is in the wings, there
may still be the slightest chance of seeing your name atop the
marquee of the Roundabout Theater Company's new 740-seat flagship
on West 42nd Street, for about $10 million, give or take a million
or two.
</P>
<P>
   With the old Selwyn Theater undergoing a $21.5 million
transformation from woebegone B-movie house to its gilded 1918
neo-Renaissance origins, the long-nomadic, nonprofit Roundabout,
which chanced upon the choice site at a prime moment, is seeking
benefactors the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got it, we name it,'' said Julia C. Levy, the executive
director in charge of external affairs and the company's chief
fund-raiser, ticking off the ``gift opportunities'' still available
in the time-honored way that cultural institutions have adopted to
finance capital improvements by conferring immortality on large
donors. About three-quarters of the needed money has been
committed, Ms. Levy said, and the theater is scheduled to reopen on
March 21, three months later than originally scheduled, with a
production of Chekhov's ``Uncle Vanya'' starring Roger Rees, Laura
Linney and Sir Derek Jacobi.
</P>
<P>
   For a subscription theater with more than its share of hard-luck
stories _ a fatal Times Square crane collapse shut down its runaway
hit revival of ``Cabaret'' on West 43rd Street for four weeks in
1998 at a loss of $2 million, and the empty Selwyn shell itself
collapsed into a pile of debris on Dec. 30, 1997 _ the Roundabout's
latest stroke of fortune is a coup. It surpasses even the
award-winning productions of ``Anna Christie'' in 1993 and ``She
Loves Me'' in 1994, which propelled the Roundabout into the
forefront of the nation's nonprofit stage companies.
</P>
<P>
   How the Roundabout snagged a key parcel amid the most
sought-after real estate in New York City was largely happenstance,
theater executives and 42nd Street redevelopment officials said.
While some other theater troupes might now cast an envious eye on
the deal, many agreed that none seemed more suited to the space, or
deserving of it, than the Roundabout, the nation's second-largest
nonprofit theater, after Lincoln Center's. The company is at a
record 41,000 annual subscribers and has a budget of $19 million,
not including its hit Broadway production of ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We considered the Selwyn, but there were a lot of other things
going on,'' said Lynne Meadow, artistic director of the Manhattan
Theater Club, which has also been intermittently looking for a
Broadway site to augment its two auditoriums at City Center that
seat 300 and 150.
</P>
<P>
   James Houghton, founding artistic director of the Signature
Theater Co., agreed. ``It makes total sense that they're there,''
he said. His company, which offers seasons devoted to one
playwright at a time, was delighted with its smaller quarters on
West 42nd Street. ``There's no way we would want a theater of that
size,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Joseph Papp Public Theater, with five stages in its
Greenwich Village headquarters and the use of Central Park for its
summer Shakespeare productions, also took a look at the Selwyn but
passed on it as an unaffordable luxury, said the theater's
spokeswoman, Carol Fineman.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Rent'' had been taken by the authentically
dilapidated setting of the Selwyn but ultimately settled on the
Nederlander in what was then an unfashionable precinct a block
south of 42nd Street. As for the commercial theater, which strives
to make a profit, a smallish house with high reconstruction costs
like the Selwyn made no sense at all, said Rocco Landesman, the
president of Jujamcyn, the city's third-largest theater chain.
</P>
<P>
   Which left, essentially, the Roundabout, whose largest capital
campaign to date had been $2.6 million for its Laura Pels Theater.
Now all the company had to do was raise the money: a price tag that
started off modestly enough at $7 million in 1996 and is likely to
top $22 million by the time the reconstruction is finished.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the last of the old showhouses on 42nd Street to be
reclaimed _ only two remain, the Liberty and the Times Square _ the
Selwyn is ripe for sponsorship, Ms. Levy said, starting with a
renaming in honor of some lucky, and very rich, benefactor. A
prospective namesake has come forward, although details remain to
be worked out, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since being turned out earlier this year from the Criterion
Center on Broadway and 45th Street, which its landlord repossessed
for redevelopment in the Times Square building boom, the Roundabout
is staging its productions, including ``The Rainmaker'' and
``Cabaret,'' in leased Broadway and Off Broadway theaters. It has
taken permanent office space in a garment center building at 231
West 39th Street and is still looking for a small stage to replace
the Laura Pels Theater, which it gave up in the Criterion Center.
</P>
<P>
   As work crews from the Ryder Construction Corp. sawed, hammered
and painted in the Selwyn around them, Ms. Levy and Todd Haimes,
the Roundabout's artistic director, who has seen the company
through a decade and a half's suspenseful cycles of bust and boom,
traipsed one recent morning through the scaffolded interior of the
theater's first permanent home in its nearly 35-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The theater, west of the New Victory Theater and the Ford
Center, is to share the 10-story New 42nd Studios (with its own
200-seat experimental theater, the Duke) owned by the sponsoring
group, the New 42nd Street Inc., which oversees the seven reclaimed
theaters on the block and gave the Roundabout a long-term lease.
The terms, including a below-market rental, remain confidential,
but with renewals the Roundabout's tenancy should extend into the
mid-21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes, in a blue pin-stripe suit and white hard hat, peered
around the edges of the sprawling stage, 75 feet wide by 50 feet
deep. ``That's the wing space we never had,'' he said. ``That's the
fly space we never had.'' He looked down, wistful. ``The orchestra
pit,'' he said. ``We never had one before.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater has only 14 rows of orchestra seats spread in a wide
arc, and a similarly shallow balcony, so the audience will be
unusually close to the action, Haimes said. Parts of the mezzanine
cornices and boxes were chopped away when the theater became a
movie house in the 1930s and are being restored.
</P>
<P>
   Prized amenities in the new theater include a 3,500-square-foot
penthouse lobby and catering area above the theater overlooking
43rd Street and just above that a smaller private lounge for large
contributors. That V.I.P. space has been underwritten by Nabisco
with a $500,000 contribution. ``We call it the `Oreo Lounge'
affectionately for our favorite cookie,'' Ms. Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   The penthouse lobby is still seeking a benefactor at three times
the price, she said, along with other variously priced components:
the green room, coat check, dressing rooms, boxes and individual
seats, even the plasterwork and the restrooms. Ms. Levy said that
the naming of the theater itself, for about $10 million, remains to
be agreed upon. That money, she said, is to go into an endowment to
keep the Roundabout solvent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Apart from that, about $15 million of the $21.5 million goal has
been committed, Ms. Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   For a theater whose name nicely captures the itinerant nature of
its turbulent history, the Roundabout stumbled into its happy
ending, accounts from executives and officials agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 the 42nd Street Entertainment Corp., as it was then
called, charged with trying to revive a street long mired in
pornography and crime, issued a ``request for use'' to redevelop
six historic theaters on the block between Broadway and Eighth
Avenue. About 800 groups received the solicitation, recalled
Rebecca Robertson, then the project's vice president and now vice
president for real estate at the Shubert Organization. Forty-four
responded, including Imax, the Knitting Factory, the Manhattan
Theater Club and the Roundabout.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout, the Flying Dutchman of theater companies, had a
long history of homelessness. Founded in 1965 and installed
initially in the basement of a supermarket in Chelsea, the
struggling troupe moved next to a nearby RKO movie house but by
1978 had gone bankrupt. Still, it stayed alive despite mounting
debts, and in 1984, the year after Haimes took over as business
manager, found temporary space in the Fashion Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   As that lease approached expiration in 1990, Haimes started
looking elsewhere. But he was not enthusiastic about derelict 42nd
Street. ``He felt sorry for me,'' Ms. Robertson said. ``He thought
I had the worst job in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The renamed New 42nd Street Inc., was first empowered to start
evaluating the redevelopment proposals in 1991, by which time many
of the prospective bidders had dropped out or had been found
unsuitable. The Roundabout itself had withdrawn, signing instead a
20-year lease on a 499-seat theater in the Criterion Center on
Broadway; in 1995 it opened a second performance space, a 399-seat
theater, the Laura Pels.
</P>
<P>
   But change was finally coming to 42nd Street. In 1992 New 42nd
Street provided a big starting push with a commitment to open the
New Victory Theater for children's productions by 1994. (It
actually opened in 1995.) In March 1993 Michael D. Eisner, chairman
of the Walt Disney Co., toured the block and by the end of the year
had agreed to take over the New Amsterdam Theater, which by 1997
would showcase ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 Livent Inc. agreed to rebuild two theaters into what
became the Ford Center, where in 1997 Livent opened its hit musical
``Ragtime.'' Soon other developers announced ambitious
entertainment plans for the block.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 15, 1996, at the memorial service for Bernard B. Jacobs,
who had been president of Shubert, Haimes found himself sitting
next to Ms. Robertson, and the question of the Selwyn came up
again. ``It sounds disrespectful, I know,'' Ms. Robertson said. But
she thought that Jacobs, of all people, would understand, and she
pressed Haimes for once and for all to look at the theater.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before the end of the year he had a series of meetings with Cora
Cahan, who had become president of New 42nd Street , and a deal was
outlined. Although she had fulfilled her requirement of two
nonprofit theaters on the block (the New Victory and the rehearsal
studios and Duke stage), adding another of the Roundabout's stature
would be seen as a responsible counterweight to the accelerating
commercial exploitation of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout still had a lease running to 2010 on the
Criterion Center. But the building's owner, Charles B. Moss Jr.,
invoking an escape clause after seven years, told the Roundabout he
intended to evict it to redevelop the building.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said that when he began looking at the Selwyn he had no
way of knowing that the Roundabout, once again, would face
homelessness. But this time, he said, his business background
really paid off. ``I noticed everything going on around me,'' he
said. ``I said, `Let's do something before a crisis.' We were very
lucky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1731EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
