<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8098 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      11-22 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUT WHAT WILL WE EAT ON FRIDAY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are doing something different this year, going to a
restaurant for Thanksgiving. We are not rejecting tradition or
creating a new one. This is only a slight modification, an
experiment to deviate from the normal ritual that turns the house
into a mess hall. We thought about it after a friend told of taking
his family of six to a Buddhist temple for Thanksgiving dinner. And
remembering that old Christmas movie where everyone ends up happily
eating Chinese food after the neighborhood dogs get the turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Some are shocked by this, as if we were boycotting the Macy's
parade and banning football talk. But, we say it will be an
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, who will continue their at home-tradition, are curious
about our plan but say their family wouldn't stand for messing with
the ritual and were they to insist, they couldn't live with the
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   We say we will still be together with family and friends. We
will still get to stuff ourselves and thank our blessings. But we
will not have to clean up after.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we won't have to clean up before. Nor will we have to
get up at 6 a.m. to handle innards and toss ole Tom around the
kitchen. We can skip the debate whether to go exotic with the
stuffing or plain, knowing that plain always wins. The man with the
knife will not have to chase crowds from the kitchen five minutes
to sit-down and the sous chef will not be spilling brandy into her
coffee before noon.
</P>
<P>
   It will not matter that we never have enough cloth napkins or
chairs. We will have a long leisurely morning. Perhaps we will take
a walk along the ocean. Maybe we'll rent a movie. If we want we can
sit in pajamas until afternoon when it's time to put on clothes and
go over the river and through the woods to a big, old Italian
restaurant known for its checkered tablecloths, jug red and
multi-course feeds.
</P>
<P>
   Does this seem shallow and pathetic? Will we be scorned for
taking the easy way out? Or will we be pitied as holiday orphans
who must break bread with strangers because they have no family of
their own? We will see.
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving rituals run deep. You are supposed to spend
Thanksgiving at home _ your own or someone's home with whom you
share, if not blood, at least history. On New Year's you can mingle
and kiss strangers, but there is to be nothing out of the ordinary
on Thanksgiving, although there was that year when we dressed as
Native Americans and Pilgrims and had a picnic at Tilden Park in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be turkey, we are asked? Of course there will be
turkey, but there will also be ravioli if one's in the mood. And
cranberry sauce? And gravy and stuffing?
</P>
<P>
   We know what's going on here. People who never even nod at a
cranberry the rest of the year require the sauce on this singular
day. On that same day they can't imagine being in a ravioli mood.
</P>
<P>
   But the real issue is leftovers. What then do we eat on the days
after? Doggy bags are not the same as having half a carcass in your
refrigerator, being able to tear off a perfect strip of dark meat
to cover with ketchup and hot peppers and stick in a dinner roll.
And then picking under foil for a forkful of cold, gooey stuffing.
What about day-old pumpkin pie, starting to pull from the crust, a
different color and some say a richer taste than when first served?
</P>
<P>
   An entrepreneurial type might do well to create a line of
holiday leftovers _ day-old mashed potatoes and gravy, broccoli
with cheese sauce, all the better and homier after sitting for 24
hours or more.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're thinking that maybe on Saturday, just for fun, we'll
do a small turkey. And, you know, if people are around to eat,
that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JOHNSTON-BOOK-ART-2TA     11-22 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSTON-BOOK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: BARREN ISLAND HAS FERTILE SOIL FOR EPIC AND AUTHOR
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it was suggested to Wayne Johnston that his new book, ``The
Colony of Unrequited Dreams,'' might be the Great Newfoundland
Novel, a smile crossed the author's face. ``Is that an oxymoron?''
he wondered during a recent interview in New York. For this
41-year-old Canadian, his birthplace _ a former British colony and
since 1949 a province of Canada _ ``may not be big, but the
struggle is heroic.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The Great Newfoundland Novel is like the Great
American Novel, it never will exist. It's just something to shoot
for.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Newfoundland the label would imply that the book
is only for people from that place. As reviewers in the United
States and Canada have realized, anyone can enjoy it, even those
without a knowledge of the province's history or those who
mispronounce its name. It's noo-fund-LAND.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colony of Unrequited Dreams'' (Doubleday) is the first of
Johnston's five books to be published in the United States.
Recently it was followed by his third, ``The Divine Ryans.'' (The
movie version, with a screenplay by the author, is scheduled to
open soon.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Colony'' is by far the longest and most ambitious of his
works. A contemporary historical novel, it is the richly layered
story of two outsiders in a remote land searching for its identity.
With some of the feeling of a 19th-century novel, it captures both
the beauty and the bleakness of this island off the coast of
Labrador.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist and narrator is a real person, Joe Smallwood,
the first premier of Newfoundland when it became a Canadian
province. Smallwood was born in 1900, and the book spans most of
the 20th century. To American readers he is as unknown as any
governor of a small state during his period, but he was a pivotal
figure in the history of his country. As Johnston said, ``When I
was growing up, he was a legend, an incredibly dynamic character.''
</P>
<P>
   A failure as a young journalist, Smallwood eventually became a
highly successful politician and a leader of the movement to join
the Canadian confederacy. In his early days as a labor organizer
and politician, he walked across Newfoundland, visiting every
railroad outpost along the way, and then he walked back home. It
took him more than two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an amazing accomplishment,'' Johnston said, and it
endeared him to the public. ``The character in the book has an epic
sense of the world and of himself as he struggles to live up to it.
That's why I find Smallwood to be so emblematic of Newfoundland:
this sense of near nationhood, near everything. If one or two
things had been different, it could have made it as a country. That
sense of loss lives on in the people who live there.'' The
fictional Smallwood's first words are, ``I am a Newfoundlander,'' a
conscious emulation of the first line of ``The Adventures of Augie
March,'' in which Saul Bellow's title character begins, ``I am an
American.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said that his Smallwood was true to the basic facts,
with one notable exception: the character of Shelagh Fielding, the
woman who shadows him throughout the book and is for a long time
his unacknowledged love. Fielding, as she is called, is an vivid
and independent woman, and she almost walks away with the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Smallwood and Fielding are friends _ and have been rivals _
since their childhood, when they were involved in an episode that
haunts them all their lives. Something similar happens in ``Fifth
Business,'' by Robertson Davies, a fellow Canadian to whom Johnston
has been compared. In common their novels deal with tumultuous,
often comic events in the lives of colorful characters.
</P>
<P>
   Physically and temperamentally, Smallwood and Fielding are
opposites. He is an incarnation of his name: small, wiry and often
a Zelig-like apparition in other people's lives. (Johnston said
that at a certain age Woody Allen would have been perfect casting
for a film.) Fielding is tall and somewhat ungainly, and as a kind
of signature carries a cane. She is bold and outspoken, a skeptic
in contrast to his role as a soapbox orator. Her character is
inspired by several people in Smallwood's life and also by her
namesake, Henry Fielding. As in Fielding's ``Tom Jones,'' her wry
commentary, and her condensed history of Newfoundland, enlivens the
narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed a voice to balance Smallwood,'' Johnston said, ``and
Fielding was a bit of a gift.'' One night while working he looked
at a photograph in an encyclopedia, a picture of the graduating
class in a girl's school in the early part of this century. A
student in the back row had ``a very evocative look.'' That was the
first image for Fielding, and he kept the book open to that page
while he created the character.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's interest in Smallwood began when he was a teenager in
a tiny town outside St. Johns. As a student at Roman Catholic
schools, he was encouraged to become a priest. (``The Divine
Ryans'' is about a family of priests and undertakers.) ``I have a
lot in common with Smallwood,'' he said. ``I wasn't as poor as he
was, but we were poor and moved from house to house as he did.''
Although they both loved Newfoundland, each also had an antipathy
to the North Atlantic, which is so much a part of local life.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Memorial University of Newfoundland,
Johnston worked as a reporter on a small newspaper in St. Johns.
One of his assignments was to go on a seal hunt, which led him many
years later to write a harrowing passage in ``Colony,'' recreating
a historical incident in which 87 sealers died after being stranded
on an ice floe.
</P>
<P>
   Covering the local courts, he met Smallwood, who by that time
had retired from office. Because Johnston mentioned him in an
article, Smallwood excoriated him in the courthouse: ``He was quite
short, and he pretty much stood on my feet. He looked up at me and
said, `I have written for newspapers in London, New York, Boston
and Halifax, and I've never read such drivel.' And it was only from
mentioning his name in a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Were he alive today, would he stand on the author's feet and
criticize the book? ``I think he would love the attention,'' he
said. ``Even that tantrum was for public consumption. A novel about
him? He would have loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Johnston published his first book when he was 26, and since then
has been a full-time novelist. He moved to Toronto, where he lives
with his wife, but he still keeps close contact with Newfoundland.
In preparation for ``Colony'' he followed his subject's path to New
York, where Smallwood spent several years writing for periodicals
and giving speeches in Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   Late in writing the novel Johnston thought of two key words for
use in his title: colony and unrequited, and played around with
variations of both while also considering other possibilities,
beginning with ``100 Years of Solitude.'' Of course, that title was
already taken, but there was something in it suggestive of his
grand theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like books that are consciously written in the knowledge
that North America is the New World, books like `The Great
Gatsby,''' he said. ``I always loved the last pages where he's
talking about how the shore must have looked when the Dutch sailors
first saw it.'' He also loved the title of V.S. Naipaul's book
``The Enigma of Arrival.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I wrote about Newfoundland as part of the New
World,'' he said. ``Though it's the oldest colony in North America,
it's an undiscovered new place where you have to build your culture
from the ground up.''
</P>
<P>
   As Smallwood says in ``Colony,'' it seemed to be ``a landlocked
country in the middle of an otherwise empty continent,'' an
``unfoundland,'' at least until Johnston wrote his novel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
