<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-WEBSITE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WEB SITE DESIGNED BY DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DEBORAH CIRCELLI   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Dr. R.S. Puri sees the Internet as the future
of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The 64-year-old internal-medicine physician is banking on it.
</P>
<P>
   Puri and 17 other Florida doctors have collectively invested $1
million to start DoctorSurf.com, a Web site designed by doctors to
provide information to doctors and patients.
</P>
<P>
   The private company also is one of the first in the nation given
permission by the Securities and Exchange Commission to give away
SEC-registered shares on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians and dentists who sign up with the company are given
100 free shares for providing information about themselves for the
site. The free stock offering will be given to the first 250,000
doctors, which will total 25 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to get physicians interested in the site, which will
receive continual funding through pharmaceutical companies that
will advertise products on the site.
</P>
<P>
   DoctorSurf.com is up and running, though aspects of it are still
being developed.
</P>
<P>
   Puri said the site will provide a variety of information written
by doctors, including new medical research and studies on various
diseases. Members will be able to link to medical journals, medical
schools, hospitals and health-care organizations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is the future. That is the way we see it,'' said
Puri, a physician in Lakeland for 25 years and one of three vice
presidents for DoctorSurf.com. ``Companies are selling groceries on
the Internet and this is far better than groceries. There is a
tremendous need for information and the right kind of information.
We define this as an informational highway for doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   The public also can use the Web site to obtain free information.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be able to log onto the site and get research
information on what is happening in medicine from around the
world,'' Puri said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1735EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
