<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-CASSIDY23-COX     11-22 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CASSIDY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Run Like a Girl' gives young women a sporting chance
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The high school girls are so covered in mud they are truly one
with the earth. Playing rugby on a soaked and well-churned field,
they run hard, tackle harder, yell ``Take her down!'' with the
gusto of Marines at boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohmigod, it felt so good!'' gushes a 16-year-old with a
mouthful of braces afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Say this for ``Run Like a Girl,'' a new public television
documentary by Atlanta filmmaker Carol Cassidy: It never goes where
you think it will. Although it focuses on girls playing sports,
there's no mention of the ones we read about all the time: soccer,
basketball, tennis. And although it's all about societal
expectations and the psychology of adolescents, there isn't a
single statistic, nor a single expert's psycho-babble.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting girls's stories
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy, a former CNN producer, is now an independent filmmaker;
``Run Like a Girl'' is part of her ``American Girls'' trilogy,
which also includes ``Baby Love'' and ``Smile Pretty.'' She's
collected the stories of all the girls she's documented into a new
book, ``Girls in America: Their Stories, Their Words,'' just out
from TV Books.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to rugby, ``Run'' also spends time with synchronized
swimmers and double-dutch jump-ropers, both of which face an uphill
battle to be acknowledged as real sports. But the hours they put
in, their self-discipline and sense of achievement count for vast
amounts no matter what you call their activities.
</P>
<P>
   The girls play hard, and talk with great candor. ``They hit him
in the head with a hammer,'' a young jump-roper says of a young
friend who got caught up with gangs. ``I hope I won't be like that.
But I don't know.'' A swimmer talks about earlier bouts of
self-mutilation, and a rugby player nervously gets dressed up for
the school dance.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Reviving Ophelia'' from the point of view of the girls
themselves: ``Ophelia Kicks Butt.'' And it's a strong antidote to
that lingering, queasy feeling so many people had after watching
the ennui-driven sex of ``The Lost Children of Rockdale County.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Run Like a Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   11 tonight on WPBA
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
