<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8111 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-FAA-Y2K-HNS &LR;      11-22 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS SAY FAA'S TRAFFIC CONTROL SYSTEM WILL BE READY FOR Y2K 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's air traffic control system will be
ready for the year 2000, lawmakers on the House Y2K task force said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The task force also reported that the vast majority of the
federal government's computers have been fixed and tested to
properly interpret Jan. 1, 2000. If computers are not fixed they
may misread the year 2000 as 1900 and fail, a potential problem
dubbed ``Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration's air traffic control system
wasn't fully ready for the year 2000 as of Nov. 15 but Rep. Connie
Morella, R-Md., the task force's co-chairman, said she fully
expects the FAA to be ready by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the FAA ranked in the ``not ready'' category is
because the agency hasn't finished testing some systems that
connect with the air traffic control system such as weather
forecasting equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has to worry about getting on a plane,'' Morella said.
``Planes will not fly if it's not safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif., the task force's other co-chair,
said he is so confident in the air traffic control system that he
plans to fly on Dec. 31 from Los Angeles to Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Many airlines have canceled some flights Dec. 31 and Jan. 1
because of a lack of demand. The Air Transport Association (ATA), a
Washington-based trade association that represents large airlines,
said the lower-than-normal flight bookings have little to do with
fears that people may have about flying on Dec. 31 and Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have been told they have to work and can't go
anywhere,'' said Thomas Browne, executive director of the ATA's
aviation millenium project. In cases where people are travelling,
Browne said they are leaving earlier and staying later than usual
to comply with minimum stays that many hotels have implemented for
the New Year's holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we don't see any reason why people shouldn't
fly,'' Browne said. ``(Air traffic control) testing has been going
on for many, many months.''
</P>
<P>
   FAA administrator Jane Garvey has repeatedly told Congress that
the FAA's computer systems are ready. Last month she told a Senate
Y2K task force that the agency is continuing to test and retest
computer systems, including air traffic control. Earlier this year
FAA moved air traffic control's clocks ahead to Dec. 31, 1999, and
flew a test flight from Grand Junction, Colo. to Denver without
incident.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
