<P>
   BUSH-ENVIRONMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At a time when Texas is gaining notoriety for
leading the nation in toxic emissions, state regulators are
collecting fewer and fewer environmental fines, records show. Fines
collected from polluters during fiscal 1999 have hit a seven-year
low, figures from the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission show. Many environmentalists say the downward trend
reflects lax enforcement by the administration of Gov. George W.
Bush and a disturbing coziness with the industries that the
commission regulates, an allegation that state officials dispute.
By JAY ROOT. Story has moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M-TRAGEDIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ All too regularly this year, volleys of
gunfire have rung out over the Texas A&AMP;M campus, blacked out and
eerily silent during the salutes to the recent dead. In the shadow
of the stately Academic Building, where a bronze statue of Lawrence
Sullivan Ross, a Texas governor and A&AMP;M president, watches over the
lawn, buglers sound taps. The doleful refrain is repeated for each
A&AMP;M student who died during the previous four weeks. This year, it
has become painfully familiar. By CHRIS VAUGHN. Story has moved in
``a'' general news category. With sidebars as they develop,
including funeral services for some victims. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHY-GUY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ As a workaholic who ate too much of the wrong stuff
and rarely exercised, Jeff Guinn was tempting fate. He ignored the
warning signs of heart disease, and when he vowed to get in shape,
it was too late and he almost killed himself. Guinn reflects on his
old lifestyle, bypass surgery, and coming to grips with changing
his ways. It's a reminder of how he used to live and an example for
others to learn from. By JEFF GUINN. Story has moved in ``l''
lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PERKINS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ If there's a pleasant surprise to this sweeps month,
it's how uncommonly sedate it has been. Heading into the final
couple weeks of this song and dance designed to boost ad rates and
make local television news look silly, we've had fewer
embarrassments than usual: not as many bloated miniseries and
elaborate musicals as in the past, and series haven't produced the
high number of episodes in which big-name guest stars are awkwardly
written into scripts. By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story will move in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROCKWELL-REMINISCENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Norman Rockwell's ``Freedom From Want'' has become
several generations of American's visual shorthand for Thanksgiving
dinner and family gatherings. As the largest Rockwell exhibit ever
takes to the road for a seven-city tour, staff writer Dave Ferman
reflects on Rockwell's career and what his work _ and particularly
``Want'' _ means to him. By DAVE FERMAN. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WRIGHT-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Reader response to a recent column on the spread and
officiousness of monopolies convinces me that I must have touched a
nerve. Many of the comments reveal a brooding sense of alienation,
of being taken for granted and treated with cavalier indifference
by the ever bigger and more remotely run companies with which the
public is increasingly forced to deal. By JIM WRIGHT. Story will
move in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
