<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-1123-COX     11-22 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-1123-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS CLINTON HEADS TO SITE OF HIS RISKIEST FOREIGN POLICY VENTURE,
KOSOVO STILL SMOLDERS WITH ETHNIC STRIFE
 &HT;    With KINGSTON-CLINTON-1123.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria _ Journeying to the heart of last spring's
Balkan nightmare, President Clinton goes Tuesday to Kosovo to
address its beleaguered citizens and buck up the spirits of
American troops struggling to enforce a fragile peace.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be briefed on the deeply troubled allied mission to
knit the war-ravaged province back together and will host a
Thanksgiving week dinner for U.S. soldiers during his eight-hour
visit.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to appeal to majority ethnic Albanians to stop the
violent retribution against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks against Serbs have threatened NATO and United Nations
efforts in Kosovo, where Clinton led the West in spring air strikes
to counter a bloody campaign of Serb repression and terror
targeting Kosovo's majority ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will make a very strong statement about the importance of
everybody getting over this ethnic hatred and going beyond it,''
Clinton told reporters here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all made a big commitment to Kosovo and its economic
and political reconstruction,'' Clinton said. ``But I think it's
very important that Kosovo, in effect, not become the mirror image
of Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to seven years of attacks by Serbs against
non-Serbs in nearby Croatia, Bosnia and Slovenia, as well as
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of bolstering the political opponents of Serb leader
Slobodan Milosevic, the president of Yugoslavia, Clinton held out
the promise Monday of large scale U.S. aid to Serbia _ but only if
Milosevic gives up power in Belgrade. Serbia is Yugoslavia's
dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with war crimes by a U.N. tribunal, Milosevic has shown
no sign of stepping down.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton touted Bulgaria, a former Soviet satellite state, as a
model of the sort of democratic and ethnically tolerant nation that
is slowly changing the face of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your neighbor, Serbia, should be part of that bright and
different future,'' Clinton said in an address to more than 20,000
people jammed into Sofia's historic Nevski Square, an hour's drive
from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am told that during the recent war you could actually hear
some of the bombs falling in Serbia from this square,'' Clinton
said, his breath showing misty in the chilled night air. ``Tonight,
I hope the people of Serbia can hear our voices when we say, if you
choose as Bulgaria has chosen, you will regain the rightful place
in Europe Mr. Milosevic has stolen from you, and America will help
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit here amounted to a badly needed vote of
confidence for Bulgaria. Once one of the Soviet Union's most
reliable client states, Bulgaria is staggering through a bold if
uneven 10-year march from communist totalitarianism to free-market
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, that journey has left Bulgaria stranded at the eastern
edge of the Balkans. Already one of the poorest nations in Europe _
with per capita income barely reaching $1,500 per year _ Bulgaria
has been further strangled by the war in Yugoslavia, through which
most of Bulgaria's international trade must flow.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's National Security Advisor, Samuel Berger, said
Milosevic is preventing the United States from helping to clear the
Danube River of a half-dozen bridges dropped by NATO warplanes
during 78 days of air strikes last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The bridges have left the Danube _ the main trade artery linking
the Balkans to Central Europe _ impassable through Serbia. The
condition is wreaking economic havoc on countries like Bulgaria,
Romania and Macedonia. All depend heavily upon Danube connections
for imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to clear the Danube,'' Berger said. Milosevic,
though, has said NATO countries may only help clear the bridges if
they also rebuild them, Berger said, adding ``That's not something
we're prepared to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the top of Clinton's agenda Tuesday will be meetings with the
allied civilian and military leaders that are administering Kosovo
_ Bernard Kouchner, the special U.N. representative for civilian
operations and German Gen. Klaus Reinhardt, commander of the 41,000
troops, 6,300 of them Americans, making up the U.N. peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also expected to meet with Albanian leaders Ibrahim
Rugova and Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, as well as Kosovo's highest Serb religious authority, Serb
Orthodox Bishop Artimije.
</P>
<P>
   The troops and humanitarian aid workers moved in last June,
following NATO air strikes. The campaign was waged to halt the
abuse of ethnic Albanians by Serbs, who are estimated to have
killed up to 10,000 Albanians while forcing more than 1.2 million
others to flee their homes and take refuge in the mountains of
Kosovo or beyond its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Five months after the NATO victory, though, the allied operation
there is listing badly:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Albanians seeking revenge have killed scores of ethnic Serbs
and intimidated and terrorized thousands more. Berger estimated
that as many as three in four of the 200,000 Serbs that call Kosovo
home have fled the province.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  While nearly 900,000 Albanian refugees have returned home,
hundreds of thousands lack basic housing. Aid workers are rushing
in plastic sheeting and plywood, in hopes of providing every family
at least one weather-proofed room before the harsh Balkan winter
sets in over the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Money promised by the West for peacekeeping and reconstruction
in Kosovo has fallen far short of pledges. As a result, a broad
array of programs, from training local police to restoring water
and electricity, has been slowed.
</P>
<P>
   The problems were largely anticipated, U.S. officials said
Monday, but they are problems just the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who saw the way the refugees, some 800,000, were
unceremoniously dumped out of railroad cars into the mud on the
borders of neighboring Macedonia and Albania understood there was
going to be a real problem trying to reconcile Serbs and Albanians
after that,'' said special White House envoy Christopher Hill, who
oversees Balkan matters for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we've got a lot further to go with Kosovo,'' said
Hill, who has spent most of the past decade working on U.S. policy
in Kosovo, Bosnia, Croatia and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you deal with these problems in the Balkans, I mean, it's
like you're pounding some warped floorboards,'' Hill said. ``You
get one down and another one pops up somewhere, so you've got to
work with that one.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
