<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV12-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., DEC. 12, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am refinishing some tables and other furniture with a
clear, high gloss varnish and I have trouble with small ``misses''
on large flat surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   I try to work carefully as I apply several coats of the clear
varnish, sanding lightly between coats. But it is very hard to tell
if I have accidentally skipped a small spot _ until after the
varnish dries. Then I have to do that surface over again.
</P>
<P>
   Any suggestion as to how this can be avoided on future jobs?
</P>
<P>
   A: One way to spot such misses or skips while the varnish is
still wet is to shine a bright light across the surface from a low
angle as shown here. Then look over the surface carefully from the
opposite direction, also from a low angle.
</P>
<P>
   The wet varnish will look shiny and reflect the light _ but any
missed or dry spots that have not been coated will show up as dull
areas that are clearly visible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently noticed mildew on the vinyl wallpaper in my
bathroom. This was an expensive vinyl, so I would like to clean it,
rather than replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any product I can use to clean this wallpaper without
damaging it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since you have a vinyl wallcovering, rather than a regular
wallpaper, you should be able to scrub it without harm. However,
some of these materials are more resistant to scrubbing than
others, so you should test in a small area first.
</P>
<P>
   There are mildew removing solutions sold in most home centers,
or you can use a solution of one part liquid laundry bleach mixed
with five parts water. If the stains are really mildew this should
remove them without need for scrubbing.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the mildew remover may also affect the
colors in some cases, so test each product first on a scrap piece
of the same material before using it on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We use a roller when painting walls and ceilings with latex
paint, but we find that washing all the paint out of the roller
cover is always difficult.
</P>
<P>
   We prefer a top quality roller cover because this gives us a
smoother job, so we don't want to throw the cover away after each
use. However, getting it thoroughly clean it is a real problem.
</P>
<P>
   What suggestions can you offer?
</P>
<P>
   A: Start by squeezing most of the paint out of the roller with
your fingers (wear a disposable plastic glove if you wish).
</P>
<P>
   Then roll the cover repeatedly over a stack of old newspapers,
discarding the top sheet as soon as it becomes saturated with
paint.
</P>
<P>
   When no more paint comes out slide the cover off and wash it in
soap and water. Rinse with lots of clean water.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The fabric-like wallpaper in my kitchen is pulling away from
the wall along the seams in several places.
</P>
<P>
   I tried fixing it with ordinary wallpaper paste, but this
doesn't seem to hold for long.
</P>
<P>
   Can you tell me what else I can do?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your best bet is to use one of the ready mixed vinyl
adhesives that are sold for use in hanging vinyl wallcoverings.
</P>
<P>
   There are special seam-sealers that come in small squeeze tubes
and are specifically formulated for use on seams that have pulled
loose.
</P>
<P>
   If the old wallcovering is stiff and doesn't bend easily when
you try to lay it flat, wet the back of the fabric down with water
first.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING LIGHT TO FIND AREAS YOU MISSED
WHEN APPLYING VARNISH'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: A bright light shining across the surface from a low
angle will clearly show up any dull, missed areas in the finish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
