NYT-11-22-99 1814EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8158 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WILDER-ESTATE-790&AMP;ADD     11-22 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDER-ESTATE-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE LIBRARY ON THE OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (lb) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Laura Ingalls Wilder Library was named after the favorite
daughter of Mansfield, Mo., who wore her best velvet dress to the
dedication ceremony in 1951. But today the little library, about a
half-block from the town square, looks forlorn. The roof leaks.
Foam insulation is taped to the windows of the concrete building to
keep out the frost. Library employees shiver in their coats through
the icy Ozark winters.
</P>
<P>
   Now the library is turning to the courts, and the will of
Wilder, its hometown author, in hopes of bringing in a rare source
of income that could be used for repairs and enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   The last wishes of Wilder, who wrote the ``Little House'' book
series, are among the issues at the heart of a simmering federal
court battle, with the library claiming that it has been cheated of
the income from the author's lucrative literary estate. By one
estimate at least $100 million could be at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The library is encountering stiff resistance from the publisher
HarperCollins and from the heir of Roger Lea MacBride, whose
lawyers said Wilder's daughter bequeathed rights to him. Court
papers filed by MacBride's estate said that the daughter, Rose
Wilder Lane, properly bequeathed certain copyrights, like renewals,
to MacBride.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the library contend in a suit filed in U.S. District
Court in Springfield, Mo., that the intent of Wilder's 1952 will
was thwarted by her daughter, who died in 1968 with no children or
surviving husband.
</P>
<P>
   They say the will stipulates that the library receive all
royalties from Wilder's 11 copyrighted works after her daughter's
death. MacBride, who died in 1995 and was a longtime friend of
Lane, augmented the ``Little House'' series with his own works and
helped create the popular television series based on the ``Little
House'' books.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers the library maintains that MacBride
``successfully perpetuated the myth of his relationship'' as Lane's
adopted grandson and the guardian of Wilder's estate.
</P>
<P>
   After Lane died, MacBride gained control of Wilder's estate by
transferring and renewing expiring copyrights in his name and
applying for new copyrights for Wilder's unpublished books, the
library asserts in its complaint.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday lawyers for the defendants fought back in court.
They asked the judge to toss out the case, saying that the
library's claims were unfounded and that the renewal rights were
handled properly. They also say that under a three-year statute of
limitations the library waited too long to bring its case.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for HarperCollins said the library should have acted
after receiving its one and only royalty check, for $28,011.05,
from Wilder's publisher in 1972. The library's complaint leaves it
to the judge whether a distinction should be drawn between the
books that were published before Wilder's death and the books,
adaptations and spinoffs produced after she died.
</P>
<P>
   The library asked the judge, Ortrie Smith, to determine what the
Wilder estate is worth. It is seeking unspecified damages from
MacBride's estate; from his daughter, Abigail MacBride Allen of
Virginia; and from HarperCollins, publisher of the ``Little House''
series.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder's writings fueled an immense empire that included the hit
television series ``Little House on the Prairie,'' starring Michael
Landon and Melissa Gilbert, which ran from 1974 to 1983 on NBC and
was seen in more than 100 countries.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a vast array of products, including cookbooks,
friendship bracelets and calendars _ merchandise that the lawsuit
said was described by a HarperCollins senior editor as ``our best
property.'' Two years ago Universal Studios acquired the rights to
make a movie based on the ``Little House'' books, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute arose in the spring when library volunteers in
Mansfield, a dairy-farming community of 1,400 in the southern part
of the state, were preparing to apply for grants to pay for
improvements at the Wright County system's three branch libraries
and asked Harold Glass, its lawyer, to review Wilder's will.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Cline, the director of the library system, said that
until then people assumed that the library had gotten its fair
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if they discovered that they had the rights to an
unpublished Shakespeare play; it's that valuable,'' said Stan
Soocher, an entertainment lawyer who is editor in chief of the
Entertainment Law and Finance newsletter, based in New York. He
calculated that Wilder's estate is worth at least $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder died in 1957, but she remains a strong, abiding presence.
Her home, which is a museum in Mansfield, receives about 50,000
visitors a year from around the world.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wilder was born in 1867 into a farm family in rural Wisconsin
that traveled and endured hardships throughout the Midwest. After
she married Almanzo Wilder and gave birth to Rose, they traveled by
covered wagon to Mansfield in 1894.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Wilder became a renowned children's author, her
daughter had made a name for herself as a journalist. Wilder, in
fact, was encouraged by her daughter to begin writing books based
on her hardscrabble frontier childhood. Wilder was 65 in 1932 when
her first book, ``Little House in the Big Woods,'' was published.
</P>
<P>
   After Wilder's daughter died at age 81 in Connecticut, MacBride
took over the management of the Wilder oeuvre. Starting in 1969 he
began renewing copyrights of Wilder's books and applying for new
ones for her unpublished books in the names of MacBride and his
lawyers, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also alleges that MacBride used an unspecified amount
of money from the royalties of Wilder's books to finance his failed
presidential bid as the Libertarian candidate in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Lane was an adherent of the laissez-faire objectivist philosophy
of the novelist Ayn Rand and had adopted MacBride as a political
disciple.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rothstein, a law professor at Georgetown University, said
the case may be settled, because it is so ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   The library has a stronger claim to revenues from books
published before Wilder's death, he said, but the entire matter is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be close,'' Rothstein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
