<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCHULZ-HEALTH-NYTR &LR;      11-22 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHULZ-HEALTH-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTPOURING OF CONCERN FOR CHARLES SCHULZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GEORGE LAUER   
 Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Just as Charlie Brown counts on his
``Peanuts'' cohorts for help in his numerous encounters with
misfortune, Charles Schulz is reaping the support of community and
colleagues after being diagnosed with colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're incredibly saddened, but I also know Sparky has a lot of
fight in him,'' said David Wiley Miller, creator of the cartoon
``Non Sequitur'' and longtime of Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know what to do or say in situations like this,''
he said. ``You feel so damn helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family are rallying around Schulz, hoping he'll
bounce back, just as his alter ego, Charlie Brown, has for the past
50 years.
</P>
<P>
   After emergency surgery last week, Schulz, who turns 77 on
Friday, is up and walking at Santa Rosa Memorial Hospital. His
prognosis has not been made public.
</P>
<P>
   Mollie Boice, an actress and another longtime friend, said
Schulz is a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a veteran,'' Boice said. ``I know he fought in the Second
World War. Hopefully, he'll be fighting now.''
</P>
<P>
   Boice said Schulz has a wide spectrum of people pulling for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who just really love him _ a lot of
very different people. Sparky is very eclectic in the people he
likes and connects with _ doctors, veterinarians, people who sell
furniture. Anybody who piqued his interest.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next several weeks, new adventures of Charlie Brown and
``Peanuts'' will continue to appear in 2,600 newspapers around the
world. Schulz, like many daily cartoonists, works weeks in advance.
But beyond that, the cartoon's future is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be a good time for him to retire,'' said Miller.
``He took his first vacation in years this year and papers ran old
strips. He hated it, I know, but maybe now is the time to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no replacing Sparky in the cartoon world,''
Miller said. ``You don't replace a Mozart. You don't replace a
Michelangelo, but you have to realize that everything has to end.
`Peanuts' will be gone someday but his impact on the art form will
never go away. His work was too important. He broke a lot of
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz, nicknamed Sparky, was moved out of Memorial's
intensive-care unit Friday and has been visiting with his wife and
five children. The family is continuing to ask that Schulz have no
other visitors.
</P>
<P>
   He underwent surgery last Tuesday to clear a blockage of the
abdominal aorta, which carries blood from the heart to the lower
body, his wife, Jean, has said.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz settled in Santa Rosa, which is about 50 miles north of
San Francisco, more than 40 years ago. He is an athletic man who
plays ice hockey, tennis and golf. He last endured a serious health
crisis in 1981 when he underwent quadruple heart bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to his drawing board not long after. His daily
routine for decades has been to start the day at his reserved table
in the cafe at Snoopy's Redwood Empire Ice Arena, which he had
built in 1969, and then walk to his nearby studio and resume
drawing the world's most popular comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   He had worked half a day last Tuesday when he lay down on a
couch, telling employees that he didn't feel good and his legs
hurt. He was rushed by ambulance to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer that surgeons discovered is a type that occurs 90
percent of the time in people older than 50, according to the
Cancer Resource Center.
</P>
<P>
   Although colon cancer is the second-leading cause of
cancer-related deaths in the nation, survival rates have risen over
the past two decades because treatments have improved and a higher
percentage of cases have been detected early.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat of Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1816EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
