<HEADLINE>
PRINT ARTIST SUITE PACKS NEW FEATURES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After writing for so many years about computer programs, I've
almost ceased to be amazed about software.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's surprising how much software publishers can cram
into a box when it comes to desktop publishing programs.
</P>
<P>
   Print Artist Grande Suite 8.0 is an example (Windows; about $60
to $70). The previous version from SierraHome was the top-selling
home-publishing program in 1998 according to PC Data. The new
version has a sophisticated Web-page design program, more than
200,000 graphics and images, and photo shop for manipulating
pictures, a wide selection of animated electronic cards for
e-mailing and an overhauled user interface.
</P>
<P>
   The program can turn out Web pages, cards, crafts, posters,
newsletters, stickers, labels, stationery, business cards,
letterhead, digital albums and Web slide shows.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 10,000 layouts designed by professionals for
the aforementioned projects. Moreover, new users get more help from
a guide that walks them through the process of using the program.
</P>
<P>
   An unlimited number of documents can be opened at one time. It's
a nice feature, but beyond having two or three documents open at
once, one that most users will never need to experience. But it's
easy to drag and drop objects between open documents _ a feature
that makes the program easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right picture to use from the program's 200,000 is
easy enough using a graphics grabber that searches for keywords.
Thumbnail pictures are also available.
</P>
<P>
   SnapShot Express is a sophisticated tool for working with
graphics and has the ability to clean up pictures (cropping,
removing red eyes and other features) and manipulate them.
</P>
<P>
   A step-by-step tutorial gives an overview of the program's ``Web
Studio Express'' for designing Web pages. It, too, contains
professionally designed templates, animations, backgrounds and
other useful tools. One of those tools is ``iCollect,'' which can
pull graphics or entire Web pages off the Internet for use later.
</P>
<P>
   If you need less power at a lower price, Print Artist Gold 8.0
and Print Artist Platinum 8.0 are also available.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call toll free (800-757-7707) or visit the
company's Web site (www.siearrahome.com).
</P>
<P>
   SUPER DUPER ARCADE
</P>
<P>
   Pajama Sam, Freddi Fish, SPY Fox and Putt-Putt are comic
characters from Humongous Entertainment computer games. They're all
on one CD with the collection of Humongous' Super Duper Arcade I
and II.
</P>
<P>
   Each CD has four arcade games and will run on either Windows or
Macintosh computers. Each game has hundreds of levels. Each CD
should be available for about $15 to $19.
</P>
<P>
   Super Duper Arcade I contains Putt-Putt and Pep's
Balloon-O-Rama, Pajama Sam's Sock Works, Freddi Fish and Luther's
Water Worries, and SPY Fox in Cheese Chase. Super Duper Arcade II
has Putt-Putt and Pep's Dog on a Stick, Pajama Sam's Lost and
Found, Freddi Fish and Luther's Maze Madness. All seven of those
titles are previously released. The fourth game on Arcade II is SPY
Fox in ``Hold the Mustard,'' a new release in which SPY Fox hurries
to save the world's supply of ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the games have game editors so kids can create and swap
new levels. For younger children, the ``Junior Helper'' feature
found in some of the games slows down the action to give younger
players a better chance.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
