<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PROFILE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE REVAMPS HIS STYLE, NOT HIS SUBSTANCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Bill Clinton picked Al Gore as his running
mate seven years ago, the future vice president's father found it
the most natural thing in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was raised for it,'' proclaimed Albert A. Gore Sr., a wily
Tennessee populist who had preceded his son in the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Although the comment's whiff of noblesse oblige grated against
the down-home, ``feel your pain'' earnestness of Clinton's New
Democrats, it seemed a fair assessment of a young man who grew up
in the shadow of Washington power, was educated at the best schools
and had launched a solid political career of his own that already
included an unsuccessful but not embarrassing presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the vice presidency of Al Gore has been marked by
a long, substantive agenda _ with a foreign portfolio that includes
a major piece of the U.S.-Russia account and a domestic
things-to-do list so extensive that one project was grandiosely
labeled ``reinventing government.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has repaid Clinton with unfailing loyalty, with the
exception of a few public chastisements about the president's
offstage sexual antics. On the day of the House impeachment vote
last December, Gore stood at Clinton's side and hailed him as ``a
man who I believe will be regarded in the history books as one of
our greatest presidents.'' He repeated the assessment earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as Gore seeks the White House himself, he seems weighed
down by his Washington upbringing, his mannered style, his
allegiance to the morally challenged Clinton and even by his
current job as vice president _ historically one of the surest ways
in U.S. history not to get directly to the top job.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's problem was bad enough when national polls consistently
showed him lagging behind the front-runner for the Republican
nomination, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. Gore's plight has been
exacerbated by the increasing draw of his only challenger for the
Democratic nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore has fought to reinvigorate his campaign, it has become a
jerry-built attempt to escape his background of political
privilege, his reputation as an uptight maven of policy esoterica
and his recent past as a Clinton subordinate. It is even an attempt
to overcome what one campaign adviser, feminist author Naomi Wolf,
sees as Gore's subservient ``beta male'' personality.
</P>
<P>
   Substantively, this alteration-in-progress is a tall, tricky
order for a serious aficionado of the intricacies of nuclear
philosophy and the author of a controversial environmental tome
ominously titled ``Earth in the Balance.'' Stylistically, it is
also far from a sure thing for a politician so formal in mien that
this joke arose in his 1988 presidential campaign: Question: How do
you tell Al Gore from his Secret Service agents? Answer: He's the
stiff one.
</P>
<P>
   But over the last few months, even as Gore has remained true to
his market-tested, top-drawer electoral issues of education, health
care and gun control, he has undertaken an almost frenzied
makeover, changing his stump speech, his approach to voters and
even his wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, by turns, can now be aggressive or warm and empathetic. He
bounded in to the macho environs of an AFL-CIO convention with
high-fives for delegates. He took charge of the pregame show for
his first major joint appearance with Bradley, signaling that he
was ready for the questions whether his opponent was or not. Gore
solicitously asks audience members their first names and about
their lives, then tosses the personal tidbits smoothly into his
answers.
</P>
<P>
   He has taken occasionally to three-button suits in earth tones
and French-blue shirts. An intense exercise program has accentuated
his angular, 51-year-old good looks.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a bit of a bodybuilder swagger, perhaps a twin
product of Wolf's admonitions to be more assertive and his daily
encounters with an ab cruncher. On a recent transcontinental
flight, Gore conducted a string of interviews in his workout get-up
of purple T-shirt, greenish shorts and flip-flops.
</P>
<P>
   The differences, however, are not all physical or superficial.
</P>
<P>
   Often in campaign appearances, before addressing his core issues
or the audience's questions, Gore has begun to talk about his
mother's childhood of poverty in western Tennessee and her struggle
to obtain a law degree. He relates his father's ``great courage''
in early opposition to the poll tax, segregation and the Vietnam
War _ which figured in Gore Sr.'s defeat in 1970. The vice
president talks of the deep disillusionment he felt on returning 30
years ago, even as a noncombat veteran, from ``the dark tunnel'' of
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I connecting?'' Gore seems to implore as he walks audiences
through the emotional perils of growing to manhood in the 1960s and
1970s. To illustrate his heightened sense of disgust three decades
ago, he can even work in the easily demonized Richard Nixon and
Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that made me feel like I didn't want to have anything to
do with politics,'' Gore says in one well-rehearsed segment of his
revamped stump speech. ``I thought it would be the absolutely last
thing I ever did in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   A few segues later, though, he is hitting on voters to elect him
to the highest office in the land and at least by implication
citing his 12 years in the House, seven years in the Senate and
seven years at Clinton's side as his best qualification.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has convinced himself that he feels good _ and genuine _
about his new style and approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about tactics,'' Gore insisted in his office aboard
the Boeing 757 that currently functions as Air Force Two. ``I am
who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore may have shed his conservative suit, but he is still clad
in the caution that seems to mark almost his every utterance, even
the attempts at self-deprecatory humor. Someone has called it the
``vice presidential pause,'' the split second in which throughout
his years as the nation's second banana Gore has forced himself to
consider how each word will reflect on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But now he's considering how it reflects on him personally and
on his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running for president of this country is far more important
than being the best vice president I can possibly be,'' Gore told
reporters on a recent swing through early-voting Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is a full-time candidate, still making a few ``official''
appearances, although almost all of them have the campaign squarely
in mind. He has trimmed back contacts with Clinton and his White
House; regular weekly luncheons with the president are a thing of
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am communicating with people about what motivates me at the
same time that I communicate with them about my agenda for the
future,'' Gore contends. ``And it's not a question of what works
(politically), it's a question of what's real.''
</P>
<P>
   But just months ago _ before the rise of Bradley _ Gore was
working with what he saw as a different reality. He had ensured
there would be no challenge for the Democratic nomination from the
usual suspects _ especially House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt,
D-Mo., a feared rival from the 1988 presidential race _ and focused
on what he thought would be a months-long campaign against
Republican Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Until late summer, Gore refused to mention Bradley by name.
Suddenly, he wanted to debate the guy every week.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has convinced himself _ at least in comments for public
consumption _ that a standoff for the Democratic nomination is
laudable and was foreordained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome a close, hard-fought race,'' Gore said. ``I think
it's good for the party, good for the country. I think in some ways
it was inevitable that if the race became a two-person race and if
Senator Bradley crossed the threshold of credibility then it would
inevitably tighten. I welcome it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is no slouch at making a virtue of a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   He will not even concede that he feels put upon to do the
inner-feelings shtick that has become such a significant part of
his basic campaign appeal _ an example of the exploration of a
candidate's psyche that columnist Charles Krauthammer calls ``part
of the trivialization of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people want to know what you're made of and where
you're coming from,'' Gore said. ``What's in your heart, not only
what's in your head.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's a bad thing,'' he adds, without remarking
on why only recently has he made the personal exploration a key
part of his campaign kit. ``I think those questions are in many
ways more relevant than some of the more cerebral questions that
supposedly were focused on in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   At heart, Gore is a traditional center-left Democrat who one day
last month claimed the endorsement of the AFL-CIO, the party's
strongest link to its working-class foundations, and appeared the
next day before the Democratic Leadership Council, a
business-backed amalgam of party leaders who got tired of losing
the White House with such unabashedly liberal candidates as former
Vice President Walter Mondale and former Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney hailed Gore for standing
``shoulder to shoulder with working men and women and our union in
fighting off the attacks of a radical Congress.'' Gore responded
with a pledge to veto anti-union legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The DLC chairman, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, could be
equally lavish in his praise for the vice president, asserting:
``Al Gore is ready to keep America changing in the right
direction.'' Gore responded with a political play on words, noting
that the Democratic Party, like the championship University of
Connecticut basketball team, ``should always have a strong
center.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats can also express their concern about Gore as a
national standard-bearer, even as they tout his ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say he's not flashy enough,'' said Rep. Ed Pastor,
D-Ariz., as he introduced Gore at a fund-raising event in Phoenix.
``But I'll tell you this, he's good.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also tireless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to shake every single hand here,'' Gore told about
200 folks at Fairgrounds Junior High School in Nashua, N.H., one
night last month. And he almost did, at the end of a two-hour
session in which the vice president answered dozens of question
from an audience of undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke to their personal problems and worries _ the need for
election materials in Braille, Social Security reform, prescription
drug costs, even the isolated foreign policy inquiry _ as well as
addressing local tragedies such as the murder of a young woman by
an Internet stalker. Gore had already talked by telephone to the
dead woman's father.
</P>
<P>
   Whether asked or not, Gore slipped in his position favoring
nuclear weapons control, his opposition to much of offshore
drilling, his proposals for additional gun control, use of light
rail to curb urban sprawl, campaign finance limits, reform but not
elimination of estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The evening was a tour de force for a politician whose manner
supposedly gives trees a bad name. After a subsequent Gore ``town
hall'' session in New Hampshire, a local reporter wrote that the
vice president was ``as warm and fuzzy as the sweaters he now
wears'' to meet voters. Earlier in the year, she wrote, Gore in a
similar setting was ``as wooden as the stool he sat on.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and supporters claim the candidate's most recent
incarnation _ caring and communicative _ is the genuine article,
and that the earlier formality had been dictated by his No. 2 role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to tell all our neighbors, friends and family about
the real Al Gore,'' Washington Gov. Gary Locke exhorted a Seattle
fund-raising dinner last month. One touching testimonial came from
Jim Frush, a lawyer-mountaineer who led Gore and son Albert Gore
III up Mount Rainier last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is not a quitter,'' Frush said of Gore's climb.
``This man was our sparkplug. ... This is a man of fortitude,
courage and physical endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Gore's campaign is to mass-market the sense of
security, ease and respect that people like Frush _ as well as many
voters _ feel after spending time with the vice president in small
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so impressed with his ability to think,'' said Dana
Rogers after Gore addressed parents, teachers and students at an
overcrowded elementary school in Las Vegas. ``I'm a registered
Republican,'' said Rogers, Miss Texas 1984 and now star of
``Jubilee'' at Bally's Hotel and Casino, ``but some of the things
he said today struck a chord with me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of Gore's evening with voters in Nashua, N.H.,
Jay Hether, who works for a military supplier, was aghast at the
difference between the Gore he expected and the Gore he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more passionate than I thought he'd be,'' Hether said.
</P>
<P>
   And more importantly for the campaign ahead, Hether could begin
to see Gore as a politician distinct from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the shadows,'' Hether said, ``but he stepped out.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about time.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Harris poll found that by a 2-1 margin (60 percent to
29 percent), voters nationally believe Gore has been hurt by his
association with the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   It's clearly a major political issue and enormous personal
quandary for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   Several longtime Gore associates said they worry about the vice
president's seeming inability to admit that he has ever been wrong
or changed his mind _ on issues big and small. This could be an
important flaw, especially in a candidate who plans to point out
what he believes are flip-flops in Bradley's record.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most startling swings for Gore has come in his stance
on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood by the swimming pool of a Brentwood mansion in Los
Angeles recently, accepting an award from a group of abortion
rights activists, it was amazing to consider that only 12 years
ago, Gore wrote to a Tennessee constituent: ``During my 11 years in
Congress, I have consistently opposed federal funding of abortions.
... In my opinion, it is wrong to spend federal funds for what is
arguably the taking of a human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Gore contends he has never changed his position on the
issue, even though he is now a full-throated advocate of abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore fights tobacco interests, and continues to tell the
story of his sister's death from lung cancer in 1984, he is
sometimes reminded of his hard pitch to North Carolinians in his
1988 presidential campaign, when he said: ``Throughout most of my
life, I raised tobacco. I want you to know that with my own hands,
all of my life, I put it in the plant beds and transferred it. I've
hoed it. I've chopped it. I've shredded it, spiked it, put it in
the barn and stripped it and sold it.''
</P>
<P>
   This ease with the about-face is striking to people who have
examined Gore's life and work, including Bob Zelnick, the former
ABC News correspondent who has written a biography of Gore that his
campaign sees as critical and negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest problem with Gore is ... I believe, a tendency in
him not to acknowledge the possibility of error on an issue he
feels strongly about,'' Zelnick said. Gore views someone who
disagrees with him as not someone to be debated, convinced or even
defeated, ''but as someone who must be discredited, someone who
must be excommunicated, must be driven out from the society of
reasonable people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not yet taken that harsh a tack with Bradley. But for
partisan crowds, Gore argues that he was exemplary _ and Bradley,
by inference, found wanting _ when faced with the ``two most
important defining moments'' for Democrats in the last 20 years _
votes on President Reagan's economic program and the reaction to
the Republican takeover of Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted against. I fought against it,'' Gore says of Reagan's
1991 budget cuts, which Bradley supported. ``Some felt that in
order to survive politically they should vote for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley served a year or so after Republicans took over, then
announced he would not seek re-election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of us was called upon to ... fight against it with
everything we had or not,'' Gore says. ``I didn't walk away from
the fight when Newt Gingrich took over the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   This has inspired a battle cry to which Gore turns now and
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud that even in the hardest hour I never gave up,
never turned back and never walked away,'' Gore declared at an Iowa
Democratic dinner last month, rousing the crowd with an impassioned
plea to ``stay and fight!''
</P>
<P>
   The heated rhetoric, whether the vice president has thought
about it, is not only part of the new, aggressive Gore but also an
echo of his populist roots from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore sorts through his old and new styles he faces another
question: What will he _ or can he _ try next if his latest
political incarnation does not move enough voters to stabilize his
campaign?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
