<HEADER>
A8195 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-WORKPLACE-INJURIES-HN     11-22 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-INJURIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS GROUPS VOW TO FIGHT NEW ANTI-INJURY RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With billions of dollars at stake, business groups
vowed Monday to battle proposed federal regulations that would
force many employers to correct injury-causing workplace conditions
that require repetitive motion, overexertion or awkward posture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business community is going to oppose the standards both
on Capitol Hill and in the courts,'' said Randel Johnson, vice
president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which represents more
than 3 million businesses and organizations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the Labor Department formally announced the
proposed rules _ which would affect about one of every three, or
1.9 million, work sites _ saying the regulations are needed to
protect more than 27 million workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees are getting hurt; workers are being sent home;
people are suffering,'' said Charles N. Jeffress, assistant labor
secretary for occupational safety and health.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders applauded the government action. ``It confirms
what workers have known for years _ that these injuries are caused
by workplace hazards and can be prevented,'' AFL-CIO President John
Sweeney said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, 1.8 million workers have injuries related to
so-called ergonomic factors, and 600,000 people miss some work
because of them, according to the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration (OSHA), the Labor Department's agency in charge of
developing and enforcing the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomics is a recent science that involves fitting a job to
the physical limitations of the worker. This is an issue in jobs
where workers might be exposed to too many repetitive motions,
loads that are too heavy, or awkward postures that result in
overexertion of certain muscles.
</P>
<P>
   The musculoskeletal injuries _ those that damage muscles,
nerves, ligaments, tendons and bones _ include such problems as
carpal tunnel syndrome, back pain, tendinitis, rotator cuff
syndrome (in the shoulder) and herniated spinal disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that work-related musculoskeletal disorders ...
are the most prevalent, most expensive and most preventable
workplace injuries in the country, and it is time we do something
about it,'' said Labor Secretary Alexis Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., a senior Democrat on a House
labor-health panel, called the new rules ``a pro-worker proposal
that builds on existing worker compensation protections and will be
particularly welcomed bu women.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said women are disproportionately affected by ergonomic
injuries, suffering 63 percent of repetitive-motion injuries and
making up 69 percent of lost-work cases from carpal tunnel syndrome
although they are 46 percent of the workforce and 33 percent of
injured workers generally.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules would cover a broad range of workers including
nurses' aides who must lift heavy patients, baggage handlers at
airports and people who work at computers or on assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules, a worker who has an ergonomic injury diagnosed
by a doctor would be entitled to have the work environment fixed to
relieve the cause of the problem _ by changing the height of an
assembly line or computer keyboard, for example.
</P>
<P>
   A worker who must be assigned to lighter duty during recovery
from an ergonomic injury would be guaranteed normal pay and
benefits. A worker who must leave the job altogether would be
guaranteed 90 percent pay and full benefits during recovery.
</P>
<P>
   At workplaces with numerous ergonomic injuries, employers would
have to provide medical help and retraining for workers in addition
to treating their physical problems.
</P>
<P>
   The rules would also require all manufacturers and companies
with workers who do manual heavy lifting to provide training to
prevent injury.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules, scheduled to be published in Tuesday's
Federal Register, cannot become final until next November at the
earliest, after a comment period that will include public hearings
in Washington and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA estimated that employers who need to correct problems will
spend an average of $150 a year per work station fixed. The agency
forecast the total cost to be $4.2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson argued that the proposed rules would cost employers
more than $100 billion the first year and tens of billions of
dollars every year afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members will literally have to retool practically every
warehouse, factory and office in America,'' he said. ``That will be
tremendously expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also criticized OSHA for proposing the rules before the
release, expected next summer, of a National Academy of Sciences
study on whether ergonomic problems at work cause injuries. Earlier
this year, the House passed legislation blocking any OSHA action
until the NAS study is completed, but the Senate adjourned before
passing similar legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there simply isn't enough scientific evidence
proving that ergonomic problems at work cause injury,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, businesses are not opposed to protecting
their workers from such injuries. ``We just feel that before we
spend billions of dollars on a problem that we know what causes the
problem and what solutions work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department estimates the new rules could prevent
injury to about 300,000 workers annually and save employers $9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomic injuries currently cost $15 billion to $20 billion a
year for workers' compensation and $30 billion to $40 billion in
other expenses such as medical care, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
