<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Nov. 23 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Iraq on Monday halted exports of
crude oil through the Turkish port of Ceyhan, effectively rejecting
a two-week extension of its oil-for-food program, the United
Nations announced. The move followed a decision by the Security
Council on Friday to extend the oil-for-food program by two weeks
instead of the customary 180 days. Some diplomats interpreted the
extension as putting pressure on the five permanent members of the
council to wrap up negotiations on a new comprehensive resolution
on Iraqi sanctions. (Summary from wires.) By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   NY-REMEDIAL-EDUC (New York) _ The New York state Board of
Regents on Monday cleared the way for the City University of New
York to begin to exclude students who cannot demonstrate that they
are ready to begin ``college level work'' in both mathematics and
English. In making the most fundamental change in standards since
open admissions was instituted nearly three decades ago, the
Regents expressed their wariness by setting certain conditions on
CUNY's policy. One compromise called for a 12 month delay until
September 2001 for the starting date at City College and Lehman
College, the colleges whose overwhelmingly minority populations
would be most affected by the new policy. CUNY will be allowed to
begin to enforce the policy at four of its senior college campuses
in January. By Karen Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TOBACCO-MONEY (Albany) _ Just as the states are about to take
in a torrent of money from their settlement with tobacco companies,
New York's top lawmakers are moving toward a consensus that most _
if not all _ of the state's share should be spent on health-related
purposes. By Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-RACE (Washington) _ Exclusive. A look at racial
attitudes in the military. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   ABUSE-WOMEN (Boston) _ Defenders of battered women long
struggled to persuade authorities to crack down on brutal men who
reigned by the fist at home, and in recent years have largely won.
But as laws and police have gotten more aggressive, they have
produced a startling side effect: In spots around the country, as
much as one quarter or more of arrests for domestic assault are not
of men but women. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-NH (Manchester, N.H.) _ In unusually blunt language,
Bill Bradley attacked his Democratic rival on Monday with a variety
of charges. He criticized Al Gore over his use of official
governmental events to help his campaign and for failing to take up
the cause of campaign finance reform. Bradley's comments seem to
signal a shift in his campaign tactics. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-INDICT (Newark, N.J.) _ Federal prosecutors today filed
charges against the IBF and requested a court-appointed monitor for
the professional boxing sanctioning group, claiming it is corrupt.
The civil racketeering lawsuit against one of boxing's governing
organizations came nearly three weeks after prosecutors indicted
IBF president Robert W. Lee Sr. on criminal bribery charges.
(Summary from wires.) By Ronald Smothers.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-ART-EXHIBIT (Detroit) _ The new director of the Detroit
Institute of Arts cancels an exhibit that had been planned for two
years, one including displays of artwork combining religious and
sexual themes. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-CORRUPTION (Kano, Nigeria) _ After Friday Prayers,
townsfolk say, Maryam Abacha, the widow of the dictator who ruled
and looted this country for five years, has begun opening the gates
of the family compound to the city's poor, who fill her courtyard
to receive free bags of rice, millet and sorghum. The practice is
regarded here as a crude attempt to burnish the image of the
Abachas, who have become the poster-family of an unexpected and
ambitious drive by the county's new president, Olusegun Obasanjo,
to root out corruption. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
