<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ensor, Once Unloved, Gets a Retrospective
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian painter James Ensor (1860-1949) may have been the
ultimate misunderstood artist. Disliked by the critics and rebuffed
by his peers early in his career, Ensor attempted to sell the
entire contents of his art studio in 1893 for a mere 8,500 Belgian
francs, then the equivalent of around $300 _ and failed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Ensor is now considered to be a precursor of German
Expressionism, among other movements, public recognition _ and a
Belgian barony _ came late in his life. Through Feb. 13, the Royal
Museums of Fine Arts of Belgium in Brussels is presenting its first
retrospective of Ensor's career to mark the 50th anniversary of his
death. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a three-year student sojourn at the Academy of Fine
Arts in Brussels, Ensor lived and worked exclusively in the coastal
town of Ostende. Much of his macabre and hallucinogenic
iconography, featuring bloated tourists and masked carnival
figures, is derived from childhood images of his parents' seaside
souvenir stand.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition groups 370 paintings, etchings and drawings with
a special emphasis placed on works created before 1900, when Ensor
was struggling to establish his singular vision. Although one of
Ensor's most monumental masterworks, titled ``Christ's Entry Into
Brussels in 1889,'' is not on loan from the Getty Museum, the
comprehensive Brussels show includes a rare 1898 print of the
painting, six drawings of ``The Halos of Christ,'' and several
preliminary sketches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Museums of Fine Arts, 3, rue de la Regence, 1000 Brussels.
Information: (32-2) 508-3333. Open Tuesday to Sunday 10 a.m. to 5
p.m.; Thursday until 9 p.m. Admission is about $9.20, based on 38
Belgian francs to the dollar. Tickets can be bought in the United
States from Global Tickets, (914) 328-2150, for $10 ($12 for
Thursday visits).
</P>
<P>
   Corinne LaBalme
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic Puts Atlas Online
</P>
<P>
   With its newly published seventh edition of the Atlas of the
World, the National Geographic Society not only puts the whole
world in your hands but also allows you to keep up with it.
</P>
<P>
   A new interactive atlas, available on the Web at
www.nationalgeographic.com/mapmachine, will record the latest
geographical and political changes so that users can download maps
and paste them into their atlases. This feature will be available
by the end of the month, according to Allen Carroll, the society's
chief cartographer.
</P>
<P>
   As of mid-November, there were two changes: the Black Canyon of
the Gunnison in Colorado, formerly a national monument, was
expanded and became a national park, and the height of Mount
Everest was increased from 29,028 to 29,035 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh edition, published this month, is a complete
reworking of the sixth edition, which was first published in 1990
and subsequently revised.
</P>
<P>
   It takes account of such major changes as the renaming of Zaire
(now the Democratic Republic of Congo), the creation of the Nunavut
Territory in Canada and the redrawing of provincial boundaries in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, the atlas, which sells for $125, roams beyond
the strictly cartographic, with articles on such subjects as
climate, economy, tectonics, cultures and energy. All told, there
are 280 pages of maps and text plus a 134-page index with 140,000
entries.
</P>
<P>
   Those who prefer more rather than less will be cheered to know
that the Web site has two million entries. Some are variations on
place names (separate entries for Florence and Firenze, for
example); others are place names that that simply could not be
included even in a large-format atlas.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Juneau Votes to Charge Cruise Passenger Fees &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Juneau, Alaska, last month approved by a 5-to-2 ratio
an initiative to charge each cruise ship passenger $5 for visiting
their city. The result came three months after a guilty plea by the
Royal Caribbean International cruise line to charges of dumping
pollutants into Alaskan waters. A similar measure failed three
years ago, Mayor Dennis W. Egan said.
</P>
<P>
   Egan said that despite apologies to three southeastern Alaska
cities by the president of Royal Caribbean, the residents remained
outraged. The line, which agreed in court to pay $18 million in
fines, pleaded guilty to polluting coastal waters around the United
States; this included dumping dry-cleaning chemicals and other
toxic wastes into a channel within the Juneau city limits and
dumping oily bilge water into a canal between Skagway and Haines.
</P>
<P>
   The convention and visitors bureau in Juneau, the state capital,
estimates that nearly 600,000 cruise passengers visited the city in
the 1999 season _ May through September _ and that they accounted
for most of the $90 million in economic activity generated by
tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Although many Caribbean islands levy port charges on ships based
on passenger totals, cruise lines operating in Alaska may challenge
the user fee on the basis that it is too narrow: visitors arriving
by plane or car are not similarly surcharged.
</P>
<P>
   John Hansen, president of the North West CruiseShip Association,
based in Vancouver, British Columbia, said that the group would
examine its constitutionality. ``There may be some legal issues
with a narrow, targeted fee,'' Hansen said. ``On another level,
what is the money going to be used for: dock development, tourism
improvements or just for the city's operating budget?''
</P>
<P>
   Egan said that a regulation, to be effective March 1, was being
written on the basis of the referendum. He said that the income
would be spent on infrastructure improvements related to the cruise
industry, possibly including landscaping.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mount Vernon to Mourn Washington Again
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 18, on the 200th anniversary of George Washington's
funeral, visitors to Mount Vernon will see a re-creation of the
services, the last of many events commemorating the bicentennial of
Washington's death at Mount Vernon on Dec. 14, 1799. More than 250
people, including descendants of original mourners, will dress in
18th-century mourning attire for the re-enactment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The event will begin at 10:30 a.m. with readings of contemporary
tributes accompanied by period music. At 11 a.m., the funeral
procession will start, with 12 people portraying the principal
mourners. They will be accompanied by Colonial soldiers with arms
reversed, the gun barrels pointed downward (an 18th-century custom
at military funerals), a militia band playing dirges, four
clergymen and a riderless gray horse with replicas of Washington's
saddle, holsters and pistols.
</P>
<P>
   Participants will carry a replica of his coffin, and visitors
will be able to follow the procession to the original family vault,
where they will witness the re-enactment of Episcopalian and
Masonic services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Dec. 14 through 18, Mount Vernon will be in mourning.
Historic interpretation for these days will feature information
about Washington's death, funeral preparations and the effect of
his death on the nation. The replica coffin will be on view in the
large dining room Dec. 17 and 18. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mount Vernon, 16 miles south of Washington, D.C., is open daily,
including Christmas Day. Admission: $8, $7.50 for those 62 and
above and $4 for ages 6 to 11. Information: (703) 780-2000, or on
the Internet at www.mountvernon.org and www.gwashington1999.org.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine House
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
