<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BULGARIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES SERBIA TO END DICTATORSHIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria _ Standing in the historic Nevski Square teeming
with enthusiastic Bulgarians, President Clinton on Monday called on
Serbia to follow the path of this former Communist stronghold and
cast aside its dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered encouragement to this new democracy, still
struggling to turn its freedoms into economic wealth, and
acknowledged the difficulties it faced during and after the
U.S.-led bombing campaign against neighboring Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The president's 10-day trip through Europe's troubled southeast
ends Tuesday with a stop in Kosovo, where he will urge the ethnic
Albanian Kosovars to stop their reprisals against Serbs and work
toward reconstruction of the war-torn province.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of flag-waving Bulgarians pressed into the square to
see the first U.S. president to visit their country. The warm
welcome was in contrast to the violence that marred his visit to
Greece, where many people also opposed the West's bombardment of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But the message was as much for Serbians as for Bulgarians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am told that during the recent war you could actually hear
some of the bombs falling in Serbia from this square. Tonight, I
hope the people of Serbia can hear our voices when we say, if you
choose as Bulgaria has chosen, you will regain the rightful place
in Europe that Mr. (Slobodan) Milosevic has stolen from you and
America will support you, too,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-led campaign sent war jets and missiles over Bulgarian
territory. An errant NATO bomb even landed in the Sofia suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must give all the people in this region a unifying magnet
that is stronger than the pull of old hatreds that has threatened
to tear them apart over and over again. Your neighbor, Serbia,
should be part of that bright and different future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president again stated his support for the expansion of the
European Union into this region and for the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization to keep its ``doors open to those democratic nations
here who are able to meet their obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Clinton voiced support for EU and NATO membership to
President Petar Soyanov and Prime Minister Ivan Kostov.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to supporting Bulgaria over the long run _
economically, politically, militarily,'' Clinton said before a
session with Soyanov.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 years since the fall of the Berlin Wall and the demise
of the Soviet Union, several former Warsaw Pact powers continue to
struggle economically. Democracy has yet to translate into
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Western Europe's sanctions against Yugoslavia and Iraq have hurt
Bulgaria's economy, which already was struggling after the collapse
of Communism. A new centrist government brought the nation's
hyperinflation rate to 1 percent in 1998 compared to more than 500
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria also is battling organized crime and its reputation as
an arms merchant to rebels and insurgents around the world. The
government has initiated several reforms. The White House announced
the Overseas Private Investment Corp. will start a new $150 million
Southeast Europe Investment Fund with pledges from other sources
and will extend a $200 million line of credit to the southeast
Europe region.
</P>
<P>
   Stoyanov encouraged the crowd to stay on the path of democracy.
``We have to go it to the end,'' he said to cheers from the throng.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must keep our courage,'' Stoyanov told the crowd. ``The
people of Eastern Europe should not allow their dreams and hopes
raised by the fall of the Berlin Wall to give away to fatigue and
disillusionment, and the people of Western Europe, on the other
hand, should not allow their enthusiasm after the lifting of the
Iron Curtain to give way to indifference and egoism.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, the president's national security
adviser, said the Kosovo campaign was an important moment for
Bulgaria. The government backed the NATO effort despite opposition
from the people. However, public opinion shifted to the
government's position, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, from the people I've talked to here, this was a very
important watershed for the way Bulgaria thinks about the future,''
Berger said of a nation that was cast into the Soviet Union's
sphere after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Serb opposition leaders view Bulgaria as a model for
a democracy they want for their own homeland.
</P>
<P>
   In a trip already fraught with security concerns, the president
will take his entourage to NATO-controlled Kosovo in defiance of
Milosevic. The United States maintains Kosovo remains a province of
Serbia and has refused to support the independence wanted by
Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will visit on Tuesday with some of the 6,000 U.S. troops
stationed as part of the peacekeeping force. The president will
skip a planned stop in Macedonia and fly directly to Pristina. He
also will meet with Kosovo and NATO leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a difficult winter, but it will be a hell of a
lot better than last winter when the Kosovars were being killed,
raped and driven from their homes,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hill, the national security council's expert on southeast
Europe, said a recent conference between the United States and
European nations netted $1 billion in pledges, including $158
million from the United States, for a United Nations operation to
rebuild the civic institutions there.
</P>
<P>
   The president also has visited Turkey, Greece and Italy during
his journey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
