<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8206 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     11-22 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACKAGE TRIP VS A LA CARTE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A frequent question to this department is how travel packages
can be offered at prices lower, sometimes, than even the cheapest
air fare to the place involved. Are the hotels terrible? Is the
flight aboard Aero Mysterioso? How do packages work?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is not always obvious.
</P>
<P>
   A travel package commonly involves three components: air travel,
transfers from and to the airport, and hotel room. There may be
more baubles: a half-day city tour, or a free travel bag, or a map
or, perhaps least persuasive, discount coupons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Hotel Monaco in Seattle, a Kimpton boutique hotel, a Wrap
It Up Package includes room, a holiday music CD, two Starbucks
drink coupons and overnight valet parking, plus free gift-wrapping
during a guest reception. The ``package'' really boils down to the
room because the reception is a Kimpton standard. The one-night
package costs $159 to $195, depending on the room; the regular
price is $125 to $180.
</P>
<P>
   I took apart two packages to price the components. Both were
offered under their apparent market value.
</P>
<P>
   The Mirror Lake Inn, an AAA four-diamond resort at Lake Placid,
N.Y., has a ``ski and spa'' package: a room for two for two nights,
breakfast from the restaurant menu, two two-day lift tickets for
nearby Whiteface Mountain and one spa treatment each. The resort
has an indoor pool, hot tubs, saunas and steam rooms, and in
winter, ice skating on Mirror Lake, with evening bonfires.
</P>
<P>
   The package price for two people is $518, plus 7 percent tax and
tips. The package is available from Nov. 28 to Dec. 16, Jan. 4 to
13, and Jan. 18 to Feb. 10, Sundays to Wednesdays only. So it's the
wintertime, excluding holiday weekends.
</P>
<P>
   This inn has 128 rooms, 19 of them suites. Package buyers get
the regular rooms, with views of the lake and Adirondacks beyond.
The cold-call weekday rate in the period is $125 to $150 a night,
single or double. Basing the nonpackage price on the least
expensive room, that puts the two-night pretax rate at $250.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteface Mountain said that two-day lift tickets bought there
will be $84 a person, bringing the cost for two people to $168. The
inn's ``hearty Adirondack breakfasts'' are given an average value
of $11 by the hotel, making that total $44 for two people for two
mornings.
</P>
<P>
   The spa treatment is limited to $110 a person. This might be an
80-minute Swedish massage ($100) or stone therapy ($110). One
treatment each, total $220.
</P>
<P>
   The components add up to $682, meaning that the package price
for two days is cheaper by $164. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Ed Weibrecht Jr., an owner of the inn, said he negotiates a
wholesale price on the lift tickets. But he says he wants people to
sample his resort when there is space for them. ``Eighty percent of
our business is repeat or referral,'' he said in an interview. ``We
don't cut corners on our packages. If you have a great experience,
you come back. A place like ours cannot exist on one-shot
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrabax, an overseas tour operator with offices in New York,
Miami and Los Angeles, is offering Colors of Spain, an eight-night
escorted tour starting in Madrid and going by bus to Cordoba,
Seville, Granada and the Costa del Sol. It leaves 18 times from
Dec. 3 to April 7, but not Dec. 23. The overall cost, with air
fare, is $949 for each of two people in a hotel room; this does not
count $55 a person in airport fees and departure taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The price includes hotels, buffet breakfasts each day, the bus
trip, one lunch and three dinners, and transfers from the airport
to the hotel in Madrid and back.
</P>
<P>
   Petrabax's brochure gives the land cost as $1,047 for two
people, or $523.50 each. Subtracting this from the $949 package
price leaves $425.50 a person for the air fare. Petrabax has annual
contracts for New York flights with Delta, Iberia and Continental.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Specifying the same Friday departures and Sunday returns, Delta
quoted $358 on Nov. 15 as the cheapest advance purchase round-trip
New York-Madrid air fare; this also omits airport fees and
departure taxes. Petrabax at this point is profiting by at least
$67.50, and since seats are cheaper by the dozen, probably more.
</P>
<P>
   Getting from the airport to the Madrid hotel, the Agumar, would
cost $20 to $30, including luggage at 35 cents a bag and tip.
</P>
<P>
   Petrabax uses mostly two-star hotels. The Agumar room rate, with
no breakfast and without the 7 percent tax, amounts to $152 a night
for two people; for three nights, $456. Two nights at the Porta
Coeli in Seville, come to $292; two nights at the Melia Costa del
Sol in Torremolinos come to $162; a night at the Gran Luna in
Granada, $84. Rough total for eight nights' lodging, $994. Half of
this, representing the cost for one person, would be $497.
</P>
<P>
   Buffet breakfasts are estimated by Petrabax itself at $10 each,
so add $80 a person. It puts the cost of dinners in Seville,
Torremolinos and Granada at $30 each, so add $90, and luncheon in
Seville, $20. Again, the company's estimate puts the city tour of
Madrid at $27 a person; of Cordoba and the Great Mosque, at $55; of
Seville, $45, and of Granada and the Alhambra, $45.
</P>
<P>
   A substitute of sorts for the over-the-road bus with tour
director is an Avis car rental for nine days. Avis International
has a promotional rate of $116 for a ``B'' group manual-drive car,
one similar to an Opel Corsa, when picked up in downtown Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Mileage is free; the value added tax is 16 percent, and the
total comes to $134.56; half of this is $67. (If collision damage
waiver is added, the cost for the nine days is $120.96, and the VAT
is then added to all, for a total of $247.87.)
</P>
<P>
   The land package adds up thus: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Half of two airport transfers, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   average.......................................$25
</P>
<P>
   Half of eight hotel nights,  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7 percent tax not included.....................497
</P>
<P>
   Eight buffet breakfasts........................80
</P>
<P>
   Three dinners, tip not included................90
</P>
<P>
   One lunch, tip not included....................20
</P>
<P>
   Four tours.....................................172
</P>
<P>
   Avis rental, half, no CDW.....................67
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL........................................$951
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So two travelers putting it together for themselves would be
paying $951 each for the land arrangements, plus $358 air fare
each, for a total of $1,309, against the operator's charge of $949
a person. The company uses its plus on the air tickets to subsidize
the land travel, said Joachim Pradas, the head of Petrabax's New
York office.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Rattner Heilman, author of ``Unbelievably Good Deals and
Great Adventures That You Absolutely Can't Get Unless You're Over
50'' (Contemporary Books) considers package trips good value for
travelers of all ages. ``You end up paying a lot less because of
the group rates and special air fares,'' Ms. Heilman said. ``The
down side is that there is no serendipity, no off-the-road
discovery.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Heilman says to be sure that the major components are
attractive to you. Don't buy a package for which a big element is a
trip on horseback if you cannot ride a horse. The balance between
program and ``days at leisure'' _ the phrase of art for being left
alone _ can also affect a choice. If you prefer to visit art
galleries rather than cathedrals, you may want a package with more
than a few unscheduled hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
