<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 28)  
(lb) 
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Japan's Gardens
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you know of agencies with tours to Japan that feature
gardens but also afford opportunities to learn about other aspects
of Japan? _ Margaret B. Brown, Holtwood, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. Elements of art, cuisine and history are often incorporated
into tours that focus on visits to gardens or temples. The trips
here are just a sampling of what a tour operator may offer. Costs
are per person, based on double occupancy, and include entry fees
and, if flights are involved, airport transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Absolute Asia, 160 Varick St., New York, NY 10014; (800)
736-8187, (212) 627-1950, fax (212) 627-4090. Traditions of
Elegance, an eight-day tour for as few as one person, starts in
Tokyo on any day a participant wants to go. Highlights: a cooking
class in Tokyo; an excursion to the Miho museum, designed by I.M.
Pei, outside Kyoto; a visit to the Katsura Imperial Villa's gardens
in Kyoto. Other stops: Kanazawa. Cost: $4,500 to $8,790, depending
on lodgings and the number of meals and days of touring with a
driver and a guide. Air fare is extra.
</P>
<P>
   At Last the Best, 10989 Dorchester Way, Truckee, CA 96161; (888)
445-8857, (530) 550-1676, fax (530) 550-1677. The 13-day Japanese
Country Inns tour departs on April 8 and Oct. 22. Highlights: the
Ryoan-ji, with a raked garden, and the Kinkaku-ji and Ginkaku-ji
(gold and silver pavilions) with gardens, teahouses and a lotus
pond, all in Kyoto; the museum of festival carts in Takayama, some
from the 1600s. Other stops: Tokyo, Hakone-Mount Fuji. Cost:
$4,305; air fare, from the West Coast, is extra. Most meals are
included.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Botanic Garden, Travel and Special Tours, 1000 Lake Cook
Rd., Chicago, IL 60022; (847) 835-6834. A Garden Journey Through
Japan runs from Sept. 10 to 23. Highlights: the Saiho-ji and moss
garden in Kyoto; the Daitoku-ji, a complex of 24 temples with a
garden in Kyoto; the Tokugawa Museum, known for antiquities and
textiles, in Nagoya. Other stops: Tokyo, Osaka, Nara. Requires
museum membership, which is $45 in the Chicago area, $33
nationally. Cost: $7,495 land only; $1,341 coach or $5,878 business
class from Chicago. Most meals included. Arrangements are being
handled by Siemer &AMP; Hand Travel in San Francisco, (800) 451-4321.
</P>
<P>
   Esprit Travel, 2120 Wilshire Blvd., Santa Monica, CA 90403;
(800) 377-7481, (310) 829-6060, fax (310) 828-3564. The Journal of
Japanese Gardening's tour of Kyoto departs May 31 and returns June
13. Highlights: the Rengei-ji, where tea is served overlooking a
brook; the bamboo groves at Okochisanso; a demonstration by a
calligrapher who uses brushes several feet long. Cost: $3,200,
including air fare from Los Angeles and most meals. Essentially the
same tour is given five other times in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Expo Garden Tours, 33 Fox Crossing, Litchfield, CT 06759; (800)
448-2685 or (860) 567-0322, fax (860) 567-0381. The tour goes from
Sept. 3 to 16. Highlights: Ritsurin-en, a 185-acre garden dating
from the 17th century in Takamatsu; Kenroku-en in Kanazawa, from
the 19th century; a visit to the Japan Flora 2000 international
exhibition on Awaji Island. Other stops: Kyoto, Nara, Okayama,
Washuzan, Naruto, Atami, Hakone, Tokyo. Most meals. Cost: $6,076
land only, $8,795 air fare from Los Angeles included.
</P>
<P>
   Fiery Seasonal Welcome
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've read that in Switzerland for the summer solstice and St.
John the Baptist's birthday, huge burning bales of hay are rolled
down the mountainside. Does this practice, depicted in the painter
Anselm Kiefer's work, still take place, and where? _ Brad Burris,
Asheville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A. A remnant of the tradition can be found in Europe and Canada,
where bonfires are lighted atop hills to welcome either spring or
summer.
</P>
<P>
   As for Switzerland, there's an annual celebration called
Sechselaeuten in Zurich; in 2000, the date is April 8. Accompanied
by bands, guild members in historical costumes parade through the
city. In early evening, a snowman filled with wadding and
firecrackers is set afire. The faster the snowman is consumed, it
is said, the faster spring arrives.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 1, bonfires are lighted everywhere to celebrate Swiss
National Day, the anniversary of the beginning of the Swiss
confederation in the 14th century. Information: (212) 757-5944 or
on the Web at www.myswitzerland.com.
</P>
<P>
   The observance closest to home is in Quebec, whose patron saint
is St. John. There are bonfires on June 23 or 24, primarily along
the St. Lawrence River. In Montreal on the June 23, there will be a
big parade followed by fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Theft at London Hotel
</P>
<P>
   Q. While in London in August my daughter had items worth several
hundred dollars stolen from her hotel room. We were assured by the
hotel manager that insurance would cover the loss. However,
repeated inquiries have not been answered. Whom do I turn to? Is
there a Better Business Bureau or hotel organization? _ Rudolf
Hofmann, M.D., Dayton, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   A. Short of seeking relief in court, you can request help from
the London Tourist Board and the British Hospitality Association.
Note, though, that neither group's actions have the force of law.
</P>
<P>
   If a hotel repeatedly fails to resolve complaints
satisfactorily, the board might stop promoting it, said Alex
Brannen, a tourist board spokesman. That means the hotel may be
dropped from a list of 400 to 500 member hotels available to guests
inquiring by phone, on the Web and at information centers.
</P>
<P>
   Guests with a complaint should write to the London Tourist
Board, Glen House, Stag Place, London, England SW1E 5LT, or fax
(44-171) 932 0222.
</P>
<P>
   Both the tourist board and the British Hospitality Association
emphasized that all thefts should be reported to the police,
because, among other things, victims will need a crime number to
pursue insurance claims. They also stressed that hotel thefts were
rare.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitality association is an organization of 25,000 hotel
and catering companies, pubs and B&AMP;Bs. Martin Couchman, its deputy
chief executive, said that in cases of negligence by a hotel (say,
the disappearance of an item put in a safe or luggage left with a
porter), the hotel was responsible for the missing item's current
worth. But if, for example, a thief breaks into a room, the hotel's
responsibility is limited to 50 pounds per article ($81 at 61 pence
to the dollar), with a maximum payment of 100 pounds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints to the British Hospitality Association should be sent
to Queens House, 55-56 Lincoln's Inn Fields, London WC2A 3BH;
(44-171) 404 7744, fax (44-171) 404 7799.
</P>
</TEXT>
