<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CHURCH-DISPUTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN LEADERS CLOSE CHURCHES TO PROTEST MOSQUE DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Christian leaders closed church doors throughout the
Holy Land on Monday to protest Israel's decision to let Muslims
build a mosque near a holy site in Nazareth, the boyhood home of
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The protest, set to continue through Tuesday, is the latest
installment in a two-year-old dispute over plans to put the mosque
on a plot of land near the Basilica of the Annunciation in Nazareth
just as the Christian community prepares for millennium
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The basilica is located on the site where Christians believe an
angel told the Virgin Mary that she would give birth to the son of
God.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has soured Muslim-Christian relations and threatened
to spoil the millennia celebrations in Nazareth. In October, it
appeared the conflict might keep Pope John-Paul II away. But
Vatican officials now say the pope's trip to the Holy Land will go
ahead as scheduled, sometime in March.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials said they organized Monday's two-day protest,
timed to coincide with Muslim plans to lay the cornerstone of the
mosque, to let the world know that they were upset about the mosque
and about the way the dispute was solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were obliged to close our churches to make our voice
heard,'' said Latin Patriarch Michel Sabbah, head of the Roman
Catholic Church in the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   Christian leaders wanted the plot of land to be used to build a
plaza for the thousands of pilgrims and tourists expected to visit
next year. Leaders of Israel's Islamic Movement said the spot
should be used to build a mosque because Shihab el-Din, a revered
medieval Muslim fighter, is buried there.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the Israeli government suggested a compromise: A
mosque would be built on one-third of the lot; the rest would
become a plaza. A wall would separate the two and a police station
would be placed nearby to prevent any unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The Nazareth municipality and the Islamic Movement accepted the
deal. On Tuesday, Muslims plan to lay the first cornerstone of the
mosque that will replace a protest tent they set up there nearly
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Christian leaders, however, did not agree to the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, 13 different denominations, including the Roman
Catholic, Greek Orthodox and Armenian patriarchates, shuttered
doors to Jerusalem's Church of the Holy Sepulchre, the Church of
the Nativity in Bethlehem, and smaller shrines and churches
throughout Israel and the West Bank. The Nazareth basilica site
also was closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision was taken after talks with the two political
parties, but not after talks with us,'' said Sabbah. ``No
consultation at all was taken (with) the Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest left tourists knocking on closed doors Monday. Some
prayed outside. One nun, reduced to tears after having flown
thousands of miles to come to Bethlehem, sang ``Silent Night''
through the crack at the bottom of the Church of the Nativity
doors.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat tried to persuade
Sabbah not to close the Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem, a town
of 30,000 just south of Jerusalem, where residents are jittery
about any unrest that may deter pilgrims and spoil million-dollar
plans for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Internal Security minister Shlomo Ben-Ami told Arafat
``not to interfere in the internal matters of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Palestinian-controlled Islamic Trust in Jerusalem
appealed to Israeli Muslims not to lay the cornerstone in a bid to
ease tensions between Muslims and Christians in Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   Last Easter, those tensions erupted into violence during a Greek
Orthodox procession outside the basilica. Stories vary as to who
started the clash. Christians say Muslims sitting at the protest
tent threw stones at them as they were passing by. Muslims say the
Christians threw the stones.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it was over, more than 50 Christians had been
injured, some hospitalized, and several Christian-owned shops had
been damaged. Church leaders accused the Israeli police of sitting
idly by during the clashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police were in the street, the army was in the street, but
they were ordered not to interfere,'' said Sabbah.
</P>
<P>
   Nazareth city officials have tried to play down the conflict as
a land dispute between the government and the Islamic Trust. They
blame the Israeli authorities for creating the problem by
suggesting two years ago that a mosque should be built at the site
as part of the preparations for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Christian leaders accuse Israel of suggesting the mosque as a
way to get votes from Israel's 1 million-strong Muslim population
at the expense of the much smaller Christian community, which
numbers about 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   In Nazareth, once a predominantly Christian town, Muslims now
make up nearly 70 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought, `you are small, you do not count,''' Sabbah said
Monday. ``Being forgotten, neglected, put aside, we said we have to
speak. That is the meaning of this closure of the churches.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel has denied it harbored ulterior motives and maintains it
was trying to find a compromise that would please everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a country of interfaith coexistence. This is the major
message, '' said the security minister, Ben-Ami.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
