</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLZMANN-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY'S BIGGEST BUILDER FACES BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Philipp Holzmann AG, the biggest
construction company in Germany, averted bankruptcy at least
temporarily Monday night when Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder stepped
in to help negotiate a compromise among banks trying to arrange a
$2.6 billion bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann has been on the brink of insolvency since last week,
when it said it had suddenly uncovered $1.3 billion in soured real
estate loans.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Holzmann's creditor banks failed to reach
agreement on a bailout and angrily began accusing each other of
either covering up evidence of trouble or being ``inflexible'' in
coming to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   But just as it seemed the end was at hand, the German chancellor
said Monday evening that he would try to arrange a deal among the
banks and political leaders in the German state of Hesse, where
Frankfurt is located, and brought the creditors back into another
round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted bailout of Holzmann highlighted the tattered state
of ``Germany Inc.,'' the once tightly knit community of banks,
industrial companies and government officials that has
traditionally rescued ailing enterprises during bad times.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, angry bankers charged that Holzmann, which has lost
money for years, appeared to have concealed bad loans while
declaring that it was on the path to a turn-around.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann's biggest shareholder, the Belgian holding company
Gavaert, charged that the big banks should have seen the problems
as well, and threatened to sue them and Holzmann's top managers.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the finger-pointing, Holzmann's chief executive, Heinrich
Binder, gloomily confronted angry construction workers as a
bitterly cold snowstorm blanketed much of Frankfurt on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Though he promised to do everything he could to keep the company
operating while in bankruptcy, Binder admitted that he ``cannot
say'' whether the company would be able to issue the next round of
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann has more than 1,200 construction sites around Germany,
and work stopped at many of them amid the bad weather and
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Because Holzmann is one of Germany's most venerable industrial
names and employs nearly 17,000 workers, the banks are under heavy
political pressure to prop it up one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, which owns 15 percent of Holzmann and holds more
than 2.2 billion marks, or $1.2 billion, in outstanding loans to
the company, had been leading the bailout and had offered to put up
about $830 million, roughly a third of what Holzmann said it
needed.
</P>
<P>
   But the bailout talks collapsed after a 15-hour meeting of
creditors on Sunday. Deutsche Bank said that ``inflexibility'' by
Commerzbank AG, Germany's fourth-largest bank, caused the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Commerzbank fired back, noting that Deutsche Bank should have
known better because one of its own top executives is chairman of
Holzmann's supervisory board.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of its problems was heightened Monday when rival
construction firms, including Hoch-Tief AG, asserted that they had
little interest in acquiring either all or part of Holzmann.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of Holzmann's problems is a huge portfolio of bad
real estate loans it took on in the early 1990s, when eastern
Germany was being reconstructed at a furious pace and the industry
was enjoying an extraordinary boom. Besides profiting from the
construction work itself, Holzmann financed many projects.
</P>
<P>
   When real estate prices in eastern Germany collapsed as a result
of overbuilding fueled by generous tax breaks, Holzmann found
itself with a growing amount of increasingly problematic loans.
</P>
<P>
   Under German law, Holzmann is required to file for bankruptcy as
soon as its creditors decide against refinancing its debt. Binder
said earlier Monday that that would take place on Tuesday at the
latest.
</P>
<P>
   But political leaders have jumped in for a last attempt. Roland
Koch, the Christian Democratic premier of Hesse, was trying to
arrange one more round of talks and was reported to be putting
heavy pressure on publicly owned banks to contribute money toward a
bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Then Schroeder said he would act as a mediator. According to
some news reports, the banks are short only about 400 million marks
of the 4.3 billion marks, or $2.3 billion, they are trying to
assemble.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Bild Zeitung, Germany's main tabloid paper,
Schroeder said the banks had a responsibility to work out a rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that is important is that sufficient capital be
made available so that Holzmann can continue its work and that the
workers can continue to be paid,'' he said. Declaring himself ready
to take a lead in talks, Schroeder said he was convinced that the
shortfall in bank commitments ``can be closed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Roland Koch, the premier of Hesse, was more pessimistic.
``It will be very difficult for Holzmann to stay alive,'' he said
shortly before the banks restarted talks Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
