u w BC-MEDICARE-HMO-NYTR &LR;      11-22 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HMO-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS MOVES TO REVERSE HMO WITHDRAWALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to stem the exodus of insurers from
Medicare's managed care program, Congress is offering companies
bonuses and other incentives to restore coverage in counties they
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   A health care measure attached to the overall budget package
would provide $4.8 billion in added spending over five years for
the so-called Medicare Plus Choice program, raising reimbursement
rates and easing rules that insurance companies complained were
burdensome and costly.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care proposal would also allow beneficiaries
deserted by an HMO to join the same plan in a nearby county, an
opportunity they did not have under the previous rules. That
provision could prove attractive to consumers willing to travel to
receive the added benefits of managed care, including prescription
drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the managed care changes hope the combination of
provisions will strengthen the overall Medicare Plus Choice program
and lure plans back into areas they deserted as well as counties
that never had HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is the overall package is going to have enough that
it will make a significant difference,'' said Rep. Charles Canady,
R-Fla., whose constituents experienced a significant health care
disruption when HMOs fled Polk County, the largest in his district.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, dozens of managed care plans in more than
30 states cut back their Medicare service or left the program
entirely, sending 734,000 beneficiaries scrambling for new
coverage. About 130,000 of those people lived in counties left with
no managed care option. Plans that did remain typically raised
premiums and cut benefits to the 6.2 million of Medicare's 39
million beneficiaries participating in managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers and health care experts are skeptical that the
reforms will accomplish their intended goal, saying that HMO
withdrawals have been due more to market forces and competition
than to federal reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and congressional critics have
consistently argued that HMOs were already overpaid. One aide to a
Senate Democrat described the provisions as ``welfare for managed
care.'' The White House was also unhappy with the amount of money
that will flow to managed care under the bill, though it supported
the overall package of Medicare changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are provisions in here we don't believe are
justifiable,'' said Chris Jennings, President Clinton's adviser on
health care policy.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said the changes will not have the
desired result since they maintain what he considers to be a flawed
payment system that ties managed care reimbursement rates to what
is paid for traditional fee-for-service. As a result, HMOs tend to
cluster in high-volume, high-cost urban areas where rates are much
higher than in more sparsely populated communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see many HMOs in medium-to-lower-cost areas,'' said
Graham, who would prefer that HMOs bid for the right to serve an
area.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers were also doubtful of the impact, but held out
hope that the changes would reverse the loss of managed care
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot more going on out there than just reimbursement
issues, but some believe it could make a difference for those who
have lost their coverage,'' said Rep. Karen Thurman, D-Fla., whose
North Florida district was rocked by HMO withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the managed care industry said the new
provisions are no panacea, but represent a first step toward
stabilizing the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This prevents health plans from losing ground further,'' said
Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans. She said Congress must still do more to correct what she
sees as a widening gap between traditional Medicare reimbursement
and managed care payment.
</P>
<P>
   She disputed the claim that the plans are now overpaid and said
the constituent pressure put on Congress to make adjustments shows
how popular managed care can be with enrollees. ``The beneficiaries
themselves have made this happen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Medicare changes, an HMO that enters a county with no
plan would get a 5 percent payment bonus the first year and 3
percent the second _ an incentive the government expects to cost
$300 million. The proposal also shortens the time an insurer is
barred from returning to an area once it pulls out from five years
to two years, and makes a number of other revisions sought by the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the additional money going to managed care comes
from an overall boost in fee-for-service spending called for in the
Medicare measure, since the payment rates are linked. The managed
care lobby said the plans will also benefit substantially from a
slower phase-in of rules intended to make certain the plans enroll
sick as well as healthier beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Both lawmakers and insurers believe beneficiaries will take
advantage of the new leeway to join plans outside their immediate
county. The measure leaves it to the discretion of the HMO to
decide whether to accept them, but Ignagni believes many are open
to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the health plans are working very hard to make this
work for as many beneficiaries as possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
