<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-BCSRANKINGS-COX     11-22 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCSRANKINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BCS rankings give Nebraska another chance at big dance
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virginia Tech fans: Don't make those reservations to New Orleans
just yet.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 2 Hokies (10-0), who finish the regular season Friday
against Boston College, received a jolt Monday from the newest Bowl
Championship Series rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech remained No. 2 in the standings after its 62-7 win
over Temple last Saturday. But Nebraska, which was 2.40 points
behind the Hokies a week ago, had closed the gap to just .63
points.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS rankings are compiled from the average of four
components: the coaches' and media polls;
</P>
<P>
   eight computer polls; strength of schedule and number of losses.
The lower the total, the higher the ranking.
</P>
<P>
   The top two teams in the final BCS standings, which will be
released on Dec. 4, will play in the Sugar Bowl on Jan. 4 for the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State (11-0), which closed out its regular season
Saturday by beating Florida 30-23, remained No. 1 by a wide margin
and clinched one of the spots. But now, it appears to be
mathematically possible for a once-beaten Nebraska team to jump
over an unbeaten Virginia Tech team into the Sugar Bowl game for
the national championship. If so, it could be a public-relations
problem for BCS backers. The explanation is pretty simple. Virginia
Tech has a better average in the media's and coaches' opinion polls
(2 vs. 3) and in the computer polls (2.14 vs. 2.57), but Nebraska
has a decided advantage in the strength-of-schedule component.
</P>
<P>
   Strength of schedule is determined by determining the cumulative
won-loss records of a team's opponents (66.6 percent) and the
team's opponents' opponents (33.3 percent). The formula rewards
teams that play in stronger conferences and play tougher
non-conference schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska has a schedule rating of 21, out of 114 Division I
schools, plays in tougher conference than Virginia Tech (Big 12 vs.
Big East) and its opponents have a combined record of 62-52.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech's opponents to date are a combined 40-53. The
Hokies' schedule is rated No. 66. One opponent, Division I-AA James
Madison, is not counted.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule strength, divided by 25 for weighting, comes out to
be an advantage of 1.80 for Nebraska _ 0.84 to 2.64. It was enough
to pull the Cornhuskers to within a point in Monday's standings.
Virginia Tech's schedule strength figures to improve when it plays
Boston College (8-2) on Friday to finish the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But Nebraska has two more games, with Colorado (6-4) on Friday
and then against Texas (9-2) in the Big 12 championship game on
Dec. 4. Texas, the only team to beat Nebraska this season (24-20),
is No. 10 in the BCS rankings and has a schedule strength of 29.
</P>
<P>
   If Virginia Tech is passed over for the Sugar Bowl, the Hokies
would go to the Orange Bowl, where they still could get part of the
national title, if they won to go 12-0.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Sugar Bowl automatically is declared the
national champion in the ESPN/USA Today coaches' poll.
</P>
<P>
   But the sports writers and broadcasters who vote in the
Associated Press poll would be free to vote for Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
