<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULGARIA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDER BULGARIANS LOOK BACK ON COMMUNIST ERA WITH FONDNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria _ Eva Dimitrova's grandmother reminisces fondly
about the communists, who the Dimitrova family believes took better
care of the Bulgarian people than the current, democratic
government.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Baltova's mother tells her this common complaint: ``Before
1989, we had many things, but nothing to buy. Now, there are lots
of things to buy when you go into a shop, but you don't have any
money.''
</P>
<P>
   And the 16-year-old schoolmates, Eva and Elena? They want out _
out of Bulgaria and out of the dismal future they envision having
in this economically-troubled, post-communist nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nasty here in Bulgaria right now,'' Baltova said, sitting
in a Dunkin' Donuts and smoking as she looked with distaste at the
run-down buildings on Sofia's main boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't have money. Our parents' wages are really low.
Our government ministers are not loyal to the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to work abroad _ definitely not in Bulgaria,'' added
Baltova, who is studying Spanish so she can get a job in Spain. ``I
don't think there are good career choices here, and we would not
make any money if we stayed in Bulgaria.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade after communism fell in Central and Eastern Europe,
Bulgaria is still suffering transition pains. Unemployment is 14
percent, and locals and economists fear the rate will grow as state
companies are privatized, and the new owners downsize the
communist-level workforces.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-aged people are finding themselves shut out of the new
job market, which is increasingly requiring English language and
computer skills. Elderly people are struggling to survive on
pensions as low as $30 a month.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton, on the first state visit to Bulgaria by
a sitting US president, extolled the democratic reforms Bulgaria
has introduced since the Berlin Wall fell in 1989, locals wonder
when _ and if _ they will feel the economic benefits of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really nice'' that Clinton is visiting, and ``I hope the
visit will bring something good to Bulgaria,'' said 72-year old
Nadezhda Nikulova, a retired teacher. ``But the president should
see for himself how people here really do live. Because it's really
hard,'' she said sadly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received a wildly enthusiastic welcome from some 30,000
Bulgarians who packed the area near historic Nevsky cathedral
Monday to hear Clinton and the Bulgarian president, Petar Stoyanov,
speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton! Clinton!'' the crowd yelled, waving Bulgarian and US
flags.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that ``when the Cold War ended, it took
much longer for the ground here to thaw,'' and that ``some here may
feel left behind while others race ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask you to remember what you left behind _ a police state
with no reason for disappointment, because there was no hope,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stay the course, Bulgaria will be a place where young
people can make their dreams come true,'' the president said. ``I
know it may seem hard now, but someday, you will look back on this
time and say, `when we were young, we brought Bulgaria back to
freedom.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thanked Bulgarians for their help during the war in
Kosovo. While Bulgaria was damaged economically by the war against
its trading partner Serbia, Bulgaria allowed NATO to use its air
space.
</P>
<P>
   In private meetings with Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov,
Clinton was pressed to support Bulgaria's NATO accession hopes.
Both leaders agreed that NATO membership for Bulgaria was a high
priority, a senior Clinton administration official said, recapping
the meeting. ``You can make a compelling case for NATO membership
in the next wave'' in 2001, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria has long been the region's laggard in making the
transition from communism to a democracy and market economy.
</P>
<P>
   The nation, which once wanted to become a Soviet Republic,
doesn't share the hatred that other former Soviet satellites had
for the communists. There was no Russian invasion here, as the
Czechs had in 1968 and the Hungarians had in 1956, to create
Bulgarian animosity toward its Black Sea neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgarians, especially older nationals, often refer to the
Russians as their ``blood brothers,'' as the two share the Orthodox
Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   With little impetus for economic reform and the loss of Russian
support, Bulgaria hit a drastic low in early 1997. The banking
system was near collapse, and people stood in bread lines.
Hospitals were forced to do only emergency surgery, as anesthesia
was too expensive to buy with rapidly devaluating Bulgarian leva,
the local currency.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis brought Bulgarians to the streets, demanding the
resignation of the previous Socialist government. New elections
brought the reform-talking Stoyanov government.
</P>
<P>
   The Stoyanov government began _ belatedly, say would-be foreign
investors _ to privatize old state-owned companies. The
International Monetary Fund imposed strict fiscal policies in
exchange for its assistance.
</P>
<P>
   On a macro-economic level, investment analysts and
businesspeople say, Bulgaria has made impressive progress.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation is low, and there are hopes that the Gross Domestic
Product might actually grow next year, said Ken Lefkowitz, an
analyst with the Sofia office of EPIC investments.
</P>
<P>
   But individuals here say they are not yet feeling the
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really poor, and crime is high. For most of society, I
don't think there is anything positive'' that came from the
departure of the communists, complained a 67-year-old man who would
give only his first name, Velin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for people, because they haven't learned to take
care of themselves,'' said 50-year-old Desislava Mihailova as she
collected free mineral water from a local spring. ``We were used to
having someone else take care of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoyanov, speaking to the crowd at Nevsky, urged his countrymen
to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize the transition has been more difficult, more
painful, and slower than we would have imagined,'' Stoyanov said.
But ``regardless of the difficulties and disillusionments, maybe .
. . the path is clear. It lies straight ahead and we have to go to
the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
