<SLUG> BC-FBC-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS HAD WATCHED THE TAPES, HAD PATRIOTS ALL FIGURED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There are some mysteries surrounding the Patriots, such
as why clutch wide receiver Troy Brown is ever on the sideline in a
key third-down situation and inconsistent Tony Simmons is ever in
the game on a key play.
</P>
<P>
   But to opponents who study the Patriots' offense closely, the
mysteries are few. The Miami Dolphins' Terrell Buckley claimed he
was able to pick off a Drew Bledsoe pass Sunday because he had
studied tape and knew what Ben Coates likes to do on his signature
pass pattern _ go 6-10 yards downfield, usually on third down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a nice read off Coates when he came out on his route,''
said Buckley. ``The previous play to that, Coates had run an `in'
route, and you just count on what they might do next. You look at
Coates when you're doing your film study and you see what he likes
to do. He might run an `in' one time, or an `out' and then run a
curl next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley went into more detail. Look very closely at tape of the
Patriots' offense, and how Coates is used in particular, the Miami
cornerback went on, and it soon becomes clear what New England
likes to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots basically use three different routes with
Coates,'' said Buckley. ``And they had already run two of them.
Logic would tell you that they have only one left _ and that's the
one I was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley stepped inside of Coates, Bledsoe apparently did not see
the cornerback, and the Dolphins had one of their five killer
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I study the tape and I know my ability versus his,'' Buckley
said. ``Mine is quickness. I'm not going to try and outmuscle
Coates; a guy my size, that's a loss for me. So just knowing what
you can do against your opponent is big, and that helped me on that
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Patriots mystery is why clutch wide receiver Shawn
Jefferson is on the sideline in a key passing situation and Vincent
Brisby is on the field. Even more of a mystery is why the page
outlining a short post pattern over the middle apparently is
missing from the New England playbook. But to opponents, the
mysteries are few.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bledsoe has such a great arm,'' said Dolphins linebacker Zach
Thomas. ``And he's so big and he sits in there in the pocket and
when we blitz, it puts us man-to-man and it puts a lot of pressure
on our corners. And he hangs in there and that's when he usually
hits his big play and hits teams big, when he doesn't have any
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the linebacker went on, ``We had pressure against Bledsoe
and that was huge. He had to get rid of it quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas can be very analytical. All defensive linemen and
linebackers, and all of their coaches, will say that pressuring an
NFL quarterback is the key to stopping a passing game. But Thomas
went deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the Patriots' quarterback quickly is even more
important, he said, because some of the New England pass routes
take time to develop. A long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't think the receivers were getting through their
routes before Bledsoe could even get rid of the ball or the
pressure was on him,'' said Thomas. ``It has nothing to do with
Drew but has to do with a lot of things around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew is one of the best quarterbacks in the league, but Drew
can't get rid of the ball until a certain route comes through. And
I don't think they even got through their routes before he could
even get rid of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Patriots mystery is why linebacker Tedy Bruschi at times
trots off the field when the opponent has third and long. Bruschi's
strength since he arrived in New England has been precisely on that
down. But to Patriots opponents, the mysteries are few.
</P>
<P>
   ``We studied the tape of them better this time than the first
game,'' said Miami defensive lineman Jason Taylor. ``I didn't take
advantage of the individual matchups and some of the things that
were there the last time but we all did a better job this time. I
know I did, personally. We studied these guys more this time and we
sort of knew some of the things they were going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When Taylor picked off a Bledsoe screen pass in the fourth
quarter, he said, he had been yelling to his teammates before the
play, ``Watch the screen! Watch the screen!''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were ready for that,'' said Taylor. ``When I
went up for the ball, I saw Trace (Armstrong, defensive lineman)
running right behind me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
