<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-INSIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Digital Insight buys rival company in $439 million dealBy Mark
Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A southern California company is buying a rival,
Norcross, Ga.-based nFront, for $439 million in stock. The
acquisition would create a powerful company in its segment of the
market: companies selling products and services for community banks
that want to reach their customers through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close by the end of February.
</P>
<P>
   John Dorman, Digital Insight's president and chief executive
will be chief executive and chairman of the new company. Tripp
Rackley, nFront's 29-year-old chairman and chief executive, will be
president. Digital Insight's seven member board of directors will
include two members from nFront, Rackley and a director to be named
later.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Insight, based in Calabasas, Calif., will exchange .579
shares for each nFront share. The deal values nFront shares at
$29.02, a 190 percent increase over nFront's June initial public
stock sale. nFront shares closed Monday at $21.25, up $2.50, or 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Insight shares were first offered to the public Oct. 1
at $14. Its shares have jumped 228 percent since, closing at $41.75
Monday, down 17 percent, or $8.37 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is part of a trend toward consolidation in the emerging
online banking industry. This month, Atlanta-based S1, formerly
Security First Technologies, closed on its acquisitions of FICS and
Edify. That company is expected to dominate the high-end of the
banking industry. Digital Insight and nFront focus on banks with
assets less than $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Financial institutions pay companies such as nFront, Digital
Insight and S1 to set them up online. NFront products allow bank
customers to manage their accounts through Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Most people still bank the old-fashioned way, with direct
deposit, hand-written checks and mailed monthly statements. The
combined companies would have contracts with banks with a potential
16 million customers. Of those, 4 percent, or 640,000, manage their
money through their bank's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   That percentage says a lot about how young the online banking
market is, said Rob D. Owens, an analyst with Pacific Crest
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says a lot also about the impact of the year 2000 issue,''
Owens said. ``You'll see banks step up their marketing efforts for
Internet banking.''
</P>
<P>
   nFront's Atlanta-area offices will stay open, the 150-person
staff remaining mostly in tact, said Jeff Hodges, nFront chief
financial officer. Hodges will be vice president of strategic
development for Digital Insight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think scale and size matter,'' Hodges said. ``It's a land
grab and we're right at the foothill of mass adoption of Internet
banking.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined company's 645 client banks will make it the largest
seller of online banking products to local banks. The new company
would have about 290 employees and $30 million in yearly sales.
Combined, the companies lost $4.8 million on revenue of $7.2
million for the three months that ended Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Insight expects to lose money at least through 2001,
according to a September filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. The company said Monday the acquisition might move that
date up three months.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
