u f BC-ERGONOMICS-RULES-BOS &LR;      11-22 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERGONOMICS-RULES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ERGONOMICS RULES CONCERN SAFETY ADVOCATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While manufacturers described the nation's new ergonomics
standard as unfair Monday, workplace safety advocates said they
were concerned about language that could limit its effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Tolle Graham, an occupational health specialist at the
Massachusetts Coalition for Occupational Safety and Health, said
the measure is weakened by a provision in the regulation stating
that implementation of the standard will be triggered by an injury
in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   `This is not a program that will evaluate signs and symptoms
with the idea of preventing an injury from occurring,'' said
Graham. ``It isn't preventative enough . . . At the same time, it
is hopeful that we have gotten this far.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Krese, director of employment policy at the
Washington-based association, said she was leery of a clause in the
standard that promises to grandfather in companies that already
have appropriate safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members have received no assurances that this regulation
will improve worker safety,'' said Krese, who called the agency's
push to develop the standard ``disingenuous.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Occupational Safety and Health Administration's new
ergonomics standard, which will be implemented by the end of the
year 2000, employers at 1.6 million worksites will be required to
develop or implement a basic ergonomics program.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA estimates accommodations to a single work station will cost
$150 per year. The overall cost to employers will be approximately
$4.2 billion, and will include the $875 million US companies spend
on injured employees who are not fully covered by workers'
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Before the standard can be implemented, a series of hearings
must be held during which time workers and employers will testify
for or against the measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
