<SLUG> BC-PRISON-WELFARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ``BOUNTY'' PROGRAM CUTS 40,000 CONVICTS OFF WELFARE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _More than 40,000 prisoners have been cut off the
public welfare rolls, thanks to a new system that pays a bounty to
states that report them to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The new system has helped the Social Security Administration to
discover $32 million in past payments to ineligible inmates. By
stopping the benefits, the government will save an estimated $38
million more, said a report issued Monday by the General Accounting
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program started two years ago, the federal government
pays states and localities
</P>
<P>
   up to $400 for reporting each ineligible recipient in their
prisons. That totalled $10 million nationwide from March 1997
through November 1998, said the GAO, which serves as the
investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The incentives have been most successful in California, Florida,
Louisiana, New York, Ohio and Texas. Together, these half-dozen
states accounted for almost half of the inmates removed from
welfare roles.
</P>
<P>
   For their efforts, California received $1.69 million in
``bounty'' money, Florida $520,000, and Louisiana $626,200, New
York $1.1 million. Ohio reaped $492,000, and Texas got $591,000
over the period of the study.
</P>
<P>
   The program is part of the broader welfare reform legislation
passed by Congress in 1996. Before the new law, inmates frequently
got a variety of federal payments, including those reserved for the
aged, blind or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates who spend a full year in prison are barred from such
benefits. Until the law was changed, it was largely left to the
prisoners to declare themselves ineligible. Although some prisons
relayed information to federal authorities, there was no systematic
check.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, greeted the
results of the study as ``great news for taxpayers and horrible
news for convicts who were illegally getting welfare and Social
Security checks in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Archer added, ``If you're doing time, you don't get a dime.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other states, Georgia received $182,600 in bounty money,
North Carolina $90,200 and Colorado $68,200 .
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
