<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8256 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-22 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRE-2K THANKSGIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is going to be our pre-millennial Thanksgiving, and we have
lots to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   While we continue to respect the perils of Y2K, not to mention
the myriad technological developments capable of wiping out the
planet, this week we prefer to dwell on the fact that Nostradamus'
prediction for 1999 turned out to be over-pessimistic. A King of
Terror did not emerge from the sky in July to create a war with the
Chinese, and we are extremely grateful. Although we were a little
nervous when America accidentally bombed that Chinese embassy.
</P>
<P>
   We are furthermore thankful that Edgar Cayce, ``the sleeping
prophet,'' was mistaken about California sliding into the sea and
the disappearance of Japan. Additionally, we are relieved that a
mysterious rainbow did not appear on Aug. 18 to suck all the oxygen
out of the atmosphere, as Criswell forecast in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Besides celebrating disasters averted, this is an excellent
Thanksgiving to contemplate millennial blessings, big and small.
Like eyeglasses. Our myopic ancestors were doomed to spend their
lives bumping into things, waiting for spectacles to be invented in
the 13th century. Europeans in A.D. 1000 also had neither zippers
nor buttons. They had to grope their way toward the Renaissance,
flapping in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   And forks. Forks were not only absent from holiday dinner tables
in Europe, they were regarded as a moral threat. When a
turn-of-the-millennium Venetian doge married a Byzantine princess,
her new neighbors were scandalized that she refused to eat with her
hands. ``She would impale (food) on a certain gold instrument with
two prongs and thus carry it to her mouth,'' complained St. Peter
Damian, a local critic. When the princess died of the plague, Peter
blamed the forks. You can read about it in his essay ``Of the
Venetian Doge's Wife, Whose Body After Her Excessive Delicacy
Entirely Rotted Away.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if your ancestors lived in Constantinople, they
already had access to a full set of cutlery. And if they came from
the Far East, the fork issue never came up. This millennium
business requires a lot of qualifications if you take a planet-wide
view.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you're eating this Thanksgiving, be grateful that it
was not what people dined on in Europe 1,000 years ago, when the
menu was pretty much limited to variations on the theme of greasy
meat. (A book of the period simply instructed the chef to ``boil
the things that need boiling and roast the things that need
roasting.'') People had salt, but pepper was so scarce it was
sometimes used as money. Forget marjoram. Forget the salad. Lettuce
was almost as dangerous as forks. One letter-writer of the era
warned that consumption of greens ``generates a humor which
putrefies the body and brings it to extremes of sickness and
death.''
</P>
<P>
   We are, by the way, also grateful to be living in an era where
there is not all that much talk of putrefaction.
</P>
<P>
   Tearing through a hunk of boiled mammal with your fingers was,
of course, the optimal culinary experience in Europe circa 1000.
Peasants were gumming their way through a hunk of rye bread in good
times, and boiling up a pot of straw soup in bad.
</P>
<P>
   But _ here's another planetary qualification _ in the Muslim
empire, which stretched all the way to Spain, people were into
gourmet cooking, whipping up spiced lamb sausages, chicken balls
and pickled fish. In China, the Sung emperor had 1,069 cooks in the
palace kitchen. The Chinese also had toothpaste, while people in
Europe barely had teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar that says next January starts us on a new
1,000-year cycle was created by the Western Europeans _ the guys
with the stale rye bread and no pepper. But all the world uses it
now, at least for commercial purposes. And although we really have
no common millennial history, all the world shares an impulse to
examine the past.
</P>
<P>
   Employers say they have a terrible time finding staff to work
Thanksgiving because it's the one holiday that everybody,
regardless of race, religion or nationality, likes. People who have
never heard of the Pilgrims still get the principle _ a big meal,
family and friends, counting blessings. The turn of the millennium
ought to be the same. A cultural milestone for some, but a moment
when everybody gets the point. Look back, in amazement, and see the
path we've walked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
