<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MICH-YOUTH-MURDER-2TA     11-22 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-YOUTH-MURDER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS WONDER WHY BOY WASN'T HELPED BEFORE KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ Nathaniel Abraham, the youngest American
charged and convicted of murder as an adult, received no special
counseling or other assistance despite warning signs years before
he fatally shot a man at age 11.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the crime and a week after his conviction, child
welfare officials are still unable to explain why.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel appeared in police reports as a possible suspect in
several crimes, including burglaries and larcenies, in the nearly
three years before he killed a man, Ronnie Greene Jr., with a
single shot to the head.
</P>
<P>
   But no charges were filed and Nathaniel, who is now 13, never
ended up in juvenile court or in any of the local counseling
programs, county officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel also fit the profile of a child at risk of getting in
trouble, county officials said. He was one of four children of a
single mother struggling to make ends meet. School officials had
diagnosed Nathaniel at the age of 8 as having below-average
intelligence and difficulty controlling his emotions. While he had
attended remedial education classes, he had received no special
counseling for his behavioral problems.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland County officials in this blue-collar city 25 miles
northwest of Detroit have acknowledged that their system of
juvenile justice and social services failed Nathaniel, and that
they do not know why.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, Nathaniel never got into the system,''
said David Gorcyca, Oakland County prosecutor. ``It's unfortunate
because we probably could have intervened earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   While Nathaniel's lawyers are trying to have the boy's
second-degree murder conviction overturned, a preliminary hearing
on sentencing has been scheduled for Dec. 14. The Oakland County
Circuit Court judge, Eugene A. Moore, could sentence Nathaniel to
life in prison. But prosecutors have said they will ask that
Nathaniel be sent to a juvenile detention center and re-evaluated
by the judge at ages 19 and 21 to determine whether he should serve
time in an adult prison.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel's mother, Gloria Abraham, returned to school in her
mid-20s and then found a job as a medical laboratory technician on
a night shift while raising her four children and caring for a
mentally disabled sister.
</P>
<P>
   When Nathaniel began getting in trouble after school, while Ms.
Abraham was at work, she asked the police and the juvenile courts
to intervene, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   County officials have been blaming each other. Gorcyca said he
thought the police should have acted sooner. But Conway Thompson,
Pontiac's deputy chief of police, said officers had twice notified
Gorcyca's office that something needed to be done about Nathaniel.
On two other occasions, Thompson said, the police had urged
juvenile court officials to immediately put Nathaniel into its
counseling program, Youth Assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Gorcyca said the prosecutor's office had not received any
referrals from the police about Nathaniel. Robert L. Bingham, the
family division administrator for the Oakland County Circuit Court,
said confidentiality rules prevented him from discussing individual
cases, but the court has been able to honor requests for counseling
under its Youth Assistance program.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Nathaniel never received any counseling, said his lawyer,
Geoffrey Fieger.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel's age may have made it easier for him to fall between
the cracks. Thompson said that while someone like Nathaniel might
be mentioned in many police reports as a possible suspect, it was
often hard to find enough evidence or witnesses to justify bringing
charges. Some of the nearly two dozen police reports mentioning
Nathaniel only said that witnesses had blamed a boy named ``Nate.''
The police never determined whether this meant Nathaniel Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court decided in 1967 that youths have many of the
same rights as adults to a lawyer and due process, in addition to
various other protections afforded to juveniles. This has made it
harder for police and prosecutors to pursue juvenile cases, county
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Called into the police station once to recover Nathaniel, Ms.
Abraham asked the police to hold him to teach him a lesson, only to
be told that such a request could be considered child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abraham became estranged from the father of her first three
children when she was 24. She moved in with her neighbors, Tommy
and Claudine Williams, two weeks after Nathaniel was born. The
Williamses, who had no children at home, raised Nathaniel after Ms.
Abraham moved into her own place nearby three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel thrived, Tommy Williams said. ``He was no problem when
he was growing up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abraham had a fourth child and then moved into a larger
house on the other side of town when Nathaniel was 8. Nathaniel
insisted on moving in with his family, Ms. Abraham told the Detroit
Free Press earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Nathaniel had trouble adjusting from life as an only child
to life as one of four children. He had trouble sharing, and his
name began appearing in police reports.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel has been confined at a juvenile detention center
during the two years since his arrest. The center, Children's
Village, normally holds children awaiting immediate trial.
</P>
<P>
   County officials have defended Nathaniel's prolonged detention,
pointing out that numerous appeals by the defense and prosecution
had delayed the trial, which began on Oct. 29, two years to the day
after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is getting counseling and he is getting an education, it's
not like he's over there rotting,'' said Gorcyca, while
acknowledging that, ``more intensive counseling could be available
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fieger, who is handling Nathaniel's case for free,
disagreed. Fieger, who ran unsuccessfully as the Democratic
candidate for governor last year, said that Nathaniel had received
no significant counseling at Children's Village. ``Michigan probate
court and the juvenile justice system is a hellhole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger has presented many of his criticisms of Nathaniel's
treatment by condemning budget cuts in Michigan's mental health and
juvenile justice system. Like many states, Michigan has been
eliminating mental health programs for juveniles, particularly
programs that allow youths to be treated at special homes. Until
the mid-1990s, Michigan had one of the nation's most renowned
systems for juvenile mental health, featuring seven residential
institutions. One of the institutions, Fairlawn Center, was in
Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   But the state has closed Fairlawn and five of the other six
centers as part of a shift toward treating more youths at less
expensive nonresidential clinics. Overall state spending on mental
health has almost doubled in the last decade, even as spending for
residential hospitals has been cut in half, said Geralyn Lasher, a
spokeswoman for the Michigan Department of Community Health.
</P>
<P>
   Experts disagree over whether Nathaniel might have benefited
from a program like Fairlawn's.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Earl, the president of Oakland Family Services, a
nonprofit group here, said the state's mental health centers have
always been reserved for people with psychiatric disorders, not
character disorders. Nathaniel's below-average intelligence and
difficulties with anger represent ``sort of a maturity factor _
that's not necessarily a psychiatric disorder,'' Earl said, adding
that, ``the character disorders tend to end up in prisons.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rosemary Sarri, a University of Michigan professor of social
work specializing in juvenile justice, said Fairlawn might have
helped Nathaniel. She said that before most of the mental health
centers closed, she had worked in one of them with children whose
problems closely resembled Nathaniel's.
</P>
<P>
   County officials said they hope there was no one else with
problems like Nathaniel's who was not getting treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But leaders of mental health groups suspect that Nathaniel's
plight is unusual only in that it ended in a slaying and a blaze of
national publicity. ``I don't know how many Nathaniels are out
there,'' Earl said. ``There are potential Nathaniels in every
neighborhood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8262 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w BC-WTO-SECRECY-SPI &LR;      11-22 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-SECRECY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HOPES TO MAKE WTO MORE OPEN TO PUBLIC SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When lawyers for fruit-producing countries in the
Caribbean wanted to watch legal arguments in a global trade dispute
over bananas, the World Trade Organization refused to let them in
the room.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sierra Club tried to submit written comments about
whether Europe should be able to ban beef treated with hormones,
the WTO turned them down.
</P>
<P>
   The World Trade Organization, which meets in Seattle next week,
is one of the least open organizations in which the United States
participates.
</P>
<P>
   But if the United States government has its way, the member
countries of the WTO will agree in Seattle to take some steps
toward opening its proceedings to greater public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO has been treated for too long like some private
priesthood for experts, where we know what's right and we pat you
on the head and tell you to just go right along and play by the
rules that we reach,'' President Clinton said in a speech last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want the world trading system to have legitimacy, we
have got to allow every legitimate group with any kind of beef,
whether they're right or wrong, to have some access to the
deliberative process of the WTO.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of openness _ known as transparency in the parlance of
trade negotiators _ is the one issue on which the Clinton
administration, the U.S. business community and WTO critics from
the labor, environmental and consumer movements are in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefksy says opening up
the WTO will be one of the United States' top priorities in the
round of negotiations that begins in Seattle. She said a lack of
openness at the International Monetary Fund has threatened
congressional support for that organization, and that the WTO runs
the same risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO is somewhat more open than people perceive, but not
nearly open enough from the point of view of the U.S.'' Barshefsky
said in an interview. ``We push on ahead for notions of greater
transparency, greater accountability, greater citizen participation
and input.''
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky said the WTO's predecessor, the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, was even more secretive, and that the WTO is
somewhat hampered by ``bureaucratic inertia.'' But she said many
countries, including European countries with a tradition of open
government, are resisting change at the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many member countries do not have the kinds of traditions of
openness and political accountability that we do, and so they are
not comfortable with the notion of greater transparency,
particularly when their own government regimes may not be
particularly transparent,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even countries in Europe have difficulty ... in accepting
broader notions of transparency in these institutions, and I've
never heard a satisfactory explanations from European member states
as to why that is so.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has pledged to push in Seattle to
open the WTO's dispute resolution procedures to the public, to
allow non-governmental organizations to file amicus curiae (friend
of the court) briefs in cases involving the environment, and to
create formal mechanisms tose the involvement of
non-governmental organizations with the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. trade official said the administration is hopeful that
the WTO might in Seattle agree to improve public access to
documents.
</P>
<P>
   But the official, who asked not to be named, said it is proving
much more difficult to persuade WTO members of the benefits of
opening committee meetings, or of requiring dispute panels to read
amicus briefs.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also is pushing to open up procurement from
other nations to competitive bidding. But this step is somewhat
controversial. The U.S. government says the step will reduce the
opportunity for corruption, bribery and insider deals. But some
consumer groups, such as Public Citizen, worry that it would
prevent countries from such steps as reaching out to minority and
women contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Public interest groups, on the other hand, want the United
States to take some internal steps to open up the U.S. trade
negotiating arena. Environmentalists recently won a lawsuit arguing
that they should be represented on certain federal trade advisory
panels, and they argue that their absence from panels on issues
like forestry are indicative of the U.S. trade representative's
advocacy for business interests rather than for labor and
environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade bodies have developed to help industry _ that's their
history and that's how U.S. officials viewed them,'' said Patti
Goldman, managing attorney for the Earthjustice Legal Defense Fund
in Seattle. ``They don't build solutions for environmental problems
in the WTO, they look for trade barriers and try to get rid of
them. It's been a slow education process even for the U.S. trade
representative's office to see that there are other values.''
</P>
<P>
   The WTO is becoming somewhat more open to public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Panel decisons are released to the public, but slowly.
Governments may release their own legal submissions, but not those
of other countries. The WTO's web site (www.wto.org) contains some
documents, but not all. And the speechmaking sessions of the WTO in
Seattle next will be webcast, although the negotiating sessions and
committee meetings will be closed.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO's conduct is in sharp contrast to the U.S. government,
which as a result of a tradition of participatory democracy and a
network of laws is required to grant the public access to watch its
proceedings, offer comment on proposed laws, and read most
government documents.
</P>
<P>
   WTO dispute panels are considerably less open to public scrutiny
than is the U.S. judicial system, in which legal filings are
generally available to the public, hearings are generally open, and
outside groups can, with the consent of the judge, offer
submissions called amicus briefs in which they comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transparency is a pervasive, daily problem with the WTO,''
said Thea Lee, a top trade policy adviser with the AFL-CIO. The
labor union, concerned that the WTO dispute settlement panel did
not include anyone with expertise on worker health, wanted to weigh
in on a dispute between Canada and France over whether France
should be allowed to ban asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AFL-CIO did submit a brief, but we never received an
acknowledgment, and it's not clear that they have any obligation to
read it or accept our input,'' Lee said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8265 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-MILK-XFILES-REVIEW     11-22 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MILK-XFILES-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EXECUTION OF JUSTICE' AND X-FILES REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:  2.5 and 3 stars  
By DAVID KRONKE 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco Mayor George Moscone was obviously better-known
than Harvey Milk, a city supervisor, when the two were gunned down
21 years ago by troubled Twinkie-ingestor Dan White. In the
intervening years, Milk has eclipsed his boss in our collective
memory.
</P>
<P>
   Milk, of course, was an impassioned gay-rights activist, the
first openly gay politician elected to public office in America,
and his murder became an ipso facto martyrdom, depicted in the
Oscar-winning documentary ``The Times of Harvey Milk.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, both Oliver Stone and Robin Williams have expressed
interest in filming Milk's story, versions that would have been
variously more overheated and sappier than ``Execution of
Justice.'' This Showtime film provocatively approaches the story
from the killer's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a play by Emily Mann, ``Execution of Justice'' is a
film of many strengths, and just one of them is that it doesn't
condescendingly deify Milk. In fact, he's merely a supporting
character in White's drama, and his matter-of-fact homosexuality
may be irksome to White, but nothing he can't cope with.
</P>
<P>
   You shudder to think how Williams, in his current mode of
reducing everything to cinematic treacle, would have played the
guy.) Peter Coyote essays Milk as smart, compassionate and a little
playful, and refuses to romanticize his subject.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``Execution,'' in ersatz documentary fashion, posits
White as the original disenfranchised conservative white guy,
bewildered and rankled that he no longer rules the roost, long
before such a role became a cultural cliche. When White, a former
cop and fireman, joined the same city board of supervisors as Milk,
and found himself jobbed on all sides _ by his constituents, by the
developers who railroaded him and by his peers _ his frustrations
burbled, Vesuvius-like, until he resigned in spite. He finally
flipped out when, after taking his ball and going home, Moscone
refused to allow him back into the political arena.
</P>
<P>
   The film, as well as a short documentary following it titled
``Witnesses to the Execution,'' points out that White's murdering
Milk was more an act of psychotic politics than homophobia. The
true homophobia was manifested when White's jury, stupefyingly,
bought the defense argument that junk food had thrust him into a
period of temporary insanity and found him guilty of mere
manslaughter rather than premeditated murder. The riots that
resulted protesting the shoddy handling of Milk's memory in
particular (and Moscone's, somewhat secondarily) ensured Milk's
enduring stature in gay-rights history. White, tormented after his
release from prison eight years later, eventually committed
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Daly takes on a daunting challenge _ explicating an unfathomable
point of view _ and humanizes White's deranged befuddlement. Almost
perpetually in a drab, styleless brown suit, Daly's White is a guy
who yearns to do good but has no wherewithal or backbone to do so
in the shark-infested political waters he tentatively wades into.
At times, when things don't go his way, Daly seems to be channeling
the precise petulance Dan Quayle displayed in the 1988 vice
presidential debates, as White uses his staid value system as a
smoke screen to attack lifestyles he doesn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Execution of Justice'' is marred by director Leon Ichaso's
occasional strident efforts to gravely pound home the importance of
his film. The heavenly choirs on the soundtrack are overkill, for
example, and using a drag queen as a preachy Greek chorus doesn't
serve the material particularly well, either. At other times,
there's a certain dramatic inertia, as the film rushes to cram in
all the pertinent, if not necessarily interesting, facts.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Execution of Justice'' is buoyed by Daly's complex,
layered performance, and Coyote's solid but more casual turn, and
by vividly capturing the righteous mayhem that fueled San Francisco
in its moment of crisis. Its powerful story is not just about gay
rights but about how a city was dragged, sometimes against its
will, into a state of greater understanding and tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   A kiss is just a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's ``X-Files'' episode indeed gives rabid fans what
they've long wished for _ Mulder and Scully smooch _ but be warned:
It's far more interested in trying to wrap up all the messy plot
strands left behind by ``Millennium,'' the Chris Carter series that
was canceled last season. Lance Henriksen appears as Frank Black,
the disgruntled former member of the Millennium Group _ heck, Frank
was disgruntled about pretty much everything _ who has checked
himself into a psychiatric hospital in an effort to lighten up when
Mulder and Scully approach him about their latest bizarre case.
</P>
<P>
   Seems someone's digging up and resurrecting the bodies of dead
Millennium Group zealots, creating an ersatz Four Horsemen of the
Apocalypse and hoping to bring on Armageddon before the year 2000.
``Millennium'' was dumped because of viewer apathy, so it seems a
dubious choice to force Mulder and Scully to spend Dec. 31 mopping
up Frank Black's dirty work _ really, who cares? _ instead of
battling a more original Y2K peril more germane to their harsh
realm. Still, it's a serviceable episode, albeit predictable vis a
vis the circumstances surrounding their clinch, which, like
everything ``X''-related, lingers ambiguously.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, these two almost kissed in the movie 18 months
ago, and if they really had been hot for one another, they probably
would have found an opportunity to pick up where they left off
before now. So let's leave these cold fish to themselves and go
find another TV couple with an initially chilly chemistry that's
just waiting to erupt in passion _ Bryant Gumbel and Jane Clayson,
anyone?
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``Execution of Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   What: Docudrama about Dan White's 1978 murder of San Francisco
mayor George Moscone and supervisor and gay-rights activist Harvey
Milk and his subsequent controversial trial, followed by ``Witness
to the Execution,'' a short documentary on the tragedy, featuring
California Sen. Dianne Feinstein and San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Who: Tim Daly, Peter Coyote, Amy Van Nostrand, Tyne Daly,
Stephen Young, Khalil Kain.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   When: 8 tonight; repeats Dec. 2, 13 and 18.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating: 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   What: Episode wrapping up ``Millennium's'' plot line and
featuring the long-awaited Scully/Mulder buss.
</P>
<P>
   Who: David Duchovny, Gillian Anderson, Lance Henriksen, Mitch
Pileggi.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Fox (KTTV, Channel 11).
</P>
<P>
   When: 9 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating: 2.5 stars
</P>
</TEXT>
