<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8281 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-CHURCHES-BOS &LR;      11-22 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CHURCHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANS PROTEST BUILDING OF MOSQUE NEAR CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The doors of Christian shrines were closed
throughout the Holy Land Monday in protest against a decision by
Israel to permit construction of a mosque near the Church of the
Annunciation in Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of the mosque is due to be laid Tuesday in a
square at the foot of the church, on the site where Christians
believe the angel Gabriel announced to Mary that she would bear the
infant Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute that led to the two-day demonstration, which church
leaders say was the first time in memory that the doors were closed
at all 35 of the most sacred shrines, has heightened religious
tensions just one month before the Holy Land prepares to celebrate
2,000 years of the Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was but the latest reminder that as the millennium
approaches, the Holy Land is as entangled as ever in the conflicts
that have shaped its history, age-old disputes and rivalries that
some fear could diminish the coming celebrations and an expected
visit by the Pope.
</P>
<P>
   The tension and squabbling has surfaced in several places
besides Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Palestinian-ruled Bethlehem, where Jesus was born,
Christian leaders are worried that the streets remain clogged by
unfinished construction projects and torn-up roads barely a month
before Christmas. The Palestinian Authority seems to have allowed
poor planning, limited funding, and intercine political battles to
tarnish an historic opportunity for Palestinian Christians to show
the world their central shrine.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Israel, the chief rabbinate has warned that any hotel from
Jerusalem to Tel Aviv that displays a Christmas tree in its lobby
or holds a public celebration of New Year's Eve will lose its
``kashrut,'' or kosher, license, a penalty that could put a hotel
out of business in the Jewish state. Rabbi Yaakov Sabag, the head
of the rabbinate's ``kashrut'' section, said the warning was issued
because ``there are some Jews who find the Christmas tree
offensive; it is a symbol, a symbol like a swastika.''
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Church of the Holy Sepulchre in Jerusalem, where
Christian faith holds that Jesus was crucified, buried, and rose
again, the six denominations that share control of the shrine are
locked in the latest of a series of quarrels. This time the issue
is where to create a fire exit for the Crusader-era church, which
is expected to be packed with tourists in the coming year. Without
a second exit, Israeli authorities fear a ``tragedy in the making''
at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Monday at the Holy Sepulchre, however, disappointed tourists
found the massive doors closed and locked.
</P>
<P>
   John Gorman, 64, a retired fireman from Queens, N.Y. and a
parishioner from Our Lady Queen of Martyrs traveling on a package
tour to the Holy Land, said, ``The doors should be open. We are
Christians here, and they shouldn't be punishing the Christian
tourists who come. I don't see the benefit in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade Suther, 37, of Key Largo, Fla, stood with his wife and said
a silent prayer in front of the closed doors. He said he was
``disappointed'' not to be able to enter the shrine, but that he
understood and supported the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that the church wanted to protest what Israel did in
Nazareth, which was to make a decision that has turned the Muslims
and Christians against each other,'' said Suther. ``If Israel
intended to do a policy of divide and conquer, I would say their
policy is working.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem's Latin Patriarch Monsignor Michel Sabbah, said,
``This land was never a land without problems. Sadly, this is the
way of life here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabbah added that closing the shrines _ a decision led by the
six largest denominations including Greek Orthodox and Roman
Catholic _ was an important and historic statement that needed to
be made.
</P>
<P>
   Although the controversy arose after a militant group of Moslems
began pushing to build the mosque in Nazareth, the Christian church
leaders are directing their protest at the Israeli government,
which they accuse of fostering divisions betwen the Muslim majority
and Christian minority in Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the mosque have triggered sporadic violence over the
course of a two-year political battle that has been cast in
religious terms. The dispute erupted when Nazareth, which is headed
by a Christian mayor, said it wanted to use municipal land
adjoining the Church of the Annunciation for a public plaza to
accommodate millions of tourists expected to come to see the place
where Jesus lived much of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Some Moslems objected that one corner of the lot was the site of
a holy shrine to a Muslim martyr who fought against the Christian
Crusaders, and that the public plaza would desecrate the shrine. A
fringe group of Muslim hardliners from the Islamic Movement then
seized part of the land, erected a makeshift mosque, and blared
Mulsim calls to prayer on loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   The municipality insisted that the land had been taken
unlawfully by the Muslims and urged Israeli authorities to evict
the Muslim group.
</P>
<P>
   But two months ago, the Israeli authorities granted permission
for the Muslims to build the new mosque. The Israelis described it
as a compromise that would allow the Muslims to build the mosque
and the municipality to build the plaza to accommodate tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Shlomo Ben Ami, Israel's Minister of Internal Security, who took
part in the government's decision, said the Christian response was
``lamentable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never our intention to infringe upon the natural and
legitimate rights of the Christians in this country,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But the Christian churches see the Israeli decision as unusual
and historic intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closure of the church doors is a protest, to say that we
as Arab Christians exist. We have our dignity, and our right to be
respected, not only as Christians, but as human beings,'' explained
Sabbah, the Latin patriarch.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Timothy, a bishop of the Greek Orthodox Church,
said, ``We get along well with our Muslim neighbors. We have never
been against the building of a mosque. What we are against is this
specific site, which is a provocation by a very small group of
Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabbah and Timothy are leaders among the steadily diminishing
Christian population in Jerusalem, the West Bank, and Israel. The
number of Arab Christians has fallen from nearly 20 percent of the
population in the early part of the century to less than 2 percent
today. At this rate, demographers predict that the indigenous
Christian community could virtually disappear within a generation
from the land where the faith began.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian community here regards the millennium celebration
as an unique opportunity to inform the world of its imperiled
existence and to point out the unique struggles it faces as a
minority religion often caught between the Jewish state and the
predominantly Muslim Palestinian population.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Kandalaft, an adviser to Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on Christian affairs, played down the controversy.
``Everybody should be excited about the expectations for peace in
the Middle East as we enter the third millennium. That is the big
celebration. So any problems, any tensions in Nazareth, any work in
Bethlehem, any overcrowding in the Holy Sepulchre, that is going to
pass,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Holy Land prepares to receive millions of pilgrims
and what is expected to be an historic visit by the Pope in March,
it remains to be seen whether the recent problems and disputes are
merely the kind of tensions that surface within a family before a
big celebration, or something more profound.
</P>
<P>
   A lot is at stake _ not just billions of dollars in tourism but
perhaps something larger, the chance for the turning of the
calendar year 2000 to be an occasion for new enlightenment and
understanding in a land shared by three monotheistic faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Rosen, director of the Anti-Defamation League in
Jerusalem, acknowledged that there were points of tension around
the coming millennium, but he stressed that there is also a spirit
of interfaith dialogue. He noted that he was at a conference Monday
that brought together Christian and Muslim leaders of Nazareth at
the very moment that the church doors were closing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a spirit that is moving ahead on interfaith
understanding,'' he said, ``even if many feel it is moving too
slowly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
