<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-GRETZKY-HALL-COX     11-22 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-HALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gretzky inducted into hockey's Hall
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Wayne Gretzky hasn't worn a pair of skates since his
tearful farewell, No. 99 waving goodbye as he circled the rink one
last time.
</P>
<P>
   But to hockey fans, he will always glide on ice, remembered as
the greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Just seven months and a few days after his final game at New
York's Madison Square Garden on April 18, Gretzky was inducted into
the Hockey Hall of Fame on Monday amid an outpouring of love rarely
showered on anyone.
</P>
<P>
   No. 99 in 1999. How perfect.
</P>
<P>
   A player is supposed to have to wait three years after
retirement to be eligible for the Hall of Fame. But not the Great
One, who first visited the Hall at its old location in Toronto when
he was 11. As a teenager he used to stand for hours looking at the
memorabilia and dreaming about someday playing in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have a plaque up there with all the ones I used to stare
at,'' said Gretzky, who was born about 70 miles away in Brantford,
Ontario. ``What a thrill. I never even dreamed about this. It's the
icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, 38, was inducted with retired referee Andy Van
Hellemond and Scotty Morrison, a former NHL referee-in-chief and
Hall of Fame chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison wore a kilt to the ceremonies. But he couldn't steal
the spotlight from Gretzky, who holds or shares 61 NHL records and
is Canada's most celebrated athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Van Hellemond said, ``I'll be part of a great hockey trivia
question, `Who were the other two stiffs that went in with No. 99?'
I wore No. 25, by the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame considered moving the induction ceremonies to
the nearby Air Canada Center, the new home of the Toronto Maple
Leafs. But Gretzky nixed the idea. ``He wanted to go in like
everyone else,'' said Bill Hay, chairman of the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets sold out quickly, with 2,000 people each paying $300
(Canadian) to sit in the BCE Place atrium and watch the ceremonies
on a large screen. About 500 invited guests were allowed into the
Hall of Fame for the ceremonies _ televised live in Canada and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was all Gretzky, all the time in Toronto, his every moved
chronicled. The Toronto Star and Toronto Sun both put out special
sections, although they already had published Wayne Gretzky
tributes when he retired.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was an emotional day for Gretzky. But not as emotional as
his last game, he said. ``I had peace of mind and knew I had made
the right decision,'' he said. ``But so many people were pulling at
me to keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky says he has no regrets about his decision, although he
``misses hockey greatly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss game day. I miss every day,'' he said. ``It's a special
bond athletes have. When you are no longer part of it, you are an
outsider looking in. All players go through it. We all become
ex-players. That's what I am now.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Gordie Howe retired, they said there would never be
another Gordie Howe. But then along came Bobby Orr. . . . Hockey
will always have its stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably miss hockey more than hockey misses Wayne
Gretzky,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his next dream was, Gretzky said, ``To come back and
play again.'' Just joking. ``I said I would retire only one time,''
Gretzky said. ``And I'm officially retired.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from idle, however. He has appeared in commercials as an
endorser for everything from tires to hamburgers to pain remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to keep from missing hockey too much is to keep
busy,'' Gretzky said.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky lives in Thousand Oaks, Calif., with his wife, former
actress Janet Jones, their two sons and a daughter. The boys enjoy
hockey, but Gretzky says he won't push them into the sport, as his
father did him.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Gretzky saved almost everything from his son's career,
and now it's part of a Hall of Fame exhibit that covers 2,300
square feet. ``We have everything but his pacifier,'' Hall official
Hay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a proud time for Wayne and me,'' Walter Gretzky said.
``I miss seeing him play, but it was his decision. He thought it
was time to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Someday, Wayne Gretzky says, he might be a part of the NHL
again, not just one of its biggest fans. Certainly, he will return
to the ice, if only for fun.
</P>
<P>
   But first he must get a pair of skates. ``I don't have any
now,'' he said. ``I gave my skates to the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   GRETZKY'S ALL-TIME TEAM
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky calls himself a ``real hockey traditionalist.''
But there is nothing traditional about his all-time NHL all-star
team, which includes only one defenseman, a surprise pick in goal
-- and no Gretzky:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bobby Orr: ``With Bobby on your team, you need only one
defenseman. And with this lineup, we wouldn't have to worry about
defense, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gordie Howe: ``My first, and still, hockey hero.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Maurice Richard: ``Who was ever better as a goal scorer?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jean Beliveau: ``One of my all-time favorites. He was so
elegant on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mario Lemieux: ``Best I ever played against in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Grant Fuhr: ``Not only the best goalie, but the greatest
athlete I ever saw play in the NHL. He was unbelievable with the
Oilers.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Curtright writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
