<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MOROCCO-BOURSE-ART-2T     11-22 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOROCCO-BOURSE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VIRTUAL OASIS FOR MOROCCO STOCKS: TRADING GOING ON HERE? 
 SHOCKING! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tunisia, Lebanon, Jordan, Egypt, Nev.) (ART ADV: Two photos, NYT 22 and 23, and a graphic are being sent.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASABLANCA, Morocco _ The trading floor of the Casablanca Stock
Exchange, with just 30 traders working in little computer cubicles,
is as quiet as a church and it is about to get even quieter.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, the trading floor is shutting down, exchange
officials say, thrusting Casablanca's small, young, but
technologically hip stock market into the growing ranks of virtual
exchanges around the world.
</P>
<P>
   As in London, Paris, Brussels, Toronto, Sao Paulo, Brazil, and a
rising number of other places, brokers here will be trading
directly from their own offices in a kind of miniature Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be cruising on the electronic highway,'' said Zouheir
Bensaid, the immediate past president of the exchange and now a
senior executive at one of the country's biggest financial
companies, Group BMCE.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion will add efficiency to domestic trading and make
it technically possible for brokers anywhere to trade directly in
the Moroccan market. It is an impressive step, and one that several
other Middle East stock markets are expected to emulate in the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
   After long, sleepy histories, this region's stock exchanges have
caught the attention of government officials as vital tools for
selling state-owned companies and attracting foreign investors as
they move from centrally planned economies to free enterprise. Like
the exchange here, in a mirror-paneled office block in downtown
Casablanca, many are being revitalized with advanced systems and
are attracting platoons of young Arab financial whizzes with MBA's
and job experience in New York, London and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Casablanca's shift to decentralized, computerized operation
comes as the New York Stock Exchange, one of the remaining great
halls of hubbub and clanging bells, is debating a move toward
greater automation. It comes as the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
with its shouting and hand-waving traders, has introduced the same
French-designed system the Moroccans are using.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the countries in this region are in the technological
vanguard, financial experts say, they will have to overcome
significant impediments before they can expect the kind of foreign
investment that has poured into the emerging markets of Asia, Latin
America and Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   One problem for Morocco and neighbors like Tunisia, Lebanon and
Jordan is size. Their markets are minuscule. There are 55 companies
traded on the Casablanca exchange, with daily volume running at
about $10 million; in New York and London, many individual trades
surpass that figure. Tunisia has about 40 listings; Lebanon has a
little more than a dozen. Jordan has more than 150 companies
listed, but its daily trading volume is only about $2 million.
Although the Cairo Stock Exchange lists nearly 1,000 companies,
daily volume there is only about $22 million.
</P>
<P>
   Angus Blair, head of equity research on the Middle East and
North Africa at the London office of ABN Amro, the Dutch investment
bank and securities firm, said it was difficult for big
international investors even to consider putting money into a
market as small as Casablanca's. Mutual fund and pension fund
managers routinely put $500,000 to $5 million in a single
emerging-market stock. A daily volume of $10 million would not give
them much room to maneuver. ``You need to have high daily volumes
so you can get in and out of a stock easily,'' Blair said. ``The
last thing you want is for it to be difficult to sell while the
price is moving against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem in Morocco is that share prices are higher than
in the rest of the region _ more than twice the level, for example,
of those in Egypt. That is because, in an attempt to husband
foreign exchange, the government officially prohibits Moroccans
from investing abroad. Having no place else to go, the insurance
companies and the roughly 100 mutual funds that have sprung up here
in the last few years compete for the few stocks traded here,
pushing prices up.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco, like some of its neighbors, has signed an agreement
with the European Union that will eliminate tariffs and, experts
say, probably lead to a loosening of foreign exchange and investing
restrictions. But, they say, the changes will take years.
</P>
<P>
   After soaring for several years, the market here has gone into a
long slump, starting toward the end of summer last year. Foreign
investors, who held about 6 percent of the market's shares, began
taking their gains, financial experts say, to offset losses in Asia
and the former Soviet Union. Local investors were scared and began
withdrawing their money. From September to the end of December, the
market lost 12 percent, but it still closed the year with a gain of
20 percent. This year, with the economy depressed by one of the
country's periodic droughts, the market has been mainly flat.
</P>
<P>
   But Rachid Ouali Alami, chairman of the Casablanca Stock
Exchange, and many of his colleagues see better days ahead. In the
coming year, he said, the government is expected to offer, for the
first time, a large number of shares in Royal Air Maroc, the
national airline, as well as in the national telephone company. One
banker said work was under way on at least a dozen initial public
offerings of private companies. One sign of confidence: Two new
brokerage firms have just taken seats on the Casablanca exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The big job for the financial community is to persuade more of
Morocco's privately owned businesses to go public, enabling the
exchange to grow. But, the financial experts say, that is not going
to be easy. Karim El Fekkak, director general of ABN Amro in
Casablanca, estimates that there are more than 500 companies with
more than $1 million in capital that would be candidates for the
exchange. But, like most businesses in Morocco, they are family
owned and so far have shown little interest in sharing ownership.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that makes them reluctant, said Eric Stoclet, head of
Citibank in Casablanca, is that the family-owned companies ``don't
want to open their books.'' In Tunis the government has given tax
breaks to companies that go public, and there has been talk of that
here. But here, as in many emerging markets, financial experts say,
the privately held businesses are believed to be enjoying
substantial tax breaks already, and these would be hard for the
government to top.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As free trade with the European Union develops, Fekkak said,
competition from European imports is likely to push some private
companies into the market in search of financing to expand and
create economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
   Like others in the region, the government here has been
criticized for dragging out the process of selling off state-owned
companies, which began in 1993. After decades of foreign domination
before independence in the 1950s and 1960s, all the governments
fear being accused of permitting foreigners to gain control of
important segments of the economy. That is one reason governments
in the region have put only minority shares of many companies on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   But in late summer the government here scored a big success. It
auctioned off a license for a mobile phone company for $1.1
billion, about three times what was expected. The winning bidders,
a consortium of Europeans and Moroccans, said they expected to
invest $800 million in equipment. This was privatization at its
best. The government, in effect, gave up a piece of paper _ the
license _ in return for lots of money and, almost certainly, a huge
improvement in telephone service in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the mobile phone company is expected to be traded on
the stock exchange. (Such a company is a star of the Egyptian
market.) But one of many government regulations that frustrate
Morocco's young, aggressive financiers prohibits any company _ no
matter how strong and stable it seems _ from selling shares until
it has done business in the country for at least three years.
</P>
<P>
   In another drag on the stock market, the government this summer
introduced a capital gains tax of 10 percent, in response to
pressures from real estate brokers who said investment money that
once flowed to them was going into the stock market because of the
tax advantages. Foreign investors were exempt, but the tax was an
unsettling reminder of how terms of business can change overnight
in Morocco and other emerging markets. Early next year, the U.S.
Commerce Department plans to hold a conference in the United Arab
Emirates to encourage Middle East governments to work on
consistency in government administration and judicial procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, the procedures here are clear,'' said Bensaid, who
studied at Cornell University and received a degree in business at
the University of Nevada. ``But in practice, things are not that
clear. Once you get involved in a problem in the courts, it can go
on for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Tension with Algeria over Western Sahara, which in 1975 Morocco
claimed as an extension of its territory and where it still has
troops, remains a lingering uncertainty. But for Morocco's
financiers, the political picture brightened this summer with the
ascension to power of King Mohammed VI after the death of his
father, Hassan II, who had reigned for 38 years. Mohammed VI, 36,
has permitted the return from exile of political opponents of his
father and says he wants to reduce poverty and illiteracy.
Illiteracy is more than 40 percent, among the highest levels in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The young people giving the Casablanca Stock Exchange its spark
say that government officials, while cordial, have little training
or experience in finance. By contrast, the financiers felt an
instant rapport with the new king, they say, because of his youth
and his professed interest in bringing change to Morocco. He is
different from the men of his father's generation who have been
running the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our king,'' Bensaid said, ``is going to force those people to
let us do our work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
