A8296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-QSCHOOL-COX     11-22 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-QSCHOOL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweet day for Gary Nicklaus, but sour day for many more
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The sixth and final day of PGA Tour Qualifying School
always lives up to its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet end of the emotional spectrum Monday became Gary
Nicklaus, 30, son of Jack, shooting a final-round 63 to attain his
first PGA Tour card after a ninth trip to Q-School.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite fate came for Jaxon Brigman, 28, of Abilene, Texas,
who shot 8-under 412, but mistakenly signed for 7-under 413, and
missed by that single stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine the feeling when I found it out,'' Brigman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly shaken was Vic Wilk, who triple-bogeyed the Doral
Resort Gold Course's island-green 18th to drop from 9-under, in
with a stroke to spare, to 6-under, out by two.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Jay Hobby, who kept Brigman's scorecard, wrote down a
4 for the par-4 13th, but circled it as birdies usually are
designated. With five birdies, Brigman just counted the circles and
signed for a 5-under 65.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it didn't happen,'' said Hobby, who missed his tour
card, finishing at even-par 420. ``I bear some responsibility, but
in the end it's still his job to check the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia Tech player Michael Clark, 30, of Dalton, Ga.,
secured his tour card after missing by one stroke in 1996 and 1998.
Clark tied for 10th at 405. ``It's awesome,'' Clark said after a
69. ``My nerves got the best of me out there today, but I hung in.
I don't think it's really sunk in yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Also qualifying was Atlanta's Jason Buha of Duke, who tied for
30th at 9-under, and former Charleston player Jason Caron
(8-under). Ryuji Imada (67) missed by a shot at 7-under, and Tripp
Isenhour was off by two at 6-under.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nightmarish day for Moultrie, Ga.'s Kevin Blanton, who
woke up at 1 a.m. sweating and vomiting, then fought dehydration.
Starting at 7-under, Blanton bogeyed three of his first four holes
to destroy his chances for a tour card and finally struggled to a
73 for 4-under 416. He must settle for fully exempt status on the
Buy.com Tour in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Jack and Barbara Nicklaus were unable to follow their son
Monday. Instead, they attended the funeral in Latrobe, Pa., for
Arnold Palmer's wife, Winnie. Gary Nicklaus finished at 14-under
406, tying for 12th, five strokes behind medalist Blaine
McCallister, the 41-year-old tour veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long grind,'' Gary said. ``Six rounds this week, a
total of 14 through first and second stage. That's a lot of
pressure the last month and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
