<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-INJURIES (Washington) _ Business groups vow to fight
proposed federal regulations that would force many employers to
correct injury-causing workplace conditions that require repetitive
motion, overexertion or awkward posture. Each year, 1.8 million
workers have injuries related to those conditions, and 600,000
people miss some work because of them, according to government
figures. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FAA-Y2K (Washington) _ Lawmakers on the House Year 2000 computer
task force say the nation's air traffic control system will be
ready for any problems related to the year 2000 computer glitch.
The task force also reported that the vast majority of the federal
government's computers have been fixed and tested to properly
interpret Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-2000 (Washington) _ Census Bureau Director Kenneth
Prewitt says Houston officials were premature in criticizing his
agency's plans for the 2000 national population count. At the same
time, Prewitt says, Census 2000 could have trouble hiring enough
head-counters because of the nation's tight labor market. By ANDREW
BROMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BULGARIA (Sofia, Bulgaria) _ Standing in the historic
Nevski
</P>
<P>
   Square teeming with enthusiastic Bulgarians, President Clinton
calls on Serbia to follow the path of this former Communist
stronghold and cast aside dictatorship. Clinton offered
encouragement to this new democracy, still struggling to turn its
freedoms into economic wealth, and acknowledged the difficulties it
faced during and after the U.S.-led bombing campaign against
neighboring Yugoslavia. By NANCY MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CHURCH-STRIKE (Jerusalem) _ Frustrated tourists and
pilgrims find themselves locked out of holy sites in Bethlehem and
Jerusalem after Christian leaders close church doors throughout the
Holy Land to protest Israel's decision to let Muslims build a
mosque near a shrine in Nazareth. By DEBORAH HORAN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-PROFILE (Washington) _ A look at presidential candidate Al
Gore, his history, his rise to the vice presidency and his run for
president, and how he is trying to reinvigorate his campaign. By
CRAGG HINES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Exeter, N.H.) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush dodges
questions about whether he would refund the money that the Texas
Department of Public Safety has spent to protect him during his
quest for the Republican presidential nomination. By R.G.
RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-POLL (San Francisco) _ Vice President Al Gore and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush have comfortable leads over their party rivals
with four months to go before the primary in voter-rich California,
according to a new survey. The San Francisco Examiner/KTVU poll
shows Gore attracting more than double the support won by former
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, and nearly twice as many voters said
they would pick Bush over Arizona Sen. John McCain. By ROBERT
SALLADAY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The better Arizona Sen. John McCain
does with the public, the worse he does with his Republican Senate
colleagues. Several of them have made it clear that they don't like
him. But is that a badge of honor reflecting independence and
character or an alarming sign that he might have trouble governing?
By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
