<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR LOAN TURNS INTO A REAL LEMON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reader response to a recent column on the spread and
officiousness of monopolies convinces me that I must have touched a
nerve. Many of the comments reveal a brooding sense of alienation,
of being taken for granted and treated with cavalier indifference
by the ever bigger and more remotely run companies with which the
public is increasingly forced to deal.
</P>
<P>
   A psychiatrist in California writes of the ``dehumanizing''
effect of this trend toward megalopolies, and the frustrating
inability of customers to get anyone to listen. He decries what he
sees happening as the ``micro-miniaturization of the individual.''
He says it's making people ill.
</P>
<P>
   The most persistent complaint expressed to me is the frustration
of trying to communicate with anyone in authority.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the story of Kay and Craig Nelson and how they became
innocently entangled, to their relentless harassment, with the
computer of a large, distant finance company.
</P>
<P>
   The Nelsons own a suburban home. Their kids are grown, now
finished with college. Both have decent jobs. They're trying to put
just a bit aside each month toward retirement. Their credit record
has been spotless.
</P>
<P>
   In June of last year, they bought an almost-new Chrysler from a
reputable local dealer. He handled interim financing through the
Chase Manhattan auto financing division of Wilmington, Del., allied
with one of America's largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   But Kay figured that they could save $500 or so in interest over
the life of the payments by borrowing from the Fort Worth Federal
Credit Union, to which she belongs. That loan was arranged, and the
credit union sent Chase a check retiring the Nelsons' car note in
full before their first payment was due.
</P>
<P>
   The first hint of trouble came in the late summer of 1998. A
surprise telephone call at their residence insisted that their auto
payments to the Delaware company were two months in arrears. They
explained that the note had been paid off. Their caller said fine!
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 10, they received a letter, printed and unsigned, from
Chase ordering them to pay $902 in arrearages ``without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Their credit union, notified, immediately called the Delaware
company, whose officer claimed that they'd never received the June
check. Credit union loan officer Kyle Victry assured Chase that he
was putting a second check (for $21,821.62) in the overnight mail
and stopping payment on the first.
</P>
<P>
   Chase promptly credited the account with this amount, noting
that it included ``all interest due and complete payoff.'' This
should have ended it.
</P>
<P>
   Victry recalls expressly asking, and being assured, that the
Nelson family's credit record be protected from any negative
reflection. The Nelsons breathed a sigh of relief. But not for
long.
</P>
<P>
   In late October, they received another telephone call at home
from Chase's telephonic collectors, stating that payments were
overdue and demanding that the Nelsons pay up promptly! Unable to
satisfy her insistent caller, Kay visited her credit union again.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 2, Victry once more called Chase Manhattan, reminding
the company that the account had been closed and faxing copies of
the canceled check and previous correspondence. Fine, he was
assured.
</P>
<P>
   In early November, another harassing call. Same result. Same
assurances.
</P>
<P>
   Comes Nov. 24. Another collection call from Chase's dunning
team. This time, the caller insisted the Nelsons owed Chase more
than $3,000, demanding immediate payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than once,'' recalls Craig Nelson, ``my wife has been
near tears in anger and frustration from trying to stop this
recurring harassment, which was Chase's error in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Again the Nelsons called Chase, were assured that all records
would be cleared up ``by the end of the week.'' They wouldn't be
bothered further.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Dec. 9, Chase unaccountably mailed the Nelsons a book
of blank payment coupons. By now gun-shy, Kay called once more,
just for reassurance. Told that ``the account is clear. It has a
zero balance,'' Kay asked for a letter to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was puzzling. It said that the account was closed and
that ``your final payment of $25.32 was received on Wednesday, Dec.
2.''
</P>
<P>
   Goofy, since the whole thing had been paid off in June, and
again in September. But reassuring. The matter was ended.
</P>
<P>
   Or was it?
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Craig _ attracted by the interest-free claims of a
new credit card advertisement _ wrote for information and an
application form. On April 2, he received a rejection, saying that
Trans Union Corp. of Springfield, Penn., (one of three major credit
bureaus) had reported derogatory information.
</P>
<P>
   Puzzled, Nelson wrote Trans Union. That company replied that
Chase Manhattan in December (two months after acknowledging receipt
of the second final payment) had reported the Nelsons' account 120
days overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, this private American family (my daughter and
son-in-law, as it happens), who'd never been behind on any of their
payments to anyone, have tried earnestly _ shall I say maddeningly?
_ to clear up their credit record.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's more than a year since the Nelsons' credit records
should have been purged of the hurtful stain so undeservedly dumped
on them by the distant bank. But last month, applying to open a
department store account, Kay was embarrassed before friends and
told her credit was unworthy, based on ``negative information from
Chase Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig, usually laid back, is boiling now. He has hired a lawyer
to straighten things out with the muscle-bound megabank. More power
to him!
</P>
<P>
   Wake up, all you greedy, distant, computer-driven institutions.
Take a moment from counting profits to consider the private
citizens whose lives you can so carelessly disrupt.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101 or e-mail him at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
