<HEADER>
A8315 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-GRETZKY-BOS &LR;      11-22 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY ACCEPTS HOCKEY'S TOP HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Looking trim, fit, and rested, Wayne Gretzky
blushingly accepted hockey's greatest honor here Monday, pulling on
the Hockey Hall of Fame's dark blue blazer and slipping one more
sparkling ring of distinction on his finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure of my next dream,'' said the 38-year-old icon,
who grew up in Brantford, Ontario, merely an hour's drive from the
august, mahogany-paneled hall. ``I spent 26 years of my life
dreaming that I'd be a part of _ and then staying in _ the National
Hockey League. I want to be clear-minded about (what's next), and
right now I'm not exactly sure what that will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The bet here is that Gretzky, who for the better part of two
decades made smithereens of the NHL record book, is a key player
again in the game, but as an owner, his stick and sweater swapped
for spread sheet and business suit.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a surprise to see that happen before 2004, the year
the current Collective Bargaining Agreement expires, because NHL
franchises at the moment are a sure ticket to bankruptcy rather
than a license to print money. Gretzky continues to amass a fortune
_ the endorsement business is that strong _ even seven months after
retiring from the Rangers. But the economics of the game at the
moment are so, shall we say, precarious (witness Roger Marino's $45
million loss in Pittsburgh and the $80 million Peter Karmanos is in
the process of blowing in Carolina), that it takes a billionaire's
cavalier mindset and black-hole pockets to even consider getting in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   By 2004, either player salaries will have become manageable
(recent cheaper signings of unrestricted free agents have given
promise there) or league owners will implement another lockout,
only this time with the resolve not to put down the ice until the
players agree to a legitimate salary cap. One way or the other, the
X factor of labor cost will be something other than the current
game of dead-man's roulette.
</P>
<P>
   When all that comes into focus, the suspicion here is that
Gretzky, a master of timing his entire career, will swoop in and
purchase a franchise, most likely with a partner or two. It would
be everything he has stood for in his life: a challenge, a true
competition, with dollar signs rather than Stanley Cups defining
wins and losses.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years after playing in his first game, Gretzky, who
was inducted along with Ian ``Scotty'' Morrisson (builder) and
referee Andy Van Hellemond, appeared comfortable and content during
the ceremony before some 200 media members.
</P>
<P>
   The Gretzky trademark humility, as telltale as his No. 99 and
his perfectly executed passes, remained predictably intact.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Gretzky on:
</P>
<P>
   --How he changed the game _ ``I don't think any one person is
going to be bigger than the game. I don't think any one person can
drastically make changes in the game. It's a great game, and it
will continue to flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   --Whether he'd like to see a trophy named in his honor _ ``One
of the special aspects of the league is its collection of trophies,
like the Stanley Cup, the Art Ross Trophy, the Hart Trophy. It's
something our league has that a lot of other leagues don't have. I
played in the '80s and '90s. I think before anything is done for
Wayne Gretzky, something has to be done for players like Gordie
Howe and Bobby Orr. I'm way down the totem pole in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if anyone showed up expecting Gretzky once and
for all to exhort a well-deserved, ``Yahoo! Check this out, man, I
did it!,'' then they haven't been paying attention for the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky was appropriately glassy-eyed when he stood to pull on
the Hall's blue jacket. More telling, his face turned a deep red.
There are those who can fake a tear or two, but even those who have
won as many Oscars as Gretzky has won Stanleys (4) cannot on cue
turn the hue of that line that runs across the middle of the ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Great One was clearly touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to come to the Hall of Fame when it was at Exhibition
Place,'' he recalled. ``I used to come for hours and look at the
old pictures _ I loved to look at those, along with the old
sweaters and old sticks. The Hall of Fame didn't have interactive
exhibits then. You came to the Hall and you read, you looked, you
absorbed, and yeah you dreamed of being in the NHL. But I don't
think any of us thought we were good enough to be in the Hall of
Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the stage where his son talked, Walter Gretzky
sounded overwhelmed by it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' said the senior Gretzky, wearing a leather
jacket with his famous son's name on the chest. ``I mean, this is
hockey, right here, this is the shrine.''
</P>
<P>
   When the induction was over, Gretzky strolled around the Hall
and did exactly what he did as a kid, only this meandering along a
lengthy row of display cases told his story. Thanks to his dad, a
meticulous keeper of artifacts (read: pack rat), Gretzky's life has
been chronicled from his very first pair of leather skates (barely
big enough to hold two decent-sized eggs).
</P>
<P>
   Above the Gretzky display, a wonderful videotape plays over and
over, spiced by remarks from dad and son. For the record, the
backyard rink in Brantford wasn't put up for the purpose of turning
Wayne into a hockey wonder. It was, said Walter, simply a response
to standing around cold rinks while his son played.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, I could stay in the house and keep warm,'' said
Walter. ``It was self-preservation, and that's the honest truth.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, the Great One had to admit, ``A nice feeling to walk
around and see your picture there.''
</P>
<P>
   All those games and points later, his likeness will remain
there, in perpetuity. For generations to stand, to stare, to
absorb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably miss the game more than the game misses Wayne
Gretzky,'' said the humble honoree.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt that's true, but it's equally doubtful he'll be gone
too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
