u s BC-BOX-IBF-CHARGES-525&AMP;A     11-22 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-IBF-CHARGES-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PROSECUTOR ASKS COURT TO OVERSEE BOXING GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Skedded in FRONTPAGE as BOX-INDICT) 
(lb) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ In the first attempt by federal law enforcement
officials to take over a private sports organization, the U.S.
attorney's office asked a federal judge on Monday to appoint a
monitor to run the International Boxing Federation, whose leaders
were indicted early this month on racketeering and bribery charges.
</P>
<P>
   If the prosecutors' request is granted in a hearing scheduled
for Tuesday, the IBF would become the first sports group to join a
collection of organizations, including the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters and the Fulton Fish Market in New York,
that have been taken over by the courts amid allegations of
corruption and racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   In making the request in a civil lawsuit, the prosecutors asked
that Zachary Taylor, a former U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, N.Y., be
appointed as the monitor. He would have subpoena power and a
sweeping mandate to restructure the organization and to replace all
its top officials, with the overall goal of changing the way the
organization does business.
</P>
<P>
   The boxing federation, with headquarters in East Orange, is the
only U.S.-based organization that ranks boxers and sanctions
championship bouts.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the action are expected to raise fears that federal
prosecutors and judges are trying to establish themselves as the
equivalent of boxing czars in the absence of any congressional
mandate. But for those who have long criticized the IBF and other
boxing ranking groups as corrupt and manipulated by a few
well-placed people in the industry, the request is likely to be
welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   The civil lawsuit, filed by U.S. Attorney Robert Cleary, the
chief federal prosecutor for northern New Jersey, comes nearly
three weeks after a federal grand jury indicted the four top
officials of the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-count indictment accused the officials of soliciting
bribes from fighters and promoters to move boxers up in the
rankings. Such rankings, whether given by the International Boxing
Federation, the World Boxing Council or the World Boxing
Association, allow fighters to qualify for bouts with television
proceeds that can run into millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is the first time that government has sought to
take control of a sports organization,'' Cleary said at a news
conference announcing the civil action. ``Along with the indictment
of November 4, this constitutes a devastating one-two punch to the
IBF, which we seek to resurrect as an organization free of
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Lee Sr., the IBF president, who was among the
officials indicted, called the latest action by Cleary's office
unfair and said it would create turmoil in boxing. Lee said the
request for a court-appointed monitor amounted to saying that he
and his three co-defendants in the federal racketeering case were
guilty before they had gone to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little heavy-handed and they are out to make it
appear that I am guilty until proven innocent,'' he said in an
interview. ``If I am convicted, it's another story. But to come in
and create this kind of turmoil looks like something that is
orchestrated to create problems.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gerard Lynch, a professor at Columbia University's School of
Law, said that the Racketeer-Influenced and Corrupt Organizations
Act of 1970 provided a powerful tool for criminal prosecutions by
the federal authorities and also created a number of civil
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The law permits the government, with the approval of a judge, to
intervene immediately in the affairs of a business or union when
there is concern about the disposition of assets. That the leaders
of a business or a union are under criminal indictment is important
in such cases, but it is not the only factor that determines
whether a judge appoints a court monitor.
</P>
<P>
   These civil racketeering actions have been criticized in the
past by the affected unions, which have complained that such
actions give prosecutors and judges the authority to make policy
that is usually reserved for Congress. Lynch said that some critics
of the tactics used by Cleary's office may argue that prosecutors
are trying to enter an area where Congress has refused to take
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still,'' he said, ``U.S. attorneys have been known to bring
cases such as this that are designed to impact whole industries.''
Lynch recalled drives against white-collar crime, including
securities fraud on Wall Street, by Rudolph Giuliani when he was
the U.S. attorney in New York in the 1980s. ``I'm sure that the
primary position of the prosecutor's office here is that they are
not trying to regulate boxing but are trying to clean up corruption
and crime wherever they find it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
