<HEADER>
A8321 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-AMERICAN-HOLLOW-RE     11-22 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICAN-HOLLOW-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KENNEDY EXPLORES RURAL AMERICAN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:  2.5 stars  
(Eds: Not for use before Monday, Nov. 29) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An exercise in perceptions: Throw white-trash hillbillies on
``Jerry Springer'' and it's considered exploitative fisticuffs.
Present them in an HBO documentary directed by a scion of the
Kennedy dynasty, however, and it's a sensitive evocation of a
disappearing culture.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes with Rory Kennedy's ``American Hollow,'' one in an
ongoing series of documentaries of life in these United States in
HBO's ``America Undercover'' series. This is one of those
documentaries that isn't really about anything in particular; the
cameras simply spend a year flitting like horseflies around
68-year-old Irie Bowling and her family _ her husband, Bass, their
13 kids, 30 grandchildren and seven great-grandchildren. All but a
son dwell in the remote Kentucky hills of Mudlick Hollow (at least
the scenery is pretty), where they're uniformly underemployed and
underengaged by life _ quaffing beer seems to be as good as it gets
'round these parts. Nonetheless, Kennedy follows the clan around,
hoping something compelling will happen.
</P>
<P>
   And something does, sort of, eventually, but Kennedy never quite
captures on film whatever it is about Irie and her kin that
inspired her and that she thought might be instructive for the rest
of the country. Likewise, it's unclear why we should be lamenting
the inevitable passing of this backward culture, as this
hard-scrabble brood clearly demonstrates that innocence and naivete
aren't all they're cracked up to be.
</P>
<P>
   There's Lanzo, one of Irie's sons, who drops pearls of wisdom
like, ``If you can't help yourself, you can't help nobody _ you
ever think of that?'' and gets fidgety because his Prozac hasn't
arrived from town. (Pep pills and ubiquitous satellite dishes are
the main evidence that the 20th century has arrived in the
Appalachians _ otherwise, the Bowling homes seem what might be
charitably called ramshackle.) Edgar, another son, is jailed under
suspicion of breaking and entering; he's eventually released, but
not before Bass sagely observes, ``Ain't no disgrace being put in
jail, just staying there'' (many in the family seem to have a
couple of drunk and disorderlies on their police record).
</P>
<P>
   Daughter Samantha veers most uncomfortably into Springer
territory, fleeing a violently abusive husband that the rest of the
family can't seem to control. Then there's Clint, a high-school
senior, who seems to comprehend that Mudlick life is a deadend, but
finds it tough to summon up the courage to leave. He'd stay if his
girlfriend Shirley would just agree to marry him _ Shirley's an old
maid by Appalachian standards; she notes that she has friends who
got married in the seventh grade and were moms by age 12, though
she allows, ``I do think that's kinda young.'' When Clint and
Shirley go through one of their routine separations, however,
Clint's own dark, misogynist side seeps through.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is punctuated by brief, incongruously perky segments
in which the family celebrates sundry holidays, accompanied by
sprightly bluegrass music on the soundtrack. But Kennedy has
unearthed too many unsettling facts about these hayseeds to
convincingly portray them as carefree in these moments. Just as the
Bowlings scour the hillsides for roots and moss that earns them
meager dollars, ``American Hollow'' pans for the grit in this
bucolic setting and discovers sobering yet unsurprising truths
about a long-ago and far-away terrain where you wouldn't even want
to visit, let alone live.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The  &LR; show &UR; : &LR;  ``American Hollow.''
</P>
<P>
   What &UR; : &LR;  Rory Kennedy's documentary in HBO's ``America
Undercover'' series about
</P>
<P>
   the trials of an Appalachian family.
</P>
<P>
   Where &UR; : &LR;  HBO.
</P>
<P>
   When &UR; : &LR;  8 p.m Monday; also Dec. 2 and 14.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating &UR; : &LR;  2.5 stars
</P>
</TEXT>
