<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8323 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ESPIONAGE-BOS &LR;      11-22 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ESPIONAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS CASE A TEST OF RUSSIAN JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If retired navy captain Alexander Nikitin thought he
was off the hook when a Russian court dismissed espionage charges
against him last year, he was wrong. Tuesday he will be back on
trial again, defending himself against the same accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Rights groups say that Nikitin's plight is a disturbing reminder
that rule of law can be a malleable thing when it suits the
interests of Russia's powerful military and security services.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this case is decided on its merits and according to the
law, we will win,'' said Yury Shmidt, Nikitin's defense attorney,
Monday. ``Our only fear is that certain political forces will try
to pressure the court and influence the verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   A retired naval officer turned environmentalist, Nikitin was
arrested in February 1996 by the Federal Security Service or FSB,
successor to the feared Soviet-era KGB.
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin's crime? He co-authored a report on the slipshod
handling of nuclear waste by Russia's northern fleet. Nikitin said
he used only public sources to write the report and was acting in
the public's interests -- trying to bring international attention
to what he calls a creeping ecological disaster _ in hopes of
attracting funds for a clean up.
</P>
<P>
   The FSB, saying Nikitin revealed state secrets, branded him a
traitor and a spy.
</P>
<P>
   After spending 10 months in prison, Nikitin was released on bond
in December 1996. In October of last year, a court in St.
Petersburg ruled that the FSB -- after investigating for nearly
three years -- had not proven its espionage case against Nikitin.
But under Russian law, a verdict of not guilty does not necessarily
mean innocent. Instead of clearing Nikitin, the court ordered the
FSB to investigate further and come up with stronger evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Now they will bring their case to court again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' Nikitin said in an interview Monday. ``I don't
want to make any predictions, but I am confident we can win. I hope
that the voice of the world community will be heard and we will
overcome the arbitrary rule of the FSB.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin's case has attracted attention all over the world. When
he was in jail, the rights group Amnesty International labeled him
a ``prisoner of conscience,'' the first Russian accorded that
designation since the late Nobel laureate Andrei Sakharov. Senator
Edward Kennedy and four other United States senators have signed a
letter to the court in support of Nikitin, Kennedy's Washington
office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The case has had its fair share of Kafka-like absurdities.
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin was charged with revealing state secrets through his
environmental work, although Russia's constitution forbids
ecological information from being classified. He was held for eight
months before he was formally charged. When he was, the indictment
was classified and investigators said its contents were so secret
that even they didn't know its contents.
</P>
<P>
   The report Nikitin co-authored, published by the Norwegian
environmental group Bellona, has been branded ``forbidden
literature'' by the authorities here. Customs officials have
confiscated hundreds of copies of the report, which is available on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With the FSB following him and his family around, Nikitin feared
for their safety. His 21-year-old daughter Yulya now studies at Mt.
Ida College in Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the law was followed in the first place, Nikitin would have
never been arrested. If the law is followed now, this case will be
dismissed tomorrow,'' said St. Petersburg-based human rights
activist Yury Vdovin.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nikitin's case was the first high-profile prosecution
of an environmental researcher, it is not unique.
</P>
<P>
   In July, military journalist Grigory Pasko was convicted of
improper conduct - but acquitted of espionage - for filing reports
to a Japanese television station about nuclear dumping by Russia's
pacific fleet.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the FSB raided the apartment and laboratory of
physicist and environmentalist Vladimir Soifer, who was studying
nuclear contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the FSB charged Igor Sutyagin, a leading Russian
nuclear arms researcher who studied nuclear safety issues, with
treason. Boston native Josh Handler, a graduate student from
Princeton University, had his Moscow apartment searched and was
questioned in Sutyagin's case. Handler has since left Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   This summer Prime Minister Vladimir Putin - who was then FSB
director - warned that Russia's security services were going to
crack down on ecologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, foreign secret services use not only diplomatic cover,
but very actively use all sorts of ecological organizations,''
Putin said in July. ``This is why regardless of pressure from the
public and the media, such organizations will always be the focus
of our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was worried that as premier, Putin would now
influence the court in Nikitin's case, his lawyer said: ``I just
hope that the prime minister is too busy with other matters to
worry about our case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
