<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8328 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BIBLE-SCHOOL-COX     11-22 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-SCHOOL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia attorney general not sure if Bible classes would survive
challenges
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Georgia wants to teach the Bible in public schools,
it faces a number of legal risks, the state attorney general said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thurbert Baker said he cannot assure the state
school board that Bible history courses would survive challenges
under the Georgia or U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courses that include reference to the Bible may survive First
Amendment scrutiny only if their content is determined to be
secular and they are taught in a secular, objective manner,'' Baker
said in an opinion sought by the state Board of Education in
August.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of Baker's six-page letter, the opinion made it
seem difficult, if not impossible, to make that judgment call
without seeing how the course was actually taught.
</P>
<P>
   Courses only about the Bible are inherently suspect, federal
courts have found, because they sidestep other religious beliefs
and are generally Christian in orientation, Baker's opinion said.
Furthermore, the ``method and context'' of the instruction would
have to be monitored, and that would be the job of local boards,
not the state board, the attorney general said.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Brumby, the state school board chairman, said he thinks the
legal opinion raises concerns that confirm the board's wisdom in
seeking Baker's guidance in the first place. But what to do now
will have to wait until the board discusses this further on Dec. 9,
he said. Clearly, the courses can't be ruled legal until it is
determined how they are taught in the classroom, Brumby said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year at least two Georgia school systems _ Decatur
and McDuffie counties _ sought state funding for courses on the Old
Testament and the New Testament as history and literature based on
course outlines developed by the North Carolina-based National
Council on Bible Curriculum in Public Schools. Lee County also took
public comment on the proposed high school elective courses, but
did not take action.
</P>
<P>
   Only McDuffie County schools actually taught the course _ for
one day _ until the state school board postponed a decision, Brumby
said.
</P>
<P>
   A third proposed course that drew the same cautions from Baker
is ``Scientific and Religious Perspectives on Life and
Intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Local school districts can offer electives at their own expense,
such as drivers' education, but few do so. Local boards would face
the same legal risks that Baker outlined for the state.
</P>
<P>
   State school Superintendent Linda Schrenko has given support for
state funding of the courses. The attorney general's opinion cited
Schrenko's assurances that these particular courses have a secular
purpose _ one of three requirements set by the U.S. Supreme Court
for a faith-related matter to be legally supported by government.
But he said other experts could disagree with Schrenko's experts at
the Department of Education on this.
</P>
<P>
   Schrenko could not be reached for comment Monday on Baker's
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Other state school board members interpreted the opinion in a
variety of ways. Cathy Henson said the warnings suggest to her that
it's safer to stay away from the Bible courses, especially since
courses in comparative religion are already offered in public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But board member Bruce Jackson said the attorney general's
opinion doesn't resolve anything. He also said the issue is
designed to raise political controversy to help certain
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said of Schrenko and others: ``She's one of the
politicians who has something to gain from this; they get the
political mileage whether we approve it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   At last Thursday's board meeting, Sen. Tommie Williams (R-Lyons)
and Rep. Tommy Smith (D-Alma) presented a bill they said they would
introduce in January in support of state-funded Bible courses if
the board doesn't resolve the issue on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kintisch, a lawyer who runs the social-justice advocacy
agency called Center for Children and Education, said the problem
with Baker's opinion is that it did not analyze the specific
courses. The Fort Myers, Fla., school system was sued last year for
offering Bible-history classes presented by the organization that
created the courses the Georgia school districts sought to teach. A
settlement of the Florida case required that the New Testament
curriculum be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   While teaching religion in a devotional way may be
constitutionally risky, teaching about religion is viewed by the
courts and many educational experts as an important aspect of high
school education.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't teach U.S. history and world history without
teaching about religion,'' said Robbyn Greer, social studies
coordinator for Clayton County, Ga., schools. Greer taught a
state-funded course in Clayton County on the Bible as literature
more than 15 years ago. More recently, Greer taught in a
state-approved course the role of religion as it shaped American
history through the Pilgrims, the Puritans, the First and Second
Great Awakenings and the development of Methodism.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the instruction legal ``takes an awareness of whether
you're actually promoting religion or teaching about religion,''
Greer said. This is not as difficult as it might sound, regardless
of the teacher's personal convictions, because ``the role of a
teacher is to teach students to think, draw conclusions and
analyze,'' Greer said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cumming writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
