u w BC-RSI-INJURIES-2TAKES(T     11-22 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RSI-INJURIES-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED FEDERAL RULES TOUCH OFF DEBATE ABOUT REPETITIVE STRESS
INJURIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ill., Ore.) (sw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Proposed new federal rules aimed at preventing
on-the-job injuries from repetitive motion touched off a
wide-ranging debate on Monday over how such injuries occur, what
they cost American businesses and what can be done to avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   Just as federal bans on sexual harassment in the workplace led
to years of training programs, lawsuits and arguments over
compensatory payments, the rules announced on Monday by Labor
Secretary Alexis M. Herman will generate thousands of claims and
counterclaims, labor and business groups said.
</P>
<P>
   Challenges will focus on the definitions of injury, the extent
to which an employer can be blamed, and the vagueness of the
government's rules, both sides said.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions said on Monday that they would train their members
to recognize and report violations of new workplace rules intended
to prevent injuries resulting from repetitive motion, heavy
lifting, bending, twisting, pushing and pulling. And employers said
they would probably challenge the rules in court.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herman unveiled the proposals on Monday and said the Clinton
administration would issue final rules, with the force of law,
before the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   More than 27 million workers at 1.9 million work sites will be
protected by the standards, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The rules do not specify how much weight a worker may lift, nor
do they explicitly limit the number of hours that a person may work
at a computer. Instead, they require employers to follow certain
procedures intended to minimize workplace injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Employers must, for example, respond promptly to all reports of
workplace injuries, analyze the risks of various jobs, change work
practices to reduce the hazards and provide free medical treatment
to employees who are injured.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce, the National Association of
Manufacturers and other business trade associations denounced the
rules as hopelessly vague. The chamber, which represents 3 million
businesses, said it would challenge the rules in court.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew L. Stern, president of the Service Employees
International Union, which represents 675,000 health care workers,
and Eric Frumin, health and safety director at the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees, hailed the rules as
a major new protection for millions of workers.
</P>
<P>
   The unions said they would teach workers how to enforce their
rights under the new rules, issued by the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The OSHA standards have the potential to make a huge
difference in the day-to-day lives of working Americans,'' Frumin
said. ``We will expand our training programs on ergonomics. We'll
make sure workers know their rights, including the right to file
injury reports and the right to get their jobs fixed. We expect
thousands of workers to file complaints with employers and with
OSHA.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said his union would teach its local leaders how to use
the new standards in bargaining with nursing homes. In addition, he
said, the union will distribute pamphlets explaining the new rules
and will develop ``incident reporting forms,'' so hospital and
nursing home employees can report hazardous conditions and
violations of the new standards.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA, which regulates workplace safety, said the rules would
cost employers $4.2 billion a year. But the agency said that
employers would save $9 billion a year because workers would be
more productive, would suffer fewer injuries and would lose fewer
days of work. At the same time, it said, employers will spend less
money on workers' compensation, health insurance, the investigation
of injuries and the retraining of workers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Individual employers, especially large employers, said they had
already taken steps like those that would be required by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Golden, a spokesman for Deere &AMP; Co., the world's largest
manufacturer of farm equipment, said: ``We're in ergonomics for the
long haul because it's wise business. We've had an ergonomics
program since 1984. Eighty percent of the problems can be fixed for
$200 or less.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden said Deere's contract with the United Automobile Workers
provided for a full-time company-paid union member in every plant
to look for ergonomic problems and to suggest improvements. At the
Harvester plant in East Moline, Ill., Golden said, the company
found a way of raising and lowering parts that have to be welded
together, so the job is equally comfortable for a 6-foot-4 man on
one shift and a 5-foot-3 woman on another.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim M. Wordsworth, the owner of a restaurant and catering
business in McLean, Va., said the rules could have a ``devastating
impact'' on some small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine, for example, that you go bowling every night and
develop a wrist problem,'' Worsworth said. ``Your job is to enter
data on a computer. The computer keyboard did not cause your
injury, but could aggravate it. In some circumstances, you could
then qualify for six months of paid leave, with 90 percent of your
wages and all of your benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules, employers may be required to maintain pay and
benefits for workers who suffer debilitating injuries, if job
activities and work conditions are ``reasonably likely to cause or
contribute to the type of injury'' reported.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA made a few changes to mollify employers. But Republicans in
Congress said they would step up efforts to block the rules at
least until January 2001, when the National Academy of Sciences is
to issue a report assessing the evidence that work activities cause
injuries like carpal tunnel syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., who is chairman of the Committee
on Small Business, said, ``The rules are so vague that employers
will not be able to tell what they can or should do to protect
their employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., who is chairman of the Committee on
Education and the Work Force, said he was disappointed that OSHA
had issued the rules because ``there does not yet exist a consensus
on the causes and effects of musculoskeletal disorders in the
workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Randel K. Johnson, vice president of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, said: ``The rules would cost businesses billions of
dollars, but the benefits, if any, are uncertain. If OSHA goes
forward with these rules, we will challenge them in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposals, employers would generally have to adopt
ergonomics programs if even a few employees suffered
musculoskeletal disorders related to work. Federal officials
conceded that it might sometimes be difficult to know whether an
injury was caused by activities on or off the job.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The government said an ergonomics program should include these
elements:
</P>
<P>
   _ Employees must have ways to report symptoms of musculoskeletal
disorders. Employers must respond promptly to such complaints.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employers must inform employees of workplace hazards that may
cause musculoskeletal disorders. They must repeat the training once
every three years, or more frequently if additional injuries occur.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employers must systematically analyze jobs to identify any
factors that may cause or aggravate musculoskeletal disorders.
Employers must eliminate the hazards or ``reduce them to the extent
feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In analyzing ``problem jobs,'' employers must consult workers
and solicit their advice on how to reduce the risks of injury.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employers must provide workers with medical care needed to
treat their work-related injuries, at no cost to the employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department said employers could fix jobs by
redesigning work stations, modifying tools or equipment, changing
the pace of work or encouraging employees to take short breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The rules say that ``ergonomic risk factors'' include forceful
exertion, ``doing the same motion over and over again,'' using
power tools, ``sitting for a long time'' in the same position,
maintaining awkward posture, reaching below the knees or above the
shoulders to grasp objects, or bending or twisting the body while
lifting heavy objects.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are to be published in the Federal Register on
Tuesday. The Labor Department will accept written comments from the
public until Feb. 1, 2000. Department officials will hold public
hearings on the proposals on Feb. 22 in Washington, on March 21 in
Portland, Ore., and in Chicago on April 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
