u f BC-MARKET-STOX-NYT &LR;      11-22 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-STOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY STOCKS RISE AGAIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks continued their rapid ascent Monday
carrying the NASDAQ composite index to its 14th high close in the
last 17 sessions. Gains in Internet stocks and big companies like
Microsoft and Intel helped to fuel the advance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gains in Nasdaq stocks, the other main stock gauges
were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a surprise to a lot of us to continue to see the market
act the way it is acting,'' said Ned Collins, head stock trader at
Daiwa Securities America. ``It continues to beat all
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Nasdaq composite index was up 23.31 points, to
3,392.56. Since the start of the month, the index has gained more
than 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Big gains in several old-line blue chips, including Coca-Cola,
AT&AMP;T and IBM, helped to push the Dow Jones industrial average up
85.63 points, to 11,089.52.
</P>
<P>
   But the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slipped 1.06 points,
to 1,420.94 and the Russell 2000 index of small companies dipped
half a point, to 460.77.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, a component of all three main market gauges, was the
biggest positive influence in Monday's session, traders said. The
stock jumped 4 3/16, to 90 3/16, after federal Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson, who is presiding over the government's antitrust
case against the company, named a mediator last week to try to help
reach an out-of-court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news from Microsoft is probably the most positive
corporate news out there,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst
at Jefferies &AMP; Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was brisk Monday, but is likely to slow as the
Thanksgiving holiday nears. The stock market will be closed on
Thursday and will be open for a half-day on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 873 million shares were traded on the New York Stock
Exchange. On the Nasdaq market, 1.2 billion shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola was among the best-performing Dow stocks. The soft
drink giant jumped 4~ a share, to 65], after a Merrill Lynch
analyst issued a positive report on the company's prospects next
year and raised his rating on Coke shares.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T was also a big winner, rising 5 7/16 a share, to 52. IBM
gained 4 1/16, to 108.
</P>
<P>
   Among Internet stocks, Exodus Communications jumped 17 3/16 a
share, to 118 3/16, after Exodus, which manages Internet sites for
other companies, announced a 2-for-1 stock split effective Dec. 14.
It is the third time the company has split its shares this year.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Arts rose 14 9/16, to 106 9/16, after the video-game
publisher said it had signed a deal to provide all content to
America Online's games site.
</P>
<P>
   A rise in long-term interest rates, prompted by a jump in spot
oil prices, did not help financial service stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter fell 1 9/16, to 122 13/16.
Citigroup dropped 1, to 55{. Chase Manhattan fell 1[ a share, to
81~.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in oil prices, though, did little to help big oil
company stocks. The Royal Dutch/Shell Group, an S&AMP;P component, fell
| a share, to 62}. Mobil declined 1 1/16, to 103~. BP Amoco lost 1,
to 59 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immediate effect of a sharply spiking oil price is
negative for the majors,'' Hogan said, ``because they hedge their
positions for a long ways into the future. Also, these companies
are much more diversified than they used to be. So it doesn't go
hand in glove that a spike in oil prices is good for the majors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
