<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     11-22 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A CLEANER SWEEPS THIS TIME AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's a pleasant surprise to this sweeps month, it's how
uncommonly sedate it has been. Heading into the final couple weeks
of this song and dance designed to boost ad rates and make local
television news look silly, we've had fewer embarrassments than
usual: not as many bloated miniseries and elaborate musicals as in
years past, and series haven't produced the high number of episodes
in which big-name guest stars are awkwardly written into scripts.
</P>
<P>
   The most thoroughly engaging production thus far has been the
continuing documentary series on the origins of New York, tucked
away on PBS, while the biggest phenomenon has undoubtedly been
ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' the crazycool game show
that has trailed only ``ER'' in terms of audience numbers and ``One
Life to Live'' in the category of can't-miss addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Those who dismissed ``Millionaire's'' winning formula _ ordinary
people watching ordinary people win extraordinary amounts in a
question-answer format with music and Regis Philbin staring you in
the face _ have been proved wrong, to say the least. And there has
been an enormous jump among viewers who normally tune in to
syndicated game shows like ``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy!,''
according to ABC research materials.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder this runaway ratings train became the first program
since 1983 to derail NBC's usually invincible Thursday-night
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Millionaire's'' success at luring viewers away from
fresh episodes of weekly favorites puts ABC into something of a
quandary, believe it or not. Knowing its power to lure, do you
bring it back at midseason as a daily or weekly series? Or do you
keep it shelved until sweeps, even though every other network plans
to have some kind of game show on the air by next season?
</P>
<P>
   You can bet that shameless Fox, which is being pummeled this
season in ratings for new series (none so far shows any signs of
longevity), will try its best to air its game show ``Greed'' daily,
since it's doing much better than anything the network has put on
in years. ___
</P>
<P>
   The big sweeps stunts now over, CBS appears to be the only
network with something left to show off as we wind down. Unless you
count NBC's ``Y2K'' _ and you shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The most-hyped show of the week, ``Y2K,'' on NBC Sunday night,
was the least enjoyable of the sweeps bunch. Ken Olin starred as a
government-employed systems expert who tries to outrace the bug as
it spreads. Part of that has to do with the fear that viewers will
actually become more panicked about what will happen at the stroke
of midnight. You have to wonder if the CBS publicity machine is
milking this for all it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting (not to be confused with ``best'') is CBS'
``Two Babies: Switched at Birth,'' (Wednesday at 8 CST), based on a
true incident. It airs following a Celine Dion concert, the first
of three consecutive evenings of hot-artist-on-the-road shows.
Gloria Estefan and 'N Sync also perform in the special, which
precedes Shania Twain's concert Thursday and Ricky Martin's on
Friday with Carlos Santana and Jose Feliciano checking in.
</P>
<P>
   At least ``Switched at Birth,'' unlike ``Y2K,'' comes with an
underlining of truth. I have to say that ``Switched'' isn't a very
good movie, but it's certainly an intoxicating one. The teasing
question serving as its hook: What would you do if your baby was
switched with that of another family, and you didn't find out
until. ...?
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Gilbert and Rosanna Arquette star as the confused and
emotionally tortured mothers who each decide to keep the child
they've been raising. As you might expect, the decision brings up a
multitude of challenges that's only accelerated by the boyfriend of
one of the women. He's written as an insensitive, opportunistic
pest, and that's just one of the liberties producers took in a film
that's not based on but ``inspired by'' actual events. (I can
imagine the real-life families hating this movie.)
</P>
<P>
   Those who remember the story when it hit the news a few years
ago also know that one of the parties was killed in an automobile
accident, prompting the other side to go more aggressively after
the other.
</P>
<P>
   None of that dramatic friction happens here. Since ``Switched''
wants to be a cheery, feel-good movie, it ends on such a mushy and
unbelievable note you might want to skip it altogether. (The
ending, not the movie.) That's because sandwiched in between are a
number of scenes that are forthright and emotionally on-target in
the telling of two families seeking an unconventional solution to
their dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   I also like how the pendulum kept swinging to each side as to
who the bad guy would be. The movie separates the two by class _
Gilbert's well-to-do Gail Barlow calls Arquette's Linda Wells, a
struggling single mother, ``flaky'' and ``unworldly.'' Linda's
refusal to send her son to preschool and ``give him the social
skills he needs'' sends Gail through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's around his cousins all day,'' barks Linda. ``How much
socializing does he need?'' (To Gail, it was the ``right''
socialization.)
</P>
<P>
   To Linda, the Barlows are rich folks who ``think they own the
world.'' It's enough to give the movie a resonance of friction as
they try to come to a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Switched'' is pieced together in true network movie form. It
moves too fast and often uses one line to explain important
matters, and although the movie is based on real events, the
characters are more or less written from some guidebook.
</P>
<P>
   But not once will you stop wondering exactly what you'd do in
each situation. The thought of waking up each morning looking in
the eyes of a child you love and will never let go but isn't yours
biologically, while knowing that your biological child is being
raised by others, has to be akin to psychological torture.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
