<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8352 &Cx1f; tad-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-AUTO-1128-COX     11-22 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AUTO-1128-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ON THE ROAD TO A LOST ERA OF AUTO TOURING
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (t) travel categories for release
Sunday, Nov. 28.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are no cars or people in John Margolies'
nostalgic pictures of roadside America. The sun is always shining.
The sky is always blue. He even picks up any litter before clicking
the camera shutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it is in my sunny little world,'' explained
Margolies, who has made an art out of chronicling tourism kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   But now the sun is setting.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is the time when travelers could eat in a restaurant shaped
like a coffee pot and buy gas from a converted B-17 bomber and
visit Jesse James' hideout and park right beside the teepee where
they would spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   Cars created this byways culture of neon and alligator farms and
eateries you entered through the mouth of a giant trout or the
label of a huge ketchup bottle. A few decades later, interstate
highways destroyed this grand, garish strip of Americana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the interstates, getting there was half the fun,''
Margolies recollected. ``Now it's no fun at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The fun has been preserved, however, in Margolies' new exhibit,
``See the USA: Automobile Travel and the American Landscape,'' at
the National Building Museum. The collection illustrates how cars
opened the nation to a new sort of leisure travel and recounts the
resulting culture of gas, food, lodging and amusements.
</P>
<P>
   Margolies, who has written and illustrated several books about
his 25 years of exploring America, is guest curator. The exhibit
opened Nov. 19 and runs through May 7.
</P>
<P>
   The collection evokes a bygone era of auto travel through
photos, paintings, road maps, picture postcards, gas pumps, neon
signs, vintage Holiday Inn furniture, menus and assorted other
artifacts. A memorable history lesson is delivered through
Margolies' affection for the wacky and the tacky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like so-called bad taste better than so-called good taste
nearly all of the time,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit begins with a 1926 Ford Model T roadster. Such
mass-produced, affordable autos gave America a mobility unimagined
in the era of train travel.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, millions of families had cars and were eager ``to
explore their country in a new way,'' Margolies said as he escorted
a visitor on a tour of the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   On the exhibit floor is a giant road map of 1939 America _ a
reproduction of an illustration from the New York Daily News. Of
course, the map is missing I-75 and I-95 and I-40 and all the other
interstate highways that now zip motorists across a homogenized
nation where identical McDonald's and Ramada Inns await at nearly
every exit.
</P>
<P>
   When Americans first set out to ``see the USA'' in their cars,
local entrepreneurs quickly responded with lodging, restaurants and
gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabin courts'' of miniature houses _ or teepees, igloos or
pyramids _ sprang up beside the highways leading into hundreds of
towns. Then came long buildings with carports connecting the rooms.
When business boomed, the carports were converted to more guest
quarters, and the modern motel was born.
</P>
<P>
   Margolies points to his picture of a ``No-Tel Motel'' neon sign.
The name was once common across the nation, he said, recalling a
clerk who boasted of renting the same room 15 times in one day. A
sign saying ``Tourists Only'' was ``road code'' for an
establishment that did not want this hot-sheets trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The curator pointed out a 1946 edition of ``The Green Book''
guide to motels where ``the Negro Motorist'' could stay in the
segregated South. ``Carry your Green Book with you,'' warns the
cover. ``You may need it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was important'' to include this reminder that
``Welcome'' signs didn't apply to all, Margolies said.
</P>
<P>
   Like lodging, restaurants and gas stations along the roads have
evolved from quirky individualist establishments into predictable,
comfortable chains.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit shows early ``filling stations'' where the buildings
behind the pumps replicated flying saucers, dinosaurs or airplanes.
Meanwhile, hungry motorists could dine inside models of everything
from an apple to the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   The garish signs and weird buildings were designed to get the
kids yelling for dad to put on the brakes. The roadside businesses
``had to stop them in their tracks,'' said Margolies, hence the
orange roof on Howard Johnson's restaurants and the original
Holiday Inn signs ``modeled after a movie marquee.''
</P>
<P>
   Regretfully, Margolies said, he has stopped his travels. As his
beloved roadscapes disappeared, he said, ``I felt like a
photographic undertaker.''
</P>
<P>
   But visitors to Washington can still see the way it was.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is located in the National Building Museum, one of
the architectural treasures of the nation's capital. Compared to
the Smithsonian museums and traditional tourist stops such as the
Capitol and White House, the massive structure is rarely crowded.
Its Great Hall, with a central fountain and eight colossal
Corinthian columns, has been a popular site for presidential
inaugural balls since 1885.
</P>
<P>
   The building originally housed the Pension Bureau. Since 1985,
it has celebrated the culture of architecture, design, engineering,
construction and urban planning. The museum is located at 401 F
Street NW, near the Judiciary Square Metro station on the Red Line.
Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call 202-272-2448 or look on the Internet at
www.nbm.org.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
