<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8354 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-MILITARY-RACE-ART-NYT     11-22 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-RACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY'S EFFORTS IN RACE RELATIONS STILL FALL SHORT, SURVEY
SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 30 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the most comprehensive survey ever conducted of
racial attitudes in the armed forces, the Pentagon has found that,
despite a decades-long effort to promote equal opportunity and good
race relations, wide gaps remain between how whites and minorities
perceive how they are treated.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of more than 40,000 uniformed members of the Army,
Navy, Air Force, Marines and Coast Guard also found that a large
proportion of military personnel had experienced what they
considered a racially offensive encounter, often from a superior in
the 12 months before the survey was taken.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 51 percent of those surveyed said that nothing was
done when a complaint was filed about a particularly bothersome
incident.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that 34 percent of whites and from 46 percent
to 56 percent of minorities said that many of these incidents
caused them to lose trust or have negative feelings about their
colleagues, a finding that could be particularly troubling to a
military that strives to promote cohesiveness and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's findings were a bit of a disappointment to current
and former Pentagon officials. The military, especially the Army,
has prided itself on doing more than perhaps any institution in the
country to foster a good racial climate and promote equal
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department's efforts have drawn acclaim from some
academics and politicians, including President Clinton, who has
praised the military's efforts in the area of race relations and
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tells us that even the military, which we still believe
is ahead of the rest of society, still has some racial tensions,''
said Edwin Dorn, former undersecretary of defense for personnel and
readiness, who commissioned the survey and has been briefed on its
findings. ``The results of this survey are not nearly as wonderful
as we might have liked. It gives a good sense of the kinds of
things that need to be worked on.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey, the largest and most detailed effort to discern
racial attitudes ever undertaken by any U.S. institution _ military
or civilian _ generally painted an encouraging picture of race
relations, indicating that large majorities of military personnel
feel comfortable living and working around people of another race
and form close friendships across racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   Many of its findings indicate that the military has created a
much more tolerant racial climate than most other institutions in
American society, and that in many ways racial attitudes in the
armed forces are more tolerant than they are in the civilian world.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 82 percent of white members of the armed forces who
responded said they had a close personal friend who is black. In a
comprehensive poll taken in 1997 by the Gallup Organization, only
59 percent of whites reported having a close black friend.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the survey also found that
minorities, especially African Americans, tended to hold a more
pessimistic view than whites of race relations in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities also are more likely to say they have received a poor
evaluation because of their race or ethnicity, compared with
whites, and are more likely to believe that the armed forces has
paid ``too little'' attention to discrimination based on race or
ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly telling was the fact that 17 percent of whites who
responded felt that the military did not pay enough attention to
the problem of race discrimination. In contrast, 38 percent of
Hispanic soldiers and 62 percent of black soldiers, sailors and air
force personnel said they felt that way.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials cautioned that further study of the survey's
findings was required before any solid conclusions or policy
recommendations were proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gave us initial answers,'' said William Leftwich III,
deputy assistant secretary of defense for equal opportunity. ``I
have to say these initial answers are not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   To conduct the study, the Defense Manpower Data Center, a
Defense Department agency, sent out a 16-page form to 76,754
soldiers, sailors and aviators from September 1996 to February
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The confidential forms were mailed to enlisted personnel and
officers up to the rank of captain in the Navy and Coast Guard and
its equivalent rank, colonel, in the Army, Air Force and Marines.
About 53 percent of the forms were returned in usable form, a
relatively high percentage for surveys returned by mail.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise was mandated by legislation pushed by Ronald
Dellums, a former Democratic representative from Berkeley, Calif.,
who was chairman of the House Armed Services Committee. The survey
is the first of a series of comprehensive studies on race relations
in the military. Pentagon researchers say they will be conducting
another survey next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the survey suggested that the military must still
grapple with racial issues, another report by the Pentagon
indicated that the armed forces had a mixed record when it came to
promoting minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``Career Progression of Minority and Women
Officers,'' indicated that in 1997 minorities made up 15.3 percent
of all officers and women, 14.1 percent, up from 7 percent and 5.9
percent, respectively, in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   But the report said that while the promotion rates for white men
and white women were about the same, African-American men and women
were being promoted at a much lower rate.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials attribute the discrepancy in the promotion
rates to factors that were not necessarily related to race. For
example, minorities and women tended to be more heavily clustered
in administrative and support units in the military. These areas
tend not to provide the faster track for promotion that combat
units do. Also, Pentagon officials acknowledge that the military
does not do a good job of mentoring women and minority personnel
who show potential to become officers or move up the officer ranks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HOLZMANN-BANKRUPTCY-1     11-22 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLZMANN-BANKRUPTCY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE GERMAN BUILDER NEARS BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE   with bailout talks failing;
Tuesday in lede cq.)  (lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Philipp Holzmann AG, the biggest
construction company in Germany, appeared headed toward bankruptcy
Tuesday after late-night talks brokered by Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder failed to reach a compromise among banks trying to
arrange a $2.6 billion bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann has been on the brink of insolvency since last week,
when it said that it had suddenly uncovered $1.3 billion in soured
real estate loans.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann's creditor banks had accused one another on Monday of
either covering up evidence of trouble or being inflexible in
coming to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor had raised some hope about a possible solution
Monday evening by arranging talks involving the banks and the
political leaders of the state of Hesse, where Frankfurt is. That
move brought the creditors back into another round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   But early Tuesday, a Hesse government representative, Dirk Metz,
told journalists that the negotiations had failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many banks didn't have the confidence in the concept of the
proposals that were put forward,'' Dow Jones Newswires quoted him
as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted bailout of Holzmann highlighted the tattered state
of Germany Inc., the once tightly knit community of banks,
industrial companies and government officials that has
traditionally rescued ailing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, angry bankers said that Holzmann, which has lost
money for years, appeared to have concealed bad loans while
declaring that it was on the path to a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann's biggest shareholder, the Belgian holding company
Gavaert, contended that the big banks should have seen the problems
as well, and it threatened to sue them and the top managers of
Holzmann.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the finger-pointing, Holzmann's chief executive, Heinrich
Binder, gloomily confronted angry construction workers as a
bitterly cold snowstorm blanketed much of Frankfurt on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Though he promised to do everything he could to keep the company
operating while in bankruptcy, Binder admitted that he ``cannot
say'' whether the company would be able to issue the next round of
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann has more than 1,200 construction sites around Germany,
and work stopped at many of them amid the bad weather and
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Because Holzmann is one of Germany's most venerable industrial
names and employs nearly 17,000 people, the banks had been under
heavy political pressure to prop it up one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, which owns 15 percent of Holzmann and holds more
than 2.2 billion marks, or $1.2 billion, in outstanding loans to
the company, had been leading the bailout and had offered to put up
about $830 million, roughly a third of what Holzmann said it
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Those talks collapsed after a 15-hour meeting of creditors on
Sunday. Deutsche Bank said that ``inflexibility'' on the part of
Commerzbank AG, Germany's fourth-largest bank, had caused the
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Commerzbank fired back, noting that Deutsche Bank should have
known better because one of its own top executives is chairman of
Holzmann's supervisory board.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of its problems was heightened Monday when rival
construction companies, including Hoch-Tief AG, asserted that they
had little interest in acquiring either all or part of Holzmann.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of Holzmann's problems is a huge portfolio of bad
real estate loans that it took on in the early 1990s, when the
reconstruction of eastern Germany was proceeding at a furious pace
and the industry was having an extraordinary boom. Besides
profiting from the construction work itself, Holzmann financed many
projects.
</P>
<P>
   When real estate prices in eastern Germany collapsed as a result
of overbuilding fueled by generous tax breaks, Holzmann found
itself with a growing amount of increasingly troublesome loans.
</P>
<P>
   Under German law, Holzmann is required to file for bankruptcy as
soon as its creditors decide against refinancing its debt.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Koch, the Christian Democratic premier of Hesse, had
reportedly put heavy pressure on publicly owned banks to contribute
money toward a bailout.
</P>
<P>
   According to some news reports Monday, the banks were short only
about 400 million marks of the 4.3 billion marks, or $2.3 billion,
that they were trying to assemble.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published by Bild Zeitung, Schroeder had said
that the banks had a responsibility to work out a rescue, adding
that he was convinced that the shortfall could be closed.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the talks on Monday evening had begun, Koch was
more pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very difficult for Holzmann to stay alive,'' Koch
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
