<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE TITANS SEE JEVON KEARSE AND THINK LAWRENCE TAYLOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Everything at shiny Adelphia Stadium is new,
especially the Tennessee Titans and their delirious fans. More than
66,000 gathered here on Sunday to see the Titans tackle Pittsburgh,
and one of their most enjoyable moments was when the song ``Le
Freak'' blared across the stadium. Children danced in the aisles.
Their parents offered a move, too. Blue and white posters were
waved celebrating ``The Freak,'' Titans defensive end Jevon Kearse.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom has a rookie in the National Football League created such
a stir.
</P>
<P>
   But Kearse has.
</P>
<P>
   He leads the Titans in sacks with 7{. According to numbers kept
by the Titans' coaches, he leads the defensive linemen and is
fourth on the team in tackles with 58, has forced a team-high six
fumbles and leads in tackles for losses with seven. His impact,
however, reaches far beyond numbers.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 foot 4 and 255 pounds, Kearse is an undersized defensive
end in weight, but in height, wingspan, speed, quickness and
agility he has few peers. His hands are huge _ he can hold the ends
of a 12-inch ruler in one hand, from little finger to thumb _ and
he wears size 14 shoes. He is easily the league's fastest defensive
lineman. He is tough and determined.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minutes of Tennessee's clash with Pittsburgh, it
was Kearse's sack of Kordell Stewart that helped ruin Pittsburgh's
potential game-winning drive. Tennessee won, 16-10, in a game in
which Kearse was nearly always double-teamed. He played the entire
game with a stomach virus, frequently vomiting on the sideline. No
matter. He was still dominating in a manner reminiscent of the Hall
of Fame linebacker Lawrence Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents recognize that Kearse (pronounced curse) is a bit of a
freak of nature _ and an exciting player able to create chaos in
any offense. He has helped revamp the Tennessee defense and
affected the entire franchise _ Tennessee owns an 8-2 record now,
is 6-0 in its division and is 5-0 this season at Adelphia Coliseum.
The Titans appear playoff-bound for the first time in six years.
</P>
<P>
   All of this from the 16th player selected in this year's draft.
There are certainly not 15 rookies currently better than Kearse,
who left Florida after his junior year and is now on pace to join
Al (Bubba) Baker as the only rookie defensive ends in league
history to earn Pro Bowl honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college at Florida, they started calling me Freak then and
it stuck,'' Kearse said. ``A lot of teams passed me up in the
draft, but Tennessee was smart. I came here expecting to come off
the bench and to get bumped around a bit. I expected the offensive
tackles to be 100 times greater than they were in college. But my
coaches tell me those guys can't block me and I've started to
believe it. I started out the season slow in my first couple of
games, but now I've begun figuring out what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates saw it from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``In training camp there was a play where Chris Sanders, one of
our fastest players, ran a slant pattern from the receiver position
on the opposite side of the field,'' said Anthony Dorsett, a Titans
cornerback. ``Jevon was rushing the passer, was in the backfield,
turned and ran upfield and 30 yards downfield caught Chris and was
in on the tackle. We all said to ourselves, man _ that's why he's
the Freak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all think he can have the impact like a Lawrence Taylor,''
Dorsett added. ``Think about it; this is his first year, so he is
going off raw ability. Just wait until he gets some smarts. He fits
in the locker room because he is not a cocky guy, not one to brag.
You barely know he's here _ until you get out on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans move Kearse from left end to right end, keeping him
in constant motion so that offenses must always find No. 90 and
alter their blocking schemes to account for him. With his rare
ability to chase quarterbacks and ball carriers, even if Kearse
does not make the sack or tackle, he often creates opportunities
for teammates to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has never seen film of Bubba Baker, who was a rookie
with the Lions in 1978. He realizes that joining him in league
history would be special.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would very much surprise me if that happened,'' Kearse said
of making the Pro Bowl. ``I didn't start out as hot as I am now,
but there are still six regular season games to go. When I'm in the
game, I feel like I'm going to get a ruckus started. I'm in a whole
different state of mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
