<HEADER>
A8358 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO-FLIR-COX     11-22 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-FLIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Justice Department nixes recreation of siege, suggests
demonstrations instead
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The Justice Department Monday opposed trying to
recreate the final day of the 1993 Branch Davidian siege in order
to determine if flashes seen on infrared video tapes are gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the government suggested court-appointed experts
demonstrate what gunshots look like on FLIR (Forward Looking
Infrared) tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``No attempt at 're-creation' of the events would meet the test
of reliability because it could not replicate and take into account
all the operative facts,'' read the government motion, filed by
Justice Department attorney Mary Louise Hagen. ``In short, it would
produce more confusion than clarity.''
</P>
<P>
   The government motion claims there are too many ``unknown
variables'' to recreate the conditions on April 19, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Such a re-creation would require, the government argued,
``precise weather information (including minute temperature
fluctuations); wind conditions (including speed and directional
shifts); the amount of moisture in the soil; the content and
location of debris generated when the gymnasium collapsed; all heat
sources (such as the tanks and the lights); and the relative
position of the heat sources, the debris, and the viewing
aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Mike Caddell, the lead attorney in the wrongful
death lawsuit filed by surviving Davidians against the government,
derided the government's argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``They operated the FLIR camera for three weeks,'' Caddell said.
``Never once did it show any flashes other than from 11:20 a.m. to
12:10 p.m. on April 19, 1993. No flashes were seen on the FLIR
until tanks started knocking down buildings. None of it explains
why flashes were only seen in the back. Was the soil different in
the back? This is really silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we can recreate the conditions at Mount Carmel. ...
These are people talking like they know it will show gunfire, and
they're trying to come up with a way to explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco last week
ordered the appointment of neutral experts to recreate the final
day at Mount Carmel, after receiving requests from both Special
Counsel John Danforth and plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs charge that flashes seen on the FBI's infrared video,
shot from a circling plane, are proof that FBI agents fired at the
Davidians, possibly preventing them from fleeing a burning Mount
Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials have always maintained they didn't fire a single
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gone from sunlight to unexplained electrical anomalies
to now saying that the flashes on the FLIR are debris from the
collapsed gym _ which doesn't explain why you see flashes before
the gym collapses,'' Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of recreating the conditions at Mount Carmel, the
government suggested Smith appoint a expert to determine whether
gunfire can be seen by FLIR technology within a specified spectral
(radiation) range (8-12 microns is the spectral range of the FBI's
sensors, according to the motion).
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's FLIR camera would not be needed for such a
demonstration, according to the motion.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the motion, the government argues that the FLIR
camera used at Mount Carmel has been modified and recreating its
1993 state would be cost-prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``System modifications include changing from analog signal
processing elements, in the original system, to digital signal
processing electronics in the modified system,'' the government
motion said. ``... Digital systems have improved signal-to-noise
ratio, and are thus better able to discern weak signals, resulting
in a clearer picture. Thus, images recorded with the upgraded
equipment would not necessarily provide a reliable recreation of
the capability of the 1993 system.''
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokeswoman said the FLIR camera used at
Mount Carmel was not commercially available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like you could go down to Office Depot and pick one
up,'' said Carole Florman. ``My understanding is that it's since
been upgraded. It's not like we shelved the older model. It's an
evolving piece of equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he'd like to see a re-creation of the final day at
Mount Carmel shot with the updated FLIR camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this camera with the upgrades shows gunfire that looks just
like the flashes from the 1993 film, how could anyone credibly
argue that's not gunfire in the FLIR tape?'' Caddell asked. ``To
say it wouldn't have shown up if the camera had not been upgraded
is just silly. You have to take the government's arguments to their
logical conclusion, and then they just fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark England writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: mengland(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
