u p BC-BRADLEY-NH-850&AMP;ADD-NY     11-22 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NH-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY ATTACKS GORE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ In blunt language that echoed Republican
attacks against the fund-raising practices of the 1996 Clinton-Gore
campaign, former Sen. Bill Bradley sharply rebuked Vice President
Al Gore on Monday, asserting that the vice president has no
interest in changing the current campaign-finance system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those fund-raising practices, he said, raised ``questions about
where politics ended and government began.'' He said those
questions were reinforced by the vice president's use of White
House perquisites in his campaign against Bradley for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few people in Washington want the system changed,'' Bradley
told the crowd here at New Hampshire College. ``Nothing is changed
because it's in the interest of politicians not to change it. The
system works to help those who are in power keep that power. So why
should they rock the boat?''
</P>
<P>
   The speech, one of Bradley's strongest efforts yet to portray
himself as a political outsider and reformer, hit Gore at one of
his most vulnerable points, accusations of fund-raising
irregularities in 1996 that critics of the Clinton administration
thought deserved an investigation by an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore responded to the speech by saying that Bradley was
a relative latecomer to campaign-finance reform, while Gore had
been sponsoring legislation in Congress to change the system as
early as 1979. They also said that while Bradley accuses others of
being beholden to special interests, he has taken numerous
contributions from bankers, lawyers and pharmaceutical companies,
as well as flights on corporate jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been a fighter for campaign-finance reform since
his earliest days in Congress,'' said Chris Lehane, Gore's press
secretary. ``While Senator Bradley has chosen to talk about the
issue of campaign-finance reform, he fails to fully disclose who
paid for and is paying for the dozens of corporate flights Bradley
is using during this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   In his attacks on fund-raising irregularities in the
Clinton-Gore campaign of 1996, Bradley risked offending many party
activists who contend that President Clinton had to push the
existing rules to keep pace with the Republicans fund-raising
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley may also anger loyal Democrats by raising an issue the
Republicans are likely to exploit if Gore is the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have already attacked Gore for appearing at a
fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple in Los Angeles and for making
fund-raising phone calls from his White House office. Attorney
General Janet Reno rejected demands that she appoint a special
prosecutor to investigate the accusations. Bradley did not mention
any specific practices from 1996 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The address was also unusually aggressive for Bradley, who has
said he is trying to avoid negative campaigning. Until now, Bradley
has tended to criticize the vice president in response to attacks
by Gore, particularly on health care issues. But the two
candidates' positions on campaign-finance reform are not very far
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides said he wanted to invigorate his oratory on
Monday because of recent news reports that Gore has been using his
official trips as vice president to help his campaign. Bradley's
unexpectedly strong challenge has forced the vice president to
spend more than he had anticipated, particularly in the early
voting states of Iowa and New Hampshire, where there are strict
spending limits for the primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign also contends that campaign finance, like
health care, provides a clear contrast in the two candidates'
styles, with Bradley taking bold positions while Gore pushes
half-way measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises the issues of what lessons the vice president
learned from the 1996 campaign,'' said Anita Dunn, Bradley's
director of communications. ``What Senator Bradley was suggesting
is that he didn't learn anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also clearly believes the issue resonates with voters in
New Hampshire, who are known for supporting reform-minded
politicians. The state's primary on Feb. 1 is the nation's first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The straight talk the people of New Hampshire value is
becoming so much more rare in Washington,'' Bradley said on Monday,
``because Washington is the capital of double talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has called for ending the unlimited contributions to
political parties known as soft money; for public financing of
House and Senate campaigns; for free broadcast time for
congressional candidates starting 60 days before the general
election, and for allowing voters to register on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   He has also said that if he was the Democratic nominee, he would
call on the party not to accept soft money if the Republican
candidate agreed to the same. Gore's campaign chairman, Tony
Coelho, has criticized that idea and only one Republican, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, has agreed to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also called for ending soft money, providing candidates
with free air time and for public financing of House and Senate
campaigns.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his speech, Bradley almost mockingly referred to a 1995
handshake agreement between President Clinton and then House
Speaker Newt Gingrich in Claremont, N.H. to appoint a commission to
revamp the campaign-finance system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is behind every public handshake, like the one in
Claremont on this issue, there has always been a secret
handshake,'' Bradley said. ``That tacit secret handshake signals an
agreement among politicians not to upset a system that they use to
their advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   He said almost nothing had been accomplished by Congress this
year on issues like gun control, managed care reform and the
minimum wage because big-moneyed interests had stifled legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever wonder why Congress seems eager to act on issues like
accelerated depreciation?'' he asked. ``Or why we still have nearly
14 millions children in America who live in poverty while
corporations get major tax loopholes for themselves. Well, I think
money has something to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley repeatedly referred to campaign-finance reform as a core
Democratic issue, suggesting that Gore had betrayed his party's
principles. And he likened the opposition to it to the opposition
to Social Security in the 1930s, to Medicare in the 1960s and to
the tax reform he sponsored in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians believe you don't really care about this issue,
campaign- finance reform,'' he continued. ``They don't respect you
enough to even hide their actions, or pretend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
