<SLUG> BC-NIKE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIEDEN &AMP; KENNEDY WIN NIKE'S CONSOLIDATED U.S. ACCOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Calif., Ill.)  (Eds: In E(asterisk)Trade, substitute the symbol, which cannot be
transmitted to some newspapers.) 
(DW) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The agency that created the signature theme ``Just do it'' for
Nike Inc. has done it again, regaining its status as the sole
agency for the Nike brand in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Nike decided unexpectedly Monday to consolidate its American
brand assignments, with billings estimated at $350 million, at
Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore., which along with ``Just do it''
has produced some of the most familiar _ and most imitated _
campaigns in advertising the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's work for Nike athletic gear ranged from the jocular
teaming of Michael Jordan and Bugs Bunny to the sardonic dismissal
of silver medals from the Olympics as what you get when you ``lose
gold'' to the defiant presentation of a gallery of battered
athletes who proudly display their scars as the song ``You Are So
Beautiful'' plays in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation, effective immediately, is the most recent
twist in a tumultuous relationship between Nike and Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy that dates to April 1, 1982, when the agency opened with
the Nike account. Since March 1997, Wieden &AMP; Kennedy had shared the
Nike account with Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners in San Francisco,
the creative hot shop best known for the ``Got milk?'' campaign for
California milk processors that runs nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Avenue had watched closely as Nike sought to respond to
challenges in its important athletic footwear and apparel markets
by shifting assignments between the two agencies. There has been
constant tension over how best to respond to the waxing and waning
of the appeal of the Nike ``swoosh'' logo and sneakers in general,
as evidenced by the brief life of a campaign last year by Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy carrying the theme ``I can'' in place of ``Just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike never disclosed how the billings were being divided between
the two agencies in the United States; the company uses agencies
including Wieden &AMP; Kennedy for campaigns overseas. At one point
estimates were that Wieden &AMP; Kennedy had 55 to 60 percent of the
billings and Goodby, Silverstein had 40 to 45 percent, but lately
that division was thought to have tilted more in Wieden &AMP; Kennedy's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation as to whether Wieden &AMP; Kennedy or Goodby,
Silverstein would emerge on top in their tug of war _ as intense
and hard fought as any athletic competition featured in a Nike
campaign _ has been one of the agency industry's most persistent
and tantalizing guessing games.
</P>
<P>
   But the guessing ended Monday when Rob DeFlorio, U.S.
advertising director for Nike, met with executives at Goodby,
Silverstein in San Francisco to deliver word of the consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the work Goodby has done recently is excellent,''
said Scott Reames, a spokesman for Nike in Beaverton, Ore.
``Goodby's apparel ads and ads for the U.S. women's soccer team
really clicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we felt we needed to get back to one agency,'' he added,
``and Wieden &AMP; Kennedy is the agency we chose.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason, Reames said, was that ``we know them best
and they know us best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we couldn't be happier with the work we've been getting
from them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we made the decision to split the business between two
agencies, there was a different business climate,'' Reames said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business climate has changed again, and we wanted to move
back to a one-agency model at the brand level,'' he added, ``and
when you do that, one agency has to be on the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Reames said the consolidation was unrelated to the arrival of a
new chief marketing officer at Nike, Ellen Turner, who had been
chief marketing officer at Kinko's, the office supplies retailer.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation is a significant gain for Wieden &AMP; Kennedy
above and beyond the additional billings it will mean. As its
relationship with Nike became increasingly turbulent, Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy executives had looked to another big client, Microsoft, for
future growth.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft stunned Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in June by dismissing the
agency. Though Wieden &AMP; Kennedy has returned to the technology
category with another large client, AltaVista, and has been landing
plum dot-com accounts like Homegrocer.com, there was speculation
that the agency needed to regain its special partnership with Nike,
as the trade publication Adweek described the relationship last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got off the plane from Thailand and got this call,''
said Dan Wieden, president at Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, referring to the
word from Nike. ``I'm still in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels terrific,'' he added. ``In some ways it's easier to
share, but everyone is more than ready to take on the added
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a brief period in the mid-1980s when Nike moved the
American brand work to Chiat/Day, Wieden &AMP; Kennedy has always
worked for Nike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never won or kept business based on an ability to
smooth clients over,'' Wieden said. ``Anything that has happened to
us is based on the work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm very proud of the work we've done over the last
year,'' he added. ``It's very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether there have been too many ups and downs in what he
characterized as the long, deep relationship between the agency and
Nike, Wieden laughed, comparing the peaks and valleys to ``my
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   At Goodby, Silverstein, which is owned by the Omnicom Group, the
loss was being taken philosophically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably a good thing in some ways for everyone
involved,'' said Jeff Goodby, co-chairman and creative director at
Goodby, Silverstein with Rich Silverstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nike will get the undivided time and attention of Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy,'' he added, ``and there'll be financial savings'' from
using one agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our standpoint, we've always been something of a minority
partner,'' Goodby said, ``and there's a lot of justifiably loyal
Wieden people at Nike.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodby acknowledged that executives at his agency sometimes
found it ``very difficult to work together'' with Nike management.
At one point last spring, Goodby, Silverstein had been poised to
resign its portion of the account, which included apparel, ads
aimed at women and specialty products like skateboarding shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs are not expected at Goodby, Silverstein, Goodby said,
because ``we're fine; we have more than enough to do.'' He listed
recent account gains like Discover Card, a unit of Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter, as well as additional assignments from clients like
Anheuser-Busch and Hewlett-Packard and the growth of the
E(asterisk)Trade Group account.
</P>
<P>
   In the tradition of the familiar ad slogan, ``When it rains, it
pours,'' Wieden &AMP; Kennedy also landed a new client Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Konami Corp. of America in Buffalo Grove, Ill., which sells
video games, awarded its account to Wieden &AMP; Kennedy's New York
office. Billings were estimated at $5 million to $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   That decision came after a two-month review that had been
narrowed to Wieden &AMP; Kennedy and two other finalists. One was the
incumbent, G Whiz in New York, the unit of Grey Advertising thatlizes in advertising aimed at children. The identity of the
third finalist was not disclosed. Konami is part of the Konami
Industry &UR;  &LR; Co..
</P>
</TEXT>
