<P>
   (NYT30) IN THE MEDITERRANEAN SEA -- Nov. 22, 1999 --
MILITARY-RACE, 11-22 -- Operations specialists aboard the aircraft
carrier USS John F. Kennedy watch ship traffic on their screens
inside the Combat Direction Center during a NATO exercise last
month. A recent survey of U.S. military personnel found that though
they felt that the military handled race-relations reasonably well,
there were areas that could be improved upon. (Isaiah Sellers, U.S.
Navy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) ABUJA, Nigeria -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- NIGERIA-CORRUPTION,
11-22 -- Then president-elect Olusegun Obasanjo in Abuja in March.
Since taking over in May as the first civilian president in nearly
16 years, Obasanjo has extended a probe into nearly all levels of
society that benefited from the military rule that made Nigeria one
of the world's most corrupt countries. (Ozier Muhammad//New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- PRISON-MAGAZINE, 11-22 --
F.E.D.S. is something of a sensation in the prison system, which
accounts for more than 90 percent of its 7,000 paid subscribers.
The magazine, on its cover, promises stories on ``convicted
hustlers, street thugs, fashion, sports, music and film.'' It also
carries a ``parental advisory'' label. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
