<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 11/22/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) IN THE MEDITERRANEAN SEA -- Nov. 22, 1999 --
MILITARY-RACE, 11-22 -- Operations specialists aboard the aircraft
carrier USS John F. Kennedy watch ship traffic on their screens
inside the Combat Direction Center during a NATO exercise last
month. A recent survey of U.S. military personnel found that though
they felt that the military handled race-relations reasonably well,
there were areas that could be improved upon. (Isaiah Sellers, U.S.
Navy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) ABUJA, Nigeria -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- NIGERIA-CORRUPTION,
11-22 -- Then president-elect Olusegun Obasanjo in Abuja in March.
Since taking over in May as the first civilian president in nearly
16 years, Obasanjo has extended a probe into nearly all levels of
society that benefited from the military rule that made Nigeria one
of the world's most corrupt countries. (Ozier Muhammad//New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- PRISON-MAGAZINE, 11-22 --
F.E.D.S. is something of a sensation in the prison system, which
accounts for more than 90 percent of its 7,000 paid subscribers.
The magazine, on its cover, promises stories on ``convicted
hustlers, street thugs, fashion, sports, music and film.'' It also
carries a ``parental advisory'' label. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- GUCCI-FASHION-2, 11-22 --
Variations on animal prints from Gucci's fall 1999 collection,
left; slinky pullover blouse from Tom Ford's spring 2000 line for
Gucci. (Dan Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- GUCCI-FASHION-1, 11-22 --
Velvet pants suit from Gucci's fall 1996 line, with cut reminiscent
of Yves Saint Laurent's tuxedo, left; coat and trousers with Saint
Laurent overtones, from Gucci's '95 line. (Dan Lecca/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- ROUNDABOUT-THEATER-2-B&AMP;W,
11-22 -- Todd Haimes and Julia C. Levy, Roundabout Theater Company
officials. The theater - currently undergoing a $21.5 million
renovation - is scheduled to reopen on March 21, three months later
than originally scheduled, with a production of Chekhov's ``Uncle
Vanya'' starring Roger Rees, Laura Linney and Sir Derek Jacobi.
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- NY-BRICK-ATTACK, 11-22 -- A
police officer holds a sketch of a suspect in last week's attack of
a woman in Midtown before going out on patrol along Riverside Park
on Monday. The family of the Texan who was smashed in the head with
a brick thanked New Yorkers Monday for their prayers and kindness,
and said they bear no anger toward the city where Nicole Barrett
was attacked. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CASABLANCA, Morocco -- Nov. 22, 1999 --
MOROCCO-BOURSE-2, 11-22 -- The trading floor of the Casablanca
Stock Exchange, with just 30 traders working in little computer
cubicles, is quiet as a church. And it is about to get even
quieter. Early next year, the trading floor is shutting down,
exchange officials say, thrusting Casablanca's small, young, but
technologically hip stock market into the growing ranks of virtual
exchanges around the world. (Joseph Treaster/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) CASABLANCA, Morocco -- Nov. 22, 1999 --
MOROCCO-BOURSE-1, 11-22 -- The exterior of the Casablanca Stock
Exchange, which is shutting down early next year, exchange
officials say, thrusting Casablanca's small but technologically hip
stock market into the growing ranks of virtual exchanges worldwide.
``We'll be cruising on the electronic highway,'' says Zouheir
Bensaid, the immediate past president of the exchange. (Joseph
Treaster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) HULL, Mass. -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SUNRISE-SURFER, 11-22 --
A lone surfer emerges from the water at dawn after some early
morning surfing at Nantasket Beach. Unseasonably warm air covered
much of the Eastern States on Monday where temperatures in the
Boston area, three days before Thanksgiving, were in the 60s. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- JOHNSTON-BOOK, 11-22 --
Wayne Johnston, author of ``The Colony of Unrequited Dreams,'' a
tale of Newfoundland. ``The Great Newfoundland Novel is like the
Great American Novel - it never will exist,'' says the 41-year-old
Canadian. ``It's just something to shoot for.'' (Chester Higgins
Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE,
11-22 -- Mary Bryant, left, and Madeline Mesnick in a meditation
class led by Dr. David Payne at Memorial Sloan-Kettering's new
center, which makes use of alternative approaches. Meditation, the
discipline of directed attention that began in India about 2,500
years ago, is among the most popular techniques now going
mainstream. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- DAY-FEATURE, 11-22 --
Kimberly Vaccaro, 9, shows off her climbing prowess on a cherry
tree in the shadow of the Washington Monument, covered in
scafolding while undergoing renovations, on Monday. Ms. Vaccaro and
her family, from Reading, Mass., were visiting the monuments in the
nation's capital on an extrodinarily warm day. (Carol T. Powers/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-BREAST-CANCER-2, 11-22
-- Lee Crespi, the facilitator for Beth Israel Medical Center's
breast cancer support group for lesbians. ``You don't want to have
to think about being gay when you're dealing with something that is
life and death,'' she says, adding that in a group where everyone
is gay, ``you don't have to justify or explain your life to other
people.'' (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-BREAST-CANCER-1, 11-22
-- Phyllis Siegel, left, and Connie Kopelov, are members of a
breast cancer support group for lesbian couples. That lesbians need
or want a separate support group may seem puzzling to the larger
heterosexual world, but women who participate in such gatherings
say they need their own group not because they are uncomfortable
with straight women, but because straight women are uncomfortable
with lesbians. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) DAVIS, Calif -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MEREDITH-WINE,
11-22 -- Carole P. Meredith, at work in her California vineyard,
has shown that several well-known wine grapes are not pure strains
but hybrids, disconcerting those who thought hybrids inferior. ``I
think we are really on the threshold of understanding these
things,'' she says. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- ROUNDABOUT-THEATER, 11-22
-- The old Selwyn Theater on 42nd Street is undergoing a $21.5
million transformation from woebegone B-movie house to its gilded
1918 neo-Renaissance origins. The theater will house the
long-nomadic, nonprofit Roundabout Theater Company. (Jeffery A.
Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- NY-REMEDIAL-EDUC, 11-22 --
Luz Schreiber, a sophmore at Hunter College, with Liam
Flynn-Jambeck during a meeting of the state board of Regents on
Monday. The board is expected to clear the way for the City
University of New York to begin to exclude students from its degree
programs who cannot demonstrate that they are ready to begin
``college level work'' in both mathematics and English. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PRINCEVILLE, N.C. -- Nov. 22, 1999 --
NC-FLOOD-HOLDOUTS-B&AMP;W-2, 11-21 -- Residents of the town, settled by
former slaves, dig their way out of a major snowstorm last century.
After recent floods in the area, some of the worst in the state's
history, Princeville's more than 2,000 citizens, many of whom are
direct descendants from the freed slaves who founded the town, are
struggling with choices that will determine whether their historic
town can ever exist again. (Edgecombe County Memorial Library/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PRINCEVILLE, N.C. -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- NC-FLOOD-HOLDOUTS,
11-21 -- Linda Whitest salvages what she can last week from her
mother's house which was ruined when the Tar River overflowed its
banks in September. After one of the worst floods in North
Carolina's history, Princeville's more than 2,000 citizens, many of
whom are direct descendants from the freed slaves who founded the
town, are struggling with choices that will determine whether their
historic town can ever exist again. (Bob Rives/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-7,
11-22 -- Crystallized saccharin, photographed by Stefan Eberhard of
the University of Georgia, as entered in the International Small
World Competition, established 25 years ago by Nikon Inc. The
contest honors photographers whose subjects are normally unseen,
visible only through the microscope. (Stefan Eberhard/Courtesy of
Nikon)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-6,
11-22 -- A parasite, Chilondella uncinata, magnified 100 times and
photographed by Christian Frie of Cologne, Germany. The
International Small World Competition honors photographers whose
subjects are normally unseen, visible only through the microscope.
(Christian Frie/Courtesy of Nikon)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-5,
