history, Princeville's more than 2,000 citizens, many of whom are
direct descendants from the freed slaves who founded the town, are
struggling with choices that will determine whether their historic
town can ever exist again. (Edgecombe County Memorial Library/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PRINCEVILLE, N.C. -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- NC-FLOOD-HOLDOUTS,
11-21 -- Linda Whitest salvages what she can last week from her
mother's house which was ruined when the Tar River overflowed its
banks in September. After one of the worst floods in North
Carolina's history, Princeville's more than 2,000 citizens, many of
whom are direct descendants from the freed slaves who founded the
town, are struggling with choices that will determine whether their
historic town can ever exist again. (Bob Rives/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-7,
11-22 -- Crystallized saccharin, photographed by Stefan Eberhard of
the University of Georgia, as entered in the International Small
World Competition, established 25 years ago by Nikon Inc. The
contest honors photographers whose subjects are normally unseen,
visible only through the microscope. (Stefan Eberhard/Courtesy of
Nikon)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-6,
11-22 -- A parasite, Chilondella uncinata, magnified 100 times and
photographed by Christian Frie of Cologne, Germany. The
International Small World Competition honors photographers whose
subjects are normally unseen, visible only through the microscope.
(Christian Frie/Courtesy of Nikon)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-5,
11-22 -- Crystals of vitamin B12, by Stefan Eberhard of the
University of Georgia, as entered in the International Small World
Competition, established 25 years ago by Nikon Inc. Though many of
the participants are scientists, the contest is open to anyone
interested in photomicrography. (Stefan Eberhard/Courtesy of Nikon)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-4,
11-22 -- A water droplet on a leaf, by Jean-Francois Gonnet of
Villeurbanne, France, as entered in the International Small World
Competition, established 25 years ago by Nikon Inc. Starting next
month, winning photographs will be exhibited at various sites
around the country. (Jean-Francois Gonnet/Courtesy of Nikon)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-3,
11-22 -- The head of a zebrafish, extremely close up, by James E.
Hayden of Blue Bell, Pa., as entered in the International Small
World Competition, established 25 years ago by Nikon Inc. The
contest prizes will be awarded in New York City next week. (James
E. Hayden/Courtesy of Nikon)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-2,
11-22 -- Lars Bech, from Naarden, the Netherlands, won second place
in the International Small World Competition, established 25 years
ago by Nikon Inc., for this image of Viagra dissolved in ammonia.
Over the years prizes have been won by prospectors, members of the
clergy, engineers and other amateur photographers. (Lars
Bech/Courtesy of Nikon)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- SCI-MICRO-PHOTOGRAPHY-1,
11-22 -- Alexey Khodjakov of Albany won first prize in the
International Small World Competition, established 25 years ago by
Nikon Inc., for this image of a lung cell from a newt, in the
process of dividing. Khodjakov used a multi-step process involving
dyes, filters and a computer to create it. (Alexey
Khodjakov/Courtesy of Nikon) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ARLINGTON, Mass. -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- AUTHOR-LERNER-BOS,
11-22 -- Rabbi Devon Lerner in her home office. Given the title of
Lerner's new book ``Celebrating Interfaith Marriages,'' you just
know she is going to rattle a few cages. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- Nov. 22, 1999 -- CRIMES-PONZI-B&AMP;W-BOS, 11-22 --
Sheriff Cone P. Blake and Charles Ponzi, right, arrive at the
courthouse after Ponzi had completed arrangements for bail. Ponzi
did something few other criminals could manage: He got his name
attached to his crime. Ponzi, who fleeced Bostonians out of
millions in 1920, did not invent what has come to be known as a
Ponzi scheme, a scam in which early investors are paid with money
from new investors. The con had been around for years. But Ponzi
did it on such a grand scale, with such flair and in such full view
of the world and the media, that he earned his place in criminal
history. (Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JERUSALEM-- Nov. 22, 1999 -- ISRAEL-CHURCHES, 11-22 --
Two pilgrims outside the Church of the Holy Sepulcher which was
closed on Monday. Churches were closed throughout the Holy Land on
Monday as part of a dispute that has soured Christian-Muslim
relations and left Israel caught in the middle. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
