<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      11-22 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALKS TO AVERT BANKRUPTCY AT GERMAN COMPANY FAIL
</P>
<P>
   Philipp Holzmann, the biggest construction company in Germany,
appeared headed toward bankruptcy after late-night talks brokered
by Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder failed to reach a compromise among
banks trying to arrange a $2.6 billion bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann has been on the brink of insolvency since last week,
when it said it had suddenly uncovered $1.3 billion in soured real
estate loans. The German chancellor had raised some optimism of a
solution by arranging talks among the banks and political leaders,
but negotiations collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI MOVE CHEERS INVESTORS
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Telecom Italia and the companies that acquired it last
spring climbed after a decision to abandon a plan to strip the
company, Italy's biggest phone provider, of its profitable cellular
phone unit. Analysts said that while investors appeared pleased
with the decision, they would not be fully reassured until Roberto
Colaninno, the chief executive of Olivetti, which used its Tecnost
subsidiary to take control of Telecom Italia in a $34 billion
takeover in May, gave more details of alternative strategies.
</P>
<P>
   NIKE CONSOLIDATES ITS AD ACCOUNT
</P>
<P>
   Nike decided unexpectedly to consolidate its American brand
assignments, with billings estimated at $350 million, at Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy, the agency that created the signature theme ``Just do
it.'' Since March 1997, Wieden &AMP; Kennedy had shared the Nike
account with Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE OVER WORKPLACE INJURIES
</P>
<P>
   Proposed federal rules aimed at preventing on-the-job injuries
from repetitive motion touched off a wide-ranging debate over how
such injuries occur, what they cost businesses and what can be done
to avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   SBC TAKES 43 PERCENT STAKE IN PRODIGY
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications, the regional telephone company, said that it
would transfer all of its residential Internet customers to Prodigy
Communications, the online service that has long been overshadowed
by America Online, in return for a 43 percent stake in Prodigy
worth about $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ ADVANCES TO RECORD AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks continued their rapid ascent as the NASDAQ
composite index rose to its 14th high close in the last 17
sessions. The other main stock gauges were mixed. NASDAQ rose 23.31
points, to 3,392.56. The Dow Jones industrial average increased
85.63 points, to 11,089.52. But the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index slipped 1.06 points, to 1,420.94.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT STOCK RISES DESPITE SUITS
</P>
<P>
   A growing wave of private lawsuits against Microsoft, including
a class-action suit filed in a state court in San Francisco, has
the company fighting on several legal fronts at once, raising the
stakes in its antitrust battle in Washington and intensifying
pressure on Microsoft to settle with the Justice Department.
Indeed, the appointment of a mediator and a prospect for a
Microsoft settlement offset any concern by investors that Microsoft
might get swamped by lawsuits. Shares of the company rose $4.1875,
to $90.1875.
</P>
<P>
   CRUDE OIL RISES TO $27 A BARREL
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil prices surged 3.6 percent, to $27 a barrel, the
highest since the Persian Gulf war, after reports that Iraq halted
oil shipments and rejected a U.N. plan to extend an export
agreement for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   TV TECHNOLOGY PROPOSED FOR BLIND
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission has proposed that
broadcasters be required to adopt technology allowing the blind to
follow the action on television by listening to a narrator describe
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
