<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8392 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ABORTION-COX     11-22 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Choose Life' license plates violate constitution, NOW, rabbi
claims
 &HT;    By John Pacenti
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A former lawmaker, who is also the son
of a rabbi, is teaming with the National Organization for Women to
thwart the state's imminent sale of the ``Choose Life'' license
plate, saying it promotes a blatantly unconstitutional
anti-abortion slogan.
</P>
<P>
   The group's game plan: Use the Bible to ``turn the tables'' on
the religious right's own arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush and his Cabinet will decide today whether to give
the final approval to a minor color tweaking of the plate's design.
If approved, the Department of Motor Vehicles and Highways will
start pressing about 15,000 tags, which will be available in
January for an extra $22 to motorists.
</P>
<P>
   The bright yellow plate has child-like crayon drawings of
children's faces with ``Choose Life'' scrawled on top _ a phrase
long associated with opposing abortion. NOW hopes to stop the plate
before it starts showing up at county comptroller offices and tag
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The organization will seek an injunction in Palm Beach County
Circuit Court by Friday, Boca Raton attorney and former Democratic
state Rep. Barry Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   The tag violates the U.S. Constitution and actually misuses
theology for political gain, said Silver, a one-term Democrat and
son of a rabbi. The state is embracing a slogan of a sometimes
violent movement, in which doctors who perform abortions have been
shot and their clinics bombed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By creating the license plate, the state of Florida has placed
its imprimatur upon a religious motto which has frequently been
used to harass, intimidate and at times kill and maim those who
seek to exercise their rights, including the right to choose
abortion,'' according to the complaint obtained in advance by The
Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the license plate mocked NOW's 11th-hour plans,
and the sponsor of the state law creating the plate that passed the
legislature earlier this year said he was extremely disappointed
that the organization failed to get the point that the tag is
``pro-adoption'' not ``anti-abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who attack this, I think, need to get a life _ no pun
intended,'' said Sen. Jim Sebesta, R-St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said he will ``turn the tables'' on the religious right
by using the Bible as part of his argument, saying that ``Choose
Life'' is a phrase that appears in Deuteronomy 30:19. He said it is
inappropriate for a biblical message to be used by the government
to support a divisive political issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida supports and endorses a motto which advances
religion,'' Silver said. The plate's supporters ``are using the
Bible to deceive.''
</P>
<P>
   Also expect an argument from Exodus 21:22 that stipulates
punishment for certain crimes: a life for a life, but a fine if a
fetus is killed. ``The Bible is clearly pro-choice,'' said Silver,
who plans to run again next year for the legislature. ``There is
not one word restricting abortion in the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver's interpretation is a stretch of the intent of the
wording, said Dana Bible, associate professor of philosophy at Palm
Beach Atlantic College.
</P>
<P>
   While the word ``fine'' does appear in many translations of the
Scriptures, he said, ``To me, the argument made from that is the
Hebrews had a different understanding of the value of an unborn
child to that of a living person.'' Nonetheless, there was a value
and there was a penalty, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver has been courting Planned Parenthood Inc. and the
American Jewish Congress to join in the complaint as well.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cabinet vote approached, NOW was lobbying certain
members, such as Attorney General Bob Butterworth. ``We hope the
Cabinet will apply some pressure and re-think the situation and do
what's best in Florida,'' said Toni Van Pelt, president of NOW's
Florida chapter. ``If not, then we will follow (Silver's) advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Cabinet says no _ something it has never done on a
specialty plate _ it would simply mean a redesign because the
Legislature already has approved the tag.
</P>
<P>
   If NOW's injunction succeeds, it will be yet another setback for
supporters of the plate. Two years ago, Democratic Gov. Lawton
Chiles vetoed it, but this year his Republican successor signed it.
Van Pelt said Bush wants to divide Floridians by supporting such
nonsensical issues.
</P>
<P>
   When told of Silver's plans, the Marion County commissioner who
designed the plate, laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to do something to justify their existence,'' said
Randy Harris, executive director of Choose Life Inc. in Ocala.
``The problem that organizations like Planned Parenthood have with
our license tag is that it can't receive any funds ... This is
pretty frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   Money is an issue. According to the complaint, money generated
from the plate will go only to ``agencies which will never refer a
woman to an abortion facility, even if the pregnancy is a result of
rape or incest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These clinics don't give family planning and explain full
reproductive rights to women,'' Van Pelt said. ``They lay guilt
trips on them if they consider to choose abortion. A lot of times
churches run these clinics.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Harris thinks the effort will fail, already an
Orlando obstetrician-gynecologist, in a separate complaint, has
forced an injunction on another abortion-related law signed by
Bush: one that requires 48-hour parental notification for minors
who get abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Silver also has been victorious on such issues. In 1997, he
obtained an injunction blocking a state law that required doctors
to provide a checklist of information to those seeking abortions.
The courts eventually struck the law down, ruling it was designed
to obstruct a woman's right to abortion, which was upheld by the
U.S. Supreme Court in the landmark Roe vs. Wade decision in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   If Silver's battle heads to the courts it will most likely come
down to whether the plate violates the separation of church and
state or is, as supporters claim, simply a pro-adoption message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is an attempt to interfere with a woman's right
to choose, and we know that they don't really mean that they just
want folks to adopt children. They are doing it just to control
women,'' Van Pelt said.
</P>
<P>
   Sebesta has said that for the license plate to be effective, the
phrase ``Choose Life'' must be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sponsored this law because I can see this happening,'' the
lawmaker said. ``A young 16- or 17-year-old pregnant girl, with a
lot of peer pressure to have an abortion but in her heart doesn't
want one, is driving down the road. She stops at a red light and
the car in front of her has a ``Choose Life'' license plate, and
she realizes she is not alone, that there is an option.''
</P>
<P>
   John Pacenti writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: johnpacenti(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
