<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8395 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-DEZWHITE-COX     11-22 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DEZWHITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Receiver corps pulling for White
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The notion of Kelly Campbell lining up without his
running mate, Dez White, doesn't set well with Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Just the thought of White, who suffered a pulled hamstring at
Wake Forest, not being able to answer the bell for Saturday's
regular-season-ending clash with rival Georgia sends chills
throughout The Flats.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an All-America-type receiver not in the offense,
you are going to miss him,'' Stan Hixon, the Yellow Jackets'
receivers coach said Monday. ``You have to.''
</P>
<P>
   White is listed as day-to-day, and Hixon said the junior from
Jacksonville expects to play against a young Bulldogs secondary
which has been reshuffled after being torched by Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a sophomore from Mays High, entered the Wake game with
58 receptions for 964 yards and nine touchdowns. But without White
to attract defensive attention, the Deacons held Campbell to five
catches for 49 yards.
</P>
<P>
   However, Campbell did set the Tech single-season record for
yards, and has 1,013. He needs two more catches and a touchdown to
set Yellow Jackets marks in those categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dez had an excellent year last year, and we knew that Dez was
going to be double-covered a lot this year,'' Campbell said. ``We
needed other receivers to come forward and make big plays in order
to spread out and help the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   But with White out of the mix, the dynamics change.
</P>
<P>
   White went down early in the first quarter against the Demon
Deacons after being hit while on punt coverage and never returned.
By the time Tech got on track, it was too little, too late and Wake
stunned the defending ACC co-champs 26-23.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss, No. 20 Tech (7-3) tumbled out of Bowl
Championship Series contention, leaving the grudge match with the
Bulldogs (7-3) at Bobby Dodd Stadium as the final shot at saving
face in a season that began with so much promise.
</P>
<P>
   While White's absence was not the sole reason for the Jackets'
collapse, an already potent Deacons defense was able to double-up
on Campbell, playing a zone defense which denied the long ball and
forced quarterback Joe Hamilton to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you missed Dez, but you have to have other players
step up,'' Hixon said. ``Missing him is one thing, but this gives
some other players an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Wake, Kerry Watkins was his normal steady self. The
redshirt freshman from LaPlace, La., had six catches for 90 yards.
White's backups, freshman Will Glover and junior Brett Basquin had
the games of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Glover delivered on the promise he has shown in practice,
catching two passes for 29 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Basquin _ who broke his foot in the preseason and
returned two games ago _ grabbed the first three passes of his
career, including a 25-yard fourth-quarter touchdown that pulled
the Jackets within 26-15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our receivers have to make plays for us to win,'' Hixon said.
``That's always our goal. And we have a big-play man in Kelly
Campbell.''
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
