<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8398 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS &LR;      11-22 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ Four days after the Texas A&AMP;M campus was thrown
into a state of shock when the Aggie Bonfire collapsed and 12 young
people lost their lives, the football team resumed preparations
Monday for its game against Texas.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The players were trying their best to concentrate on football,
but their mood before practice remained somber. Many talked of
wanting to honor the memory of the deceased with a win over
archrival Texas, but they realized the tragedy is not going to be
washed away by anything that happens at Kyle Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that's going to be looming around this
campus and this city for a long, long time,'' said offensive guard
Chris Valletta. ``It's definitely something that we're thinking
about. As far as football practices and things like that getting
back to normal, yeah, but even when we're out there we're always
thinking about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Aggies coach R.C. Slocum gave the players Sunday off to spend
time with their families and friends, giving them an extra day to
deal with the tragedy. For his part, Slocum wasn't sure what to
expect when the Aggies play the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people are conditioned to believe that it's only old
people that die,'' said Slocum. ``When something like this happens,
it's shocking to them. Here are people they see around campus,
people like them, and all of a sudden they are no longer here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something they're going to quickly forget. The
whole campus has been engulfed in the sadness, the sorrow. The
players are a part of this family. I really don't know what it will
be like Friday. I've had people tell me they don't even know what
the crowd in the stands will be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that once the ball is kicked, it'll be football as
usual. I think that will be a positive thing for everybody
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies canceled practice Thursday and Friday and had a brief
workout Saturday. Slocum thought it would be best to give the
players Sunday off, but he expected they would be ready to resume
preparations for a game that has taken on deeper meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to come back ready to focus on the challenge of
the game and the responsibility we have because of the tradition,''
said Slocum. ``That's what the whole Bonfire was all about. It
wouldn't make sense for us not to focus on getting ready for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way we can honor these students who were victims is
to take seriously our obligation to prepare well and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Valletta and guard Semisi Heimuli, two of the Aggies who took
part in rescue efforts after the Bonfire collapse Thursday, both
had a sense of becoming closer to the student body in the period
since the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, we weren't out there (at the Bonfire site)
as football players,'' said Valletta. ``We were out there as
students of this university. We realized they needed help, so we
all took off and went out there. So many people came together that
day, it was unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing made Texas A&AMP;M real to me for the first time.
The spirit of this place is just unbelievable. For the first time,
I really know what it means to be a Texas A&AMP;M student.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Heimuli, one of the first players to arrive on the scene:
``Everybody was coming up to us thanking us for being out there and
helping. I felt that was the only place we should have been. We had
to be out there. We had to do whatever we could to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I feel we owe the school a win. A lot of guys might not
feel up to it, but we owe everybody a win over Texas. We've got to
deal with playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior wide receiver Matt Bumgardner wants to put his focus on
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very weird week _ that's the word that keeps
coming back to me,'' said Bumgardner. ``This is such a tragedy, and
it's not just a natural tragedy. People were working on such a
great tradition, and it's all about football. This game is always
large, but after everything that's happened, it's almost hard to
talk about. Nobody knows how it's going to affect the players
getting ready. You've got to push on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first day we came out (to practice) Saturday, our minds
weren't there. After thinking about something so much, it has an
effect on you whether you think it does or not. We made a lot of
mental mistakes. I think with each day, we'll get more and more
into playing football. You don't want to say, `Yeah, we're doing
this for them.' But it is in the back of everyone's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people were out there for us. No matter if the guys say
that or not, it's in the back of everyone's head, so it's
definitely going to have an effect on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior cornerback Jason Webster spent his time off Sunday
reflecting and praying for the victims and their families. Webster,
one of the team's leaders, seemed Monday to be emotionally caught
up in the tragedy and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough,'' said Webster. ``I look at those lives lost,
and I'm wondering if on that day they had any thought in their
minds about death _ I'm sure they didn't. It makes me realize how
precious life is. We all take life for granted. I have so much
compassion for their families, especially this time of the year,
Thanksgiving. I look and see my parents being in the position that
those parents are in, and it brings a lot of sorrow to my heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that everything happens for a reason. I just don't know
what this reason is, and I'm not trying to figure out what it is. I
just pray for their families and for the souls that were lost.''
</P>
<P>
   During team meetings since last week's tragedy, Slocum said he
has stressed to the players that dealing with life's problems is
part of the maturation process. In no uncertain terms, Slocum told
the players they will have to face up to sadness throughout their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we tell them is that it's not the bad things
in life that happen to you that's important, it's how you react to
them,'' said Slocum. ``I told them that for the rest of their lives
they're going to have to deal with the emotions they were feeling
right now. It's inescapable. This is a reality of life that we all
have to deal with. As a young person, that's a little bit
startling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you leave home, that may be the last time you see
your mom, or your little sister, or your big brother. You need to
live life like that. You base your actions on the reality that life
is very fragile. You try to put some meaning into this.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got kids grappling with what's going on, and you try to
explain that this is the way it works. You have to deal with it.
Life has to go on. You can't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies are getting ready for their game against Texas, but
to a man they know they will never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed basically everything about all of us, I think,''
said Valletta. ``I don't think any person can say they haven't been
affected by this. It puts life in perspective. People my age, 21 or
22 years old, we have this attitude of invincibility. You don't
think things like this could happen to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you see fellow students in this tragedy, it shows no
one can control their own destiny. Football is a game, and a lot of
people think it's important, but it's entertainment. This is so
much more important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
