<HEADER>
A8402 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-ALCOHOL-NOTIFICAT     11-22 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ALCOHOL-NOTIFICATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School administrators back away from notification policy
 &HT;    By Stephen Kiehl
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Stung by criticism from students and
administrators, state college officials on Monday backed away from
plans to notify parents when their children violate drug or alcohol
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Regent Steven Uhlfelder, who proposed the mandatory notification
policy in May, said the state should focus instead on providing
more education and counseling to students and only call parents in
the most extreme cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be parental notification when the health and
safety of the student is in jeopardy, but under most circumstances,
for just the first-time offense, we don't need to be notifying
parents,'' Uhlfelder said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That's welcome news to students, who opposed the notification
plan on grounds that it invaded their privacy and treated them like
children. Many college administrators also thought an automatic
call policy was too strict _ and too unwieldy to carry out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can provide students education and a safe environment
for experimentation, then we don't need to tell the parents every
time they pick up a can of beer,'' FAU assistant vice president for
student affairs Connie Foley said at a forum Monday.
</P>
<P>
   FAU formed a task force last month to figure out when and how
parents would be notified. While there is agreement that the
parents of first-time violators should not be called, after that it
gets murkier.
</P>
<P>
   After how many offenses in what time period should parents
notified? Should consideration be given to students whose parents
may pull them out of school because of a violation?
</P>
<P>
   FAU senior Raquel Charles, 22, was cited by FAU police for
serving alcohol to underage students when she was a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had called my dad, I would not be at FAU now,'' the
Panama native said Monday. ``He would have sent me back to Panama
because he does not allow that kind of behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Regents are considering parental notification in the hopes
parents will be able to do what universities have struggled with
for years: change a culture of drinking on campuses that has led to
serious injury and death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education alone has not altered or stopped these more severe
things from happening,'' said Barry Gregory, a substance abuse
counselor at FAU.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Florida in September, two young men _ one a
UF student _ died in alcohol-related violence at off-campus
apartments. Earlier this year, the UF fraternity Delta Chi was
kicked off campus for alcohol violations, among others.
</P>
<P>
   A parental-notification rule has already proven successful at
one college. University of Delaware officials, who tell parents of
all student violations, say parents end up talking to their
children about alcohol, preventing future problems.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 public universities and 15 private ones have adopted
parental-notification rules, most of them this year. For years,
colleges had only contacted parents when drinking led to death or
serious injury. But under other circumstances colleges were
reluctant because of federal privacy laws protecting students.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, however, Congress approved legislation that
explicitly allowed colleges to let parents know when students under
21 commit alcohol or drug violations.
</P>
<P>
   Uhlfelder said he will ask the Board of Regents in February to
require Florida's 10 public universities to come up with some sort
of parental-notification policy, but the specifics will be left to
each university.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, though, this policy will not stop under-age drinking,
Uhlfelder said. He has endorsed a plan drawn up by the Florida
Student Association to establish more counseling, education and
intervention plans on campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Uhlfelder said the Board of Regents will also request $2 million
from the state legislature next year to hire more substance abuse
counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give Uhlfelder credit for addressing this issue in a
way to give students rights and autonomy,'' said Kevin Mayeux,
executive director of the student association. ``Students are
adults, and they should be given some credence as adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Kiehl writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: stephenkiehl(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
