<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-THOREAU-LANDFILL-BOS &LR;      11-22 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOREAU-LANDFILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP WANTS TO RESTORE SITE WHERE THOREAU WALKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ Somewhere under a mountain of garbage is Ripple
Lake, a tiny kettle pond where Henry David Thoreau used to watch
the wind kick up the waves. The path he followed on everyday walks
near Walden Pond is down there, too, along with the dips in the
land he carefully mapped in his job as a surveyor.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes a powerful imagination to conjure up America's most
famous naturalist at the Concord landfill today. Though the dump is
closed, the dirt-covered hills of trash remain, surrounded by a
wasteland of compost heaps, paint recycling shacks, and _ perhaps
soon _ cellular phone towers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a twist on the usual preservation fight, activists
including rock star Don Henley are rallying to save the dump,
calling on the town to turn the 35-acre site over to the state to
restore a 19th-century-style landscape, even if it is not the same
one Thoreau knew.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a national community preservation group called Scenic
America plans to declare the dump site and the Walden Woods around
it one of 12 ``last chance landscapes'' in the United States that
deserves protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just keep in mind the vision of the future. I view this as a
temporary condition,'' said Kathi Anderson, executive director of
Henley's Walden Woods Project, surveying the weed-strewn moonscape
that was a forest in Thoreau's time. ``We are in the midst of a
national treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Town officials say they, too, want to honor Thoreau's legacy,
but not at the expense of services to current residents. They say
they have agreed to conserve part of the dump for restoration as
long as one section remains in town hands for public works, such as
serving as a dumping ground for snow plowed from the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in beautifying the area, but at the same
time, we've got some very real public safety and public health
concerns that are not going to go away,'' said Concord town manager
Chris Whelan.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over the Concord landfill is part of a bigger fight
to reclaim the 2,680-acre Walden Woods, one of the most storied
natural landscapes in the country, but also one of the most abused.
Since Thoreau lived in his rustic cabin on the banks of Walden Pond
from 1845 to 1847, the woods have been chopped up by development,
from busy Route 2 to a trailer park to the landfill, which opened
in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Walden Pond itself became an enormously popular swimming hole
visited by over 600,000 people annually, making for a
disillusioning experience for anyone who expected to commune with
nature on a hot summer day.
</P>
<P>
   However, since the late 1980s when developer Mortimer Zuckerman
tried to build an office complex on Brister's Hill, where Thoreau
did his seminal study of forest growth, conservationists have gone
on the offensive. Backed by the celebrity power and resources of
Henley, a member of the 1970s rock band the Eagles, the Walden
Woods Project has acquired 100 acres around the pond, including
Brister's Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Now, state and federal agencies have teamed up with the
conservationists to pursue even more ambitious goals. The state
Department of Environmental Management, which manages Walden Pond,
is planning to relocate Route 126 away from the pond's banks, and
Congress has authorized a study of the Walden Woods area by the
National Park Service and Walden Woods Project to develop a long
range plan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the landfill remains perhaps the ugliest blight on the
woods, sitting right on Route 2 less than 300 yards from Thoreau's
cabin site. Townspeople were reluctant to create the dump in the
first place, voting for it only after local officials promised the
dump would be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years later, in 1994, residents voted unanimously to
close the landfill, and Walden activists thought they had won the
fight. In partnership with the Department of Environmental
Management, the Walden Woods Project even offered Concord $500,000
to defray the $1.2 million cost to cap the landfill, as long as the
land was turned over for conservation.
</P>
<P>
   However, Concord officials had second thoughts about giving up
the landfill site. The land was perfect for storing leaves and yard
waste, as well as winter snow, they felt, and no one lived nearby
to complain about all the trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, selectmen plan to open part of the dump site for cell phone
towers, in part to settle a lawsuit from AT&AMP;T over the town's
refusal to set aside other places for the towers.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson of the Walden Woods Project argues that all the current
uses of the landfill site, with the possible exception of the
compost heaps, ``are incompatible with the history of the area and
the ecology,'' but she has gamely sought to find alternative sites
for the town.
</P>
<P>
   Working with researchers from the Massachusetts Audubon Society,
the Walden Woods Project has suggested a 10-acre state-owned site
that the town could have for free. But Concord officials say
neither the state land, nor any alternative so far, is good enough;
for instance, a wetland on the state-owned land would limit
development.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to agree with town officials, Anderson flew to Washington
for the press conference with Scenic America, highlighting 12
important but endangered landscapes across the country. Walden
Woods is the only New England site on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson acknowledges that it is too late to turn the landfill
back to the pitch pine forest and series of gullies that existed in
Thoreau's time. Because of the garbage underneath, it may not even
be possible to plant trees on the site.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jeff Collins of the Audubon Society has suggested
creating an open grassland reminiscent of farm fields in the
mid-19th century, and he has even found a spot to recreate Ripple
Lake, where Thoreau once watched butterflies and salamanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this site, present day, we're talking about a very
expensive restoration project and a very long-term one,'' said
Anderson. However, the landfill site is too important to let it
become a repository ``for any undesirable project that doesn't have
a home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
