<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8408 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     11-22 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     How to Give Without Giving Up 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: My husband and I are in our early 80s. Our assets total &LR; 
 &UR; approximately $1.3 million, and our income approaches $70,000 &LR; 
 &UR; yearly. We would like to begin giving our children tax-free &LR; 
 &UR; gifts each year. We are healthy, but in the future, we may need &LR; 
 &UR; to pay for long-term home care. If we were to establish &LR; 
 &UR; certificates of deposit naming our children as joint owners, &LR; 
 &UR; would these be considered tax-free gifts? We want the money &LR; 
 &UR; available to ourselves throughout our lifetimes, and upon our &LR; 
 &UR; deaths, the children could cash in the certificates. &LR;
<P>
   &QL; 
A: What you are describing does not qualify as a gift for tax
purposes, says Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller. He
says that under your plan, the money in the CDs would be considered
part of your estate and subject to estate taxes after you die.
</P>
<P>
   The money in the CDs would qualify as a gift if your children
withdrew the funds from the CDs during your lifetimes, or if you
removed your names from the account title. But you indicate that
you are specifically trying to avoid such moves, because you are
concerned about potential long-term-care expenses.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to discuss this matter with an estate lawyer.
There are compromises you can make _ such as setting up certain
kinds of trusts _ that would allow you to remove the money from
your taxable estate without completely giving up control of the
funds. As a rule, however, you would have to share control with
your children.
</P>
<P>
   Before you do this, you might want to re-read ``King Lear.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Q: I expect that at the end of the year, I will have a total of &LR; 
 &UR; $15,000 in short-term capital gains and $10,000 in short-term &LR; 
 &UR; capital losses for a net gain of $5,000. Also, I expect to have &LR; 
 &UR; $5,000 in interest from certificates of deposit. I will have &LR; 
 &UR; paid my stockbroker $8,000 of margin interest. Can I use the &LR; 
 &UR; entire $8,000 as a deduction to offset my investment gains? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   You can use margin interest _ the interest you pay your broker
to buy stock with borrowed funds _ to offset the full amount of
taxable investment income, such as capital gains and CD interest _
on Schedule A of IRS Form 1040. Since your net capital gain and
your CD interest total $10,000, you can use the full $8,000 of
interest as an offset.
</P>
<P>
   Even if your margin interest were to exceed your investment
income, you wouldn't lose any part of the deduction; you would
simply carry over the surplus to succeeding tax years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the concise information you enter on Schedule A,
you must file Form 4952, on which you provide fuller details about
your investment income and the interest you paid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Avoiding Double Tax
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: My grandmother passed away recently, leaving me the bulk of &LR; 
 &UR; her estate and appointing me trustee. Her estate was worth well &LR; 
 &UR; over a million dollars, so it is subject to estate taxes. Part &LR; 
 &UR; of my inheritance includes U.S. savings bonds worth $150,000 _ &LR; 
 &UR; including accrued interest _ on the day my grandmother died. My &LR; 
 &UR; tax guy says that figure is the amount to be used in figuring &LR; 
 &UR; estate taxes. However, I'm also being told that when I go to &LR; 
 &UR; cash in these bonds, I will have to pay taxes again. Is this &LR; 
 &UR; correct? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: It could happen. This is one of those unusual cases where an
inheritance might not be tax-free to the beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the rules:
</P>
<P>
   The full $150,000 value of the bonds, consisting of principal
and of interest accrued before your grandmother's death, is subject
to estate taxes. In addition, the accrued interest is subject to
income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   You haven't given me the information needed to say whether you
will be the one who pays the income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If your grandmother was reporting interest on her bonds each
year and paying taxes on it, then whatever interest she received in
1999, up to the time of her death, must be reported on her final,
posthumous income-tax return. In that case, you won't have to pay
tax on any interest that accrued on the bonds before your
grandmother died. However, you will have to pay tax on the interest
that accrued after her death.
</P>
<P>
   If your grandmother wasn't paying tax as the interest accrued,
then you and the other people administering the estate have a
choice. The taxes on the accrued interest can be paid off on your
grandmother's final return. Or you, as the beneficiary, can assume
the liability for the interest and pay the tax with your own
return. If you choose the latter method, you are entitled to deduct
from your income the amount of estate taxes that was paid on the
interest.
</P>
<P>
   You should do the arithmetic and decide which method puts the
greatest amount of after-tax money in your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, if you assume the tax burden yourself, you don't
have to pay the taxes on the accrued income right away. You can
wait until you cash in the bonds _ or until they mature, which is
essentially the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
