<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8410 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ADVISERS-ADVISERS_SFC     11-22 1642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVISERS-ADVISERS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Riding the Internet to Retirement  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Many well-to-do people these days are turning away from
professional investment advisers and financial planners, opting
instead to manage their own money with help from the Internet.
<P>
   The Internet abounds with Web sites offering information and
advice to help you optimize your finances. Many of these sites are
free, while others charge just a few dollars per month.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a professional money manager typically will charge
a fee of 1 percent to 1.5 percent of your assets per year. That's
$2,500 to $3,750 on a $250,000 portfolio, which is about the
minimum size that most professionals consider worthy of their
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The substantial fees _ combined with a long bull market that
just won't quit _ has left many people believing that they don't
need the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   After all, who needs expert advice when they can pick big
winners by throwing darts at the daily stock tables? Or by putting
their money in an index mutual fund and letting it ride?
</P>
<P>
   That kind of thinking could prove dangerous if the stock market
ever tanks, some experts warn. Once it becomes tough to succeed
financially, a lot of people might switch off their computers and
come flocking back to the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many permutations in life, and it is difficult
for any software product to handle that,'' says Robert Sterling, an
analyst with Jupiter Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if you have three kids going to college? What if you have
a handicapped sibling or child? There are very specific financial
needs out there. It will be a while before there are solutions on
the Internet good enough to eclipse a professional planner.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, such warnings have fallen on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   Do-it-yourselfers can find not only investment advice, but also
scads of retirement-planning calculators on the Internet. They also
can find tips on how to plan for college, draft wills, minimize
taxes and determine their insurance needs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these resources are pretty basic, but others are quite
sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   The king of them all _ the one against which the others are
judged _ is Financial Engines (www.financialengines.com), a
retirement planner created by Nobel Prize-winning economist William
F. Sharpe of Stanford University, a leading expert on portfolio
modeling.
</P>
<P>
   The site was opened to the public in June. Previously, it was
available only to employees of companies that subscribed to the
service at a cost of about $50 per employee per year.
</P>
<P>
   After you log on to the site and register, Financial Engines
prompts you to list all the holdings in your portfolio and to
answer numerous questions about your income, risk tolerance and
when you hope to retire.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharpe model crunches the numbers and feeds in assumptions
about future inflation, interest rates, dividends and the relative
performances of various classes of assets, such as bonds versus
stocks and large stocks versus small. It then tells you the
percentage probability that you will wind up with enough retirement
income to fit your plans.
</P>
<P>
   Up to that point, Financial Engines is free.
</P>
<P>
   If you want detailed investment advice on how to improve your
portfolio, you will have to subscribe to the service at a price of
$14.95 every three months. Financial Engines will then name
specific mutual funds and tell you exactly how many shares to buy
or sell.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Maggioncalda, chief executive of Financial Engines, says
100,000 people have registered on the site since June, including
10,000 paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial professionals say they aren't too concerned about
their Internet competition.
</P>
<P>
   Says Norm Boone, of Boone Financial Advisors in San Francisco:
``Most of us who have taken in-depth looks at Financial Engines or
other retirement programs figure that if we were to give that same
kind of advice, we might be graded as a C.''
</P>
<P>
   People with ``unusual issues about cash flows, mortality and how
long they are going to work'' will always need professionals, Boone
says. Harold Evensky, a Florida financial planner and president of
the Certified Financial Planner Board of Standards, figures that
Internet financial sites might actually be a plus for his
profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``An educated consumer is good for us,'' he explains. ``It makes
it easier to work with people and helps them make better
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a growing number of hard-core consumers who
consider the Internet sufficient in itself, and have no intention
of delegating their financial planning to the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   When her husband died a few years ago, retired San Francisco
saleswoman Iris Berman, 72, an investment novice, found herself
sitting uneasily on hundreds of thousands of dollars in assets _
mostly cash.
</P>
<P>
   In bygone days, that would have made her an exceptionally hot
prospect for a financial planner. In fact, several of them
solicited her, and she interviewed them conscientiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was very lovely,'' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   But she decided to do it herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``One lady was going to charge me $2,500 every three months,''
she says. ``I don't think she could have earned me that much money.
Financial advisers don't know any more than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Practically every day she browses the financial sites maintained
by America Online, Yahoo and TheStreet.com. She also rummages
through the analyst reports, financial data and news on the Web
site of Charles Schwab, her broker.
</P>
<P>
   She has big gains from investments in Microsoft, Intel and,
especially, Cisco _ ``I own a tremendous amount.`` She concedes
that such volatile stocks might seem dicey for a septuagenarian,
but says they are ``for my childrens' inheritance.''
</P>
<P>
   To balance her tech-stock gambles she has placed 57 percent of
her $850,000 portfolio in fixed-income securities. She says she
needs them for current income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security doesn't pay the rent in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Chatterjee, 66, a retired Air India pilot who lives in San
Francisco, says he was ``totally dependent'' on a financial planner
until early this year, when he dismissed her and began managing his
money himself, drawing on the resources available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I acquired a personal computer, taught myself how to use it
and have been doing pretty good on my own,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He gets many of his investment ideas from the Motley Fool Web
site (www.fool.com), which contains a retirement calculator and
provides profuse information about insurance, trusts and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Satterjee says his human financial planner was ``too
conservative,'' putting 40 percent of his roughly $300,000 in
assets into bonds and cash. Although he is retired, he wanted a
livelier portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   He boosted the proportion of stocks and stock mutual funds to 86
percent, with a heavy emphasis on tech issues such as Applied
Materials, Cisco, Intel and Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to personal investments, one can do quite
successfully and effectively when one takes sufficient time and
interest to read up and follow up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Trudy Jaycox, 43, a Berkeley consultant to the Peace Corps, says
she has amassed a ``substantial'' portfolio by investing her
savings in no-load stock mutual funds. She is particularly partial
to those operated by the hot-performing JanusFund group, which was
recommended to her by her father, a successful investor in his own
right.
</P>
<P>
   She researches funds through the Morningstar Inc. Web site
(www.morningstar.com). She also is a steady user of Motley Fool and
Yahoo (www.yahoo.com), which is notable for its many links to other
sites that specialize in retirement planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a letter from a woman planner who invited me to lunch at
a restaurant,'' she recalls. ''I said: `I don't need you to make
money, I'm doing fine.' Investing is not rocket science. Right now,
you have to be a knucklehead to not be making money.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fulton, 58, of Danville, a retired General Motors executive
with a seven-figure portfolio, says he makes ``100 percent of my
own investment decisions,'' based almost entirely on what he can
glean from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sites he favors are Hoover's Inc. (www.hoovers.com),
which lets you screen thousands of stocks in seconds, using the
parameters of your choice; CNN Finance (www.cnnfn.com), which
includes a mortgage calculator, a college planner and a stock
screener, and CBS MarketWatch (cbs.marketwatch.com), which offers
advice on estate taxes, insurance and writing wills.
</P>
<P>
   Do-it-yourself investing ``has always been my hobby,'' he says.
He says he is ``amazed'' at ``how little sophistication financial
planners have.'' He says many of them seem incapable of offering
sound advice about such fundamental matters as whether to convert a
traditional individual retirement account to a Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Like Satterjee, Fulton complains that planners are ``too
conservative,'' trying to get clients to put ``half your money in
bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very aggressive investor and feel I am going to live to
my mid- to late 80s,'' he observes. ``There are a lot of years left
in there to stand some ups and downs in the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalls that when he was working in Rochester, N.Y., some
years ago, he discussed his retirement package with a Peat Marwick
financial planner whose services were paid for by GM. G.M.  &LR; The man
was sent over from Buffalo, because Peat Marwick didn't have a
planner in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   ``After about two hours,'' Fulton recalls, ``he said: `I'm
embarrassed. I'm learning more from you than you're learning from
me.''' He offered Fulton the opportunity _ which he declined _ to
work for Peat Marwick in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
