<HEADER>
A8412 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-CEBALLOS-TEX     11-22 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CEBALLOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEBALLOS UNVEILS LAKE-VACATION LIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Remember a few years ago when Cedric Ceballos
impulsively left the Los Angeles Lakers in the middle of the
1995-96 season to go on a four-day fishing trip to Phoenix?
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Ceballos now says it didn't happen that way.
Ceballos says the Lakers, with his good graces, fabricated the
story to protect a touchy personal situation involving a member of
his family which he didn't want to be publicly known.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a problem we had to iron out, it got emotional,
and it got tough,'' Ceballos said. ``I just was not thinking
straight. I explained it to the organization, and I explained it to
my teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just something that, for the sake of my family member,
I tried not to get it out publicly. I congratulated the Lakers, and
I appreciate all of them for not saying anything and for keeping it
as a problem toward me, and for just putting the blame all on me
instead of them letting my family business out in the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Ceballos, now the top Mavericks' reserve, says he
believes some NBA executives mistook him as a malcontent who walked
out on his teammates for selfish reasons. He wonders if that might
have had something to do with the lack of interest in signing him
as a free agent the past two off-seasons. He settled for a
two-year, $7.4 million contract to re-sign with the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   He now acknowledges that perhaps he should have said what he's
saying now sooner to avoid getting a bad reputation around the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to sacrifice my job for a couple of days, and if I
had to sacrifice losing some money, then I don't have a problem
with leaving and trying to help \Rmy family\S fight through their
crisis,'' Ceballos said. ``This way it kept my family business
inside the family, and it didn't embarrass or keep my family
members in a bad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Ceballos is really a Renaissance man. He has his own
website. He worked as a television reporter during the WNBA
playoffs this summer. And he has a record company that employs a
lot of friends whom he grew up with.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos, 30, sings R&AMP;B and rap music on a album that is
scheduled to be released in January. The name of the album: Nuff
Ced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real fun album,'' Ced said. ``We do a lot of comical
stuff on it. It's really an entertaining album; everybody in the
family will be able to relate to it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Ceballos cannot relate to is the rash of flagrant fouls
that has cost him portions of the past three seasons. Loren Meyer,
Danny Manning and Chris Mills have committed flagrant fouls on
Ceballos, leaving him with two broken wrists early last season and
knee injuries the two previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe my season ended like that three years in a row
after flagrant fouls by friends of mine,'' Ceballos said. ``I still
haven't seen the \RMeyer hit\S from last year, and I really don't
want to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing against Loren or the rules in the NBA, but I just
wanted to play. It's real tough to sit there and watch and not be
able to show by example. It's good for Dirk \RNowitzki\S to come
out of the game and I tell him something, but it's even better if
I'm out there fighting the battle with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos is the Mavericks' second-leading scorer with 17.9
points per game but has been in a slump of late; he is 5-for-24
from the field in his past two games.
</P>
<P>
   However, forward Michael Finley says Ceballos needs some scoring
support from his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have so much respect around the league as one of the
best one-on-one players in the league like Cedric, when he gets the
ball he's going to attract a lot of attention,'' Finley said. ``If
guys around him are knocking down shots, it's going to take more
pressure off of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos worked with a personal trainer, Marcus Reed, this past
summer for the first time in his 10-year NBA career. Reed used to
run track for UCLA and helped Ceballos strengthen his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past during the summer, I just goofed around,''
Ceballos said. ``I was a real bad stretcher, so I worked on
stretching, conditioning, and I put myself in the right frame of
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when you do that, you can come out a little tougher
mentally. For instance, when we're doing sprints, running up the
hill or weight lifting, you try to compete, and it makes it more
fun.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
