r s BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-22 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAUNTING WEEKEND AWAITS COUPLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Fred Couples steps onto the national stage this week, a
stand-in tapped by tragedy to play a starring role.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight the golfer has basked in before will swathe him in
little warmth. The privilege of playing in the Skins Game Saturday
and Sunday in Indio, Calif., will be hard for Couples to feel for
the pain.
</P>
<P>
   For a few days in the desert, the Los Angeles resident will get
a glimpse of what it must have been like to be Lyndon B. Johnson
running the country in the weeks after John F. Kennedy's
assassination in November of 1963. Or Chris Knight running the
floor for Loyola Marymount University in the weeks after center
Hank Gathers' death in March of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Like Johnson and Knight, Couples is standing in for a fallen
cohort.
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart was slated to join David Duval, Mark O'Meara and
Sergio Garcia in the 18-hole, made-for-television tournament. His
death in October in a freakish plane crash left a hollow too deep
for one man or one month to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Couples, 40, understands this. His insides have been like the
middle of a fallen souffle since he heard the news on October 25
that the private jet carrying Stewart and five other people crashed
in a grassy field in South Dakota after flying a few hours on
auto-pilot, the plane's shell rendered a tin coffin by some
mechanical failure early in the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just bizarre the way he died,'' Couples said. ``I still
can't believe he's gone. If Payne had been sick and we all knew it,
it would have been hard enough to deal with his death. But it was
such an unbelievable thing that happened to him, it makes it harder
to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples knows he isn't the only one shaken to his spikes by
Stewart's death.
</P>
<P>
   He suspects people on both sides of the ropes at Landmark Golf
Club will look at him and see Stewart's ghost. That's why you won't
catch Couples wearing the plus-fours Stewart favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't,'' said Couples, who'd sooner play in his boxers
than give the specter substance.
</P>
<P>
   He expects taming the 7,068-yard layout will be a breeze, next
to controlling his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an awkward feeling, no doubt,'' said Couples, a two-time
winner and seven-time participant in the Skins event, which has
been held since 1983. ``I always appreciate playing in this event,
but in this situation I guess I really don't know how to feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great thing they've chosen me to play. It's not a great
thing that I'm here. I obviously wish I wasn't playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples won his first Skins title in 1995 and repeated the feat
in 1996. His father's death kept him out of the 1997 field. Couples
returned last year and won three skins and $150,000 to increase his
all-time-leading Skins earnings to $1,340,000.
</P>
<P>
   He won't pocket a dime this week even if he wins every hole and
hoards the $1 million purse. Couples has pledged all his earnings
from the event to the Payne Stewart Memorial and the First Orlando
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing for his charity,'' Couples said, ``so every time I
make a putt, I'll be doing something to honor him.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-year tour veteran is known for his loose, loopy swing,
not his loose lips. Considering the circumstances, Couples came off
sounding more classy than brassy when he announced, ``I hope to win
every cent. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples said he's ``playing for Payne and his family and I'm not
the only one.''
</P>
<P>
   That right there is the silver lining. If anything has been
gained by losing Stewart, it's that the public portrait of
professional golfers as cardboard personalities wrapped in
cardigans has been torn to shreds.
</P>
<P>
   As players have honored Stewart in ways great and small, the
tour's camaraderie is what has stood out, not its cutthroat
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The public saw golfers form a human chain around Stewart's
widow, Tracey, at his funeral and wear knickers at the tournament
he was headed to when he died. The public saw a lot of so-called
robots in danger of rusting, so fierce were their tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a first- or second-year player that not everybody
knew,'' Couples said. ``Payne played on the tour 21 years. It's
going to be awkward not just this week but next year and every year
at tournaments where he played and won.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart played in the Skins event four consecutive years,
beginning in 1991. He made more money in the event than anyone save
Couples.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart assuredly will be a major focal point again this year,
if Couples can help it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is try to do my best,'' Couples said, ``and make
everyone remember why I'm here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
