<HEADER>
A8415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHICAGO-MARKETPLACE-1     11-22 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-MARKETPLACE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: DISCORD AT THE CHICAGO BOARD OF TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ After more than 150 years at the top, the Chicago
Board of Trade can no longer call itself the world's largest
futures and options exchange.
</P>
<P>
   It has been eclipsed by an electronic marketplace called Eurex,
formed nine years ago and adopted last year in a merger of the
German and Swiss derivative exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Though the board of trade remains the biggest futures and
options exchange in the United States, it is torn over just how to
meet the growing challenge of electronic trading systems, the same
challenge facing the nation's biggest stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the once-pioneering board of trade _ which began as a
place to trade commodities and now incorporates complex financial
instruments _ can retain its domestic leadership depends in part on
its ability to put internal squabbles to rest.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the last year, the board of trade has been mired in
a series of nasty disputes that have thoroughly disrupted
operations and pitted its chief executive against its chairman.
More recently, the disputes have set a group of traders against the
chief executive and the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   The discord was so pronounced that earlier this year six
investment banks decided not to advise the exchange on its plans to
become a for-profit corporation. Seat prices at the exchange have
plummeted 25 percent in the last month, and other firms are having
second thoughts about alliances with it, fearing gridlock,
according to people who work there.
</P>
<P>
   ``These issues are symptomatic of the problems going on here,''
said Jacob Morowitz, a longtime exchange member. ``We are
directionless and rudderless. We don't have leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest volley in the dispute came just a week ago, when
board of trade members _ mostly traders and brokers in the
agricultural and financial trading pits _ voted in favor of four
petitions seeking, in part, to curtail the power of the board and
Thomas Donovan, the longtime chief executive and president who has
pushed for more electronic trading.
</P>
<P>
   That move came just months after David Brennan, the chairman
popular with the traders in the pits, tried to oust Donovan in a
coup attempt that was strongly rebuffed by the board.
</P>
<P>
   The two men say they have since buried their differences, but
people close to them say they are merely being cordial and that bad
feelings remain.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan has overseen the day-to-day operations of the exchange
for more than a decade; last month he received a series of
petitions that forced him to make his salary public and stripped
him of the power to nominate public directors. He published his
salary _ $1.4 million a year _ then derided the petitions, calling
them the work of a small group of dissidents bent on undermining
top executives at a critical time. ``While we're doing this,'' he
said, ``Rome is burning.''
</P>
<P>
   The cry is a familiar one these days in the nation's financial
markets, which face a period of upheaval brought on by rapid
technology and rapidly increasing investor demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the exchanges are facing the same problem,'' said Barry
Lind, chairman of Lind Waldock, a discount futures broker in
Chicago. ``They've had a system that worked for more than 100
years, and now there's a more efficient system. If the exchanges
don't adapt, they die.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to move to electronic trading without disrupting or
cannibalizing the existing market of face-to-face ``open outcry''
trading is problematic, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the trading pits in Chicago fear the exchange could do
away with the old system of shouts and hand signals too quickly;
others fear the exchange will move too slowly into cyberspace _ and
eventually lose its grip on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition used to come from domestic exchanges and foreign
exchanges and now it comes from ECNs,'' said Donovan, referring to
fast-growing electronic communication networks that match orders.
</P>
<P>
   The divisions surfaced more than a year ago, when the membership
narrowly voted out Patrick Arbor, a pro-technology chairman, in
favor of Brennan, a 41-year-old soybean trader whom Arbor dubbed
``a member of the Flat Earth Society'' partly because of his
opposition to an alliance to build a joint electronic trading
platform with Eurex.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Brennan took over, the members voted to end the
alliance. Later, it reversed that decision and agreed to spend $50
million on a link with Eurex scheduled to begin operation next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan now says he is an enthusiastic backer of the plan.
``We're embracing technology,'' he said. ``Sometimes we get a bad
rap because we have a floor.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his office recently, Brennan looked
confident. He said he had named a task force to study how to speed
decision-making at the exchange so that it can compete better with
electronic upstarts.
</P>
<P>
   Challenges are coming from Cantor Fitzgerald, a large broker
that has begun trading futures electronically; possibly from the
NASDAQ stock market; and from BrokerTec Global, an electronic
alliance being formed by the biggest Wall Street firms, all members
of the board of trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seven largest firms are going into competition against
us,'' Brennan said. ``We need to modernize and get ready to
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan and Donovan do agree that the exchange should do what it
has long done best: hedge. They will offer electronic trading and
open outcry trading side by side, and let the customer choose.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange will also reduce the number of people on its floor
and use computers to create a faster route for transactions to get
to the trading pits. By forming the alliance with Eurex, the
exchange hopes volume, down 8 percent this year, will begin to
rebound next year.
</P>
<P>
   Arbor, the former exchange chairman, has an alternative plan. He
has asked the exchange to spin off its electronic unit into a
separate public company, which would compete against the floor
traders, but would also reward them as shareholders in a system
that he expects will eventually dominate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is like the perfect hedge: Let's spin it off and raise
money. Bank One did it with Wingspan,'' Arbor said, referring to
Bank One Corp.'s online banking arm. ``No matter who wins, Bank One
or Wingspan, the shareholders of Bank One win.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbor _ who says he is considering running for chairman again
next year _says that if the exchange runs both a floor and an
electronic system, pressure from the floor traders will impede the
growth of the online unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``To accept my plan, the membership has to accept the fact that
cannibalization can occur,'' he said. ``Ergo, it's better to eat
ourselves than let someone else eat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brennan and Donovan appear to be trying to mend their
relationship. After the petition vote a week ago, they issued a
joint statement: ``The members have spoken and we move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bloomfield, a longtime exchange member who helped write
several of the petitions, said they were not an attack on Donovan
or on the board, but simply a desire to know more about the
decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to an electronic trading format and converting to public
ownership are very difficult steps, he said. ``As we evolve, the
question is what kind of a format do we want? I don't know. But
what we needed was transparency and accountability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
