<HEADER>
A8418 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-N.H.-TEXT-NYT     11-22 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-N.H.-TEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCERPTS FROM BRADLEY'S SPEECH ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from prepared remarks by former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey for a speech on Monday at New Hampshire
College in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of that famous handshake between the leaders of
our two political parties in 1995 _ President Clinton and Newt
Gingrich. It was a very public handshake signifying a very public
commitment to campaign finance reform. And then nothing happened.
Nothing happened in 1995, in '96, in '97. Nothing happened in '98
or '99.
</P>
<P>
   Five years have passed. Two elections have passed. Two sessions
of Congress have come and gone. And still nothing has happened.
Even after 1996, and the very public problems with both parties,
we've still seen no action. Why is that?
</P>
<P>
   I'll tell you. It's because no one in Washington wants the
system changed. The reality is that behind every public handshake
on this issue, there has always been a secret handshake. That
tacit, secret handshake signals an agreement among politicians not
to upset a system that they use to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The public handshake was meant to be a commitment by politicians
to the public. But the secret handshake is a commitment to the
status quo, a deal between politicians and business to keep things
as usual. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Now let's go back to 1996. At that time, there were questions
about where politics ended and government began in the Clinton-Gore
fund-raising efforts. Now we hear that Cabinet officers are
structuring their schedules and their announcements so that the
vice president can finance his political campaign when his funds
run short.
</P>
<P>
   What's happened here? What's changed? The answer is the same now
as the handshake _ nothing has happened. Nothing has changed. The
more politicians talk about change, the more things stay the same.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   I think people understand that campaign finance reform is the
beginning of real reform throughout government.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I've challenged all the other candidates to promise
that if they are their party's nominee, they will join me in not
using soft money for their campaigns. And you know what? The vice
president's campaign chairman actually attacked me for espousing
this core Democratic Party principle _ a principle that is in our
party's platform, a principle supported and endorsed by President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   We can restore trust among the people of this country. We know
how to do it; the question is if we have the will to do it. It can
be done, if we want it to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, reforming the way we finance campaigns _ getting big
money out of politics _ is the key to making progress on the issues
that matter most. We need campaign finance reform. We need it now.
It is time to stop talking. We must restore trust in government.
It's time to do so. The American people shouldn't have to wait any
longer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
