<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MR. BARAK'S SUMMONS TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 23:
</P>
<P>
   Addressing an audience of American Jewish leaders the other
night, Ehud Barak chose the ancient words of Ecclesiastes, ``there
is a time for war and a time for peace.'' It was a particularly apt
quotation. As a former general and a former foreign minister under
Shimon Peres, Barak has seen his share of warmaking and
peacemaking. Now, as Israel's prime minister, he well knows that
the next few months offer a rare and perhaps fleeting opportunity
for clinching a Middle East peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has no illusions about the risks and difficulties ahead.
He understands that a written agreement cannot by itself assure
lasting peace. But he rightly recognizes that a quick and
successful conclusion to negotiations with the Palestinians as well
as future talks with Syria on Lebanon and the Golan Heights are
essential steps on the longer road to true peace that would leave
Israel stronger domestically and internationally
</P>
<P>
   Several factors combine to make this moment so crucial. After
100 years of bitter and unforgiving conflict, Israel and the
Palestinians now have leaders with the vision to see that for one
side to win, the other need not lose. Barak and the Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, have come to understand that their own
fates, and those of their peoples, are now intertwined in a
potentially positive way.
</P>
<P>
   From the Israeli side, that new reality was affirmed in the
election that brought Barak to power last spring. He proceeded to
build a broad new peacemaking coalition out of Israel's fractured
political parties, and set early deadlines for preliminary
agreements with the Palestinians and Syria. Even the defeated Likud
Party of the former prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, now
recognizes that Israel is committed to yield at least part of the
West Bank and Gaza to Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Barak recognizes that Israel will be better off if it can reach
an agreement with the Palestinians before Arafat, who looks
increasingly frail, yields power to his successor, who is as yet
unknown. As difficult as Arafat has been for Israelis to deal with
in the past, no other Palestinian leader today has the political
authority to make the painful compromises necessary for completing
the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Additional urgency comes from the approaching end of the Clinton
presidency. While the next occupant of the White House may prove as
committed to promoting Mideast peace as President Clinton has been,
the coming American election season will make it harder for
Washington to take an active role in encouraging the two sides to
reach agreement. With these factors in mind, Barak's announced
timetable for reaching a broad understanding with the Palestinians
by mid-February of next year seems about right.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves fewer than 90 days to work out the basic features of
an agreement covering issues like Palestinian statehood and
boundaries, Jerusalem, Jewish settlements and the rights of
Palestinian refugees. That is a daunting timetable. But with
fortitude on both sides it can be met.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0477 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8429 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     11-22 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REQUESTED REPEAT MODESTI COLUMN FROM LAST WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ A billboard labeled ``Countdown to History'' looms
over the Hollywood Park winner's circle these days, bearing the
career victory totals for Bill Shoemaker (8,833) and Laffit Pincay
(8,818 and counting).
</P>
<P>
   Each time Pincay wins a race, he strides to the board and hangs
a new number beside his name as a track photographer snaps his
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park and Santa Anita are having contests promising an
$8,834 prize to a fan who predicts the day and race when Pincay
passes Shoemaker. Further promotions revolving around Pincay's
record pursuit are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting exciting, especially on days like Wednesday, when
it seemed like old times, with the Panamanian riding in seven races
and winning three, the last by a neck in classic Pincay Power Play
style.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for ``the great man,'' as track announcer Michael
Wrona referred to Pincay in a plug for the contest between races
Thursday, it's as close to business as usual as he and his agent
can make it.
</P>
<P>
   So far, with Pincay 15 wins from tying Shoemaker, trainers and
owners aren't lining up to book his services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't changed at all,'' said agent Bob Meldahl, who has
booked Pincay's mounts since 1991. ``Nobody's expressed, `I'm going
to put you on all these 8-5 shots.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it'll change when he gets to seven or eight (from the
record).''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, people might be angling to have Pincay ride
!ital!their horse to the record.
</P>
<P>
   But if it doesn't happen that way _ if his winning opportunities
don't increase in the next few weeks _ it appears that will be all
right with Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope I don't ride seven, eight horses a day. It's too
demanding,'' Pincay said after his triple on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The only luxury in riding a full card is that Pincay could eat
100 more calories at dinner that night.
</P>
<P>
   At 52, living on 750 calories a day to maintain his 117-pound
riding weight, Pincay feels stronger riding four or five a day.
</P>
<P>
   Often, he rides fewer than that because fields at Hollywood Park
are typically small, and competition for mounts is as keen as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep it to three or four (a day),'' Meldahl said
in the Hollywood Park racing office Thursday morning. ``He's
fresher.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without extra chances, Pincay is riding as well as he has
in years. He has passed the 140-win mark in 1999, already his best
season since '95.
</P>
<P>
   If he kept winning at the rate that put him third in the jockey
standings at the Oak Tree meet, the countdown to history would end
Wednesday, Dec. 29, at Santa Anita. That happens to be Pincay's
birthday _ the day he has said he'd like to do it.
</P>
<P>
   If he kept winning at his 1999 pace, he'd get the record on
Friday, Dec. 31, the fifth day of the Santa Anita season. Then
Pincay might have to allow himself half a glass of champagne that
night.
</P>
<P>
   If he kept winning at his recent pace _ 15 victories in the past
12 racing days, including one Thursday _ he would blow past
Shoemaker on Sunday, Dec. 5. That's practically impossible, though,
because Pincay is scheduled to be in Panama Dec. 2-5 to be honored
at a Latin American jockeys' competition.
</P>
<P>
   Meldahl said a couple of out-of-town stakes assignments later in
December are possible as well. Although a win is a win wherever it
happens, such trips could slow him down simply by reducing his
number of mounts.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Pincay might be helped along if, as usual,
other veteran riders take vacations in December.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's asking for help. Business as usual has always been
good enough for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest with you, I don't think Laffit would
want it any other way,'' Meldahl said. ``He wants trainers to give
him good horses. But he's never in his life asked for anything
special, and he doesn't expect it now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
