<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TEAMSTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE TEAMSTER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times saidi in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 23:
</P>
<P>
   In winning a conviction last week against the former political
director of the Teamsters union for his role in an illegal campaign
finance scheme, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, Mary Jo White,
provided an example of vigorous law enforcement _ and a sharp
contrast to Attorney General Janet Reno's desultory pursuit of
campaign finance abuses by President Clinton's 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters official, William Hamilton, was convicted on fraud
and conspiracy charges stemming from his role in helping to divert
close to $900,000 in union money to finance the re-election
campaign of the union's former president Ron Carey. Carey narrowly
defeated James Hoffa in the election, but federal monitors
overturned his victory after discovering the campaign finance
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   While five people have pleaded guilty to participating in
different aspects of the conspiracy to swap union contributions to
outside political groups in order to generate contributions to the
Carey campaign, Hamilton was the first person to be tried in the
scandal. Depending on Ms. White's next steps, he may not be the
last.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial the prosecution presented testimony linking two
other well-connected figures to the effort to raise money for Carey
_ the AFL-CIO secretary-treasurer, Richard Trumka, and President
Clinton's friend and all-purpose fund-raiser, Terence McAuliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses indicated that Trumka had worked with Hamilton
on a complex operation designed to funnel $150,000 to help the
Carey campaign. As for McAuliffe, he was described in testimony by
the Democratic National Committee's former finance director,
Richard Sullivan, as playing a role in promoting another scheme to
swap campaign funds between the Democrats and the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   This plan, according to Sullivan, who received a no-prosecution
agreement for his testimony, called for the Teamsters union to
channel $500,000 or more in soft money to various Democratic Party
committees in exchange for a Democratic donor's making a
contribution of at least $50,000 to the Carey campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, this deal did not go through _ not, apparently,
because of any ethical misgivings but because Democratic officials
did not turn up a suitable donor. Ms. White's spokesman says the
investigation is continuing. McAuliffe's attorney insists his
client did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan's account is troubling. It should prompt Vice
President Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton, for whom McAuliffe is
now raising money, to ask for a full explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, Hamilton's conviction has left Ms. White with some
judgment calls to make as to whether she has the evidence for
additional prosecutions. But this case already stands as an
exemplary change from the reluctance of Ms. Reno's Justice
Department to look into potential campaign law violations by
prominent Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
