<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8437 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CENSUS-2000-HNS &LR;      11-22 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS WORKERS MAY BE HARD TO FIND, OFFICIALS ACKNOWLEDGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW BROMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Faced with filling almost 900,000 jobs by next
spring, the U.S. Census Bureau expressed concern Monday about heavy
competition for workers in a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau Director Kennwitt said he was ``reasonably
optimistic'' about finding the 860,000 temporary workers and fended
off Houston officials' criticism that the agency is not ready for
the national head count.
</P>
<P>
   Houston officials have accused the bureau of not moving fast
enough to ensure it has enough workers who are familiar with
minority neighborhoods and the languages spoken by residents.
</P>
<P>
   These concerns are ``slightly premature,'' Prewitt said. ``They
are bringing complaints ... about the census operation before all
the census operation has taken place.''
</P>
<P>
   To help with recruiting, the bureau has altered its hiring
practices somewhat since 1990, Prewitt said. For example, the
bureau is prepared to hire noncitizens with work permits, a
practice largely prohibited during the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau is also looking to form partnerships with
corporations and employment agencies to beef up its recruitment
efforts, particularly among college students, homemakers or others
who want to supplement their income with a short-term, second job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say that we are on track with respect to the
recruitment effort, I don't mean to suggest that we are relaxed
about that,'' Prewitt said during a briefing in Washington. ``It is
a very tight labor market.''
</P>
<P>
   With the economy setting records, the jobless rate has been
holding steady near 4 percent, a level at which the nation is
considered fully employed. In some areas of the country,
low-paying, low-skilled jobs are going unfilled.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston _ where census officials want to hire 6,600 workers _
the jobless rate stands at 4.4 percent. Kristin Capp, census
manager in Houston, said the agency is preparing for a ``worst-case
scenario'' to ensure enough workers are in place for measuring the
population.
</P>
<P>
   Houston City Councilman John Castillo and others have been
skeptical about the bureau's readiness to ensure the accuracy of
the census by improving the count in minority neighborhoods. In
1990, only 56 percent of the heavily minority Houston population
participated in the census compared to 65 percent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is if you raise these alarms too early, then it's
premature, but if you wait until it's over, then you're too late,''
Castillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Correcting the undercount problem partly depends on people
mailing back their forms, which the Census Bureau is trying to
encourage through a $167 million advertising campaign slated to
begin this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the equation, bureau officials acknowledge,
hinges on finding people who fail to respond to questionnaires they
receive by mail. This is accomplished with door-to-door interviews,
which will begin after the April deadline for returning census
forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (bureau) may need to dig a little deeper to compete in the
labor market,'' said Cheryl Abbot, an economist at the Texas Bureau
of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, bureau officials said they want to fill 20,000
positions. In an economy with an unemployment rate of 4.6 percent,
officials said they realize they will need to distinguish
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers are looking high and low for help, and we're no
different,'' said Donna Stovall, a Census Bureau recruiter in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Stovall said the bureau will pitch schedule flexibility and
higher wages to lure applicants. In Houston and Harris County,
door-to-door interviewers will get $10.25 an hour, but wages could
vary in neighboring counties, Stovall said.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that it may face an employment pinch, the bureau has
begun a recruiting pitch aimed at luring 150,000 Texas applicants
by next March in its effort to fill the 20,000 positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really front loading our operation because the
challenges out there are extreme,'' Stovall said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
