<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT, GREATER OR GREATEST GRETZKY ENTERS HOCKEY HALL OF FAME  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It will be up to future generations to decide whether
The Great One really was the greatest hockey player of all time.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, Wayne Gretzky took his place among the
National Hockey League's greatest players with his induction into
the Hockey Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Monday evening's ceremony was a mere formality, given the 61
National Hockey League records Gretzky either holds or shares
following his 21-year career. The waiving of the mandatory
three-year waiting period for Gretzky was testament enough to how
great he really was.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky is keenly aware of the rich tradition he inherited and
lifted to a new level. As a teen-ager, Gretzky _ who grew up in the
nearby Brantford, Ontario _ spent countless hours in the old Hall
of Fame facility, soaking up the game's rich history.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I was hoping was that one day I would get a chance to play
in the National Hockey League,'' Gretzky said.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving his ceremonial ring and blazer, Gretzky insisted
that his retirement did not mark the end of hockey history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Gordie Howe retired, there had never been anyone like
Gordie Howe before, and along came Bobby Orr,'' said Gretzky, the
historian, citing the two other players most often mentioned as
candidates for hockey's greatest player ever. ``When Bobby Orr
retired, along came Guy Lafleur. You always have these great
players come along to carry the torch. I probably miss the game
more than the game misses me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky was being modest, as usual. The game misses Gretzky
tremendously. So does his last team, the New York Rangers, on the
power play especially. But Monday, Gretzky again insisted he got
out at the right time, even if his father did not agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he could play another year,'' 61-year-old Walter
Gretzky said of his 38-year-old son. ``He told me, `Dad, you don't
understand. Every year at training camp, the other players get
bigger, faster, stronger and better. And I just get a year
older.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky said: ``I wish I could still play. I miss it
tremendously. But as I said before, I was going to retire one
time.''
</P>
<P>
   When he first learned of his Hall of Fame selection, Gretzky
said he immediately thought of Howe, Jean Beliveau and Orr, and how
he would be taking his place alongside them.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to provide his own list of hockey's greatest players,
Gretzky said four names immediately came to mind: Howe (``my
childhood idol''); Beliveau (``maybe one of the most elite athletes
in any sport''); Maurice (the Rocket) Richard (``for what he did
for the game, not only in Montreal, but in North America''), ``and
of course, Bobby Orr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two greatest players I ever saw were Bobby Orr and Gordie
Howe,'' Gretzky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any one person is ever going to be bigger than
the game,'' he said. ``What I think I did do, I paved the way for a
lot of other players. I was told that I wasn't big enough, that I
wasn't fast enough, that maybe I wasn't strong enough. Now people
can say, `He made it, maybe I can make it, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's induction class included the league's longtime referee
in chief and vice president of officiating, Ian (Scotty) Morrison,
in the builder category, and Andy Van Hellemond in the
referee/linesman category. Van Hellemond refereed 19 of 20 Stanley
Cup finals before retiring in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's enshrinement overshadowed the other inductees. But as
Van Hellemond said: ``Going in, in 1999, with No. 99, we'll always
be part of a trivia question: `Who were the other two?' As long as
they spell my name right, that's OK with me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because of the surgery he underwent for a brain aneurysm in
1991, Walter Gretzky has retained little memory of his son's
accomplishments from the early 70s to the early 90s.
</P>
<P>
   He does remember sitting with Howe when Gretzky broke Howe's
record for career points. Walter Gretzky also remembers Dec. 30,
1981, the night his son shattered the record for the quickest 50
goals by scoring his 50th in his 39th game.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky had phoned home after the game, saying, ``I got
it.''
</P>
<P>
   His father replied, ``What took you so long?
</P>
<P>
   But, said Canada's most famous father, ``I wasn't supposed to be
here tonight.'' Walter Gretzky nearly lost his life when Wayne was
3 in an accident at his job as a telephone repairman. ``I'm not
cheated. Not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Walter and Wayne Gretzky both had a chance to live
out a dream. Wayne Gretzky was asked if he now had a new dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``That I could come back and play again like I did when I was
20,'' the Great One said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
