<SLUG> BC-SBC-PRODIGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SBC WILL TRANSFER RESIDENTIAL INTERNET CUSTOMERS TO PRODIGY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SBC Communications Inc., the local telephone giant, said Monday
that it would transfer all of its residential Internet customers to
the Prodigy Communications Corp., the online service that has long
been overshadowed by America Online, in return for a 43 percent
stake in Prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   SBC, which does business as Ameritech, Pacific Bell and
Southwestern Bell, said Monday that Prodigy had agreed to assume
day-to-day management of SBC's 650,000 residential and
small-business Internet customers. SBC also said it had agreed to
make Prodigy its exclusive Internet service for consumers and small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Prodigy's market value Monday of almost $2 billion, the
43 percent stake taken by SBC would be worth about $900 million.
Prodigy's current primary shareholders, Telmex of Mexico and Carso
Global Telecom, will hold about one-third of Prodigy. SBC will
control only three of the nine seats on Prodigy's board, but the
company will have a veto over major acquisitions and key executive
hires.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, SBC said it would spend $6 billion to deploy
high-speed Internet systems throughout its service region, which
covers more than one-third of the United States population. SBC
intends to deploy a technology called digital subscriber line, or
DSL, which uses standard telephone wires to transmit digital data
at speeds many times faster than those using normal modems.
</P>
<P>
   SBC is known as one of the best-run regional Bell phone
companies, and the DSL announcement reflected the company's
confidence that it can profit from the exploding demand for
Internet access, particularly at high speeds. But none of the Bells
have had wild success as retail Internet providers, perhaps because
their brands are so throughly associated with voice telephone
service.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's deal, SBC agreed to market Prodigy's service
exclusively and to deliver 1.2 million new customers to Prodigy,
based in White Plains, over the next three years. If Prodigy
consumers use high-speed DSL lines, Prodigy will pay SBC for the
use of those lines. Consumers who use normal lines will almost
always be able to choose an independent Internet provider.
</P>
<P>
   SBC executives said Monday that not only would the deal give
them access to Prodigy's brand but it would also give them access
to Prodigy's stock as a potential currency for future acquisitions.
SBC's stock generally trades as a multiple of the company's
projected per-share earnings. Because of the potential for
dilution, that can make it difficult to use SBC stock to acquire
high-flying Internet companies that may not have earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shields us from significant earnings dilution if we
decide we want to grow that business substantially,'' Stephen A.
McGaw, an SBC managing director for business development, said in
an interview. Referring to a widely used tool for valuing stocks,
he added, ``If you run a discounted cash flow of some of these
Internet companies, you can't come near to what's ascribed in the
market. Having a currency there is a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   Prodigy was advised in the negotiations by Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co..
SBC was advised by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
