<SLUG> BC-NY-TIFFANY-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIFFANY'S OWNS THE BUILDING ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fifteen years after Tiffany &AMP; Co. sold its flagship
store on Fifth Avenue, the jewelry maker has repurchased the
property, which was featured in Truman Capote's novel ``Breakfast
at Tiffany's.''
</P>
<P>
   The luxury jeweler, whose robin's-egg-blue gift boxes are an
international status symbol, paid $94 million for the 10-story
building at the southeast corner of Fifth Avenue and 57th Street.
Just as there are few bargains in Tiffany's bejeweled showcases,
the building did not come cheap: Tiffany paid $29 million more than
it got for the building in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``That location became known as the Tiffany corner,'' said Scott
Latham, managing director with CB Richard Ellis, a real estate
brokerage. ``It's a good defensive move. Their lease comes up for
renewal soon, and I think they were going to get clobbered. Of
course, $96 million is a major-league commitment to lock up that
location.''
</P>
<P>
   It was business as usual on Monday beneath the soaring
first-floor ceiling of Tiffany's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building serves as a tangible symbol of our retailing and
merchandise initiatives throughout the world,'' Michael Kowalski,
president of Tiffany, said in a statement Monday night. ``In
financial terms, the tradeoff between the cost of leasing and the
cost of ownership is not expected to have any effect upon
earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its symbolic value for Tiffany, the property was
something of a loser for the Japanese company, Daiichi Real Estate
Co., that sold it. Daiichi bought the building for $94.35 million
at the height of the real estate boom in the 1980s. But when the
recession hit in 1991, property values dropped by 50 percent or
more, leaving Japanese buyers like Daiichi with grossly overpriced
investments. The once eager buyers have been sellers ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese banks and insurance companies are trying to clean
up their balance sheets,'' said Jack Rodman, the director of
Asian-Pacific operations for Ernst &AMP; Young. ``None of these
investments was a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the times last year, Ernst &AMP; Young changed the name
of its annual report ``Asian Investment in United States Real
Estate'' to ``United States Investment in Asian Real Estate.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1989, the Japanese went on a $7.4 billion shopping
spree in New York, buying trophy properties like Rockefeller
Center. That spawned a xenophobic reaction from critics who decried
the sell-off of American landmarks. But New York trophies lost
their luster when the recession hit Japan and New York real estate
almost simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, it was not a profitable shopping trip,''
said Richard Baxter, a senior managing director at Insignia/ESG
Capital Advisers. ``The Germans are now the largest buyers of real
estate, but unlike the 1980s, everything trading today has some
economic justification.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
