<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AVOIDS QUESTIONS ABOUT EXTRA DPS CHARGES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRATHAM, N.H. _ Gov. George W. Bush dodged questions Monday
about why he has refused to pay for the extra costs incurred by his
state security guards during his Republican presidential bid even
though he is returning part of his salary to Texas taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to talk to the DPS about what their charge is and
what their mandate is,'' Bush said. ``The Department of Public
Safety has got a charter, and that is to keep me safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The DPS earlier this month released records showing it had
incurred $1.8 million in expenses this year to protect Bush. That
is six times more than the agency spent during his re-election
campaign last year and 11 times more than it spent protecting Bush
in his least-expensive non-election year.
</P>
<P>
   When the question of his security first came up in July, Bush
announced he was returning to the state the $316 he normally would
earn each day as governor even if he was campaigning outside of
Texas. Bush said Lt. Gov. Rick Perry also gets that pay any day
when Bush is out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that one of the reasons he decided not to take
federal matching campaign funds this summer was because he did not
want taxpayers to support his primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a reason but not the main reason,'' Bush said Monday.
``The reason I didn't take federal matching money, taxpayer
matching funds, is because I'm running against somebody who has
unlimited money to spend. I'm not going to let happen to me in the
state of New Hampshire what happened to Bob Dole.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was referring to millionaire Steve Forbes, who largely
self-financed his 1996 campaign and is doing so again this year.
Dole's campaign suffered early in the 1996 primary campaigns
because he was operating under state-by-state spending limits
imposed on candidates who take matching funds. Forbes, who like
Bush this year, rejected the matching funds, did not have to comply
with the limits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also repeated that he will not meet with the Log Cabin
Republicans, a gay rights Republican group. One of Bush's GOP
rivals, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, met with the group, and Forbes
has said he is willing to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly disagree with them on issues such as gay
marriage,'' Bush said, adding that he would accept financial
contributions ``and votes'' from members of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they're for me. I welcome people from all walks of life
into my campaign,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign affairs, Bush was asked under what circumstances he
would commit troops to the Middle East. Bush said it would require
a circumstance such as the one that led his father, former
President Bush, to launch the Persian Gulf War when Iraq invaded
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our economic interests are threatened, something akin to
what happened in Kuwait, or if our friend Israel _ the security of
Israel is threatened,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor spent most of his day campaigning in the first
primary state of New Hampshire, finishing with a speech to a
standing-room-only crowd of about 350 people at Brown's Lobster
Pound in Seabrook, N.H. He acknowledged that some New Hampshire
voters may have been upset when he missed a debate last month to be
with his wife, Laura, as she received an award from Southern
Methodist University.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, I missed the first debate. That's the last debate
I'm going to miss,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush missed a debate Sunday in Arizona. He is returning to
New Hampshire on Dec. 2 for his first debate with other Republican
presidential candidates. He also is scheduled to participate in a
Dec. 6 Arizona debate and one Dec. 13 in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, as Bush toured the Timberland boot factory in Stratham,
one factory worker in a conference center meeting asked Bush how
his mother was doing, and he responded that she is full of advice
for his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on one of those TV shows yesterday morning, `Face the
Nation,' after it was over, mother called me with a little
critique,'' said Bush, who actually appeared on `Meet the Press.'
</P>
<P>
   One factory worker asked Bush if he was sincere in his promise
to provide an additional $1 billion for military pay increases and
as recruitment incentives. The man, whose brother is in the
military, said such promises in the past have fallen through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first question is: Does ol' George W. mean what he's
saying? If there's any doubt in your mind or the voters' minds that
I'm just up here talking, you shouldn't vote for me,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said part of the money from his plan would come from
savings created by a strategic overhaul of nation's weapons
systems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
