<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCANN HAS THINGS TO PROVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Quarterback Ryan McCann played well against USC in
the first start of his career but not well enough to avoid a
spring-practice duel with fellow freshman Cory Paus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ryan had had an outstanding game, it probably would have
really solidified his position (as the starter),'' Bruins coach Bob
Toledo said. ``But because of the interceptions, and he still has
some things to prove, it's only right to make it a competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't know that I'll name anybody (a starter) after
spring. That way, they'll work hard over the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus started seven games before breaking his collarbone against
Washington. He completed 48.2 percent of his passes this season,
with seven touchdowns and nine interceptions. His collarbone is
expected to heal in two months. He'll have surgery this month to
tighten loose shoulder ligaments, but he expects to be ready by
April.
</P>
<P>
   McCann, of Westlake, was the fourth-string quarterback when UCLA
broke training camp, but he improved dramatically in the final
month as his understanding coalesced with his size and strong arm.
He played sparingly until the USC game and finished the season with
a 52.4 completion percentage, no touchdowns and three
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, he's got a lot of tools,'' Toledo said. ``He just
needs time.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Work to do: Sophomore tailback DeShaun Foster's sprained
ankle (and disappointing season) greatly increased the chance he'll
play four years. If Foster had dominated this season, then played
well next year, he might have declared for the 2001 NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Foster rushed for fewer yards (375) than he did last year (673)
and ended the season with a crushing fumble against USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on his year next year, but I don't think he's ready
to come out,'' Toledo said. ``He needs time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injury really hurt him, but he needed to work harder
(last) summer. He needs to run more and lift weights with the
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Come one, come all: At his postseason press conference
Monday, Toledo promised competition for most positions in spring
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Three starters who missed most/all of the season _ receiver
Brian Poli-Dixon (broken wrist) and cornerbacks Jason Bell (painful
heel) and Marques Anderson (suspended) _ will compete for their
starting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bell and Anderson will have to beat (Ricky Manning
Jr.) out,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which redshirt freshmen appear ready to play, Toledo named
several: defensive tackle Rodney Leisle, guard Shane Lehmann,
defensive end David Ball, defensive end/linebacker Mat Ball,
linebacker Asi Faoa, tailback Akil Harris and receiver Jerry Owens,
of Newhall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not redshirt as many freshmen in the future,'' Toledo
said. ``Because of scholarship limits and injuries, you don't have
enough guys to go around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
