<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GOVERNORS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN GOVERNORS, WANTING ONE OF THEIR OWN, DECIDED EARLY ON
BUSH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Texas, Pa., Ohio, Utah, La., Mich., Okla., Mass.,
Mont., N.C.)  (nk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ More than one Republican governor looked at
making a presidential run this year, and there was a touch of envy
directed at the one who ultimately did. When Gov. Tommy G. Thompson
of Wisconsin decided against a campaign, he observed that his Texas
counterpart had a more famous name and more money, was
better-looking and came from a much bigger state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than those few little things,'' Thompson said, ``I'd
have been the front-runner.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gov. Michael O. Leavitt of Utah puts it now, ``It became
pretty clear pretty early that the one among us on whom fate seemed
to be settling was George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Bush emerged, the nation's Republican governors,
eager for a greater say in the affairs of the national party in
2000 and privately irritated with what they regarded as
congressional Republicans' bungling of public sentiment, had
largely concluded that the time had come to nominate one of their
own for president.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bush has assembled a remarkably unified team from the ranks
of the Republican governors _ the chief executives of 31 states,
and of eight of the nine most populous _ with whom he frequently
consults for both campaign advice and policy ideas. Many of them
endorsed him long before he officially jumped into the race in
June, and led fund-raising drives that helped him amass more
campaign money than any other presidential candidate in history.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governors are united behind Bush not so much by
any firm ideological ties as by the concerns that all governors
share and by a common hope among the Republicans that, as Gov. John
Engler of Michigan put it, ``a Republican president in Washington
would be enormously helpful'' in reducing the power of the federal
government and granting more to the states.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the governors' own ideologies range from the moderate
stances of Northeasterners like George Pataki of New York and
Christie Whitman of New Jersey to the staunchly conservative views
of some Westerners and Southerners like Mike Foster of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   But any such differences are clearly being shelved, at least for
now, and a visitor to the recent meeting of the Republican
Governors' Association in this Southern California community might
well have confused the event with a Bush-for-President strategy
session. It was here that the governors gathered not only to
discuss campaign themes but also to vote their support for Bush,
the first such endorsement with a primary battle still under way in
the organization's 36-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The governors hold regular conference calls with Bush, and he
often refers to them as some of his closest friends in politics or
singles them out for praise in campaign speeches. One of them, of
course _ Jeb Bush of Florida _ is his younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   That the governors could wind up playing so large a role says a
great deal about their popularity among the public. While a recent
New York Times/CBS News poll found that just 37 percent of
respondents approved of the way the Republican-controlled Congress
was handling its job, many Republican governors boast approval
ratings that are nearly twice as high. The governors are reaping
the benefits of a strong national economy, which has allowed them
to cut taxes and increase spending on popular programs at the same
time. They also seem to fare better than their congressional
counterparts because the public does not associate them with the
drive to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews at the meeting here, many governors said Bush had
brought a fresh political attitude to the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically adopts the strategy that you concede no issue,
you concede no voter, you concede no region,'' said Gov. Tom Ridge
of Pennsylvania. ``Every voter's an opportunity. For too long,
there's been a notion that maybe we can win nationally if we can
put together the least common denominator: `Let's figure out how we
can get just enough to win.' And George's approach, my approach,
the approach of a lot of governors, is, `Hey, how do we put our
arms around this whole thing and get as many votes as we possibly
can?'''
</P>
<P>
   Engler, a vigorous Bush backer, said that as early as last year
he and his colleagues were holding informal talks about advancing a
governor as the party's next candidate for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there was discussion among the governors about the
advisability of leading with our strength in the next presidential
election,'' he said, in the kind of comment that reflects
continuing tensions between Republicans in the governors' offices
and Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, for all the reasons that Thompson well knew, quickly
emerged as the informal consensus choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't all go out and do our secret handshake and do a
vote,'' Engler said. ``That didn't happen. But there was just a
clear sense that George W. Bush would be a very good president and
a feeling, `Hey, let's go out and do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Their shared outlook and familiarity with the man they have now
endorsed only enhance the prospect of payoffs for the governors:
cabinet posts, perhaps, should he win election, or maybe a spot on
the national ticket as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the governors say it is far too early to speculate on
the makeup of a ticket, and Bush, should he gain the nomination,
might well get advice to pick a running mate with congressional
experience.
</P>
<P>
   But at least a few of the governors are willing to promote the
idea of a vice-presidential nominee from among their own ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ```Outside of Washington' works,'' said Gov. John G. Rowland of
Connecticut. ``A governor would be perfect,'' he added, before
suggesting his colleague from Pennsylvania: ``Tommy Ridge would be
great.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And Whitman, who has been mentioned as a possible
vice-presidential candidate, said a congressional career was not so
vital a prerequisite as it used to be for a running mate of a
governor seeking the presidency: ``balance'' is simply no longer
deemed so crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I don't think the public is particularly enamored of
D.C. experience these days,'' she said. ``I think it is very
important to have had executive experience.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, the governors promote themselves as more moderate and
more pragmatic than many congressional Republicans. Frank Keating
of Oklahoma, departing chairman of the Republican Governors'
Association, calls the states ``hothouses of experimentation'' in
which the governors are leading a ``solution revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Thad Beyle, a political scientist at the University of North
Carolina, echoes the thought, noting for instance that it was the
states that took the lead in promoting the vast welfare overhaul
ultimately adopted by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel they had to virtually go out and get welfare reform
done,'' Beyle said of the Republican governors. ``They do not want
another U.S. senator or a national figure from the Republican Party
to be the leader in 2000. They want someone who has felt the fire
of being in the governor's chair.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The concerted effort on Bush's part was led by several
governors, including Engler, Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts and
Marc Racicot of Montana, who, beginning early this year, called
colleagues around the country urging them to endorse him, even as
he was saying he would not make up his mind about running until
after the Texas legislative session ended in May.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bob Taft of Ohio remembers getting a call from Engler but
replying that he would hold off since an Ohioan, Rep. John R.
Kasich, was in the race. ``Then the day after John dropped out'' in
July, ``Marc Racicot was on the phone,'' Taft recalled. ``And it
was, `OK, can you do it now?'''
</P>
<P>
   An earlier Bush boomlet occurred in February at a meeting of the
National Governors' Association, where several other governors
announced for Bush. ``It was the only spontaneous thing I've seen
happen in RGA/NGA politics in five years,'' Rowland said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Others who had held off on shelving their national ambitions
eventually saw the light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched George Bush come out of the blocks so fast,''
Thompson said. ``And as he did, I thought, `I better get on that
horse.''' Thompson, who calls Bush a ``wonderful candidate,''
endorsed him this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in Bush's favor was that many of the governors
had long links with the Bush family, dating from his father's run
for the White House starting in 1979. Ridge, for instance, led that
Bush campaign's effort in Erie County, Pa., and as vice president,
George Bush returned the favor with campaign help during Ridge's
successful run for Congress in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gov. Bush has done nothing to dampen speculation
that he might just tap a fellow governor to run with him if he wins
the nomination. He has even registered BushEngler, BushPataki,
BushRidge and BushWhitman as names for Web sites, though his
campaign says that it has reserved many other such names and that
no preferences should be read into the move.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, though naturally parrying questions about a
vice-presidential selection, Bush certainly does nothing to rule
anybody out. During a two-day fund-raising tour of Pennsylvania in
June, when he and Ridge took a break to go for a run along the
Susquehanna River, he jokingly referred to Ridge as his ``jogging
mate.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Iowa in August, he ran into Thompson, who was helping to
promote his successful bid to win a straw poll there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Tommy T.!'' said Bush, throwing his arms around the man
who had wanted to run for the presidency himself but declined in
the face of the Bush juggernaut. ``Tommy T.,'' Bush said, ``he's
the best. I know how lucky I am to have him with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
