<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GUCCI-FASHION-ART-960     11-22 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-FASHION-ART-960&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUCCI INSIDER TO LEAD SAINT LAURENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it was announced last week that Gucci had
finally closed its deal to buy Yves Saint Laurent for about $700
million in cash, there was a flurry of phone calls from journalists
in Europe and elsewhere to Gucci's chief press officer, Lisa
Schiek, in New York. They wanted to know one thing: Who was Mark
Lee?
</P>
<P>
   To a lot of people in the fashion world, and on Wall Street,
where news of the deal sent Gucci's stock up nearly 4 percent,
Saint Laurent is the ultimate prize. It is a label so steeped in
the history of the last 30 years that it has gathered meaning
beyond clothes. To be ``very Saint Laurent'' is to be not only
chic, with a ready knowledge of cut and seduction, but also modern.
</P>
<P>
   There are women who when asked to recall the 1970s will
invariably mention Saint Laurent. For women like Miuccia Prada, who
wore his clothes while distributing fliers for the Communist Party,
he alone showed them a new way to be women.
</P>
<P>
   He also meant something to Gabriella Forte. Putting aside her
long association with the house of Giorgio Armani and, more
recently, Calvin Klein, where she was president, Ms. Forte said,
``For my generation, I can't think of fashion without Saint
Laurent.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor can one think of Saint Laurent without Pierre Berge, the
power behind the throne. Theirs is the defining business
partnership in fashion, the one by which others are measured, and
it was not out of arrogance that Berge once remarked that Saint
Laurent was ``a man of exceptional intelligence practicing the
trade of an imbecile.'' It is simply that Berge understood better
than most how to protect the genius of one while exploiting the
weakness of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Thus when Domenico De Sole, the chief executive of Gucci, let it
be known last week that the most venerated fashion house in Paris,
with ties to the government and establishment, would be run by an
American named Mark Lee, there was a collective ``Who?''' And as if
to underscore how anonymous Lee is, Gucci _ for whom Lee has
directed global sales since 1996 _ did not even have a prepared
biography of him.
</P>
<P>
   What is intriguing about Lee's appointment, aside from the fact
that it is the first at Saint Laurent to be announced by De Sole
and Tom Ford, Gucci's creative director, is that at 36 Lee has
inherited one of the most visible positions in French fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Ford will shape Saint Laurent's style and image, and
Gucci's successful team approach will be applied to management. But
it is Lee who succeeds Berge, who built Saint Laurent's name into
an international status symbol largely by force of his own
personality.
</P>
<P>
   As managing director of Saint Laurent, Lee will be in charge of
the day-to-day business of the house's ready-to-wear, perfume and
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci is not the first company to own part or all of Saint
Laurent. A succession of corporations and individuals, beginning in
1963 with J. Mack Robinson, an Atlanta investor who made his
fortune in used cars, have owned stakes in the brand. But Gucci is
the first to control it completely.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Berge will run only Saint Laurent
haute couture, which is still controlled by Artemis SA, a holding
company. It is not quite Elba, but for a man accustomed to calling
the shots, who 10 years ago was predicting the demise of couture,
it isn't the whole empire, either.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a serious, soft-spoken person who in 1980 came to Manhattan
from San Francisco to study film at New York University, is well
regarded by fashion insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's smart,'' Philip Miller, president of Saks Fifth Avenue,
said, echoing similar comments by Ford and De Sole, who praised Lee
as a behind-the-scenes player whose knowledge of retailing helped
establish Gucci's handbags as hot accessories. De Sole said Monday
from Paris, ``If something makes sense, Mark implements it
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Another quality that friends like Sandra Brant, the publisher of
Interview magazine, and Stephen Sills, the interior designer,
mention is a reserve backed by powers of observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very, very shy, yet he can repeat things I've said a year
before,'' said Sills, who decorated the upstate country house that
Lee shares with Ed Filipowski, a senior partner in the fashion
public relations firm KCD.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brant, a friend of Saint Laurent and Berge since the early
1970s, when they were frequently out with Andy Warhol, added:
``Mark is always listening, always watching. But more than that, I
sense he's someone who's genuinely moved by people who put
themselves on a line creatively, and I think this will make him a
great warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lee does seem to be a strategist. He was suitably cautious
during an interview last week from Paris, where he was meeting
Saint Laurent managers. He began his fashion career as a factotum
for a video company, and then joined Saks as an assistant Eursportswear buyer. This sounded mildly impressive, but Lee denied
that. ``I wasn't in the forefront,'' he said. ``I was more in the
basement.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, after working briefly at Valentino, Lee was
hired by Ms. Forte to run Armani's collection business, which was
being pulled out of many department stores in a successful move to
build cachet for the brand. Ms. Forte recalled Lee's reaction when
she told him that her strategy was not to sell the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was totally devastated,'' Ms. Forte said with a
laugh. ``But what he learned was how to market a luxury brand. You
don't look for quick money. You plan every detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee followed that approach at Jil Sander and later at Gucci.
``You never focus on what you sell in the showroom, only what you
do at retail,'' he said. ``And that's the key to Gucci's success.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although old friends like Keith Scott, who worked with him at
Armani, and Sills see in Lee's reserve an alert mind, full of
references to fashion and obscure films, some find him inscrutable.
``He's difficult to read,'' a former colleague said. It's also hard
to weigh praise for Lee against his performance at Gucci, since
it's relatively easy to sell a brand that people want.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of Saint Laurent, Lee doesn't conceal his awe. He
met the designer last week. ``It was extremely emotional for me,''
Lee said. ``He's a legend. He's Saint Laurent.''
</P>
<P>
   Saint Laurent is also one of the most profoundly intriguing
people in fashion, the center of gossip, speculation and reverie in
a small, strange world that is fading fast. He once said, ``At 21,
I entered a kind of stronghold of glory that's been the trap of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee is hard-working and conscientious. He has in common with
Ford a respect for Saint Laurent and its culture, which will not be
lost on the Gucci management, whose designs already reflect Saint
Laurent's influence and are likely to bring fresh currency to the
label if Ford takes over the Rive Gauche ready-to-wear collection,
which seems inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But does anyone in this Ayn Rand age of managers and strategies
and incremental retailing understand what it took to remain in that
stronghold of glory?
</P>
<P>
   Lee sounds as if he's at least willing to try. ``My first
priority is to understand the existing organization,'' he said,
``to understand all that exists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
