<SLUG> BC-NY-LOBSTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATHS OF LOBSTERS IN LONG ISLAND SOUND TIED TO TINY PARASITE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Maine, Mass.)   By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYVILLE, N.Y. _ The mysterious deaths of hundreds of thousands
of lobsters in Long Island Sound this fall may have been caused by
a tiny parasite that is deadly to crustaceans but not a threat to
people, marine scientists in New York and Connecticut said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is probable that the deaths of lobsters and crabs in the
Sound are the result of an infestation by a parasite known as a
paramoeba, which does not present a hazard to human life,'' said
Ernest Beckwith, director of the marine fisheries division of the
Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said Monday that the parasite was found in dead
lobsters and crabs collected within the last month and that tests
showed that the parasite was present in almost all of the
specimens.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most of the dead lobsters that fishermen have found in
their traps have been pulled from the western waters off Long
Island Sound. Lobstermen who ply the waters between here and
Greenwich, Conn., have reported crustacean death rates of up to 50
percent. They say the infestation now appears to be spreading
eastward, said Nicholas Crismale, president of the Connecticut
Commercial Lobstermen's Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people relying on incomes from this industry, and now
our lives are on hold,'' Crismale said. The industry has grown to a
$16 million-a-year business in recent years because of record
catches, according to managers of marine fisheries in New York and
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said more research would be needed to determine whether
the paramoeba definitely caused the crustacean deaths this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection and
the New York Department of Environmental Conservation have been
working with the National Marine Fisheries Services Laboratory in
Milford, Conn., to determine the causes of the lobster deaths,
which were described as the worst to hit Long Island Sound in
almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Marine biologists say an examination of water quality in Long
Island Sound and an evaluation of bottom sediment have so far
failed to identify any environmental conditions or toxins that
could explain the high mortality rate.
</P>
<P>
   As their next step, pathologists began injecting the paramoeba
Monday into parasite-free lobsters obtained from a Massachusetts
hatchery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have results from the tests from this control group in
about two weeks,'' Beckwith said.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith cautioned, however, that although the parasite might be
the cause of the deaths, it could be a secondary infection in
crustaceans already weakened by another as yet undocumented cause.
He also said that parasite infestation or other causes of morbidity
and mortality in lobsters could be caused by changes in ecological
conditions in Long Island Sound, such as water temperature, that
need to be investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said the population of lobsters in Long Island Sound
over the last several years had exploded, providing lobstermen with
their best takes in decades. ``With so many lobsters, their natural
enemies may now be gaining ground, correcting the balance,'' he
said. ``Lobsters are not disappearing from the Sound, they are just
dropping back to more normal levels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
