<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THROAT-SLASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL SEEKING TO BAN THE THROAT-CUTTING GESTURE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Football League has become increasingly angry with
players who make throat-slashing gestures after scoring a touchdown
or making a big play. Now, league executives are taking steps to
ban the gesture in what would be a stunning but politically tricky
move.
</P>
<P>
   The act of taking an imaginary knife and running it across the
throat as a way of celebrating, or taunting an opponent, has
increased in popularity in professional football this season. Some
players believe using such a display is cruel and unnecessary while
others think it is a harmless way of celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   What matters most are the beliefs of owners, general managers
and league executives. Many of them believe the gesture is violent
and bad for the game's image. There is also a concern, though
probably unwarranted, that the gesture is gang related.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has spent the past week examining ways to eliminate the
gesture from the field of play. The league concluded a player
pretending to slash his neck violated league protocol, specifically
the sportsmanship portion of the rule book which states, in part, a
lack of ``mutual respect'' or other unsportsmanlike conduct, which
includes ``abusive'' acts aimed at players, coaches or other
personnel, are forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   This week the NFL will send a memo to each of its 31 teams,
asking them to remind the players of existing rules that prohibit
such behavior. Once players have been warned, game officials will
enforce that portion of the rules, flagging the player for a
15-yard unsportsmanlike conduct penalty. The player could also be
fined by the league office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the league goes through with this, they will have my
support, and probably 99 percent of my colleagues,'' said one
general manager, who asked not to be identified. ``It is an ugly,
violent thing to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore owner Art Modell said: ``When players do that,
it's just terrible. We do try to have a family-oriented game and we
don't need any nonsense to distract from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting worse,'' said Modell. ``On Sunday I was watching
a bunch of games and I saw players do it. We have rules in place
but we really need to crack down. The taunting, the theatrics, it's
bizarre. I hate it. A coach can't tell a player not to do it,
because that will make him do it more. But if something comes down
from the league, and it includes a penalty or fine, then players
listen. Then it will stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The league has tried to reel in excessive celebration,
strengthening rules to stop dances in the end zone after
touchdowns. Players and the news media criticized the league for
trying to weed levity out of the game. The NFL was nicknamed the
``No Fun League.''
</P>
<P>
   The throat-slashing gesture, however, is trickier. Since most of
the players who make the motion are black, there will be those who
will claim the league is specifically targeting black players.
</P>
<P>
   The league insists that is not the case.
</P>
<P>
   What the NFL believes is that something needs to be done. An
increasing number of players, league officials believe, are making
the motion, including well-known names such as Tampa Bay's Warren
Sapp, the Jets' Keyshawn Johnson and Green Bay's Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   A recent high-profile example of the gesture raised the NFL's
ire to the boiling point and prompted the league to consider
immediate action.
</P>
<P>
   During the Jets game against New England last Monday night,
Johnson scored on a touchdown catch, and then made the slashing
gesture to the crowd in Foxboro, Mass. Television cameras caught
Johnson's act _ he was not penalized.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said afterward that he did not mean the gesture as
anything other than a way to celebrate in what was an intense,
passionate game.
</P>
<P>
   Another example that irked the NFL happened this past Sunday and
involved one of the game's biggest stars in Favre. When Detroit
beat the Packers in Week 2, cornerback Robert Bailey flaunted the
cut-throat motion, irritating Green Bay players, including Favre.
</P>
<P>
   During Green Bay's 26-17 victory on Sunday, Favre threw a
touchdown pass, ran 20 yards up field to Bailey's vicinity and made
the gesture in his face. It was the second time Favre had taunted
the Lions with the gesture. The first time he was not penalized;
the second time he was, for unsportsmanlike conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``They batted the ball down on fourth down and they were doing
one of these in our first game,'' said Favre, drawing his thumb
across his neck. ``That hurt. When you taunt, it's going to come
back to haunt. I'm not that kind of player but I was today, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Favre added, ``When I see guys do that, I usually always say,
`Those guys shouldn't do that. It looks bad.' And then I'm out
there doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
