<SLUG> BC-SEATBELT-DRIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVE TO PUSH SEAT BELT USE BY CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police officers nationwide will be stepping up
enforcement of the laws on seat belts for children during this
Thanksgiving week, Department of Transportation officials said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enforcement translates into higher restraint use,''
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said. ``And higher restraint
use translates into real lives saved.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six of 10 children killed in automobile crashes in 1998
were not wearing seat belts, according to the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The travel days around Thanksgiving are among the busiest of the
year. And law enforcement officers will issue citations to drivers
with unrestrained children in the car in an effort sponsored by the
Air Bag and Seat Belt Safety Campaign, the Department of
Transportation, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
and the International Association of Chiefs of Police.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies in every state will conduct child
safety checkpoints. The officers will also enforce the laws on seat
belts for adults.
</P>
<P>
   All states have laws requiring that children under 4 be
restrained while riding in a car. But the laws vary with regard to
older children, the type of vehicle and even whether a passenger is
in the front seat or back seat. Twenty-five states require that
children up to 16 be restrained at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Over the two years that the campaign has focused on drivers not
buckling up their children, seat belt use is up and deaths are
down. Fatalities for children under 5 have declined 12 percent. And
seat belt use has increased from 62 percent to 70 percent, meaning
19 million more Americans are wearing seat belts, according to the
Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Still motor vehicle crashes remain the leading cause of death
for children age 5 to 14, according to the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration. Last year, 2,009 children under 16 died in
auto accidents, with nearly 320,000 injured.
</P>
<P>
   A study of 800 adult drivers that was released Monday by the
seatbelt campaign contained both bad news and good news: The study
found that 13 percent of those who regularly drove with children
under age 12 admitted not making sure the children were always
restrained. On the other hand, 70 percent of drivers said they felt
angry when they saw unbuckled children in a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drivers who consciously break the law and knowingly place
children at deadly risk by failing to buckle them up are deadbeat
drivers,'' said Janet Dewey, executive director of the seatbelt
safety campaign. ``And they need to be stopped, ticketed and
fined.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
