<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-ART-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRICK ATTACK VICTIM GAINS ENOUGH TO ASK QUESTIONS, FAMILY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 24 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a week of drifting in and out of consciousness
in an intensive care unit, Nicole Barrett, the woman who was struck
in the head with a brick in midtown Manhattan, has begun to speak
and ask about what happened to her, her family said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Peering up from her hospital bed, through the medication and the
confusion, she has shown the most determined signs of progress so
far, advancing past merely opening her eyes and moving her limbs to
trying to sit up and pose complex questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is talking with us,'' said her mother, Sharon Barrett.
``Sometimes she knows us by name. She knows quite a bit more than
we expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett, 27, has been in critical condition at Bellevue
Hospital Center since last Tuesday afternoon, when she was attacked
at the intersection of 42nd Street and Madison Avenue by a man who
slammed the back of her head with a brick.
</P>
<P>
   The brick, described by Police Commissioner Howard Safir as a
``six-and-a-half-pound paving stone,'' fractured her skull and sent
her pitching to the sidewalk face-first, leaving her with severe
brain trauma and facial bruises. In the hours after the attack, she
underwent two operations to relieve swelling and blood clots on and
near her brain. She was unconscious for days.
</P>
<P>
   In their effort to find Ms. Barrett's assailant, police
responded in force Monday morning after a woman reported seeing a
man hurl a stone through the window of a parked car on Manhattan's
Upper West Side. Officers fanned out into Riverside Park and the
adjacent neighborhood to see whether anyone else had seen the man.
But police ultimately determined that the description the witness
gave did not match the one given by witnesses to the assault on Ms.
Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to respond to each and every report,'' said
Marilyn Mode, a Police Department spokeswoman. ``We take what
happened last Tuesday very seriously, naturally, and so we're going
to investigate the calls we receive.'' Safir continued to appeal
for more information from New Yorkers. So far, he said,
investigators have looked into hundreds of tips. ``We check them
all out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett's mother and brother, accompanied by Safir and Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, met with reporters Monday to provide the latest
reports about her condition.
</P>
<P>
   Their update, based on a week of observation as the brain
swelling has subsided, included clearly optimistic signs. The
family said Ms. Barrett had begun speaking, asking, for instance,
how she ended up in the hospital, and telling her mother that she
hurts. She has also struggled to sit upright in her bed and appears
to have considerable physical strength, they said.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Mrs. Barrett said, the doctors and visitors have
refrained from telling her daughter that she was attacked. ``Her
boyfriend is with her, and he just told her she had a bad
accident,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the news conference, a hospital official offered further
details, saying that within the last two days Ms. Barrett had
started eating small amounts and was speaking in compound
sentences, not merely uttering names or simple thoughts. She is
also complaining of a headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is making very nice progress, but we are still calling her
critical,'' said Lorinda Klein, a hospital spokeswoman. ``Lots can
happen yet. She's doing well, but she could have another setback,
and we're being cautious about what we say.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Klein said she expected Ms. Barrett to be in the hospital
for weeks. Once she leaves intensive care, doctors will have to
evaluate the extent of the brain damage and what course of
rehabilitation to undertake, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the news conference was noteworthy for its cheerfulness.
Mrs. Barrett and her son, Scott, 24, who traveled last week from
the family home in Athens, Texas, appeared calm and at ease in
front of the crush of cameras and microphones. They said that they
had achieved a certain peace of mind through closeness and prayer,
and that they were feeling strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rely on God a great deal,'' Mrs. Barrett said, and noted
that the churches in their hometown had formed continuous prayer
chains for her daughter, known as Nikki, and that a priest was one
of the first people to assist her after she fell to the street. She
said they had asked God for a miracle.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Barretts also had warm words for New York. Giuliani, who ran
the conference, all but glowed beside her as she said they had been
overwhelmed by their treatment since arriving from East Texas last
week. ``Now we know why Nicole loves New York. Now we do, too,''
Mrs. Barrett said, later adding, ``We just can't believe there are
so many kind people in the world, much less in one city.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, during his remarks, announced the formation of a
city-supervised Friends of Nikki Fund that will accept donations to
help the family pay for Ms. Barrett's treatment and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the fund would assure donors that their money will
be properly accounted for. ``There are people who take advantage of
times like this and run around pretending to collect money,''
Giuliani said. Donations can be submitted to the Friends of Nikki
Fund, Mayor's Community Assistance Unit, 51 Chambers St., Room 630,
New York, NY 10007.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett's father, Arlen, who has been undergoing treatment
for cancer, was not at the news conference. The family said he was
exhausted and was resting.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Barrett said the family planned to remain with Nicole
indefinitely and would share the holiday with ``a nice turkey meal,
by her side, wherever she is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
