<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: TIES TO LIBYA
</P>
<P>
   After a 15-year break, Britain will resume diplomatic ties with
Libya next month because Tripoli has followed through on its
promise to compensate the family of a London policewoman killed in
1984 by shots fired from the Libyan Embassy. Relations have also
been improved by Libya's handover in April of two suspects in the
1988 bombing of the plane over Lockerbie that killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: CHIRAC SETBACK
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac, suffered a first-round setback to his
ambition to be re-elected in 2002, when his supporters slighted his
choice to run his Rally for the Republic party. Many political
analysts are saying that Chirac's choice, Jean-Paul Delevoye, may
not be able to win the final round of voting on Dec. 4, either.
Chirac's party has been in disarray since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: MAD COW DISEASE
</P>
<P>
   While the French and British continue to negotiate their dispute
over France's refusal to import British beef, officials said they
had discovered their 26th case of mad cow disease in France this
year. The animal was from Savoie and was born in 1991. Britain has
detected some 1,600 new cases of the disease this year.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: GONZALEZ CLEARED AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled that former Prime Minister Felipe
Gonzalez cannot be investigated in the deaths of four suspected
Basque terrorists in 1983 and 1984, reaffirming a decision in 1996
that cleared him in a 1983 kidnapping. Lower courts have
investigated accusations that his government conducted a campaign
that killed 27 suspected Basque separatists.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL ACCUSED
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Social Democrats and Greens have accused former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Party of accepting a
bribe in the form of a $520,000 campaign donation in 1991 to allow
the export of 36 tanks to Saudi Arabia. Kohl said he had no
knowledge of such a donation and welcomed the chance to explain the
sale to an inquiry next year.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF IN COURT
</P>
<P>
   The ousted prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, said that accusations
against him for kidnapping, treason, hijacking and conspiracy to
murder were ``cooked up,'' and that he had ``gone through mental
torture'' while held by the country's new military government.
Sharif was making his second appearance in the anti-terrorist court
and is expected to appear again on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: NEWS MEDIA RACISM
</P>
<P>
   An interim report on racism in the news media has found that
mainstream newspapers perpetuate negative stereotypes of blacks.
The report, by the Human Rights Commission, was both applauded and
criticized by various journalists and civic groups. A final report
is expected in January.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: ALLIES ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Officials said allied warplanes injured 10 ``citizens'' in
attacks in southern Iraq. Navy jets struck a missile site near An
Najaf, 85 miles south of Baghdad, but Pentagon officials said they
had no confirmation of casualties. U.S. jets also attacked air
defenses in northern Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
