<HEADLINE>
ARENA FOOTBALL GETS TV DEALS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arena Football League, the high-scoring downsized version of
traditional football, which helped the St. Louis Rams quarterback
Kurt Warner learn to make quick decisions, announced three-year
television deals Monday with TNN, ESPN, ESPN2 and ABC worth $25
million in cash and promotional value.
</P>
<P>
   The deals ensure that TNN will carry regular-season games on 14
consecutive weeks, plus four playoff games; ESPN and ESPN2 will
show up to six playoff games, and ABC will carry the Arena Bowl
championship game, as it has for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The deals cut ESPN and ESPN2's coverage of games, which were not
scheduled at regular times, and brought in TNN, a cable network
owned by CBS. TNN becomes the league's main TV carrier and will buy
the time required to show the games on ESPN, ESPN2 and ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were attracted to TNN's ability to promote our sport,''
Commissioner David Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   By holding costs down and creating a successful complement to
the National Football League, the AFL, which will add its 18th team
next week, has been the most successful second-tier sports league.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are worth $7 million each, and the NFL earlier this year
purchased an option to buy 49.9 percent of the league.
</P>
</TEXT>
