<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TOBACCO-970&AMP;ADD-NY     11-22 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOBACCO-970&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK IS NEAR DEAL ON USING TOBACCO SHARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Just as the states are about to take in a torrent
of money from their settlement with tobacco companies, New York's
lawmakers are moving toward a consensus that most if not all of the
state's share should be spent on health.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Gov. George Pataki proposed spending
three-quarters of the money on reducing the state's debts; the
Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, said a large chunk of it might go
toward school construction; and the Senate majority leader, Joseph
Bruno, said he wanted a major share to go to tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But as the distribution of the settlement money approaches _ the
first payments are expected in the first half of December _ none of
the three men have voiced such views lately. Bruno and Silver have
said that all of the state's share, $1 billion for the first year,
should go toward health care, though they differ on the definition
of that term. Pataki's office has kept his plans intentionally
vague, but there, too, officials are talking about using it for
health care.
</P>
<P>
   The clearest shift has come from Bruno, a Republican, who began
the year saying he favored spending about one-third of the tobacco
money on health care. But last week Bruno said he thought virtually
the entire amount should go toward health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since that money comes from a result of a settlement with
tobacco companies,'' Bruno said, ``and the settlement was based on
increased health care costs to the citizens of this country and
this state, we think it's appropriate that we target it for health
care.''
</P>
<P>
   The money stems from the lawsuits filed by most of the states
against the major tobacco companies to recover Medicaid costs for
health care related to tobacco use. The main case was settled late
last year on behalf of 46 states for $206 billion, to be paid over
25 years. Four other states settled for $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The precise amounts of the disbursements will vary from year to
year, but New York will receive $1 billion a year, for a total of
$25 billion. Of that, slightly less than half will go to local
governments, including $6.7 billion to New York City, which share
in Medicaid costs. The state government will receive the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said Monday that his first priority would be to spend $125
million a year to subsidize drug prescriptions for elderly people
who have limited incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Next, he said, should be an effort to provide health coverage
for some of the more than 3 million people in the state who have no
health insurance, and to run an aggressive anti-smoking program,
including advertising, education and treatment. Some Senate
Republicans propose $100 million a year or more for anti-smoking
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The final decisions are likely to be made in next year's budget
negotiations, so a resolution is probably at least six months away.
Even so, anti-tobacco groups are encouraged by what they hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased because we've seen a great change since
last winter,'' said Russell Sciandra, director of the Center for a
Tobacco-Free New York. ``We are hoping that for once, in Albany,
they won't just use the money to take care of as many special
interests as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said he changed his mind when he learned that the health
care programs he wanted were far more expensive than he had
thought, and when he received advice from other Senate Republicans.
Republicans are concerned that their 36-to-25 edge over Democrats
in the Senate could slip in next year's elections, and they have
been seeking ways to appeal to centrist voters in swing districts.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, a Democrat, has said all along that he favors using most
of the money for health care, primarily coverage for the uninsured,
and his aides say he has all but abandoned the school construction
idea. He has also proposed an anti-smoking program that would cost
$90 million a year. ``His position is, it's all for health, one way
or another,'' said Patricia Lynch, Silver's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   When asked recently, the governor, a Republican, declined to say
whether he still favored spending the settlement money on debt
reduction, and would not offer anything in its place. But
anti-smoking advocates and legislative aides say Pataki's office
has been working on a package of health care uses for the money.
The governor has also spoken favorably of expanding the state's
anti-tobacco programs, though he has not made any proposals or
cited any figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at all those issues,'' said Michael McKeon, the
governor's press secretary, adding that he could not be more
specific. ``Health care is important, and debt reduction remains an
important issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But anti-smoking groups fear that talk of spending the
settlement money on health care could mask plans to use it to
supplant existing allocations for existing programs. In particular,
Republican lawmakers have been looking for a way to reduce the
state surcharges that are added to all hospital bills to reimburse
hospitals for treating the indigent, and for postgraduate training
of young doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said last week that he was still open to using some of the
money to replace those surcharges, effectively using the tobacco
settlement to lower costs for health insurers. But Silver rejected
that idea, saying it was not a legitimate health care purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get any additional spending that way,'' Sciandra
said. ``If they turn it into a zero-sum game, tobacco control will
lose out.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, New York was one of just four states to do any
kind of anti-tobacco advertising. Now, 20 states have programs that
include advertising, and they all spend more per capita than New
York does. New York spends $8 million a year on its program,
compared with more than $100 million by California.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Gov. Christie Whitman has said that all of her
state's share of the settlement should go toward health programs,
but legislators are calling for spending it on everything from
school construction to transportation. As in New York, the dispute
is expected to become part of next year's budget negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   For the first two years, Connecticut lawmakers have committed
the money to several health programs _ including vaccinations and
dental care for children, community health centers and a
stop-smoking program _ and to schools.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 21 states have made decisions about how to spend the
money, according to the National Conference of State Legislatures.
Of the money that has been earmarked, the group says, 30 percent
will go to health care, 23 percent to education, 11 percent to
anti-smoking efforts, 10 percent to programs for children that are
not related to health care, and 9 percent to services for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   New York City and Nassau County, the two local governments that
will receive the largest shares of New York's settlement income,
have decided to sell bonds backed by the 25-year revenue stream,
rather than waiting for the money, a strategy that a handful of
states are also using. The city recently sold $709 million in
bonds, Nassau is preparing a $302 million bond sale, and each plans
more sales in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
