u f BC-TELECOM-ITALIA-545&AMP;AD     11-22 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-ITALIA-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM ITALIA SHARES RISE AFTER END OF SPINOFF PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Shares in Telecom Italia SpA and the companies that
acquired it last spring climbed Monday after a decision to abandon
a plan to strip the company, Italy's biggest phone provider, of its
profitable cellular phone unit.
</P>
<P>
   On the Milan exchange, shares in Telecom Italia and Telecom
Italia Mobile, the cellular phone unit, as well as Tecnost SpA, the
company through which Olivetti SpA bought Telecom Italia, rose 4
percent to 5 percent in heavy trading early in the day. Shares of
Telecom Italia finished up 0.19 euro, or 1.8 percent, to 10.37
euros, while shares in the mobile unit added 0.25 euro, or 3.7
percent, to 7.18 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Tecnost climbed 0.09 euro, or 4.6 percent, to 2.23 euros.
Olivetti gained slightly, rising 0.01 euro, to 2.16 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that while investors appeared pleased with the
weekend decision, they would not be fully reassured until Roberto
Colaninno, the chief executive of Olivetti, Tecnost and Telecom
Italia, gave more details of alternative strategies.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Colaninno planned to transfer the cellular phone
unit to Tecnost, an Olivetti gambling-machine subsidiary that took
control of Telecom Italia in May in Olivetti's $34 billion
takeover. Tecnost would have used the unit's cash flow to help pay
back the almost $17 billion in debt it took on.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, minority investors punished shares of the
companies involved for the decision to strip Telecom Italia of its
most valued asset.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Telecom Italia, for instance, tumbled below 8 euros,
or $8.25, compared with the 11.5 euros Olivetti agreed to pay when
it acquired the company. Late last week, the prices regained ground
as investors grew convinced that Colaninno would reconsider his
plan. Analysts said Monday that the shares remained undervalued and
would most likely continue to gain.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings on Sunday, the boards of Olivetti and Tecnost killed
the plan, announcing instead that Telecom Italia would sell shares
in its Internet unit, Tin.it SpA, whose 1.2 million customers and
55 percent share of the Italian market make it the country's
biggest access provider. Telecom Italia did not say how much it
would sell of Tin.it, which analysts value at as much as $10
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of Colaninno's move go beyond Telecom Italia. The
Italian stock exchange has lagged behind its European counterparts
this year, gaining little more than 2 percent despite bull markets
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts attribute this in part to investor displeasure
with a persistence in Italy of old-style financial dealings in
which corporate control is exercised, as at Telecom Italia, through
opaque holding companies, with minority investors often finding
their rights trampled.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the plunge in Telecom Italia's share price fueled
speculation earlier this month that the phone company could become
a takeover target, much the way Mannesmann AG, the big German
engineering and telecommunications group, has become a target for
Vodafone Airtouch in a $123 billion hostile takeover attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government took the speculation so seriously that
government officials warned earlier this month that Rome would
invoke antitrust legislation to block a hostile bid by a major
European competitor for Telecom Italia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert Mocatta, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston in
London, said Colaninno's reversal was encouraging for minority
shareholders because it showed that Colaninno ``cannot choose to
move value around in his chain of holdings.'' But he described it
as a ``win-win situation,'' saying it also benefited Colaninno by
forcing him to find strategic alternatives, such as taking part of
Tin.it public.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts played down the protests of minority
shareholders, saying that Colaninno was merely reacting to the
plunge in Telecom Italia's shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market simply moved against them,'' said Rod Chisholm, an
analyst at HSBC Securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
