<SLUG> BC-PRESBYTERIANS-COURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.)  
 PRESBYTERIAN COURT DENIES TWO EFFORTS AGAINST GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A regional court of the Presbyterian Church dealt
a setback Monday to conservatives trying to categorically ban gay
marriages and the ordination of gays.
</P>
<P>
   In two decisions released Monday, the 12-member Permanent
Judicial Commission of the Synod of the Northeast let stand a
decision by a group of southern New Jersey churches to admit to the
level of candidate _ just one step below an ordained minister _ an
openly gay man who had refused to promise to be celibate. The panel
also upheld the authority of a church in Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., to
conduct ``holy union'' ceremonies for gay couples.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions were the commission's third and fourth this year
on issues affecting gay men and women in the church. In the two
earlier decisions, the commission sided with a more sweeping
interpretation of the church ban on gay and lesbian marriages and
gay ordination.
</P>
<P>
   Those on both sides of the issue predicted Monday that the stage
was set for yet another battle over interpretation of church
regulations before the group's national governing body, the General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decisions pivoted on narrow interpretations of a 1997
amendment to the church's Book of Order, which decrees that
marriage is a union between a man and a woman and that those
ordained in the faith ``live either in fidelity within the covenant
of marriage between man and woman or chastity in singleness.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Dobbs Ferry church, the commission said that
the Book of Order did not deal with the concept of ``holy unions,''
and that the church was within its rights to conduct such services
since it had accepted the fact that ``these ceremonies do not
constitute marriage'' as defined by the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the southern New Jersey churches, the commission
found that the post of candidate was not an ordained position in
which the church required fidelity in marriage or chastity in
singleness. But it said that if the candidate were to seek
ordination, his avowed intention to have an active homosexual life
should be taken into account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0513 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8603 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-STADIUM-AZR &LR;      11-22 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1ST LOOK AT STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Gov. Jane Hull's stadium task force got its first
look Monday, Nov. 22, at the kind of home the Arizona Cardinals
want: a $329 million venue with a movable grass field, a roof that
opens, 94 luxury suites and seats for 67,000.
</P>
<P>
   However, the task force did not talk about how the stadium would
be paid for or discuss any potential sites, both of which are
expected to be taken up in later meetings and create the most
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The $329 million cost estimate does not include the purchase of
land for the stadium or for parking.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's morning meeting at a Phoenix hotel was open to the
public, marking a reversal of the task force's initial policy of
closed meetings.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away at Maricopa County Superior Court, lawyers
squared off over the issue before Judge Donald Daughton.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for The Arizona Republic and the Associated Press argued
Monday, Nov. 22, that the task force should comply fully with
Arizona's Open Meeting Law. Daughton said he tended to agree and
told task force lawyers to keep that in mind as they draft an
agreement under which the meetings would be run in accordance with
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Daniel Flores, Hull's general counsel, told the judge,
``The governor will disband this commission if they do not
comply.''
</P>
<P>
   A full hearing on the matter was continued until next week.
</P>
<P>
   Task force members did not vote on anything during Monday's,
Nov. 22, 90-minute session, though there was general agreement that
the panel's main goals should be to recommend a facility that keeps
the Cardinals in Arizona, gets Arizona into the NFL's rotation of
Super Bowl sites and presents an attractive option for the
collegiate Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hull wanted the panel to look chiefly at a football
venue, task force members Monday, Nov. 22, also agreed to do a
quick marketing survey to determine whether there were other uses
for a stadium _ professional soccer, for example, or certain
convention events.
</P>
<P>
   There also was consensus to abandon a proposal for Arizona State
University and the Cardinals to share a stadium, either by
overhauling ASU's Sun Devil Stadium or moving both teams to a new
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to stay at Sun Devil Stadium, and we respect that,''
Cardinals Vice President Michael Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   Design consultants estimated that it would cost $202 million to
remodel Sun Devil Stadium as an open-air NFL stadium with arm-chair
seats, larger, enclosed loge boxes and wider concourses. The design
would fall short of what Bidwill says the team needs: a domed
facility that can be air-conditioned, offers more modern comforts
for fans and has lucrative luxury seating.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants offered a ``guesstimate'' of $352 million to enclose
Sun Devil Stadium, although it isn't clear whether it's even
structurally possible.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Monday's, Nov. 22, meeting focused chiefly on what
the Cardinals would like the stadium to look like.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Aylesworth, executive vice president of Huber, Hunt &AMP;
Nichols, a general contractor that has been involved in other
stadium projects, described a venue with a partly opening roof, an
end wall that would open to the outdoors and a movable grass field
that would slide outside to keep the turf alive when games weren't
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   With 94 luxury boxes and 6,800 clubs seats with a lounge area,
the stadium would earn more than the team takes in at Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The 67,000 capacity could be reconfigured for special events,
such as a Super Bowl, to seat an extra 11,000. If work began next
year, it could be ready by the fall of 2003, Aylesworth said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed roof would open roughly the width of the field but
would not retract entirely. When open, it would look something like
Texas Stadium in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   With the movable wall at one end, the stadium would have an
outdoor feel at winter events, but both roof and wall could be
closed to air-condition the stadium during warmer months.
</P>
<P>
   The open roof would let sunlight reach the turf, but the entire
field would slide like a tray out of the stadium. That would expose
a concrete floor that could be used for other activities.
</P>
<P>
   The design is similar to a one rejected by voters as part of the
Rio Salado Crossing stadium and convention center in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Aylesworth said the movable field, a $6 million item, would
eliminate the need for a far more expensive, fully retractable dome
to keep natural grass
</P>
<P>
   Several task force members questioned the need for a roof
opening if the field could be moved. The proposed roof accounts for
about $54 million of the estimated cost.
</P>
<P>
   Aylesworth responded that the scaled-back sun roof was not as
costly as a fully retractable dome, and would preserve the
stadium's desert ambiance in winter, a factor several panelists
felt would help lure the Super Bowl and sell Arizona during
national television broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium would take up 10 acres, with 8 more acres needed to
slide the field outside. Parking would require more acreage.
</P>
<P>
   Financing alternatives are expected to be discussed at the next
meeting on Dec. 2. Public financing options being considered
include so-called tourism taxes _ hotel or motel bed taxes and
rental-car surcharges _ and sports ticket surcharges. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-22-99 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
