<DOCNO> NYT19991122.0514 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-22 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FASHION-NOTES-NYT &LR;      11-22 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBC DOCUMENTARY LOOKS AT MODEL AGENCIES  
 PROMOTING A SECRETARY'S BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)  (lb) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scoring impressively on a moral rectitude exam has never been a
requirement for landing a powerful job that puts one into daily
contact with 16-year-old girls earning more than ice-cream-parlor
wages for standing in front of a camera with very little on.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the degree to which a number of modeling industry
executives have apparently just failed such a test _ one they had
no idea they were taking _ is causing quite a stir in the world's
fashion capitals this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night in England, BBC One will show a documentary
that it says is based on a year of undercover research and will
show people in the modeling business boasting of sexual conquests
with their young charges, supplying the women with drugs and
pawning them off to middle-aged businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   The program is part of a series of investigative reports on
current-affairs issues called ``MacIntyre Undercover.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the program, four employees of Elite Model
Management have been suspended, pending an inquiry by the agency:
Gerald Marie, president of Elite's European division; Olivier
Daube, director of recruitment in the New York office; Xavier
Moreau, president of the Elite Model Look contest, and Daniele
Bianco, who has worked as a chaperone in Milan, Italy, where he was
entrusted with driving and protecting models during their off
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's episode of ``MacIntyre Undercover'' was being
edited Monday, and no one from Elite or the press had yet seen it.
But the BBC said in a news release that Marie is seen telling Donal
MacIntyre, the chief correspondent, that he's planning to have sex
with young girls who have succeeded to the final round of the
international Elite Model Look contest.
</P>
<P>
   MacIntyre and his crew obtained this footage, and much of the
material in the program, using hidden cameras, a tactic that has
led to lawsuits against television newsmagazines in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   MacIntyre disguised himself as a photographer for a fictitious
fashion magazine, Polka Dot. A crew member, Lisa Brinkworth, posed
as a model, and in an article published on Sunday in The Daily
Mail, a British newspaper, she said she filmed Marie offering her
$500 to go to bed with him.
</P>
<P>
   John Casablancas, Elite's founder and chairman, said in a
statement Monday that the comments reportedly made by his employees
are ``if true, wholly inappropriate and run completely against the
principles, standards and conduct'' of his company.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he scoffed at the notion that Marie, who was
once married to the model Linda Evangelista, would have
propositioned Ms. Brinkworth.
</P>
<P>
   Casablancas is having all the models who have ever been in the
care of Bianco, whose job as a chaperone required him to escort
young women to nightclubs, questioned about any sexual
transgressions he may have committed. He also said he is demanding
written explanations from all those accused of offensive behavior
in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ideal world, we would like none of our employees to have
anything to do with our models,'' Casablancas said.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting a Secretary's Book
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Early last summer, Arie L. Kopelman received an
assignment from his boss that usually falls to underpaid
30-year-olds at publishing houses, not middle-aged presidents of
fashion empires.
</P>
<P>
   Kopelman, the president of Chanel Inc., was asked by the
company's chairman, Alain Wertheimer, to play book publicist for a
first-time novelist who also happened to be the secretary to
Wertheimer and his brother, Charles Heilbronn, Chanel's executive
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was a groan _ one more thing to do,''
Kopelman said. But he added that he found the book, Helen Ellis'
``Eating the Cheshire Cat,'' a story about social competition and
the high cost of the quest for beauty among young women, to be
engrossing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was different from almost anything I've read,''
he said. He then wrote to 10 editors at various fashion magazines,
including Anna Wintour of Vogue, asking them to take a look at the
book, which is to be published by Scribner in January.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellis, 29, worked at a Talbot's clothing store on the Upper
East Side before she took a job at Chanel, arranging Wertheimer's
mail and putting theater tickets into the shoes of Heilbronn, who
liked to work in stocking feet, so he would remember them at the
end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Tuscaloosa, Ala., Ms. Ellis says she has enjoyed
working at Chanel, although she admits to being afraid to visit the
marketing department, where everyone is especially well dressed.
That should no longer be a problem. With part of her book advance,
she said, she bought a Chanel leather jacket.
</P>
</TEXT>
